<HEADLINE>
MEL GIBSON GETS `LETHAL': FOURTH TIME'S THE CHARM 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Mel Gibson with Danny Glover and Chris
Rock in a scene from ``Lethal Weapon 4.'' 
 By CINDY PEARLMAN  
 World rights except Chicago 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    It's hard to get Mel Gibson to do something he doesn't want to
do.
 &HT;    Not only can he be highly intimidating on a personal level _
those cheery blue eyes have turned icy in everything from ``Mad
Max'' (1979) to ``Ransom'' (1996) _ but few can match the Hollywood
clout of an actor/director who has not only a string of
$100-million-plus hits but also a couple of Oscars for
``Braveheart'' (1995).
 &HT;    Which means that for as long as Gibson said that three was
plenty, the ``Lethal Weapon'' series wasn't going anywhere. Without
his key role as cop-on-the-edge Martin Riggs, it just wasn't
happening.
 &HT;    ``I know, a few years ago I said I would never do another
`Lethal,''' Gibson admits, sipping coffee at the Regency Hotel in
New York. ``I told people they should just send the script to
another action star. Maybe they could call it `Angry Bruce 4.'''
 &HT;    Nevertheless, here is ``Lethal Weapon 4,'' opening July 10 and
bringing back Gibson, Danny Glover, Rene Russo and Joe Pesci _ plus
newcomer Chris Rock _ for a typically explosion-laded action
comedy.
 &HT;    Gibson may still have his reservations _ at one point, Glover's
Detective Murtaugh asks him, ``Aren't we too old for this sh-t?'' _
but he seems comfortable with his decision.
 &HT;    ``I liked that we decided to do more of a personal story with
this one, instead of just having an archvillain,'' Gibson says.
``We get more deeply into the lives of Riggs and Murtaugh ... and,
of course, there are some explosions and sh-t.''
 &HT;    Surprise _ it's not Shakespeare.
 &HT;    ``It's an action series that has never taken itself too
seriously,'' Gibson says amiably. ``It's fun. It's not meant to be
a night at the opera.''
 &HT;    It was nighttime, however, when Gibson and series director
Richard Donner, struck by the idea for the sequel, called Glover
for his opinion,
 &HT;    ``It was late at night,'' Gibson recalls. ``I said, `Danny,
let's do another ``Lethal Weapon.'' Are you up for the ride?'
 &HT;    ``He said, `Yeah.'
 &HT;    ``I said, `OK, so you're excited?'
 &HT;    ``He said, `Oh yeah.'
 &HT;    ``I think he was sleeping when I called,'' Gibson concludes.
 &HT;    Later, though, Glover got more into the spirit of things.
 &HT;    ``Danny and I started talking about the sequel, and we were
crying with laughter,'' Gibson recalls. ``We just kept one-upping
each other, and it became obvious we had to do it.''
 &HT;    Actually making the movie was less hilarious, though.
 &HT;    ``I experienced something that has never happened before on one
of these movies,'' Gibson says. ``I was sprinting after a bad guy.
I jumped over a park bench and pulled a hamstring muscle.
 &HT;    ``Maybe we are getting too old for this, uh, stuff.''
 &HT;    It's his call, though, because Gibson controls his Hollywood
destiny, both through his own starpower and through his flourishing
production company, Icon Films.
 &HT;    And no, the icon referred to is not Gibson himself. The company
had its roots one day when the actor and a longtime friend,
accountant Bruce Davey, were shooting the breeze in Gibson's den on
the Australian cattle ranch he shares with his wife Robyn and their
six children.
 &HT;    ``I said, `I am so sick of seeing stupid movies,''' he recalls.
```We should just start a company and stop yapping about how things
stink.'''
 &HT;    All they needed was a name.
 &HT;    ``My eyes started scanning the bookcase, and there was this
reference book about Russian icons,'' the actor says. ``I thought,
`Hmmm, Icon. That's not too shabby.'''
 &HT;    Icon quickly made a name for itself, producing the box-office
hit ``Maverick'' (1994), ``Immortal Beloved'' (1994), the
Oscar-winning ``Braveheart,'' ``187'' (1997) and, most recently,
the children's film ``Fairy Tale _ A True Story'' (1998). Its next
offering is Gibson's ``Payback,'' due this fall.
 &HT;    ``That one I wanted to do because it's just a quick, slam-bang
thriller,'' Gibson says. ``It's about a guy who gets f--ked out of
some money and goes through all sorts of stuff to get it back. The
whole thing happens in 95 pages. It's like a whack in the face.''
 &HT;    Gibson relishes the Hollywood heft Icon has given him.
 &HT;    ``As an actor, you're kind of like this leaf being battered
constantly in the breeze,'' he says. ``And some days the breeze
turns into a hurricane. Your will is not your own, to a degree.''
 &HT;    Now Gibson's will is his own, and his company has a dozen
projects in development, with four films apiece in the works at
Twentieth Century Fox, Warner Bros. and Paramount.
 &HT;    ``I'll star in some and direct others,'' Gibson says. ``It's all
pretty loose, which is the way I like it.
 &HT;    ``But I won't star in many movies I direct,'' he adds, ``because
doing both literally kills you. It's too hard.''
 &HT;    Gibson's current enthusiasm is a new version of Ray Bradbury's
classic story, ``Fahrenheit 451.''
 &HT;    ``We've adapted it for the '90s, with this really cool
screenwriter Terry Hayes, who did `Road Warrior' (1981),'' he says.
``We get on like ham and eggs. And we departed from the book a long
way and went to the year 2035.''
 &HT;    Filming is expected to begin next year, with Gibson directing
but not starring.
 &HT;    What else is Icon working on? Gibson laughs.
 &HT;    ``My favorite rumor concerning the company is that we're doing
`Braveheart II,''' he says. ``I will say, `Um, I died at the end of
the first one.'
 &HT;    ``Some people in Hollywood have said, `Mel, why don't you just
do a prequel?'''
 &HT;    Gibson shakes his head.
 &HT;    ``The truth is, at this point in my career I just want to do
whatever catches my fancy,'' he says. ``There are no rules. There
are no regulations. There is no map or a blueprint _ I don't do
10-year plans. I just want to do what captures my attention.''
 &HT;    It's an informal approach in keeping with Gibson's reputation as
one of the most down-to-earth Hollywood stars.
 &HT;    ``You just can't take yourself too seriously or buy into all the
hype,'' he says.
 &HT;    ``Fame reminds me of when I got sent to the principal's office
in third grade,'' he adds. ``I sort of liked it. I would walk
through the halls going, `Hey, I'm famous. I'm going to the
principal's office.'
 &HT;    ``Now I have that same feeling about fame,'' he says, laughing.
``It's like you're constantly being sent to the principal's
office.''
 &HT;    And, unlike many movie stars, Gibson doesn't have a riff about
how terrible it is to be a celebrity. He may resent the occasional
ludicrous rumors that circulate _ one had him dead in a plane
crash, another had him losing an arm in a motorcycle accident _ but
he isn't complaining about the whole package.
 &HT;    ``You know what?'' he says. ``Being a movie star is a good
gig.''
 &HT;    Especially when you can get away from it all when you want to _
and a ranch in Australia is a good place to hide.
 &HT;    ``I usually have two or three kids with me,'' he adds. ``We do
simple things like go out and check a fence. We feed the rabbits.
 &HT;    ``It's all about living a normal life.''
 c.1998 Cindy Pearlman  
<TEXT>
