<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SINGER-SHANIA-TWAIN-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHANIA TWAIN: COUNTRY FINDS A FRIEND 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of singer Shania Twain. 
 By KATHY HENDERSON  
 c.1998 McCall's  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sitting cross-legged among scented candles, Shania Twain looks
like a college student in slim, black-silk pants and a matching
shirt. But at 32, Twain has a lot on her mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have time to enjoy my success,'' she says quietly.
``I'm always thinking about my future.''
</P>
<P>
   And when she adds ``I feel as if I've lived three lifetimes,''
she isn't quoting from her new CD, ``Come on Over'' (Mercury
Records, 1998). She's had more than her share of tragedy. After a
poverty-stricken childhood, at 21 she took on the responsibility of
tending to three siblings when her mother and stepfather died in a
car crash.
</P>
<P>
   Yet perhaps her suffering has made her success seem sweeter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to cut this off short,'' she says of her career.
``This is a once-in-a-lifetime opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Twain came virtually out of nowhere _ Canada, to be precise _ to
achieve astonishing popularity: Her 1995 CD, ``The Woman in Me,''
sold 12 million copies, and her appearance at the Mall of America
drew 20,000 fans.
</P>
<P>
   Like other country superstars _ Reba McEntire or Dolly Parton,
say _ Twain owes her success, at least in part, to her ability to
connect with her audience by singing about their everyday concerns.
On ``Come on Over,'' she deals with jealousy, respect, abuse and
romance.
</P>
<P>
   But you don't have to be a country fan to hum these songs, and
that's the whole idea for Twain and her producer/husband, Robert
John ``Mutt'' Lange.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goal is to appeal to as many people as I can,'' she says.
``As a child I was influenced by the Carpenters as much as by Dolly
Parton.''
</P>
<P>
   Twain downplays the importance of her looks, though she was
savvy enough to call in the late film director John Derek, noted
for his depictions of beautiful women, and his wife Bo Derek, star
of the sexy hit ``10'' (1979), to photograph the cover of ``The
Woman in Me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a very ugly kid,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Even today, she adds, her glamorous image ``doesn't mean
anything. I don't need it to be satisfied.''
</P>
<P>
   The future musical star knew almost from the beginning what she
wanted to do with her life. Childhood photos of Twain reveal a
little girl _ named Eilleen Twain, incidentally _ with a huge
guitar propped on her lap.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad was the first person to show me a few chords, when I
was about 7,'' she recalls.
</P>
<P>
   Home was Timmins, Ontario, 500 miles north of Toronto, where
Twain's stepfather, an Ojibway Indian, and mother were raised. The
Twains married when Shania was 2, and she has had minimal contact
with her biological father since.
</P>
<P>
   Recognizing her talent, her parents would awaken the 8-year-old
at midnight and take her to perform at a bar after the liquor
stopped flowing.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's young, isn't it?'' Twain says. ``I was mature for my
age.''
</P>
<P>
   The little girl was paid $20 or $25 for her late-night
performances.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was gas money _ I never thought of keeping any of it until
I was about 16,'' she recalls.
</P>
<P>
   But Twain doesn't feel she was pushed too hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not as if I were a prisoner of my parents' dreams,'' she
says. ``It's something I wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   After high school, Twain supervised a work crew in her
stepfather's reforestation business for several months a year. She
spent the rest of her time on the road with bands.
</P>
<P>
   ``My parents were absolutely confident I would make it,'' she
says.
 &UR; A TRAGEDY PRODUCES STRENGTH &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Alas, the Twains were not to see their daughter's success. They
died suddenly in a collision with a logging truck. When Twain was
21, she assumed responsibility for her brothers, then 13 and 14,
and her 9-year-old sister.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't willing to let them be separated,'' she says, ``and
the only way they were going to be able to stay together was if
they lived with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Twain downplays the sacrifice she made.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was only for three years,'' she says, ``which actually went
by pretty quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   When her brothers turned 16, she adds, ``They were out of my
control, and I had my life back again.''
</P>
<P>
   Twain's sister is now a homemaker in Canada. As for her
brothers, the singer says only, ``They're still trying to figure
out what they want to focus on. I think it's going to take a long
time before they get settled in life.''
</P>
<P>
   Dealing with her parents' tragic death gave Twain the courage to
move to Nashville in 1990, three years after the accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being told no in my career,'' she says, ``was nothing compared
to what I had been through.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the first piece of professional advice Eilleen
Twain received was to get rid of her name. Still grieving for her
parents, she wanted to keep it.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, however, she recalled the first name of an Ojibway
wardrobe mistress she'd once worked with _ Shania, pronounced
``shuh-NY-uh,'' which means ``I'm on my way.'' It seemed fitting.
</P>
<P>
   She may have been on her way, but her debut CD, filled with
songs written by the leading lights of Nashville, flopped.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Mutt hadn't come along,'' she says, ``I don't know what
would have happened to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Lange was already a successful music producer who had worked
with such stars as Bryan Adams, Def Leppard and Foreigner. After
listening to Twain's CD, he asked to hear some of her own songs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then,'' she recalls, ``he said, `You need to record your
music.'''
</P>
<P>
   Six months later, in December 1993, they married. A year after
that, their first collaboration, ``The Woman in Me,'' took off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a spontaneous person,'' Twain says with a smile, ``but
there was no hesitation about marrying Mutt. We were both so
happy.''
</P>
<P>
   The 40-something Lange, who shies away from publicity, is
credited as Twain's co-writer on her recordings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We love writing together,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Given the couple's frequent work-related separations, though,
Twain says she's not surprised that tabloid-television shows have
been claiming that her marriage is in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's fabricated,'' she says immediately. ``We're very
happy.''
</P>
<P>
   The couple will be separated even more later this year, as Twain
gears up for her first international tour. Most of the time she'll
be traveling alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see each other, but he couldn't be with me all the
time,'' she says of her in-demand husband, who's now working with
Michael Bolton and the Backstreet Boys. ``He's busy doing his own
thing, which is great.''
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, after having served as de-facto parent to her
siblings, Twain is in no hurry to experience parenthood itself. And
she's getting no pressure from Lange, she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have enough time as it is,'' the singer says. ``It
wouldn't be fair to the child. Maybe we'll be ready someday, but
not now.''
</P>
<P>
   At the moment she's happy concentrating on her work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remind myself,'' Twain says, ``that if I don't get
everything possible out of my career, I'll look back with regret.
So I'm going to keep on doing what I do until people don't want me
to do it anymore!''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Kathy Henderson is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) &QL; 
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
