<SLUG> BC-DENNIS-QUAID-IN-EVERYTHING-THAT-RISES-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DENNIS QUAID STEPS BEHIND THE CAMERA 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Dennis Quaid with Ryan Merriman in a
scene from ``Everything That Rises.'' 
 By BONNIE SIEGLER  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    ``I was up at 7, got the cereal and fruit out, made sure he had
his vitamins, checked the lunch box, took him to school and got in
line,'' actor Dennis Quaid says, ticking off his morning with his
6-year-old son, Jack.
 &HT;    If this seems an unlikely agenda for Dennis Quaid, the Hollywood
wild man who battled cocaine and alcohol addiction during the 1980s
and early 1990s, who earned a reputation for on-set problems and
who vacillated between riveting performances and by-the-numbers
hack work, it still shouldn't surprise anyone.
 &HT;    Since marrying Meg Ryan seven years ago, Quaid has mellowed.
These days, he's taken firm control of a career which was
jump-started by ``Breaking Away'' (1978) and re-energized in 1983
by his role as cocky Gordon Cooper in ``The Right Stuff,'' before
bogging down in a sea of mediocrities spiked only occasionally by
strong performances in such films as ``The Big Easy'' (1987) and
``Wyatt Earp'' (1994).
 &HT;    The actor readily agrees that his career, like his life, had
lost its way.
 &HT;    ``I started to really lose it around the time of `Great Balls of
Fire!' (1989),'' Quaid admits, sipping his morning coffee at a Los
Angeles hotel. ``I lost where I was going.''
 &HT;    He pauses.
 &HT;    ``I like my life now.''
 &HT;    Credit that to a happy marriage and a beloved son.
 &HT;    ``We're not into all that Hollywood stuff,'' he says.
``Actually, when I'm filming, I miss the ordinary things of being a
parent. We're really into tee-ball right now. Tonight we're having
a first sleepover with one of the kids from school. No sleep
tonight!''
 &HT;    Quaid met Ryan on the set of their first film together,
``Innerspace'' (1987), but they became a couple only during their
second pairing, ``D.O.A.'' (1988). They married in 1991, after a
year's postponement while he went into rehab.
 &HT;    ``She stayed in there and stuck it out with me,'' Quaid says.
``It was a big test in life _ on me and on her and on the
relationship _ but we really loved each other enough to hang in
there.''
 &HT;    So gone forever are his wild-and-crazy days.
 &HT;    ``Thank God I didn't have a kid when I was in my party days,''
he says. ``It would have been impossible. I had all that. That was
another life. This is my life now, and I just embrace it.''
 &HT;    Emblematic of that life is his directorial debut with the TNT
movie ``Everything That Rises.''
 &HT;    At 44, Quaid is now playing fathers offscreen and on, both in
``Everything That Rises'' and in a remake of ``The Parent Trap''
(1961), due later this summer.
 &HT;    The former, premiering July 12 on TNT, offers the challenge of
directing, as well as a meaty role as an emotionally distant
Montana farmer, Jim Clay, struggling to hold onto his family land
while dealing with a crisis that threatens his family _ his wife
(Mare Winningham) and son (Ryan Merriman).
 &HT;    ```Everything That Rises' means everything rises and falls and
comes back up in life,'' Quaid says. ``The Clays can't afford to
live on their land because outsiders have moved into the area and
driven up the price of land. That's going on today in the same
place where we filmed the movie.''
 &HT;    Shot in 31 days _ ``we had 32 to do it in,'' the fledgeling
director says proudly _ the film was more complicated than Quaid
had expected.
 &HT;    ``Location scouting, making sure a shirt looks good against the
palette, casting ... I cast everybody, but I had no idea how to
hire an art director,'' he admits, laughing. ``All of a sudden
these art directors are coming in to have meetings, and I'm sitting
there with my mouth open _ I knew how to talk to actors, but art
directors?''
 &HT;    Originally written in the 1960s and set in Wyoming, the updated
script is set in Montana, a place Quaid knows well. He and Ryan own
a vast spread in Montana, including four sleeping cabins and a main
house, christened Camp Warren Oates, after the actor who sold them
the place.
 &HT;    ``I had been coming there for 20 years,'' Quaid says. ``Our
first location in Paradise Valley was two miles from my house. So I
knew that area really well: When the script called for a ravine, I
knew just the one. When I needed blue skies, fluffy clouds against
miles of nowhere, I knew where to go.''
 &HT;    Quaid also felt he truly knew the people of Montana.
 &HT;    ``That's why I chose this movie for my directorial debut,'' he
says. ``Directing had always been in the back of my mind, but it
was a question of finding material that would touch me deeply
enough to want to spend that much time with it.
 &HT;    ``When you just act, there's a lot of downtime,'' he adds.
``Directing needed all my attention and a lot of stamina. I was
amazed at all the minutia that goes into making a movie that I
really abhor as an actor. I became obsessed by it all.''
 &HT;    Set against Montana's landscape, the film's dramatic fulcrum is
a complex father-son relationship.
 &HT;    ``Certainly one of the themes of the story is this
relationship,'' the actor says. ``It's very central to what's
happening around them.''
 &HT;    Pushing his son to become a man, Clay lacks the skills to be a
skilled, nurturing dad.
 &HT;    ``Jim Clay has feelings,'' Quaid says in his character's
defense. ``All of us as parents _ and I'm in no way like Jim, but I
understand some things about him, like doing the best you can. I
see myself making mistakes, too. We're all sort of stabbing in the
dark as parents, sometimes.
 &HT;    ``Jim had feelings,'' he adds. ``He just didn't know he was
having them. Men of the '60s were shut-down men. They came out of
the era of the Depression, and times were hard _ your feelings and
kids weren't top priority.''
 &HT;    Born in Houston, Quaid had a much different real-life
relationship with his own dad, who died 10 years ago.
 &HT;    ``My father was a very affectionate guy,'' the novice director
recalls. ``Looking back now, I have so much respect for him, and
I'm so proud that he rose above his own relationship with his dad,
who was never around.
 &HT;    ``My dad was like a kid himself,'' he adds. ``Sure, he had his
own issues sometimes about expressing emotions, but he was real big
on the touchy-feely thing. I try to keep that going in my house _
lots of hugs and kisses going on. And my dad had a real sense of
humor.''
 &HT;    Besides instilling a sense of humor in Jack, Quaid also wants to
show him a sense of right and wrong.
 &HT;    ``Also that he can do whatever he wants to do if he applies
himself to it,'' the actor says. ``Feel good about himself _
self-esteem is a big issue. It's a big issue for us as adults,
too.''
 &HT;    Near the end of the movie, Jim Clay, after an emotional scene
with his son, says ``It's important to finish what you start.''
 &HT;    What does Dennis Quaid have to finish?
 &HT;    ``Besides everything?'' he says, flashing his trademark grin.
 &HT;    ``Parenting is an ongoing process,'' he says, turning serious.
``You just don't ever put that project down. There are times I'd
like to have a thought just to myself _ I need my 30 minutes of
privacy. But then I'm ready again.
 &HT;    ``Right now,'' he adds, ``I'm getting ready to star in Jack's
first directorial project, `Space Cases.'''
 &HT;    He pauses.
 &HT;    ``Great casting, don't you think?''
 c.1998 Bonnie Siegler  
<TEXT>
