<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIRSTEN-DUNST-IN-SMALL-SOLDIERS-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KIRSTEN DUNST: GROWING UP TO FACE `SMALL SOLDIERS' 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Kirsten Dunst in a scene from ``Small
Soldiers.'' 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 World rights except Chicago 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Anyone who saw prepubescent Kirsten Dunst passionately kissing
Brad Pitt in ``Interview with the Vampire'' (1994), or later as a
raunchy hooker frustrating saintly George Clooney on ``ER,''
wouldn't have her pegged as the playing-with-dolls type.
 &HT;    After all, she was tough enough to hold her own with Robert De
Niro and Dustin Hoffman in ``Wag the Dog'' (1997) and handle the
title role in the recent television movie, ``15 and Pregnant''
(1998).
 &HT;    But that's just one side of her.
 &HT;    ``I loved Barbie dolls, and I used to always wear these nice
little Alice in Wonderland costumes my mom bought me one year,''
Dunst recalls. ``I loved My Little Pony, Lady Lovelylocks and
Barbie dolls, and I watched `Full House' all the time when I was
little.''
 &HT;    The young actress's past and present collide in her latest film,
``Small Soldiers,'' opening nationwide on July 10.
 &HT;    A science-fiction action/comedy, ``Soldiers'' casts Dunst as a
kid from suburban Ohio who finds herself enmeshed in a war between
bands of new, high-tech action figures, toy soldiers with minds of
their own.
 &HT;    ```Small Soldiers' is basically a fun family film,'' the
speed-talking, effusive 16-year-old says by telephone during a
break from shooting ``Dick,'' her next film.
 &HT;    ``It's really for everyone,'' she says. ``There are so many good
comedians in it, like Phil Hartman and Jay Mohr and Denis Leary,
and there are jokes for all ages.
 &HT;    ``I'm the heroine, and I save my friend Alan (Gregory Smith) a
few times,'' she adds. ``That's good, the girl saving the guy for a
change. Actually, I save a lot of people.''
 &HT;    Nevertheless, Dunst spent much of her time on the film by
herself, acting opposite dolls that would later be added by
computer.
 &HT;    ``All of these things were attacking me, and nothing was there
to actually attack me,'' Dunst says. ``It was all up to me to make
it happen, to imagine these dolls crawling all over me, tying me
up, flipping me over.
 &HT;    ``I'd done `Jumanji' (1996), where I acted with nothing, but
this was different because they were supposed to be on me, all over
me,'' Dunst says. ``It was really weird.''
 &HT;    On a sadder note, ``Soldiers'' represents Dunst's third and
final collaboration with Phil Hartman, who died along with his wife
in a murder/suicide in May.
 &HT;    Hartman plays Dunst's father in ``Soldiers,'' after also playing
her dad in ``Greedy'' (1994). They also worked together on ``Kiki's
Delivery Service,'' a direct-to-video animated feature due for
release in the fall.
 &HT;    ``We got along well, and he was so funny,'' Dunst says. ``What
happened was such a tragedy, and I just hope his kids will be OK.''
 &HT;    It may seem odd that so young an actress could have done three
films with Hartman, not to mention movies with Tom Cruise, Kirk
Douglas, Michael J. Fox, Robin Williams, Brad Pitt, Susan Sarandon
and Wynona Ryder. Actually, though, the native of Point Pleasant,
N.J., is a grizzled veteran of sorts, having been acting for 13
years _ since she turned 3.
 &HT;    ``From that age to now, I can't think of anything I'd rather
do,'' she says. ``I have such a passion for playing all different
kinds of roles. I just love it so much. I can't think of any other
career I'd want to have.
 &HT;    ``I also want to direct and write and start my own production
company,'' she bubbles. ``I have one book that I want to turn into
a movie, so I already have things clicking in my head for what I
want to do.''
 &HT;    She may seem like a natural, but Dunst insists that she's worked
hard to get where she is.
 &HT;    ``If it were so easy more people would be doing it,'' she says.
``I work so hard to try to make it look easy. I've worked very hard
with my acting coach. I worked especially hard on `Vampire,'
because that was such a hard concept to get at such a young age. I
was only 10.
 &HT;    ``My acting coach helped me understand everything as much as I
could,'' she recalls, ``because you can't act what you don't
understand. That's what I think, anyway.''
 &HT;    At present, she admits, she's caught in an awkward niche, too
old for kiddie roles and too young for adult parts.
 &HT;    ``There aren't a lot of roles for young women my age that are
really meaningful,'' she says. ``Right now, I'd still say that
`Vampire' was my best performance. It was so difficult, and I love
to be challenged.''
 &HT;    The roles may not be as meaty as she'd like, but Dunst is
definitely in demand. Since wrapping ``Small Soldiers,'' she's
already finished ``Strike,'' in which she plays a girl whose father
divorces her mother to marry the mother's sister, and ``Dick,'' a
comedy/drama set during the Watergate era that co-stars Michelle
Williams.
 &HT;    ``The basic story of `Dick' is that these two young girls who
are kind of daffy and airheady end up as secret youth advisers to
President Nixon, and we see all this information that we shouldn't
see about Watergate,'' Dunst says.
 &HT;    ``People were telling me a lot about Watergate, because I didn't
learn about it in school,'' she adds. ``It's not important to my
character, because she's a bit of an airhead _ or to the film,
really, because it's more about my friendship with Michelle.''
 &HT;    Following ``Dick,'' Dunst shot a spoof entitled ``Dairy
Queens,'' and in July she'll be in Toronto to star in ``The Virgin
Suicides.'' A black comedy written and directed by Sofia Coppola,
daughter of filmmaker Francis Ford Coppola, ``Suicides'' will also
feature James Woods and Kathleen Turner.
 &HT;    Dunst relishes the diversity of her roles and projects to date,
but makes no bones about her eagerness to graduate to more mature
roles.
 &HT;    ``There are so many roles right now that I'd love to do that I'm
way too young for or that I'm just missing,'' she says glumly.
``It's hard to make that transition from teen-ager to adulthood as
an actress.
 &HT;    ``I played a street hooker on `ER' and was pregnant in `15 and
Pregnant,' but it's tough to be too young for something you want so
badly,'' she says.
 &HT;    ``I remember that I went in to read for `Romeo and Juliet' when
I was 13,'' she recalls. ``They just looked at me and said I was
too young. I had to accept that and think, `What's meant to be is
meant to be.'
 &HT;    ``That's how I look at things,'' Dunst says. ``I'll be right for
something one day, and someone else will be too young for it _
that's just how it works.''
 &HT;    Though Dunst aspires to stardom and a career like that of her
heroine, actress/director Jodie Foster, she says she doesn't put
any pressure on herself nor, for that matter, does she let anyone
else pressure her.
 &HT;    ``I'm doing this for myself and not for other people,'' she
says. ``Acting is what I love to do, and I just want to keep
grounded as I go along. It's nice if people compliment you, but you
have to know that's right in your heart.
 &HT;    ``My mom treats me like a normal 16-year-old,'' she says. ``I
have a very normal life at home, and I go to a regular school and
hang out with good friends.
 &HT;    ``So I just try to keep normal. I think it's working so far.''
 c.1998 Ian Spelling  
