<HEADER>
A3146 &Cx1f; tab-z
w l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WOMEN-VS-HEART-DISEAS     06-30 1558
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMEN-VS-HEART-DISEASE-LIFEBEAT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMEN AND HEART DISEASE: IT'S NOT JUST FOR MEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's LifeBeat
lifestyle package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to LifeBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing articles with color art.) 
 By GURNEY WILLIAMS III  
 c.1998 Family Circle  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Patsy Colley had no idea she was having a heart attack.
</P>
<P>
   The 51-year-old was the first up that Saturday morning. She
began making breakfast for her friends at a North Carolina beach
house.
</P>
<P>
   ``The nausea hit me when I was separating slices of bacon with a
fork and thought, `I can't stand the smell,''' Colley recalls.
</P>
<P>
   She told her friends that she felt sick, and her back ached the
way it had during labor 23 years earlier, when her daughter was
born. Late that evening she vomited.
</P>
<P>
   Her friends thought she had the flu. One gave her an aspirin,
which may have saved her life by thinning her blood.
</P>
<P>
   Most women, if faced with similar circumstances, wouldn't think
``heart attack.'' According to a recent American Heart Association
survey, only 8 percent of women realize that heart disease and
stroke are their greatest health threat. Almost two-thirds think
it's cancer.
</P>
<P>
   But cardiovascular disease _ an umbrella term for heart disease,
stroke and other blood-vessel disorders _ kills nearly twice as
many women as all forms of cancer combined. The toll: More than
500,000 women a year and, since 1984, more women than men.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's true that women are reasonably protected against heart
disease until menopause,'' says Dr. Michael E. DeBakey, chancellor
emeritus at Baylor College of Medicine in Houston. ``But then they
catch up with men very rapidly.''
 &UR; TAKING WOMEN SERIOUSLY &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Until recently most doctors weren't aware of the seriousness of
heart disease in women, says Dr. Nanette Wenger, professor of
medicine at Emory University School of Medicine in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Tody Berls, of Mobile, Ala., says that when she suffered chest
pains 19 years ago, doctors discounted her symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   ``They told me it was stress,'' the 51-year-old recalls.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors actually suggested she buy a new dress or ask her
husband to take her out to dinner. It wasn't until she had a heart
attack in 1988 that she got the treatment she needed.
</P>
<P>
   Recent studies show that emergency-room staff still don't
evaluate and treat women's chest pain as aggressively as men's.
Women are also less likely to get front-line medications such as
aspirin, which thins the blood, and beta blockers, which reduce the
cardiac workload.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the gender difference may be due to what Wenger calls
``information bias.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't done as good a job as we should in community
education,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, women may refuse tests or treatments more often
than men.
</P>
<P>
   ``And,'' she adds, ``women typically don't go to the doctor
until pain is severe and has lasted longer'' _ when they're no
longer likely to benefit from these drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Women also tend to come to ERs later in life _ a difference that
can change the way doctors handle their cases. On average, women
have heart attacks at 73, while the average male sufferer is 63.
</P>
<P>
   ``Older people's heart attacks are less likely to be treated as
aggressively,'' says Dr. Robert Jesse, co-director of acute cardiac
care at Virginia Commonwealth University's Medical College of
Virginia Hospitals in Richmond.
</P>
<P>
   This timidity results in part from fear of causing serious side
effects such as stroke, he says.
 &UR; FACING FACTS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Like so many women, Patsy Colley never worried about her heart
health _ nor about her smoking habit, her regular
sausage-egg-and-cheese breakfast or her exercise regimen, which
consisted of walking the dog.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of her getaway weekend, Colley promised her friends
she'd call her doctor. He discovered that she was suffering a heart
attack.
</P>
<P>
   An ambulance took her to Virginia Commonwealth, where she
underwent angioplasty. Doctors threaded a thin tube called a
catheter, to which was attached a tiny deflated balloon, through
her artery to the blockage. They then inflated the balloon, pushing
open the artery and restoring normal blood flow.
</P>
<P>
   Patients who undergo angioplasty fare about as well as those who
have bypass operations, in which surgeons reroute blood around
blockages with a blood vessel implanted from another part of the
body. But in as many as half of angioplasty patients, swelling at
the blockage site narrows vessels again, sometimes requiring
further treatment.
</P>
<P>
   To avoid that setback, Colley's doctors implanted three stents _
expandable, coil-like metal tubes _ to maintain the opening.
Research suggests stents provide added insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Over six weeks Colley recovered fully. She stopped smoking and
began eating less fat and taking daily walks, sometimes swimming or
riding a stationary bike as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``During heart attacks portrayed on TV, men grab their chests
and fall over,'' she says. ``It might not happen that way for you.
You've got to learn the signs and give up dangerous health
habits.''
 &UR; REDUCING YOUR RISK &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Both genders share many of the same heart-disease risk factors:
advancing age, smoking, a high-fat diet, obesity, stress, a
sedentary life style, high blood pressure, diabetes, high
cholesterol and a genetic predisposition.
</P>
<P>
   But women do face special risks. Here's what experts recommend
to counter them:
</P>
<P>
   + Get active.
</P>
<P>
   Research shows women tend to be more sedentary than men, which
is as dangerous as high cholesterol, high blood pressure or
cigarette smoking.
</P>
<P>
   Prescription: Get your doctor's OK to start an exercise program,
perhaps walking three times weekly for half an hour each time.
</P>
<P>
   + Keep blood pressure in check.
</P>
<P>
   Men are more likely to have high blood pressure before age 55.
Thereafter, though, women are more at risk.
</P>
<P>
   Prescription: If you're overweight, try to slim down. Exercise,
and limit sodium and alcohol intake.
</P>
<P>
   Getting at least 1,000 milligrams of calcium daily is still
recommended to keep blood pressure normal, but now Harvard
researchers have found potassium to be even more protective. Other
experts recommend a combination of these two minerals, along with
magnesium.
</P>
<P>
   + Don't smoke.
</P>
<P>
   Smoking is particularly dangerous for women who use
birth-control pills or who are on hormone-replacement therapy.
</P>
<P>
   Both can encourage blood clotting, but when either is combined
with smoking, ``the risk goes out of sight,'' says Dr. Gordon A.
Ewy, chief of cardiology at the University of Arizona College of
Medicine in Tucson.
</P>
<P>
   Smoking also makes the heart beat faster and harder, and can
damage arterial linings.
</P>
<P>
   Prescription: Particularly if you are on the Pill or HRT, quit
smoking. Ask a doctor about medical interventions that can help,
such as a nicotine patch.
</P>
<P>
   + Monitor your cholesterol.
</P>
<P>
   Women's cholesterol numbers tend to be low when they are young,
but after 45 they may rise. The average woman between 35 and 44 has
a total cholesterol level of 195 milligrams per deciliter _
anything under 200 is healthy. After 45, though, her level can rise
well above 200. After 55, more women than men have high
cholesterol.
</P>
<P>
   Further confusing the issue is HDL _ or ``good'' _ cholesterol,
which is beneficial to heart health. The latest research suggests
low levels of HDL are a stronger predictor of heart disease in
women than in men. Smoking and being overweight or sedentary can
reduce HDL.
</P>
<P>
   Elevated triglycerides, another fat in the blood, may also be
especially dangerous to women. And high blood levels of
homocysteine may encourage clogged arteries.
</P>
<P>
   Prescription: To keep cholesterol in check, exercise, lose
weight, quit smoking if you smoke and eat a diet high in fiber and
low in fat, particularly saturated fat. Recent research also
suggests that diets high in vitamins B6, B12 and folate reduce
homocysteine.
</P>
<P>
   + Consider hormone-replacement therapy.
</P>
<P>
   Before menopause, estrogen protects by keeping HDL levels up and
reducing risk of developing plaque _ fatty deposits that interfere
with circulation and lead to heart attack.
</P>
<P>
   Prescription: When you're approaching menopause, talk to your
doctor about HRT. The hormones may help protect against heart
disease and osteoporosis, but for some may heighten the risk of
breast or uterine cancer. You and your doctor must weigh all of
your risks.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Gurney Williams III is a free-lance writer based in upstate
New York.) &LR; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to LifeBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing articles with color art.) &QL; 
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-98 0009EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
