<HEADER>
A3147 &Cx1f; tab-z
w l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VACCINE-FACTS-AND-FAL     06-30 1582
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VACCINE-FACTS-AND-FALLACIES-LIFEBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VACCINATION: SEVEN MYTHS AND THE FACTS YOU SHOULD KNOW 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's LifeBeat
lifestyle package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to LifeBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing articles with color art.) 
 By LISA COLLIER COOL  
 c.1998 Child magazine  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Any parent has heard horror stories about vaccinations _ bad
reactions to shots, unnecessary and expensive treatments, even
vaccinations that caused the diseases they were supposed to cure.
</P>
<P>
   Such stories resonate, says Dr. Mark Sawyer, an
infectious-disease specialist at the School of Medicine at the
University of California at San Diego, but they don't really tell
much about vaccinations. The benefits far outweigh the mild risks,
he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Serious vaccine reactions are rare,'' the doctor says.
``Possible mild side effects, such as low fever and slight swelling
of the injection site, have to be weighed against the possible
risks of the diseases themselves, which can be very serious or even
fatal.''
</P>
<P>
   Overall, American children are better protected by vaccines than
ever. Since 1992, the immunization rate for children between 19
months and 35 months has increased from 55 percent to an all-time
high of 78 percent, according to the federal Centers for Disease
Control and Prevention in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Still, getting the right shots in the right sequence and at the
optimal time isn't always easy, especially since recommendations
change as new or safer vaccines become available.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, for example, the Food and Drug Administration
approved an improved vaccine against whooping cough that has fewer
side effects than the previous one. FDA approval of a new vaccine
to protect against rotavirus, the leading cause of severe diarrhea,
is expected this year.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a look at seven common vaccine myths, along with the
latest scientific information on the shots your kids need: &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; MYTH NO. 1: VACCINES CAN DAMAGE IMMUNE SYSTEMS OR CAUSE ILLNESSES &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Because the whole idea behind vaccines is to prevent disease,
they work to augment _ not damage _ the immune system,'' says Dr.
Celine Hanson, a clinical immunologist and director of the
immunization program at Texas Children's Hospital in Houston.
``When your child is given a killed or inactivated bacteria or
virus in a vaccine, his body reacts by producing antibodies that
will prevent the onset of a particular disease.''
</P>
<P>
   The myth that vaccines are dangerous originates with a small but
extremely vocal group of opponents, Sawyer says.
</P>
<P>
   ``CDC statistics show that 1 percent or less of Americans are so
strongly against immunizations that they ask for an exemption from
the vaccines that are mandatory before children can attend
school,'' he says. ``Some object to shots on religious grounds, or
believe their children have been injured by vaccines.''
 &UR; MYTH NO. 2: VACCINES CAN CAUSE SIDS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Most often, this claim concerns the DTP shot, until recently
recommended against diphtheria, tetanus and pertussis, or whooping
cough.
</P>
<P>
   But a study conducted in 1991 by the Washington-based Institute
of Medicine, a branch of the National Academy of Sciences, showed
no evidence of any causal relationship between the DTP shot and
sudden infant death syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   ``Simply by chance, some babies who get the shots may later die
of SIDS, but the events aren't connected,'' Hanson says.
``Similarly, some people who eat bread may subsequently crash their
cars, but the bread they ate is not what caused them to crash.''
</P>
<P>
   The overall risk of serious injury from vaccines is less than
0.1 percent, estimates Dr. Michael Marcy, professor of pediatrics
at the UCLA School of Medicine in Los Angeles.
 &UR; MYTH NO. 3: BREAST-FEEDING PROVIDES IMMUNITIES &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Breast-feeding is good for your baby and gives limited
protection against some diseases,'' says Dr. Jan Drutz, associate
professor of pediatrics at Baylor College of Medicine in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Your baby will probably have fewer colds and diarrheal
infections if she nurses, but breast-feeding does not inoculate
children against many serious illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Vaccines, unlike breast-feeding, give your baby systemic or
whole-body immunity to a particular illness, says Dr. Blaise
Congeni, director of infectious diseases at Children's Hospital
Medical Center of Akron, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are several classes of immunity,'' he says, ``and by
mimicking a real infection, vaccines may induce all of them. So
there's immunity to the disease in your child's bloodstream, her
lymph system and, in some cases such as the oral polio vaccine, her
gastrointestinal tract.''
 &UR; MYTH NO. 4: THE WHOOPING COUGH VACCINE HAS SERIOUS SIDE EFFECTS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A new pertussis vaccine, approved for use by the FDA in 1996, is
a significant improvement over the older DTP vaccine.
</P>
<P>
   The improved pertussis vaccine, DTaP, greatly reduces the
incidence of fever, fretfulness, drowsiness, vomiting and local
reactions such as swelling and redness associated with the old
vaccine.
 &UR; MYTH NO. 5: CHICKEN POX ISN'T FATAL, SO DON'T VACCINATE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Of all the diseases that there's a vaccine for, chicken pox is
the least severe, but it's not a totally benign illness,'' Sawyer
says.
</P>
<P>
   About 100 people a year die of it in the United States, and
thousands more are hospitalized with complications such as bone or
staphylococcal infections, pneumonia or toxic shock. These
infections can result when harmful bacteria enter the body through
the skin lesions that typically result from the disease.
</P>
<P>
   No serious reaction has been linked to a child's receiving the
chicken-pox vaccine since 1995, when it first became available for
kids older than 1 year, Sawyer says. The main side effect,
experienced by only a tiny percentage of children, is a mild rash.
</P>
<P>
   Although some parents worry that the chicken-pox vaccine won't
give long-term immunity, there's no evidence that this is true,
Sawyer adds.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vaccine has been in use in Japan for 20 years, and adults
there are not developing chicken pox,'' he says. ``Live-virus
vaccines _ like the one for chicken pox _ tend to induce very
strong, lasting immunity, so it's quite unlikely that the
protection would fade.''
 &UR; MYTH NO. 6: KIDS DON'T NEED A POLIO VACCINE ANYMORE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Because polio was eliminated from the United States by 1979 _
thanks to vaccines _ and from the entire Western Hemisphere by
1994, the need for a polio vaccine may soon disappear.
</P>
<P>
   But due to frequent travel between the United States and
countries where polio still exists, such as Russia and India,
Sawyer warns that ``an infected traveler could pass along the
disease.''
</P>
<P>
   Until polio is stamped out worldwide, he adds, ``it would be a
tragedy to stop immunizations and to put kids at risk.''
</P>
<P>
   To ensure that the polio vaccine does not itself cause the
recipient to contract the disease, in 1997 the CDC advised doctors
to switch from giving an oral polio vaccine, which carries a
1-in-750,000 risk of causing polio, to an inactive or killed polio
shot, which poses no risk. The oral form can safely be given for
boosters.
 &UR; MYTH 7: EVERY CHILD SHOULD GET EVERY VACCINE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Actually, there are a small number of children who shouldn't get
certain vaccines or who should have them later than usual.
</P>
<P>
   ``Children with AIDS or other disorders of the immune system
should not receive live vaccines, such as the chicken-pox or oral
polio vaccine,'' Congeni says.
</P>
<P>
   For children with seizures, the pertussis part of the DTP
vaccine should be delayed until the cause of the seizures is known
and the child has been seizure-free for six months.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, if there's a poorly understood neurological disorder,
Congeni says, some immunizations should be deferred until the
problem has been identified.
</P>
<P>
   If your child has a serious reaction to any vaccine, including a
fever of 104.9 or higher, seizures, limpness, shock, hives or
difficulty breathing, boosters of that shot should be avoided.
</P>
<P>
   But, barring any immunological impairments or a history of
convulsions or neurological disorders, Marcy says, ``vaccines are
by far the most beneficial of all medical procedures.''
</P>
<P>
   Illnesses such as meningitis, diphtheria and polio used to cause
tens of thousands of cases of brain damage, disability and death in
children each year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now they've virtually disappeared,'' he says. ``Making sure
that your child receives every recommended vaccine is the single
most important step you can take to get him off to a safe, healthy
start in life.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Lisa Collier Cool is a Pelham, N.Y.-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
