<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAUGING-VEGETABLE-YIELDS-LIFEBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PREDICTING YOUR GARDEN'S FUTURE: GAUGING VEGETABLE YIELDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's LifeBeat
lifestyle package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to LifeBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing articles with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of an assortment of peppers. 
 By SUSAN McCLURE  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you've ever been on the receiving end of an overly ambitious
vegetable garden, you may have had more than your fill of
boat-sized zucchini and buckets of tomatoes.
</P>
<P>
   But a vegetable garden need not be so excessively productive as
to exhaust its gardener. All you need to do is make a sensible
start with reasonable quantities of vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   With a little advance planning, you can anticipate the potential
yields of any crop and prepare the size of the planting
accordingly. New gardeners may want to begin modestly to get a feel
for how much food they can handle. Then you can add extra rows to
freeze, dry or can, or to give to nearby hunger centers.
</P>
<P>
   When estimating yields, think about the nature of the harvest. A
leafy green such as lettuce or Swiss chard can be eaten almost in
its entirety, little lost or wasted. Even in small spaces, a large
number of modest-sized lettuce plants can be grown.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, large plants such as rhubarb that need three
feet of garden space each while providing only modest-sized stems
for kitchen use are by nature inefficient. Squeezing 10 lettuce
plants into the same space is not at all difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Among the lowest-yielding vegetables are peas and lima beans. As
vegetables that need to be shucked from pods, they provide ounces
instead of pounds of food. You will have to grow considerably more
to have enough for occasional enjoyment by a family of four.
</P>
<P>
   Another variable to consider is the length of time you can
harvest any particular crop. Radishes provide a one-time harvest,
primarily during the cool weather of spring and fall, but can be
planted at weekly intervals during the appropriate season to
provide an extended harvest.
</P>
<P>
   Pepper plants, on the other hand, may start yielding peppers in
July and continue through October. A couple of plants may be all
that are necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Use the tips below as a starting point for your planting
estimates: &QL; 
 &UR; GAUGING YOUR CROP YIELDS: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   + Tomatoes: Three plants per person.
</P>
<P>
   Tomato plants tend to be big producers, and are particularly
reliable if you start with disease-resistant cultivars.
</P>
<P>
   There is some variation in the yield of different classes of
tomatoes. Beefsteak tomatoes, for instance, bear fewer but larger
fruit _ softball-sized tomatoes of a pound or more each.
</P>
<P>
   Cherry tomatoes are just the opposite: They produce hundreds,
even thousands of little, bite-sized tomatoes all through the
summer and into fall.
</P>
<P>
   Tomatoes classified as determinate, compact growers such as
``Celebrity,'' ``Floramerica'' and ``Daybreak,'' reach a modest
height and then produce their tomatoes all at once. Their harvest
season is intense but soon over.
</P>
<P>
   Indeterminate tomatoes, including most beefsteak and cherry
tomatoes, keep growing and fruiting as they grow, bringing in a
bigger harvest over a longer period.
</P>
<P>
   + Eggplant: Two plants per person.
</P>
<P>
   Oriental eggplant such as ``Millionaire'' and ``Japanese
Pickling,'' with long, slim fruit and purple, leaflike calyxes at
the top, may be only a quarter or a fifth of the size of large,
oval eggplants.
</P>
<P>
   But they may outdo classic types such as ``Black Beauty,'' which
typically bear four to six large, oval eggplants per year. In
contrast, Oriental eggplants are ready to cut earlier and keep on
coming to offer dozens of little eggplants in all.
</P>
<P>
   + Peppers: Three plants per person.
</P>
<P>
   Choose early-maturing, smaller-fruited types such as ``Gypsy''
and ``Jalapeno'' for the most reliable and abundant yields in
cold-climate areas.
</P>
<P>
   To encourage maximum production, pick peppers when young and
green, which spurs the plant to produce additional fruit. But for
fruitier flavor, forget about high yields and allow peppers to
ripen until they become red, yellow or orange.
</P>
<P>
   + Onions: A quarter-pound of sets for a family of four.
</P>
<P>
   The trick to getting a large onion harvest is to grow extra-big
onions. You need to get seedlings or sets into the soil at the
first possible moment in spring. This is when they put on the
vigorous growth that translates into huge bulbs later in summer.
</P>
<P>
   But because young onions can falter in cold early-spring
weather, cover them with a plastic or floating row-cover tunnel to
protect them until the weather becomes mild.
</P>
<P>
   Another way to maximize yields is to plant onion sets extra
thickly. Once the green tops stretch up tall, pull out the smaller
plants to use as scallions and leave extra growing room for the
remaining onions.
</P>
<P>
   + Beans: At least 36 bush-bean plants per person, or 15
pole-bean vines per person.
</P>
<P>
   Snap beans are productive and compact plants which, like
lettuce, can be densely planted in small spaces. However, they bear
the bulk of their beans within several weeks, yielding a
concentrated harvest.
</P>
<P>
   To extend the fresh-bean season, make several different
plantings two or three weeks apart in the early to middle summer.
Or plant pole beans, which need trellises to climb, but grow into
vines many times larger than bush-bean plants and produce beans all
summer.
</P>
<P>
   + Cucumbers: Three plants for a family of four.
</P>
<P>
   As long as cucumber vines remain healthy _ if protected from
cucumber beetles and resistant to foliage diseases _ they can be
big yielders. To encourage an extended harvest, pick cucumbers when
young, so vines will continue to bear new fruit.
</P>
<P>
   For an extended fresh-cucumber season, plant cucumber seeds
around Memorial Day and also several weeks afterward.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Susan McClure is a Valparaiso, Ind.-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to LifeBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing articles with color art.) &QL; 
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
