<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS RISE ABOVE INJURIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GORDON VERRELL  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ It occurred to Anaheim Angels manager Terry Collins
during an eight-game suspension that his team didn't need him much.
During his hiatus, the result of a bench-clearing brawl against the
Kansas City Royals, the Angels won six of eight games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just like the eight games before that. We won all eight of
them and I didn't do much then, either,'' Collins said. ``I just
sat there, watching, trying not to screw things up.''
</P>
<P>
   Not to worry. Collins, the second-year manager of the Angels,
didn't mess up a thing. In fact, the only ones who have tilted the
Angels' halo lately are the San Diego Padres. They won two out
three during the weekend, the first time in a month the Angels have
lost a series.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Angels have won 21 of 27 games this month and have a
2{-game lead in the American League West. It's the best month in
the club's 38-year history. And it's not over yet. Tonight, back
home in Anaheim, they'll finish off June against the San Francisco
Giants.
</P>
<P>
   And it's not that they are winning, it's that they are winning
despite a rash of injuries. The catcher is on the disabled list. So
is the second baseman. The right fielder is hurting and so are most
of the starting pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing new there, of course. All teams experience injuries. But
this? ``The DL is totally out of our control,'' Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   The team brought in rookie Justin Baughman _ he was in the
California League last year at this time _ to play second base. He
has responded with a .274 average, including four hits Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels also brought in inexperienced pitcher Jarrod Washburn
from the minors. The left-hander has responded with a 4-0 record
and a 3.38 ERA. The Angels have won all six of his starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Either they're good enough or they're not,'' Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   So what happens when the blissful month of June passes, in July,
and August, and September...?
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel we're going to be in the race,'' Angels general
manager Bill Bavasi said. ``We don't expect to run away with it and
we don't think anyone's going to run away from us.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the makeup of this team and because of some of our
starting pitching, that'll keep us out of any long losing
streaks.''
</P>
<P>
   Flash back to 1995:
</P>
<P>
   The Angels were humming along with a 10{-game lead in
mid-August. Then poof! _ two nine-game losing streaks in the final
47 games knocked them into second.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three of our four outfielders, our shortstop, some of our
pitchers... they were here then, they remember,'' Bavasi said.
``The word is `experience.' I sense our guys are very realistic.
They don't sugarcoat anything. They know it's a daily grind. If we
win, they enjoy it for a time, then come back the next day. If they
lose, they brood for a while, then forget it and come back the next
day.''
</P>
<P>
   Just like this past weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels were nearly no-hit Saturday _ the Padres' Sterling
Hitchcock beat them 5-1 with a two-hitter _ but Sunday, the Angels
battered the National League-best Padres 11-3, only the ninth time
in 39 games the Padres lost at home.
</P>
<P>
   Call it realism or maturity, but after Saturday's loss, Phil
Nevin, who broke up Hitchcock's no-hitter with a leadoff homer in
the eighth inning, said, ``For a month now the ball's been bouncing
our way. That isn't going to go on forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe not, but there's no denying the Angels are a force in the
American League.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started putting everything together,'' Collins said. ``We
pitched, we hit, we fielded. We got the whole package.''
</P>
<P>
   No, they don't have the whole package.
</P>
<P>
   A major part, right fielder Tim Salmon (.270, 15 home runs, 41
RBI), has been bothered by an injury to his left foot. He was able
to pinch hit on Sunday, his first appearance in six games, and will
probably be able for designated-hitter duties tonight.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, three-fifths of the starting rotation is on the
disabled list, although that, too, will change. Allen Watson, who
was placed on the DL on May 24 (tendinitis, left flexor muscle) is
set to return, likely tonight. But, Collins said, don't assume
Watson will immediately return to the starting rotation.
</P>
<P>
   All part of not messing with a good thing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
