<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 00:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3158 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-MARINERS-MESS-SPI     06-30 1690
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-MESS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINER MESS: BIG BATS NO LONGER MAKE UP FOR SHORTCOMINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM STREET  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The Mariners have tumbled from the top to the bottom
in the American League West this season because for too long they
defied a baseball bromide _ that superior pitching and defense win
pennants.
</P>
<P>
   The M's won two division championships the previous three
seasons while bucking the maxim, but their inconsistent pitching
and horrible defense have caught up with them _ translation: 34-48
_ this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``You might say that,'' right fielder Jay Buhner said. ``I've
always been a believer that pitching and defense wins games, but
over the past couple of years the mental aspect (of having to score
so many runs to win) kind of wears on you.''
</P>
<P>
   After 82 games this season, the Mariners are last in fielding
with a league-high 75 errors, and 10th in pitching with a 5.15
earned-run average. Such shortcomings were overlooked in 1995, when
the Mariners came within two wins of the AL championship despite
having the 12th-worst defense in the league; in '96, when Seattle
challenged for the division title with the ninth-worst defense and
11th-ranked pitching staff; and in '97, when they won the West with
a 12th-ranked defense and 11th-ranked pitching staff.
</P>
<P>
   While other postseason teams relied on pitching and defense,
offense was the name of the Mariners' game. And it worked for a
while.
</P>
<P>
   They sent baseballs over fences (setting an AL record last
season with 264 homers), scored more runs than anyone and captured
the fans' fancy, luring nearly 3.2 million spectators to the
Kingdome and another 2-plus million on the road. They were a
popular and productive team and fun to watch.
</P>
<P>
   Yet despite having their weaknesses exposed by the Baltimore
Orioles in the AL Division Series last October, the idea was to
allow the star-studded lineup _ five position players have All-Star
experience _ another opportunity to reach the World Series. Those
slick Mariner ads say you have to love these guys, but the win
column does not agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game plan was to keep the team intact and then try to add
to the bullpen,'' said Woody Woodward, the team's vice president of
baseball operations. ``We felt we had solid starting pitching. When
we took the field with any of those three guys (Randy Johnson, Jeff
Fassero and Jamie Moyer), we were always in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   As the M's approach the All-Star break this season, they still
are hitting a lot of home runs (127) and the bullpen is
inconsistent (14 blown saves). Johnson (7-6) only recently has
demonstrated the enthusiasm and stuff that made him the game's most
dominating pitcher this decade. Fielding miscues are almost a daily
occurrence, clutch hitting has been sporadic and home attendance
has declined 9 percent, from a 37,987 average a year ago to 34,540
now.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners lead the league in homers and runners left on base.
They also share the role of most-disappointing team with the
underachieving Baltimore Orioles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got some great players,'' manager Lou Piniella said. ``A
great shortstop (Alex Rodriguez). A great center fielder (Ken
Griffey Jr.). We've got some really good players, like Edgar
Martinez, David Segui, Dan Wilson ... and what we don't do around
them is a damn shame. I'd hate for this team's legacy to be, `a
damn shame.'''
</P>
<P>
   There are several factors for the Mariners' surprising demise
this season:
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)Management telling Johnson in November that his contract
would not be extended beyond this season _ and then failing to
trade him _ which backfired big-time. Johnson predictably went into
a mental funk that has damaged his performance and hurt team
chemistry.
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)The failure to address the obvious need of bolstering team
speed, especially in the leadoff spot. Second baseman Joey Cora is
a fan favorite, but he is not a prototype leadoff batter and is
making far too many errors.
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)Salary constraints prevented the M's from re-signing left
fielder Roberto Kelly, who made $750,000 last season and batted
.298 after being acquired from Minnesota (.308 in the playoffs). He
eventually signed with the Texas Rangers for $1.65 million.
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)Signing free agent Glenallen Hill as Kelly's replacement
was a good bargain ($300,000) but didn't solve the team's speed
shortcomings and added a third defensive liability to go with Cora
and third baseman Russ Davis.
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)The failure to upgrade the bullpen. The M's did not make
an offer to Randy Myers _ a Vancouver, Wash., native who saved 45
games for the Orioles last season and wanted to play for the
Mariners _ or Rod Beck, both available on the free-agent market. By
the time $3 million was added to the payroll, Myers already had
signed with Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   The M's then re-signed erratic Bobby Ayala to a two-year, $1.5
million contract and Heathcliff Slocumb to a one-year, $3 million
deal, giving Seattle the highest-paid bullpen in the majors. They
both have ERAs over 7.00 and have combined for just 11 saves.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shocks me that they are in last place,'' said Peter
Gammons, ESPN's top baseball analyst. ``I never thought the
pitching could fall that far, and one of my criticisms is they
didn't change the bullpen during the offseason. If they had signed
another closer, it would have given the team hope that things were
differing. Some new blood would have taken some attention off the
bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ``But now, it's almost like the team has been worn down by what
they knew what was coming in the first place: a questionable
bullpen and defense. Even when they are leading in the late
innings, you get a feeling that the other team is going to win
because of the bullpen. Teams get worn out when they have the same
weaknesses cropping up all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Signing free-agent first baseman Segui has turned out to be a
brilliant move _ he has provided superb offense, Gold Glove-caliber
defense and intensity _ but overall the lineup has not produced as
expected. Where has all the clutch hitting gone?
</P>
<P>
   ``We have had the men on base, but haven't done nearly as good
of a job getting them in as in other years,'' Piniella sad.
``Offensively, that is where we have struggled.''
</P>
<P>
   Piniella saw it coming.
</P>
<P>
   Two days after the Orioles eliminated his team, the most
successful manager in franchise history said the team needed some
offseason changes because the offense was too one-dimensional. He
said more speed and better situational hitting was necessary, even
at the expense of home runs. But small-ball never materialized. One
reason, as Buhner said, is that it is tough to think just one run
at a time when pitchers too often give them back in bunches.
</P>
<P>
   The batting order has remained practically intact _ except for
Segui at first and Hill in left _ but the production has plunged.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't manufactured runs the way good teams find a way to
do it,'' Pinella said. ``We have been a power team for the past
three or four years, but in prior years, we did a better job of
getting people in when they were in scoring position.
</P>
<P>
   ``The three-run homer is a thing of beauty, but when it doesn't
come, you need to get two-out hitting and situational hitting to
sustain your offense, and that is where we have struggled.''
</P>
<P>
   Consider:
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)The M's are batting .160 with the bases loaded and fewer
than two outs, compared to .477 last season.
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)The M's are batting .216 with runners in scoring position
with two outs, compared to .257 last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``My philosophy is when you are getting base hits and keeping
runners on base, it puts more stress on the (opposing) pitcher,''
Piniella said. ``There is nothing wrong with home runs, but they
usually end innings. If you can keep an inning going, it forces the
pitcher to throw more stress pitches, and two-out hitting is very
deflating to the other team. The pitcher has almost worked his way
out of the inning, and all of a sudden, he has given up two or
three runs.''
</P>
<P>
   Just the opposite has happened this season. An inadequate
defense has led to extra outs, extra runs and more wins for the
opposition. The bobbles have prolonged innings, forcing Seattle
pitchers to throw more ``stress'' pitches.
</P>
<P>
   Davis (19 errors) and Cora (13) are the main culprits. Piniella
says it is remarkable that a team that plays more than half its
games on artificial turf leads the league in errors. ``We're right
at the bottom, this year, last year, every year.''
</P>
<P>
   Seattle's Big Three pitchers _ Johnson, Fassero and Moyer _ were
right at the top of the big-league rotations last season, combining
for a 53-18 record. They are 16-17 this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pitching-wise, we probably are not closing the door early in
the games like we did last year,'' Moyer said. ``It seemed like
last year, when (the top three) starters would go five or six
innings and give up one or two runs, we would score five or six
runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like to make excuses and don't believe in them, but
the way things have gone this year, it's almost as though if we
don't have bad luck, we wouldn't have any luck at all. I'm not
whining or complaining because you can bang your head against the
wall and throw things all you want and it won't help.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone is frustrated, especially since there are such high
expectations. We're supposed to be winning, are trying our darndest
and still not (winning). Something is going to click. When, how and
why, I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Two things are certain: the pitching and defense must improve
for the defending division champions to have any chance at all of
spending September in a pennant race. But, aside from Johnson's
past two starts, there have been very few signs of a turnabout.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have good pitching and defense, you are going to be
in every game,'' said Rodriguez, who has combined with Griffey to
hit 59 home runs and drive in 137 runs for a team 14 games under
.500.
</P>
<P>
   ``Junior and A-Rod are having MVP seasons,'' Gammons said, ``but
it's going to be overlooked because of the team's performance.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
