u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-STARR-1STLD-W     06-30 1139
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-STARR-1STLD-WRITETHRU-840&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARGUING ATTORNEY-CLIENT PRIVILEGE, STARR AND WHITE HOUSE CHANGE
COURSE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs 1st and 2nd grafs for re-editing) (ps) 
 By STEPHEN LABATON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A discussion of the possible impeachment of
President Clinton served as the backdrop Monday to a historic legal
fight over the attorney-client privilege.
</P>
<P>
   Taking a page from the Whitewater independent counsel, the White
House argued that the potential impeachment of the president made
the privilege a crucial matter, while while the independent
counsel, Kenneth Starr, argued that the possibility of impeachment
was too remote to be considered.
</P>
<P>
   While the competing views put forward by the two sides in a
federal appeals court hearing Monday on the immediacy of
impeachment appeared at first-blush to be counter-intuitive, they
made sense in the framework of the legal fight that has arisen in
the Lewinsky inquiry over the parameters of the lawyer-client
privilege.
</P>
<P>
   The White House maintained that because Starr had recently told
the Supreme Court that he might file an impeachment report to
Congress, President Clinton was entitled to receive confidential
advice from his government lawyers in the Lewinsky investigation.
</P>
<P>
   But in an unusual twist, Starr walked away from what he had said
about an impeachment report, telling the three-judge panel that the
president was not entitled to keep the advice confidential because
impeachment was too remote an issue.
</P>
<P>
   The case focuses on the issue of whether Clinton can receive
confidential advice from government lawyers in a criminal inquiry.
Since both the White House and the independent counsel maintained
Monday that Clinton could use such lawyers to defend himself in an
impeachment inquiry in Congress, the argument focused in part on
the likelihood and timing of such a prospect.
</P>
<P>
   The White House lawyer, W. Neil Eggleston, contended that since
Starr had raised the prospect of an impeachment proceeding, the
president had every right to rely on government lawyers to defend
himself, as a matter of the constitutional principle of separation
of powers.
</P>
<P>
   As it became clear in the argument that the president stood on
firmer legal ground in a congressional inquiry, rather than in
grand jury proceeding, Starr told the appeals court there was no
need to consider impeachment issues. Instead, Starr urged the
judges to focus on whether they really wanted to put their
endorsement on the White House's position, establishing a rule that
every federal government lawyer would have a legal obligation to
forward evidence of a crime to investigators, except for White
House lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   The case arose when the president appealed a lower court
decision ordering one of his closest aides, deputy White House
counsel Bruce Lindsey, to answer questions before a federal grand
jury about conversations that he had with Clinton and other
witnesses, including Vernon Jordan, who helped Ms. Lewinsky to find
a job in New York. Clinton, Jordan and Ms. Lewinsky are involved in
the independent counsel's investigation trying to determine if
there was an attempt to cover up the President's relationship with
the former White House intern when her deposition was sought in the
sexual harassment lawsuit brought by Paula Jones.
</P>
<P>
   In the public phase of Monday's hearing, the judges sharply
questioned both sides, invoking lessons from the Watergate and
Iran-Contra scandals but giving few hints about their positions.
The panel, which also held a closed hearing on the more sensitive
grand jury aspects of the appeal, consisted of A. Raymond Randolph,
Judith W. Rogers and David S. Tatel. To each lawyer, Tatel asked
whether the President had any special rights to confidential advice
from White House lawyers in impeachment proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Eggleston, the president's top lawyer for privilege issues,
replied that ``in a run-up to possible impeachment,'' it was beyond
question as a matter of Constitutional law that the president
should be able to rely on the confidential advice of government
lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The independent counsel has said in his Supreme Court brief
that a referral of impeachment is certainly under consideration,''
Eggleston said. ``Impeachment involves an official function. It
would be incumbent on the President to defend himself if he
believes it appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   But Starr replied that the prospect of impeachment was too
remote a possibility to be considered by the court, and that the
judges should only focus on the fact that the White House was
seeking to limit grand jury testimony, not testimony in a
congressional proceeding.
</P>
<P>
   In a concession that surprised some White House lawyers, Starr
told the judges that government lawyers ``could actually represent
the president in an impeachment setting.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But that's not where we are,'' Starr hastened to add. ``It is
premature for this court to look down the road and look at
impeachment. It is beyond the compass of this case.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The position of the office of the president misunderstands the
vision of what it means to be a government lawyer,'' Starr told the
three-judge panel, citing a federal law that requires federal
employees to report any evidence of a crime to the attorney
general. ``If there is wrongdoing, it must be exposed.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Starr first raised the prospect of an impeachment proceeding
four weeks ago. In a brief asking the Supreme Court to bypass the
appeals court and take the case on an expedited basis, Starr wrote
of the urgency of a final decision so that he could quickly proceed
with possible indictments and possibly send an impeachment report
to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The court turned down Starr's request and suggested that the
appeals court consider the matter quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Under the independent counsel law, Starr must report any
``substantial and credible information'' that ``may constitute
grounds for impeachment'' to the House. The Constitution then gives
the House the authority to decide whether to recommend an
impeachment trial, which would be held in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The arguments over impeachment and the attorney-client privilege
were unusual in part because the Justice Department has broken
ranks with the White House, and in a friend of the court brief,
taken an intermediate position between that of the president and
the independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Starr has argued there is no privilege for government lawyers to
withhold evidence from a federal grand jury. The White House argued
that there is an absolute privilege. The Justice Department, in a
brief signed by Attorney General Janet Reno, asserts that there
should be a qualified privilege which a federal judge should
balance against the needs of investigators.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-98 0035EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980630.0014 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 00:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3162 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-LOCKOUT-SPI &LR;      06-30 1286
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LOCKOUT-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBA DECREES LOCKOUT A NECESSITY WITHOUT A HARD SALARY CAP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE Sonic center and dedicated Midwesterner Jim McIlvaine
undoubtedly will spend a good portion of his summer riding a
tractor mower in his hometown of Racine, Wis.
</P>
<P>
   But as secretary/treasurer for the National Basketball Players
Association, McIlvaine also will be wrapped up in the league's
labor strife. He and nearly 400 other union members have the money
and are ready to take on NBA commissioner David Stern with every
dribble and dunk in what promises to be a summer of hardball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, both sides consider how important the fans are in
this,'' McIlvaine said before last season ended.
</P>
<P>
   In announcing Monday that the NBA is locking out its players
until a new collective bargaining agreement can be reached, Stern
sounded anything but optimistic. The NBA is the only major pro
sports league that has not missed a regular-season game because of
a work stoppage.
</P>
<P>
   During a lockout, teams are not permitted to have contact with
players. Clubs are not allowed to conduct player negotiations or
hold summer camps. Players cannot use team practice facilities.
Athletes do not receive regular paychecks from their teams,
although players can hold scheduled charity games.
</P>
<P>
   The owners and players have almost three months before training
camps are scheduled to open. But both sides are so far apart on the
economic issues that the season is in jeopardy. The crux of the
labor dispute deals with revenue sharing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, there are a number of clubs that will do better
not operating than operating. That's something the players don't
yet understand,'' Stern said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Stern said the lockout was inevitable considering neither side
has met since an abrupt, 30-minute gathering last week.
</P>
<P>
   The owners voted 27-2 in March to reopen the collective
bargaining agreement because player salaries exceeded the agreed to
48 percent of basketball-related income. The league says players
earned roughly 57 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The owners are afraid that huge contracts for some players
threaten the league's financial health.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't afford to play the season under the current system.
That's just the reality,'' Stern said. ``Since the primary
beneficiaries of the current system are the players, the risk (of
not having a season) is the players', although there is a mutual
risk with the fans.''
</P>
<P>
   The lockout will begin at midnight Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The difference between this labor battle and the one that took
place in 1995 is the players are unified. There are no signs of
union decertification, and the players are primed for a fight.
</P>
<P>
   Players went into last season knowing the collective bargaining
agreement was going to be reopened in March, so the union asked
members to save part of their income to cover potential
unemployment. The 12-member Dream Team also was ready to pull out
of the World Championships next month as a protest against a
lockout. But USA Basketball replaced the NBA players with other
professionals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone, including agents, thought there would be a
divergence, but it appears everyone is on the same page,'' said
agent Steve Kauffman, a member of the agents' advisory committee to
the players association. ``Everyone feels they can't give back what
they already have.''
</P>
<P>
   It is certainly too early to determine which side has more to
lose. But the NBA, which has been a public-relations model for
other sports leagues, is gambling with its fan base.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both sides face fan reaction,'' Kauffman said. ``We saw what
happened in baseball. Who would have thought baseball would have
such problems and take so long to recover?''
</P>
<P>
   The Larry Bird exception has emerged as the key issue in the
labor war. That is the clause in the collective bargaining
agreement that allows a team to re-sign its free agents without
regard to a cap on salaries for the entire team. It is the primary
reason for the escalation in salaries, which owners say are
increasing at a faster rate than league revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the Bird exception, 24 of the league's 29 teams are
over the salary cap of $26.9 million. The Chicago Bulls were
already over the cap when they signed Michael Jordan to a $33.1
million contract. Last season, the Bulls' payroll exceeded $61
million.
</P>
<P>
   Miami used the Bird exception to sign Alonzo Mourning to a
seven-year, $105 million deal. Minnesota is paying Kevin Garnett
$126 million over six seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Owners want a hard cap without loopholes or clauses that allow
salaries to escalate. A team attempting to re-sign its free agents
would have to fit that player under the salary cap as it would
another team's free agent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've always had to be the ones to protect owners from
themselves,'' Houston Rockets free agent Eddie Johnson said. ``We
can't just keep giving back to help protect them from themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Stern's stance is that the Bird exception is affecting the
league more than individual teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're prepared to negotiate the percentage,'' Stern said.
``We'd like to agree to pay a higher percentage than the old one
that was promised. But then we'd like to pay no more or no less.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the league wants:
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)Marijuana added to the list of banned substances, and
mandatory testing for players, league and team personal.
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)The duration of rookie contracts, currently three years,
increased to five or six.
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)Tougher penalties for player misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   The union wants:
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)To reduce Stern's power to discipline players.
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)Licensing rights to the players association logo.
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)Teams to include revenue from naming rights for arenas in
basketball-related income, which would raise the salary cap.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the other things we could have solved without reopening
the agreement,'' said Russ Granik, NBA deputy commissioner. ``We
try not to focus on the Bird exception, but we need an agreement
that's not as open-ended.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made four different proposals. All of them involve player
salaries going up, just hopefully not as fast. The players made a
proposal April 1 and have not moved off that proposal.''
</P>
<P>
   The league and its union met nine times since the collective
bargaining agreement was reopened. The sessions ranged from three
to five hours. The league contends that since the 1992-93 season _
the year of its highest profits _ there has been a steady decline
in profitability.
</P>
<P>
   Stern claims 15 teams did not make money this season. The
players believe that number is more like five. (The Sonics made
money, but NBA owners historically do not reveal financial
records.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Some teams are losing money, but I don't think the league in
general is losing money,'' Jordan said. ``I won't accept that until
they open up the books.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no arguing that the league's revenue growth has been
strong. NBC and Turner Sports will pay more than double for the
next four years than what they paid for past rights to broadcast
NBA games. The league garnered $2.64 billion _ $1.75 billion from
NBC and Turner's $890 million _ over four years.
</P>
<P>
   If the lockout continues through the beginning of next season,
the contracts provide that both networks will keep paying the NBA
for up to a year. NBC and Turner would be reimbursed later by the
league.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nothing we look forward to and it's something we have
managed thus far to avoid in the ultimate losing of games,'' Stern
said. ``But if you don't face up to reality, then you can't have an
intelligent negotiation. ... We're not trying to run away from the
payment, but we need to slow the growth.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
