<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 00:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3170 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SORRY-CANDIDATE-LADN     06-30 0891
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SORRY-CANDIDATE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAD BLOOD CONTINUES BETWEEN DEMOCRATIC CANDIDATES FOR STATE SENATE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Will move in the ``n'' California news file.) 
BY RICK ORLOV  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _Escalating tensions in the 20th state Senate
District, City Councilman Richard Alarcon has issued a ``formal
apology'' for a controversial last-minute campaign mailer but
former Assemblyman Richard Katz flatly has rejected it as
insincere.
</P>
<P>
   Since winning the June 2 Democratic primary by 29 votes over
Katz, Alarcon has been trying to put the issue of the mailer _
widely criticized as false and racially inflammatory _ behind him.
</P>
<P>
   In his five-paragraph letter to Katz on Monday, Alarcon
continued to insist he had not seen or authorized the mailer and
complained that Katz's campaign literature was unfair and contained
false statements.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am writing to offer my formal apology,'' Alarcon's letter
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although I did not see or authorize the piece prior to it
being sent, I take full responsibility for it since it emerged
relating to my campaign. I realize the piece could have been taken
to imply you were somehow involved in the poll guard incident and I
know that you were not.''
</P>
<P>
   Katz refused to accept the apology.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nowhere in this letter or in any statements has Mr. Alarcon
condemned the contents of the mailer nor has he called to task
those individuals responsible for it,'' Katz said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Alarcon's letter is neither genuine nor sincere and I
cannot settle for anything less than an unconditional apology.''
</P>
<P>
   Alarcon has been under increasing pressure since the election to
disavow the mailing _ signed by state Sen. Richard Polanco, a
powerful Eastside Democrat _ in which Katz was portrayed as being
linked to a 1988 election effort by Orange County Republicans to
exclude Latinos from voting.
</P>
<P>
   The mailing arrived in the days leading up to the election and
prompted criticism from Jewish groups, such as the Anti-Defamation
League of B'nai B'rith.
</P>
<P>
   Although Alarcon had sought to distance himself from the
mailing, the Daily News reported last week that his campaign
consultant Richie Ross prepared the piece, which was paid for by
Polanco's Latino Political Action Committee but reported as an
Alarcon campaign expenditure because of Ross's role.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, Alarcon acknowledged that his campaign was
involved, but he continued to maintain he was unaware of the
mailing prior to its distribution.
</P>
<P>
   Katz said it was only because of public pressure that Alarcon
issued his statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Four weeks after the election, following four weeks of
community outrage and one day after editorials in the Daily News
and Los Angeles Times calling upon him to apologize, Richard
Alarcon has written ... to offer his formal apology,'' Katz said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Alarcon never acknowledges what the mailer was intended to
accomplish. Mr. Alarcon has made conflicting statements about what
he knew and when he knew it.''
</P>
<P>
   Alarcon indicated he believes Katz should understand how
elective politics work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Campaigns are tough,'' Alarcon wrote. ``With your 16 years in
office, you know that better than anyone. I think most candidates
try to abide by clean and fair tactics. I know I did in all of the
communications that were authorized and paid for (by) my
campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Alarcon has said he did not know until after the election that
the mailing was an in-kind contribution from Polanco instead of an
independent expenditure from Polanco's PAC.
</P>
<P>
   The difference is that campaigns for candidates are not to have
any direct involvement with independent expenditure committees.
Using Ross to prepare the mailing made it a direct contribution.
</P>
<P>
   Alarcon said he remained upset over Katz's mailers, including
one that used the phrase ```dirty' hands'' to refer to the loan the
councilman and his wife got from a developer-lobbyist firm for
their home. The mailer contained Alarcon's Social Security number.
</P>
<P>
   ``I must say though I was deeply offended and disappointed by
several of the pieces your campaign sent to voters, during the
course of this campaign,'' Alarcon said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most notably, the `dirty' hands piece which has personal
attacks on my wife and me falsely stating that we do not pay our
taxes and also unfairly linking me to (Councilman) Richard
Alatorre.''
</P>
<P>
   Alarcon said he was not requesting a personal apology from Katz,
but believed one should be given to his wife, Corina.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Alarcon said he and Katz should be proud of
the voter turnout in the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``More than 100,000 voters came to the polls, over 40,000 more
than in any similar election in the history of the San Fernando
Valley,'' Alarcon said. ``We should also not diminish the work that
is ahead of us, that is unifying the Democratic Party and our
community as a whole.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier on Monday, Katz appeared on a radio program during which
he insisted his own mailings did not have racist overtones.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I used the term `dirty hands,' that is an old political
term referring to someone who got their hands caught in the cookie
jar,'' Katz said. ``The difference with the Polanco mailing is it
was an attempt to use race as a way to excite a voting electorate.
It was race-baiting.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-98 0058EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
