<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 01:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3174 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WENATCHEE-VERDICT-SPI     06-30 1591
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WENATCHEE-VERDICT-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO CIVIL RIGHTS VIOLATIONS FOUND IN WENATCHEE SEX CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANDREW SCHNEIDER  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The jury in the first civil trial prompted by the
Wenatchee sex cases decided Monday that police, city officials and
state social workers did not violate the civil rights of eight
plaintiffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the Lord's will,'' Pastor Robert Roberson said to his
daughter, Rebekah, as the verdict was read. His wife, Connie
Roberson, hugged the 8-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   At 3:40 p.m. on the fifth day of deliberations, a buzzer linking
the jury room to the chamber of Superior Court Judge Michael
Donohue blared.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a verdict,'' the jury forewoman told bailiff Mary
McGarry.
</P>
<P>
   Within 20 minutes, the courtroom was packed, and reporters,
photographers, lawyers and court watchers filled the outside
hallway.
</P>
<P>
   Anxiety was thick inside. Thirteen weeks of trial and
deliberation had honed tensions to needle sharpness.
</P>
<P>
   At issue was whether police and state Child Protective Services
caseworkers encouraged children to falsely accuse the plaintiffs,
including Roberson, of sexual improprieties.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs argued that their civil rights and rights to fair
trials were violated and sought $30 million to $60 million in
damages.
</P>
<P>
   In the courtroom, everyone wanted it over, but it appeared that
no one really wanted to hear the words spoken. As jurors weaved
their way to their all-too-familiar seats, the only sound was their
footsteps on the dirty tan carpet. Spectators perched on the edge
of their seats. Lawyers on both sides looked pale. The only ones in
the room who seemed at ease were the Robersons, who were
plaintiffs.
</P>
<P>
   As Donohue read the verdict forms that the jury had completed,
Roberson checked off a sheaf of photocopies and everyone else
followed along.
</P>
<P>
   Were the plaintiffs' civil rights violated?
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' read the judge, in a firm but low voice.
</P>
<P>
   Was there malicious interference with a parent-child
relationship?
</P>
<P>
   ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   False arrest?
</P>
<P>
   ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   False imprisonment?
</P>
<P>
   ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   Negligence?
</P>
<P>
   ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   As the litany continued, each answer was the same.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers asked the judge to poll the jury, to see how
they voted.
</P>
<P>
   To each question, at least 10 jurors raised their hands. For
three of the charges, all 12 hands were raised.
</P>
<P>
   It was difficult to determine whether Robert Van Siclen, who
headed the plaintiffs' team, was more stunned than the three
defense lawyers, who showed no expression.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, the only frustration Roberson expressed was his
concern that the verdict might diminish the legal chances of others
swept up in the community-wide arrests in 1994 and 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope this verdict doesn't hurt Mark and Carol or the
Everetts. And what will it do to the 14 people still in prison? And
the other civil trials?'' Roberson asked of no one in particular as
he was surrounded by television cameras.
</P>
<P>
   He was referring to Mark and Carol Doggett and Idella and Harold
Everett, two couples whose criminal conviction is now being
reviewed by the state appeals court; and to at least seven civil
suits that are winding their way through the system.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs in the first lawsuit were: the Robersons; Honnah
and Jonathan Sims and their son, Daniel; and Donna Rodriguez and
her daughter, Kim Allbee.
</P>
<P>
   Only the Robersons were in court to hear the verdict. They were
accused of molesting and raping children in their East Wenatchee
Pentecostal Church of God House of Prayer in central Washington,
and were acquitted in 1995 on multiple counts of child rape and
molestation.
</P>
<P>
   Charges against Rodriguez were dropped after four of her five
accusers recanted.
</P>
<P>
   All these cases were spawned during a two-year period in
Wenatchee and East Wenatchee when 43 adults were arrested for the
rape and molestation of 60 children. Fourteen of those charged
remain in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Although investigators initially talked about a circle of adult
predators, they later admitted that a ``sex ring'' never existed.
</P>
<P>
   The label first surfaced in early 1995 in police reports by
Wenatchee Detective Bob Perez and in CPS episode reports and in
correspondence to and from Department of Social and Health Services
headquarters. However, they deny using the sex ring tag, and
instead blame it on the news media.
</P>
<P>
   In January 1995, soon after accusing her parents, the Everetts,
of nearly 10,000 counts of sex abuse, a 10-year-old girl named
Donna, who was a foster child in the Perez household, made
additional accusations to the detective.
</P>
<P>
   Donna said she had been raped or molested by almost every adult
she knew and the same had happened to every child she'd played
with, met at school or prayed with at Roberson's church. Three
months later, her 12-year-old sister, Melinda, parroted the
accusations and added more names to Perez's already long list of
targets.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs' legal team spent nine weeks challenging the
evidence that led to the Robersons' convictions, including the
testimony of both young girls.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the verdict we anticipated, and I don't believe it's
the verdict the evidence justified,'' said Ken LeMaster, a lawyer
on Van Siclen's team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the jury's opinion. We have to live with that. It seems
to me to be pretty clear that the evidence was there that there was
a lack of professional police discipline to the investigation
process _ a rush to judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   Defendants were the city of Wenatchee; its police chief, Kenneth
Badgley; and Detective Bob Perez; Douglas County and its sheriff,
Dan LaRoche, and two of his deputies, Robin Wagg and David Helvey;
the state's Department of Social and Health Services and its
employee, Tim Abbey, who is the CPS supervisor in Wenatchee.
</P>
<P>
   None of the defendants was in court Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the trial, the number of lawyers crammed around an
L-shaped table often outnumbered the jurors, but those standing to
do battle were usually Van Siclen for the plaintiffs and a trio for
the defense _ Patrick McMahon for Wenatchee, Stan Bastian for
Douglas County and Jeff Freimund for the DSHS.
</P>
<P>
   Did Van Siclen think that being outnumbered three to one made
the difference? No.
</P>
<P>
   The defense strategy that may have persuaded the jury centered
on the concept of probable cause _ that prosecutors and judges in
Wenatchee had been given evidence showing there had been adequate
grounds for the arrests.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probable cause, in the context of this case, means facts that
would cause a reasonably cautious officer to believe that the
person had committed the crime for which the arrest was being
made,'' said the instructions given to the jury.
</P>
<P>
   The instructions told the jurors that if they found there had
been probable cause for the arrest and prosecution of the
plaintiffs ``then your verdict should be for the defendants.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for both sides are interested in finding out what
arguments influenced the jury. But they must wait for jurors to
contact them voluntarily.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the jury agrees to talk to us, we should be able to
determine how much the probable-cause defense impacted the verdict,
if at all,'' Van Siclen said.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers had their own interpretations.
</P>
<P>
   ``This shows that the jury believed what Officer Perez did was
appropriate under the law,'' said Robert Sealby, who was one of the
team representing Wenatchee's defendants. ``This decision should
renew the public's confidence in the law and in Wenatchee's police
department.''
</P>
<P>
   Another defense laywer, Freimund, said: ``The jury saw the facts
as we believe them to be. That the people involved were doing their
best to find out what happened and did what they were obligated to
do under state law.''
</P>
<P>
   As he bounded down the stairs to leave the courthouse, Freimund
added, ``Vindication is a strong word. We are very pleased with the
outcome.''
</P>
<P>
   Bastian, who defended Douglas County, admitted he was surprised
at the verdict but said it was important because ``the reputations
and the very careers of people were on the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mostly, at least at this point, I'm just glad it's over.''
</P>
<P>
   But it may not be over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would be very surprised if we don't appeal,'' said Van
Siclen. ``There are a variety of issues that must be explored, but
first I've got to discuss it with my clients, my co-counsels and,
hopefully, we'll get a chance to talk to members of the jury.''
</P>
<P>
   With or without the appeal, another round is already scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   For participants in this trial _ judge, jury, defendants,
plaintiffs and their lawyers _ the past three months or more may
have seemed like a play that would never end. In reality, it has
just been the first of two acts.
</P>
<P>
   ``This portion of the trial has only presented half the case
against the state and Cindy Andrews,'' said Van Siclen, referring
to a DSHS therapist who treated several of the Wenatchee children.
``What they did to the Robersons and the Sims will be tried at a
later time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be the mostly the same witnesses, many of the same
questions and I'll probably get different answers, because they've
got a good idea of what I've got.''
</P>
<P>
   The reason this trial and the suit against DSHS were split apart
was a simple mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somehow in the rush to comply with Judge Donohue's request to
join the multiple actions, we dropped a paragraph, two short lines,
listing the actions against the state and Cindy Andrews, so we get
to do it all again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
