<SLUG> BC-SOC-SAMPSON-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. TEAM WAS OUT OF CONTROL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT FRENCH  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTPELLIER, France _ This is the way things work in the world
of international soccer: You win or you resign. And if you refuse
to resign, you're fired.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Sampson learned that lesson Monday morning, when he was
relieved of his duties as U.S. national team coach during a Paris
breakfast with U.S. Soccer president Alan Rothenberg. They are
calling it a ``resignation,'' but unless Sampson had a complete
change of heart sometime in the past week, that's just semantics.
</P>
<P>
   It comes as little surprise. Bora Milutinovic, Sampson's
successor, was fired _ officially, he ``resigned'' _ after the
success of a World Cup, although that was clouded by the
federation's stated desire for the U.S. coach doubling as technical
director, an idea that was abandoned once Sampson was in charge.
</P>
<P>
   Far different circumstances govern Sampson's departure and
that's a pity. In his three-plus years with the national team,
Sampson enjoyed greater success than any previous coach. He's
directed the team through a period of unprecedented on-field
growth, he _ like Bora before him _ successfully introduced a new
generation of talent to America's top team, and he opened a door
that had previously been closed to U.S.-born coaches.
</P>
<P>
   It's sad that there was no choice but to dismiss him following
the Americans' horrid World Cup experience, one in which they
looked like amateurs in losses to Germany, Iran and Yugoslavia. He
lost the support of veteran players such as Eric Wynalda, Alexi
Lalas, Tab Ramos and Jeff Agoos _ they claimed the coach sought
credit for everything his squad had done.
</P>
<P>
   Whether you believe the disgruntled players were upset in their
diminished roles or that the players were perceptive to realize
that Sampson had gone too far, there's a bit of truth in both.
</P>
<P>
   But what was obvious was Sampson lost control of his team during
the most important event of his tenure. For that alone, he had to
be dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, that is likely what he will be remembered for.
And it would be wrong to forget the positives, the wins of 1995
over Argentina and Nigeria and Mexico that forced U.S. Soccer to
make him coach; the successful (if difficult) qualification run for
this World Cup, in which the Yanks lost just twice, both times in
Costa Rica; and the phenomenal win over Brazil during the CONCACAF
Gold Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Sampson's teams were 26-22-14, the best record a U.S. coach has
ever posted, and he leaves it better equipped to compete at the top
level than it was when he took charge, no matter what occurred in
France.
</P>
<P>
   The job was never meant to be his. When Bora was dumped, U.S.
Soccer wanted a big-name foreigner, and Portugal's Carlos Queiroz
and Brazil's Carlos Alberto Parreira were offered the post. When
they turned it down and Sampson started winning, the federation had
to remove the ``interim'' portion of his title.
</P>
<P>
   No other American-born coach had held the post, a fact Sampson
took great pride in. He said, many times, that he was carrying the
banner for American coaches into the World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean an American won't take his place. D.C. United
coach Bruce Arena, although his arrogance has won him few friends
at U.S. Soccer, is a favorite. Rothenberg, whose tenure as U.S.
Soccer president ends in August, still could seek out a top foreign
coach. There's a lot of Nike and TV money in the federation's
coffers, and perhaps it will be put to good use.
</P>
<P>
   Queiroz, who was U.S. Soccer's technical director until a couple
weeks ago, would have been a superb choice. He won two under-20
World Cups with Portugal and is considered one of the world's great
tacticians. But he's now in charge of United Arab Emirates.
</P>
<P>
   Parreira is available _ Saudi Arabia cut him loose after its
first two World Cup losses _ and so are several others with Cup
experience.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his shortcomings and the team's failure in the World
Cup, Sampson has value. The perfect position might be the director
of Project 2010. Project 2010 was designed to help the United
States become a world soccer power within 12 years. It's a post in
which Sampson, who helped the U.S. take major steps toward that
goal, could succeed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
