<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-CHASS-COLUMN-665&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: NUMBERS SHOW INTEREST IN INTERLEAGUE GAMES
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Never have so many making so much lost to so many making so
little. It is, without question, the highlight of this season's
interleague schedule, the Montreal Expos' sweep of a three-game
series from the Baltimore Orioles.
</P>
<P>
   The weekend series was an encounter between a team with the
tiniest 1998 payroll, $9.2 million, against a team with a record
payroll of $69.2 million. In another venue, it might have been
called David against Goliath.
</P>
<P>
   The series and the outcome were hardly noticed around here, what
with all of the excitement generated by the confrontations between
the Yankees and the Mets at Shea Stadium. Who in New York, after
all, cared about a series between teams with losing records, clubs
that are no threats to the post-season plans of the teams that
lured 160,740 fans to Shea?
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Mets and the Yankees drew 168,719 to Yankee
Stadium, meaning 329,459 fans have seen the Mets and the Yankees
play six games the past two seasons. That number, then, will be the
barometer for the 1999 season because the Mets and the Yankees will
play three games at each team's home.
</P>
<P>
   The schedule is still in the discussion stages, but when it
becomes official, it will have the Mets at Yankee Stadium on June
4, 5 and 6 and the Yankees at Shea Stadium on July 9, 10 and 11. If
one series has been terrific, will two be twice as terrific?
</P>
<P>
   The home-and-home series are part of a a slightly altered format
for interleague play. When the interleague interlude in this
season's schedule ends on Thursday, each American League East and
National League East team will have played 16 interleague games.
Four of the five series were three games each, and one was a
two-game home-and-home pairing.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed 1999 schedule has 18 games for East Division teams:
the same four three-game series plus a three-game home-and-home
series. Thus, the Yankees and the Mets will play six games, as will
the other two pairs of natural rivals, Toronto and Montreal, and
Tampa Bay and Florida. Of the other teams in the East divisions,
Baltimore and Philadelphia will play six games, and so will Boston
and Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday was the designated date for management to submit a
schedule to the Players Association for its approval, but Monday,
management asked for and received a two-week extension. No matter.
The discussions that have been held indicate that the two sides
should have little trouble agreeing on an official schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Agreement will also mean that the two sides agree to extend
inter-league play. It has been an experiment the last two years,
and the owners and players must approve its continuation. The two
sides also will agree to continue the use of the designated hitter.
The owners had been muttering about eliminating the d.h., the most
expensive position they have, but they have made no serious attempt
to do it. They know the players would not agree to extend
interleague play if they were forced to give up the d.h.
</P>
<P>
   No overwhelming reasons have been presented to end the
interleague experiment; on the contrary, fan interest is generally
high, with even some so-called purists succumbing to the
attractiveness of some series. But not every matchup has fans
racing to the ticket lines. When Kansas City played a two-game
series in Cincinnati last week, the total attendance of 36,750
produced a lower average than the Reds had attracted for their
other games.
</P>
<P>
   The White Sox had a slightly higher average than their season
average for their three-game series with Milwaukee, but the total
attendance of 56,342 lagged well behind the 91,985 who saw a
three-game series between the Brewers and the Cubs at Wrigley Field
10 days earlier.
</P>
<P>
   But no matter what the schedule is _ interleague, intraleague;
interdivision, intradivision; East vs. East, East vs. Central _
some series simply will not attract fans. It is the upside, not the
downside, that management and union officials are looking at.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   And they can't get more ``up'' than the Mets and the Yankees,
with this year's series averaging 53,000 a game, last year's
56,000. So next season, they will try to duplicate both of those
numbers. The Yankees also will play three-game series at home
against Atlanta and Montreal; Toronto and Boston will visit the
Mets.
</P>
<P>
   The Expos will play in Baltimore next season, where more fans
will see them play one game than the teams drew in Montreal
(36,817) for three games last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Claude Brochu, the Expos' managing partner, was resigned to
seeing small crowds no matter who the opponent is. ``Our fans are
discouraged,'' he said Monday. ``It's going to be a tough year. We
just have to deal with it.''
</P>
<P>
   But the tiny crowds did not detract from the pleasure the Expos
derived from the series sweep over their wealthier partners.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels great,'' Brochu said. ``Whenever something like that
happens, I feel wonderful.''
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
