<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 01:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3191 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-DAY-2NDLD-WRITE     06-30 1012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-DAY-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-(950)2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICANS SEE LIVE ACCESS TO CHINESE TV AS HIGHLIGHT OF SUMMIT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: Subs 1st and 5th grafs for re-editing) (See also: CHINA-SUMMIT, CHINA-TRADE, CHINA-TV-COVERAGE,
CHINA-PEONY) 
(ps) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHANGHAI, China _ It was not until minutes before the Saturday
news conference by President Clinton and President Jiang Zemin that
Clinton was told that the event was to be broadcast live on
television.
</P>
<P>
   And Jiang did not inform the United States that he would permit
the broadcast of Clinton's Beijing University speech on Monday
until less than an hour before the address was to begin.
</P>
<P>
   American officials said Monday that they were elated at both
decisions, which had been a central demand of the United States and
gave an American President unfiltered access to the Chinese people
for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   American officials also said that progress at the summit on the
spread of weapons technology and the joint agreement not to aim
nuclear weapons at each other's cities were important, though
largely symbolic. It was the live television access to the Chinese
audience that made the summit meeting a breakthrough, according to
American officials.
</P>
<P>
   But American officials are still not clear why Jiang allowed the
wide dissemination of Clinton's statements.
</P>
<P>
   One theory they put forward to reporters as Clinton flew from
the Chinese capital to Shanghai was that Jiang used Clinton as a
sort of ventriloquist's dummy to raise the most sensitive topics in
Chinese society and then to defend his position to the Chinese
people and to reactionaries in his own government.
</P>
<P>
   Another school of thought was that Jiang knew how much the
American side valued access to the Chinese audience, and was not
willing to risk harming the relationship by denying that access.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no question that these decisions were made at the
highest level, by Jiang himself,'' said a senior American official.
``One can only speculate about his motivation. They recognized that
the price of engagement with us was giving us access to their
people. Jiang knew he needed to do that to make this a successful
summit.''
</P>
<P>
   It remained uncertain how deep or lasting an impact these events
would have on Chinese politics and society. Nor was it likely that
Clinton had silenced his critics at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real answer is going to come not from American officials,
but, of course, from the people of China,'' said Stanley Roth,
assistant secretary of state for East Asia. ``And we've seen
repeated quotes in the press from people indicating that it will
have profound reverberations from here. I think this will be
percolating within China for quite some time to come.''
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton's aides were unreservedly crowing Monday about the
``extraordinary,'' and ``historic'' summit meeting, and they
arranged a briefing for reporters by a senior official to talk ``on
background'' about all the 18 months of preparation Clinton and his
staff had made to pull off the event.
</P>
<P>
   The two-day meeting in Beijing was the fruit of a risky decision
in November 1996 to conduct reciprocal summit meetings in
Washington and Beijing without any conditions, and thus no
guarantee of success, the official said, giving this account of
what happened:
</P>
<P>
   The first of the two summit meetings, in Washington in October,
was judged a success by both sides. The meeting produced a handful
of substantive agreements, including China's pledge to stop sending
missiles to Iran and aiding Pakistan's nuclear program, and a
deepening of the personal relationship between Clinton and Jiang.
The two countries set up a bug-proof hotline between their
capitals, a link that was used for the first time in May after the
Indian nuclear tests. It was the first time that an American
President and a Chinese leader had spoken by telephone, according
to American officials.
</P>
<P>
   The atmosphere for the meeting in Beijing was more difficult,
the official said, with controversies swirling in the United States
over allegations of Chinese meddling in the 1996 Presidential
election and the suspected pilfering of sensitive American
technology through the launch of American satellites on Chinese
rockets.
</P>
<P>
   But administration officials turned the difficult domestic
climate to their advantage, according to an account by a
high-ranking participant. The crescendo of criticism and a series
of congressional hearings on Chinese missiles and money put Clinton
in a quandary. He could cancel the summit meeting _ as 151 members
of Congress demanded _ or he could travel to Beijing without any
assurance that the meeting would bring results.
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Berger, the president's national security adviser, went to
Beijing the first week of June with two messages for Jiang. He told
the Chinese leader that Clinton was ``unshakable'' in his
determination to make the summit meeting. But, he added, the
meeting had to produce a positive outcome or risk giving Clinton's
critics new ammunition and setting back United States-China
relations for months, or longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there was not a summit that moved the relationship forward,
it would feed the critics back home,'' a senior administration
official said.
</P>
<P>
   The discussions boiled down to one central concern on the
American side, which they believed would nurture the relationship
while quieting domestic critics: Clinton must have access to the
Chinese people, through television, radio and public appearances
that were not unduly restricted by the Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese leadership was noncommittal on the access question,
as well as the substantive matters still under discussion _ the
targeting of nuclear missiles, the spread of weapons technology and
human rights. Berger returned to Washington uneasy about the
meeting, then less than three weeks away.
</P>
<P>
   ``As always with the Chinese, nothing much happens before the
end game,'' a senior White House aide said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Berger's deputy, James Steinberg, flew to Beijing on June 22,
four days before Clinton was to arrive in China, to try to nail
down progress on the nuclear targeting plan and China's membership
in an international non-proliferation agreement known as the
Missile Technology Control Regime.
</P>
<P>
   After hours of word-by-word negotiation of the statement on the
missile agreement, Steinberg and his Cambridge-educated Chinese
counterpart, Yang Jiechi, agreed that the two nations would
announce that China would ``actively consider joining'' the missile
accord. American officials consider that a significant step that
will ultimately lead to China's acceptance of international rules
governing sales of medium- and long-range missiles capable of
carrying nuclear, biological and chemical warheads.
</P>
<P>
   The talks on the targeting of nuclear missiles went down to the
wire. On Friday, American officials expressed doubt that a deal
could be reached, because the Chinese insisted that the United
States renounce any first use of nuclear weapons, a policy change
the United States was unwilling to make. Agreement was finally
reached late Friday night, and was announced Saturday morning at
the news conference.
</P>
<P>
   One large question remained: Would Jiang permit the live
broadcast? Although American officials did not indicate in advance
that Clinton intended to criticize the Chinese crackdown on
pro-democracy protesters in Tiananmen Square in 1989, Jiang
appeared prepared for the rhetorical broadside. And he in fact
invited Clinton to respond to his comments on Tibet and other human
rights issues, rather than curtailing the news conference, as he
easily could have.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
