<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-MEXICO-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICO FALLS TO GERMANY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT FRENCH  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTPELLIER, France In the end, Mexico didn't achieve what it
wanted most, couldn't accomplish what had been thought impossible,
hadn't quite enough to turn this World Cup on its side.
</P>
<P>
   But in a heartbreaking loss to Germany in a second-round war on
a hot Monday afternoon at Stade de La Mosson, the Tricolor
demonstrating the spirit that has made it the surprise of France
this summer finally gained the respect it has sought, and that has
eluded it, for so many years.
</P>
<P>
   A superb Luis Hernandez strike and the prospect of another
almost had the Mexicans through to the quarterfinals before the
Germans, on goals by Juergen Klinsmann and Oliver Bierhoff, the
last in the 86th minute, pulled out a 2-1 triumph that left both
sides physically and emotionally spent.
</P>
<P>
   It was akin to a tussle between heavyweight champions, except
that only one of the combatants has ever won the championship. The
other, the Mexicans, has dreamed about the scenario, certainly, but
only in the last two weeks or so has it shown a semblance of the
fight, of the character, needed to do so.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the pride and the character of every player,'' said
forward Francisco Palencia, the Mexicans' best player until
departing in the 53rd minute. ``We weren't given a chance, but give
us the ball and we'll play against anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we came here with big plans,'' said Manuel Lapuente,
the Tricolor coach. ``We played very inspired, attacked a lot,
scored a lot of goals ... it was quite fun.''
</P>
<P>
   It was never more agreeable than after Hernandez, with his
fourth goal of the tournament, fired the Mexicans ahead just two
minutes into the second half. It was a lead that held until the
75th minute, long enough for the Tri to smell an upset, long enough
so that when the Germans, playing to their strengths, rallied for
the victory, the Mexicans thought it an opportunity lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we might (win),'' admitted goalkeeper Jorge Campos,
whose extraordinary performance his best of the Cup prevented
Germany from a romp. ``We had two chances to score the second goal,
but we lost them. If we had scored it is had been 2-0 it's a
different game.''
</P>
<P>
   Cuauhtemoc Blanco, who caused the Germans havoc all day on the
left wing, set up Hernandez's goal, bringing the ball across the
top of the box, then sliding it to his teammate. Hernandez, about
16 yards from the net, turned as he received the pass, stepped past
a sliding Michael Tarnat, and took off for the right post. He
eluded Markus Babbel at his heels, then fired across the goal and
past goalkeeper Andreas Koepke.
</P>
<P>
   It was nearly 2-0 a quarter of an hour later, after an insipid
Babbel pass in midfield left substitute Jesus Arellano with the
ball and an empty field in front of him. He raced to the box,
crossing paths with Hernandez along the way, then tried to shoot.
Lothar Matthaeus beat him to the punch, firing at his own goal in a
desperate attempt to clear the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Koepke got a hand on it, enough so to redirect it into the left
post, but Blanco tracked it down on the left side of the box and
fed Hernandez in the goalmouth. Koepke came up big again,
smothering the close-range shot.
</P>
<P>
   That, it turned out, spelled the end for Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goal was a shock, a real shock ...,'' said Klinsmann.
``But we play according to our strengths, our fighting spirit. We
keep going and going and fighting and fighting for 90 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must be tough, we must be physically prepared for the heat
in all the stadiums. We're not a Latin American team. We're not the
Brazilian team. That's not our mentality. We try to fight to
instill fear in the other team.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mexicans weren't afraid, but an error cost them one goal,
Klinsmann's, and Bierhoff scored on an extraordinary header to
finish them off.
</P>
<P>
   The first came after several strong German chances had failed,
the best a Bierhoff header that struck the underside of the
crossbar late in the first half, and occurred only after a crucial
mistake by defender Raul Lara.
</P>
<P>
   Dietmar Hamann sent a cross from deep on the right wing into the
box, where it cleared Bierhoff and landed at Lara's feet. His touch
deceived him, leaving the ball on the doorstep; Klinsmann dove at
it, knocking it past Campos.
</P>
<P>
   Lara was again the defender in the middle of the action on
Bierhoff's goal, which followed a nice sequence from Matthaeus to
Tarnat to Ulf Kirsten on the right wing. Kirsten then sent in a
fine cross, and Bierhoff with Lara marking him from behind soared
to nod the ball into the upper-right corner.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the Mexicans, Lara was most disconsolate when the final
whistle blew.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am gutted,'' he said. ``We were so close to qualifying.''
</P>
<P>
   The Germans, who will face Croatia or Romania on Saturday night
in Lyon their 11th quarterfinal appearance in the past 12 World
Cups were happy just to have survived.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a difficult game today,'' Berti Vogts, the Germans'
weary coach said. ``I don't want to go through another day like
today.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
