<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 01:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3201 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MIDWEST-FLOODS-ART-1S     06-30 1282
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDWEST-FLOODS-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-990&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STORMS CUT PATH OF DESTRUCTION FROM MIDWEST TO EAST COAST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs 5th graf to update number of dead or missing persons.) (ART ADV: Map has been sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(sw) 
 By PAM BELLUCK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nancy Wheeler was home in her trailer by a trickle of a creek in
Elkview, W.Va., when the weather hit on Sunday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't hear it or see it or nothing,'' Ms. Wheeler said.
``The water just came all at once. I got out of my trailer five to
10 minutes before it floated off. It just went right down the
stream and then busted apart.''
</P>
<P>
   But the storm that savaged the middle and eastern parts of the
country over the weekend and on Monday had worse in store for Ms.
Wheeler, 50, who has lived her entire life in this small town just
northwest of Charleston. As she rushed over to the trailer where
her son and daughter-in-law lived, the predatory current swept the
couple's four-month-old son out of his mother's arms. The baby,
Dakota Chyan Taylor, still has not been found and is presumed dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was up over my neck and I went under twice, and I was
looking for my grandson,'' Ms. Wheeler said on Monday from a school
where she and other families were being sheltered and fed. ``I
pulled myself up by some weeds and I lost him. I tried to look for
him and I just couldn't find him.''
</P>
<P>
   A maelstrom of wet and violent weather has lashed across the
Midwest, Northeast and Appalachian states in the last few days,
leaving at least 23 dead or missing. Floods wrought devastation
from Wisconsin to West Virginia, Indiana to Vermont. A tornado and
heavy rains battered Ohio. And lightning strikes over the weekend
killed a Maryland girl, a camper in upstate New York and a
56-year-old farmer in Meire Grove, Minn., who had been turning over
matted hay with a pitchfork.
</P>
<P>
   Rain also fell in parts of Florida, where Vice President Al Gore
was visiting areas affected by drought-induced wildfires that have
charred 237,000 acres since Memorial Day, and more rain was
predicted in coming days. But officials said that it did not appear
sufficient to offset the danger of further fires.
</P>
<P>
   In several states, including Ohio and West Virginia on Monday,
people braced for pounding from another storm predicted to pass
through Monday night or Tuesday. Meanwhile, across the region, the
National Guard and state transportation and emergency management
teams were searching for the missing, clearing out fallen trees and
houses, and trying to restore electricity and water to tens of
thousands of people.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a real toad-choker of a storm,'' said D.R. Smith, the
emergency services director in Wood County, W.Va., near the Ohio
border, where about two dozen homes remained completely surrounded
by water on Monday. ``It rained pretty doggone hard up until this
morning.''
</P>
<P>
   Floods dislodged about 35 mobile homes from a trailer park near
Parkersburg on Sunday, which floated away with about 80 people
inside them, Smith said. The volunteer fire department chased after
them on boats and jet skis, plucking people out while the homes
were sailing by.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the most devastation that this area has ever had, as
far as I can remember,'' said Capt. Larry Sims of the Muskingum
County Sheriff's Department in southeastern Ohio, part of an area
that got up to nine inches of rain Sunday and overnight Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The greatest death toll from the storms so far has been in Ohio,
with 11 people killed by floods or tornadoes. On Monday, Gov.
George Voinovich increased to 24 the number of central and
southeastern Ohio counties placed under a state of emergency.
Weather conditions were so bad that the governor could not even
visit some of the damaged areas on Monday, where 9,000 people have
been put out of their homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just recovered the last body five minutes ago,'' said
Sheriff Landon Smith of Noble County, Ohio, where six people died,
``five drowning victims and one from a tornado.''
</P>
<P>
   An elderly couple from Caldwell, Frank and Marie Hardesty, 90
and 89 years old, were killed when their home was ``washed away
with them in it,'' the sheriff said. ``The home was totally
destroyed. There were just pieces laying everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   A 71-year-old man, Edward Granger of Caldwell, drowned in his
car. And on Monday afternoon, authorities found the body of
31-year-old Michael Clark, whom they had been searching for since
Saturday night, when his wife, Brenda, and 6-year-old daughter,
Brittany, were rescued, after they were found clinging to trees.
</P>
<P>
   In four Ohio counties, public water systems were crippled and
the National Guard was hauling in water in tankers and bottles. In
the town of Cambridge, more than 200 residents of a nursing home
were being moved to a hospital for safety and the state mental
hospital there was being evacuated.
</P>
<P>
   In Vermont, where seething floods had pummeled mobile homes,
ripped through bridges and roads, and trapped people in trees and
on rooftops, Gov. Howard Dean declared a state of emergency in nine
communities in four counties and said on Monday that he would seek
federal help.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unbelievable,'' the governor said Sunday as he flew over
his state's midsection. ``The personal losses in these homes is
just terrible.''
</P>
<P>
   Hardest hit were towns in the Mad River Valley, where a large
music festival at the Sugarbush ski resort were called off, with
hundreds of concert-goers turned back by police at barricarded
roads. About a dozen roads were closed, including parts of Route
100, a major north-south artery.
</P>
<P>
   In New Hampshire, a man died after being sucked into a culvert
he was trying to clear of debris. In Wisconsin, a 35-year-old man
was missing after his boat stalled an plunged over a dam on Lake
Arbutus. In Minnesota, two were dead and one was missing. And three
people were dead as a result of weekend storms in New York.
</P>
<P>
   In Indiana on Monday, eight bridges in Owen County were
uprooted, causing an estimated $5 million dollars in damage.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But the Ohio and West Virginia communities along either side of
the swollen Ohio River seemed to suffer the most. In West Virginia,
floods and mudslides were so severe that the American Red Cross
opened seven emergency shelters in Wood, Jackson and Kanawha
counties for storm evacuees. Gov. Cecil Underwood toured the worst
areas and named 24 counties state disaster areas.
</P>
<P>
   In Clendenin, one of the hardest hit towns where nearly eight
inches of rain fell in two days, rescue crews in boats were
floating door to door on Monday, assisting or evacuating residents.
Kent Carper, a county commissioner in Kanawha County, said that 50
homes were destroyed, about 25 were severely damaged and about 15
bridges were submerged. On Sunday, a congressman, Rep. Bob Wise, a
Democrat, was trapped in his home for eight hours until the water
subsided.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ground is already saturated and the little tributaries
have nowhere to dump their water so they become rivers,'' Carper
said. ``It just wiped out houses.''
</P>
<P>
   It was in Kanawha County that Ms. Wheeler's grandson was pulled
into the vicious water. And a blind man in his wheelchair was
whisked off his front porch, where relatives had placed him while
they gathered his belongings and prepared to evacuate the house.
Another man suffered a heart attack in Clendenin and died because
an ambulance could not get to his house for nearly five hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is just horrible,'' Ms. Wheeler said. ``I lost
everything I had.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
