<HEADLINE>
LIBERTY BACK FROM DEAD  
 MERCURY'S HAGIWARA MISSES LATE TRY FOR TIE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ File the obituary for another day.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Liberty, conquerors of the Mercury in the 1997 WNBA
playoff semifinals, slowed the Mercury express on Monday night,
71-68.
</P>
<P>
   In the process, the Liberty officially established that a 1-4
road start was a fluke and that at 5-4, it remains a force in the
10-team league.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first three games, we were not ourselves,'' Liberty Coach
Nancy Darsch said. ``We had a lot of players who needed to remember
what a 40-minute game is like, what it feels like to compete that
hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix (6-2) saw its three-game win streak end before a
celebrity-dotted crowd of 12,683 at Madison Square Garden and a
national cable audience. The Mercury dropped a game behind Houston
in the Western Conference, but not to the chagrin of its coach.
</P>
<P>
   Beaming broadly, as if she knew a secret about the loss that
made it OK, Cheryl Miller gathered her team on the court for a pep
talk after Mikiko Hagiwara's try for a tying three-pointer just
before the buzzer missed everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was happy,'' Miller said. ``We had some points where we let
down with our intensity, and like any good team, they made a run at
home. I don't think it was lack of execution on our part or
anything like that. I just think they made made a run, and we
didn't. . . . We executed well down the stretch and got the shots
we wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mercury put together a 9-0 run to pull even at 64 with 4:35
remaining, taking the steam out of a 10-0 Liberty run. That made
model Tyra Banks and actor Gregory Hines, sitting two seats apart
directly across from the Mercury bench, and billionaire developer
Donald Trump and TV host Rosie O'Donnell squirm.
</P>
<P>
   Sophia Witherspoon, one of two 23-point scorers for New York,
canned a 7-footer off an inbounds pass. Then during a timeout,
Miller called a play for Bridget Pettis.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was our plan, to go one-on-one and kind of suck them
in,'' said Pettis, who put a between-the-legs, dazzling display on
WNBA Defensive Player of the Year Teresa Weatherspoon but missed a
short jumper.
</P>
<P>
   About a minute later, Witherspoon intercepted a Jennifer Gillom
pass intended for Michele Timms and took it for a layup and a 68-64
lead.
</P>
<P>
   Again, Miller called on Pettis, who had three 20-point games in
the past four but was slowed Monday after picking up her fourth
foul with 16:15 left. Her 15-footer against Weatherspoon rimmed
away.
</P>
<P>
   The Liberty pushed its lead to six when Umeki Webb slipped
trying to cover Vickie Johnson, and Sue Wicks hit the streaking
Johnson with an inbounds pass for an easy layup at the 1:08 mark.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson added a free throw, her 23rd point, for a 71-66 with 49
seconds left, then Miller and her staff almost worked coaching
magic.
</P>
<P>
   Going away from Pettis and to leading scorer Gillom inside, the
Mercury got two free throws with 35 seconds left. Weatherspoon ran
down the shot clock before whipping a pass on the wing to Johnson,
who traveled under Webb's defensive pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Pettis forced a shot just inside the three-point line with 2.8
seconds on the clock and drew a foul from Weatherspoon. Miller
already was substituting 6-8 Maria Stepanova to rebound an
intentional miss of the second free throw when Pettis, the WNBA's
best free throw shooter last season, bounced the first high off the
rim.
</P>
<P>
   Two Liberty timeouts later, Pettis purposely missed. Stepanova
rebounded and found Hagiwara on the right wing. The Japanese
three-point specialist had a good look but overshot the basket.
</P>
<P>
   ``She saw the defense coming at her, so she did ponder on either
faking or not,'' said Hagiwara's interpreter, Kyoko Takahashi.
``She wasn't sure if she had enough time to fake and shoot, so she
decided to shoot because she was bumped. She thinks she should have
faked it. She regrets that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mercury has a day off in New York, then travels to
Cleveland, where it resumes a five-game trip Thursday. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
