<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-LOCKOUT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STREAK OF NOT LOSING GAMES TO LABOR WOES AT RISK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The NBA imposed a long-expected lockout Monday, setting the
stage for a labor dispute that threatens the 1998-99 season.
</P>
<P>
   As of 9 tonight Phoenix time, the league will cease business
with its players.
</P>
<P>
   Trades and free-agent signings will be put on hold. Players will
not be allowed into arenas or practice facilities owned by league
clubs to work out or even to get medical treatment. No summer
leagues, no informal workouts.
</P>
<P>
   It will remain that way until a new collective bargaining
agreement is reached between the league and the National Basketball
Players Association.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations over the next several months will determine whether
the NBA can maintain its distinction of being the only one of the
four major professional sports leagues never to lose a game to a
work stoppage. Training camps are scheduled to open in October,
followed by the regular season in the first week of November.
</P>
<P>
   ``The current system does not work,'' Commissioner David Stern
said in a conference call with the media Monday. ``We can't afford
to play next season under the current system. That's just the
reality. That's why the owners elected to lock out.''
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of the dispute is the so-called Larry Bird
exception, which allows a free agent who has spent a minimum number
of years with the same team to re-sign with that club without
regard to the salary cap.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the Chicago Bulls paid Michael Jordan $33 million
last season. That's $7 million more than the cap for an entire
team.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the league maintains, players were paid about 57
percent of league revenue last season, while the collective
bargaining agreement was supposed to limit their share to 52
percent.
</P>
<P>
   But in the last negotiating session between the league and the
union two weeks ago, the players association refused to go forward
unless the Bird exception remains. That session broke off after 30
minutes, and no further talks are scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's important to note that just because we have a
lockout and that puts a stop to everyone doing business, that
doesn't prevent anyone from beginning to talk the next day,'' said
Suns President Jerry Colangelo, who is on the league's labor
relations committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now it's in the hands of the negotiators. The most important
thing, in my opinion, is that somehow, some way, people understand
the severity of the issue and the problem. And at some point, these
people will get together and try to resolve these things.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you break the logjam? That's the $64 question.''
</P>
<P>
   The logjam is substantial.
</P>
<P>
   The players don't want a hard salary cap and believe that the
owners have only themselves to blame for escalating salaries.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA never has lost a game to a labor dispute, but that could
change this time. The players union was divided into two factions
three years ago, when the last contract expired.
</P>
<P>
   A group of players, led by Jordan, New York's Patrick Ewing and
their agent, David Falk, did not support what eventually was agreed
upon. The owners didn't like it much either, and it included a
clause that allowed the owners to reopen negotiations this summer
if the players' share of revenue went above 52 percent.
</P>
<P>
   NBA Deputy Commissioner Russ Granik said in a conference call
Monday that the league isn't focusing entirely on the Bird
exception.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the last bargaining meeting, the union said that unless the
owners were prepared to agree to maintain the Larry Bird exception
as is, they had nothing further to talk about,'' Granik said. ``We
need an agreement that is not totally open-ended, and if there's a
way to do so that keeps the exception, or some elements of it,
we're prepared to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Also at issue are the rookie salary scale, which allows a new
player to become a free agent in three years, and the league's drug
policy, which does not include marijuana as a banned substance and
does not allow for random testing.
</P>
<P>
   Already lost in the dispute is a team of 12 NBA players set to
represent the United States at the World Championships. They will
be replaced by a team of Continental Basketball Association and
college players. Last week, union Executive Director Billy Hunter
said, ``I think we're in for a long summer.''
</P>
<P>
   After Stern and Granik made their announcement Monday, Hunter
said he hopes for a negotiating session in mid-July.
</P>
<P>
   Colangelo said he's aware of predictions that it will be a long
dispute.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to speculate what I think will happen,'' he
said. ``I've already been wrong once on this one. I thought there
was a good chance we could head it off.''
</P>
<P>
   Are the owners prepared to take the disagreement into the
season?
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say that the owners are prepared to do what's
necessary to correct the system because the system doesn't work,''
Colangelo said. ``I wouldn't go any further than that.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
