<HEADLINE>
DIA MONDBACKS WEATHER VISIT TO SOUTH BEND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By CURT RALLO  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTH BEND, Ind. _ Groundskeepers at Coveleski Stadium put in a
path from the pitcher's mound to home plate, just like the one at
Bank One Ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   Too bad South Bend also didn't copy the retractable roof.
Adverse weather forced officials to call the exhibition game
between the Diamondbacks and their Class A affiliate, the South
Bend Silver Hawks, after the Diamondbacks batted in the sixth
inning. The game ended in a tie at 4.
</P>
<P>
   Lightning caused a 31-minute delay, and the game was played
despite occasional rain and a tornado watch listed for nearby St.
Joseph County. Tornadoes were reportedly sighted in two adjacent
counties. Attendance for the game was 6,275, the 14th-largest crowd
in South Bend history. South Bend's all-time attendance record is
7,827, set on July 4, 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too bad we didn't get the whole game in,'' Diamondbacks
Manager Buck Showalter said. ``We'd love to come back here. To me,
it's an honor to play in these games. It's very convenient for us
since we're going to take the bus over to Chicago (for a game today
against the Cubs). What more could you ask than to play to a tie
with your farm team? Did you notice we didn't let them bat in the
bottom of the sixth, though?''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Osborne supplied thunder of a different kind in the first
inning for South Bend against Arizona starting pitcher Stephen
Randolph, who was called in from High Desert to pitch for the
parent team. Osborne crushed a three-run homer to center field as
the Silver Hawks jumped to a 4-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Jamie Sykes, who helped lead Valparaiso University on its
magical NCAA basketball run in March, opened South Bend's first
inning with a double. He scored on a single by Brian Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not every day you get an opportunity to play against the
big league team,'' Osborne said. ``Everybody was real excited. The
home run was an extra. It was just a fun day for everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Osborne, a catcher drafted in the third round in 1996, said he
hopes the home run signals a return to full strength after battling
thumb and elbow injuries this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt good swinging the bat,'' Osborne said. ``I'll be glad
to start catching every day. I feel like I've let the team down
when I just DH. I want to contribute behind the plate, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Arizona answered South Bend's outburst with three runs in the
second inning, two on Karim Garcia's towering home run to right
field. The Diamondbacks knotted the score at 4 in the fifth inning
when Damian Miller scored on a double by former South Bend star
Mike Robertson.
</P>
<P>
   South Bend right fielder Brian Gordon turned in the defensive
gem of the game, hauling in a rocket hit by Tony Batista as he
crashed into the outfield wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of the South Bend players were impressive,'' Showalter
said. ``I was especially impressed with (pitcher) Jeff Andrews. He
has a real nice sinker.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrews worked six innings and gave up four runs on 10 hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, the adrenaline was flowing,'' Andrews said. ``It
takes a lot for me to control it. Sometimes it can work against
you. I just tried to do what I've done all season, throw it down in
the zone. It was a great opportunity for me to face big league
hitters. It was a learning experience and an opportunity to gauge
where I am.''
</P>
<P>
   South Bend Manager Roly de Armas said the game was a success as
far as he was concerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank God we got it in,'' De Armas said. ``Everybody got an
at-bat. Our kids went right after them. They weren't
intimidated.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
