<HEADLINE>
POLITICS LARGELY OVER, CLINTON IN SHANGHAI TO SEE CHINA'S FUTURE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for further updating on Clinton's appearance on radio show;
re-editing throughout)   (See also: CHINA-DAY, CHINA-TRADE, CHINA-TV-COVERAGE,
CHINA-PEONY) 
(sw) 
 By SETH FAISON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHANGHAI, China _ With the issue-laden leg of his China trip now
behind him, President Clinton and his entourage came to the
country's most cosmopolitan city Monday evening.
</P>
<P>
   To put his finger on the vibrant pulse of modern China, his
aides said, Clinton will spend two days and three nights here
talking to regular people.
</P>
<P>
   Driving down the winding avenues of neon that advertise a
distinctly commercial sensibility in Shanghai, his motorcade went
from the airport to the thriving waterfront, the visual centerpiece
of any tour of this mega-city of 14 million, China's largest.
</P>
<P>
   A meeting on Tuesday morning with entreprenuers, community
leaders and homeowners in Shanghai was meant to accent the dynamic,
fast-growing economic side of China, though it veered off into
other topics from the law to religion. President Clinton also
assembled seven ``agents of change'' for a roundtable discussion at
the Shanghai Library and then appeared on a call-in radio show.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone understands there is a new China that is more
prosperous, more open and more dynamic,'' Clinton said. ``The
purpose here is to help me and my wife and the American people
understand the changes that are going on in modern China and the
challenges that are out there and what all of your are doing in
your lives to deal with those changes.''
</P>
<P>
   The group included a law professor, a consumer advocate, a
physicist, an economist and a bishop who spent years in prison.
Unlike two earlier addresses by Clinton in China, this event was
not carried live on Chinese television.
</P>
<P>
   The bishop, Jin Luxian, who is attached to a Chinese Catholic
church that is independent of the Vatican, appeared to surprise the
president with the declaration that he did not think ``belief in
religion'' was ``restricted in any way'' in China.
</P>
<P>
   Jin also said his church cooperated with the government. ``Why
should church believers do something against our government?'' he
asked. ``Here we adopted the policy of dialogue instead of
contending with each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who gave lengthy responses to many of the questions,
had no reply to Jin.
</P>
<P>
   Zhu Lanye, deputy dean of the international department at the
East China University of Politics and Law, told the president that
the state of the legal profession in China remained primitive but
had improved. Mrs. Zhu, who is in her 40s, said China needed to
train thousands more lawyers and persuade people to seek legal
remedies to their grievances with the Government or in the private
economy.
</P>
<P>
   Wang Xiaoying, 51, a novelist, said she had little trouble
getting her novels about family life published. ``The problem is
not getting novels published,'' she said. ``but coming up with good
ideas each day.''
</P>
<P>
   To address ordinary Chinese, Clinton also appeared on an
hourlong live call-in program on Shanghai Radio 990, the most
widely heard show in China, with a potential audience of 30
million.
</P>
<P>
   The government had resisted allowing Clinton to appear on the
program, American officials said. But last week the government
agreed to the appearance, considered by the White House to be an
important event because it allowed Clinton to speak directly to the
Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   Like talk-radio in the United States, conversations are
broadcast with a seven-second delay, but American officials said
the calls were not going to be screened for content.
</P>
<P>
   The questions were indeed wideranging, from the economy (``I
believe that China has done a very good job in holding its currency
stable and trying to be a force of stability during the Southeast
Asian crisis,'' Clinton said), to the World Cup soccer tournament
(``It's hard for me to predict, but I think the Brazilians are
pretty hard to beat.''), to his health (the president keeps in
shape on a mechanical stairclimber ``because it's quicker than
running'').
</P>
<P>
   The relaxed air of the radio show was reflected on Monday
evening as the president stepped out of his limousine at the
Portman Ritz-Carlton Hotel, on a busy street lined with crowds of
people craning their necks for a glimpse. Clinton waved to
acknowledge the cheers.
</P>
<P>
   Then he went inside for the evening, passing up the chance to
peek at Shanghai's boisterous night life at the bars and supper
clubs that self-consciously fashion themselves after the styles set
in the 1920s and 30s, when Shanghai was the most cosmopolitan city
in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   On Clinton's daytime itinerary on Tuesday and Wednesday are
three landmarks that have opened in just the last two years: a
stock exchange that is a leader technologically, a world-class
museum with inventive display techniques and the Shanghai library,
China's most modern.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's aides have portrayed his itinerary as one that traces
China's history. In Xian, the first stop, one sees relics of
ancient China; in Beijing, the largest icons of Communist China are
on view; Shanghai is clearly the most forward-looking city in the
country. Of course, that neat description does not account for
Guilin, the pleasure spot, or Hong Kong, which lie ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``In many ways, Shanghai is the future of China,'' said Mike
McCurry, the White House spokesman. ``The changes that are taking
place in China are reflected in the very dynamic growth,
economically, and the changes taking place in South China.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   To Shanghai residents, actually, the rate of economic growth is
palpably slowing. The real estate boom of the mid-1990s has created
a bubble of supply that seems poised to burst.
</P>
<P>
   In comparison with much of the rest of Asia, however, Shanghai
looks healthy. Round-the-clock construction continues on
skyscrapers throughout the city, if on fewer than before. The
unemployment rate is rising steadily, as state-owned factories
downsize, yet average family income is still climbing marginally.
</P>
<P>
   There are relatively few formal events planned during Clinton's
stay here, and officials doing advance work say that offers the
Clinton family the flexibility for shopping and walks, or quiet
time away from their 1,000-member entourage.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's itinerary includes only three events, leaving almost
the entire afternoon free for something unscripted. Wednesday's
plans are almost as relaxed. On Monday, after speaking at Beijing
University, the Clintons took it easy. They stayed in, at Diaoyutai
Guest House, playing cards and board games, McCurry said.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Rodham Clinton also has a handful of nonofficial visits
planned in Shanghai. To combine her interest in health care and
children's welfare, she is to visit the Shanghai Children's Medical
Center, a new hospital built by Project Hope, an American-based
foundation, and Shanghai's Second Medical University. It is the
first hospital in China devoted to treating children, and it was
created by nongovernmental entities.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was not in any five-year plan,'' said William Walsh,
president and chief executive of Project Hope, which has been
active in China since 1983, training and advising medical workers
in public health. ``It reflects the kind of volunteerism that is
starting to grow in China today.''
</P>
<P>
   It has also helped, Walsh said, that two of Shanghai's former
leaders who welcomed Project Hope here were later promoted to the
nation's top posts: President Jiang Zemin and Prime Minister Zhu
Rongji.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton also plans to visit a women's education and
training center and the Shanghai No. 3 Girls' School. On Wednesday
she will visit the Ohel Rachel Synagogue, originally built for Jews
who lived in Shanghai before the Communist-led army arrived in
1949.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton also joined her husband at the roundtable
discussion on Tuesday at the Shanghai Library. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
