<HEADER>
A3344 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-SHANGHAI-HNS &LR;      06-30 0811
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SHANGHAI-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE CLINTONS HOPE PERSONAL GLIMPSES OVERCOME CHINESE SUSPICIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHANGHAI, China _ President Clinton and first lady Hillary
Rodham Clinton treated a radio talk show Tuesday with details about
their personal lives in an effort the White House spokesman said
was designed to overcome any distrust by the Chinese public.
</P>
<P>
   The president talked basketball, workouts, golf and World Cup
favorites during a call-in radio program that is routinely heard by
10 million of China's 1.2 billion people.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was the first non-Chinese guest to appear on ``Citizens
and Society,'' a daily call-in radio broadcast hosted by Zuo
Anlong.
</P>
<P>
   ``People everywhere want to engage their leaders in dialogue,''
Clinton told the radio audience.
</P>
<P>
   The president took listeners on a tour of his personal
recreational preferences in response to a telephone call from a
university student who expressed admiration for the 51-year-old
chief executive's health, ``very nice figure,'' and ability to
maintain ``your energy in your work.''
</P>
<P>
   The student asked what sports Clinton likes to play; how he
maintains his energy and his prediction on the winner of the World
Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton recalled playing basketball in college and jogging for
almost 30 years for exercise before suffering a knee injury and
switching to a stair-stepping machine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do that quite a lot now because it's quicker than running,''
Clinton explained. ``And I play golf. I like golf very much. It's
my favorite sport. Even though it doesn't burn a lot of calories,
it makes my mind calm.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said after the program concluded, he realized that he
had forgotten to tell the student how he maintains his energy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just try to exercise whenever I can and get enough sleep and
keep my mind occupied,'' Clinton told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, conceding that he as ``not an expert'' in soccer, said
that the ``Brazilians are always hard to beat,'' adding: ``I've
watched them play a lot and they're very good.''
</P>
<P>
   White House Press Secretary Mike McCurry said the Clintons'
decision to offer the Chinese glimpses into their personal lives
was an effort to allay Chinese fears that the Clintons' nine-day
visit to China and Clinton administration overtures to China mask
some hidden, sinister motive.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese citizens ``are so used to leaders who have ulterior
motives that I think that both Clintons felt like if they could be
as personal as they could be, they would be able to breakdown some
barriers,'' McCurry said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   The Clintons decided to launch their personal charm offensive at
previously scheduled events after the president was questioned
about his sincerity by a student at Bejing University on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The student, expressing concern about possible U.S. efforts to
``contain China,'' asked the president if he had a ``hidden''
agenda ``behind this smile'' during his five-city tour of China.
</P>
<P>
   The president replied: ``The answer is no. I want partnership.
I'm not hiding another design behind a smile.''
</P>
<P>
   McCurry said Clinton mentioned the question several times in
subsequent conversations with aides.
</P>
<P>
   The student's inquiry ``really went to the heart of some of the
insecurities that Chinese people have,'' McCurry said. ``The
question was about what's behind your face and the Clintons felt it
had to be a very personal answer.''
</P>
<P>
   McCurry conceded that the gestures by the Clintons are ``unusual
for a Chinese audience because they're not used to hearing
discussions like this.''
</P>
<P>
   But McCurry said White House officials are hopeful that the
Clintons' efforts will help magnify the impact of the newly
jocular, confident relationship between Clinton and Chinese
President Jiang Zemin that the pair showcased at a 70-minute
nationally televised news conference in Beijing on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even when we're talking about fundamental differences, it's
not being done by us because we're trying to subvert their
government or produce some change or trying to throttle back
China's aspirations on the world stage,'' McCurry said.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton, participating in a round-table discussion with her
husband, expressed frustration at the constant public scrutiny and
criticism of her activities.
</P>
<P>
   She said it was a ``very unusual experience'' to serve as First
Lady, a role that draws so ``much attention for things that you
have no real conscious awareness or purpose for.''
</P>
<P>
   In another event that offered the family-oriented Chinese an
insight into the Clintons, the president took his daughter Chelsea
on an afternoon stroll through the picturesque old quarter of
Shanghai filled with Chinese shoppers and workers making their way
through a maze of streets lined with pagoda-style buildings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
