<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV02-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLUMNISTS AND TRUTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Thursday July 2)  
 By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The fact that a scandal involving a newspaper columnist in
Boston would hit as a national association of newspaper columnists
was meeting in San Diego is a small example of why you don't have
to make up coincidences in this business.
</P>
<P>
   Before coffee and even before name tags, word spread that a
Boston Globe columnist, a Pulitzer Prize finalist, Patricia Smith,
had been forced to resign for fabricating characters and quotes in
her columns.
</P>
<P>
   This was not only a story that fell right into our laps but
threatened to splatter all over us.
</P>
<P>
   Smith wasn't at our conference. More of us are writers from
medium- and small-sized papers. But waiting in the wings to be
first-up keynote speaker was Smith's colleague, Eileen McNamara,
also a Boston Globe columnist and last year's winner of the
Pulitzer Prize.
</P>
<P>
   There were actually three Pulitzer winners at this conference,
brought in as speakers, exemplifying the top of the craft. But
their job is no different from the rest of ours. The role and
responsibility of any newspaper person have nothing to do with
paycheck and name recognition.
</P>
<P>
   Eileen McNamara talked about the thrill of writing for the paper
she'd grown up reading, about creating a column in a hospital
waiting room while her mother was in surgery and going after a
baseball owner who hired a convicted wife beater. Sister Eileen
made you glad to be in her club and ended her talk with a back-away
grin, saying, ``I don't suppose anyone has any questions.''
</P>
<P>
   We had, of course, lots of them. But just as many for ourselves
as for her.
</P>
<P>
   Newspaper people know that we are not beloved. People are always
getting mad at the mass media and while we often jump in to
separate ourselves from that mass, protesting, ``We're print,
that's TV'' or ``You're thinking of the grocery store tabloids,''
we know we're often regarded with the same sneer.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago a friend and I were having a compatible lunch
until she brought up Clinton's shame, narrowing her eyes and saying
``it's all because of you people.''
</P>
<P>
   I told her I didn't start it and she asked if I'd written about
it and I said, ``Of course,'' and she said, ``See.''
</P>
<P>
   Columnists, who get to write with an edge and a passion, are
accused of being everything from male bashers to bleeding hearts,
often both, or Clinton-lovers to Clinton-haters, often both, of
being unpleasant, tasteless, too soft, too hard, PC and pithy.
</P>
<P>
   We get to play with the language and even contribute to it. Herb
Caen gave the world ``beatnik,'' Alice Kahn coined ``yuppie.''
Molly Ivins gets to call Texas politicians ``runts with attitude''
and Mike Royko snipped that Rupert Murdoch was an ``alien.''
</P>
<P>
   But we cannot make up subjects and give them our words to drive
home a point, any more than a cop reporter can put accusations in
the mouth of the chief of police to call the mayor a crook.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes columnists give subjects anonymity, as in ``A man
we'll call Harold...'' because that way Harold, who is really
Ronnie, gets to tell his story without repercussions from his boss
or ex-wife.
</P>
<P>
   We protect people but we don't invent them. Her name is false
but the homeless woman is as real as the sons she has in college
and the blue eyeliner she puts on every morning.
</P>
<P>
   When someone who has won prizes and been heralded as a bright
light in journalism gets hauled in for Oliver Stoning the truth, we
all wince.
</P>
<P>
   All that McNamara told us in San Diego about her former
colleague was that ``she is an extraordinary writer.'' Then she
noted, ``Great writing and great journalism aren't the same
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   McNamara said the Smith case and a similar discovery that New
Republic magazine reporter Steven Glass' sizzling scoops were full
of hot air ``brings home the need for all of us to be
accountable.''
</P>
<P>
   She said, ``Credibility is all we have.'' It is, she said, ``the
currency we exchange with the public.''
</P>
<P>
   There's something else going for the truth. It really is better
than anything you could make up. Even if you don't believe in the
ethics of truth-telling, any newsie knows that true stories are
wiser, goofier and more outrageous than fiction. Real human beings
are more colorful and naturally quotable than the creations of a
mere journalist.
</P>
<P>
   Our gift is that we know what to ask, when to listen and how to
recognize a gem of truth when it comes tumbling out. In a
reporter's notebook there is often a big asterisk next to certain
scribbled words. When the writer caught that quote she said a
silent ``thank you.'' Then she rushed it to print to preserve it,
so that someone else would read it and gulp or cry or smile or even
pick up the phone and say kill the messenger because it was so
amazingly true.
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Swartz is a columnist for The Press Democrat in Santa
Rosa, Calif. Her e-mail address is sfswartz(at)pressdemo.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-98 1012EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
