<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 10:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3430 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EVERGLADES-RESPITE01-     06-30 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EVERGLADES-RESPITE01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dryness a good thing for Everglades, scientists say
 &HT;    By Robert P. King
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ While the rest of us swelter, watch our
gardens wilt and ask when the rain will return, scientists are
calling the dry spell a blessing for the Everglades.
</P>
<P>
   After all, it was just a few months ago that El Nino-driven rain
was drowning marsh-dwelling trees and making life miserable for
wading birds. The dry skies offer a chance to breathe _ and breed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know with the lower water, the healing will begin,'' said
Herb Zebuth, a coordinator for the state Department of
Environmental Protection's West Palm Beach office. ``And for that,
we're grateful.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Anderson, a wildlife biologist for the Florida Game and
Fresh Water Fish Commission, added: ``We needed something like
this.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact is, the Everglades still is not exactly bone-dry. Lake
Okeechobee, the heart of South Florida's water system, is a foot
higher than average for this time of year.
</P>
<P>
   But they're both drier than they were this winter, when the
lake's overflow was fouling the St. Lucie and Indian rivers while
water managers fretted that protective dikes might burst.
</P>
<P>
   The drying helps in many ways.
</P>
<P>
   Receding water creates smaller and smaller pools for the
Everglades' fish, frogs and other tiny creatures _ producing a
concentrated smorgasbord for wading birds.
</P>
<P>
   The handy food supply lets many birds continue nesting past the
beginning of June, when the rainy season normally makes them
abandon their nests. The birds must make up for lost time this year
because the winter rains kept many from nesting earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The dry period may have saved a colony of wood storks in
Everglades National Park, said John Ogden, a biologist for the
South Florida Water Management District. He said they didn't even
start forming nests until late May.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had no chance at all of survival, except that it hasn't
rained,'' Ogden said.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, willows that grow on teardrop-shaped islands in the
Everglades have wilted from too much water in recent years. Now
they might have a chance to revive, Anderson said.
</P>
<P>
   In Lake Okeechobee, water is dropping enough to help the lake's
fringe marshes, which filter pollution and offer crucial habitat to
birds and fish, Zebuth said. He said years of high lake levels have
drowned those marshes, spread pollution and helped noxious hydrilla
weeds to migrate.
</P>
<P>
   The lake was at 14.69 feet above sea level Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The dry spell is proving far less benign elsewhere in the state,
where it's contributing to a spree of wildfires. Even in the
Everglades, a severe drought could lead to catastrophic fires that
would hurt plants and animals by burning away the muck soil.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the drought was extended to next year or March, then we
could possibly have a problem with muck fires,'' Anderson said. For
now, ``we're not too concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   Scientists around the state don't know yet whether the fires
have caused lasting environmental harm, said Nick Wiley, the game
commission's wildlife management bureau chief.
</P>
<P>
   Fire is part of nature's cycle, and native plants and animals
are adapted to it. Animals seek water or burrow in the ground.
Native slash pines and longleaf pines have bark that can withstand
the heat, and they grow their limbs above most fires.
</P>
<P>
   ``In fire-tolerant habitats, fire is beneficial,'' Wiley said.
``In a few weeks you see fresh, green growth. Everything renews.''
</P>
<P>
   But much of Florida is far from natural.
</P>
<P>
   Some places have gone too long without fire, which means
underbrush and other kindling have built up. So when a fire finally
strikes _ boom! Then it can be hot enough to penetrate the bark and
kill the trees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably the worst fires are in areas that haven't been burned
recently,'' Wiley said.
</P>
<P>
   To reduce the danger, he said, the state tries to conduct
controlled burns on all of its lands an average of every two to
three years. But not all landowners follow suit.
</P>
<P>
   Paradoxically, fire also helps the spread of some noxious pest
plants, such as the melaleuca tree. Another exotic pest, the Old
World climbing fern, makes fires more damaging by helping them
spread to treetops.
</P>
<P>
   Robert P. King writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-98 1052EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980630.0043 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 10:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3431 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PENNYFLETCHER01-TAKE1     06-30 1810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PENNYFLETCHER01-TAKE1-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dream cruise became a Caribbean nightmare
 &HT;    (In two takes _ take 1)
 &HT;    By D.L. Stewart
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   XENIA, Ohio _ If they had to die, Penny and Jim Fletcher
resolved, it would not be at the end of a hangman's rope.
</P>
<P>
   They would go by their own hands, using the prison-issued Valium
they had been hiding ``anywhere we could.'' Pills hoarded as a
death-insurance policy in the event a judge on the Caribbean island
sentenced them to be executed for the murder of a water-taxi
driver.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were going to kill ourselves that day had we been
convicted,'' Penny Fletcher says. ``We talked about it. I would die
at my own hand before I would let these people put me in a noose.''
</P>
<P>
   The Huntington, W.Va., couple knew that the sentences would be
appealed. But the appeal process, their lawyers told them, could
take as long as four years on St. Vincent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think either one of us would have lived that long,''
Penny Fletcher says now.
</P>
<P>
   As it was, they spent 283 days in Her Majesty's aged prisons.
Nine months of sharing cells with killers and drug dealers, rats
and roaches and scorpions. Nine months of living on bread and water
and rice. Nine months of not knowing if they would ever again see
their homes, their families or even the sunshine.
</P>
<P>
   Nine months of what Jim Fletcher would call ``our season in
hell.''
</P>
<P>
   Nightmare over and over
</P>
<P>
   The island's prime minister branded them ``classic ugly
Americans.'' Their home-state newspaper described them as ``rich,
loud and boorish.'' Most of the stories written about them included
accounts of boozing and brawling, with innuendos of drugs and
promiscuity.
</P>
<P>
   Penny Fletcher listens to these indictments without visible
reaction. She has heard them before and her response is
unhesitating.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guilty,'' she says. ``We knew exactly what we were.''
</P>
<P>
   Tanned and slender now, 36-year-old Penny Fletcher bears faint
resemblance to the pale, puffy woman who spent nine months in a
Caribbean prison. The physical reminders of her season in hell are
gone.
</P>
<P>
   But Midwestern sunshine and a healthful diet have not driven
away the nightmare that comes every night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't sleep,'' she says, pausing to light one of the dozen
cigarettes she smokes during a two-hour interview. ``I can't sleep.
I can't even put my head down because I know it's going to
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   She declines to describe it, but the nightmare is ``the same
one, over and over.'' The same one that followed her from a dank
prison cell in St. Vincent to her comfortable home in Huntington.
And now it is her nightly visitor in Xenia.
</P>
<P>
   Penny Fletcher is there for an extended visit with her sister,
hoping that time in the peaceful Ohio setting will help exorcise
the tropical demons that already have taken away a year of her
life.
</P>
<P>
   Setting sail with hope
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes it is difficult to tell where Penny Fletcher's real
life ends and the movie of the week begins.
</P>
<P>
   She is the second of three children born to an Olive Hill, Ky.,
retired naval officer and his wife. She married for the first time
at 21, a marriage that took her to Huntington, produced a daughter
and a son, and ended after five years.
</P>
<P>
   In Huntington she was politically active, eventually becoming
president of West Virginians for Life. It's also where she met
James Fletcher, the scion of a wealthy family. He was a Republican
who had twice run unsuccessfully for the state's House of Delegates
and a father of three with two past marriages.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Fletcher attended Choate Hall, a New England prep school,
and DePauw University in Indiana. The family money comes from J.H.
Fletcher and Co., which manufactures customized equipment used in
coal, salt, diamond and copper mines around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Jim and Penny were married in Bermuda in 1994. Two years later,
their marriage already beginning to fray, they decided to see if
they could patch it by going on an extended cruise. At the age of
48, Jim took early retirement. In May 1996, aboard the $250,000
sailboat he had purchased from his father, they set off with plans
to circumnavigate the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   Wild times in Bequia
</P>
<P>
   By August they had reached St. Vincent, an independent monarchy
within the British Commonwealth of Nations. They were 1,600 miles
south of Miami and 210 miles northeast of Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
   Its official name is St. Vincent and the Grenadines. It is a
string of 600 small islands, islets and reefs ranging from the
island of St. Vincent in the north to Grenada in the south.
Kingstown, the capital city, is on the island of St. Vincent. The
land is agricultural and its primary export is bananas. Its second
most important crop is marijuana. It also has a reputation as a
major gateway for cocaine trafficking from Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   But tourism also is an important part of the economy on small
islands such as Bequia (BECK-we), nine miles south of the island of
St. Vincent, where a permanent population of 5,000 reaps rewards
from a harbor filled with the boats of well-heeled tourists. Jim
and Penny Fletcher's boat was among 100 or so floating in the clear
waters off Bequia. Their 50-foot craft was named, with future
irony, Carefree.
</P>
<P>
   For a while, life was carefree for the Fletchers. They spent
their days on the boat and their evenings on the islands, dining at
restaurants called The Plantation House or the Gingerbread House,
drinking at Buddy's Bar. They partied often and they partied hard.
Penny, especially, built a reputation for drinking a great deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sailing is different from anything else you do,'' she says.
``When you port-in, you're going to drink. That's what you do. It's
part of the life.''
</P>
<P>
   The stories start
</P>
<P>
   But confrontations also became part of her life and stories of
her barroom hassles spread quickly. Penny doesn't deny the stories.
Just the details.
</P>
<P>
   The one about throwing beer bottles at another customer, for
instance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a glass,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   And the one about biting a man in Buddy's Bar.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was way off, that situation was,'' she says. ``I didn't
bite him. I hit him. Sure, I hit him. Three men were attacking me
and I was fighting back.''
</P>
<P>
   Also widely circulated was a story about how she had been thrown
out of a restaurant owned by the former wife of James ``Son''
Michell, the prime minister of St. Vincent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't thrown out,'' Penny says. ``I just had words with her
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Penny Fletcher doesn't dispute, or apologize for, the stories.
She just asks for some balance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good things we did were never pointed out,'' she insists.
``We were not always bad and drinking all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   But even the times they tried to be good turned out bad.
</P>
<P>
   When they learned that the St. Vincent government was low on
funds, they established a $25,000 trust to buy children's school
supplies. They also announced they would give 10 percent of the
income from chartered trips on their yacht to the school system.
That announcement, a defense attorney would later note, may have
served mostly to embarrass the prime minister in a country already
sensitive to hints of American meddling.
</P>
<P>
   What Penny calls an attempt to feed hungry kids from the island
of St. Lucia led to three broken ribs and a story in the Bequia
Herald that accused them of trying to kidnap the children.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have enough children between us,'' Penny scoffs. ``We have
five already. Why would we want more?
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened was that we were in a restaurant and there were
these three children, all under the age of 10, going around and
begging for food. We ordered them all dinner. Then they asked if
they could spend the night on our boat. Their mother said it was
all right, even though she didn't know us from Adam. We agreed to
meet her back on the dock the next morning at 8:30.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next morning she didn't show up, so we kept them on the
boat and fed them breakfast. At lunchtime we took them to a
restaurant and fed them, then took them back to the boat for a nap.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then a man that we don't know comes along in a banana boat and
says, 'I want the children.' I said, 'I don't know you. I'm not
going to hand over the children to you.' So he starts to come
aboard the boat, which is the equivalent of breaking and entering.
I grabbed a big stick of sugar cane and swung it and connected with
his neck. He got back down in his boat and took a seven-foot wooden
oar and broke three of my ribs with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``So then Jim runs down from the bow and the man swung at him
and hit him in the knee. I went and got my gun, which had no clip
in it, and threatened him to get him off the boat.
</P>
<P>
   ``As it turned out, it was a boyfriend of the mother's.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the details, the stories surrounding the Fletchers
helped set them up for what would happen in their season of hell.
</P>
<P>
   `We set ourselves up'
</P>
<P>
   Oct. 6 was a Sunday. The day, Penny remembers, was uneventful.
The evening was quiet and calm.
</P>
<P>
   At 9:15 p.m., the Fletchers used channel 68 on their VHF radio
to call water-taxi driver Jerome ``Jolly'' Joseph, whose services
they previously had used several times. They told him they needed a
ride from their boat to the island, where they planned to have
dinner at the Plantation House.
</P>
<P>
   The 30-year-old Joseph was widely regarded as the most popular
water-taxi driver on the island. One news story described him as
``a friendly chap eking out a living shuttling tourists to and from
yachts he could never afford.''
</P>
<P>
   Penny Fletcher would write that story differently.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know he ran drugs,'' she says. ``We know he had a large
bank account. Our investigators found those things out.''
</P>
<P>
   When Joseph and the Fletchers reached the island in Joseph's
taxi, The Jolly Joseph, the restaurant was closed. He took them
back to the Carefree and collected his $6.20 (U.S.) fare. Before he
dropped them off, Penny says, he received another call on his
hand-held radio to pick up a fare at the dock.
</P>
<P>
   But Joseph was not seen again until three days later, when his
body was found floating off Bequia in an area known as Moon Hole.
He had been killed by a .22-caliber bullet to the chest.
</P>
<P>
   Jim and Penny Fletcher were the last persons known to have seen
him. Penny had registered a .22-caliber handgun and 200 rounds of
ammunition when they arrived in Bequia. And they had that
reputation. That hard-drinking, quick-tempered reputation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were an easy target, we really were,'' Penny Fletcher
acknowledges. ``We set ourselves up perfectly.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, when they were arrested Oct. 30 and charged in the murder
of Jolly Joseph, Penny says she was stunned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just about fainted. Everything just went black. I don't
think I ever felt so numb.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
