</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980630.0044 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 10:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3432 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PENNYFLETCHER01-TAKE2     06-30 1893
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PENNYFLETCHER01-TAKE2-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dream cruise became a Caribbean nightmare
 &HT;    (In two takes _ take 2)
 &HT;    By D.L. Stewart
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   XENIA, Ohio: ... felt so numb.''
</P>
<P>
   Jail brings rats, fear
</P>
<P>
   Jim Fletcher was taken to Her Majesty's Prison in Kingstown,
which had a population of 400 inmates in a facility designed for
150. From his cell, which he shared with as many as 19 other
prisoners, he could not see the sky.
</P>
<P>
   Penny went to Fort Charlotte, built on a hill above the city in
1806 by the British to defend the island against French invaders.
Today the upper levels of the fort are open to tourists. But they
are not allowed to go down the stone steps to the level that
includes the three cells that constitute her Majesty's Prison for
Women.
</P>
<P>
   Penny Fletcher's cell contained three bunk beds and one single
bed _ wooden pallets without mattresses, pillows or blankets. In
the corner was a 5-gallon bucket for the prisoners to use as a
communal toilet. It was emptied once a day.
</P>
<P>
   A few days after their release, in an interview on ABC's
``Nightline,'' she described the living conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had roach bites on my legs and then the rats would come up
out of the floorboards. And we stuffed paper down the spaces
between the boards and the rats, you could actually see their
heads, you know, come up while we were awake, you know, before we'd
go to sleep at night.''
</P>
<P>
   For Jim and Penny Fletcher, the only good news was the belief
that their confinement would be over by Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of our attorneys was approached (for a bribe),'' Penny
says. ``We gave him permission to go up to $100,000. Would we have
paid that much? To get out of prison? Sure. In a heartbeat.
Whatever we paid would have been cheaper than the six-attorney
'dream team' we had.''
</P>
<P>
   She declines to reveal what the final legal bill was, but says
it was more than $500,000.
</P>
<P>
   Before the deal could be concluded, though, a South African man
named Alan Heath was arrested in St. Vincent and charged with the
machete slaying of his wife aboard their yacht. He was released, he
publicly claimed, because he paid a $25,000 bribe to St. Vincent
officials. That claim, the Fletchers are sure, kept them
imprisoned.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been my belief all along that the only reason Jim and
Penny were arrested was for a bribe,'' Jim's sister, Sally Duncan,
told the Charleston (W.Va.) Gazette . ``But because of the Heath
case, that wasn't an option.''
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Mitchell called the stories of bribery
solicitations ``rubbish'' and challenged the Fletchers' attorneys
to name names.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't say who it was. But, oh yeah, we know,'' Penny
Fletcher insists. The reason they won't go public with the names,
she explains, is because there may be a need for similar deals in
the future and the attorneys ``don't want to lose their
connections.''
</P>
<P>
   A sensational inquiry
</P>
<P>
   Rubbish or not, the publicity surrounding Heath's claim
apparently made any bribe from the Fletchers too hot to handle and
they remained in Her Majesty's prisons. Four months after their
arrest, the preliminary inquiry was held.
</P>
<P>
   There were seven days of lurid testimony.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution called Benedict Redhead, a Grenadian-born
deckhand who claimed he witnessed Penny Fletcher kissing Jolly
Joseph.
</P>
<P>
   The defense denied the story and countered that Redhead was a
disgruntled former employee who had been fired by the Fletchers for
attempting to rape Penny. After he was fired, they said, crack
cocaine was found in his cabin.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution noted that the Fletchers had brought a
.22-caliber handgun and 200 rounds of ammunition to the islands.
</P>
<P>
   The defense claimed that the ammunition did not match the slug
found in Joseph's chest and that the gun had been stolen by
Benedict Redhead a month before the murder.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution countered that witnesses heard Penny
``bragging'' about firing the gun at the small dinghy on their
yacht on her 35th birthday in October, just four days before the
murder.
</P>
<P>
   The defense dismissed it as an untruthful boast.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I never said I shot the dinghy,'' she insists now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Penny likes to say things, sensationalize things,'' Sally
Duncan said in an interview with the Charleston Gazette.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the hearing, a magistrate declared that there was
sufficient cause to proceed to trial.
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorney Ralph Gonsalves called it ``a travesty of
justice.'' According to ``Nightline,'' Sandra Ingram, a
representative of the U.S. Embassy who monitored the hearing, wrote
a scathing confidential memorandum to the U.S. ambassador. She
wrote, ``There was not one scintilla of physical evidence'' and
said the case looked to her like a ``witch hunt.'' A fair trial,
she wrote, ``was unlikely.''
</P>
<P>
   A troublesome inmate
</P>
<P>
   While they waited for the wheels of Vincentian justice to grind,
Jim and Penny handled their confinement in ways that were as
different as their backgrounds. Jim worked crossword puzzles,
taught other inmates to read and lost weight.
</P>
<P>
   ``There wasn't any room to exercise, and exercising certainly
wasn't encouraged,'' he said a week after his release in an
interview with Cox News Service. ``I did pushups against the wall,
although people looked at me like I was crazy.'' A diet of rice,
bread and hot sugar-water known locally as ``tea'' left just 125
pounds on his 6-foot-1 frame.
</P>
<P>
   Penny, meanwhile, read ``whatever I could get my hands on. ... I
read 197 books in 283 days.'' She also received supportive letters
from strangers who were following the story in the media. She says
she is grateful for them, as well as for the phone calls to
lawmakers that were made on their behalf.
</P>
<P>
   Penny admits she was not a model prisoner.
</P>
<P>
   She says she fought off a matron who tried to confiscate her
engagement ring and wedding band. She protested when inmates were
taken to an exercise area next to the gallows. A Roman Catholic,
she refused to attend the prison's daily Anglican or Seventh-day
Adventist services, even though it would have meant getting out of
her cell for a while.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, 'I'm not listening to this (the services).' So they
locked me down during that time.''
</P>
<P>
   After four months, she also refused to work for food.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of our jobs every Tuesday was to clean the rice,'' she
says. ``They'd bring it in in a bag and dump it out and you had to
go through it and pick out the stones and the black pieces. After
four months I finally said, 'I'm not doing this anymore.' They
said, `If you're gonna eat it, you're gonna clean it.' So for the
last five months I lived on bread and tea.''
</P>
<P>
   Penny Fletcher concedes she could have made things easier on
herself by being more cooperative.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew the consequences and I did it anyway,'' she agrees. ``I
had the attitude in there that I've already been `bent' by being
there. I refused to have their way of thinking imposed on me. Their
rules. Their laws. What are you going to do, arrest me? What else
can you do to me? I can't go any lower.''
</P>
<P>
   She was wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Horror at the hospital
</P>
<P>
   Despite the spartan diet, Penny did not get thinner. Instead,
she grew bloated and puffy as the result of malnutrition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could press m finger against my flesh and the indentation
would be there two days later,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   In June she was taken to a hospital that, she says, had roaches
on the floor and dried blood on the examination table. A doctor
operated on her for a precancerous cervical condition. She says the
surgery was performed without an anesthetic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I screamed a whole lot,'' she admits. ``Fifteen minutes after
the surgery they transported me back to the prison and I fainted,
so they took me back to the hospital.''
</P>
<P>
   Penny says she still doesn't understand why no anesthetic was
permitted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't even pretend to know what these people think,'' she
says.
</P>
<P>
   While the Fletchers coped with life in prison, attorneys,
politicians and the news media turned the case into an
international squall.
</P>
<P>
   After ``Son'' Mitchell referred to the Fletchers as ``classic
ugly Americans,'' West Virginia Sen. Jay Rockefeller called on the
State Department to take measures to assure a fair trial for the
couple. At an international conference, President Clinton pulled
Mitchell aside and also sought assurances that the trial would be
fair.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides agree that media coverage had an impact. But they
differ as to what the impact was.
</P>
<P>
   ``Had it not been for the efforts of the American media and of
our families to ensure that we were given a fair trial, I am quite
certain that the outcome would have been death,'' Jim Fletcher said
on ``Nightline'' after the trial.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Mitchell saw it differently. In a radio broadcast
the week the trial ended, he charged that his country had been the
butt of ``racist U.S. media attacks'' and said, ``We have all
suffered from the vicious sledgehammer of the United States
media.''
</P>
<P>
   The trial begins
</P>
<P>
   Against this background, the trial of James and Penelia Fletcher
for the murder of Jerome ``Jolly'' Joseph finally opened in
Kingstown on July 28, 1997. When the trial began, they had been in
prison just two days short of nine months.
</P>
<P>
   Although most observers agreed the state's case was weak, Penny
Fletcher feared ``with every fiber'' that they would be convicted.
</P>
<P>
   ``The island is 98 percent black and we are white. The
illiteracy rate is at least 70 percent. That's not what we would
term `a jury of our peers.' Our cultures are so very different. You
can't be in a situation like that and not be scared.''
</P>
<P>
   But neither the judge nor the jury saw merit in the
prosecution's case. On Aug. 8, a dozen days after the trial began,
Judge Dunbar Cenac recommended to the jury that it dismiss the
charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question remains, who shot Jolly Joseph?'' Cenac declared.
``There is no evidence before me, direct or indirect, that the
accused committed this act.''
</P>
<P>
   The jury agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just started crying,'' Penny told ``Nightline.'' ``I just
started crying and I had to hold Jim's hand. I was afraid I was
going to break his fingers.''
</P>
<P>
   That evening, Jim and Penny Fletcher flew away from St. Vincent,
bound for his parents' home in Key Largo, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   But the story was not finished.
</P>
<P>
   No happily ever after
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 17, in Cabell (W.Va.) County court, citing
``irreconcilable differences,'' Jim Fletcher filed for divorce.
Penny Fletcher has countersued.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think when something like that happens, it either makes you
closer or drives a wedge between you,'' Penny told The Associated
Press. ``In this case, it drove a wedge between us.''
</P>
<P>
   But they still are, she says, ``best friends'' and have frequent
phone conversations. They talk about the kids and about the
Carefree. They talk, too, about their season in hell.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the only one I can talk to about it,'' she says. ``He's
the only one who can really understand.''
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally, the discussion turns to a proposed movie of the
week based on their experience. And about the book, which is in
progress but does not yet have a name.
</P>
<P>
   The working title is ``Nightmare in Paradise.''
</P>
<P>
   D.L. Stewart writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
