<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 10:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3435 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMMENTARY-BJT01-COX     06-30 0391
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMMENTARY-BJT01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE WEDNESDAY COMMENTARY BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These columns for release Wednesday, July 1, 1998, are moving
today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   All columns have moved, in the commentary (k) category. If you
have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the Cox News
Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ One way to hold down the crime rate is to stop
passing laws against stuff that isn't crooked. Congress is off on
two such toots. Republicans are proposing bills that would ticket
youths caught smoking and make it a crime for an adult in a state
that requires parental consent for an abortion to accompany a girl
to a non-consent state. It's the silly season. (Teepen, Cox News
Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ William Jefferson Clinton may be faster on
his feet than was Muhammad Ali in his prime. He showed it the other
night while answering questions from students at Peking University.
But how much of what he had to say in response to the students'
unanticipated tough questioning was a smoke screen; condescending
language while working his way offstage?
</P>
<P>
   Howard Kleinberg is a former editor of the Miami News.
(Kleinberg, Cox News Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SKUBE-COLUMN _ Pulitzer winner Michael Skube is on assignment.
His column will resume next week. (Skube, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
