<SLUG> BC-LANE-COLUMN01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Fire season puts summer under a cloud
 &HT;    By Mark Lane
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORMOND BEACH, Fla. _ The weather report calls for scattered
ashes this afternoon through, oh, September. And the sun will be
the color of blood rising through a haze of black followed by
partial late-morning clearing.
</P>
<P>
   Like a lot of natural-disaster stories, the fires sweeping
northern and central Florida are better understood as a weather
story gone bad. However huge and devastating, forest fires are part
of the rhythm of the Florida seasons. Always will be. And as we
have grown better at forgetting this, the fires mysteriously have
gotten worse.
</P>
<P>
   However expected fires may be in a time of unrelenting heat
without rain, their scale and effects have been dramatic this past
week.
</P>
<P>
   And not just for those who have lost homes or fear for their
property. The smoke and smell have drifted far from outskirting
highways and forest-hugging housing developments.
</P>
<P>
   For more than a week, the sky has been about the same color as
in the Mars Sojourner photographs of another sky far from town.
</P>
<P>
   A third of the state smells like a barbecue gone horribly wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Town dwellers walk out to their cars in the morning and find
them sprinkled with slivers of white ashes the size and shape of
baby fingernail clippings.
</P>
<P>
   Walking on the beach at dusk, I watched the dark outlines of
surf kids catching a few desultory wavelets through a dreamlike
haze. The smoke combined with the evening mist to create a salty
sea-smog. It's visually striking but makes you rub your eyes.
</P>
<P>
   These are small things, but they leave nobody unaffected.
</P>
<P>
   The cycles of water and fire that make up the Florida year are
easy enough to ignore in mild times. So easy, that people move here
and live unaware of them. They buy nice houses in the pine woods
and expensive condos on the barrier islands. In storm years, tides
threaten the shore. In dry years, fires threaten the pine-forest
homes. Everyone is surprised by these things. Every year, every
time.
</P>
<P>
   In between, the people living in these places complain to their
appropriate government agencies that the beaches need to be built
up and that something should be done about the smoke from
controlled burns because it's annoying and outrageous and
dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   People can accept summer hurricanes and autumn windstorms as
pranks of nature in an otherwise sweet climate. Fire, though,
demands culprits _ arsonists, kids fooling around, deep-woods trash
burners. And though fire starters are out there, they are harmful
only because they're working within a larger cycle of things.
</P>
<P>
   The cycle is on the floor of any pine forest. Needles and
underbrush and scrub that build over time. They ignite, go up fast
and make way for the next round of trees. Then it all grows around
again.
</P>
<P>
   But Florida real estate is getting too valuable for the burn
cycle. Little fires are put out before they can do their work. The
idea
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-98 1056EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980630.0047 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 10:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3437 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIRFORCEONE01-COX     06-30 1127
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRFORCEONE01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Air Force One: A small piece of history
 &HT;    By Tom Hopkins
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ In the movie Air Force One , Russian terrorists
run amok on the president's Boeing 747 and take the chief executive
and his family hostage.
</P>
<P>
   So much for Hollywood soundstages.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who attempts to run amok on the Air Force One now
displayed at the U.S. Air Force Museum may run headlong into a
plexiglass wall.
</P>
<P>
   The Boeing 707 is tiny compared to that 747, and the airplane
seems even more cramped now that technicians have walled off all
the rooms, seats and equipment with clear plastic windows to keep
them safe from visitors' inquisitive hands.
</P>
<P>
   Nontheless, a walk down the aisle of the retired Air Force One
is a step back into history that is both glorious and grim.
</P>
<P>
   Emblazoned with the words UNITED STATES OF AMERICA, the blue and
white airplane may be the world's most famous aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   The flying command center has been restored to look as it did in
the era of John F. Kennedy_an era that ended in November 1963, when
the plane that had flown the President and his family to Dallas
later took his body back to Washington, D.C., in a casket.
</P>
<P>
   Public tours opened Monday in the museum annex, a hanger
familiar to motorists on Springfield Street in Dayton because of
the gigantic painting of Orville and Wilbur Wright adorning its
front wall.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors must get a pass in the museum lobby and drive their
cars down Springfield Street to the annex to see Air Force One.
</P>
<P>
   If you're overweight, you may be denied access: Each person must
squeeze through a narrow framework at the bottom of the stairway
where a sign reads: ``Caution: Interior passageway narrows to 17
inches.''
</P>
<P>
   After a peek into the cockpit and a look at the communications
console, you come to the kitchenette that served the pilots and
crew. The small, cramped and antiseptic-looking room is covered by
plastic and stainless steel and has a refrigerator, electric range
and microwave oven.
</P>
<P>
   Leather-covered seats on both sides of the hallway were for
dignitaries, but there was nothing dignified about the comfort
level, museum historian Dean Kallander said.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are extremely uncomfortable seats,'' he said. ``I have
not a clue why, but before they put the plastic up, we had a chance
to sit in them, and it's like sitting on a board.''
</P>
<P>
   We come to a stateroom equipped with a conference table, lounge
chairs and a TV set, followed by a family lounge.
</P>
<P>
   A placard announces our arrival at the staff room where Lyndon
B. Johnson took the oath of office in Dallas. It may be the most
memorable photo ever taken on an airplane: Johnson is holding up
his right hand beside a Jacqueline Kennedy who is still in shock
and still wearing a blood-splattered dress.
</P>
<P>
   Next comes the infamous press section, with 16 seats on both
sides of the aisle for reporters. If you think this was a place of
honor, think again.
</P>
<P>
   ``If an individual had written unkindly of President Nixon, he
would require them to ride on this plane instead of the press
plane, which was a much more fun airplane,'' Kallander said. ``On
the press plane, they could get up and walk around and enjoy
themselves. Here, they weren't allowed to get up.''
</P>
<P>
   Another kitchenette is near the rear door. Across the aisle is
the area where Kennedy's casket was placed. The bulkhead was cut
away and four seats were removed to make room for the casket. The
partition has been replaced, and you can clearly see the cut made
in it.
</P>
<P>
   The two tiny restrooms in the rear seem almost forlorn,
considering the size of the 707.
</P>
<P>
   Kallander recalls that when Air Force One took Presidents Nixon,
Ford and Carter and national security adviser Henry Kissinger to
Anwar Sadat's funeral in 1981, ``There were so many people lined up
that Kissinger wondered if he should take a number to use the
restroom.''
</P>
<P>
   Air Force One, commissioned in 1962, arrived at Wright-Patterson
Air Force Base on May 19 to be added to the museum's collection of
eight presidential aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   The presidential plane is crammed into the hanger with several
smaller planes that once carried U.S. chief executives. There's
Dwight D. Eisenhower's Columbine, Franklin D. Roosevelt's Sacred
Cow and Harry S. Truman's Independence.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting beside the 707 is an Air Force Beech C-45H Expediter, a
taildragger; a twin-engine Aero Commander used by President
Eisenhower; and a North American L-17A, a small single engine
reconnaissance plane with a 33-foot wingspan.
</P>
<P>
   Air Force One at a glance
</P>
<P>
   _ President Kennedy broke with tradition and didn't give his
aircraft a personal name, so the news media popularized the call
sign Air Force One. The airplane is known officially as SAM 26000
(for Special Air Mission).
</P>
<P>
   _ Air Force One has served every U.S. president since John F.
Kennedy. It was the first jet designed exclusively for presidential
use, acquiring the title Air Force One only whenever the president
was aboard.
</P>
<P>
   _ Lyndon Johnson, who liked to keep an eye on his passengers,
ordered the seats reversed to face the rear of the aircraft_toward
the President's compartment. And he installed a chair and desk that
could rise or lower at the press of a button.
</P>
<P>
   _ The plane flew Johnson to visit the troops during the Vietnam
War, Richard Nixon to China for a historic meeting in 1972 and
Secretary of State Henry Kissinger to Paris for secret negotiations
to end the Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   _ Before Kennedy's assassination in 1963, the airplane broke 30
speed records, including the fastest nonstop flight between the
U.S. and the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   _ Air Force One was used as a backup plane to the current Air
Force One from 1972 to 1991, when it was removed from the primary
presidential fleet. The decision was made to retire the aging plane
because of its high maintenance costs.
</P>
<P>
   _ In January of this year, the plane went to pick up President
Clinton when the current Air Force One, a Boeing 747, got stuck in
the mud in Champaign, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   How to go
</P>
<P>
   WHAT:Tour of Air Force One.
</P>
<P>
   WHERE: U.S. Air Force Museum annex, Wright-Patterson Air Force
Base, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   WHEN: Museum is open to the public from 9 a.m. to 5 p.m. seven
days a week except Thanksgiving, Christmas and New Year's Day. Air
Force One is open from 9:30 a.m. to 5 p.m. Imax Theatre showings
begin at the top of each hour.
</P>
<P>
   COST:Admission to the museum, Air Force One and parking are
free. Admission to the Imax Theatre is $5 for adults, $4.50 for
seniors, $3.50 for students and $2.25 for children 3-7.
</P>
<P>
   MORE INFO: visit the museum's web site at
www.wpafb.af.mil/museum
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
