</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIREWORKS01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Welcome to Professor Pyro's fireworks appreciation class
 &HT;    By Sarah Franquet
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Oooooo! Aaahhhh!
</P>
<P>
   If that's the extent of your fireworks commentary, help has
arrived. Pay attention as Professor Pyro teaches us Fireworks
Appreciation. Then use your newfound knowledge to wow your wife,
show off for your kids, impress your friends. They'll ooooo and
aaahhhh at your brilliant bursts of intellect.
</P>
<P>
   The professor went straight to Marcy Zambelli, of the famous
Zambelli Internationale Fireworks. Here's a closer look at a few of
the bursts you're likely to see at ...add info about your own
fireworks show here....
</P>
<P>
   The Chrysanthemum
</P>
<P>
   This symmetrical burst lives up to its floral namesake. A
Chrysanthemum (as with all shells) can come in almost any size, but
the one that makes the most lasting impression is the 12-inch
shell. It bursts up to 1,200 feet high, has a radius of 996 feet
(that's more than three football fields) and can last nine seconds
before it fades away. The Chrysanthemum has a high ``wow'' factor
because it overwhelms the sky with its size. It comes in many
colors, but usually the two-color combo is employed. The one
pictured here is called a Brocade Chrysanthemum because of its rich
texture and the tips you see at the ends.
</P>
<P>
   The Silver-Crested Wave
</P>
<P>
   One of the most distinctive displays, the Wave's streaking
silver bullets explode upward and then drift gently down, creating
a glittery mid-air waterfall. The ``fancy star'' shells are usually
3 to 6 inches around and shoot up to 600 feet high before bursting.
</P>
<P>
   The Titanium Salutes
</P>
<P>
   A salute is the loud boom you hear, usually during a finale.
This Titanium Salute has ``royal flourishes,'' a frenzy of sparkles
that explode like popcorn, and ``rising tails,'' the trails of
light you see along its flight path. Most salutes come from 3-inch
shells and travel up to 300 feet in the air.
</P>
<P>
   Peonies
</P>
<P>
   These brilliant bursts billow from a center core. When several
of these shells are tied together, they go off in succession to
create a `flight of Peonies,' as shown here. They come in a variety
of colors, and usually create large bursts, up to 800 feet high
with a radius of more than 600 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Golden Palm Tree
</P>
<P>
   When this one breaks, you know how it got its name. A stunning
display of golden strokes arch from a center point to resemble palm
leaves. It is sometimes accented by vivid green tails. This shell
comes in a variety of sizes.
</P>
<P>
   Glossary:
</P>
<P>
   Salutes: The ear-splitting booms you hear, most often at the end
of the show.
</P>
<P>
   Battle in the clouds: A number of salutes that explode in
succession, sounding like rapid gunfire.
</P>
<P>
   Hummers: A small tube that spins and creates a screaming or
humming sound.
</P>
<P>
   Tourbillons: An ignited shell that spins like a top when it
rises.
</P>
<P>
   Stars: Chemical pellets packaged in a shell that provide
patterns and effects.
</P>
<P>
   Weeping Willows: The slow-burning after-effects of a shell, that
look like drooping branches of a willow as they fall to the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Dud: A shell that fails to explode.
</P>
<P>
   Star mine: A glittery effect that rises right from the mortar
with a loud ``THUMP,'' emitting sprays of sparkling color.
</P>
<P>
   How get the best fireworks photographs:
</P>
<P>
   Point-and-shoot cameras are usually not worth the effort at
fireworks shows, professional photographers say. But if you're a
more advanced shutterbug _ and have a camera that can switch to
manual, allowing you to set the aperture and shutter speed _ you,
too, can take stunning photos of fireworks.
</P>
<P>
   Palm Beach Post photographer Greg Lovett, who's had a lot of
experience photographing fireworks, shares these tips:
</P>
<P>
   _ Carry a small tripod and a few lenses (24mm, 50mm and maybe a
70-200 zoom). Take a small flashlight, so you can see what you're
doing in the dark.
</P>
<P>
   _ Arrive early to find a good spot and give yourself ample time
to set up. If you're close to the water, you will need a wide angle
lens, such as a 24 or 35mm. A 50mm will also work, depending on how
much of the bursts you want in your picture. For the Flagler show,
one of my favorite spots is the Flagler Memorial Bridge sidewalk
about halfway across. The fireworks illuminate the sky and reflect
in the water, which is filled with boats. If you stand behind the
sea wall, or just a few steps back, you can have people silhouetted
in the foreground.
</P>
<P>
   _ I like to use 100 speed negative film. It has beautiful color
reproduction and nice tight grain. The negative film allows you
some latitude in exposure and allows you to make a few mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   _ I put my camera on a tripod and set my aperture at f/8. You
can set your camera shutter on ``bulb'' or ``B'' and open the
shutter using a cable release when you see a burst. I usually open
the shutter for about 8 seconds, a little less (4 seconds) for the
bright grand finale. For the first couple of bursts, I look through
the camera to get my composition the way I want it and to decide
which lens to use.
</P>
<P>
   _ Remember to relax and take your time. You will have at least
20 minutes of shooting time. Try a few lenses in the beginning if
you want, but then have your special shot planned for the finale
when the biggest most beautiful bursts usually occur. And take
plenty of pictures. I normally shoot about two rolls on a 20-minute
show.
</P>
<P>
   Sarah Franquet writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
