<SLUG> BC-MINOR-COLUMN01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Perfect phone: square, clunky, wired to the past
 &HT;    By Emily J. Minor
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   I see them everywhere. The baseball game. The grocery store.
Even the dressing room at Loehmann's. They're stashed in purses and
slung on hips. Ring. Ring. Ring, they go, usually at the oddest of
moments. And on the days when I'm sitting here, dreaming instead of
writing, I think:
</P>
<P>
   Wouldn't it be great if I could divulge to the world that no one
out there is using cell phones to do important things like trade
Sunbeam stock or order more Viagra. Indeed, people are simply doing
in public what everybody used to do in private. That is, telling
their mothers they're too busy to talk and yelling at their kids.
</P>
<P>
   I am perhaps one of the few ambulatory Americans who does not
own a cellular telephone in 1998, and I guess that's because I have
enough to remember each morning when I walk out of the house. But I
did, just the other day, have occasion to go phone shopping for _
now pardon my squareness on this _ a regular old desk telephone for
my office at home. You know, the kind with a clunky base,
push-button dialing pad and a receiver you can actually hold in the
crink of your neck.
</P>
<P>
   You want WHAT? the first salesman said, eyes big, eyebrows
arched, tone reproachful. And suddenly I felt as though I was 13
with a round little middle and had just asked my mother, for the
50th time, to please get me a pink Trimline. (They had a lighted,
push-button dial, ya know.)
</P>
<P>
   Now, before the mail starts pouring in accusing me of being a
romantic, live-in-the-past, head-in-the-sand person, allow me to
assure everyone out there that I am a liberal, forward-thinking
woman. I shudder when people say things like ``I wish we could go
back to the good old days'' because who wants no blacks and no
women in newsrooms. I think gays should be allowed to marry. My son
prefers art over karate.
</P>
<P>
   It's just that some people don't see the world through my
particular shade of rose lenses.
</P>
<P>
   Man at Office Depot: I haven't seen one of those kind of phones
in a long time, Ma'am.
</P>
<P>
   Man at Circuit City: Oh. Oh. I know exactly what kind of phone
you want. (At this point, he walks me to his cash register where
there sits a gorgeous, gray desk telephone, just like the one I
want.) Gosh, he says, I don't know where you can buy this kind of
phone. Mike, he hollers, do you know where she can buy one of
these?
</P>
<P>
   It was at this point, forward-thinking be damned, that a tiny _
OK, huge _ part of me wanted to go back to that comfortable period
in my life when the Ohio Bell man brought the phone we wanted right
to our family's door. I even began to crave Campbell's tomato soup
and grilled cheese.
</P>
<P>
   I'm told this whole phone-choice thing started with a little
something called deregulation, which I am certain was a good idea
30 years ago. Why should one big company have all the business?
Except to say that back then I had the kind of phone I wanted and
there was no one calling during dinner trying to sell me 30 minutes
of free Saturday long distance.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, I persevered and won because, after all, it is 1998
and forward-thinking women get what they want. I'm looking at the
fruit of my labor right now.
</P>
<P>
   It's brown. It's clunky.
</P>
<P>
   It's almost as beautiful as that pink Trimline I never had.
</P>
<P>
   Emily J. Minor writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
