<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Recipes for great hair
 &HT;    By Lynda Edwards
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ This is a jungle heat wave. It's just
too hot and humid to trek out to a salon and get beautiful. But
local colorist Melissa Peverini (whose clients include Marla
Maples, Roxanne Pulitzer and _ on her annual LA junkets _ Heather
Locklear and Gillian Anderson) swears all the ingredients for great
hair are in your kitchen. Here, some beauty secrets and homemade
concoctions:
</P>
<P>
   1. ``Florida water is full of chlorine and iron; it gives hair
the color of a dirty penny,'' says Peverini, who works at Cosmo &AMP;
Co. in West Palm Beach, Fla. Sprinkle baking soda into shampoo to
strip the chemical buildup off your hair, she says.
</P>
<P>
   2. Glacial blond and ebony brunette look fine amid canyons of
gray concrete, steel and icy glass, i.e. New York City. But women
in the tropics _ surrounded by sun blaze, blue ocean and green
palms _ need lusher tones.
</P>
<P>
   3. ``Blondes can rinse their hair with a cup of chamomile tea
for golden highlights,'' Peverini says. ``Redheads should use
raspberry tea and brunettes should use coffee or even espresso to
enrich and deepen their color. Leave it on for 15 minutes for the
best results.''
</P>
<P>
   4. Rub drops of olive oil through wet or dry hair to tame
frizzes.
</P>
<P>
   5. That old 1970s teen product Sun-In really worked. The
lightener can be duplicated by mixing half a cup of water with half
a cup of lemon juice, pouring it onto the hair and then strolling
under the sun for 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   6. Kool Aid hair dye was invented by punk rockers during the
'80s and is still a club-hopper's staple. (For God's sake, be 25 or
under for this look). Follow regular instructions to make the drink
and then add a pinch of cornstarch. ``Orange gives a coppery
sheen,'' Peverini explained. ``Paint it on with your fingers. Grape
and cherry make pretty streaks on blondes. Brunettes can pour it
all over their hair for an iridescent, opal-ine glimmer.'' Die-hard
rockers let the drink dry on their hair; the more demure should
rinse after 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   7. To add body to limp tresses, massage a cup of milk into
shampooed hair then rinse it out with cool water.
</P>
<P>
   8. Drink twice as much water as you normally do. ``It helps
prevent hair, nails and skin from drying,'' Peverini says.
</P>
<P>
   9. Repair sun-damage by spreading avocado pulp over hair and
wrapping it in plastic wrap for 15 minutes. It's the same deep
conditioning you get at a salon and costs $50 less.
</P>
<P>
   10. Men find vanilla one of the most erotic of scents, according
to the Smell and Taste Research Foundation in Chicago. Mix 2 drops
of olive oil with 3 drops of vanilla and run through wet hair.
``The scent lingers; it won't evaporate from hair the way it does
from perspiring skin,'' Peverini said. (And it's a far more fun way
to study romantic chemistry than having guys sniff test tubes in a
lab.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
