<HEADER>
A3447 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MANGO-RECIPES-COX     06-30 1712
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MANGO-RECIPES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Make a meal of a mango
 &HT;    (With MANGOS-IDEAS.)
 &HT;    By Jan Norris
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are some recipes for cooking with your mangoes.
</P>
<P>
   These two recipes are easily made and transported for your next
grill outing.
</P>
<P>
   Grilled mango kebabs
</P>
<P>
   1 large mango, cubed
</P>
<P>
   1 cup pineapple chunks, drained
</P>
<P>
   2 oranges, sectioned, sections cut in half if large
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons honey
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup lime juice
</P>
<P>
   Wooden skewers, soaked in water
</P>
<P>
   For dipping sauce:
</P>
<P>
   1 cup plain yogurt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup freshly squeezed orange juice
</P>
<P>
   Alternate cubes of pineapple, mango and orange on wooden
skewers. Brush with honey-lime juice mixture. Grill over medium
heat until pineapple is glazed brown.
</P>
<P>
   Remove and serve hot with dipping sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 10-12 skewers.
</P>
<P>
   This recipe is a take-off on the famous Australian dessert. The
nonfat dessert makes a stunning presentation when served on a
solid-color plate. Quick grilled mango dessert
</P>
<P>
   1 angel food cake, sliced
</P>
<P>
   2 or 3 large mangoes, sliced
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup honey mixed with 2 tablespoons lime juice
</P>
<P>
   Flaked coconut for garnish
</P>
<P>
   Toast angel food cake on grill; remove to cool. Grill mango
slices, brushed with honey mixture, on foil over medium heat until
lightly browned.
</P>
<P>
   Alternate layers of cake and mango slices for each dessert,
drizzle with small amount of honey and garnish with flaked coconut.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings.
</P>
<P>
   Mango Pavlova
</P>
<P>
   3 large egg whites
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup superfine (or regular sugar)
</P>
<P>
   Dash salt
</P>
<P>
   1 cup nonfat plain yogurt
</P>
<P>
   1 cup raspberries, fresh or frozen, pureed
</P>
<P>
   1 large mango, peeled and thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons finely diced mango for garnish
</P>
<P>
   Make meringues: Grease and flour two baking sheets. Trace 6
4-inch circles on the sheets with the tip of a knife. (Note:
Measurement doesn't have to be exact.)
</P>
<P>
   In medium bowl, with mixer on high speed, whip egg whites until
they hold soft peaks. Add sugar, a little at a time, until all is
incorporated. Add salt and blend well.
</P>
<P>
   Fill pastry bag fitted with large star tip with meringue. Pipe
spirals of meringue beginning in center of marked circles on pastry
sheet, and continuing to edge of circles. (Or, gently spread
meringue with spatula to cover circles; smooth tops for even
baking.)
</P>
<P>
   Bake meringues in 200-degree oven for 2 hours, or until just
lightly browned and dry. Remove and let cool completely before
removing with thin-bladed spatula. Note: Handle carefully, as they
are very fragile. They can be stored in an airtight container
between waxed paper if not using right away, but keep away from all
moisture.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, mix yogurt and all but 2 tablespoons of the raspberry
puree in a small bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Just before serving, plate the dessert: Place one meringue on
plate, layering with 1/4 of yogurt-raspberry mixture, and 1/4 of
mango slices. Repeat. End with meringue, set at an angle.
</P>
<P>
   Repeat with second plate. Drizzle both plates with reserved
raspberry puree, and garnish with finely diced mangoes. Serve
immediately as the meringues become soggy quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 2 servings.
</P>
<P>
   (Adapted from The Perfect Recipe, by Pam Anderson, Houghton
Mifflin, 1998.)
</P>
<P>
   Easy mango sorbet
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 cups water
</P>
<P>
   2 cups mango puree
</P>
<P>
   Dash of lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   Cook sugar and water to a syrup stage - it will reduce in half
in volume.
</P>
<P>
   Remove from heat and blend in mango puree and dash of lemon
juice. Freeze; allow to thaw slightly. Blend in blender to sorbet
consistency. Serve in wide champagne goblets using melon ball scoop
to make balls of sorbet.
</P>
<P>
   To make frozen mango pops, pour mixture into bathroom-sized
paper cups; add wooden sticks and freeze solid. To eat, remove
paper from cup.
</P>
<P>
   Mangoes are indigenous to India; it is there the British
developed their affinity for the fruits.
</P>
<P>
   Indian yogurt-mango cream
</P>
<P>
   (Amrakhand)
</P>
<P>
   4 cups whole-milk yogurt
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons sugar, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 1/3 cups diced mango pulp
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped nuts (chirongi, an Indian nut, is
recommended, but almonds suffice)
</P>
<P>
   Line a colander with cheesecloth or a large paper filter. Place
the yogurt in colander, and drain overnight, or until very dry.
</P>
<P>
   Once dry, remove yogurt and put into bowl. Beat well with wooden
spoon or whisk, adding the sugar a little at a time.
</P>
<P>
   When the yogurt is light in texture, stir in mango pulp. Pour
into four attractive dessert glasses, and chill.
</P>
<P>
   Serve ice cold, sprinkled with nuts.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   (From The Indian Spice Kitchen by Monisha Bharadwaj, Dutton
Books, 1998.)
</P>
<P>
   Serve this salsa with fish, meats or grilled vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   Mango salsa
</P>
<P>
   1 ripe mango (about 1 pound)
</P>
<P>
   1 small red bell pepper, seeded and julienned
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon peeled and minced fresh ginger
</P>
<P>
   1 red chili, seeded and finely chopped (optional)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup thinly sliced red onion
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped fresh cilantro
</P>
<P>
   5 tablespoons fresh lime juice
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup fresh orange or pineapple juice
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Peel mango and cut into 1/4-inch dice. Combine all ingredients
in a bowl. Let stand at room temperature for 30 minutes before
serving.
</P>
<P>
   Makes about 3 cups.
</P>
<P>
   (From Pacific Light Cooking by Ruth Law, Donald I. Fine Books,
1998.)
</P>
<P>
   Sugar-free mango upside down cake
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup packed brown sugar substitute
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon polyunsaturated oil
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons water
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sliced mangoes, drained
</P>
<P>
   1 cup fresh (or frozen) cranberries
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup sugar substitute
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup skim milk
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup plain nonfat yogurt
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons polyunsaturated oil
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4 cups sifted cake flour
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon salt substitute
</P>
<P>
   2 egg whites
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. In a small saucepan, combine the
brown sugar substitute, 1 tablespoon of the oil and water. Stir
well. Cook over medium heat until brown sugar substitute dissolves.
Stir occasionally. Pour the mixture into a 9by 9-inch nonstick cake
pan. Arrange the mango slices in the bottom of the pan. Place the
cranberries on top of the mangoes; set aside.
</P>
<P>
   In a small bowl, combine 3/4 sugar substitute, skim milk,
yogurt, 3 tablespoons of the oil and vanilla extract. Stir well
with a wire whisk.
</P>
<P>
   In a large bowl, combine the sifted cake flour, baking powder
and salt. Stir well with fork. Add yogurt mixture to the flour, a
little at a time, beating until well blended. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Place egg whites in a small bowl and beat until stiff peaks
form. Fold the egg white mixture into the large bowl of mixed
ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   Pour the batter on top of ingredients in cake pan. Bake for 40
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately invert the cake onto a serving platter; allow to
cool before serving.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 9 to 12 servings.
</P>
<P>
   Spicy mango chutney
</P>
<P>
   6 large ripe mangoes, peeled and sliced
</P>
<P>
   3 cups apple cider vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups chopped green peppers
</P>
<P>
   1 cup and 2 tablespoons raisins
</P>
<P>
   1 cup currants
</P>
<P>
   1 cup slivered almonds
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup lime juice
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup minced onions
</P>
<P>
   5 tablespoons honey
</P>
<P>
   1 piece ginger, 3 inches long, peeled and finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 tablespoons crushed mustard seeds
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 tablespoons minced hot chili pepper, or 1 dried chili
pepper, ground
</P>
<P>
   Combine all ingredients in a large saucepan. Bring to a boil,
then simmer for 30 minutes, stirring occasionally. Drain off juice
and boil juice down to half of its volume. Add it to the chutney,
and reheat.
</P>
<P>
   To can the chutney: Pour the mixture into hot, scalded pint
jars, leaving 1/4-inch head space. Seal and process for 5 minutes
in a boiling-water bath.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 pints.
</P>
<P>
   (From Preserving Summer's Bounty, edited by Susan McClure,
Rodale Press, 1998.)
</P>
<P>
   Chicken salad with curry lime mayo and mangoes
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 teaspoons curry powder
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons fresh lime juice
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons mango chutney, roughly chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 cup mayonnaise
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup shredded, unsweetened coconut
</P>
<P>
   1 whole chicken breast, poached, cooled and shredded
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup cashews, coarsely chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons currants (or raisins)
</P>
<P>
   1 mango, peeled and cut into cubes
</P>
<P>
   4 8-inch tortillas
</P>
<P>
   In a small frying pan, heat the oil. Add curry and stir until it
begins to foam and becomes fragrant. Set aside to cool.
</P>
<P>
   In a bowl, mix the lime juice, chutney, mayonnaise and cooled
curry paste. Toast the coconut in an ungreased frying pan or in the
oven until golden, and allow to cool.
</P>
<P>
   Combine mayonnaise mixture with chicken, coconut, cashews,
currants and mango and stir to distribute the dressing evenly.
</P>
<P>
   Lay out tortillas on a clean, dry work surface and place
one-fourth of the filling on each tortilla. Roll up and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 wrapped sandwiches.
</P>
<P>
   (From Wraps Around the World by Iris Sutton and Shelby Sewell,
Abbeville Press, 1998.)
</P>
<P>
   The wonderful world of mangoes
</P>
<P>
   PEELING MANGOES: Before you work with mangoes, perfect the art
of peeling one. There is a flat side to every mango - hold the
fruit at eye level, stem end up, and turn it till you see the
thinnest view; slice down both sides of mango next to the pit. You
now have two juicy halves to peel. To remove the mango flesh from
each half of the mango, make cross-hatches through the fruit flesh
down to the skin (but not through skin), and flip the skin
inside-out. Now, slice off the diced mango chunks. Do this over a
bowl for best results.
</P>
<P>
   SUBSTITUTING MANGOES: You can substitute mangoes for any recipe
that calls for peaches, or combine the two for a unique flavor.
</P>
<P>
   KEEPING MANGOES: Mangoes don't last fresh. Once they begin
getting sugar spots - those black dots on the skin which indicate
ripeness - it's time to eat them or freeze them.
</P>
<P>
   FREEZE MANGO SLICES on a cookie sheet until hard, then bag up
the slices and use as desired. Mango puree and mango pulp also can
be frozen in bags for up to a year with good results.
</P>
<P>
   QUICK RECIPE TIP: Freeze mango puree in an ice cube tray with a
mint leaf in each compartment, then use those cubes for your iced
raspberry tea for a pretty and delicious drink.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
