<SLUG> BC-JUSTFORFUN01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EasyPhoto scanner offers more colors and detail
 &HT;    By Yusuf Davis
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The EasyPhoto SmartPage Pro is a high-performance scanner from
Storm Technology that combines the best features of flatbed and
hand-held scanners. Its 30-bit technology promises more colors and
detail than 24-bit rivals.
</P>
<P>
   Versatility is the strength of this image-transfer device. It
boasts a straight paper path that won't bend, shred or mutilate
hard-to-replace photos and documents, and it has a detachable head,
which, like a hand-held scanner, can be used to scan books,
magazines or other bound materials. The removable head also makes
it easy to clean. EasyPhoto's ClearScan II technology is designed
to automatically brighten, sharpen and color correct dull images.
</P>
<P>
   Priced at $149, the EasyPhoto scanner can be seen at
http://www.easyphoto.com.
</P>
<P>
   Clicking in comfort
</P>
<P>
   Users of the TrackMan Marble FX input device may have less
reason to fear the effects of repetitive-strain injury. The
point-and-click tool from Logitech combines comfort and
functionality in a futuristic design that eliminates the
multiclicking death grip sometimes required to operate a mouse.
</P>
<P>
   Equipped with four programmable buttons, the Marble FX is easily
customized via the Mouse Properties dialog box. The bundled
MouseWare software provides a host of commands, which can be
assigned to any of the buttons _ from double-clicking to closing an
application.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike some of its competitors, the TrackMan can scroll through
any Windows application.
</P>
<P>
   The Marble FX has a suggested price of $99.95 and can be seen at
http://www.logitech.com.
</P>
<P>
   Versatile videocamera
</P>
<P>
   Digital videocameras were once exotic toys for the well-heeled,
but like many things digital, cost and technology have put them in
the hands of the average consumer.
</P>
<P>
   Take the Kodak Digital Science DVC323, for example. At $169,
this videocamera is within the budget of many computer users. It
has a wealth of fun and practical applications.
</P>
<P>
   Its two main functions are capturing still and video images for
transfer to computer files and for real-time videoconferencing.
Small enough to fit atop a monitor, the DVC323 will let you chat
face-to-face with friends from around the world. (Provided, of
course, you have friends around the world and they, too, have
videoconferencing capability.) It can be used to send still image
and video clips downline, as e-mail messages. Bundled with loads of
image-editing software, video quality is good, but installation is
reported to be a little challenging.
</P>
<P>
   For information, visit the Web site http://www.kodak.com.
</P>
<P>
   If you never learned to type
</P>
<P>
   For anyone wanting to learn typing without going back to middle
school, there's Typing Instructor from Individual Software.
</P>
<P>
   The award-winning CD program uses a fun travel theme, plus
videos, photos, animations and music to add enjoyment and eliminate
the drudgery of mastering the letters, numbers and symbols of the
keyboard.
</P>
<P>
   Designed for ages 7 to adult, Version 9 of this deluxe edition
suggests the right lesson for each user, after a short test to
determine the user's skill level. The program promises to improve
accuracy and wpm scores of beginners and advanced typists.
</P>
<P>
   Easy-to-follow lessons help users master a few keys at a time or
users can build their own custom lesson plan.
</P>
<P>
   The $29.95 software is widely available and can be seen at
http://www.individualsoftware.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
