<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 10:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3454 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWSSTAND01-COX     06-30 0740
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSSTAND01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NEWSSTAND
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Robert F. Kennedy was assassinated 30 years ago, Congress
reacted by passing an act that banned most interstate sales of guns
and outlawed ownership by felons, minors and the mentally ill.
Today, Time ($2.95) reports, America is still under the gun. A
haunting photo essay by British photographer Zed Nelson portrays
born-again Christians, female executives, housewives and doctors,
all armed and ready to defend themselves. The most troubling
photograph shows a young Dallas father holding his infant daughter
in one hand and a pistol in the other. In a companion article,
writer Margot Hornblower interviews Charlton Heston about his plans
to revive the National Rifle Association.
</P>
<P>
   Life ($3.95) addresses the same subject with a twist. The
magazine visits nine heroic teenagers who helped disarm Kipland
Kinkel when he opened fire at Thurston High School in Springfield,
Ore. Says Josh Ryker: ``I don't feel like a hero _ it still hasn't
hit me that I saved a lot of people.'' Now the people of
Springfield are trying to figure out how to make such heroism
unnecessary ever again. On a lighter note, Life presents exclusive
photos of Maya Angelou's 70th birthday bash on a Caribbean cruise
with Oprah Winfrey, Coretta Scott King and Quincy Jones.
</P>
<P>
   ALL IN THE FAMILY: Violence can occur even when no guns are
involved. In a compelling cover story, Mother Jones ($3.95)
explores domestic violence and its toll on children. Kids act out
what they see, writes Claudia Glenn Dowling, a senior editor at
Life magazine who spent a year following a Vermont family in a
study of violence. ``Opposite-sex siblings tend to be at more risk
to act out exactly what their parents do,'' psychologist Carla
Garrity says. ``Girls align with the victim, boys align with the
aggressor.'' And, in a terrifying statistic, Garrity predicts that
half the 3 million children who live in violent homes will become
violent adults.
</P>
<P>
   SEX AT THE TOP: Some say that if President Clinton were the head
of a corporation, he would have been fired because of alleged
sexual misconduct. That's not necessarily so, says U.S. News &AMP;
World Report ($2.95) in an article on Milan Panic. As CEO of ICN
Pharmaceuticals, Panic (pronounced PAH-neesh) has tripled the
company's value in the past year. The 68-year-old father of five
also has been involved in four sexual harassment cases. The women
claim Panic repeatedly propositioned them or groped them and
rewarded or punished female employees based on their responses. The
ICN board of directors responded not by kicking him out, but by
sweetening his $644,680 salary with a $1.8 million bonus. And, in
its continuing coverage of the Monica Lewinsky case, the magazine
explains why race may be a hidden factor. Lewinsky's attorneys seem
to be betting that she could win a jury trial in the largely
African-American and Democratic District of Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   WAR STORIES: Steven Spielberg's war epic ``Saving Private Ryan''
is so realistic that during a screening, historian Stephen E.
Ambrose asked the projectionist to stop the film until he could
compose himself after seeing the combat scenes at Omaha Beach. One
of the reasons the film is so moving, reports US ($3), is that it
is inspired by real people and their sacrifices. Spielberg based
his film on the story of the four Niland brothers of Tonawanda,
N.Y. Two of the sons had died on D-Day, Edward was missing in
action in the Pacific and Frederick was fighting somewhere in
northern France. Aware of the outcry that had occurred when all
five Sullivan brothers had been killed two years earlier, the Army
organized a successful search for Frederick. A year later, the
family received word that Edward was alive in a Japanese POW camp.
</P>
<P>
   CIRCLING THE WAGONS: When Harry Thomason watched Clinton make
his first public statement about Lewinsky on Jan. 21, he knew his
old friend was in trouble. So, according to Jeffrey Toobin in a
juicy New Yorker ($3) article, Thomason and his wife, Linda
Bloodworth-Thomason (creator of TV's ``Designing Women''), offered
their help. Clinton's subsequent _ and more forceful _ denial is
credited to Thomason's advice. ``Harry is like a throat lozenge,''
says Clinton adviser James Carville. ``There's something very
soothing about him.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
