<HEADER>
A3457 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SMART-HOMES01-COX     06-30 1472
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMART-HOMES01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Smart homes good for the smart owner
 &HT;    By Cheryl Crabb
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Owning a smart house can be great, especially once you
figure out how to use it.
</P>
<P>
   Lora and Chip Gonzalez moved into their high-tech house at Creek
Ridge Point in Alpharetta, Ga. last December, and they're still
learning about all the things it can do.
</P>
<P>
   ``For someone who doesn't know it, it can be fairly complicated,
'' said Chip Gonzalez, a 33-year-old salesman for a mutual fund
company.
</P>
<P>
   The couple has yet to master home entertainment. Although they
have the capability to play the same movie on all the televisions
in the house, right now, they are using standard cable like almost
everybody else. With only one computer hooked up, the Gonzalezes
also have yet to make use of wiring that enables home computers to
share information.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Gonzalez said, having a smart house is starting to pay
off.
</P>
<P>
   A state-of-the-art security system with video cameras hooked up
to the home's television sets is one of the couple's favorite
features. A ``baby cam'' in the nursery allows them to keep an eye
on their 3-month-old son, Alexander. A similar video monitor on the
front porch allows the couple to see who is at the door by using
their TV's remote bontrol to click on a designated home channel.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife was here by herself one night when a salesman came to
the door,'' Gonzalez said. ``She was able to click on the TV
instead of going to look at him through the lead glass door.''
</P>
<P>
   The house's intercom system, which allows the couple to talk to
each other over any phone in the five-bedroom, five-rath house, is
also starting to come in handy, Gonzalez said. ``It's not a huge
house, but you can be in the far corners and not hear anybody,'' he
added.
</P>
<P>
   The Gonzalez family paid about $2,000 extra to wire the house
with the Lucent Homestar system, a joint project of BellSouth
Corp., Lucent Technologies and Trademark Homes. Alpharetta-based
Digital Interiors Inc., an authorized Smart House Inc. dealer, was
recently hired to help install the system and to teach homeowners
how it works.
</P>
<P>
   The Gonzalez's subdivision is among a few metro Atlanta
neighborhoods being wired with smart-house technology. But that
number is rapidly increasing. The wiring will enable tech-savvy
homeowners to create the ultimate home kffice; choose from endless
channels of music and entertainment; automate heating, air and
lighting systems; and control state-of-the-art security systems.
</P>
<P>
   Although most smart houses in metro Atlanta are priced at
$300,000 and up, they aren't only for the super rich in
neighborhoods surrounding high-tech business hubs. In nearby
Cherokee County, developer Hutson Homes is including high-tech
wiring in the cost of houses priced in the $150,000 and $200,000
ranges in his new subdivision Walnut Creek. For houses smaller than
2,500 square feet, upgraded wiring can be added for a few hundred
dollars extra, said George Ide, a home system designer with Digital
Interiors.
</P>
<P>
   One of Walnut Creek's first buyers, 25-year-old software writer
Josh Nunez, can't wait to get rid of the wires now strewn
throughout his Vinings, Ga. apartment. His wife Nicole, a speech
pathologist, also hopes the system will speed up research on the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Central cable and phone connections inside the home form the
backbone of a smart house. Communications lines branch out like
spokes on a wheel. Numerous hardware and software systems use that
wiring to bring smart houses to life. Currently, the upgraded,
reconfigured wiring can provide services such as high-speed
Internet access. In the future, it will enable homeowners to take
advantage of a wide range of technology, such as high-definition
television or interactive cable.
</P>
<P>
   ``The telephone company is beginning to offer video over
telephone lines, and homes need to be wired to handle that,'' Ide
said. ``The TV will become like the computer. You'll be able to
order movies from a Web site on the TV using a remote control.''
</P>
<P>
   Bethany Green in Alpharetta provides a glimpse into that future.
The buyer of Chatham Holdings' model smart house there will be able
to control a multiroom, multisound audio system from a keypad on
the kitchen wall. The system includes a compact disc player and a
radio, and is tied into music channels from an 18-inch satellite.
</P>
<P>
   The owner will be able to program ``lifestyle preferences'' into
the home's central control panel tucked away in a small hallway
between the main foyer and the kitchen. The main control panel is
the base for the house's security, lighting, and heating and
air-conditioning systems.
</P>
<P>
   Similar to smart keys on a computer, the system gives homeowners
the ability to program their heating, air, security and lighting
systems for frequently used settings. When away, homeowners can
change preferences by calling their house on the phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``With your 'good night' button you can arm your security
system, turn off the lights and set your heating and air at the
preferred temperatwre,'' Ide said. ``'Vacation' does things like
set heating and air at a minimum and program lights to come on at
night so it appears you're home.''
</P>
<P>
   Smart-house technology has been around for at least a decade,
but builders have steered clear of it until now because of
additional costs to upgrade the interior wiring, said builder Jim
Bankes, who plans to build 80 high-tech houses at Rivermoore Park,
a 530-house neighborhood in Suwanee. The wiring adds about $1,200
to the cost of a 3,600-square-foot house. House prices at
Rivermoore Park start at nearly $300,000.
</P>
<P>
   The new fiber-optic cabling being rolled out in metro Atlanta,
and increasing reliance on home offices, is making the technology a
necessity rather than a ``little toy,'' Bankes said. Home computers
are now in 40 percent of American homes. But they are a fixture in
65 percent of metro Atlanta homes, according to a new Horizon Metro
Poll released by The Atlanta Journal-Constitution. Industry experts
estimate Americans will spend as much as $5 billion this year on
networks and other home-automation products.
</P>
<P>
   Upgraded wiring was ``definitely a selling point'' for Richard
Woyce, a 34-year-old computer software product manager. He works
from his house up to 40 percent of the time. Woyce and his wife,
Debra, moved into Rivermoore Park in March. High-speed Internet
access and more reliable online service are key benefits of owning
a smart house, he said. The couple also forked out $3,000 to hook
up a state-of-the-art security system. Eventually, Woyce envisions
installing a home theater. The house is wired for surround sound,
but building a home entertainment center costs $5,000 to $30,000,
said Ide, the home system designer.
</P>
<P>
   Families with busy lifestyles are the biggest market for
smart-house technology, but some senior citizens also are looking
for automated houses to make their lives easier, said Lisa
Montgomery, editor of Wayland, Mass.-based Electronic House
Magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes things easier for seniors because of instead of
running all over the house switching off every light, you do that
automatically with one command on your key pad,'' Montgomery said.
</P>
<P>
   Even if people don't want a smart house now, it might pay to put
in wiring when building, redecorating or adding space. The idea is
to create the capability for a wide range of future services. It
can cost 50 percent more to rewire an existing house.
</P>
<P>
   Buyers should do their homework before investing in home
technology products offered by builders and sold off the shelves at
the local computer super store, Montgomery warns.
</P>
<P>
   Voice-controlled systems are still in the development stage, as
some homeowners in Florida discovered. The sound of one couple's
pet parrot regularly activated their system, turning on the lights
and stereo while they were away. A barking dog led another
homeowner's system to place repeated long-distance calls to her
parents. And one homeowner, whose system was programmed to call
police at the mention of ``911,'' got visits from the police
whenever the TV program ``Rescue 911'' came on.
</P>
<P>
   In metro Atlanta, upgraded wiring is one of the most popular
features being built in new houses. But for most Atlantans, owning
a smart house is probably at least five years away, said Joe
Padilla, an Atlanta Home Builders Association spokesperson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Five or 10 years ago, we were talking about Corian countertops
and two-car garages; this (home technology) is taking us to the
next level,'' Padilla said. ``Five or 10 years from now, this will
be commonplace in every home.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheryl Crabb writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
