<HEADER>
A3458 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SODERBERGH-CLOONEY01-     06-30 1105
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SODERBERGH-CLOONEY01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Clooney may finally have a hit with ``Out of Sight''
 &HT;    By Dave Larsen
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Steven Soderbergh wiped the smirk off George
Clooney's face.
</P>
<P>
   The Cincinnati-area native and star of television's ER employed
his patented head-down, eyes-up acting style in a string of films
that included The Peacemaker , Batman &AMP; Robin and One Fine Day ,
with marginal box-office success.
</P>
<P>
   For his latest feature, Out of Sight , director Soderbergh
stripped down what he called Clooney's mercurial approach, forcing
him to be still. ``That's hard for an actor,'' Soderbergh said.
``It's hard to believe that you can stand there and not do a lot
and still have people want to watch you, but he can. He's
compelling.''
</P>
<P>
   The result is Clooney's most impressive performance, in the best
film of his career. Adapted from the Elmore Leonard novel of the
same name, Out of Sight opened Friday to strongly favorable
reviews.
</P>
<P>
   Clooney, more than anyone, knew that he needed a hit _ ``stat!''
as his television alter-ego, Dr. Douglas Ross, might say.
Especially since next season will be his last on the show.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was the first project that wasn't about, `OK, listen,
this is a great opportunity,' or `This is a great break,' ''
Clooney said, discussing the film earlier this month at a Beverly
Hills hotel. ``This is the first project that I read, after nine
months of looking for a script, and went, `This is the project I
want to do,' and went after it.''
</P>
<P>
   Out of Sight was executive produced by Barry Sonnenfeld, who
produced and directed the acclaimed adaptation of Leonard's Get
Shorty . Scott Frank, who earned a Golden Globe nomination for that
film's script, again adapted the screenplay. Soderbergh, best known
for independent films such as sex, lies and videotape , brings what
Clooney calls a filmmaker's sensibility to his first mainstream
feature.
</P>
<P>
   The actor _ an avid Leonard fan _ plays Jack Foley, a hard-luck
bank robber serving his third prison term, after his latest getaway
attempt was halted by a dead car battery. Foley escapes with plans
to steal $5 million in diamonds from a Wall Street billionaire who
served time for insider trading, but his jailbreak is nearly foiled
by a beautiful deputy federal marshal named Karen Sisco.
</P>
<P>
   Karen, played by Jennifer Lopez, winds up locked in the trunk of
a car with Jack. The two form an unexpected bond, leaving them both
wondering about what might have happened had they met under
different circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   ``I read four pages of the screenplay and called up my buddy and
said, `I found it,' ' Clooney recalled, looking characteristically
suave in blue shirt and charcoal suit. ``I hadn't even read the end
of the movie yet, and was like, `OK, I got the script.'
</P>
<P>
   Clooney was just coming off of Batman , which he described as a
tough year of work. ``Not just because physically it was kind of
demanding doing seven days a week for a year (shooting Batman and
ER ), but it was also that the project wasn't great,'' he admitted.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't just about the box-office being disappointing, which
it was. It was that the film itself was disappointing. And if I'm
going to play the role of Batman in Batman &AMP; Robin , then I have to
take some responsibility for that, which means that the next
project I do, I have to have more responsibility in the script.''
</P>
<P>
   Clooney would don the rubber Batsuit again if the movie focused
on the Dark Knight character, rather than cartoonish villains, but
knows that's unlikely. ``I think I buried that franchise,'' he said
with a self-effacing grin. ``I don't think I'll have to do that
again.''
</P>
<P>
   The 37-year-old actor was born in Lexington, Ky., and raised in
nearby Augusta. As a child, he pitched in on his father Nick
Clooney's Cincinnati talk show, but it wasn't until he was 20 _
when his late uncle, actor Jose Ferrer, came to Kentucky to make a
movie _ that George was bitten by the acting bug. His aunt,
Ferrer's third wife, is jazz singer and occasional ER guest star
Rosemary Clooney.
</P>
<P>
   It was Ferrer and his son Miguel, who provides the voice of the
villainous Shan-Yu in Disney's Mulan , who convinced him to move to
Los Angeles in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first play I ever did, (Jose) came to see me _ it was this
little Equity waiver play in downtown Los Angeles _ and I thought I
was brilliant in it,'' Clooney recalled. ``I was crying and yelling
and doing everything I thought was brilliant, and then at the end
of it, he's sitting there and I walk over and say, `What did you
think, Uncle Joe?' And he goes, `I would say to you to keep the
scenery out of your mouth, you don't know where it's been.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Clooney laughs at the memory. ``He was a great teacher for all
of that.''
</P>
<P>
   The actor's fondest recollections of growing up in this area
involve his beloved Cincinnati Reds, for whom he tried out after
playing college baseball at Northern Kentucky University. ``That's
what I was going to do,'' he quipped. ``I was only lacking skill.''
</P>
<P>
   Clooney attended the last game played at Crosley Field, and said
the 1970s, when the Reds were one of the best teams to ever play
the game, ``was the greatest time to be a kid, ever.'' His hero is
Tony Perez.
</P>
<P>
   He returns home four or five times a year to visit his parents.
His father is a host on the American Movie Classics cable channel,
and his mother, Nina, is on the Augusta city council. ``I always
spend time in Cincinnati because I happen to think that Cincinnati
is a great town,'' Clooney said. ``It's one of the few towns you go
into and the downtown is alive.''
</P>
<P>
   When in Cincinnati, Clooney frequents the Blue Wisp, a downtown
jazz club, for Big Band night on Wednesdays. ``It's just the
greatest place to hang,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Out of Sight , Clooney also has a cameo role in
Terence Malick's highly anticipated war drama, The Thin Red Line ,
which stars John Travolta, Sean Penn, Woody Harrelson, John Cusack
and Nick Nolte. He's considering another film with Soderbergh
called Leatherheads , about the birth of the NFL in the 1920s.
(Clooney is also a devoted Bengals fan.)
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, he's focusing on his final season of ER . He
credits the phenomenally popular medical drama with everything
that's come his way, but said that after five years, he will have
run the gamut with Dr. Ross.
</P>
<P>
   `` ER wasn't a stepping stone for me,'' Clooney said. ``It was a
landing area.''
</P>
<P>
   Dave Larsen writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
