<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 11:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3460 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DELL-IRELAND-ECONOMY-     06-30 1548
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELL-IRELAND-ECONOMY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tech companies help spur Irish economy
 &HT;    (EDS: Part of CoxNet's Dell/Ireland package)
 &HT;    By Jerry Mahoney
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMERICK, Ireland _ In the alley behind Gerry Walsh's
148-year-old business, a 50-foot-tall crane swings across the gray
sky. The racket of a concrete truck backing up to one of several
downtown apartment projects makes it impossible for Walsh to have a
conversation with an employee.
</P>
<P>
   The dapper, silver-bearded merchant doesn't mind. The
construction, as much as the parade of consumers that crowds the
sidewalk in front of his Newsom's department store on a blustery
afternoon, signals unprecedented prosperity for him and this city
of 80,000 on the River Shannon.
</P>
<P>
   The boom is not just in Limerick, where Dell Computer Corp. and
other large U.S. and European technology companies are hiring
furiously, but also in Dublin, Cork and most of the rest of the
Irish Republic.
</P>
<P>
   Just three decades ago, Ireland was a poor nation of small
villages and farms that had more in common with some Third World
countries than with the industrialized West. For more than 150
years, its best and most dependable export had been its people.
</P>
<P>
   Now Ireland has become Europe's top-performing economy. Last
year, the gross domestic product grew by 8.3 percent, compared to
2.2 percent growth in Germany, 3.5 percent in the United Kingdom
and 3.8 percent in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Record job growth and surging exports have been fueled by low
corporate taxes _ the corporate income tax is 10 percent _ and a
national policy that pays foreign companies to create jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly can't think of any time that has been comparable
in Ireland, or even in Europe. It's really quite astonishing,''
said Terry Baker, an economist with the Economic and Social
Research Institute, a consulting company in Dublin.
</P>
<P>
   Still, many Irish, imbued with their country's history of
poverty, famine and often brutal domination by England, worry that
the good times will disappear, like the elusive leprechauns of
Irish folklore hiding their pots of gold.
</P>
<P>
   It appears, however, that this pot of gold is no fairy tale.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of jobs
</P>
<P>
   Dell Computer Corp.'s expansion plans symbolize Ireland's
growing industrial clout.
</P>
<P>
   Dell is increasing its manufacturing capability in Limerick,
people and adding to its sales and support center in the Dublin
suburb of Bray. Overall, the expansion is expected to add 3,000
jobs to Dell's Irish operations over the next two to three years.
</P>
<P>
   Other American companies are expanding as well. Motorola Inc.
plans to hire more than 100 workers at an electronics plant in the
southern city of Cork, where it also is starting an advanced
semiconductor design facility.
</P>
<P>
   Intel Corp. last month opened a second Pentium chip
manufacturing plant near Dublin. The entire complex, Ireland's
largest manufacturing site, is expected to employ 4,000 workers by
2000.
</P>
<P>
   Xerox Corp., even as it is cutting jobs in other countries,
recently announced it will create 2,200 jobs in Dublin and in
Dundalk, near the Northern Ireland border.
</P>
<P>
   For many young people in Ireland, the jobs are opening doors to
new worlds.
</P>
<P>
   James Keays, 27, and his wife, Tracey, 26, bought a house in
Limerick two years ago. This spring, they took up skiing, jetting
off to the Pyrenees Mountains in Spain for a weeklong vacation on
the slopes.
</P>
<P>
   Before joining Dell, Keays was a waiter at a Limerick coffee
shop. Tracey, his then-girlfriend, worked at Dell and urged him to
apply.
</P>
<P>
   ``She said the money was good,'' said Keays, who installs
software on Dell computers for large customers. ``Before that, I
wouldn't have seen myself buying a house.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, technology companies, global pharmaceutical and
banking firms and thriving Irish-owned businesses, which have
piggybacked on the business of the multinationals, created 10,000
jobs. That is a record for this nation of 3.6 million people.
</P>
<P>
   More than any other factor, credit for the boom goes to
government policies, dating to the 1970s, that entice foreign
companies with generous cash incentives.
</P>
<P>
   The Irish also get high marks for their higher-education system,
which turns out graduates with skills geared toward key industries.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us, they're coming out with just the right degrees,'' said
Intel spokesman Howard High. ``When we rated them out, they came
out comparable to a University of California-Berkeley or a Stanford
University over here.''
</P>
<P>
   To maintain the good times, the government is pouring money into
schools and computer networks _ the equivalent of $450 million over
the next several years _ to prepare the country for the time when
the global companies move manufacturing sites to lower-cost
countries in Asia or Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where Ireland is unique is it offers a high-skill environment
at a moderate cost,'' said Martin Cronin, who directs the
government's effort to lure multinationals from his office in
Dublin.
</P>
<P>
   The average manufacturing wage in Ireland is about $19,200 a
year. In the Austin area, it is $21,400.
</P>
<P>
   Global concerns such as Dell, Intel and Citibank are providing
more than jobs. They are introducing modern management practices
that had been foreign to Irish workplaces.
</P>
<P>
   They are teaching their Irish managers skills whose benefits are
beginning to ripple across the economy, said Ed Walsh, a visionary
educator who founded Limerick University in the 1970s and built it
into a model for cooperation between higher education and business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Irish manufacturing was poor before, very inefficient,'' Walsh
said, sitting in a red overstuffed chair with his morning cup of
tea. ``We have a new generation of Irish people who are
well-educated and experienced in the best management practices.''
</P>
<P>
   Although they are not used to good economic times, the Irish
have been quick to capitalize on them.
</P>
<P>
   Gerry Walsh, the merchant, heads a Cork-based company that
recently purchased small department stores, including Newsom's, in
four cities.
</P>
<P>
   Sales at the Limerick hardware and housewares store have
increased 35 percent in three years, Walsh said.
</P>
<P>
   Several nearby merchants who are enjoying the vibrant trade are
remodeling stores and refurbishing dated facades.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lot of money in Limerick and the surrounds,'' Walsh
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lot of work in the computer industry in Limerick,
and the workers make good incomes.''
</P>
<P>
   Readers of ``Angela's Ashes'' might be amazed at the bustle, not
to mention the optimism. But reminders linger of the gritty city
described so poignantly in Frank McCourt's Pulitzer Prize-winning
book about his poverty-wracked Limerick family a half-century ago.
</P>
<P>
   On a sunny but cool morning this spring, a young homeless couple
and their two dogs slept near a boarded-up storefront on the fringe
of Limerick's downtown.
</P>
<P>
   Business and government leaders chafe at the nickname, ``Stab
City,'' that the Dublin newspapers gave Limerick a few years ago
after an outbreak of violence.
</P>
<P>
   There are pockets in both cities where unemployment runs as high
as 60 percent, said Jan O'Sullivan, a member of the Irish
Parliament and former mayor of Limerick.
</P>
<P>
   The problem persists despite hundreds of openings at Dell and
other employers, and O'Sullivan said the government must attack it
with training programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's basically a cycle,'' she said. ``The father and
grandfather were without jobs. A lot of people can't just go out
and get jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Even those benefiting from the new prosperity have complaints.
The most serious is the rising cost of housing.
</P>
<P>
   Demand for housing in the Dublin area, where the average cost of
a home is $132,000, will push prices up 25 percent this year,
according to a recent study by NCB Stockbrokers.
</P>
<P>
   Investors keen to take advantage of rising prices are buying new
apartment buildings before they're completed.
</P>
<P>
   Older buildings are snapped up and longtime residents are forced
out by rising rents.
</P>
<P>
   The Irish government said earlier this year that affordable
housing would be a national priority in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the economic growth, many mom-and-pop businesses
languish while the government pays companies such as Dell to create
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is very little money available for the guy who has a
small business and will only hire three or four people,'' said Doug
McLernon of Trinity University's economics department.
</P>
<P>
   Still, young and old alike are brimming with pride about the
country's economic health and membership in the European Union.
</P>
<P>
   There also is intense hope that the historic Northern Ireland
peace agreement, which voters overwhelmingly approved in May, will
finally put an end to the killings in the North and the South.
</P>
<P>
   While this may be Ireland's finest moment, the country's sad
history always clouds the national consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you put everything together,'' said Baker, the Dublin
economist, ``things have never been this positive for Ireland,
which, of course, makes everyone wonder what can go wrong and when
it will go wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Mahoney writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
