u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DELL-IRELAND-RILEY-CO     06-30 0829
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELL-IRELAND-RILEY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dell Computer attempts to build up service in Ireland
 &HT;    By Jerry Mahoney
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ When Dell Computer Corp. called last summer,
Mike Riley said, ``No thanks.''
</P>
<P>
   The 53-year-old manager had just opened a state-of-the-art call
center for Halifax plc, the British bank where he had built a
rewarding career over 35 years. Content, proud of the center and
confident in his understanding of banking, Riley brushed off the
overture from Dell. ``Technology is often a young man's game,''
Riley said he worried at the time.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, Dell wanted to move him from his home in Yorkshire,
England, to the Dublin suburb of Bray, to run the company's sales
and customer-support center for Ireland and the United Kingdom.
</P>
<P>
   Dell's operation in Bray handles more than 3,000 calls a day
from Irish and British customers seeking technical help.
</P>
<P>
   Such facilities have become corporate nerve centers that can
play a key role in a competitive environment.
</P>
<P>
   As the leading direct seller of computers, Dell has developed
its close contact with customers into an asset. For example, orders
received by phone, in which customers select the components they
want, may foretell shifts in buyer preferences.
</P>
<P>
   The increasing emphasis on providing good service that is
rippling across the computer industry adds pressure on PC makers to
quickly and accurately help customers who phone in with problems.
What's more, because the labor-intensive call centers are expensive
to operate, companies seek ways to make them as efficient as
possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``He set up some of the best call centers in Europe, period,''
said chief executive Michael Dell. ``So he got on our radar screen
in the search process.''
</P>
<P>
   But Riley, having spent most of his life in northern England,
did not relish the idea of moving his wife and two daughters across
the Irish Sea.
</P>
<P>
   That was last summer, and much has happened since, beginning
with a flight to Austin and a 90-minute conversation with Dell at
the company's Round Rock headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thirty-five years with the bank in the U.K., and I gave up
everything after talking to Michael,'' Riley recalled,
half-sitting, half-leaning, with arms folded, against a table in
the burgeoning Bray facility that he has run since last fall. ``It
was a leap of faith.''
</P>
<P>
   The two men talked about Dell's opportunities and challenges and
the role Ireland would play in the company's plans, said Dell, who
meets with most candidates for senior positions.
</P>
<P>
   ``(He) got very intrigued with the opportunity to do something
different and be a part of something special.''
</P>
<P>
   The United Kingdom is the oldest of Dell's overseas operations
and is its No. 2 market after North America. Dell's U.K. sales grew
by more than 50 percent last year, to more than $1 billion. While
Dell relies on large corporate accounts for more than half of its
sales, its consumer business more than doubled.
</P>
<P>
   On the job only eight months, Riley is making plans to hire 400
more workers and to double the size of the 106,000-square-foot
building in Bray, a Dublin suburb between the sea and green Wicklow
mountains.
</P>
<P>
   The company wants to push U.K. sales to $2 billion this year.
Riley finds Dell's rapid growth unsettling at times.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing I've learned is, if you don't manage growth, it
manages you,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite any concerns he may have about Dell's industry-leading
pace of growth, Riley has started a friendly competition with the
home office.
</P>
<P>
   Emboldened by strong fourth-quarter sales of the popular
Dimension desktop computer, which resulted in a higher average
price than it brought in North America, Riley challenged the Texas
headquarters to beat the U.K. on average price this year.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Larson, Dell's vice president and general manager for the
United Kingdom and Ireland, learned of the challenge in a meeting
with Riley and other supervisors two days after she arrived from
Austin in February.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm thinking, 'Uh oh ... I haven't even had a chance to review
these numbers yet','' she said. `` 'What is this guy talking
about?' ``
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, 'Come on, Susan,' `` Larson recalled, laughing. ``
'Let's not be a wimp. You're over here now. You're one of us. We've
got to go challenge those guys.' ``
</P>
<P>
   The competition is now formal, with updates posted for employees
on Dell's internal network.
</P>
<P>
   Another Riley goal, when he finds the time, is to establish a
paperless workplace at the Bray center. That means that every
letter, report and memo from a multitude of sources is properly
dealt with immediately -- scanned in and filed in the database.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dream is to come up with something so good that the
Americans have to swallow deeply and say, 'We're going to do that.'
``
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Mahoney writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
