<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980630.0066 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 11:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3464 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DELL-IRELAND-MAIN-COX     06-30 2277
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELL-IRELAND-MAIN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dell Computer bases assault on Europe from Ireland
 &HT;    By Jerry Mahoney
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMERICK, Ireland _ Shortly after boarding a plane in Chicago
for a flight to Austin in 1989, Desmond O'Malley pulled out notes
on his next appointment.
</P>
<P>
   Ireland's minister of industry and commerce couldn't believe his
eyes. His staff was sending him to drum up investment from a $17
million computer company called PC's Limited, whose founder and
chief executive was only 24.
</P>
<P>
   O'Malley couldn't imagine someone so young would be worth his
time, and he let his staff know he was displeased. ``But they told
me this was a very special 24-year-old,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   O'Malley's skepticism dissipated shortly into his two-hour
meeting with Michael Dell.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very impressed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dell already had a sales operation in London, and the CEO was
``in a great hurry'' to go after the European market. O'Malley knew
of a vacant Atari plant in Limerick.
</P>
<P>
   By early fall 1990, only 10 months later the meeting, several
hundred workers in Dell's new Limerick plant were rolling out
desktops and notebook computers.
</P>
<P>
   The irony of the story grows every time O'Malley, now a member
of the Irish Parliament, tells it. Dell Computer Corp. is now the
third-biggest PC maker in the world. And Ireland has become the
staging area for Dell's assault on the ready-to-boom European
market, the next big battleground in the PC wars.
</P>
<P>
   Dell now has a sales and support call center in suburban Dublin
and two plants in Limerick that make computers for customers
throughout Europe, the Middle East and Africa. A planned third
Limerick plant will increase Dell's Irish work force to 4,500, its
largest outside of Central Texas, where it has 12,000 employees.
</P>
<P>
   Ireland ``is really the backbone of Dell's infrastructure in
Europe,'' Michael Dell said in a recent interview.
</P>
<P>
   And Europe is crucial to Dell's ambitions to become the No. 1
computer maker.
</P>
<P>
   Europe provides nearly 25 percent of Dell's revenues _ $3
billion in the last fiscal year. Analysts' projections for this
year are as high as $5 billion. Many European countries are coming
out of a recession, and the European Union is knocking down trade
barriers, forcing companies to modernize their operations to
compete.
</P>
<P>
   The Irish, from government agencies in Dublin to Dell employees
in Limerick and the Dublin suburb of Bray, are well aware of their
country's role in Dell's ambitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The message from Michael Dell is so clear and unequivocal
about Ireland's importance for Dell in Europe,'' said Fiona
Hopkins, a technical support supervisor in the Bray call center.
Ireland's strength
</P>
<P>
   Ireland, known for its lush scenery and rich literary tradition,
may seem an unlikely place for a company like Dell. But Ireland has
emerged in the last decade as one of the strongest economies in
Europe. It has lured scores of foreign companies, many of them
high-tech firms, with low taxes, job-creating incentives and a
well-educated work force.
</P>
<P>
   Dell is both a foundation of the new Irish economy and an engine
of change, exporting from the U.S. its lean build-to-order
manufacturing approach and modern management practices.
</P>
<P>
   Its employees recite the benefits of the Dell approach but have
had to adapt to the rapid, sometimes frenetic pace that the system
demands. Dell doesn't build a computer until it's been ordered and
paid for, and some PCs are shipped within hours of the order.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't tend to have the kind of red tape where you have to
go through the correct chain of command,'' said Aine O'Dwyer, who
works at the Bray call center, which handles orders from Irish and
British customers. ``Decisions are made so quickly that you just
don't have time for that kind of bureaucracy.''
</P>
<P>
   Across the island in the original Limerick plant, Denis Kelly,
42, a manufacturing manager, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care who solves the problem,'' he said. ``I just want
it solved.
</P>
<P>
   At the brightly lit Limerick factory, the employees, aware that
competitors are adopting Dell's approach, are under constant
pressure to shave even pennies and seconds from operations. The
loudest sound in the factory is the occasional hum from a power
tool. On average, the plant produces more than 4,000 computers a
day.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the only thing that differentiates my process is
automation, they (competitors) can buy it as quick as I can,'' said
Kelly. ``So there has to be something different for us to stay
ahead of them. They can't instill the Dell philosophy as fast as I
can here.''
</P>
<P>
   The factory moves so quickly that employees returning from even
brief vacations are required to meet with training instructors to
see whether the system they learned is still in use.
</P>
<P>
   Dell is growing so fast in Ireland that new jobs are always
available, offering employees bigger paychecks and training in new
skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm measured on how successfully I move people into other
operations,'' said Kelly, who by mid-morning one recent day had
interviewed eight employees for a new post on the factory floor.
</P>
<P>
   Since joining Dell five years ago as an assembly-line operator
at Limerick, James Keays, 27, has graduated to three other
positions, including repair technician and training instructor.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Higgins, 27, leads an area known as Dell Plus, where large
orders of computers are diverted briefly so software specific to
corporate customers can be installed. He's putting in 50 hours a
week and plans to advance up the ladder.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look toward a manager role,'' Higgins said. ``It's a policy
of the company.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Dell culture challenges traditional Irish assumptions
and practices.
</P>
<P>
   The Irish are not accustomed to working weekends, particularly
Sundays. Contract workers help keep the Limerick plants and the
Bray call center going seven days a week.
</P>
<P>
   Dell doesn't allow smoking at work, a problem in a country of
heavy smokers. But employees have no complaints about the chance to
share in Dell's success by owning stock. ``The growth is beneficial
for everybody. It means there are always new opportunities
coming,'' O'Dwyer said. ``We're all very keen to see the stock
price rise.''
</P>
<P>
   Dell has had to make some adaptations of its own. Because many
Irish don't drive, Dell buses employees back and forth every day.
</P>
<P>
   Standing on the polished factory floor, Kelly reflected on the
clash between modernization and Irish culture that surfaces when he
has to correct an employee's performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Ireland, the family is still very strong,'' he said. ``Most
of us (supervisors) will see these boys and girls as adopted sons
and daughters. If 'twas my daughter, I'd put my arm around her and
say, 'Look, honey, you ain't doin' what you're supposed to do.'
</P>
<P>
   ``You obviously can't do that in a corporate environment,''
Kelly said, adding. ``Unfortunately, in my opinion.'' The Irish
deliver
</P>
<P>
   Michael Dell praises the performance of his company's Irish
operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ireland has just exceeded all of our expectations,'' he said.
``And we've continued to make commitment after commitment,
investment after investment there, because the operation and the
people there keep delivering.''
</P>
<P>
   Dell will need its Irish work force to keep delivering.
</P>
<P>
   In the battle for Europe, the second-largest market behind the
United States, Dell faces archrivals Compaq Computer Corp., IBM and
Hewlett-Packard Co. as well as ambitious smaller European companies
such as Vobis Microcomputers of Germany.
</P>
<P>
   But at the moment, Dell may be the most feared of the big PC
makers. With its efficient manufacturing system, it can fill orders
and upgrade technology faster than its rivals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I describe 1997 as the year of Dell paranoia,'' said Simon
Pearce, an analyst with International Data Corp. in London who
studies the European market. ``When I went to the vendors, all they
could talk about was Dell.'' Changes in Europe
</P>
<P>
   Three looming changes in Europe offer PC companies a market with
staggering opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   First, Europe is emerging from a recession that stifled spending
and may have created pent-up demand for computers as well as other
goods. Second, companies may go on a spree of computer buying as a
way to avoid potentially massive computer confusion when the
calendar switches to 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The most important change begins Jan. 1, when 11 European
nations become a single market that will phase in a single
currency, the euro. Trade barriers between them also will fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's happening is a lot of these companies are waking up to
the old idea of productivity,'' Dell said in an interview earlier
this month, two days after returning from visiting customers and
operations in Italy, Switzerland and Germany.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're a banker or a construction company or any kind of
business, you pretty much realize that you're going to have
competition from European competitors and you're no longer in this
island market that's protected under one country,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Western Europe's Europe's economy is roughly the same size as
the U.S. economy but has half as many computers. Europeans bought
only 23 percent of 80.6 million computers sold worldwide last year.
The United States accounted for nearly 48 percent, according to
Dataquest, an industry research company.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a common currency and lowered trade barriers,
pan-European trade will have little resemblance to commerce in the
United States, where companies easily cross state lines. Each
market will require a tailored marketing strategy, said Chris Jones
of Dataquest.
</P>
<P>
   Through 18 subsidiaries in Europe, Dell is tailoring its
approach to individual markets. Selling computers in Germany will
require a different approach than selling them in Italy. The
Internet is increasingly important to Dell's direct-sales models,
and it has Web sites in more than a dozen European languages.
</P>
<P>
   Dell's European customers include such blue bloods as British
Petroleum and the German automaker Daimler-Benz. Dell's desktops
and servers help run operations throughout the government
bureaucracies of England and Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   But at Trinity University in Dublin, the economics department
recently replaced a half-dozen or so Dell computers with Gateway
machines because of complaints among faculty and staff about
service.
</P>
<P>
   The Irish government's Department of Enterprise, Trade and
Employment has nearly 400 Dell computers out of 660 throughout the
department.
</P>
<P>
   While they're ``very reliable,'' Dell's slowness to send help
when a problem does arise is annoying, said Richard Barry, who
helps maintain the department's computer network.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes we have to remind them that we have a three-year
warranty,'' Barry said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about these complaints, sales director Tim McCarthy in
Bray acknowledged that some customers have legitimate concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I can give you names of many happy customers,'' he said. A
crowded field
</P>
<P>
   Among the handful of global computer makers that control the $80
billion industry, Dell had the best financial performance in 1997.
Revenue soared 58 percent and profit rose 82 percent. While working
with a larger base, Compaq's revenues rose 22.8 percent and profits
were up 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Dell maintained its momentum in the first quarter of this year,
earning $357 million on $4.3 billion, while IBM, Compaq and
Hewlett-Packard disappointed investors because of price cuts. The
quest to become No. 1 requires Dell to elbow aside an aggressive
Hewlett-Packard, which passed Dell as the fastest-growing PC maker
in the first quarter and leads Dell in France and Germany. Dell has
a much bigger challenge catching Compaq, which not only leads Dell
in the major European markets but overtook Dell as Ireland's No. 1
PC vendor in the first quarter, according to estimates by
International Data Corp. Compaq got a third of its $25 billion in
sales last year from European customers.
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard recently opened a second European plant in
Holland, and Compaq acquired an up-to-date manufacturing site in
Scotland when it bought Digital Equipment Corp. this spring.
</P>
<P>
   Dell executives hope to take market share from Compaq while it's
busy combining its operations with those of Digital. ``Compaq is
looking more like a sumo wrestler now,'' said Ashok Kumar, an
analyst with the Piper Jaffray investment firm. ``With the DEC
acquisition, they've put on some weight.''
</P>
<P>
   Compaq officials declined to comment about the coming battle in
Europe. Several European companies have formed a coalition across
borders to reduce the prices they pay for components. Vobis and
Siemens Nixdorf lead the American-based PC companies in the German
market, but analysts expect that, in time, Dell and the other U.S.
companies will dominate Germany as well as the rest of Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The PC business has always been fiercely competitive, and that
will continue as key battlegrounds shift around the world.
</P>
<P>
   The coming battle is in Europe, but Dell also is planting its
stake in other markets.
</P>
<P>
   The company is building a small manufacturing and sales facility
in China, another country with huge potential. Later this year
comes a factory in South America, probably Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way I think about it is, look, there's 300 million PCs in
the world today,'' Dell said. ``About 30 percent get replaced every
year. Ten years from now there will be 1.4 billion machines.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean this is the beginning of an industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Mahoney writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
