<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 11:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3503 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HORSE-MEAT-HNS &LR;      06-30 0881
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HORSE-MEAT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INITIATIVE TO ASK CALIFORNIANS THIS FALL TO `JUST SAY NEIGH' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT SALLADAY  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ Here's a secret that won't be whispered to
many horses: California every year supplies the world's restaurants
with thousands of pounds of horse meat for cold cuts, sausages,
steaks and stews.
</P>
<P>
   It's something Barbara Clarke of Carmel doesn't like to tell the
38 equine tenants of the sprawling Redwings Horse Sanctuary. Clarke
regularly attends ``killer-buyer'' auctions to rescue horses from
becoming dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Clarke once bought a sad-looking pony at auction for $28.40,
about the same price that two servings of the tiny white-haired
pony, now called Angel, might have fetched in a Japanese or
European restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   In November, a popular way to dispose of unwanted race horses
and family ponies _ selling them for pennies a pound to
slaughterhouses _ could become a felony in California, punishable
by up to three years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   An initiative slated for the ballot would outlaw the export of
California horses for human consumption, the first such outright
ban in the country. The ``Save the Horses'' initiative also makes
selling horse meat a misdemeanor, although no restaurants are known
to serve the meat in the state.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign's slogan: ``Just Say Neigh.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We know it's going to put a stop to this favorite dumping
ground for horse owners,'' said Clarke, who became a vegetarian
after attending horse auctions and who strongly supports the
initiative. ``It's going to make people take a second look at their
responsibilities as owners of sentient beings.''
</P>
<P>
   The initiative has brought out officials at horse
slaughterhouses in Texas and elsewhere, who defend their killing
methods as humane despite gruesome tales from activists.
</P>
<P>
   Even some horse lovers have a few reservations about the
initiative. Grace Belcuore, president of California Equine
Retirement Foundation, which rescues and rehabilitates discarded
race horses, said she supported the movement but worried about
where the horses would end up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm crowded right now,'' said Belcuore, who takes care of
about 40 horses at her Riverside County ranch. ``I won't put 100
horses in the field. ... This is a wonderful thing that is
happening, but where are they going to go?''
</P>
<P>
   Non-Muslim and non-Jewish Europeans and Asians have been eating
horse meat for centuries. The Celts and Mongols ate horse, and the
citizens of Venice developed a taste for it in the early Middle
Ages during a famine.
</P>
<P>
   In modern Japan, diners pay huge amounts to eat raw, thinly
sliced horse sashimi with soy sauce, wasabi and ground ginger. A
restaurant in rural Belgium, De Kuiper's, serves horse meat and
proudly displays a sign outside: ``Major specialists in horse meat
since 1859.''
</P>
<P>
   Although frontier explorers, including Louis and Clark, ate
horse for survival, most Americans take a more romantic view of the
equine family. It's a folklore that stretches from the Wild West to
the New Age's ``The Horse Whisperer'' book and movie.
</P>
<P>
   There are no bovine equivalents to Black Beauty and Trigger, and
the initiative backers believe that, like cats and dogs, horses are
different from other food animals.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are our heritage,'' said Cathleen Doyle, founder of the
California Equine Council and chief sponsor of the November
initiative. ``Certainly today, the horse is a companion animal, and
we would no more allow our dogs and cats to be secretly bought up
and slaughtered and sent off to other countries than we would our
horses.''
</P>
<P>
   Americans can easily buy horse meat through mail-order companies
in Canada, Japan and Denmark. Two years ago, the U.S. Department of
Agriculture, which inspects horse slaughterhouses, even advised
Americans about the proper ways to store and cook horse flesh.
</P>
<P>
   ``Retail cuts of horse are similar to those of beef,'' a USDA
advisory from February 1997 reads. ``The meat is leaner, slightly
sweeter in taste, with a flavor somewhat between that of beef and
venison.''
</P>
<P>
   After getting stonewalled in Congress and the California state
legislature, partly because of the powerful farm lobby, Doyle
teamed up with activists Sherry DeBoer and Sidne J. Long, heiresses
to the Long's Drug Store fortune and founders of Political Animals.
The trio has so far raised $700,000 and produced a 30-second TV ad
for the initiative.
</P>
<P>
   They have enlisted the support of numerous celebrities,
including ``The Horse Whisperer'' star Robert Redford and Diane
Keaton. They have secured endorsements from the U.S. Equestrian
Team, the Thoroughbred Owners of California and race tracks
including Golden Gate Fields.
</P>
<P>
   The group's biggest concern is how the horses are treated on
their way to slaughter and after they arrive. A hidden-camera video
taken by farm animal rights activists shows some horses writhing
after being shot through the skull with a four-inch bolt, the
standard killing method.
</P>
<P>
   The USDA says 113,499 horses were slaughtered last year in the
country. Doyle estimates as many as 10,000 California horses are
slaughtered every year. California is home to 750,000 horses, about
20 percent of all horses in America.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
