</P>
<P>
   HIV-THERAPY (San Francisco) _ Although drug treatments greatly
suppress many HIV patients' level of the AIDS-causing virus, most
patients will experience resurgences of the virus within a year,
researchers forecast. By KEAY DAVIDSON.
</P>
<P>
   GOP-CONVENTION (San Antonio) _ Visiting Republican Party
officials checked out the Alamodome as a possible site for the
party's 2000 presidential convention. They said they were impressed
with the welcome. By ANITA McDIVITT.
</P>
<P>
   NY-POLL (Albany, N.Y. ) _ Given a blank check, New Yorkers would
spend more to improve mass transit, education and health care. They
are also willing to pay higher prices for milk to help struggling
dairy farmers. But they're not anxious to boost funding for welfare
or build new prisons, according to a new poll. By TRACEY TULLY.
</P>
<P>
   NY-ECONOMY (Albany, N.Y.) _ New Yorkers are feeling better about
the state's economy than they have in years, according to the
latest Times Union-Syracuse Newspapers poll, and that should bode
well for Gov. George Pataki and other incumbents on Election Day.
By ALAN D. ABBEY
</P>
<P>
   NY-SENATE-DEBATE (Bolton Landing, N.Y.) _ One credits her
mother. One points to Ralph Nader. Another praises his daughters.
The three Democrats _ Geraldine Ferraro, New York City Public
Advocate Mark Green and Congressman Charles Schumer _ answered the
question: ``Who has been the greatest influence on your life?'' By
JAMES M. ODATO.
</P>
<P>
   GULF-SYNDROME (San Francisco) _ Writer Seymour Hersh, author of
``Against All Enemies _ Gulf War Syndrome: The War Between
America's Ailing Veterans and Their Government,'' said his hunch is
that ailing veterans and active duty soldiers were exposed to toxic
substances in the Gulf. By KATHLEEN SULLIVAN.
</P>
