<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BE CAREFUL HOW YOU WEAR YOUR FLAG 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Thanks partly to California Sen. Dianne
Feinstein, we should be seeing a lot more flag burnings. That is to
say, more than almost none. There's nothing like making something
illegal to make it fun.
</P>
<P>
   It was barely noted in the press, but last week Feinstein helped
a constitutional amendment against flag desecration get through the
Senate Judiciary Committee, of which she is a member. Other
Democrats fought hard against it.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation was passed by the House two weeks ago, and now
it goes to the full Senate, where it is only a few senators short
of the two-thirds vote needed for passage, according to the
American Legion.
</P>
<P>
   If it is ratified by the legislatures of three-quarters of the
states (which is likely, given the prevalence of political
pandering), you can kiss your old Abbie Hoffman flag shirt and your
old First Amendment goodbye.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court ruled in 1989 that flag burning is a form of
speech warranting First Amendment protection. I don't like people
who burn the American flag, but why write them into the
Constitution when a punch in the nose will do?
</P>
<P>
   The court also has ruled that money donated to politicians is a
form of free speech. You don't see a rush by Congress to pass an
amendment banning that form of speech, which has proven much more
destructive to democracy than imaginary flaming flags.
</P>
<P>
   No, Congress is wrapping itself in the flag and bravely
attacking a problem that doesn't exist. Even the Citizens Flag
Alliance, which lobbies for the amendment, can count only six flag
burnings this year.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the amendment doesn't mention flag burning, but
says Congress can outlaw flag ``desecration,'' which means to
profane, or treat as not sacred.
</P>
<P>
   This could be extended to flag bikinis, flag running shorts, or
Jasper Johns paintings of the flag, if they're deemed unpatriotic
by the likes of Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Admittedly, it might be nice to outlaw photos of Monica Lewinsky
hanging all over Old Glory in Vanity Fair, but the cost to liberty
isn't worth it.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
