<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 13:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3667 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-HISTBOX     06-30 0648
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-HISTBOX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    WESTERN BUSINESS MAKES A COMEBACK IN CHINA
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    With CHINA-CLINTON-MAIN 
 &HT;    By JOSEPH ALBRIGHT and MARCIA KUNSTEL 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service (at)
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Western business in China stopped after the 1949
communist revolution, and not until top leader Deng Xiaoping opened
his economic reforms did the Chinese market become accessible
again. Here are some high points of the comeback:
</P>
<P>
   June 1978 - Henry Ford II and other Ford executives meet Chinese
paramount leader Deng Xiaoping, as a prelude to Ford Motor Co.
becoming the first U.S. auto manufacturer to enter the Chinese
market.
</P>
<P>
   Jan. 1, 1979 - President Jimmy Carter normalizes relations with
the People's Republic of China.
</P>
<P>
   Jan. 24, 1979 _ A shipment of 20,000 cases of Coca-Cola is
unloaded in Canton, the first Western goods to be sold in China for
three decades.
</P>
<P>
   Mid-1979 - Ford sells 750 F-series trucks to China in mid-1979,
the first American-made cars sold in China since the 1949 communist
takeover. Ford's China business would plateau in the 1980s. But
activity picks up in 1997 when a minivan called the China Transit
begins rolling off a Ford joint venture's assembly line.
</P>
<P>
   1985 - Hewlett-Packard becomes the first American company to
establish a high-tech joint venture in China. It launches a
partnership with Beijing Computer Industry Co. and a Chinese state
electronics import company.
</P>
<P>
   1987 - Motorola sets up a small office in China. Over the next
decade, Motorola would grow to $1.1 billion of investment, with
plans to reach $2.5 billion by 2000. Motorola is China's biggest
wholly owned foreign company and the largest foreign investor in
the electronics industry in China.
</P>
<P>
   1993 - GM's Delphi Automotive Systems opens a China
representative office with three expatriates working out of a
hotel. Over the next five years, GM and Delphi would buy major
stakes in 17 Chinese car and auto parts factories with 9,000
Chinese workers. Late in 1999, a GM joint venture is due to roll
out its first Chinese-made car, a luxury model patterned on the
Buick Regal.
</P>
<P>
   1995 - Motorola invests $53 million in the Leshan-Phoenix joint
venture in Sichuan Province, its first in China. The plant now
makes 1.4 billion semiconductor parts.
</P>
<P>
   Feb. 6, 1996 - President Clinton signs waivers for four launches
of American-made satellites aboard Chinese rockets. One of the
launch rockets crashes, destroying a $200 million satellite of the
U.S.-based Loral Space Systems. Loral engineers help determine the
cause of the Chinese rocket crash, and some U.S. congressmen charge
that Loral's assistance may have helped the Chinese improve the
reliability of their long-range nuclear rockets.
</P>
<P>
   June 1996 - Eli Lilly begins assembling a state-of-the-art
factory in the city of Suzhou, using building modules imported from
Sweden, to manufacture the antibiotic Ceclor. Within two years Eli
Lilly would spread a sales network of 350 people in 28 Chinese
cities to sell antibiotics, insulin and the antidepressant Prozac.
</P>
<P>
   Dec. 31, 1997 - A Chinese survey shows 21 out of the 30 largest
U.S. Fortune 500 companies had investments in China. Overall,
American investors had contracted to invest $40.1 billion in 24,436
projects in China.
</P>
<P>
   March 28, 1998 - Coca-Cola opens its 21st bottling plant in
China. Chinese news agencies report that investment by Coca-Cola
and its Chinese venture partners will reach $800 million by 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Mid-April 1998 - China bans all direct-selling firms, including
Avon, Amway and Mary Kay, from person-to-person sales in China,
saying the practice ``damaged social stability.'' A protest by
visiting U.S. Trade Representative Charlene Barshefsky fails to
reverse the Chinese ban.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
