<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 13:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3697 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JULY-FOURTH-AWFUL-FLI     06-30 1012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JULY-FOURTH-AWFUL-FLICKS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AWFUL FILMS FOR THE HOLIDAY WEEKEND 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (This has already moved to clients of Richard Roeper's popular
weekly columns, now being offered as a regular New York Times
Syndicate feature. For a bio &AMP; photo _ as well as special contract
rates _ please contact your sales representative:
 &HT;    _ If you're in the Eastern time zone or Canada, call BOB FARNELL
at 1-800-535-4425. Or send a fax to him at (717) 646-4850.
 &HT;    _ If you're in the Central time zone, call CONNIE WHITE at
1-800-444-0267. Or fax her at (816) 822-1444.
 &HT;    _ If you're in the Pacific or Mountain time zones or in Latin
America, call OLIVIA VASQUEZ at (310) 996-0075. Or fax her at (310)
996-0089.
 &HT;    
 By RICHARD ROEPER  
 c.1998 The Chicago Sun-Times  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Forget about that American Film Institute list of the 100
greatest American films of all time.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, forget about great movies altogether. On this
Independence Day weekend, I salute ``Independence Day'' _ and 49
other turkeys _ as the worst movies I've ever seen.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, ``ID4'' was a monster hit, but try to sit through that
piece of drek again if you consider yourself a fan. It's riddled
with more sappy cliches than a boxed-set video of the Jerry Lewis
Telethon.
</P>
<P>
   After perusing countless film guides and soliciting suggestions
from dozens of film-loving friends, I've compiled a list of 50
movies so bad they make your teeth hurt.
</P>
<P>
   Why 50? Because a list of 100 would make your head hurt, and
besides, it wouldn't fit in this space.
</P>
<P>
   The criteria: No cheapie slasher flicks, no low-budget bombs, no
straight-to-video duds. When these movies were released, they were
not thought of as camp classics or interesting failures; they were
supposed to be mainstream hits, but they missed.
</P>
<P>
   By a mile.
</P>
<P>
   In alphabetical order _ there's no way you can say ``North'' is
worse than ``Heaven's Gate,'' awful is awful _ here are the 50
lousiest movies I've ever seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arthur 2: On the Rocks'' (1988). Arthur sobers up, loses sense
of humor.
</P>
<P>
   ``BAPS'' (1997). Demeaning would-be comedy. What was Halle
thinking?
</P>
<P>
   ``Ben-Hur'' (1959.) The most boring epic ever made.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Babe Ruth Story'' (1948). Awful athlete William Bendix as
the Babe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beverly Hills Cop 3'' (1994). Eddie looks bored. So are we.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bio-Dome'' (1995). There's no excuse for Pauly Shore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob &AMP; Carol &AMP; Ted &AMP; Alice'' (1969). Boring &AMP; Trite &AMP; Dated &AMP;
Stupid.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chitty Chitty Bang Bang'' (1968). Sputter sputter klunk klunk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Crash'' (1996). Sick people get turned on by serious auto
accidents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Days of Thunder'' (1990). Testosterone turkey driven by Tom
Cruise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Death Becomes Her'' (1992) Shrill and pointless.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't Tell Her It's Me'' (1991) Steve Guttenberg vehicle about
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dune'' (1984). What's that thing in their noses?
</P>
<P>
   ``Exit to Eden'' (1994). Rosie O'Donnell in leather and chains.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forget Paris'' (1995). Bird gets stuck in Debra Winger's hair.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Godfather, Part 3'' (1990). Sofia Coppola and George
Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Godzilla'' (1998). It's only going to get worse with time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Great Race'' (1965). Endless.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Green Berets'' (1968). Horrible propaganda.
</P>
<P>
   ``Heaven's Gate'' (1980). Legendarily bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``Independence Day'' (1996). Insultingly awful.
</P>
<P>
   ``Indecent Proposal'' (1993). Like Redford would have to pay.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ishtar'' (1987). Even worse than you remember.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jinxed'' (1982). Bette Midler and Ken Wahl, a match made in
purgatory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Johnny Be Good.'' (1988). Anthony Michael Hall as a jerko
jock.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Last Boy Scout'' (1991). Loud, vulgar, sexist and idiotic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leonard Part 6'' (1987). Bill Cosby's worst effort in any
medium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Link'' (1986). Chimp lusts after Elisabeth Shue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Listen to Me'' (1989). College debate team drama with Kirk
Cameron.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mall Rats'' (1995). I'd rather chew tinfoil than watch this
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mame'' (1974). Still mad at my mom for making me sit through
this.
</P>
<P>
   ``Man Trouble'' (1992). Nicholson and Barkin in a deadly comedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Me and Him'' (1987). Griffin Dunne has conversations with his
sex organ.
</P>
<P>
   ``My Stepmother is an Alien'' (1988). And she can't act!
</P>
<P>
   ``1941'' (1979). Spielberg's biggest bomb.
</P>
<P>
   ``North'' (1994). Try to watch this from start to finish. It's
impossible.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, Heavenly Dog!'' (1980). Benji out-acts Chevy Chase.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Pest'' (1997). John Leguizamo is funny. Just not in this
movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Postman'' (1997). Nice futuristic mailman premise, Kev.
</P>
<P>
   ``Problem Child'' (1990). John Ritter adopts a brat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rambo III'' (1988). Even Stallone must be embarrassed by this
one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Regarding Henry'' (1991). Harrison Ford gets shot and it makes
him nicer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Showgirls'' (1995). Porno movies have better plots _ and
better acting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Speed 2'' (1997). Made Keanu Reeves look like a genius.
</P>
<P>
   ``Striptease'' (1996). Neither funny nor sexy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tommy'' (1975). Ann-Margret slithers in baked beans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Toys'' (1992). Cloying, precious message satire with Robin
Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``Weekend at Bernie's'' (1989). Corpse comedy is D.O.A.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where the Buffalo Roam'' (1990). Gonzo doesn't translate to
film.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yentl'' (1983). Barbara Streisand disguised as a boy. Right.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Send your comments - and nominations for the worst films
you've ever seen to Richard Roeper at 401 N. Wabash Ave., Chicago,
IL, 60611. E-mail: rroeper(AT)suntimes.com) &LR;
