<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COWBOYREUNION-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORTER ASSIGNED TO COWBOY REUNION IN '36 TO LEAD ITS PARADE 62
YEARS LATER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART CHAPMAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABILENE, Texas _ When 84-year-old Harry Holt first saw the Texas
Cowboy Reunion in Stamford, it was 1936 and the Dust Bowl days
still hung over the vastness of West Texas. Holt was a pup reporter
then, running behind the chutes in the sweltering heat, trying
desperately to get a story.
</P>
<P>
   This year, he will be comfortably up front in the 68th reunion,
serving as grand marshal of the parade that kicks off four days of
celebration on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This deal is more than just a rodeo,'' explained Gary Mathis,
manager of the Swenson Ranches and organizer of the event. ``This
is a Texas cowboy reunion, and Harry has been in this part of the
country a long time. It is an honor for us to have him be a part of
this year's event.''
</P>
<P>
   Holt worked for 15 years as a reporter and columnist for the
Abilene Reporter News. He left the paper in 1953 and began a weekly
TV program called ``West Texas This Week'' and a daily ag report on
Abilene radio. They continue today.
</P>
<P>
   He remembers the heyday of the reunion, which began in 1931; he
has seen the difficult times as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``The year before I started covering it was 1935, the year that
Will Rogers was there,'' he said. ``Rogers came to Abilene with his
pilot, Wiley Post. Post once lived just outside Abilene.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyway, Rogers got a taxi and went to Stamford, unannounced,
and sat up in the bleachers in the hot sun.''
</P>
<P>
   Holt remembered that John Selman was manager of the Swenson
ranches back then and that when Selman recognized Rogers, he called
him down to the arena, gave him a horse and turned him loose.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rogers did his rope tricks and put on a show for the crowd,''
Holt said.
</P>
<P>
   A month later, Post and Rogers were killed in a plane crash.
</P>
<P>
   Holt had the painful job of informing Post's wife of her
husband's death. It was, he said, the hardest thing he ever had to
do.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was that Will Rogers touch, his presence, that put the
Cowboy Reunion over the top,'' Holt said. ``That, and the fact that
it was a pet project of Amon Carter.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter, the Fort Worth Star-Telegram's first publisher, and
Rogers were good friends, and after Rogers made his appearance at
Stamford, 40 miles north of Abilene, Carter began dispatching
reporters to West Texas to cover the Fourth of July weekend event.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters Mabel Gouldy, C.L. Richhart and Frank Reeves blanketed
the Cowboy Reunion, Holt said. The Abilene and Wichita Falls papers
then boosted their coverage, and the media attention made the event
irresistible to politicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last governor I remember coming was Preston Smith,'' Holt
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Cowboy Reunion has always been a ranch rodeo. Although
the neighboring ranches didn't enter as teams, the cowboys would
travel to Stamford together and camp together.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reunion was unique in that way,'' Holt said. ``The
contestants were real working cowboys. They would enter the wild
cow milking contest because they were used to roping cows out in
the pasture. Some of the cowboys today have never seen a wild
cow.''
</P>
<P>
   The women who participated were ranch hands, too, Holt said.
Riders like Ardeth Copeland, Fern Sawyer and Christine Northcutt.
</P>
<P>
   The first approved and sanctioned American Quarter Horse
Association show was held at the Cowboy Reunion. ``The King Ranch
was big then. Mr. Bob Kleberg came himself,'' Holt said.
</P>
<P>
   There were also a lot of good cutting horse competitions.
</P>
<P>
   Money was never really the object at Stamford, Holt said. It was
an amateur rodeo. First prize was only $35.
</P>
<P>
   ``But they gave away saddles and people would spend a lifetime
trying to win one of those saddles,'' Holt said.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, the reunion dwindled. The crowds and entries
shrank. It was, Holt said, simply a sign of the times. Every small
town now has its own rodeo and the competition for competitors is
tough.
</P>
<P>
   But Mathis said the Texas Cowboy Reunion is holding on. ``The
last four to five years we've really been coming back,'' he said.
``We've brought back some of the old activities like the wild cow
milking and a ranch horse competition. There has been interest in
the bit and spur show, the trade show and the chuck wagon cook-off
contests.
</P>
<P>
   ``We now give six trophy saddles, 13 buckles and last year we
handed out $53,000 in prize money.''
</P>
<P>
   It's the tradition, he said. No one wants to lose the tradition.
</P>
<P>
   Information on schedules and ticket prices for the Texas Cowboy
Reunion is available at (915) 773-3614 or (915) 773-2411.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
