<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HIV-THERAPY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESEARCHERS SAY HIV REBOUND IS NOT SO DIRE A SIGN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KEAY DAVIDSON  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Although drug treatments suppress the level of
the AIDS virus in patients, most of them will experience a
resurgence of HIV within a year, according to a group of California
researchers.
</P>
<P>
   But scientists at the University of California at San Francisco
say illness has struck surprisingly few of those whose viral levels
have risen again.
</P>
<P>
   This suggests many patients can stay healthy even if their
bodies contain measurable levels of the human immunodeficiency
virus, said Dr. John Nienow, who conducted the study with seven
colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   Hence, therapists should not prematurely alter the drug regimens
of patients by thinking that the resurgence of HIV to ``very low''
levels of detectability is a sign of treatment failure, Nienow
said.
</P>
<P>
   The findings were to be reported Tuesday by Nienow's colleague,
Dr. Donald Abrams, at the 12th World AIDS Conference in Geneva.
</P>
<P>
   The finding shows it is too early to suggest that new drug
treatments for AIDS have been over-promoted, Abrams said in a
telephone interview from Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patients are still benefiting from these treatments,'' Abrams
said. ``They are feeling better; their weight is up. ... Anybody
who takes care of HIV patients or knows an HIV patient on these
drugs knows that people are benefiting from the drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is, how long will they (benefit), and what are
the delayed side effects?'' That remains uncertain, Abrams added.
</P>
<P>
   The study focused on 233 patients who had been treated with
combination anti-retroviral therapy at 10 clinics in the San
Francisco area. Most were men, and 36 percent were ethnic
minorities. Five of the 233 were injection drug users; 55 percent
of the group had been diagnosed with AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   The drug treatments, including protease inhibitors, suppressed
their HIV levels to undetectable amounts, below 500 copies of the
AIDS virus per milliliter of blood. Ten months later, the study
found, the average patient's viral load had risen back to 2,932
copies of the virus per milliliter of blood.
</P>
<P>
   That is a relatively low amount of HIV, Nienow said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been my experience that patients on therapy who break
through at low levels remain at low levels and stay well,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good news that the vast majority of patients are doing
well clinically, though over one-half had a resurgence in their
viral load,'' Nienow said. ``What is surprising is that, so far,
many of the viral load breakthroughs have not been very high, and
we have seen very little progression of HIV disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``These findings suggest that maintaining undetectable viral
load levels may not be necessary to sustain wellness,'' he said.
``Loss of viral suppression doesn't appear to lead automatically to
clinical progression of disease.''
</P>
<P>
   The study was a combined effort of the university and the
Community Consortium, an association of 200 health care providers
that cares for HIV and AIDS patients in the San Francisco area.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-98 1339EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
