<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 13:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3723 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HONGKONG-YEAR-2ND &LR;  &UR; TA     06-30 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HONGKONG-YEAR-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 HONG KONG: ... Chinese businesses.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not everyone is so cynical. Peter Churchhouse, managing director
of Morgan Stanley's Hong Kong office, gives China high marks for
its conduct. He argues that Beijing has not interfered in Hong Kong
and has been supportive of its right to run its own affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Tang, chairman of the Federation of Hong Kong Industries
and a member of Chief Executive Tung Chee-hwa's Cabinet, says
Beijing never has tried to influence any meeting he attended. ``If
anything, we have more protests and more freedoms today,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But if Beijing has scored fairly high marks across the political
spectrum for leaving Hong Kong alone, the local government has been
given failing grades.
</P>
<P>
   David Zweig, a politics professor at Hong Kong University of
Science and Technology, says it is difficult to rate Hong Kong
leaders when they have had to cope with a spate of disasters _ from
the economic crash to a mysterious bird flu, from poisoned ice
cream to poisoned fish, from a mad cow scare to an arsenic spill on
the street. ``It's like trying to give a report card to a student
when the school walls have collapsed, his computer is
malfunctioning, and his pencils are breaking,'' Zweig said.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to keep track of all the demonstrations in front of
Government House these days, and citizens are demanding that the
Hong Kong government be accountable even for things it cannot
control.
</P>
<P>
   Investors whose brokers went bankrupt want compensation.
Homebuyers who put their life savings in down payments now cannot
get mortgages because of the collapsed real estate market. Chicken
vendors and fishermen want reimbursement for their financial losses
from the bird flu and the red tide disaster.
</P>
<P>
   The government and big business ``don't care about us _ the
common people, the poor _ and they are unable to come up with any
solution to ease the crisis,'' complained C. Cheung, a 45-year-old
hawker protesting his lost down payment one recent afternoon.
``They are just corrupt and impotent.''
</P>
<P>
   Just how did a civil service so highly esteemed before the
transfer sink so low?
</P>
<P>
   Sunny Lo, a political scientist at the University of Hong Kong,
suggests that locals and colonial officials ``exaggerated the
competence of the civil service'' to reassure people that
everything would be the same after the handover. ``But now they
cannot turn to expatriate officers for crisis decision-making, and
they themselves seem to be quite indecisive,'' he noted.
</P>
<P>
   It hasn't helped that the government has been caught napping,
flip-flopping, or simply clueless during numerous crises this year.
</P>
<P>
   The health secretary was on vacation at the height of the bird
flu. When the territory's chickens were slaughtered, at least
hundreds escaped the ax or were disposed of unhygienically. The
financial secretary gave the economy an A+ when it was the weakest
it has been in years. He declared that Hong Kong would enjoy 3.5
percent growth, and then revealed the next week it would contract 2
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Last month (June), after vowing to proceed with government land
sales despite pressure to restrict them, officials canceled the
auction a day before it was to happen.
</P>
<P>
   After the handover ``the civil service was supposed to take
front and center and political parties were supposed to fade away.
But just the opposite has happened,'' said Michael DeGolyer,
director of the transition project. ``The civil service went to its
offices and fell asleep ... while politicians who campaigned on
populist issues won big in the May elections.''
</P>
<P>
   Even more startling has been the seven-party coalition of
democratic and pro-Beijing parties formed to pressure the Hong Kong
government to improve its performance with the economy. The
coalition controls 48 of 60 legislative seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea was that if you just shut up and make money, there's
no need for democracy,'' DeGolyer said. But the plummeting economy
brought together former legislative rivals and helped push voter
turnout an astonishing 50 percent higher than it was for the last
elections under British rule.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a retooled electoral system that favors small parties
and business groups, the territory's popular Democratic Party
managed to secure the same percentage of votes it did in 1995. Yet
even after winning two-thirds of the votes cast for directly
elected posts, pro-democracy candidates were rewarded with only
one-third of the seats under the redesigned system.
</P>
<P>
   The pro-Beijing Liberal Party won nine seats with just 1,300
votes for seats held by special interest groups. The Democrats,
meanwhile, elected nine people with 633,000 direct, geographic
votes.
</P>
<P>
   And so what do those who warned of the worst say now? A year
ago, Martin Lee, Hong Kong's most famous democrat, said he didn't
think he would be jailed after the handover, but he couldn't be
sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today my answer is exactly the same,'' he said in a recent
interview. ``I can say things to you and not be put in jail because
of the law. But the law can be changed. ... The system works when
the pendulum swings to the left in China, and they still allow us
freedoms when they tighten up on the mainland.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet there are many people like Mary Chan, 55, a retired office
clerk, who believe that ``China is more free now'' and who hope
that Hong Kong will over time influence mainland China, rather than
vice versa.
</P>
<P>
   But the key is time. ``We still have 588 months to go for the
50-year pledge'' by China, said Liu, the editor. ``Please let's
keep a long horizon.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
