<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 13:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3726 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HONKONG-YEAR-2TAKES-B     06-30 0867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HONKONG-YEAR-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A YEAR LATER, HONG KONG'S WORST FEARS GO UNREALIZED 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ One year since doomsayers predicted the fall of Hong
Kong after its return to Chinese rule last July 1, David Chu wanted
fearmongers to eat their words _ literally.
</P>
<P>
   At his ``I Told You So'' party two days ago, the pro-Beijing
legislator triumphantly carved a cake decorated to ape the Fortune
magazine cover that prophesied ``The Death of Hong Kong.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Politics here has turned out better than anybody's
predictions,'' said Chu, 54, a Shanghai native who moved to
Bedford, Mass., as a teenager and spent 15 years in the Boston area
before settling in Hong Kong. ``The transition was peaceful. There
is freedom of expression. The press was recently rated one of the
freest in Asia. For once, we're proud of everything being the same
here.''
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone is breaking out the champagne for the one-year
anniversary Wednesday. Albert Chan, a pro-democracy politician,
expects to be picketing somewhere _ although he admits it may be
over the economy, not politics. Even so, he added, ``There's no
reason to celebrate ... there's still no democracy here.''
</P>
<P>
   One year into the experiment in ``one country, two systems'' _
the vow by China to let free-wheeling Hong Kong rule itself and
keep its capitalist system for at least 50 years _ Beijing
generally appears to have honored its promise.
</P>
<P>
   No Chinese troops have marched through the streets. No local
politicians or dissidents have been imprisoned. No presses have
been shut down. No limits have been put on the free flow of
capital.
</P>
<P>
   Beijing did, however, dissolve Hong Kong's elected legislature
and limit the voting franchise before allowing new elections. And
questions have arisen over judicial fairness following a few
controversial decisions, such as exempting the Chinese government
from Hong Kong laws, as Britain &UR;  &LR; had been exempted under colonial
law.
</P>
<P>
   But even China's critics admit that the worst evil to strike has
not been any move by the Beijing government, but the unexpected
blow of the Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Chan, a former legislator, says that if he had been asked a year
ago what he would be demonstrating about today, he would have
replied, ``Human rights and political repression, no question.''
Instead, he was marching through downtown during a recent lunch
break with a megaphone, banners, and 100 placard-bearing followers
furious over the collapse of the economy and the Hong Kong
government's perceived incompetence.
</P>
<P>
   Many pre-handover predictions, both good and bad, have been
proved wrong. A Cantonese expression often heard these days _ ``dai
deed ngan gang,'' or ``we dropped our spectacles'' _ refers to the
shock among Hong Kong people over the surprises of the past year.
</P>
<P>
   Voter turnout in recent elections was huge despite a supposedly
apathetic populace. Democrats dominated the polls despite a system
rigged against them. Demonstrations against China's 1989 crackdown
in Tiananmen Square proceeded without interference.
</P>
<P>
   The economy is suffering the worst unemployment in 15 years and
negative growth for the first time in more than a decade. And the
once-esteemed, British-trained civil service has floundered in the
face of innumerable crises.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was supposed to be `Hong Kong people running Hong Kong,'
but now it's Hong Kong people ruining Hong Kong,'' quipped Liu
Kin-ming, opinion page editor of the Hong Kong Economic Times.
These days, his letters-to-the-editor page overflows with rockets
aimed at the local government.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd been slaves so many years and all of a sudden we have
freedom to run ourselves,'' Liu said. ``But it seems we're not so
capable.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the Hong Kong government's latest opinion survey,
only 32 percent of residents are satisfied with its performance.
</P>
<P>
   Even more striking, the Hong Kong Transition Project, a
long-term, multiuniversity study, recently found that 67 percent of
those surveyed are satisfied with the Chinese government, up 22
points since the handover. Only 48 percent are happy with Hong Kong
leaders, down 18 points since a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it should not be surprising that Beijing has left Hong
Kong alone. It knew the rest of the world was watching its every
move _ particularly Taiwan, which Beijing wants to regain under the
rubric of ``one country, two systems.''
</P>
<P>
   What's more, said David Newman, a politics professor at Lingnan
College and coauthor of ``Red Flag over Hong Kong,'' the Basic Law,
Hong Kong's constitution, enables China ``to keep its hands off
while still achieving its goals.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``You have rigged elections where the Democratic Party
is ensured not to get a majority. You have a chief executive who is
handpicked, not elected'' and who knows what Beijing wants without
having to be told. Newman asserts that China has not interfered
economically _ by buying Hong Kong assets cheaply in exchange for
promises of mainland business favors _ because the financial crisis
has made raising capital difficult for Chinese businesses.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
