<SLUG> BC-COURTING-BABY-BOOMERS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAPPING THE MIDDLE-AGED MOOD 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature from Women's Wear
Daily _ the rate is not prohibitive _ contact one of these New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives:
 &HT;    (_ U.S. and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444.
 &HT;    (_ Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (_ Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles at (310)
996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089.
 &HT;    
 &HT;     (-----They also have information on how to subscribe to ``HIGH
STYLE AND MORE,'' a complete lifestyle and entertainment package
composed of stories _ with accompanying B&AMP;W and color art _ from
numerous publications issued by Fairchild Publications.-----) 
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' general news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By KARYN MONGET 
 c.1998 Fairchild Publications  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Personal-care products like Rogaine or Retin A are aimed
specifically at a maturing populace, but age is not a big issue
when it comes to marketing fashion to baby boomers.
</P>
<P>
   Industry executives say the strategy they employ to lure
middle-aged Americans into buying apparel transcends age.
</P>
<P>
   Fashion firms target the baby-boom generation by portraying
their products as fitting a certain lifestyle or state of mind.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty once was considered over the hill, but now it is widely
regarded as an age when people are at the peak of their
professional and personal lives.
</P>
<P>
   This new attitude is especially appealing to female consumers of
this era, who have broken the stereotype that maturity means a
woman is no longer attractive or desirable.
</P>
<P>
   That sort of fresh self-esteem among the middle-aged is the
target of many fashion firms: They're marketing their products as
part of an aspirational goal _ looking and feeling great,
regardless of age.
</P>
<P>
   A brand _ whether it's as generic as Coca-Cola or has the
distinct cachet of Calvin Klein _ is often what compels consumers
to buy a bra, dress, suit or pair of jeans.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the power of a brand, targeting baby boomers _
generally defined as people born between 1946 and 1964 _ can be a
complicated issue.
</P>
<P>
   While the post-World War II generation can be characterized by
distinct demographic, social and economic traits, baby boomers have
a broad range of lifestyles.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, fashion marketers said they are just as hard to peg as
their junior counterparts, who can range from 13 to 30.
</P>
<P>
   The segment includes boomers still living the disco lifestyle of
the '70s, those who prefer a quiet evening watching ``Seinfeld''
reruns, people dedicated to careers above all else, health
enthusiasts and those who ``shop till they drop'' at
Bloomingdale's.
</P>
<P>
   So while baby boomers may be an affluent and appealing target
segment, they also present a challenge to marketers because of the
complexity.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what some top executives _ a majority of whom are baby
boomers _ had to say about mid-life marketing:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Linda J. Wachner, &LR;  president, chairman and chief executive
officer of The Warnaco Group, said, ``I really don't think it's the
consumer as much as it is a state of mind when it comes to baby
boomers. As a matter of fact, I think consumers are sick of being
called baby boomers. It's really about an attitude and a look.
Staying sexy and pretty _ that's what the consumer wants.''
</P>
<P>
   In Wachner's estimation, the image of the glamorous, buffed
supermodel Christy Turlington is a main ingredient of the success
of Warnaco's ads for Calvin Klein Underwear and Calvin Klein Jeans.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of women out there who don't look like Christy
Turlington, but many certainly want to look like her _ even though
they might not necessarily be young,'' Wachner said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Albert Shapiro, &LR;  vice president of corporate marketing at Liz
Claiborne Inc., stated, ``It's really all about a brand, not an
age. Fashion is all about lifestyle and attitude. I think in order
for fashion products to be successful, they need to have a
lifestyle appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't think that mature and glamour are relatively
exclusive. In fact, they are very clearly aligned. In part, the
more mature the woman, the more glamorous she is because she has a
sense of style, self-confidence and sophistication.''
</P>
<P>
   Shapiro noted that the ad campaigns for Liz Claiborne are
``distinguished to have universal appeal,'' and do not target
younger or older consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why we selected Niki Taylor for our campaign,'' he
said. ``She's very appealing and approachable. We did consumer
focus groups with our ads, and compared her with other
possibilities. She does not turn people away. She represents the
Liz Claiborne attitude and lifestyle, regardless of age.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Kenneth Zimmerman, &LR;  chairman and ceo of Kenar Enterprises,
said, ``We merchandise for a modern mind _ whether it's career or
casual. We use Linda Evangelista in our ads because she's a woman
in her 30s, not a girl. Kenar is addressing the real world. In our
ads, we show clothes for the woman with a family.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kenar is about lifestyle and looking good. If you walk into my
Madison Avenue or East Hampton shops, my customers include three
generations, ranging from 21-year-olds to 40 and 70-year-olds,''
Zimmerman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm 48. I have a son who's 20, and I feel as young as him. He
borrows my clothes and I sometimes borrow his jeans. I think a lot
of people in America think like that today.''
</P>
<P>
   Zimmerman said he has taken the message of fashion one step
further by addressing two hot-button issues: breast-cancer
awareness and pediatric AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   One campaign for early detection of breast cancer is targeted at
the baby boomer who buys Kenar; the other ad for pediatric AIDS is
aimed at a younger woman who most likely has young children, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our customers _ young and old _ are concerned about these
issues,'' Zimmerman said. ``We want them to know we are, too.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Barry Boyd, &LR;  executive vice president of the Hanes and Hanes
Her Way megabrands at Sara Lee Knits, noted, ``Our strategy
definitely is about brand, not age. Our brands are as generic as
Coca-Cola. And they have very broad, public appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly have customers who are older, younger and people
in-between. We are very aware of demographics and age trends.
However, a lot of ad agencies today tend to think very young _ too
young. I try to discourage that. The 50-year-old of today is very
different from the 50-year-old of yesterday. She's far more
confident and she doesn't think like her mother.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Nancy Friedman, &LR;  vice president of marketing for Slackers, a
men's pants brand at Levi Strauss Co., noted, ``We introduced the
Slackers brand two years ago specifically to meet the needs of male
baby boomers, who are trying to adjust to the casualization and new
dress codes in corporate America. They felt they needed more
options between khakis and suits.
</P>
<P>
   ``The launch has been very successful. The newest ad campaign
will be all about a competitive edge, doing well at work and home,
wanting to be noticed. We chose models in their late 30s _ men who
were not too modely, but nice looking; looks a consumer can relate
to,'' Friedman said. ``We've heard a lot of feedback from women
about doing a line for female baby boomers. That's on the
horizon.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _______ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Karyn Monget is a reporter for Fairchild Publications.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _______ &QC;
</P>
<P>
