<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 13:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3744 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LINKS-SERVICE-ART-BOS     06-30 1457
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LINKS-SERVICE-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LINKS IN THE CHAIN OF LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUZANNE C. RYAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; As a worldwide product manager for Chiron Diagnostics Corp.,
Stephanie Wilson travels twice a month from her home in
Massachusetts to cities throughout Europe, Asia, and the United
States. When the chemist actually sits in her East Walpole, Mass.
office, she works 12-hour days and sacrifices her lunch break.
</P>
<P>
   Still the career-minded divorcee _ who left her grown son behind
in Cincinnati to take the Chiron job three years ago _ is adamant
about one thing: that she find some time in her busy life to serve
her community _ the African-American community.
</P>
<P>
   That's why Wilson joined The Links Inc., a community service
group of 10,000 black women from across the United States, Germany,
and the Bahamas whose members include Secretary of Labor Alexis
Herman, Harvard University &UR;  &LR; associate dean for faculty development
in the School of Public Health Deborah Prothrow-Stith, and
BankBoston's First Community Bank president Gail Snowden.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't come live in a community and not give back,'' says
Wilson, who manages to dedicate 20 hours a month to the Links, even
if it means dropping off mailings at the post office at 7 a.m. ``I
got that from my parents. Just because you're successful doesn't
mean you can sit on your laurels. ... We have to help those who
didn't have the benefit of education.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson isn't alone in her thinking. This week, more than 3,000
Links and their families have joined her for a biennial national
assembly _ the first one in Boston since 1969.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, these women aren't just talking about community
service. As professional black women in a sometimes isolating white
society, the Links have come together for a few days to experience
feelings of sisterhood and cultural commonality, affirmation, and
belonging. After a four-day networking frenzy where personal
achievements are being shared and phone numbers exchanged, they
hope to return home rejuvenated by what will essentially be a
massive group hug from women like themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of us work in environments where we don't get an
opportunity to interact with women of color on a daily basis,''
says Colette Phillips, a Link who owns the public relations firm
Colette Phillips Communications in Needham. ``As a businesswoman,
it can be a very lonely existence. A lot of Links are professional
women who understand the stresses and the challenges of being a
black professional in the workplace. We can be supportive of each
other.''
</P>
<P>
   Says Patricia Hardiman Long, a lawyer and Link who is running
for Congress against Edward Markey, ``This is a form of networking
in the black community that has become very important to people
like us who live in the suburbs. African-Americans are in need of
forums in which to express their ideas and celebrate their
culture.''
</P>
<P>
   For the out-of-towners staying here this week at five downtown
Boston hotels it's doubtful the conference will disappoint.
Wednesday the famous Boys Choir of Harlem is scheduled to entertain
at the Marriott, and Thursday has been billed as the ``night with
the stars.'' Singer Melba Moore and Harvard religion and philosophy
professor Cornel West are a few of the high-profile types expected
to arrive for a black-tie dinner at the Marriott. Friday night is
the White Rose Banquet where all 3,000 Links will wear white
evening gowns in ballrooms at two hotels.
</P>
<P>
   When it's all over, the Links say a slew of unofficial
post-convention parties will kick off on Martha's Vineyard,
starting Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   It took three years to plan this lineup, and more than 100 Links
from three Massachusetts chapters were involved. Audrey Coleman,
the convention general chairwoman, sometimes worked eight hours in
the evening after her job as director of comprehensive school
planning for the Boston Public Schools. She hosted committee
meetings at her house and attended planning sessions. ``We're one
of the smallest clusters in the history of Linkdom to host a
convention,'' she explains. ``We were limited as far as woman
power.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Links, who define themselves as a service organization,
weren't focused only on the conference these last few years. The
Middlesex, Mass. chapter recently gave $10,000 in college
scholarships and $8,000 to a women's shelter. The Boston chapter
gave $15,000 in college scholarships and provided ongoing mentoring
at a Boston elementary school. Both chapters also hosted a joint
walk for hunger.
</P>
<P>
   These kinds of projects translate into about 12 hours of work a
month for Links such as Long, who sometimes wonders ``Why do I do
these things? How do I get myself involved?'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   The answer, she believes, stems from her childhood. ``My
grandfather was a minister, my father a college professor, and my
mother a homemaker who did a lot of volunteer work. ... That was
the life of my parents, and it was the model given to me as a
child,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   When Long moved to Lexington, Mass. from Kansas City, Mo., in
1970, she met four other black women in the area who were restless
and feeling isolated. ``Several of us were in graduate school. We
had families and we were looking for an outlet outside of the
family,'' she says. ``We were looking for a connection and a
closeness among women, black women in particular.''
</P>
<P>
   After the women organized the Middlesex chapter in 1976, they
started hosting events like book signings and receptions. That led
to aggressive fund raising. In the chapter's 22-year history, its
members _ now 38 strong _ have raised about $250,000.
</P>
<P>
   The funny thing about Linkdom _ as its members like to call it _
is how it permeates lives. Long says six out of eight members of
her bridge club are Links. Ruth Fitch, a Link and partner at Palmer
&AMP; Dodge LLP in Boston, remembers hearing stories about the Links as
a child after her aunt joined in the 1950s. Coleman says 12 out of
50 members of her local sorority are Links.
</P>
<P>
   The families of Links are also touched by the group. Husbands
are called Connecting Links and children Heir-O-Links. A number of
Boston Connecting Links are playing host to visiting men this week,
taking them to area golf courses, tennis courts, and tourist areas
while their wives meet during the day. Heir-O-Links are being
entertained at various tourist sites such as Plimoth Plantation and
the JFK Library.
</P>
<P>
   In the black community, the Links is considered an exclusive
organization, partly because its membership includes judges,
doctors, TV personalities, and high-profile entrepreneurs. Most
members are well established in their careers or in their
communities and they typically range in age from about 35 to over
70. Often, entire families are members. Bennie Wiley, the president
and chief executive of The Partnership (a networking and support
organization for black professionals) is a Boston Link. Her sister,
Sharon Pratt Kelly _ the former mayor of Washington _ is a Link in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The Links were founded in 1946 by two Philadelphia women _
Margaret Hawkins and Sarah Scott _ who felt that in the aftermath
of World War II, the black community was in need of support via
services for youth, exposure to the arts, and fund-raising for
health care and other issues.
</P>
<P>
   Some people have criticized the group, based in Washington, for
being downright snooty: you don't join, you're invited to join.
Donna Levy Wray, a Link spokeswoman, says, ``We were organized at a
time when that's the way things were done. ... Fifty-two years ago,
we didn't have the Internet.'' The Links haven't changed their
policy because ``we haven't found a need,'' says Wray. ``We're
growing, reaching out to African-American women all over this
country.''
</P>
<P>
   No one can deny that the group is getting things done. Even
during the event-packed convention this week, the Links are finding
time for community service. Monday, Judge Joyce London Alexander, a
Boston Link, taught some Boston-area kids about the importance of
responsible citizenship. Harvard's Stith talked to them about
controlling anger, and another Link stressed to the kids the
importance of reading books.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember as a child being driven to Mississippi to hear a
concert by Leontyne Price,'' says Wilson, who grew up in a
segregated community in Mobile, Ala. ``We (the Links) feel as
adults we have to give back just as much. ... I'm a very busy
person. I travel a lot. But I never say no. You make a way. You can
do something. There's always something you can do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-98 1344EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
