<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 13:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3748 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-HILLARY     06-30 0765
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-HILLARY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    ``I WILL NOT RUN FOR PRESIDENT,'' HILLARY CLINTON TELLS CHINESE
SCHOOLGIRL
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By JOSEPH ALBRIGHT and MARCIA KUNSTEL 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service (at)
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Students at a Chinese girls high school threw frank
questions at Hillary Rodham Clinton Tuesday, and the first lady
opened up with candor she seldom allows back home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mrs. Clinton, we are all very interested to know if you will
run for president,'' said one student at the elite Shanghai No. 3
Girls School. ``And do you think the American people will have a
woman president in the future?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I will not run for president,'' said Mrs. Clinton, a
smile spreading across her face.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I do hope that a woman will run and be elected president
sometime in the early part of the next century....If I agree with
her politically, I will vote for her. If I do not agree with her
politically, I will not vote for her, but I will be very proud that
she is running for the presidency.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Perhaps one of you will be in that position,'' she said. ``I
will be happy to see that.''
</P>
<P>
   Another student asked Mrs. Clinton if she feels there is a
``generation gap'' between her and her daughter Chelsea.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is especially hard to see daughters grow up and leave,''
answered Mrs. Clinton. ``When my daughter left to go to Stanford,
it was all the way across the country from Washington _ she
couldn't have gone any further without falling into the Pacific
Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very hard on her father and me, but at the same time,
we were so proud that she was so independent and able to take care
of herself.''
</P>
<P>
   What does Mrs. Clinton think about single-sex education, another
teenager asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to Wellesley College, outside Boston, Mass., and I am
very happy I did that,'' the first lady answered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think girls schools are a very good opportunity for many
young women, if that is what they choose. Now my daughter did not
want to go to a girls college....She made a different choice.
Despite my encouragement of her to look at my own college, so I
think it is an individual matter.''
</P>
<P>
   And then a question about whether Mrs. Clinton knew how to use
chopsticks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even as a student, I used to eat a lot of Chinese food,'' Mrs.
Clinton said. ``I am not expert in using chopsticks, but I can get
most of the food into my mouth.''
</P>
<P>
   For Mrs. Clinton, the last six days in China have proved an
engaging, animated interlude where she could talk about her
favorite big issues, from childrens health to women's rights,
without risking questions about Whitewater and Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   With the American media being kept at a safe distance, the first
lady has seemed to relish opening herself to the kind of polite,
yet highly personal queries that she has received from many of her
Chinese questioners.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday was typical of her China itinerary. The first lady began
her day by joining the president in a round-table discussion at the
new Shanghai Library.
</P>
<P>
   What does Mrs. Clinton really feel, asked Chinese novelist Wang
Xiaoying, about having her every ``gesture or word'' become the
object of media coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you feel some kind of restriction on your movement or
impact on your personal life?'' pressed Mrs. Wang. ``Is there any
difference when you were not the first lady, for example, as a
wife?''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton answered: ``I often refer to my life before the
White House as when I was a real person, because when you are in a
position like this, people, particularly all those people with
their pencils and their cameras, try to record everything you do
and then they try to put meaning into it _ whether you intend the
meaning or not. So it is a very unusual experience . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Then, as the president headed off to a Shanghai radio call-in
show, the first lady led her own 25-car motorcade to Shanghai's
Pudong district.
</P>
<P>
   First she opened a new high-tech Shanghai children's hospital,
then she visited a women's job retraining center.
</P>
<P>
   At noon, she joined the president and daughter Chelsea for lunch
at a Chinese restaurant. Later, Chelsea stayed with her father for
some downtown sightseeing while Mrs. Clinton's motorcade sped off
to her Q and A session at the Shanghai No. 3 Girls School.
</P>
<P>
   The school's 2,000 students are admitted through competitive
tests. Many of those in the audience were conversant enough with
English that they could react to the first lady's responses even
before they were translated.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
