<SLUG> BC-O'SULLIVAN-FUNERAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAUREEN O'SULLIVAN RECALLED AS MOTHER, FRIEND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KIMBERLY MARTINEAU  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLONIE, N.Y. _ Maureen O'Sullivan played many roles during her
acting career. But it was her role as a mother that mourners
remembered as family members carried her coffin down the steps of
the St. Mary of the Angels Chapel at Siena College here.
</P>
<P>
   O'Sullivan, who played Tarzan's Jane three generations ago, died
last week in Scottsdale, Ariz., at age 87. Her six children,
including actress Mia Farrow, and two dozen grandchildren and
great-grandchildren were among the 80 family members and close
friends who attended Monday's funeral service. Following the solemn
90-minute ceremony, O'Sullivan was buried at Most Holy Redeemer
Cemetery in nearby Niskayuna.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was my mother and my best friend,'' Farrow said in her
eulogy. The actress tearfully left the chapel holding a child on
each arm. O'Sullivan's son John Farrow also spoke. He recalled the
time as a little boy, when he bought his mother a flower in Spain
for her birthday. He said he was amazed when 15 years later his
mother pulled the same flower from her Bible where she had
preserved the gift all those years.
</P>
<P>
   One of O'Sullivan's friends lingered on the chapel steps long
after the hearse and nine-car funeral procession had pulled away.
``She was able to have a career and a very large family at the same
time,'' said Judy Lynch of Schenectady, N.Y., who became friendly
with O'Sullivan in 1983, when O'Sullivan married her second
husband, James Cushing.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the children came she just bowed out of acting. When the
children grew up she went back to acting, in New York City, on the
stage.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Hugh Hines delivered the funeral homily. Hines awarded
O'Sullivan an honorary fine arts degree from Siena College in 1983
and performed the ceremony when O'Sullivan married Cushing that
summer.
</P>
<P>
   Hines, a movie buff, said he became fascinated with O'Sullivan
in the 1950s, thanks to the many afternoons he spent watching the
``Tarzan'' movies, among others. Decades later, he met the actress
through Cushing, then her fiance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went out for breakfast and I sat there agog,'' he recalled.
``I couldn't believe it was her.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Hines and O'Sullivan became friends. One night,
he said, he arrived at her house with plans to go to dinner.
</P>
<P>
   ``She came to the door and said, `We've decided to stay home.
I'm cooking.' I said, `I didn't know you could cook.' She said,
`Father, I've had seven children.'''
</P>
<P>
   Those children, and especially their children, cried
uncontrollably during the funeral service, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was the glue that held the family together,'' Hines said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1958, O'Sullivan's son Michael Farrow died in a plane crash.
Her husband, screenwriter and director John Farrow, died in 1963.
Hines attributed her strength in overcoming those obstacles to her
``Irish faith.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to dozens of family members, O'Sullivan leaves a
legacy of films: ``Anna Karenina'' and ``Cardinal Richelieu'' from
1935; ``Pride and Prejudice,'' 1940; and 1948's ``The Big Clock,''
directed by her husband, John Farrow.
</P>
<P>
   In 1985, she appeared with Mia Farrow in Woody Allen's ``Hannah
and Her Sisters,'' where, fittingly, she played the mother of her
daughter's character.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
