<HEADER>
A3753 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX     06-30 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE PAST, THE FUTURE AND TEXAS DEMOCRATS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ So I'm walking out of the Alamodome the other day,
and I run into former U.S. House Speaker Jim Wright.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are you doing here?'' Wright inquires.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't say it in a hostile way. He was genuinely curious as
to why an inveterate Democrat-baiting, liberal-bashing character
like me would be hanging around a convention of the Texas
Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   Uh, would you believe I just wanted to spend a few days in San
Antonio to get away from the relentless heat in North Texas? Going
into the weekend, the local prognosticators here weren't even
expecting the temperature to hit 100 during the Democrats' two-day
invasion.
</P>
<P>
   You know what they say, of course: It isn't the heat _ it's the
humidity. They use the word ``muggy'' in the weather reports around
these parts, which is a concise way of saying that if you plan to
do much walking in San Antonio, be sure to take along a canteen and
a towel.
</P>
<P>
   A person can get soaked just soaking up the history in the Alamo
City. If Democrats wanted to spend the weekend reveling in bygone
days of glory, they came to the right place. The little
mission/fort on Alamo Plaza stands as the Lone Star State's
proudest memorial to Texas courage and determination.
</P>
<P>
   It is somewhat ironic that the Democrats should convene in this
bastion of state history, for it was the state's Republican Party
that vowed earlier this month to ``change the course of Texas
history'' with its conservative political and social agenda.
</P>
<P>
   During their convention in Fort Worth, the Republicans predicted
that they would sweep to victory in the November elections,
capturing every statewide office on the ballot and seizing control
of the state House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats, meeting within walking distance of the Alamo,
seemed less intent on changing the course of Texas history than on
preserving some small place in that history for their party and
their ideology.
</P>
<P>
   They came to town touting their ``1998 Strong Families Agenda,''
a Clintonesque platform emphasizing education, health care and
child care. Sure, it worked for Bill Clinton in '92 and '96, but
don't forget: Clinton lost Texas in both those elections.
</P>
<P>
   Wright pointed out that more Democrats than Republicans voted in
this year's party primaries. That proves, he said, that there are
still plenty of Democrats in Texas, notwithstanding the GOP's
astounding growth in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats can win elections, Wright said, if ``we can get people
excited, get them out to vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Therein lies the rub, especially in a year when the election for
governor shapes up as a mismatch _ a mismatch so monumental that
Democrat Garry Mauro must feel a bit like the 180-plus defenders of
the Alamo felt when they peeked across the walls and saw Santa Anna
and his thousands of soldiers bearing down on them.
</P>
<P>
   Travis and Crockett and the rest put up a gallant fight back in
1836, but they never had a chance.
</P>
<P>
   The coming months will tell us how gallant Mauro might be, but
last weekend's optimistic rhetoric couldn't change reality: Mauro
trails incumbent Republican Gov. George W. Bush in some polls by
more than 50 points. And the challenger is showing no signs of
closing the gap.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing wrong with Mauro as a candidate. He's dynamic,
energetic and as personable as you could ask a politician to be.
But Mauro is trying to sell a new car to voters who are pleased as
punch with the car they have.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro would like us to believe that Bush's first term was a
train wreck of misdirection and broken promises, but the truth is
exactly the opposite. Bush kept virtually every promise he made
when he ran four years ago. Most Texans consider him a terrific
governor.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the whole problem with Democrats in 1998 is that they are
trying to sell something that voters don't want and don't need. The
Democrats' best ideas these days are the ones they steal from
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Here in San Antonio, the Democrats were immersed in Texas
history. But the state's future seems to be slipping away from
them.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-98 1347EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
