<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 13:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3754 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MAINE-BOOMLET-BOS &LR;      06-30 1117
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAINE-BOOMLET-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TECHNOLOGY BOOMLET ENERGIZING MAINE'S ECONOMY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MACQUARRIE AND LOIS R. SHEA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Maine _ It's not just about paper, shoes, and lobsters
anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Maine is undergoing one of the most profound changes in its
economic history. Long dependent on textiles, logging, and fishing,
Maine is enjoying a boomlet driven by the sorts of things that
people ``from away'' associate more with Route 128 than
Kennebunkport.
</P>
<P>
   A major computer-chip manufacturer recently expanded its
operations in South Portland. Statewide, 5,000 telephone jockeys
sell everything from Red Sox credit cards to European rental cars.
Biotechnology is now worth more than the lobstering and potato
industries combined. And Maine's top international export last year
was not lobsters, Bass shoes, or paper products _ it was electronic
equipment.
</P>
<P>
   ``And Moody's is questioning if we have a diversified economy.
Ha!'' state treasurer Dale McCormick says of the bond-rating
company that recently reviewed Maine's financial situation for
money borrowing purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Maine suffered with the rest of New England during the recession
of the late 1980s. But by the spring of 1997, state officials said,
it had regained all of the 35,000 jobs it lost, and since then, has
added 5,000 more. Since January 1990, the state's nonagricultural
employment has grown by 6.7 percent, according to the US Bureau of
Labor Statistics.
</P>
<P>
   Maine's resurgence, impressive as it is, has been outpaced by
New Hampshire, Vermont, and Massachusetts, whose nonagricultural
jobs this decade have grown by 12.8 percent, 8.4 percent, and 7.7
percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   But emerging in Maine, perhaps more than elsewhere in New
England, are economic shifts that could neutralize the state's
geographic isolation, long seen as an impediment to economic
health.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're no longer at the end of the line,'' says Governor Angus
S. King Jr., the popular Independent who has preached the gospel of
economic development from Kittery to Calais.
</P>
<P>
   That optimism seems to ring true outside the state as well.
Despite any questions Moody's may have had, Maine's bond rating was
upgraded recently for the first time since 1982, enabling it to get
a favorable interest rate on money it borrows.
</P>
<P>
   But not all of Maine has prospered so neatly from the recent
economic upswing. Although the unemployment rate in Cumberland
County, the hub of Maine's economy, is a statewide-low 2.1 percent,
Washington County on the Canadian border lags with 9.1 percent of
its population out of work.
</P>
<P>
   And while Maine as a whole has recovered from the recession, job
growth in most of the state's 16 counties has not nearly kept pace
with Cumberland and York in the south. Between 1990 and 1996,
according to state economist Laurie Lachance, more than 10,000 jobs
were created in Maine _ and 8,000 of those were in Cumberland
County, which includes the city of Portland.
</P>
<P>
   King does not like to use the term, ``the two Maines,'' but he
acknowledges the division exists. And how to narrow the gap between
rural and suburban Maine is as difficult a question as it has ever
been. &UR;  &LR; ``It's the most serious economic issue we have,'' King says
of the imbalance in wealth and jobs. ``It's why I decided to run
again.''
</P>
<P>
   In Aroostook County, for example, more than 10,000 people have
moved away this decade; unemployment is 7.2 percent, or nearly
twice the state average; and longtime residents wonder how they can
persuade their children to stay.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While low-paying jobs such as laborers and store clerks are a
hard fact of life for many in remote Maine, the state's coast and
Interstate 95 corridor are bustling. And the jewel of the crown,
the sea-girt city of Portland, fairly glistens.
</P>
<P>
   The Old Port section has been a hot attraction for tourists for
20 years _ and is even hotter now. Its cobblestone streets are
lined with boutiques. Its bars evoke a nostalgic, inviting feel of
maritime New England. And its restaurants rise significantly above
the provincial.
</P>
<P>
   Theater, arts, and sports contribute to the feel of a hip city
on the move. Add to that a jetport, soon-to-be-revived rail service
to Boston, proximity to beaches and mountains, and the city seems
to have it made.
</P>
<P>
   Says Scott Bonney, 36, the former manager of the Old Port
Tavern: ``I've been around the world three times. And from April to
October, there's no better place to be than here. You don't find
these places in America anymore.'' He said many Maine-raised
engineers who fled in search of work are coming back to take
advantage of new opportunities here.
</P>
<P>
   Morten Asbjornsen would agree. Asbjornsen edits Interface
Monthly magazine and directs the Old Port Technology Center, a
recently opened collection of high-tech businesses operating under
one roof in Portland.
</P>
<P>
   ``These folks who are doing technology can do it anywhere,''
Asbjornsen says. ``And there's no reason to go to Boston or New
York City or California when you can do it in Portland, Maine.''
</P>
<P>
   Computer-chip manufacturer National Semiconductor recently
invested $830 million in a new facility in South
Portland. &UR;  &LR; National and its spinoff, Fairchild Semiconductor,
employ more than 2,000 people here. Other major employers include
insurance companies, paper and shoe manufacturers, supermarket
chains, hospitals, and retailers. Bath Iron Works, a defense
contractor, remains the state's largest private employer.
</P>
<P>
   Demand for high-tech workers in Maine now outpaces supply, as it
does in the other New England states.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Griffith runs the Great Moose Lake Corp. in Scarborough, a
recruiting company for high-tech firms.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be: `Come back to Maine! Work twice as hard for
half the pay!''' Griffith said. ``That doesn't happen anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Maine has 50,000 miles of fiberoptic cables and sophisticated
switching systems that make its telecommunications infrastructure a
major selling point.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I can say, with a pretty high level of assurance, that
we have the best telecommunications infrastructure in all of New
England,'' King boasts.
</P>
<P>
   That advantage helps explain why Maine has approximately 5,000
jobs in call centers _ offices where operators handle a company's
telephone work, such telemarketing, catalog sales, technical
support or billing questions _ and recently announced the addition
of 750 more. &UR;  &LR; Another factor may be that wages generally are less
than they are in places like metropolitan Boston and New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some ways,'' King says, ``the call center is the factory of
the '90s.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
