<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-RODGERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIOGRAPHY FAILS AT GETTING TO KNOW RODGERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ED SIEGEL  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
RICHARD RODGERS 
By William G. Hyland. 
Yale University Press, 362 pp., illustrated, $30 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One hopes that William Hyland did a better job unmasking
espionage operatives than he does in discovering the real Richard
Rodgers. This may seem like an odd subject for Hyland, who worked
for the Central Intelligence Agency, the National Security Council,
and the State Department from 1954 to 1977 _ though readers of le
Carre or of Norman Mailer's ``Harlot's Ghost'' may enjoy concocting
a perverse image of an American spy humming ``Getting to Know You''
as he overthrows a foreign government.
</P>
<P>
   But Hyland is already the author of a survey history of American
songwriting and has now written a biography of America's great
composer of Broadway melodies that any Rodgers aficionado should
have on hand. It is loaded with good, interesting information about
the tunesmith's progress over the years with Lorenz Hart and Oscar
Hammerstein 2d and does a good, if not unique, job of explaining
why he and his partners were so important to the history of musical
comedy.
</P>
<P>
   Rodgers himself, however, remains as elusive as ever. Hyland
can't be fully blamed for that. Shortly before he died, Hammerstein
said, ``We've worked together all these years and I don't really
know him.'' Rodgers was apparently a rather ill-formed personality:
The book has many quotes from people who didn't particularly like
him. Stephen Sondheim said Rodgers had ``infinite talent _ but
limited soul.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet Hyland is clearly taken with his subject. He is honest
about Rodgers's flaws but enamored of his virtues, particularly his
musical ones. Listening to and reading through the scores has
clearly been an enjoyable task for the author. He seems most turned
on by Rodgers's unapologetic romanticism. At times Hyland is
articulate on the matter: ``Rodgers displayed an affinity for the
traditional centrality of the tonic chord, pure and simple. He once
said that he was suspicious of a songwriter who was afraid of a
strong tonic chord. He risked banality with this traditional
approach, but it imparted a pristine clarity to his melodies. In
Rodgers's hands it was always fresh and compelling.''
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, though, Hyland writes too dispassionately on
a subject he so obviously feels passionate about. There's an ``And
then he wrote'' quality about the book, which fills in the gaps _
as when ``Allegro'' broke the great R&AMP;H run between ``Oklahoma!''
and ``Carousel'' on the one hand and ``South Pacific'' and ``The
King and I'' on the other.
</P>
<P>
   But for those not as infatuated with Rodgers as Hyland, the
biography merely bogs down when it should be charging ahead. It's
more difficult to write about what made Rodgers's music unique than
to talk about the lyrics of Hart and Hammerstein, but Hyland's
writing on music made me wish that this had been a CD-ROM with
auditory accompaniment to go along with the sometimes academic
discourses.
</P>
<P>
   Still, ``Richard Rodgers'' is worth the read. People tend to
think of him as a pretty melodist and naive sentimentalist. Hyland
establishes once again that Rodgers, whether working with Hart on
``Pal Joey'' or with Hammerstein on ``Oklahoma!,'' was also one of
the Broadway musical's great innovators.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
