</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980630.0096 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 13:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3767 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-MYTOWN-2ND &LR;  &UR; TA     06-30 0910
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-MYTOWN-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 BOSTON: ... sistah here!''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``We got the lights, the darks, the caramels,'' Miranda adds.
</P>
<P>
   Around the table, it's clearly the youth and myriad shades of
color that give life to the participants' faces, music to their
laughter. MYTOWN seeks applicants of various ethnicities, incomes,
schools, and locales. &UR;  &LR;  The push for diversity is fueled by the
need to learn from others, the talk-story that can unite
cultures. &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Hoang, for example, came to the United States from Vietnam in
the early 1980s when her parents, ethnic Chinese, fled from
persecution. ``I hear stories about me coming here on a boat, I
hear stories of me coming here on a plane,'' recalls Hoang, of
Allston. ``It's hard for my parents to talk about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Through MYTOWN, Hoang can get paid for listening and retelling
those familiar tales of the silenced, the oppressed, and the
triumphant. ``We deal with stories of immigrants, the working
class, people of color, people who don't have a voice,'' she says.
``Their stories are in the dark.''
</P>
<P>
   Sitting at the table, the teenagers guard MYTOWN's admission
gates. They hold the keys during the interview process, too. How do
they make the final selection? Says Miranda: ``Oh, we ask the
finalists to bark or sing _''  &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``Or how they want to die,'' Hoang says.
</P>
<P>
   ``One girl sang, and I just felt it, you know?'' Miranda says.
``It's just flavor.''
</P>
<P>
   It was her distinct, determined flavor that last year secured
Miranda a job at MYTOWN. A lifelong resident of Boston's Roxbury
neighborhood, Miranda started volunteering at 13 for the Dudley
Street Neighborhood Initiative, an &UR;  &LR; example of community action and
change.
</P>
<P>
   Early on she witnessed the struggles often associated with
working-class urban neighborhoods: ``If you grew up in my
community, you would see the drugs and violence. It's just there.
You can't really bypass it. So you can get involved or stand in a
corner and see other people get involved. The more you know, the
farther you'll go.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (MYTOWN tours are available by appointment year-round Tuesdays
through Saturdays. Individuals may also attend already scheduled
Saturday tours from noon to 2 p.m. today, July 11, July 18, and
Aug. 8. Sliding fee, from $2.50 to $15 per person. Call (617)
357-TOWN.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
FEATURED MYTOWN TOUR SITES &QL; 
 &QL; 
1. A. Philip Randolph statue, inside Back Bay station on the Orange
Line. From 1911 to 1963, Randolph helped desegregate the armed
forces, organize the march on Washington and establish a trade
union for Pullman porters _ one of the first black labor
unions. &UR;  &LR; One of few statues in Massachusetts commemorating and
depicting an African American.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
2. Tent City, corner of Columbus Avenue and Dartmouth Street. In
1968, activist Mel King and nearly 100 others pitched tents on a
vacant lot to protest the need for affordable housing during urban
renewal. &UR;  &LR; The Tent City &UR;  &LR; developers completed building this
affordable apartment complex in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
3. Southwest Corridor Park. This area, a 19th-century railroad
corridor, was designated in the mid-1960s as the site of the
multilane Inner Belt highway and became the focal point of a
decade-long protest by South End residents. After the highway was
scrapped, neighorhood residents ended up with some 50 acres of
parkland, which stretches over and alongside the Orange Line, some
5 miles from the Back Bay subway station through Roxbury and
Jamaica Plain to the Forest Hill station.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
4. Harriet Tubman House, 25 Holyoke St. Julia O. Henson, a friend
of Underground Railroad organizer &UR;  &LR; Harriet Tubman, founded this
residential settlement to accommodate new women migrants from the
South.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
5. Charlie's Sandwich Shoppe, 429 Columbus Ave. &UR;  &LR; When jazz clubs
burgeoned along this block, it was one of the few places where
black musicians could eat here after their shows. Owner Charlie
Poulos, a Greek immigrant, also allowed Pullman porters to convene
on the second floor of the shop as they began unionizing.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
6. Union United Methodist Church, 485 Columbus Ave. This church was
founded in 1818 on Beacon Hill and moved several times before
settling in the South End. It was also a stop on the Underground
Railroad.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
7. Sparrow Park, off West Newton Street between Columbus Avenue and
Southwest Corridor Park. During construction of this park during
the 1970s, former semi-pro tennis player Titus Sparrow offered to
teach free tennis lessons here once it was finished. Sparrow died
of a heart attack before the park was completed in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
8. Academy of Musical Arts, 547 Columbus Ave. &UR;  &LR; Anna Bobitt-Gardner
founded this studio to provide working-class families with
affordable dance and piano classes. It survived nearly 75 years
before closing this year due to low enrollment.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
9. Wally's Cafe, 427 Massachusetts Ave. Joseph ``Wally'' Walcott
opened this jazz club &UR;  &LR; in 1947. It is Boston's longest
consecutively black-owned business and was a stop on the ``Chitlin'
Circuit,'' a gig tour frequented by Billie Holiday and Erroll
Garner.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
10. Former home of Dr. Martin Luther King Jr., 397 Massachusetts
Avenue, two houses next to the Mass. Ave. T stop on the Orange
Line. &UR;  &LR;  King lived in this row house apartment as a theology
graduate student at Boston University. King led 10,000 people in a
march from the Carter Playground to the Boston Commons in 1965,
protesting the racial imbalance in the public schools.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
