<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO X'S AND O'S _ JUST X 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   At least ESPN has a sense of humor about its X Games.
</P>
<P>
   David Letterman plans to run a spoof later this week. All of the
details are not known. X Game anchor and former Boston sportscaster
Jack Edwards flew to New York to provide voice-over for four skits,
three of which include a laundry mat, a used car, and a rusty razor
blade.
</P>
<P>
   ``The X Games are perfect for Letterman,'' Edwards said. ``He
probably looks at them as if they were mainstream. Wasn't he the
one dropping bowling balls from four-story buildings?''
</P>
<P>
   Everything is relative. Four years ago, ESPN created the Xtreme
Games, a collection of cutting-edge sports popular among Generation
X. Bungee jumping was one of the sports, but last year, ESPN
eliminated it from the X Games because it had become passe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cool'' events remain, including downhill skateboarding,
bicycle tricks, mountain climbing, air surfing, and, of course,
snowboarding. Last weekend, for example, ESPN paid for 360 tons of
snow for its snowboarding competition in, of all places, San Diego.
The events were held early in the morning before the smow melted.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, it's a bit whacky. But the event attracted 225,000 zany
fans over the weekend, and more important, advertisers. Mountain
Dew, Adidas, Taco Bell, and AT&AMP;T were among the corporations that
put up $2 million for on-air spots.
</P>
<P>
   The reason is simple. The X Games attract one of the most
isolated demographics in the country _ teenagers and
twentysomethings. Ratings are still small, but unlike covering the
NFL, where ABC-/ESPN had to pay $900 million to broadcast the
games, the X Games have no rights fee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Advertisers adore the X Games,'' Edwards said.
</P>
<P>
   And ESPN loves the X Games, so much so that when MTV wanted to
compete for a slice of the pie, ESPN produced the X Games concerts,
a series of music features with artists such as No Doubt,
Jamiroquai, U2, Jimi Hendrix, Third Eye Blind, Might Mighty
Bosstones, and Chumbawamba.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ESPN will air the Home Run Derby live from Coors Field during
the 1998 All-Star Game July 7. Chris Berman and Joe Morgan call the
action and are joined by New York Mets catcher Mike Piazza. ESPN
plans to use 17 cameras throughout the two-hour telecast, including
one located in the left-field parking lot. ``Home Run Derby''
earned a rating of 5.7 last year, the highest non-NFL rating
achieved by ESPN ... ``Street &AMP; Smith's Black College Football,''
the only national magazine to exclusively cover the subject, debuts
in September ... CBS will make network history Saturday when it
airs an auto race during prime time _ NASCAR Winston Cup's Pepsi
400 at 8 p.m. Ken Squier hosts coverage from the Daytona
International Speedway. Mike Joy calls the race with analysts Ned
Jarrett and Buddy Baker.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-98 1353EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980630.0098 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 13:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3776 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-OTHER-ONES-BOS &LR;      06-30 1212
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-OTHER-ONES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE OTHER ONES: COMING BACK FROM THE DEAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Long, diligent rehearsals? They were never a Grateful Dead
trademark, but they define The Other Ones, a new band that brings
together Dead alumni and other latter-day hippies intent on
carrying forth the Dead's legacy with as much respect as possible.
</P>
<P>
   The Other Ones are headlining the third annual Furthur Festival.
The band has worked up almost 50 Dead songs, including some vintage
catalog numbers the Dead hadn't performed in decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're putting the shoulder to the wheel,'' says Bob Weir,
formerly of the Dead. ``We're determined to do this.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're rehearsing every day from 11 to 6, and there aren't any
two-hour breaks, like there were in The Grateful Dead,'' says
fellow alum Mickey Hart.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're rehearsing longer than we're gigging,'' adds Bruce
Hornsby, an auxiliary member of the Dead since 1990. ``We're doing
six weeks of rehearsals for four weeks of gigs.''
</P>
<P>
   Will the hard work pay off? Time will tell, but there's no
denying that this is a watershed year in post-Dead history, since
the death of Jerry Garcia in 1995 caused the group to disband.
</P>
<P>
   No one is calling this a reunion, but, percussionist Hart says,
``this is as close as it's going to get. And the spirit is right.''
(The only Dead survivors not participating are drummer Bill
Kreutzmann, who declined to tour, and keyboardist Vince Welnick,
who wasn't invited because the keyboard chair was given to
Hornsby.)
</P>
<P>
   The Other Ones are anchored by Weir, Hart, and Hornsby, who have
played in separate bands at the Furthur Festival, such as Weir's
Ratdog and Hart's Planet Drum, before jamming together at the end
of each show. But this year, they're playing only in The Other
Ones, and are boosted by the return of Dead bassist Phil Lesh, who
hasn't toured since Garcia's death.
</P>
<P>
   ``Phil has a completely unique style that makes it easier to go
to those musical places that are Dead-like,'' says Hornsby.
</P>
<P>
   The addition of four new players _ guitarist Steve Kimock from
the band Zero, guitarist Mark Karan from The Rembrandts, drummer
John Molo from Hornsby's solo band, and saxophonist Dave Ellis from
Ratdog _ helps give Deadheads legitimate cause for hope, though no
one pretends that Garcia's void can be filled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any new guitar player is going to take a little heat,'' Weir
says from his car phone in San Francisco. ``But it occurred to us
that having two new guitarists would help dilute the heat. No one
person is going to fill the shoes of old Jerry.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying not to think about it. It would just get in the way
of the music,'' guitarist Karan says. ``There's also a lot of
Internet gossip about who is cooler _ me or Steve (Kimock), but we
just won't go there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody can take Garcia's place. He was a very individual
player, a very brilliant player, and a social icon,'' adds Karan.
``What this is about is carrying on the tradition of the music.''
</P>
<P>
   The final Other Ones lineup came together after a typical bout
of Dead craziness. Another guitarist, Stan Franks (from the David
Murray Octet), was considered, but that didn't pan out. Then a
debate ensued about whether Karan or Kimock would be better; both
were chosen after a jam session revealed their combined, unselfish
strengths.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was a crazy idea at first to have both of them,
because there was already so much going on in the band,'' says
Hornsby, who adds that the group also considered alternating the
two. ``But it's worked out well. It feels more open with the two of
them. I know that seems impossible, but it's true.''
</P>
<P>
   Karan, 43, grew up in San Francisco and caught nearly 50
Grateful Dead shows as a youth, in such places as the Fillmore West
and Golden Gate Park. So he knew the band's material.
</P>
<P>
   ``A couple of my friends used to call me `Baby Hippie,''' says
Karan, who once saw the Dead play on a flatbed truck in
Haight-Ashbury and was even photographed on the ``Live Dead'' album
cover. ``I'm in the picture if you look closely,'' says Karan, who
has played with the Dave Mason Band, Delaney Bramlett, and Sophie
B. Hawkins.
</P>
<P>
   For his audition, Karan was a nervous wreck. ``I don't do well
in auditions. I'm not what they call a `Yo!' cat. I don't schmooze
and work the room well. At many auditions, there's a sense of
secrecy and a weird vibe. But the Dead audition couldn't be further
from that. There was no secret, Machiavellian BS going on. I met
everybody and had a sandwich and started playing. Then I looked up
and realized who I was playing with. I thought, `Hey, wait a
minute. These are the guys I grew up listening to.'''
</P>
<P>
   The audition included jams of the Dead's ``Truckin','' ``Friend
of the Devil,'' ``The Other One,'' and ``Playin' in the Band.''
Says Karan: ``It took a while to get used to the freedom in this
group, but I've always loved real stretchy bands like the Dead, The
Allman Brothers, and Quicksilver Messenger Service.''
</P>
<P>
   Then came the surprise of Kimock, 42, joining after the
rehearsals started. ``Steve and I are old friends,'' Karan says.
``We greeted each other, he unpacked his guitar, and we started
playing. Stylistically, we're different, but we both have the
influence of Jerry's playing. Steve is probably a more trained
player. I'm more raw, more intuitive. But the gist of what goes on
here is pretty loose. Nobody is a testosterone-filled 20-year-old
with a lot to prove. We're all just into the music.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah yes, the music. ``I expect deep grooves mixed with a lot of
love, a lot of spice, and a lot of fun,'' says Hart. ``There's
growth left in everybody _ and there's a new hunger. You just can't
go out and expect it to happen. You have to have a deep hunger to
bring it up to the surface.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the new guys have been chosen for their talent, and in The
Grateful Dead, that's very specific,'' he adds. ``You have to be
able to change and morph and be quick on your feet. And you have to
be kind, and love what you do, and listen to your brother.''
</P>
<P>
   Hart also plans a new series of ``drums and space'' jams with
Molo, much like Hart used to do with Kreutzmann. ``Molo and I have
a lot of chemistry. ... We played a lot at the jams during the
earlier Furthur Festivals. He's conscious. He listens. We're after
the feeling. We're not after virtuoso playing. It's not the notes.
It's what's in between them that counts.''
</P>
<P>
   The Other Ones will play some new songs, such as Weir's ``Banyan
Tree'' and ``Lao Tzu Blues.'' But there will be many Dead rarities,
too. Among them are ``Saint Stephen,'' ``The Eleven,'' and
``Mountains of the Moon.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to balance it out by doing classics and yet still
have fun with the new stuff,'' says Weir. ``And we're looking at 2
1/2-hour sets. We're going to take our shoes off and get real
comfy.''
</P>
<P>
   And how about further into the future?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, we're still practicing the left-foot-right-foot method
here,'' says Weir. ``But the plan is to re-cord the last two gigs
and beyond that, chances are that we'll take it to the studio.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting a lot of encouragement. But we've still got to
get out and produce the magic.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
