<HEADLINE>
FILM FESTIVAL A FIRST FOR MAINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Film festivals have been popping up throughout the country, and
the world. Now, Maine will be holding its first International Film
Festival July 10 through 19 in Waterville, a small city in central
Maine.
</P>
<P>
   The festival will feature at least 40 American and international
films with several having their premiere at the festival. ``The one
thing everyone involved in this project has in common is that we
enjoy going to the movies and seeing good films,'' said project
director Joan Phillips-Sandy. Ken Eisen, one of those who selected
the films to be shown, added, ``The festival is going to offer
everyone a sense of discovery.''
</P>
<P>
   Films will be shown at the Railroad Square Cinema, an art house
since 1978, and the 940-seat historic Waterville Opera House (``a
wonderful reminder of the kind of theater where movies used to be
shown,'' said Phillips-Sandy).
</P>
<P>
   Among features of the festival is a look at ``Maine in the
Movies'' and the opportunity for visitors to spend time with the
filmmakers.
</P>
<P>
   One of the best parts of the festival is that it gives visitors
a chance to discover the vacation opportunities of the central
lakes area of the state. Special four- and seven-day vacation
packages are being offered that include white-water rafting,
canoeing, hiking, and other activities. For information, call
800-393-8629. For information on the festival, call 207-861-8138 or
visit the Web site at www.mint.net/movies/miff.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Windjammer sail
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sailing on a windjammer is part of the New England experience.
Unfortunately, not everyone has the time even for a three-day sail.
Fortunately, there is one schooner, the 67-foot Wendameen, that
offers one-night sails out of Rockland, Maine. Captain Neal Parker
sails the 14-passenger schooner through Penobscot Bay wherever the
winds and tide allow. A sail is $155 a person and includes meals
and music from the Wendameen's original Victor Gramophone. For
information, call 207-594-1751.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Beads and bones
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Beads, Bones and Ancient Stones: 70 Years of Collecting;
10,000 Years of History'' is the anniversary exhibit of the Abbe
Museum in Bar Harbor, Maine. The exhibit of Maine Native American
objects commemorates the impact the collection's objects have had
on makers, users, collectors, and viewers. Sara Lustsky, 15, of Bar
Harbor, wrote about an ancient bone flute on view: ``I love music.
I have my radio on all the time. Al I have to do is push a button
and sounds fill my world. Prehistoric Abenakis had to create their
own music. They had to select the bone, know where to put the
holes, how to make the sound. The music came from them, from
within.'' Other items on view range from baskets, beads, and
barkwork to a bone of a 4,000-year-old dog. For information, call
207-288-3519.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
First law school
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Noblest Study: The Legacy of America's First School of
Law'' has opened at the Litchfield (Connecticut) Historical
Society. The state-of- the-art exhibit tells of Tapping Reeve's
school, which began in his living room and soon moved to its own
building. In doing so, the exhibit illustrates students'
experiences of travel, study, entertainment, and courtship. The
first student was Aaron Burr, Reeve's brother in law, and soon
included future leaders of the country, including Vice President
John C. Calhoun, educator Horace Mann, and Supreme Court justices.
The exhibit, Tapping Reeve House, and Law School are all near the
Litchfield Green, one of the most picturesque in New England. For
information, call the historical society at 860-567-4501.
</P>
</TEXT>
