<SLUG> BC-LANGUAGE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROSE THAT BREAKETH GRAMMAR'S RULES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAN FREEMAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   William Shakespeare is alive and well, currently lighting up the
New York stage as the inspiration for ``Love's Fire,'' a collection
of mini-plays by seven playwrights, each based on a different
sonnet.
</P>
<P>
   But Shakespeare's grammar is taking a beating, often from people
who should know better _ such as the headline writer who handled
last week's review of ``Love's Fire'' in The New York Times. ``How
Aged These Sonnets, but They Doth Speak Fresh,'' proclaims the
six-column headline, blithely ignoring the fact that doth is a
third person singular verb, the equivalent of the modern does.
</P>
<P>
   In Elizabethan English, a he, she, or it is the subject of verbs
like doth, singeth, runneth. ``The lady doth protest too much,''
says Hamlet's mom; ``Pride goeth before a fall,'' we say,
condensing the biblical verse to a more user-friendly length. The
other archaic verb forms, the ones that end in -st, are second
person singular: ``Whither thou goest,'' ``That time of year thou
mayst in me behold.'' But plural forms, in general, are the same
then as now: ``Rough winds do shake the darling buds of May.''
</P>
<P>
   Some writers, though, seem to think these forms have become
meaningless, mere verbal jesters' caps to give words the look of
Olden Days.
</P>
<P>
   Another Times attempt at Shakespearean language, celebrating
Valentine's Day 1997, landed in a grammatical badger hole with
every other step. A mock interview with the aging Romeo and Juliet,
the Sunday magazine piece makes Juliet sound like a tourist groping
her way in a foreign language: ``They'd all gangeth up on us like
the furies,'' she says. ``Cupid's bow doth got put in storage. At
one time Romeo wouldst have slain love for me. ... We couldst not
find a resolution.'' Romeo, given fewer lines, gets off with fewer
missteps: ``And we taketh separate vacations'' is his worst moment.
</P>
<P>
   These are highly visible examples, but of course the Times is
not alone. A 1996 Globe column was headlined ``Their cups runneth
over,'' and it probably wasn't the first appearance of that
variant. Other newspapers surely have their share of misplaced
doths and runneths, whether in headlines or hiding in the small
type.
</P>
<P>
   The question, as always, is how much we should care. Most of us
learned what we know of this grammar from Shakespeare or the King
James Bible, not from Elizabethan grammar books; we're not experts,
and we might well have trouble navigating the thees, thous and
yous, which have usage subtleties, like tu and vous in French, that
no longer exist in English.
</P>
<P>
   But the verb forms are simple enough that the wrong one sounds
comical to any reader with a few sonnets or psalms stored away in
his or her memory bank. Not comical-funny, as having Juliet use the
20th-century gang up might be, but comical-pitiable.
</P>
<P>
   Some writers who dabble in archaic verbs are surprised that
anyone would care about correctness. They know that if they mangle
an Italian phrase or get a Yiddish word wrong, readers will let
them hear about it, but few people today speak Shakespeare _ and
they seem to have their hands full without policing the daily
papers. Still, an archaism gone awry is likely to annoy as many
readers as it amuses; here, as so often, the better part of valor
is discretion.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Voter turnout delays tally
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The enthusiastic response to The Word's reader survey of bring
vs. take usage was too much for my computer printer, which is lying
on its back with its feet waving feebly in the air, figuratively
speaking. That means a tally of the results will have to wait
another fortnight, so if you haven't cast a vote, the polls will be
open for a few more days; just write or e-mail saying which verb
you would probably use in the following sentence:
</P>
<P>
   ``For a pain-free vacation at the beach, be sure to (bring/take)
along plenty of sunblock.''
</P>
<P>
   Assume, to avoid ambiguity, that you're reading the sentence in
the newspaper (as, indeed, you are), not hearing it from, say, a
friend on the telephone. And again, please note where you spent
your early years, to help us track the paths of these competing
usages.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (What's the word? Write or e-mail yours to Jan Freeman at The
Boston Globe, Boston, MA 02107-2378; freeman(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
