<SLUG> BC-JORDAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARSHBARGER FIRMLY IN LABOR'S GOOD GRACES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT JORDAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If there was a defining moment in the battle to be the next
governor of Massachusetts, it arrived Thursday when the state's
largest union organization gave its endorsement to Attorney General
Scott Harshbarger.
</P>
<P>
   While winning the state Democratic convention's endorsement
earlier this month was an important step for Harshbarger, that
victory was largely the result of a struggle between his team and
party insiders who had hoped to embarrass him by denying him that
endorsement.
</P>
<P>
   But the state AFL-CIO approval will have influence far beyond
convention walls, reaching to virtually every corner of the state.
Which is why Harshbarger wanted it so badly, and why his two
Democratic rivals, Patricia McGovern and Brian Donnelly, wanted so
badly to deny him the necessary two-thirds vote of the AFL-CIO
Executive Council.
</P>
<P>
   With this backing, Harshbarger will now have organized labor
working in his behalf, not only for the September primary, but
leading to the November final. That gives the AFL-CIO ample time to
build support for him among rank-and-file union members.
</P>
<P>
   Although Harshbarger actively sought the AFL-CIO's endorsement,
there was no assurance that he would get the support from the
executive council. Some unions were reluctant to support him, and
several others expressed outright opposition, largely over
perceptions that he was not aggressive enough against state wage
law violations, a charge that Harshbarger denies.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Harshbarger and key AFL-CIO officials worked right
up to the day of the vote to persuade enough union leaders on the
council to support the Democratic front-runner, making the case
that Harshbarger is the only Democratic hopeful who can defeat
Acting Governor Paul Cellucci, should he survive his own primary
challenge.
</P>
<P>
   When the votes were counted after the candidates made their
pitch, Harshbarger won, 40 to 16, an overwhelming victory for a
candidate who was not high on labor's list of potential
endorsements at the beginning of the campaign season.
</P>
<P>
   If half of the 400,000-member AFL-CIO, plus a 100,000 of their
friends and relatives, voted for Harshbarger, that could help put
him over the top in November.
</P>
<P>
   If Harshbarger had not received the council's endorsement, he
would have been politically weakened, giving his rivals and other
critics an argument that he neither earned nor deserves organized
labor's support. That could also have sparked new life in
McGovern's campaign, which has been lagging Harshbarger's in voter
support.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the one candidate who could have impeded Harshbarger
last week was not McGovern, but Donnelly. Although he is a distant
third in the campaign, Donnelly had a good enough labor record
during his years in Congress to gain significant support from the
AFL-CIO's Executive Council.
</P>
<P>
   However, his thus-far subpar performance in this election has
prevented him from winning greater support on the council. He lost
ground early when the media printed revelations that contradicted
earlier stories about being a high school and college football
player. Donnelly lost a bit more ground when he had to retract two
union endorsements his campaign said he received. Had Donnelly's
campaign not made such mistakes, his candidacy might have been more
viable.
</P>
<P>
   McGovern still believes she can appeal to ``rank-and-file''
union members in an effort to diminish the impact of the AFL-CIO
endorsement of Harshbarger, but that will not be an easy task,
since the rank-and-file membership is more likely to support
Harshbarger for the same reason the AFL-CIO leadership endorsed
him: as the best chance of unseating Cellucci. If he is elected,
Harshbarger is likely to be as supportive of labor's agenda as
labor was of his candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   Organized labor needs no reminder that some candidates who
received its backing ended up on the losing end of elections. One
was James Shannon, who lost his 1990 bid for attorney general to
Harshbarger.
</P>
<P>
   But now with Harshbarger and the AFL-CIO working together in
this election, Harshbarger is likely to be in better shape for the
November final than Cellucci may be after his bitter primary battle
with State Treasurer Joseph Malone.
</P>
<P>
   This endorsement, however, is only the official beginning of
organized labor's efforts to put Harshbarger into the governor's
chair. Now the AFL-CIO and its supporting affiliates must go out
and persuade as many union workers as possible that a vote for
Harshbarger is a vote for union workers and working families.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Robert A. Jordan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
