   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   BOOMERS _ WASHINGTON _ For Baby Boomers entering their 50s,
staying healthy may be the key to being wealthy. For people between
the ages of 51 and 61, ``health shocks'' such as cancer and heart
attacks are increasingly frequent and are an important determinant
in whether a family accumulates weath or depletes it, said James P.
Smith, senior economist and chairman of labor markets and
demographic studies for the RAND Corp. (Dart, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   ECONOMY-2000 _ WASHINGTON _ Saying that danger is rising that
the Year 2000 computer problem could cause a global recession, the
National Association of Manufacturers called Tuesday for a
four-point attack on the software glitch. The industrial coalition
asked Congress to provide antitrust protection for companies that
cooperate on the problem and liability protection for those who do
not completely solve it. It also asked for major federal spending
to fix government computers and a broad information campaign to
alert people to the seriousness of the problem. (Glass, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   TRUCKERS-TAXES _ WASHINGTON _ A family-owned trucking business
located in Wilmington, Ohio, is in a battle with the IRS, which
claims it owes more than $3.5 million in taxes. (Moskal, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   ISSUEADS _ District Court judge in Washington to rule on a
request from the Democratic and Republican parties to use more soft
money on issue ads. The ruling could have a huge impact on the
money spent on issue advocacy this election year. (Foskett, Cox
News Service).
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   PENNYFLETCHER _ Tanned and slender, now 35-year-old Penny
Fletcher bears faint resemblance to the pale, puffy woman who spent
nine months in Her Majesty's Prison for Women on the Caribbean
island of St. Vincent on a murder charge. Those physical reminders
of her season in hell are gone. But sunshine and exercise have not
driven away the nightmares. They have followed her from the prison
on the Caribbean island of St. Vincent to her home in Huntington,
W.Va. And they are with her now in Xenia, Ohio, where she is making
an ``extended visit'' with her sister. Hoping, perhaps, that time
in the bucolic American heartland will help exorcise the tropical
island demons. (Stewart, Dayton Daily News) 103 inches.
</P>
<P>
   EVERGLADES-RESPITE01 _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ While the rest of
us swelter, watch our gardens wilt and ask when the rain will
return, scientists are calling the dry spell a blessing for the
Everglades. After all, it was just a few months ago that El
Nino-driven rain was drowning marsh-dwelling trees and making life
miserable for wading birds. The dry skies offer a chance to breathe
_ and breed. ``We know with the lower water, the healing will
begin,'' said Herb Zebuth, a coordinator for the state Department
of Environmental Protection's West Palm Beach office. ``And for
that, we're grateful.'' (King, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   ALA-RUNOFF _ Report on the Alabama gubernatorial runoff.
(Manuel, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA: Late.
</P>
