u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BARNICLE-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-30 0802
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARNICLE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASIC VALUES UNITE FRIENDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MIKE BARNICLE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fred Suplee walked into Doyle's Cafe at precisely 12:15 the
other afternoon and waited by the bar for a few minutes until his
old pal, Jack Spinney, came in out of the heat in order to wrap his
hands around a good, cold beer. The two men, Suplee and Spinney _
one 82, the other 77 _ have been getting together at noon, on the
same stools, in the same marvelous Boston tavern for nearly 50
years, ever since discovering that they shared a common past as
prisoners of war in 1944.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had it easy,'' Freddie Suplee said, smiling at Jack
Spinney. ``He got to ride all over Europe. He was in the Air Force.
I was in the infantry. We got a ditch and a can of beans.''
</P>
<P>
   Jack Spinney's story: Dorchester High. Joined the Army Air Corps
on Dec. 8, 1941. Assigned to the 449th Bomber Group, 417th Wing as
a ball-gunner, the guy who sits in a tiny turret attached to the
belly of the bomber; by spring 1944 his unit was flying out of an
American base in Italy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had flown 36 missions,'' Spinney recalled. ``April 11, 1944
was my 37th. And it was also `adios.' We got shot down over
Romania, bombing the oil fields at Ploesti. I got sent to a POW
camp in Bucharest.''
</P>
<P>
   Fred Suplee: Drafted in 1941 out of Our Lady of Lourdes High.
Walked across France after D-Day with the 26th Infantry Division
until the first week in October when he and three others in his
anti-tank gun crew got separated from their unit in the Saar Valley
along the German border, and hid upstairs for two days in a
farmhouse as 80 German soldiers ate and slept downstairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had us outgunned,'' Suplee said simply. ``Our lieutenant
ordered artillery in on our own position to kill the Germans. He
was a brave guy, but they got us. There were only four of us, and
they brought us to an SS unit in the nearest town where they lined
us up in front of a row of machine guns. I figured that was it, but
they changed their minds and walked us almost all the way to Berlin
to a POW camp 7 miles outside the city.''
</P>
<P>
   Both men found freedom in the spring of 1945 when the Russian
Army liberated their camps. Spinney came home and worked for
decades as an ambulance driver for Boston. Suplee returned and got
on the cops, working for decades in old Division 10 at Jackson
Square until retirement.
</P>
<P>
   They are part of an uncomplaining generation who first saved and
then helped transform the United States from a sleepy, isolationist
outpost to the economic, industrial powerhouse that dominates the
stage today. Unfortunately, with their modesty, self-reliance,
sense of obligation, loyalty, and lack of any feelings of
victimization both men are nearly completely at odds with the
confused, celebrity-crazed, self-pitying culture currently around
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't bad,'' Suplee said. ``Most of the guards were good
guys. They were all old. The camp was outside Berlin. We'd hear our
planes going overhead all day and all night; it was a beautiful
sound, made us feel good until they dropped a bomb in the camp one
day and killed a couple hundred guys.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That was us then,'' Jack Spinney told Suplee. ``We bombed in
the day. The British bombed at night. Funniest thing, though, was
getting freed by the Russians. Turns out they weren't bad bastards
after all.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to walk in circles all day, saying the Rosary on our
fingers,'' Freddie Suplee added. ``Then we'd go to Confession.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We had that, too,'' Spinney remembered. ``I could never figure
that out. I mean, what the eff are you going to confess in prison
camp? What could you do? They wouldn't even let us smoke. The
Germans actually were ahead of their time: They made me stop
smoking.''
</P>
<P>
   The liberated young men both came back the same summer _ 1945 _
to a different country, to their families, jobs, and neighborhoods.
And ever since they discovered each other nearly 50 years ago they
have grown old keeping the light of memory and nobility alive at a
time when much in our midst seems neither memorable or essential
when compared to the courage and sacrifice each man displayed
without ever being asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Funny thing is when I got back and came into Doyle's the first
time, the bartender said to me, `Where the hell you been?''' Fred
Suplee recalled with a laugh. ``His name was Sean Bradley. He was
from Ireland.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Tom Whalen and Tom McDonough were the other two bartenders,''
Jack Spinney pointed out. ``They said the same thing to me. Like we
was gone a week or so.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That was OK,'' Fred Suplee said to his friend Jack Spinney.
``We were just glad to be home. It wasn't any big deal.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mike Barnicle is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
