<HEADLINE>
AROUND THE WORLD _ WITH TOWELS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Summer is a busy time for hotel chains. Take the Hampton Inn
group, which will accommodate 6 million travelers at its more than
800 properties from Memorial Day through Labor Day. The hotels
expect to:
</P>
<P>
   _Distribute more than 8 million bars of soap and 3 million
bottles of shampoo.
</P>
<P>
   _Supply guests with more than 32 million towels _ more than
enough, if laid flat, to circle the Earth.
</P>
<P>
   _Wash more than 1.5 million loads of laundry. That's equal to
washing 11 loads every minute throughout June, July, and August.
</P>
<P>
   _Provide 432,000 gallons of juice. That's enough to fill more
than 11,000 bathtubs.
</P>
<P>
   _Serve more than 9 million complimentary breakfasts, which will
include nearly 3.5 million bagels and more than 14 million cups of
coffee. That's enough coffee for every resident of Florida to have
a cup.
</P>
<P>
   _Distribute more than 5.5 million copies of USA Today. We know:
You'd rather read the Globe.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Travel Trivia: &LR;  This question has nothing to do with travel except
that we heard it during a trivia game on the Grand Princess cruise
ship. A man leaves home, heads right, turns left, then left again,
then left one more time, and returns home, where he encounters a
masked man. Who is that masked man? (Answer at end of column.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; In a name: &LR;  In his book ``Team Rodent,'' Carl Hiaasen refers to
Walt Disney World's new Animal Kingdom theme park as ``Honey, I
Shrunk the Serengetti.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Quotable: &LR;  ``I looked up and saw the outline of the island. And I
knew right away that there was the place I'd been looking for all
my life.'' _ W. Somerset Maugham, on Tahiti.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Freebie: &LR;  Youngsters 17 and under will be admitted free to the John
F. Kennedy Library and Museum in Dorchester on Wednesday evenings
from 5 to 8 through Labor Day. Children 12 and under are already
admitted free throughout the year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Today's fractured English lesson: &LR;  A souvenir bookmark given to
tourists in Barbados lists a ``Conscious Traveler's Tip.'' (With
thanks to Sue Hamar of Aunt Suzie's Bayside Bed &AMP; Breakfast in
Wellfleet.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Heads up: &LR;  For the first time since 1939, Fourth of July fireworks
will soar above the president's heads that are carved into Mount
Rushmore in South Dakota.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Congrats, Wayne! &LR;  Las Vegas residents were surveyed on their choice
of worst hotel entertainer. They picked Wayne Newton.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Did you guess it? &LR;  The masked man is a catcher or umpire. The man
who encounters him is the batter at a baseball game.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
