<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 14:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3811 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-MAPS-BOS &LR;      06-30 1167
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-MAPS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAPPING OUR PLACE IN TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KENNEY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ After Norman B. Leventhal has guided a
visitor through his collection of historical maps of Boston and New
England, he calls attention to a rather ordinary 1930 map of
Dorchester that has pride of place in the exhibit at MIT's Compton
Gallery, right inside the door, hanging above the visitors' book.
</P>
<P>
   It is not immediately obvious why that map is hanging where it
is. What significant _ or insignificant _ bit of local history
could it represent? Is it what Dorchester would look like if it had
remained a separate city instead of being annexed by Boston? Or
does it show how Blue Hill Avenue and Dorchester Avenue provided
escape routes to suburbia?
</P>
<P>
   Both true, but neither are what Leventhal had in mind, so he
resolves the issue _ quite impishly _ by pointing to a small red
dot pasted on a small side street off Columbia Road.
</P>
<P>
   It marks Wolcott Street, he tells a visitor, pausing for an
unspoken ``and?'' before he explains with a very quiet chuckle that
it's the street where he grew up.
</P>
<P>
   And if you are Norman B. Leventhal, 81 years old this summer,
developer of some of Boston's most recent landmarks and owner of
what is regarded as one of the finest private collections of maps
in New England, you are more than entitled to a bit of fun.
</P>
<P>
   But even if you are not Norman B. Leventhal, these maps let any
Bostonian, longtime resident or newcomer, see the city with a new
awareness, even a sense of rediscovery.
</P>
<P>
   Leventhal's collection _ begun some 30 years ago with the
purchase of a small map of Boston _ now comprises some 300 items,
ranging from speculative maps drawn before Columbus's voyage of
discovery to contemporary ones created with the most advanced
technology. The MIT exhibit, ``Mapping Boston: Delineating the City
and Its Region,'' is open weekdays only through July 31.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, 69 maps from Leventhal's collection are on permanent
display in the lobby of the Boston Harbor Hotel, developed by
Leventhal's Beacon Companies, and another 26 in the lobby of the
Hotel Meridien, another Beacon project.
</P>
<P>
   In its seeming ordinariness _ it lacks the rich details of the
cartographers' art that mark the other maps in the exhibit _ that
``Plan of Dorchester'' illustrates what most intrigues Leventhal
about maps.
</P>
<P>
   It is, he said, ``the stories behind them'' _ whether they are
of his personal Dorchester in the days of his youth, or of how, and
why, Boston changed through the 360 years of its history.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see how things were viewed at the time the map was
drawn,'' Leventhal said. Then with later maps of the city, ``you
see a history evolving through them.''
</P>
<P>
   There is, for instance, the map that first catches the visitor's
eye (assuming that visitor has walked right past the Dorchester
map).
</P>
<P>
   It is a richly colored map, produced in 1776 by a German
cartographer, in which Boston _ still pretty much the tiny
peninsula of its first settlement a century and a half before _
appears overwhelmed by the surrounding hills and Harbor Islands,
studded with the small red blocks of army encampments and artillery
fortifications.
</P>
<P>
   That map should have bluntly suggested to the city's British
commanders that they were in a most untenable situation and that it
was time to think about pulling out and heading for Canada.
</P>
<P>
   A beautifully detailed map from 1838 suggests how much the world
changed over the next half-century. Its Boston is depicted as the
hub of a great transportation network _ railroad lines
crisscrossing the bend in the Charles River that would become the
Back Bay, the broad Boston Wharf along what is now Fort Point
Channel eclipsing the slender wharves of the old Colonial
waterfront.
</P>
<P>
   Taken together, the 1776 and 1838 maps illustrate the point made
by urban historian Kevin Lynch in ``The Image of the City,'' that
as a city like Boston develops, its ``specific character'' becomes
``perhaps as much the result of human action and desires as of the
original geological structure.''
</P>
<P>
   A pair of maps, from the Municipal Registers of 1852 and 1855,
pinpoint the time when the Back Bay began to take shape. In the
earlier map, that area &UR;  &LR; is still a widening of the Charles River, a
waterfront edge for the Public Garden, labeled ``Receiving Bay''
and still crisscrossed by the trestles that carried the Providence
and Worcester railroad lines. But just three years later, a grid of
streets had been superimposed over the bay, the future Arlington,
Berkeley, Clarendon, and the rest.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, there is a 1914 city map with the routes of a
proposed new street over the Boston and Albany Railroad tracks and
a railroad tunnel under a new street to be built between North and
South stations. They suggest the logic _ perhaps even the
inevitability _ of the future routes of the then
not-even-dreamed-of Massachusetts Turnpike and Central Artery.
</P>
<P>
   Leventhal likes poking around for additions to his collection in
rare and used book stores. And urban planner Alex Krieger, a fellow
map fancier and curator of the collection, keeps his eye open for
possible additions as well. Krieger is co-editor for a book based
on the Leventhal collection to be published next spring by MIT
Press.
</P>
<P>
   For all the time that Leventhal has spent studying his maps
since he brought his first one some 30 years ago, there remains the
thrill of fresh discoveries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time I look at them I see something new,'' Leventhal
said, pointing to an 1800 map that is of historical interest
because it is the first one to show the city divided in wards for
voting purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Prominent in this map is the long street running down the narrow
neck of land that connected the original peninsular city to Roxbury
on the mainland. Soon it would be renamed Washington Street _ and
much later be a trolley route _ but then it was still Orange
Street.
</P>
<P>
   Until looking at the map recently, as he was selecting it for
inclusion in the MIT exhibit, Leventhal said, ``I never associated
Orange Street with the Orange Line.''
</P>
<P>
   There is one other map that intrigues Leventhal's playful
nature.
</P>
<P>
   It's an 1886 map drawn for the Boston Park Department _ one on
which the Emerald Necklace and other city parks are marked in
bright green.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent visit to the exhibit, Leventhal peered closely at it
for several minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hummm,'' he said very much tongue in cheek, ``how come there
isn't any green at Post Office Square?'' That, of course, could
only be colored green now, as the site of the popular Financial
District park created by Leventhal and other abutting property
owners on the site of a parking garage.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (``Mapping Boston: Delineating the City and Its Region,'' at the
Compton Gallery, Massachusetts Institute of Technology, 77
Massachusetts Ave., Cambridge. Weekdays only; through July 31, 9
a.m. to 5 p.m. Call 253-4444.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
