<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-MYTOWN-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE HISTORY MEETS THE STREET 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-ART-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LAURA YUEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Sixteen-year-old tour guide Shauna Rigaud is delivering
her standard tour-guide pitch. She is explaining the significance
of a Victorian-era brick apartment building in Boston's South End.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. lived here, she
says &UR;  &LR; matter-of-factly, when he was a theology graduate student at
Boston University. King met his future wife during these years in
Boston at a social gathering, Rigaud tells the group.
</P>
<P>
   A wide grin appears beneath the rim of her baseball cap. ``At a
frat party or something,'' she adds, as though sharing a playful
secret. ``He asked his friend, `Aw, who's that fly honey over
there?' His friend said, `That's Coretta Scott. She goes to the New
England Conservatory of Music.' And the rest is civil rights
history.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, the ``fly honey'' comment might be a bit revisionist for a
tour of Boston. But Rigaud knows her facts about the subject of her
tour, the South End, a community steeped in neighborhood activism
and ethnic diversity.
</P>
<P>
   Rigaud is one of 20 tour guides employed by the Multicultural
Youth Tour of What's Now (MYTOWN). Nearly three years old, the
nonprofit group uses young people to point out lesser-known
neighborhood landmarks, providing tour groups with a deeper
understanding of recent local history. While other Boston
excursions may dwell on Colonial and revolutionary times, the young
historians of MYTOWN focus on the last 100 &UR;  &LR; years of urban
development.
</P>
<P>
   On their guided two-hour walking tours, they tell the less
traditional stories of community action and contributions to the
city by people of color. ``Stuff doesn't get told because people
don't ask,'' tour guide Elizabeth Miranda, 18, says. ``Whether you
work in Fidelity or you're cleaning the streets, you better know
that street. It's all about ownership.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the South End is often associated with young, well-to-do
residents of gentrified bow-front homes, longtime South Enders know
its rich history of immigrants and minorities. A potpourri of
Irish, African-American, Afro-Caribbean, Chinese, Greek, Syrian,
Puerto Rican, and Jewish people have filled the neighborhood over
the years.
</P>
<P>
   The South End was built on filled land when Beacon Hill grew
overcrowded with well-to-do Brahmins in the 1850s. These families
migrated to the South End _ or built houses there for their
servants _ but soon fled to the Back Bay during strong waves of
immigration. Over the years, its brick and brownstone row houses
were turned into rooming houses, and it is only within the past 30
years that so many high-income residents have found a haven in this
neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Each MYTOWN tour selects 10 to 12 neighborhood stops from a pool
of more than 60 points of interest. In her debut stop, rookie guide
Danielle Youngblood, 17, of Dorchester, explains how Charlie's
Sandwich Shoppe on Columbus Avenue was one of the few places black
jazz musicians would be served after their gigs in the 1920s and
'30s. She points to her feet. Members of her tour group see two
pairs of dice _ lucky sevens _ embedded in the sidewalk, indicating
the gambling scene at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Things like that often go unnoticed in an everyday stroll. The
small Union United Methodist Church, 485 Columbus Ave., was a stop
on the Underground Railroad. The attractive apartment complex of
Tent City, 130 Dartmouth St., was the fruit of neighborhood protest
for affordable housing during urban renewal. State Representative
Byron Rushing's campaign headquarters are stationed at the former
Academy of Musical Arts, 547 Columbus Ave., a studio that offered
dance and music lessons to working-class families for 75 years.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the legwork needed to unearth South End history took
place outside library doors. Few of the stories told by tour guides
are documented; MYTOWN historians collect them by taking the oral
histories of the South End residents who remember the desegregation
crisis, urban renewal, and King's march on Boston in April 1965.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boston is the preservation capital of the world,'' says
co-founder Karilyn Crockett. ``But at MYTOWN, we don't put history
in a climate-controlled box that's never to be used again. To us,
preservation is an act of sharing, not hoarding, information.''
</P>
<P>
   MYTOWN is the brainchild of Crockett and Denise Thomas, both
Yale University seniors in 1995 when they came up with the idea. As
an African-American raised in Dorchester, Crockett says, she found
it hard to feel like a Bostonian when the schools taught her only
about the likes of Paul Revere and John Hancock.
</P>
<P>
   Children ``at school are learning about the Tea Party and our
patriot fathers,'' Crockett says. ``They sound like cool enough
guys, but they don't help people understand what's happened in our
neighborhoods for the past 150 years. There's a broader part of
history that must be told.''
</P>
<P>
   The two women started MYTOWN out of a combination bedroom and
office in the Dorchester home of Crockett's uncle, alternating
nights sleeping on the cot and bed. They first secured the initial
$30,000 grant from the New York Echoing Green Foundation, which
awards money to college graduates who start social justice
projects. Since then, MYTOWN has subsisted on money from local
foundation and individual contributors. Tour prices are set on a
sliding scale, anywhere from $2.50 to $15 per person. (For example,
school groups pay less than for-profit organizations.) MYTOWN's
target audience is Boston residents, primarily middle- and
high-school students.
</P>
<P>
   In the organization's cramped downtown office above a Downtown
Crossing storefront, the largest room belongs to the youth
historians who make MYTOWN happen. Three young but experienced
guides are shouting out their picks for the newest batch of MYTOWN
youth guides. Over 70 teenagers have applied for just 13 spots for
the summer. Thomas holds a fat Magic Marker as she points to each
name on the oversize tablet.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need a Latino here,'' says Miranda. ``This is
multicultural.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We need an Asian, yo!'' shouts Huong Hoang, 17. ``I'm the only
sistah here!''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
