<HEADER>
A3822 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS     06-30 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BUFFETT OF THE BOGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE BAILEY AND STEVEN SYRE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Warren Buffett is the widely admired ``Wizard of Omaha,'' and
the entire investment world is constantly trying to divine his
every move. Class A stock in his company, Berkshire Hathaway, sells
for an astounding $78,400 a share.
</P>
<P>
   No one we know has ever called Christopher Makepeace ``the
Wizard of Wareham,'' but at $11,600 a share his company, A.D.
Makepeace Co., has the distinction of being the priciest stock in
all of Massachusetts. If Buffett knows investing, Chris Makepeace
knows cranberries.
</P>
<P>
   A.D. Makepeace is the largest owner of Ocean Spray Cranberries
Inc., the giant cooperative that dominates the cranberry business
in a way that General Motors could only dream about in the auto
business. And Makepeace is maybe the largest private land owner in
Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   But don't rush out to load up on the stock. With about 80
percent of Makepeace still held by the family and the rest by a
couple of institutions and a handful of ``collectors,'' the stock
rarely trades. The last trade, in fact, was April 2, when two _
yes, two _ shares traded at $11,600. There's a long waiting list to
get in. ``A 10-share transaction is cataclysmic,'' says one Boston
broker who follows the stock for a few clients.
</P>
<P>
   Among institutions, the T. Rowe Price Small Cap fund owns a
small stake and Wellington Management's Binkley Shorts, who has
long followed the company, has some for clients. Wellington won't
comment, but a Price spokesman says its small-cap manager, Greg
McCrickard, likes the ``asset-rich company.''
</P>
<P>
   Asset rich, indeed.
</P>
<P>
   Makepeace owns 15,000 acres of land, about 12,000 of that in
Eastern Massachusetts. The land is carried on the balance sheet at
about $17 million, its value in 1922. But consider: Makepeace has
about 1,750 acres in cultivation; value that at the going rate of
$40,000 an acre and the cranberry bogs and the abutting land alone
has a value of about $70 million. This is a company with a market
value of just $81 million.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the land, Makepeace is Ocean Spray's biggest
producer. The company harvested nearly 300,000 barrels of
cranberries last year, up 54 percent for a disappointing 1996 crop.
Makepeace had net income of $1.9 million on $14.7 million in
revenue last year.
</P>
<P>
   As Ocean Spray's biggest producer, Makepeace is also the
cooperative's biggest owner, with a 7 percent stake. If Ocean Spray
were valued at maybe two times revenues _ the number being used to
value Seagram's proposed spinoff of Tropicana _ the cranberry co-op
would be worth about $3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Ocean Spray's slow growth and flat payouts to cranberry growers
has created a fair amount of unrest down on the farm, particularly
among younger growers who are stuck with big debt to pay off their
bogs. Makepeace in its annual report says it is encouraging Ocean
Spray ``to explore structural alternatives.''
</P>
<P>
   Industry analysts say those alternatives could range as wide as
taking a part of the company public to selling a piece of the
company to a strategic partner such as Pepsico, which has a
distribution agreement with Ocean Spray. Robert L. Rosbe Jr.,
Makepeace's vice president for finance, talks in considerably more
modest terms of ``finding ways to raise growth capital'' and the
``constraints'' of being a cooperative.
</P>
<P>
   Makepeace still operates more like a private company than a
public one. But those who follow Makepeace say it has been shifting
away from a tightly managed family enterprise. Rosbe came from a
venture capital firm two years ago and handles much of the business
side, allowing Chris Makepiece, the chief executive, to focus on
the actual cranberry production. John Drew, who is married to a
family member, was brought in about 1 1/2 years ago to manage the
real estate side.
</P>
<P>
   Makepeace's development plans have generated some concern,
particularly in the towns of Carver and Wareham. Rosbe says
developing Makepeace's huge holdings ``is going to be a much
longer-range process than most people would expect.''
</P>
<P>
   Another long-term issue to watch: the family itself. The
Makepeace family is now in its sixth generation, many of them far
removed from the cranberry business. How many similar situations
have we seen where the issue was not how did the business get the
family here, but what kind of returns can it produce for the kids
going forward?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Steve Bailey and Steven Syre can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
