<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 14:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3828 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LUCAS-STRANGEODYSSEY-     06-30 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LUCAS-STRANGEODYSSEY-960(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HENRY LEE LUCAS ENDED UP ON DEATH ROW BECAUSE OF HIS OWN WORDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN MORITZ 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HUNTSVILLE, Texas _ In many respects, Henry Lee Lucas was the
author of his own death sentence.
</P>
<P>
   The Virginia-born drifter was scheduled to be executed June 23
for what had been the all-but-forgotten rape and murder of an
unknown woman near Georgetown in 1979. But that sentence was
commuted to a life term on Friday by Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   At first blush, any suggestion that the man who once confessed
to some 600 killings deserves mercy might seem ludicrous. Beginning
15 years ago this month, Lucas joined law enforcement officials
from numerous states at one crime scene after another where he
coldly described a series of stabbings, drownings and
strangulations.
</P>
<P>
   Even after investigations by news reporters and the Texas
attorney general's office proved that most of the confessions were
false, Lucas generated little sympathy because law officers
remained convinced that he had killed somebody.
</P>
<P>
   After all, he had served 10 years in a Michigan prison for
fatally stabbing his 74-year-old mother and, more recently, led
police to a prairie in Denton where they found the dismembered
remains of the 15-year-old girl whom he described as his wife.
</P>
<P>
   So there was little surprise when Lucas was condemned to die for
the Georgetown slaying. But the conviction rested not on eyewitness
accounts, not on rock-solid physical evidence and not on a mountain
of circumstantial evidence.
</P>
<P>
   It was Lucas' own words _ repeated to lawmen, captured on
videotape and written on paper _ that put him on Death Row.
</P>
<P>
   ``I killed her ... by strangling her with my hands,'' Lucas said
in a written statement presented to jurors at his 1984 trial. It
describes the slaying of a brown-haired woman whose body, clad only
in orange socks, was found in a culvert off Interstate 35 in rural
Williamson County on Halloween 1979. ``She was later undressed, and
I had sex with her after she was dead,'' Lucas said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the chairman of the Texas Board of Pardons and Paroles
last week said the recommendation that the death sentence be
commuted hinged on doubts that Lucas was in Texas when the woman
was killed, prosecutors and jurors at the time were not swayed by
any alibi testimony.
</P>
<P>
   ``Henry Lee Lucas is a cold-blooded murderer,'' said Williamson
County District Attorney Ken Anderson, who as a deputy prosecutor
in 1984 helped win the conviction. ``The jury looked at all the
evidence that his defenders now say clears him and they rejected
it. So have the 23 judges who have looked at this case on appeal.''
Because of the publicity Lucas' confessions generated in Williamson
County, the trial in the ``Orange Socks'' murder was moved to San
Angelo and began in April 1984. Anderson and then-District Attorney
Ed Walsh built their case on the numerous confessions that Lucas
had handed them.
</P>
<P>
   But by that time, Lucas had recanted the confessions, saying
that they were hoaxes designed to toy with police. He claimed that
he had actually been working as a roofer in Jacksonville, Fla.,
when ``Orange Socks'' was killed.
</P>
<P>
   According to trial transcripts in the archives of the Texas
Court of Criminal Appeals, prosecutors read aloud for the jury of
eight women and four men Lucas' single-page admission of guilt,
which he had signed at 10:47 a.m. on June, 23, 1983, in the
presence of then-Sheriff Jim Boutwell.
</P>
<P>
   They also played audio tapes of Lucas talking with Boutwell
about the strangulation and postmortem sex.
</P>
<P>
   Then they showed a video of Lucas at the crime scene. Handcuffed
and wearing jeans and a plaid shirt, Lucas is seen stepping over a
guardrail as he simulates dragging the woman's body to the huge
concrete culvert near the interstate.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas' lawyers argued that the confessions should not have been
admitted into evidence. But Judge John Carter rejected their
assertions that the statements had been coerced and that Lucas,
heavily medicated with Thorazine to control a mental illness, was
incompetent.
</P>
<P>
   In testimony, Boutwell said Lucas was often informed of his
rights and just as often waived offers that an attorney be provided
for him. On at least one occasion, Boutwell testified, Lucas
insisted that a lawyer who had shown up uninvited at the jail be
turned away.
</P>
<P>
   Boutwell, who died in December 1993, said that an uncoached
Lucas led them to a culvert about 30 miles north of Austin where a
woman's body had been found.
</P>
<P>
   During cross-examination, Boutwell acknowledged that on some
occasions, Lucas had key facts about the case wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyer Max Parker asked Boutwell: ``Isn't it a fact,
sheriff, that when you first talked to him on June 22nd (1983) ...
he thought the lady had blond hair, not brown hair?''
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   Boutwell: ``He mentioned a lady with blond hair, yes, sir.''
</P>
<P>
   Parker: ``Initially, didn't he tell you he took the body out
into a field or some type of ... secluded area?''
</P>
<P>
   Boutwell: ``That's correct.''
</P>
<P>
   Two foremen from the Jacksonville roofing company testified that
work records showed that Lucas was on the job during the last week
of October and early November 1979.
</P>
<P>
   But prosecutors again used Lucas' own words to poke holes in the
alibis. They played tape recordings of Lucas saying that the
foremen had accepted kickbacks from absent roofers who were marked
present for work.
</P>
<P>
   The foremen adamantly denied falsifying work documents. But
during cross-examination, Anderson confronted them with records
showing that each had served prison time for convictions such as
fraud, theft and passing hot checks.
</P>
<P>
   Testimony from psychiatrists suggesting that mental illness
prompted Lucas to make a false confession also had little or no
effect on the jury.
</P>
<P>
   When the testimony ended, jurors deliberated a little more than
nine hours before returning the guilty verdict. Then they decided
on the death penalty after a 45-minute discussion.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Virginia on Aug. 23, 1936, the last of 12 children,
Lucas said he grew up neglected and abused, taunted by a mother who
was a prostitute and who committed sex acts in his presence. His
father, a railroad brakeman whose legs were severed when he was hit
by a rail car in a freight yard, spent his spare hours drunk, Lucas
said.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas recalled being an unsupervised child whose family migrated
from Virginia to Maryland to Michigan. He never made it past the
fourth grade and said his first arrest came at age 15 for stealing
food. He was sent to a reformatory.
</P>
<P>
   In 1960, Lucas was convicted of second-degree murder in Michigan
for the stabbing death of his mother, Viola.
</P>
<P>
   A drifter with an extensive criminal record, Lucas began his
rise to notoriety inauspiciously in June 1983 when he was taken
into custody in Montague County for being an ex-con with a weapon.
</P>
<P>
   The sheriff actually suspected that he killed 80-year-old
Ringgold resident Kate Rich 10 months earlier, but lacked enough
evidence. But the sheriff got a break when Lucas confessed to the
stabbing and mutilation of the elderly woman.
</P>
<P>
   He also confessed to killing Freida Lorraine ``Becky'' Powell,
the 15-year-old he called his wife. Soon thereafter, he became a
confession machine who earned him international headlines.
</P>
<P>
   Now 61 _ the oldest of the 454 inmates on Texas' Death Row _
Lucas bears little resemblance to the lean, cold-eyed desperado who
came forth with those ghastly confessions 15 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   His once-rugged face is wrinkled, pale and puffy. The coarse
black hair is mostly gray, and his words are tinged with regret
over what he calls his wasted life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I blame myself for letting people walk all over me,'' Lucas
said. ``I should have been a man and stood up on my own two feet.
But I didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   There is little chance that Lucas will ever walk free again. He
is serving 10 sentences, including six life terms, and he still
faces murder charges in other states, including a Florida case that
could carry the death sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Many who question his guilt in the ``Orange Socks'' case believe
that he killed Powell, Rich and possibly others. Few express
sympathy for Lucas.
</P>
<P>
   Wise County Sheriff Phil Ryan, who as a Texas Ranger was among
the first lawmen to hear Lucas' confessions, said he wouldn't have
lost any sleep if Lucas were executed. Ryan said he believes that
Lucas is a killer but remains undecided about his guilt in the
``Orange Socks'' murder.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anybody deserves to die for something he didn't do,'' Ryan
said, ``it would be Henry.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
