<HEADER>
A3838 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UNABOMBER-SUSPECT-HNS     06-30 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNABOMBER-SUSPECT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHRISTIAN BROTHER HAS A CHANCE ENCOUNTER WITH BIG BROTHER 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SCOTT WINOKUR  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ More than two years have passed since the FBI
decided St. Mary's College communications professor Ray Berta, a
Roman Catholic brother, might be the Unabomber.
</P>
<P>
   Brother Ray is OK now, but for a while there, the man of God's
mild clerical demeanor went on sabbatical and he stormed about the
college's Moraga, Calif., campus breathing fire and brimstone.
</P>
<P>
   `I felt terribly violated,'' Ray, a member of the religious
order Fratres Scholarum Christianarum, told the college newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any notions Americans have of personal privacy are bogus _ it
just does not exist,'' he told me.
</P>
<P>
   I can't blame him for taking such a dim view of things.
</P>
<P>
   Ray, 57, found out he was a target only when a television
reporter called the public information officer at St. Mary's for
comment.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI had worked up a dossier on Ray without his knowledge _
to the extent of secretly presenting the college with a court order
for his personnel file. Someone then leaked it all to a reporter.
</P>
<P>
   Result: Brother Ray was among the last to learn that Big Brother
thought he might be the terrorist who turned out to be Theodore
Kaczynski. The FBI had zeroed in on Ray so stealthily and in such
detail, it made the hair on the back of his neck stand up like
stalactites in a catacomb. He was a match on 13 of 16 key
identifiers in the portrait FBI profilers had worked up.
</P>
<P>
   Some identifiers were simple, like gender, facial hair, glasses
and both academic and connections in the San Francisco area. Others
were out there in the Major Improbabilty Zone _ if you assume, as
Ray did (incorrectly), that government isn't watching all of us,
all of the time.
</P>
<P>
   Such as: Born in the early 1940s in or near Chicago; graduated
in 1958 from a Chicago-area high school; worked or studied in the
southern part of mid-Michigan in the late '60s and early '70s;
dislikes technology; and at some point was linked to Northwestern
University.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the one that gave Ray the absolute creeps and, as he
claims, made the G-men and women especially attentive: flew out of
Salt Lake City on Aug. 8, 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had been in the Chicago area because my father was ill, but
the doctors told me I might as well return to California,'' Ray
recalled. ``So I left O'Hare in the morning, but the plane had
trouble and landed in Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   ``While I was there, the airline contacted me, said my father
had passed away and arranged for me to get back to Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``The same day, the Unabomber had something to do with Salt Lake
City; what it was, I don't know. So my presence in Salt Lake for
two or three hours triggered that match with the FBI profile.''
</P>
<P>
   Federal public defender Quin Denvir, Kaczynski's attorney, said
that while the Unabomber was linked to Salt Lake City on several
occasions in the '80s, he wasn't aware of anything in the summer of
1995. But Ray is certain of the date, Aug. 8, 1995, because that's
when his father died.
</P>
<P>
   I asked FBI spokesman George Grotz about this matter. He
politely declined.
</P>
<P>
   ``We received over 55,000 calls in this case, and of those about
2,100 rose to a level for us to take a look,'' Grotz said, ``but
we're not saying who they were.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Kaczynski's name came up, there were maybe 1,000 names
remaining on the list. For a short period of time agents continued
to work those names. The overwhelming majority weren't aware they
were on the list.''
</P>
<P>
   But a Christian brother? ``All I can say is we received
information about individuals from very diverse backgrounds.''
</P>
<P>
   After Ray learned the FBI was on his tail, he was told by a St.
Mary's administrator that the bureau wanted him to call a toll-free
number. He was informed, in a very official, totally unapologetic
way, that his profile had been cranked into a worldwide web of
computers. He'd auditioned for bogeyman without knowing it.
</P>
<P>
   What made the whole affair especially disturbing was the fact
that the Unabomber's carnage had indirectly touched the college in
1993, when University of California at San Francisco geneticist
Charles Epstein, brother of St. Mary's Dean Edwin Epstein, was
wounded by a bomb.
</P>
<P>
   Back then it all hurt a great deal; now Ray laughs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, when I'm teaching freshmen,'' he said, ``I know a hand
will go up and a student will ask, `What's this about the
Unabomber?' I'll say, `You'd better get a good grade _ or I'll blow
you up.'''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Scott Winokur is a reporter for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
