<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980630.0122 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 14:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3840 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MAINE-BOOMLET-2ND &LR;  &UR; TA     06-30 1130
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAINE-BOOMLET-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 (a and f coding)  
 PORTLAND, Maine: ... of the '90s.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not everyone is cheering over the growing opportunities for
telemarketers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The worry some people in Maine have is the jobs that are being
created are not high-paying jobs,'' said John Davulis, an economist
with Central Maine Power. ``So we get a call center, and it's not
providing nearly the livable income that one would get from working
at a paper mill.''
</P>
<P>
   Although some call centers, such as that run by credit card
giant MBNA in Belfast, pay a starting annual salary of $20,000 with
health benefits, other companies pay less. But many offer a good
benefits package.
</P>
<P>
   The new economy also has changed the face of many small towns.
</P>
<P>
   While York, which is within commuting distance to Boston, once
had much unused commercial space, ``everything that's available is
now being gobbled up,'' said planner Brian Chernack. And places
like Falmouth that once were sleepy farming and fishing villages
are being transformed into bedroom communities and retirement
havens.
</P>
<P>
   Many of these towns are now grappling with school crowding and
overburdened municipal services.
</P>
<P>
   The economic activity is contributing to what Lachance calls
``the bathtub effect.'' Look at Maine's census data, and it appears
that someone pulled the plug in York County and the population
started draining south.
</P>
<P>
   Much of that has flowed from Aroostook County, the vast, mostly
wilderness area of northern Maine that has awed outdoorsmen but
discouraged new businesses. There, in small towns that border
rolling acres of potatoes and broccoli, the future is far removed
from the simple certainties that colored life for generations.
</P>
<P>
   Aroostook County, the least-populated county in the state, has
lost 11.3 percent of its residents since 1990. Much of that loss
occurred after Loring Air Force Base closed in 1994, and 9,000
people _ military personnel and their dependents _ left the small
town of Limestone for new assignments.
</P>
<P>
   But the complaint heard over and over again in ``The County,''
as Aroostook residents refer to their home, is that young people
with educations are leaving as soon as practicable.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing to keep our kids here anymore,'' says Jo-ann
Lewis, 57, who calls numbers for senior-citizen bingo games at the
American Legion hall in Caribou.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis smiles faintly when asked about the call-center jobs and
other telecommunication work that King hopes will help keep young
adults in northern Maine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are the type of calls we used to hang up on,'' Lewis
says. ``People here aren't used to that kind of work.''
</P>
<P>
   The loss of the air base is also felt keenly in the Caribou
business district, where a once-bustling commercial strip is now
dotted with vacant department stores and dozens of empty parking
spaces.
</P>
<P>
   Marcia Sloan, a saleswoman at the Buzzels clothing store, is
discouraged about the local economy, but hopes the state can find
some long-term solutions for the region. ``Don't think of us as the
end of the line,'' she pleads.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; King says he has made economic assistance for the area, and
other rural counties, a priority of his administration. ``We want
people to stay if they want to,'' the governor says. ``No young
person should have to leave Maine to find a decent job.''
</P>
<P>
   Across the street from Buzzels clothing store, a small step is
being taken to make that goal a reality. There, in a previously
empty building bought for a dollar, two brothers have moved a
business that sells computer software for tax preparation.
</P>
<P>
   Forty employees, most of them from the area, will work in
downtown Caribou, eat lunch there, and begin using those empty
parking spaces.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really think this is a neat thing to do, we really do,''
says Gregory Jackson, marketing director for ATX Forms, the
software company. ``We decided we'd like to be part of the rebirth
of a downtown, if possible.''
</P>
<P>
   So &UR;  &LR; when co-owner Glynn Willette was searching for a place to
move the business from cramped quarters in nearby Washburn, the
withering environs of Caribou looked like the place.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we have an employee who wants to live in northern Maine,
that takes a certain kind of person,'' Jackson said. ``He's
committed.''
</P>
<P>
   And with the telecommunications infrastructure in Aroostook
County, Jackson says, ATX can put down roots in Caribou and compete
globally.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're as much in the world as anybody,'' he says, waving to
Willette as his boss jogs up the street to his son's Little League
game.
</P>
<P>
   That attitude matches the pep-rally enthusiasm that Brian Hamel
brings to his job as president of the Loring Redevelopment
Authority. With missionary zeal, Hamel extols the benefits of the
base's sprawling facilities and the area's ready pool of workers.
Already, Hamel says, the base has attracted enough new jobs and
commitments to replace the 1,100 civilian positions that were lost
when Loring closed.
</P>
<P>
   Hamel, a native of Amesbury, Mass., knows firsthand that the
popular perception of northern Maine is an uninviting one. But now,
his wife and three daughters would fight any decision to leave
Aroostook County after their four years there.
</P>
<P>
   ``My friends and family thought I had lost my marbles,'' said
Hamel, who previously worked on the redevelopment of the former
Pease Air Force Base outside Portsmouth, N.H. ``Now, my house is
like a bed and breakfast in February.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the economy in remote Maine is depressed enough that
Galen Rose, an economist with the state planning office, says that
``if it's not as bad as it gets in New England, it's pretty
close.''
</P>
<P>
   And Michael Donihue, an economics professor at Colby College, is
skeptical that high technology is on the verge of becoming a major
player there.
</P>
<P>
   ``To try to say that we are going to develop a Silicon Valley in
Bangor or Caribou, that just isn't going to happen,'' Donihue says.
However, he adds, ``a few software manufacturing firms would make a
huge difference'' in the region.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Despite the challenges of spreading the state's economic
benefits more evenly, Maine has rarely had as much appeal _ for
vacationers and entrepreneurs alike.
</P>
<P>
   King senses that, and is criss-crossing the state with a mantra
of jobs, jobs, jobs. And that appeal must be working. Up for
re-election this fall, King enjoys soaring popularity ratings. But
he deflects credit from himself to the ripple effects of the
national economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like someone who woke up on third base and thinks he
hit a triple,'' the governor says. ``Maine is one of the most
beautiful places on the planet. It is. It's a beautiful place with
a great infrastructure and great people. Therefore, we're going to
succeed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
