<SLUG> BC-YIP-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOW RATES POWER UTILITY STOCK SURGE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PAMELA YIP 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Utility stocks have had a good run lately.
</P>
<P>
   What's unusual about that is that they've done it in a
still-strong stock market.
</P>
<P>
   ``Utilities have been the best-performing sector of the market
for the last four weeks,'' said Hugh Johnson, chief investment
officer at First Albany Corp. in Albany, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Utility stocks, as measured by the Dow Jones utility average,
were up 3.3 percent, compared with a 0.9 percent decline in the
benchmark Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is unusual in bull markets,'' Johnson said. ``The worst
sector for the market during a bull market has consistently been
the utility sector since 1945.''
</P>
<P>
   That's because in a bull market, investors care more about the
price appreciation of their stock than the dividends it pays out.
Consequently, utility stocks traditionally have been a safe haven
for investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stock market has become increasingly vulnerable due to the
fact that corporate earnings are not going to be able to keep pace
with these high PEs (price/earnings ratios),'' said Bruce Bittles,
market strategist at J.C. Bradford &AMP; Co. in Nashville, a brokerage
firm. ``Investors are going to get more defensive as times go on.''
</P>
<P>
   The other factor juicing up utility stocks is that interest
rates are low. Electric utilities historically have been loaded
with debt because they borrowed money for projects such as power
plant construction. As interest rates fall, it becomes cheaper for
them to repay their debt.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the construction is virtually over, and they're using
their excess capital to pay down debt,'' said Geraldine Weiss,
editor of Investment Quality Trends in La Jolla, Calif., an
investment newsletter. ``They've pared them way back.''
</P>
<P>
   Lower interest rates also make utility stocks more attractive,
compared with bonds. Because of their steady dividend income,
utility stocks have behaved more like bonds than stocks and compete
with bonds.
</P>
<P>
   The stock price of utilities depends heavily on their dividend
yield, which represents the annual percentage return on your
investment flowing from a company's dividends. When interest rates
are low, it makes the dividend yield more attractive to investors.
</P>
<P>
   When you invest in utilities, you're betting that rates will
stay low.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks to me like it's going to be very difficult for the
Federal Reserve to raise interest rates anytime soon, primarily due
to the deflationary forces that continue to filter throughout our
economy,'' Bittles said.
</P>
<P>
   When looking at utility stocks today, be very selective because
utilities no longer have the lock on the market as they used to,
thanks to deregulation and increased competition.
</P>
<P>
   For example, non-utility companies such as Houston-based Enron
Corp. are getting into the electric business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look for utilities in areas where the population is growing,
where industry is growing,'' said Les Fox, a money manager at Dain
Rauscher in Houston, an investment firm. ``Look for utilities that
have shown an ability to diversify outside of their own
traditionally regulated business, such as selling power directly to
consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   Deregulation and consolidation are forcing utilities to watch
their bottom line, and that's good.
</P>
<P>
   ``Deregulation of the electric utilities is causing a lot of
consolidation, causing utilities to get more cost-conscious than
they have been in the past, more bottom-line and
investor-friendly,'' Bittles said.
</P>
<P>
   Don't just invest in Houston Industries, the parent company of
Houston Lighting &AMP; Power.
</P>
<P>
   ``Traditionally, people simply buy their own local utilities,''
said Alan Skrainka, chief market strategist at the Edward Jones
brokerage firm in St. Louis. ``We think that's a dangerous practice
today. You really have to do your homework and invest in
high-quality companies.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't get hung up on the dividend yield.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yield is not the best indicator of the return you should
expect,'' Skrainka said. ``It's really the dividends plus any
change in the stock price, and companies that are high-quality,
low-cost companies should be able to grow earnings and dividends
and therefore the stock price.''
</P>
<P>
   Make sure the utility isn't paying too fat a dividend from its
earnings. That's called the ``payout ratio,'' the percentage of a
firm's profits that's paid in dividends.
</P>
<P>
   Skrainka said a reasonable payout ratio for utilities is 65 to
80 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a company is paying out 90 percent of its earnings in
dividends, there is no cushion and margin for error, and a dividend
cut may be looming,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Pamela Yip can receive electronic mail via the Internet. Address
your comments and questions to pamela.yip(at)chron.com, or call
(713) 220-2000 and enter access code 1003. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
