<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RENO ERRED BIGTIME IN HANDLING THE LEWINSKY CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (k and w coding.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- To arange the scenery properly for Linda Tripp
Week, it helps to know a few things about Attorney General Janet
Reno's slipshod handling of this entire mess in January, confirmed
by past and present associates:
</P>
<P>
   _The attorney general made no effort to inquire into the content
of the Tripp-Monica Lewinsky tape recordings made in the months
before Tripp was wired by the independent counsel's office for one
last recording on Jan. 14.
</P>
<P>
   _The attorney general, moreover, made no serious effort to
inquire into that final, roughly 90-minute tape _ neither its
content nor circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   _She also did nothing to check Kenneth Starr's claim in his
request for jurisdiction in the Lewinsky matter that there was an
overlap between people caught up in it and in other subjects he was
investigating that involved (Reno's words) ``possible efforts to
influence witnesses.''
</P>
<P>
   _The attorney general was (pick one) bullied, intimidated, or
threatened by Starr and his people into making a snap decision. By
telling her that Newsweek was preparing an article on the Tripp
tapes, they were telling Reno that if she did not give them the
case, Newsweek would be reporting a sensational sex and coverup
story along with her refusal to let an independent counsel
investigate it.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday Starr and Reno had a private meeting. No details
available, but one hopes she is finally getting serious about
Starr's having played her like a violin.
</P>
<P>
   It is, after all, an issue that goes to the heart of the case,
or to its official origin. The one refrain always heard from
Starr's office and its Republican and journalistic amen corner as
the rookie prosecutor's credibility and behavioral problems mount,
is that his investigation was based upon the determination of the
attorney general herself.
</P>
<P>
   Baloney. It was not a determination by a fact-finding
gatekeeper, it was paper shuffling along an automated transmission
belt. The stupid law under which independent counsels operate has
many, much-discussed flaws, but it has no chance at all of ever
working properly unless the attorney general performs the tasks
assigned that office with far more diligence than Reno has shown.
</P>
<P>
   As things stand now, one of the least accurate sentences in the
entire Lewinsky so-called investigation was made by the AG at the
top of her jurisdiction-expanding petition to the allegedly
supervising US Court of Appeal panel here on Jan. 16.
</P>
<P>
   ``In accordance with the Independent Counsel Reauthorization Act
of 1994, I hereby notify in writing the special division of the
court that I have commenced a preliminary investigation ... into
whether violations of federal criminal law were committed by Monica
Lewinsky or any other individual, as described below.''
</P>
<P>
   That ``preliminary investigation'' consists in Reno's petition
of nothing beyond the Jan. 14 tape of Tripp, wearing the FBIs wire,
and Lewinsky. And, in fact, it did consist of nothing beyond that,
which means there was no such investigation at all.
</P>
<P>
   Had there been, she might have learned that the tapes Tripp
herself made of Lewinsky consist of a variety of conflicting tales,
none of them bearing directly on obstruction of justice, and all of
them raising questions about just who was suborning whose perjury;
she might also have learned, had she inquired, more about how the
final tape came about, particularly how Tripp was scripted by
Starr's office to elicit alleged obstruction comments regarding
Vernon Jordan that have yet to receive an ounce of direct
corroboration.
</P>
<P>
   In her defense, Reno associates note that she was at least
exposed to Monica Lewinsky's words that she intended to lie when
deposed in the Paula Jones case, that she was urging Tripp to lie,
and that Reno had an obvious conflict there because the Jones case
involved President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   No sale. The whole idea of the independent counsel law is that
its trigger must be credible evidence, which is subverted if there
no serious effort to assess credibility.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, perfunctory or no examination makes an attorney general
vulnerable to the presentation of a slanted or edited case. At this
point, given what he knew and didn't know in January, Starr's
presentation to Reno resembled the cut and paste job Representative
Dan Burton's slimy aide, David Bossie, did on Webster Hubbell's
prison tapes this year.
</P>
<P>
   And Reno's response didn't ask for what Starr didn't tell.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
