<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980630.0129 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 14:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3853 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDONESIA-REVOLUTION-     06-30 1088
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-REVOLUTION-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVOLUTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 INDONESIA COULD TRAVEL THE PATH OF THE RUSSIAN and IRANIAN &HT;     (This article has already moved to Centerpiece clients. To
publish as a ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased _ the
rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. 
 &HT;    
 By WALTER RUSSELL MEAD  
 FROM: The New York Times Magazine  
 &HT;    As Indonesia's new president, B.J. Habibie, settles into office,
soldiers are returning to their barracks and students to their
dorms, and some hardy American investors are mulling over returning
to Indonesia.
 &HT;    For investors, getting in on the ground floor of an Indonesian
recovery would be a bonanza. In the last year, political
instability and Asia's economic turmoil combined to reduce prices
of Indonesian debt and equity to almost derisory levels.
Bottom-fishing investors can now buy what were once well-regarded
companies and financial assets for pennies on the dollar. An
economic rebound would make millions for those daring enough to
fish in Indonesia's murky, choppy markets.
 &HT;    With Washington and Tokyo seemingly determined to stabilize the
yen and promote a regional recovery in Asia, this might look like a
good time. But Indonesia's troubles run deep, and what looks like
an opportunity today may become a disaster in the not-too-distant
future.
 &HT;    Indonesia, an archipelago of 13,000-plus islands, is the largest
Muslim country in the world and the fourth most populous country
overall. Nevertheless, the Indonesian state is fragile. Its 214
million people speak hundreds of different languages. Their
backgrounds range from the ritualized and ancient Javanese
civilization to tribal cultures of Irian Jaya.
 &HT;    As with many African countries, the only thing many of
Indonesia's peoples had in common at independence was the
experience of colonial domination by the same nation. In
Indonesia's case, that was the Dutch, who finally withdrew in 1949.
 &HT;    Bad as the former president, Suharto, was in many respects, he
ran a stable regime that kept Indonesia's disparate elements in
place. He also steadied a turbulent region while helping to balance
China's growing power. The climate of peace and cooperation that
Suharto promoted _ notably with his neighbors in Malaysia and
Singapore _ did much to set the stage for the region's explosive
economic growth.
 &HT;    Suharto relied on the armed forces and the economy to hold the
country together. Both were built up _ primarily through patronage
and corruption _ under his long reign and both now face the
difficult task of gaining popular trust and legitimacy.
 &HT;    That won't be easy, and the main reason is the economy.
Indonesians _ like Americans _ seem willing to tolerate
presidential hanky-panky when the economy is strong. And for most
of Suharto's tenure the economy was extremely strong.
 &HT;    Thanks to family planning and economic growth, per capita gross
domestic product rose by an average of 4.3 percent annually from
1965 to 1988. As the Far Eastern Economic Review points out, this
was one of the highest sustained increases in living standards in
the world.
 &HT;    The poverty rate dropped from an estimated 70 percent of the
population in 1970 to about 15 percent two decades later. At the
same time, however, Suharto allowed the Chinese minority in
Indonesia _ about 3 percent of the population _ to control an
estimated 70 percent of the national economy.
 &HT;    Now that the economy _ and living standards _ are in free fall,
there are widespread calls to investigate the Suharto family's
extensive web of partnerships and cross holdings. Because Suharto
did so much of his business with ethnic Chinese, and because the
Chinese prospered so greatly during his tenure, calls to
investigate and return Suharto family wealth could turn into
something like a general assault on the Chinese businessmen who
largely control the economy.
 &HT;    The trouble, however, is that once the Indonesians start picking
at the threads of economic corruption and political cronyism, the
whole fabric of their national life could unravel. It isn't just a
few bankers and real-estate developers who are tied to the former
ruling family. The whole business class was implicated in an
economic development that was systematically perverted to favor the
Suharto clan.
 &HT;    And it isn't just a handful of generals who participated in
repression and corruption under the ``ancien regime.'' Over the
last 30 years, Suharto reshaped the Indonesian armed forces in his
image.
 &HT;    Meanwhile, a vicious circle is likely to develop as economic
turmoil leads to more anti-Chinese agitation and to calls for new
trials and investigations that a weak government may be powerless
to resist. This would further undermine confidence among the
country's business elite, leading to more capital flight and more
economic turmoil.
 &HT;    Having repressed moderate politicians and prevented responsible
opposition leaders from developing strong national organizations,
Indonesia's elites may now face an inexorable rise of popular fury
as living standards continue to fall.
 &HT;    If this scenario unfolds, both Indonesia and the region are in
for much more tumult than we have yet seen. Indonesia could well be
in the early moments of a two-stage revolution _ such as the
Russian and Iranian revolutions. In Stage 1, the old emperor goes
out; in Stage 2, an ineffectual transitional regime is overthrown
by a radical and more permanent successor.
 &HT;    Czarist Russia was a promising emerging market and a friend of
the United States before its October Revolution. Indonesia, many of
whose people rightly accuse Washington of supporting Suharto
through decades of repression, could yet emerge as a world-class
foreign-policy and economic headache.
 &HT;    Without a quick economic recovery, Indonesia could all too
easily slide into chaos or move toward an anti-Western radicalism,
conceivably with Islamist overtones.
 &HT;     c.1998 Walter Russell Mead  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Walter Russell Mead is a senior fellow at the Council on
Foreign Relations.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ------------------- &QC;
</P>
