<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 14:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3858 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOORDA-UPDATE-NYTSF &LR;      06-30 2215
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOORDA-UPDATE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MATTER OF HONOR 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (This article has already moved to Centerpiece clients. To
publish as a ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased _ the
rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. 
 &HT;    
 By NICK KOTZ  
 FROM: Washingtonian Magazine  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    The U.S. Navy has ruled that the late Adm. Mike Boorda was
entitled to wear two combat award designations that were being
called into question when he committed suicide two years ago.
 &HT;    Boorda, the Navy's highest-ranking officer as chief of naval
operations, shot himself on May 16, 1996, in the garden outside his
residence at the Navy Yard. As Boorda was taking his life, two
Newsweek reporters arrived at the Pentagon to question him about
whether he had improperly worn ``Combat V'' devices on medals
awarded during the Vietnam War. The V device signifies that a medal
was won for service in combat operations.
 &HT;    The Navy's recent ruling certifying Boorda's awards was not
publicly announced. In a ``memorandum for the record'' dated April
3, 1998 _ almost two years after Boorda's death _ Navy secretary
John Dalton ordered corrections made to Boorda's official Navy
transcript certifying that he was entitled to wear the Combat V on
two medals awarded for his service in Vietnam.
 &HT;    ``Admiral Mike Boorda's citations for awards of the Navy
Achievement Medal and Navy Commendation Medal plainly state they
were awarded for service including `combat operations' and `while
operating in combat missions,''' Dalton wrote.
 &HT;    He also cited the authority of retired Adm. Elmo Zumwalt, who
commanded U.S. naval forces and served as chief of naval operations
during the Vietnam conflict. In a memorandum also made a part of
Boorda's record, Zumwalt wrote that Boorda was ``clearly authorized
to wear the Combat V insignia on his medals.''
 &HT;    With Dalton's action, the Navy has tacitly acknowledged that its
Office of Awards and Special Projects was mistaken three years ago
in advising Boorda that he did not rate the combat designations.
The restoration of Boorda's combat awards was reviewed and approved
by Adm. Jay Johnson, chief of naval operations; Steven Honigman,
the Navy's general counsel; and the office of the secretary of
defense.
 &HT;    As detailed in ``Breaking Point,'' a story in the December 1996
issue of The Washingtonian, the medals controversy was only one of
many Boorda faced during his tenure as chief of naval operations.
Other pressing issues included how the Navy should deal with
continuing repercussions from the Tailhook scandal, disputes over
the role of women in combat, scandals at the Naval Academy, and
pressures to perform expanded naval missions with reduced forces in
the post-Cold War era.
 &HT;    In 40 years in the Navy, Boorda had forged a unique career. A
high-school dropout who enlisted at 16, married at 17 and fathered
four children before he was 22, Boorda didn't fit the mold of
leaders in the nation's most traditional military service.
 &HT;    He was the first chief of naval operations who had not attended
the U.S. Naval Academy, the first former enlisted man to reach the
office, the first Jew to become CNO, and only the second
surface-ship officer _ all others had been aviators or submariners
_ to head the Navy in four decades.
 &HT;    Only five-foot-four, Boorda was called ``a sailor's sailor'' by
the enlisted men and women from whose ranks he had come. Exuberant,
down-to-earth and competitive, Boorda earned their loyalty _ and
the ire of some officers _ by cutting through the chain of command
to solve problems.
 &HT;    Feeling that he had ``grown up'' in the Navy, he was devoted to
it and to his family, including his handicapped oldest son, David.
 &HT;    In disputes over Tailhook and the role of women, Boorda's
critics accused him of being a ``politically correct'' admiral who
didn't stand up for the ``warrior'' values of Navy culture. His
defenders cited his accomplishments as a military commander from
Vietnam to Bosnia. But the insinuation that he was not a
``warrior'' made him vulnerable to accusations that he wore combat
decorations to which he was not entitled.
 &HT;    In addition to coping with the Navy's problems, Boorda was being
urged by his wife to resign in order to relieve the strain of the
CNO's job on the family. In the days before his death, Boorda had
told family members that he did plan to resign early.
 &HT;    The question of whether Boorda was entitled to wear the Combat V
on his Vietnam medals first arose in 1995, when Roger Charles, a
retired Marine lieutenant colonel acting as a correspondent for the
National Security News Service, filed a Freedom of Information Act
request to examine the official record of Boorda's medals.
 &HT;    When Charles' inquiry was brought to Boorda's attention, the
admiral asked the Navy's awards office for an opinion. When the
awards office replied that he was not entitled to wear the combat
insignia, Boorda removed the Vs from his medals.
 &HT;    Ten months later, Charles gave the story to David Hackworth, a
highly decorated, retired Army colonel who was then a contributing
editor to Newsweek. Hackworth in turn took the story to Newsweek
editor Maynard Parker. Hackworth told Parker that his exposure of
Boorda's medals could end the admiral's career.
 &HT;    Less than three hours before Boorda's suicide, an aide informed
him that Newsweek Washington bureau chief Evan Thomas and defense
reporter John Barry were coming to the Pentagon to question him
about the Combat V awards.
 &HT;    Telling his aides that he was going home for lunch, Boorda drove
his official car to the CNO's residence, wrote a note to his wife
and a note ``to my sailors,'' then went into the garden and shot
himself.
 &HT;    In the note to Navy enlisted personnel, discovered on Boorda's
desk at home after his death, he had written:
 &HT;    ``I am about to be accused of wearing combat devices on two
ribbons I earned during sea tours in Viet Nam. It turns out I
didn't really rate them. When I found out I was wrong I immediately
took them off but it was really too late. I don't expect any
reporters to believe that I could make an honest mistake and you
may or may not believe it yourselves. I've made it not matter in
the big scheme of things because I love our Navy so much, and you
who are the heart and soul of our Navy, I couldn't bear to bring
dishonor to you.''
 &HT;    In the months following Boorda's suicide, the Navy refused to
offer an opinion as to whether Boorda had been entitled to wear the
two Combat V devices.
 &HT;    Dalton's recent ruling follows a two-year effort by Boorda's
widow, Bettie, and son Cdr. Edward Boorda, now captain of the USS
Russell, a guided-missile destroyer on duty in the Arabian Gulf, to
clear the admiral's name of the allegations that he had worn combat
awards that he should have known he was not entitled to wear. The
effort was supported by many retired and active-duty military
officers, including Zumwalt.
 &HT;    After examining the history of Boorda's awards, Dalton and other
Navy officials concluded that Boorda was entitled to the combat
designation on both.
 &HT;    Officials say that changes in Navy regulations governing the
Navy Achievement Medal, which Boorda won as weapons officer on the
destroyer USS Craig in 1965, created confusion. Boorda initially
was awarded not a Navy Achievement Medal, which didn't exist at the
time, but a Navy Commendation for Achievement ribbon. The
Commendation for Achievement, won by Boorda and two other officers
on the Craig in 1965, did not qualify for the Combat V.
 &HT;    But two years later, in 1967, the Navy retroactively upgraded
all the Navy Commendation for Achievement ribbons awarded between
1961 and 1967 into a new award, the Navy Achievement Medal. The
Navy mailed the new medal to thousands of personnel, including
Boorda, to replace the Commendation for Achievement ribbon. The new
Navy Achievement Medal was eligible for the Combat V if it was
earned during combat operations.
 &HT;    Authorization for the Combat V was specifically written into the
citation for each eligible Navy Achievement Medal beginning in
1967.
 &HT;    But the Navy never reviewed the thousands of Commendation for
Achievement ribbons that had been upgraded to Navy Achievement
Medals to determine which ones were eligible for the Combat V, and
so issued no authorizations for the device on the retroactively
awarded medals. In the absence of such a review, the only record
available for determining eligibility for the Combat V is the
language in the original citation awarding the Achievement ribbon.
 &HT;    The citation for Boorda's ribbon stated:
 &HT;    ``For meritorious service while serving as Weapons Officer in
USS John R. Craig while operating in combat missions supporting the
Republic of Vietnam from 10 April to 10 August 1965. ... Craig was
assigned duties as commander of the Vietnam Naval Gunfire Support
Unit from its inception until the ship's departure from the area.
 &HT;    ``Boorda's unparalleled knowledge of the tactical and
operational aspects of the employment of Naval gunfire support
contributed immeasurably to the successful introduction ... of
Naval gunfire support'' of U.S. Marine infantry and Republic of
Vietnam forces on shore.
 &HT;    In Boorda's fitness report, Cdr. James K. Jobe, the Craig's
captain, commended him for developing and implementing the naval
gunfire support plan for the entire destroyer support group and
noted that the Craig had fired more than 3,000 five-inch shells to
support U.S. and South Vietnamese forces engaged with the Vietcong
on shore.
 &HT;    At the outset of U.S. naval involvement in Vietnam, Jobe
observed, Boorda frequently had gone ashore to develop gunnery
support plans with officers of the U.S. Third Marine division and
Republic of Vietnam I and II Corps.
 &HT;    Most clearly supporting the case that Boorda rated the V device
was that Jobe himself was awarded a Navy Commendation Medal with
Combat V ``for meritorious achievement'' in the same
gunfire-support mission that Boorda oversaw as Jobe's weapons
officer. Only with the upgrade of Boorda's award two years later
did it become eligible for the Combat V.
 &HT;    In certifying Boorda's entitlement to wear the Combat V on his
second medal, officials relied on Zumwalt's verbal directions to
Navy personnel in Vietnam during the war.
 &HT;    In 1973, during his second tour of duty in Vietnam, as executive
officer of the destroyer USS Brooke, Boorda was awarded a Navy
Commendation Medal for ``meritorious achievement ... during combat
operations.'' The award citation praised Boorda for ``training,
organizing, and directing ... a combat-ready crew in a variety of
demanding roles including protection of vital units and rescue of
downed aviators.''
 &HT;    The Brooke's primary role was to protect U.S. aircraft carriers
whose planes flew missions over Vietnam. In one instance, the
Brooke assisted in rescuing a flyer whose plane had been shot down
by Vietcong anti-aircraft fire. In a fitness report, Cdr. W.D.
Pivarnik, captain of the Brooke, called Boorda ``without
qualification, the finest officer with whom it has been my pleasure
to serve.''
 &HT;    Navy regulations in effect in 1973 stated that the Combat V was
warranted only when the medal citation specifically authorized it.
Boorda's medal citation did not mention the Combat V.
 &HT;    But Zumwalt had issued other instructions. In his recent
memorandum to Boorda's file, Zumwalt recounted: ``As Chief of Naval
Operations (1970-74), I achieved a verbal understanding that
directives would be clarified to stipulate that the `V' could be
worn on any ribbon resulting from operations in the combat zone of
Vietnam. In over 100 visits to ships and shore stations, I
reiterated to Navy personnel time and time again that the `V' was
authorized for any ribbon awarded for duty in the combat theater of
Vietnam _ on shore and off shore.''
 &HT;    In reviewing the matter, Navy officials confirmed that many
naval officers who won medals in Vietnam wore the Combat V at the
direction of Zumwalt, and that other officers had received
authorization for the combat designation on the Commendation Medal
for performing duties almost identical to those Boorda performed on
the Brooke.
 &HT;    In May, copies of the memoranda to the record by Dalton and
Zumwalt, along with an updated transcript of Boorda's official Navy
record restoring the Combat Vs, were sent without comment to Bettie
Boorda.
 &HT;     c.1998 Washingtonian Magazine  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Nick Kotz's ``Breaking Point,'' a 20,000-word story about the
life and death of Adm. Mike Boorda, appeared in the December 1996
Washingtonian. It was a finalist for the 1997 National Magazine
Award for Reporting.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ---------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
