<HEADLINE>
BIG TOBACCO'S PRIME STRATEGIST 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (This article has already moved to Centerpiece clients. To
publish as a ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased _ the
rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. 
 &HT;    
 By JEFFREY GOLDBERG  
 FROM: The New York Times Magazine  
 &HT;    Steven F. Goldstone, the chairman and chief executive officer of
one of the four most reviled corporations in America, looks like a
man in need of a cigarette.
 &HT;    A dismal funk has settled over the Benton Convention Center in
Winston-Salem, N.C., which is where his company, RJR Nabisco, is
about to open its annual shareholders' meeting.
 &HT;    The meeting won't be pleasant for him, but what is these days?
It's reefer madness out there _ not so much in Winston-Salem, one
of the last of the country's pro-tobacco redoubts, but almost
everywhere else.
 &HT;    It is perhaps the worst moment in history to be a tobacco CEO.
The industry Goldstone leads is a pariah, the Libya of American
commerce. Congress has spun itself into a frenzy, weighing huge tax
increases on tobacco and considering measures to let the Food and
Drug Administration regulate the nicotine out of cigarettes.
 &HT;    Wall Street, meanwhile, views the tobacco companies the way
Sloan-Kettering views smoking. RJR Nabisco Holdings Corp. is a
highly leveraged company, and its stock price is so depressed that
the company's market cap _ the total value of all outstanding
shares _ is actually exceeded by its debt.
 &HT;    Goldstone, a shortish and combative 52-year-old, is Big
Tobacco's prime strategist. Last year he led his fellow CEOs into
historic negotiations with their enemies, the state attorneys
general who had made it their mission to take down Big Tobacco.
 &HT;    Two and a half years ago, before he became president of RJR
Nabisco, which owns R.J. Reynolds, the nation's second-largest
tobacco company, he was just another rich Wall Street lawyer. But
now that Goldstone oversees the production of Camels, Winstons and
Dorals, it seems an article of faith among tobacco's foes that he
pushes drugs to children.
 &HT;    When I asked C. Everett Koop, the former surgeon general, if he
thought Goldstone was actually evil, he answered, ``Is it evil to
know that the product you sell is going to kill one-third of your
customers, and then sell it anyway?''
 &HT;    Lying in ambush for Goldstone this May morning in Winston-Salem
are a number of Koop's acolytes. Goldstone knows he's in for it _
he calls the annual meetings ``a continuing psychodrama'' _ so it
is no surprise that he looks as if he needs a cigarette. Alas, he
quit 20 years ago. ``At some point, I just said, `Jeez, I'm killing
myself,' so I stopped,'' he explains. ``The pleasure component was
beginning to be outweighed by my anxiety that I was injuring my
health.''
 &HT;    And so he has become addicted _ if that is the word _ to Breath
Savers, one of the noncontroversial products manufactured by his
company. He pops one into his mouth and, tagged by security agents,
makes his way to the main conference hall.
 &HT;    ``Let's go do this thing,'' he says. At the first opportunity,
the anti-tobacco contingent crowds the microphones. The first to
speak, a Virginia woman named Anne Donley, asks Goldstone to
describe the provisions made by the company should ``you or the
other directors be indicted.'' Goldstone maintains his equilibrium,
thanking her for her question without providing an answer.
 &HT;    Another critic, a Virginia physician named David Lewis, says to
Goldstone: ``I had to tell one of your customers a few days ago
that the shadow in her chest is lung cancer. I suspect that she is
still crying. I believe there is higher power, Mr. Goldstone, and I
believe that one day you will have to answer to that higher
power.''
 &HT;    ``Thank you, Dr. Lewis,'' Goldstone replies. He becomes testy
only once, when another woman announces that a petition drive in
support of a Nabisco boycott has already netted 12,000 signatures.
 &HT;    ``I'm sorry that 12,000 people are not using Nabisco products,''
he says, a malevolent grin spreading across his face. ``We're doing
a great job on Snackwell's, and when they see their weight going up
they might come back.''
 &HT;    This draws a laugh from his cigarette-subsidiary executives, who
fill the front rows and smoke like fiends through the meeting. They
don't really trust Goldstone, who is decidedly not a tobacco man,
but today he is a hero to them. He is a hero to his shareholders
too. It's not because he has figured out a way to grow the
cigarette business.
 &HT;    Quite the opposite: He is certainly one of the only CEOs in
America who tell their employees and shareholders that the most
they will achieve for them is a ``slow and manageable decline in an
increasingly obsolete industry.''
 &HT;    Nor is he a hero because he has formulated the magic arguments
that would convince the country that his company never manipulated
the nicotine levels in cigarettes, never marketed its products to
teen-agers and never thought, even for a moment, that Joe Camel
could be attractive to 5-year-olds.
 &HT;    He is a hero instead because on April 8, he stood at the dais of
the National Press Club in Washington and let Congress know that if
it wanted to legislate his industry into oblivion, it could do so
without his help. The man who marched his industry's CEOs into
cease-fire negotiations with the states was marching them back to
war.
 &HT;    ``I finally saw that there wasn't a chance in hell of any
resolution to this problem in the near future,'' he says.
 &HT;    Goldstone's pullout wasn't entirely impetuous. The CEOs had all
been stewing for some time about the Republican Congress'
election-year conversion to the anti-tobacco cause. But it was
still something of a cliff jump. Goldstone says that he made his
announcement with only the cloudiest sense of his industry's
future.
 &HT;    ``It would scare my shareholders to know this, but in my own
mind I do not have an endgame plan,'' he would tell me later. ``The
only thing we can do now is continue fighting.''
 &HT;    After the annual meeting, Goldstone sinks into the back seat of
his chauffeured sedan and considers his fate, as laid out to him by
the crusaders. ``So, I'm going to jail or I'm going to hell,''
Goldstone says. ``Some choice.''
 &HT;    One year ago, when Goldstone and his fellow tobacco CEOs
approved the agreement with 40 state attorneys general, they
believed it would put an end to their troubles. In exchange for
protection against future lawsuits, the CEOs agreed to pay the
states $368.5 billion over 25 years, end many forms of advertising
and accept FDA oversight of their product.
 &HT;    For an industry that had never ceded a penny to its foes, it was
a landmark moment _ irrefutable evidence, the tobacco chiefs
believed, of their good will.
 &HT;    In the months that followed the June 1997 signing, however, it
became clear that the public-health lobby, the White House and
Congress _ which would have to legislate the settlement into law _
all believed, for reasons ranging from the idealistic to the
mercenary, that $368.5 billion was too small a price to pay for
absolution.
 &HT;    Nine months after signing the agreement, when Sen. John McCain,
the Arizona Republican, introduced a bill that would nearly double
the tax on a pack of cigarettes proposed in the settlement with the
states, Goldstone decided that the process was ``off the rails.''
And so, the pullout.
 &HT;    What he was pulling out of no one was sure, since McCain's
Commerce Committee barred Big Tobacco's lobbyists from the
bill-writing process. I could not allow these people to have veto
power over the bill, McCain told me.
 &HT;    Newt Gingrich, the ardent, if recent, foe of tobacco, gave me
this explanation for why Congress would no longer listen to
tobacco's arguments: ``Their deliberate mendacity for a generation
earned them exclusion.'' Referring to Goldstone's pullout, the
Speaker said, ``I thought it was an irrelevant act.''
 &HT;    But it wasn't. All along, advocates of a comprehensive
settlement argued that industry cooperation was necessary to cut
the rate of teen smoking, and it was the fight against teen smoking
_ not the raising of tax revenue _ that was the ostensible reason
for the entire process.
 &HT;    President Clinton apparently felt Goldstone's participation was
important enough that, shortly after his speech at the National
Press Club, he secretly dispatched Sen. John Breaux, the Louisiana
Democrat, to New York, where he tried to figure out what it would
take to coax Goldstone and the CEOs back in the process. Breaux
left New York empty-handed.
 &HT;    Today, anti-tobacco legislation is moving tortuously through
Congress. The tobacco companies have launched a campaign to
convince American smokers that Congress is trying to oppress them
with new taxes. The slowdown in momentum is the result of $50
million of advertising by the tobacco companies, Vice President Al
Gore told me. There's no question it's easier for us to pass this
with the companies inside the tent. But we will pass it.
 &HT;    I asked Goldstone one day why he believes tobacco's enemies,
faced with a CEO who claims he's ready to compromise, would rather
make war than reach a peaceful settlement.
 &HT;    ``They're more comfortable demonizing us than anything else,''
he replied. ``They think they can demonize us out of this business,
and when you try to explain to them that this product is not
disappearing, it only angers them more. It isn't a resolution
they're looking for, it's eradication. In political terms, that's
prohibition.'' He paused and then added: ``This process is now
completely irrational. I didn't count on vengeance being a part of
it. Not at all.''
 &HT;    None of the chief executives of the four major American
cigarette companies counted on vengeance. They still do not seem to
appreciate how bottomless the well of anti-tobacco feeling in
America really is. Nor are the CEOs convinced that they are the
authors of their own misery.
 &HT;    In fact, Goldstone is the only one to acknowledge that real
ethical lapses on the part of the tobacco industry, and not just
failures of public relations, account for the industry's current
predicament. His fellow CEOs, in recent interviews with me, spoke
with surprising defiance.
 &HT;    Geoffrey C. Bible, the CEO of Philip Morris, which produces 50
percent of the cigarettes sold in America, is in absolutely no mood
to apologize. Unlike Goldstone, he has been a true tobacco man for
nearly 30 years. At one point he oversaw the sale of Marlboros in
nearly 200 countries. He is Australian-born, 60 years old and an
enthusiastic smoker.
 &HT;    ``Do I feel badly about selling cigarettes?'' he says. ``No, I
do not, and I don't know why I should. I feel badly about children
smoking cigarettes, but I don't know how to deal with that. I tell
you, I feel worse about under-age people getting alcohol more so
than cigarettes.''
 &HT;    In a recent conversation at Philip Morris headquarters in New
York, Bible even argued the merits of smoking. ``There's an
interesting question you should ask the public-health people,'' he
said. ``What do you think smokers would do if they didn't smoke?
You get some pleasure from it, and you also get some other
beneficial things, such as stress relief. Nobody knows what you'd
turn to if you didn't smoke. Maybe you'd beat your wife. Maybe
you'd drive cars fast. Who knows what the hell you'd do?''
 &HT;    A few blocks away, at the headquarters of the Loews Corp., whose
subsidiary, Lorillard Tobacco Co., manufactures nearly 9 percent of
the cigarettes sold in this country, the defiance was even more
palpable.
 &HT;    ``There are only four companies in America that care about youth
smoking and want to stop it,'' Laurence A. Tisch, co-CEO of Loews,
told me. ``Those companies are Lorillard, Brown &AMP; Williamson, R.J.
Reynolds and Philip Morris. We're the only four genuine people out
there. Everybody else is giving it lip service.''
 &HT;    The tobacco CEOs are not exactly friends. That would look too
collusive, and besides, they are all in terrible competition with
one another, each fighting for market share in a slowly shrinking
business.
 &HT;    ``We don't trust each other on financial issues one jot,'' Nick
Brookes, the CEO of Brown &AMP; Williamson Tobacco Corp., told me.
 &HT;    But by virtue of often being sued collectively, they communicate
with some regularity, meeting face to face _ with their lawyers
present _ to discuss common strategy. As a result, they have
managed to come to unanimous decisions on several key issues. In a
recent state anti-tobacco case in Minnesota, for instance, they all
agreed to settle with Minnesota's attorney general _ for $6.5
billion _ rather than take their case to the jury.
 &HT;    This was done, they claimed, out of deference to RJR Nabisco's
tenuous financial situation: ``If they'd have listened to me, we
would have gone to verdict in Minnesota,'' Tisch said. ``And I
would have appealed if we lost. But RJR couldn't have survived
that.'' Bible too deferred to Goldstone's thinking. ``We'd be the
last to go bankrupt, because we're the biggest,'' Bible said.
 &HT;    Philip Morris had sales last year of $72 billion, $40 billion of
which came from tobacco (and of that, international sales
contributed two-thirds). RJR Nabisco is in far more tenuous shape.
Without the $1.4 billion in annual operating profit made by its
tobacco subsidiary, the company could barely afford to service its
annual debt.
 &HT;    Despite RJR's shaky financials, Goldstone _ a ``smart fella,''
Bible allows _ seems to have emerged as the chief theoretician of
the four. Brookes and his superior, Martin Broughton, the
London-based CEO of BAT Industries, are the bad boys of the bunch.
Broughton and Brookes have gone along with Goldstone's ideas only
grudgingly at times.
 &HT;    Tisch, a billionaire who is the king of New York philanthropy,
is said by his fellow CEOs to be the one who feels most keenly
betrayed by Washington. Like Goldstone, he is not a tobacco man _
he says he has visited the North Carolina headquarters of Lorillard
just once in the 30 years he has controlled the company. His anger,
he says, grows from what he calls the irrational vilification of a
legal industry.
 &HT;    ``When the truth is undermined in America, then you've
accomplished everything the fascists will want to try to do 20
years from today,'' he told me. Under cover of a children's
crusade, he argues, Washington is engaged in a huge tax grab.
 &HT;    ``The Big Lie is prevailing, Tisch says. The Big Lie is that
these companies were ever marketing to kids. What worries me is
that if you can get away with this against a legitimate industry,
what could be the next big lie? This is McCarthyism.''
 &HT;    Like Tisch, Bible believes dangerous historical forces are
motivating the anti-tobacco crusade.
 &HT;    ``The American people fought a war for freedom,'' he said. ``It
was an ugly, horrible war that engulfed the world. We fought that
war for the freedom to choose. Hitler and Hirohito were going to
take that away from us. We fought vehemently to prevent that from
happening.''
 &HT;    Are you equating your opponents to Hitler and Hirohito? I asked.
 &HT;    ``I'm not going to say that at all,'' he responded, ``but I
think we've seen in the past individuals influencing a whole
nation.''
 &HT;    The individuals to whom Bible is referring, he makes ringingly
clear during the course of conversation, are Koop and Dr. David
Kessler, the former commissioner of the Food and Drug
Administration _ the two enemies of tobacco generally credited with
(or blamed for) sinking last year's settlement.
 &HT;    Goldstone, by contrast, does not spend much time predicting a
blitzkrieg of health fascism. He was made CEO because he was a
lawyer skilled at complex negotiation. ``I took this job because I
thought I had a set of skills and an opportunity to resolve a very
dangerous problem for this company,'' he says.
 &HT;    Koop and Kessler, Goldstone will even cede, know what they're
talking about.
 &HT;    ``They don't know what gives an individual pleasure, he says,
but I have absolutely no doubt they know what's best to prolong a
person's life.''
 &HT;     c.1998 Jeffrey Goldberg  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Jeffrey Goldberg is a contributing writer for The New York
Times Magazine.) &LR;
</P>
