<P>
   Entertainment and culture stories in sight at this hour from The
N.Y. Times News Service for Wednesday, July 1.
</P>
<P>
   For information and repeats call the News Service at (212)
556-1927. And be sure to look for other entertainment stories from
our partners: Bloomberg News, The Boston Globe, Cox News Service,
Hearst Newspapers, The Houston Chronicle, The Arizona Republic,
Kansas City Star, Fort Worth Star-Telegram, Los Angeles Daily News,
San Francisco Chronicle and Seattle Post-Intelligencer.
</P>
<P>
   CUBA-ALBUM (Undated) _ The ``Buena Vista Social Club'' album
quietly crept into the marketplace in the fall of 1997. It was an
an unpretentious record steered by an American musician, Ry Cooder,
and made in Havana by 80- and 90-year-olds singing a gentle,
prerevolutionary pop music that had mostly been forgotten. Then it
started selling. The tempo picked up, and now some 10 months after
its release, it has sold nearly a million copies around the world.
By Peter Watrous.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-ROYAL-OPERA (London) _ The Royal Opera House, beset by
persistent accusations of elitism and financial mismanagement, came
under renewed attack today when a government-sponsored report said
that its internal organization often ``resembles a World War I
battlefield.'' By Sarah Lyall.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE-AMERICAN-CENTER (Paris) _ The French will buy the
American Center, designed by Frank Gehry. By Alan Riding.
</P>
<P>
   SPAIN-PHILIP-III (San Lorenzo de el Escorial, Spain) _ King
Philip II not only lost the Invincible Armada in 1588 while trying
to invade England, but he also sunk in most history books as the
epitome of cruelty and intolerance associated with imperial Spain.
But now, on the 400th anniversary of his death, the government has
organized three major art exhibitions to portray a different side
of Philip, as a renaissance connoisseur of art and literature, a
bon vivant in his youth who loved royal parties and a devoted
family man.
</P>
<P>
   NICHOLAS-DANCE (Undated) _ The Scripps American Dance Festival
award to Nicholas Brothers.
</P>
<P>
   ARMAGEDDON-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Armageddon,'' Michael Bay,
director. Reviewed by Janet Maslin.
</P>
<P>
   SEA-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Where the Sea Used to Be,'' by
Rick Bass (Houghton-Mifflin). Reviewed by Richard Bernstein.
</P>
<P>
   TV-NOTES (Undated) _ News and notes on television. By Bill
Carter and Lawrie Mifflin.
</P>
<P>
