<SLUG> BC-LIVING-COLUMN-HAHN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN GOING TO SEED BECOMES TRENDY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JON HAHN  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Be quiet, Grasshopper, and listen to the sound of the vacuum
cleaner and scissors in the tall grass of the living room.
</P>
<P>
   You must be in tune with the current flow of trendiness in
interior design, which may well require you to wear high boots. The
latest thing for home and office interiors is a pot of grass.
</P>
<P>
   Large shallow pots, bulbous medium pots and thimblelike tiny
pots planted with domestic grasses and neatly trimmed. The idea,
which is called a concept in trendy circles, is to place the pot of
trimmed grass where people coming into a room will see it and reach
out and touch it.
</P>
<P>
   Like, Pet Lawns.
</P>
<P>
   Our daughter-in-law confirmed these reports of Eastern
trendiness and added that the smaller, coffee-cup-size of interior
lawns are reportedly the most popular. Such little excavated clumps
of grass are common on our golf courses, where they are called
divots. But the little signs advise us that these little chunks are
to be returned to Mother Earth.
</P>
<P>
   Do not laugh, Grasshopper, as I did when Honorable Wife Person
mentioned that her viewing of a television feature revealed this
pot-of-grass trend was taking root in all the beautiful East Coast
places filled with beautiful people. These little carry-out lawns
fulfill an inner need to commune with, literally touch, the living
grass.
</P>
<P>
   I must communicate this information also to our friend, Bill the
Artist, whose loft building in New York City's SoHo District has
the only tree on his section of Wooster Street. The concept of Pet
Lawns would grow well in an area where people do not have real
lawns or trees and where what they know as grass is sold in little
Baggies.
</P>
<P>
   You and I know, Grasshopper, that there are mushrooms growing
under the desks of some people at work. These people are not just
slobs, Grasshopper. Rather, they are necessary elements in the feng
shui of the workplace, the balance of natural elements.
</P>
<P>
   So, too, in the home, where the rooms of young people harbor
mysterious growths and fumes of growing sweat socks and old running
shoes, there must be a harmony. And this harmony, according to the
experts Back East, is accomplished by planting grass in a small
shallow pot in your home or office.
</P>
<P>
   If the winds and water and most life forces naturally flow from
west to east, it has been determined by Great People in corporate
board rooms and media production facilities that all things
beautiful and important must originate in the East and flow
westerly until we simple folks learn what is beautiful and
important. Like Pet Rocks and Pet Lawns.
</P>
<P>
   And grass in a pot on the kitchen counter or the coffee table or
the reception desk is very big in the East now, so it must be
important. So I will tell you about the living magic of the plant
world and why people must be in harmony with it instead of just
smoking it or sticking it up their noses.
</P>
<P>
   As you know, Grasshopper, I have several plants on the
windowsill of my office overlooking Elliott Bay and Myrtle Edwards
Park. These plants serve to bring the park inside, where I can
appreciate the living forces up close. I must be careful, however,
not to apply any more Alaskan Fish Fertilizer, because my
journalistic colleagues say the odor greatly upsets the feng shui
of our common space.
</P>
<P>
   At our home beneath the tall firs, there are many plants and
almost too much lawn, Grasshopper. This grass is prospering partly
because it is over the septic tank drain field, and partly because
I upset the natural balance by fertilizing the newly sown seed last
spring. Now I must walk upon the grass every week and trim it so
the yard achieves enough feng shui for the family dog to do to it
what I do to my office plants with that fish fertilizer.
</P>
<P>
   I would walk barefoot in the new grass to better commune with
nature, little Grasshopper, but as you know, there is dog doo-doo
and slugs upon the grass, which are parts of nature better left
outdoors and untouched. The Eastern experts do not mention
doggy-doo or slugs in their televised talks of trendiness.
</P>
<P>
   To bring the soft winds of harmony to our home, Grasshopper, I
stopped snickering long enough to dig up a bunch of grass and plop
it into a pottery vessel. I presented it humbly to Wife Person to
satisfy her desire to be trendy, but she scoffed and said it looked
too much like a bunch of grass plopped into a pot.
</P>
<P>
   ``It must be grown from seed evenly spaced in good soil,'' she
said, repeating the carefully memorized instructions from the Back
East television program. She suggested, Grasshopper, that I remove
the planted vessel and do it right, the way one of Martha Stewart's
many lackeys would do it just before she went on camera.
</P>
<P>
   My great failing, Grasshopper, is impatience in dealing with the
temporal circumstances that give rise to things such as Pet Lawns.
And in my impatience, I may have suggested to Honorable Wife Person
that it would be a cold day in another world before I planted
individual grass seeds in a pot so that grass would grow in our
house.
</P>
<P>
   And if people coming to our home want to touch live grass, I
will invite them to remove their Birkenstocks and socks and walk
barefoot upon my free-range mixture of red fescue, perennial rye
and whatever. Only I will remind them not to step in the feng shui.
</P>
<P>
   Jon Hahn is a staff columnist for the P-I.
</P>
<P>
   He can be reached at 206-448-8317 or e-mail him at
jonhahn(at)seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-98 1440EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
