<SLUG> BC-FILM-ARMEGEDDON-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ARMAGEDDON' IS A NO-BRAINER OF THE FIRST ORDER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   As expected, Disney's $100 million-plus, end-of-the-world
thriller, ``Armageddon,'' has the exact same premise as ``Deep
Impact'' _ a heavenly object the size of Texas is hurling toward
Mother Earth and has to be nuked off course.
</P>
<P>
   And yet it's a totally different movie. While ``Impact'' was
somber, reflective and dull, this instant rehash is moronic, filled
with non-stop action and special effects, and played mostly for
wisecracky guffaws and chest-pounding heroics.
</P>
<P>
   The model for producer Jerry Bruckheimer and director Michael
Bay (``The Rock'') appears to be 1996's ``Independence Day,'' and,
as in that film, the filmmakers are less interested in scaring
anyone with any real apocalyptic possibilities than in jiving a
lowest-common-denominator audience for every second of the lengthy
screen time.
</P>
<P>
   The teenagers roared through the Seattle preview last week, and
the movie smells like a hit, but be warned it's a no-brainer of the
first order. The script is filled with story holes as large as its
asteroid, and _ if you're resistant to its adolescent humor and
action overkill _ that 144-minute running time can seem like an
eternity.
</P>
<P>
   The heroes this time are not astronauts but a team of rough-neck
oil drillers, whose tough-guy leader (Bruce Willis) is whisked from
his rig in the South China Sea back to the States and given the bad
news: an asteroid will impact with the Earth in exactly 18 days,
wiping out all life (``even bacteria'') _ unless he can help stop
it.
</P>
<P>
   So he gathers up his crew (who, in a bizarre time warp, have
scattered over the country _ and taken up new lives and new
pursuits _ in the few hours that have elapsed since he left them in
the South China Sea) to be trained by NASA so they can intercept
the asteroid and drill a hole in it suitable for planting a nuclear
device.
</P>
<P>
   To its credit, a lot of the staggering budget for ``Armageddon''
is up there on the screen. It looks like a hugely expensive movie
in almost every frame, the effects are generally better than those
of ``Deep Impact,'' and several of them _ particularly the meteor
showers that practically wipe out New York and Paris _ are as good
as they get.
</P>
<P>
   But the film's over-produced, MTV-style quickly distances us
from the characters and gradually pulls the movie down. As in ``The
Rock,'' Bruckheimer and Bay are intent on making every scene play
like a gushy, super-glossy television commercial. And there are no
low points _ just one crisis after another, to the point of
numbness.
</P>
<P>
   There's zero suspense. Because the characters are so absorbed
with delivering one-liners, and blithely unconcerned about the
possibility of extinction, so are we. In fact, the overworked
interpersonal drama here _ which is built around Willis'
disapproval of the relationship between his daughter (Liv Tyler)
with one of the crew members (Ben Affleck) _ would be highly
irrelevant if there was any real chance the world was about to end.
</P>
<P>
   The last act of the film is one long action sequence on the
asteroid: thousands of quick cuts, hundreds of explosions, endless
shots of characters in space suits hurling through the air. But
it's so poorly staged as narrative, it's almost impossible to
figure out who is who, and what exactly is going on. The entire
finale is altogether about as engaging as a video game glimpsed
over someone else's shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Armageddon. Directed by Michael Bay. Screenplay by Jonathan
Hensleigh and J.J. Abrams. Cast: Bruce Willis, Billy Bob Thornton,
Liv Tyler, Ben Affleck. Disney/Touchstone. 144 minutes. Rated PG-13
for violence.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-98 1440EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
