</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILDREN-BOOK-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICA IS BEAUTIFUL, FROM STETSONS TO PATRIOTIC POETS TO BLACK
COWPOKES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JANE P. MARSHALL 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Seldom does a children's book come along as well-conceived,
-written and -executed as ``Boss of the Plains: The Hat That Won
the West'' (DK, $16.95).
</P>
<P>
   Laurie Carlson has taken a complex subject and cleverly whittled
it to a simple tale full of history, rich in nuances and lovely to
read.
</P>
<P>
   The story of the birth of the Stetson hat has a better plot than
``Godzilla,'' as many twists and turns as ``The X-Files'' and the
epic proportions of ``Titanic.'' Immigration, gold fever,
economics, fashion, health ... what a story.
</P>
<P>
   John Batterson Stetson grew up in a New Jersey hat-making
family. He could make hats, but he couldn't shake his dreams of
going west. Gold fever beckoned, and the young Stetson headed to
Colorado Territory. He didn't find much gold, but he found a need
for a hat that kept off the sun and rain, impressed the ladies,
could serve as a bucket and more. He wanted a hat that was ``big
and picturesque.'' He invented the Boss of the Plains hat.
</P>
<P>
   Holly Meade's distinctive cut-paper illustrations add a lively
cowboy spirit to the book. She uses dusty colors and a stock tank
of wit with delightful results.
</P>
<P>
   Stetson ``put energy into improving his own life and the lives
of others around him. Biographies of people like him give kids
much-needed heroes,'' she writes. ``I have a Stetson of my own. ...
There's something about putting on one of these regal hats that
reflects the spirit of the West. You find yourself standing a bit
taller, a bit straighter, and looking people right in the eye.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stetson Hat Co. still makes Boss of the Plains hats.
</P>
<P>
   _ Another journey west is the topic for ``Purple Mountain
Majesties: The Story of Katherine Lee Bates and America the
Beautiful'' (Dutton, $16.99).
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Younger begins the Bates story with a child who loved
words and ``stories, rhymes, and clever ways of saying things.''
When she was 9 her mother gave her a red leather diary. She kept
writing in diaries and notebooks as she grew up, went to a new
college for women called Wellesley, taught English literature there
and traveled.
</P>
<P>
   In 1893 her travels took her to Colorado Springs, Colo., where
she had been invited to lecture. She journeyed by train, and what
she saw captured her poet's imagination. In Colorado, she and a
group of teachers rode a wagon to the top of Pikes Peak. There
Bates gazed at the Rockies purple in the sun.
</P>
<P>
   The sight became a line in a poem. ``Oh beautiful for halcyon
skies/For amber waves of grain./For purple mountain majesties ...''
</P>
<P>
   The poem was set to music, several times, and became one of the
country's most popular songs. ``A the B,'' her family called it.
She won fame but not money. Bates never requested payment for the
use of her words.
</P>
<P>
   Younger's story of the trip that gave us ``A the B'' is a
smidgen of history, but one every child can relate to. Stacey
Schuett's charming, detailed illustrations have a primitive quality
that helps carry Younger's (and Bates') message.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Black Cowboy, Wild Horses: A True Story'' (Dial, $16.99)
looks at the plains from horseback, not a train window or a
mountaintop.
</P>
<P>
   The team of writer Julius Lester and illustrator Jerry Pinkney
has another winner on its hands. Lester's story is beautifully
woven. The lackadaisical pace is more reminiscent of a hawk's
flight than a horse's gallop. But it does envelop the ways of Bob
Lemmons, on whose life the book is based.
</P>
<P>
   Lemmons, a former slave, was a well-known cowboy. He could think
like a horse, put himself in the middle of a herd of wild mustangs
and, with patience, bring in a whole herd by himself. He did it
because he made horses think he was one of them.
</P>
<P>
   Lester tells how he did it, describing one roundup and weaving
the texture of the plains _ lonely, exciting, boring, hot, wet,
dirty, tense. And there was the waiting, waiting.
</P>
<P>
   Pinkney's paintings (pencil, gouache and watercolor) are
beautiful. Once again, he proves his versatility. He can do cute
and charming. But he captures the very essence of wild mustangs on
the harsh open plains in a flurry of wild strength and freedom.
</P>
<P>
   These three top-notch books, each revealing a different player
in the history of the West, demonstrate a method good children's
authors know and wannabes don't: research. Imagine tidily
condensing the history of a song and its writer into 29 pages, and
most of that art.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
