<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-CONVENTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAN ANTONIO THROWS GRAND OLD PARTY FOR REPUBLICAN SEARCH PANEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANITA McDIVITT  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Thousands of people here staged a grand old party
trying to convince the Republican National Committee to stage its
2000 presidential nominating convention in this South Texas city.
</P>
<P>
   Chanting ``We want you,'' some 5,000 people were at the
Alamodome Monday to cheer Republican Party scouts touring potential
sites for the convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we just saw on Monday at noon ... is absolutely
incredible,'' said Jan Larimer, chairwoman of the Republican Site
Selection Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not gotten a facility reception like this at all,''
RNC spokesman Tim Fitzpatrick said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the crowd, the RNC committee was greeted with
10,000 balloons and fireworks at the home of the San Antonio Spurs,
a National Basketball Association franchise.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've put on a very good show,'' Larimer told a news
conference after the rally. ``But you've also put together a very
good proposal.''
</P>
<P>
   San Antonio was the GOP's fifth stop on a nationwide tour of
eight cities, each fiercely competing for the party's political
bash.
</P>
<P>
   San Antonio, once considered an unlikely site for the convention
because the city had lacked sufficient hotel accommodations, has
added hotel rooms and bolstered its convention presence in the past
four years.
</P>
<P>
   The city of more than 1 million people is seen as a strong
candidate for the Republican convention because of its large
Hispanic population and strong Republican presence.
</P>
<P>
   Larimer said the matter of hotel rooms _ city leaders say there
are about 22,000 _ is still under discussion.
</P>
<P>
   The convention could have an estimated economic impact of $100
million to $200 million from 35,000 conventioneers.
</P>
<P>
   The City Council voted earlier this year to commit $6.3 million
to the convention, and a private host committee has pledged to
raise another $12 million.
</P>
<P>
   Charlotte, N.C., New Orleans, New York and Philadelphia wined
and dined committee members earlier this month. The search
committee is scheduled to visit Chicago, Indianapolis and
Minneapolis in the coming weeks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
