   These business stories for release Wednesday, July 1, 1998, are
moving today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the financial (f) category. Stories also
moving in lifestyle will be marked with (f, l).
</P>
<P>
   Separate budgets move daily with spot news, features, sports and
commentary.
</P>
<P>
   All stories have moved, except those with an ETA.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   GATECH-CLOUGH _ ATLANTA _ G. Wayne Clough, the new Georgia Tech
president, is a nearly perfect Georgia story _ a Douglas, Ga.
native, graduate of the state's premier emporium of technology, and
now the first alumnus-president. But there is much more. Clough
brings the experience of witnessing firsthand much of the
collaboration between universities and the Silicon Valley, where
theoretical expertise joined entrepreneurship to spark the growth
of a global industry. It is that formula that Wayne Clough hopes to
embellish and adapt to the fledgling but highly ambitious strategy
to create simular technological growth in the Georgia and the
southeast. (Holsendolph, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA: 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   GATECH-QNA _ ATLANTA _ G. Wayne Clough talks frankly about
Tech's modest standing among the greatest technical schools around
the country, and what must be done to bolster it. (Holsendolph,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA: 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   GATECH-ATDC _ ATLANTA _ Profile of Georgia Tech's Advance
Technology Development Center (ATDC) , formed in 1980, which
assists in the formation and growth of startup technology
companies, supporting the commericalization of technolgy and
attracting technology companies to the state. (Kanell, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) ETA: 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   GATECH-GTRI _ ATLANTA _ A small laboratory at the Georgia Tech
Research Institute, an applied research arm of Georgia Tech, is
designing the hands-free, wearable computer system. At least two
Georgia poultry plants are interested in it; one, Cagle's in south
Georgia, may turn their inspectors into cyborgs within the year.
(Rochelle, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA: 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   IRELAND-DELL-MAIN _ LIMERICK, Ireland _ Shortly after boarding a
plane in Chicago for a flight to Austin, Texas, in 1989, Desmond
O'Malley pulled out notes on his next appointment. Ireland's
minister of industry and commerce couldn't believe his eyes. His
staff was sending him to drum up investment from a $17 million
computer company called PC's Limited, whose founder and chief
executive was only 24. O'Malley's skepticism dissipated shortly
into his two-hour meeting with Michael Dell. ``I was very
impressed,'' he said. (Mahoney, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
WITH PHOTOS in Austin's database with a keyword of Dell, or on the
Cox server.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   DELL-IRELAND-ECONOMY _ LIMERICK, Ireland _ Just three decades
ago, Ireland was a poor nation of small villages and farms that had
more in common with some Third World countries than with the
industrialized West. For more than 150 years, its best and most
dependable export had been its people. Now Ireland has become
Europe's top-performing economy. Dell Computer Corp.'s expansion
plans symbolize Ireland's growing industrial clout. (Mahoney,
Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   DELL-IRELAND-WIRED _ ENNIS, Ireland _ Ireland, in a furious pace
to transform its agrarian economy to a technological marvel in just
over one generation, hopes to have the world's first fully wired
city. The project is a joint effort between Ireland's national
telecommunications company, Dell Computer Corp. and Ennis, a
prosperous city of 20,000 whose origins date to the 13th century.
(Mahoney, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   DELL-IRELAND-QNA _ ROUND ROCK, Texas _ An interview with Michael
Dell. (Mahoney, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   GM _ Members of UAW Local 696 vote today on a strike
authorization as the crippling strikes by two other UAW locals in
Flint, Mich., drag on and on and on with no end in sight. Local 696
leaders will hold a news conference after the final voting session
at 3: 45 p.m. (Wagner, Dayton Daily News). 15.
</P>
<P>
   MEAD _ Speculation is mounting that Mead Corp. is shopping for
at least one of rival International Paper Co.'s coated paper mills,
two weeks after the Dayton-based paper company announced the sale
of its flagging Zellerbach distribution unit to IP. (Drummond,
Dayton Daily News)
</P>
