<HEADLINE>
VARIETY ADDS SPICE TO SUMMER READING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BEVERLY MEDLYN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   June's kid books range from counting red-eyed tree frogs to
scary disaster stories to a scholarly collection of biographical
portraits of queens.
</P>
<P>
   One highlight is an innovative series called ``We Both Read.''
It is designed to make story time more interactive for beginning
readers, with parents and children taking turns reading each page. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; POTS AND PANS &QL; 
 &UR; Patricia Hubbell; illustrated by Diane deGroat (HarperCollins,
$9.95)
</P>
<P>
   ``Pots and Pans, pots and pans, Baby's in the kitchen with the
pots and pans. GRAB those lids! CLANG those pans! Baby's in the
kitchen with the pots and pans.''
</P>
<P>
   The fun for this toddler starts simply enough, but add a cat and
dog to the mix, plus some canned goods and cereal boxes, and you
end up with _ a very messy floor and a very happy kid. Cute
illustrations capture the mayhem. Sturdy pages for tiny hands. For
infants to age 2. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; ANIMAL 1-2-3's &QL; 
 &UR; (World Wildlife Fund, $12.95)
</P>
<P>
   No one beats the World Wildlife Fund for dazzling pictures of
exotic animals. In this 1-20 counting book, children start counting
one owl, then progress through bright-eyed lemurs, grazing wart
hogs, leaping kangaroos, lounging polar bears, flying macaws,
red-eyed tree frogs, rare bald eagles, splendid zebras and regal
lions.
</P>
<P>
   ``World Wildlife Fund Bugs'' presents vivid photos of 26 creepy
crawlers, from the Ladybug to the Stink Bug. For ages 1-4. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; POOH'S FIRST CLOCK &QL; 
 &UR; Inspired by A.A. Milne (E.P. Dutton, $12.99)
</P>
<P>
   It's a busy day at the Hundred Acre Wood, starting at 8 a.m.,
when Pooh and Christopher Robin wake up, get dressed and eat
breakfast. By 10 a.m., Tigger, Roo, Owl, Piglet, Rabbit and Eeyore
are in the thick of activities, gathering fir cones, digging holes,
and washing clothes.
</P>
<P>
   At noon _ you guessed it _ time for lunch with a little honey.
There's no better way to learn to tell time than with these beloved
characters. A three-dimensional clock with internal gears that
click and hands that move will fascinate young children. For ages
3-5. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; ADVENTURE ON KLICKITAT ISLAND &QL; 
 &UR; Hilary Horder Hippely; illustrated by Barbara Upton (Dutton,
$15.99)
</P>
<P>
   As a nighttime storm picks up on Klickitat Island, a boy and his
bear set out from their cozy bed to help keep the forest animals
dry. The boy takes control, directing the deers, otters, rabbits,
birds and raccoons on how to build a fort with tree limbs and
stones. The happy group settles in for a nice, long snooze, and the
boy and his bear creep back to their bed.
</P>
<P>
   Hippely, a poet, tells the charming story about leadership and
cooperation in rhyme, with white print set against dark blue pages.
Upton's soft illustrations glow with warmth. The animals'
expressive faces capture emotions ranging from alarm to blissful
contentment. For ages 3-5. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; WE BOTH READ: JACK AND THE BEANSTALK &QL; 
 &UR; Adapted by Sindy McKay; illustrated by Lydia Halverson (Treasure
Bay, $7.99)
</P>
<P>
   What a great idea! Now parents and kids can read stories
together, taking turns reading pages. In the new series of
storybooks called ``We Both Read,'' parents read the left-hand
pages, which have more sophisticated vocabulary and structure, and
children read the right-hand pages, with short, easy sentences.
</P>
<P>
   More difficult words are introduced first in the parent's text
with bold lettering. Each child's page advances the story line, so
young readers truly are contributing.
</P>
<P>
   The series has books at three reading levels, for preschool
through third grade. The first four books, available in August, are
adaptations of well-known classics for grades one to two. Besides
``Jack,'' they are ``The Emperor's New Clothes''; ``The Tales of
Peter Rabbit and Benjamin Bunny''; and ``The Frog Prince.'' McKay
is best known for her Emmy-winning writing for the Muppets. For
ages 4-7. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; MY BIRTHDAY BOOK &QL; 
 &UR; Catherine Hoesterey; illustrated by Mary Lake-Thompson (Little,
Brown &AMP; Co.,
 &UR; $14.95)
</P>
<P>
   This offering takes up where the baby book leaves off. Children
are invited to record their memories of five birthdays, within such
categories as ``My birthday wish,'' ``How I celebrated,'' ``The
best thing that happened'' and ``Friends and family who celebrated
with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Another page, called ``About Me,'' is devoted to
autobiographical reflections. The book has plenty of space for
party invitations, photos and mementos. OK, maybe it's more for Mom
and Dad than for kids, but someday they'll appreciate it. For ages
4-12. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; THERE'S A FROG IN MY SLEEPING BAG &QL; 
 &UR; Susan Clymer (Scholastic, $3.50)
</P>
<P>
   Goodbye classroom! Hello Camp Buffalo! Janna and her third-grade
friends are enjoying their summer camp activities _ boating, hiking
and telling ghost stories at night _ when mysterious pranks begin.
</P>
<P>
   First, Janna's stuffed snake disappears and ends up on a buffalo
head in the dining hall. Next, peanuts are scattered on her cabin
floor. Then the trickster slips a slimy frog in Janna's sleeping
bag. Who is playing tricks? And why are they picking on Janna?
</P>
<P>
   Scholastic publishes a wide selection of inexpensive paperbacks
that are perfect summer fare for young readers. For ages 6-10. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; TRAPPED &QL; 
 &UR; George Sullivan (Scholastic, $3.99)
</P>
<P>
   Is someone in your house fascinated by disaster? Here's a
collection of six true adventures, starting with the gripping drama
of little Jessica McClure of Midland, Texas. Few adults can forget
the 1987 near-tragedy that had Americans riveted to their
television sets, rooting for the toddler trapped in a dark,
abandoned well for more than two days. She made it, and today,
Jessica has no memory of the ordeal.
</P>
<P>
   Other stories are equally compelling. They include a brave
kindergarten teacher who led her 14 students to safety after they
were trapped in an elevator during the 1993 World Trade Center
bombing; a group of mountain climbers trapped on Mount Everest; and
a foolish but gutsy Cuban stowaway who escaped his country by
hiding in the wheel well of a jetliner bound for Spain.
</P>
<P>
   Though the stories end on an uplifting note, their intensity may
be too much for some youngsters. For ages 9 and up. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; DOUGAL DIXON'S DINOSAURS &QL; 
 &UR; Dougal Dixon (Boyds Mills Press, $17.95)
</P>
<P>
   This is the definitive dinosaur book. Recommended by The
Dinosaur Soci ety, Dixon's authoritative text, pub lished in 18
languages, has been updated with the latest dinosaur dis coveries,
including Argentinosaurus, the biggest dinosaur known.
</P>
<P>
   Colorful illustrations and photographs bring the great beasts to
life. A Q &AMP; A in the back covers everything you'd want to know,
including which was the most intelligent dinosaur (Troodon); which
had the smallest brain (Stegosaurus, at 2.5 ounces); and which
nation has the most dinosaurs (the United States). Aficionados will
love it! For ages 8-12. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; TEN QUEENS: PORTRAITS OF WOMEN OF POWER &QL; 
 &UR; Milton Meltzer; illustrated by Bethanne Audersen (Dutton, $24.99)
</P>
<P>
   Esther, the Jewish wife of King Ahasuerus of Persia, gives us
historical perspective on the women's movement. In the fifth
century, B.C., Esther foils the plot of the king's prime minister,
Haman, to wipe out the Jews _ an accomplishment celebrated
worldwide ever since with the Feast of Purim, a popular folk
festival.
</P>
<P>
   Nine other strong women who ruled in their own right are
profiled, including Cleopatra, Isabel of Spain, Catherine the Great
of Russia and Elizabeth I of England. Their lives are portrayed in
an interesting way by Meltzer, who has written more than 90 books
for young people and adults in the fields of history, biography and
social reform. For ages 10 and up. &QL; 
(Beverly Medlyn can be reached at bevmedlyn(at)aol.com via
e-mail.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
