<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-NEW-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW AND NOTABLE BOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ A survey of recently published books:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; aol.com &QL; 
 &UR; Kara Swisher (Times, $25)
</P>
<P>
   When Swisher, who writes for the Wall Street Journal, began work
on this book in 1996, America Online was considered a goner. What a
difference a year makes. This is a story of entrepreneurial savvy
and dogged determination after Bill Gates told Steve Case, in 1993,
``I can buy 20 percent of you or I can buy all of you, or I can go
into this business myself and bury you.'' It was a time when Case's
struggle at AOL, Swisher writes, was ``like jumping from one
unstable ice floe to the next in a frantic attempt to prevent the
whole enterprise from sinking into the icy depths of capitalism's
ever-churning sea.'' All of this was complicated by the fact that
everything was new _ this was the Internet, on which everyone and
everything had just been born. Now we know what happened _ or at
least what has happened so far. Swisher's book is an entertaining
account of how this time, Microsoft didn't bury anyone. It's all in
the subtitle: ``How Steve Case Beat Bill Gates, Nailed the
Netheads, and Made Millions in the War for the Web.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; SUITS ME: THE DOUBLE LIFE OF BILLY TIPTON &QL; 
 &UR; Diane Wood Middlebrook (Houghton Mifflin, $25)
</P>
<P>
   In 1989 in Spokane, Wash., a teenage boy named William summoned
an ambulance to a trailer park where his father, Billy, an aging
and very ill White jazz musician, had passed out. When paramedics
examined the old man, they discovered _ to the surprise of William,
the women who had lived with Billy and everyone else who knew him _
that he was a woman. Pronounced dead at the hospital, Billy Tipton
had fooled them all, from the time she was 19 until ``he'' died at
74. She began life as Dorothy Tipton, probably a lesbian, who was a
jazz pianist and saxophonist at a time when women were not accepted
in those roles. Her remarkable charade was known, at first, by some
tolerant fellow jazz players, and later, when her disguise had
fooled everyone else, she had several lovers and adopted three
sons, none of whom ever suspected that Billy was a woman.
Middlebrook was in Spokane in 1991 to publicize her previous book,
``Anne Sexton: A Biography,'' when she was approached by Kitty
Tipton Oakes, Billy's former wife, who asked Middlebrook to write a
book about him. It's the fascinating story, set against
Depression-era Oklahoma, of a woman born in 1914 and reborn in 1933
after she discovered, Middlebrook writes, ``that being taken for a
man provided access to almost everything she wanted _ music,
travel, the love of adventures and caretaking women.'' And she kept
it up, flawlessly, for nearly 60 years. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; RATTLESNAKE CROSSING &QL; 
 &UR; J.A. Jance (Avon, $23)
</P>
<P>
   Joanna Brady, single mother and sheriff of Cochise County, is
investigating a shooting rampage on a local ranch when she stumbles
upon the body of a rural gun dealer whose fortresslike shop has
been cleaned of all its merchandise, apparently by his killer. Two
more killings follow, with both victims shot and scalped, and
suspicion settles on a local rancher and isolationist who wages his
own little war against the government and those he calls
``enviro-nuts.'' But the discovery that the dead gun dealer was
suffering from AIDS sets Brady looking for another solution to the
crime spree. Jance's sixth Joanna Brady novel is like its
predecessors _ notable here for its Arizona settings, but not for
its prose or plot. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; 8 WEEKS TO OPTIMUM HEALTH &QL; 
 &UR; Andrew Weil (Fawcett, $13.95)
</P>
<P>
   Change your life _ eat some broccoli. Get rid of the lard, save
the olive oil. Read those labels, buy some flowers, make friends
with vitamin C and (you might have to gear up for this one)
``fermented soybean products.'' Exercise, and throw out your
electric blanket. And whatever you do, don't keep your electric
clock radio within a foot of your head. Weil's seventh book, now
new in paperback, is an eight-week program that he says will ``give
you the information you need to keep your healing system in optimal
working order so that you can stay healthy as you encounter the
obstacles and challenges of day-to-day life.'' He includes lots of
testimonials from people who swear by his approach, and recipes
that involve things like tofu and gingerroot. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; MONSTER &QL; 
 &UR; John Gregory Dunne (Vintage, $12)
</P>
<P>
   New in paperback is Dunne's funny, enlightening look at one
screenplay and what happened to it in Hollywood after eight years,
27 drafts and many daunting battles with a monster called money (in
this case, it belonged to the Walt Disney Co.). In 1988, Dunne and
his wife, Joan Didion, were asked to write a movie script based on
the life of the late television journalist Jessica Savitch. Savitch
died horribly in 1983 when she was trapped in a car that overturned
in a Pennsylvania canal. Her messy life had involved drug abuse,
promiscuity, mental instability and the disdain of her colleagues.
(David Brinkley called her ``the dumbest woman I have ever met.'')
In 1996, however, the screenplay once based on her dark life was
released as ``Up Close &AMP; Personal,'' a sappy fairy tale starring
Robert Redford and Michelle Pfeiffer. The rough road from one
extreme to the other is great reading about modern Hollywood,
behind the scenes. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
