<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-AUTHOR-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARVARD PROFESSOR WEIGHS IN WITH NOVEL THAT CHARMS READERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Sanjay Nigam was doing his medical residency in Dallas 14
years ago, he learned two things that would change his life.
</P>
<P>
   The first was how not to sleep, a talent that came in handy at a
busy hospital where residents were responsible for most of the
patient care. The second was how to enjoy big, challenging novels,
the kind he'd never read before. Nigam had grown up in Arizona,
where in high school and later at Arizona State University in Tempe
he had taken only the basic writing and literature courses required
of him. He was, after all, a scientist, and had other interests.
But in Dallas, in the frenzy of a residency that was one of the
most demanding things he would ever do, he suddenly discovered
Tolstoy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I started reading as some kind of coping mechanism,'' he
says today from Boston, where he is an associate professor at
Harvard Medical School.
</P>
<P>
   ``I finished `War and Peace' and `One Hundred Years of
Solitude,' Dostoyevsky, `Dr. Zhivago,' all those big Ayn Rand
books. Anything that was heavy, I read. I don't think I `took them
on,' as you say. It was more that I just dissolved into them. They
are good stories, and they were big enough to get swallowed up in.
</P>
<P>
   ``After reading like that, you find that this is what you admire
_ good literature. I also think when you get into the intensity of
a residency you develop a kind of double vision. I'd always had a
strong theoretical, abstract, scientific bent. And then I got hit
with (begin itals) life. (end itals) The extremes of an emergency
room or an ICU. You have this abstract thing going on in your head,
but there are people bleeding and throwing up all over you. I think
out of that tension, plus my growing admiration for good
literature, I decided to write.''
</P>
<P>
   Nigam's first novel, ``The Snake Charmer,'' was released in June
to good reviews and strong reader interest, but it is not the book
you would expect from a man whose inspiration was some of the
weightiest fiction ever written. Just over 200 pages and written in
spare, accessible prose, it is the story of Sonalal, a poor, Indian
snake charmer who is set on a journey of self-discovery when in a
fit of anger he kills his beloved cobra, Raju.
</P>
<P>
   The story is deceptively simple (one critic called it ``the
midlife crisis of a snake charmer''). At times, it reads like a
fable. But there are many themes tucked into the folds of Sonalal's
dilemma: the quest for artistic perfection, the elusive beauty of
scientific thought, the importance of responsibility, of love and
of even a poor man's sense of self-worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sonalal is definitely a flawed character,'' says Nigam. ``On
the one hand, he's noble _ he wants to find perfection in art if
not in life. On the other hand, life just keeps getting in the way
and his own flaws keep tripping him up. He doesn't have a degree in
philosophy and he's not the most pro-active guy you'll ever meet.
There's this tension between what he's after and what he has the
talents to find. I think that's what drives the story forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Nigam learned to write when he went to New York City to do
scientific research after he finished his residency. He made his
own work schedule, and was able to take advantage of the city's
cultural life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Almost from day one I got involved in writing workshops and
went to readings and met other writers,'' he says. ``You have the
opportunity there to commune both with big-name writers and a lot
of wannabes. It's informal, but I suspect that's the only way a
writing education can be. You can almost do your own tailored MFA,
just by living in New York and looking at the poetry calendar each
day.''
</P>
<P>
   Nigam was born in India, but left as a baby when his father came
to attend graduate school, first in Canada and then in the United
States (the family has lived in Arizona since he was 5). He
returned to India regularly throughout his childhood for long
visits with his grandparents. Some of the scenes in ``The Snake
Charmer'' _ most notably those set in Chandni Chowk, a colorful and
chaotic part of Old Delhi _ are based on firsthand knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   But Nigam is quick to point out that he grew up in Arizona and
his identity is Indian-American, even though he now is being linked
to some of the grandest Indian writers, including Vikram Chandra,
Salman Rushdie and Arundhati Roy.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me right now, it's nice to be compared to people who are
so well-known _ it's flattering, frankly,'' he says. ``But with all
the attention on Indian writing, it becomes hard to distinguish
yourself. And it's even more complicated than that, really, because
there are two issues _ distinguishing yourself period, and
distinguishing yourself in the Western mind. Even for someone who's
deeply interested in literature _ let's even say foreign literature
_ how many Indian writers can you hold in your head? Five? Ten?
Whereas you can hold 50 or even 100 American or English writers in
your head.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's a tendency to categorize. To lump. Right now
I'm grateful for it, but I can see how it might become annoying
later on.'' Nigam admits that he belongs to another category that
he likes even less, that of the doctor/writer. He can rattle off
the names of others _ Perri Klass, Robin Cook, Michael Crichton,
Ethan Canin, Richard Selzer, Samuel Shem.
</P>
<P>
   That, however, is not something he will change. He has no plans
to leave his work in medicine, nor will he stop writing. He has
gone back to a long novel he was working on sporadically before he
stopped two years ago to write ``The Snake Charmer.'' He has a
family, a job and stories to write, but says he has the stamina to
do it all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't sleep much,'' he says, laughing. ``I never quite
recovered my ability to sleep after my residency. It's too bad in
some ways. But I suppose if I had, I'd never have written
anything.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-98 1515EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980630.0151 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 15:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3992 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-BRIDGET-AZR &LR;      06-30 0778
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-BRIDGET-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARE SOME WOMEN REALLY LIKE THIS?  
 
BRIDGET JONES'S DIARY 
</HEADLINE>
  Helen Fielding (Viking, $22.95)  
 
 (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here's an ugly thought: What if someone were to put Helen
Fielding's new novel, ``Bridget Jones's Diary,'' into a time
capsule so as to preserve for women of the distant future an image
of what they might have been like if they had lived today?
</P>
<P>
   Think about that as you accompany the beleaguered Bridget
through a year in her terribly trivial life. Has evolution really
been working in reverse all this time? At least Neanderthal Woman
had something mildly pressing _ survival _ to occupy her mind
between boyfriends. Bridget has nothing better to do than to tint
her eyelashes, nurse her hangovers and evade her couple friends
(the ``Smug Marrieds'') as they try to fix her up with ruddy men
who wear braces and refer to women as ``fillies.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Bridget is single and in her 30s, and therein lies her
crisis. She has a job that is largely unexplained, except that it
involves a computer on which she sends flirty messages to Daniel, a
co-worker with whom she is smitten but who we know will treat her
badly. Her mother has left her father after 35 years of marriage,
and run off with a con man from Portugal. Bridget smokes and drinks
too much, and sometimes treats a hangover by eating muesli out of
the package with a spoon and finishing off the dregs of wine in the
refrigerator. Her weight goes up and down, which never helps. And
she is beginning to have those single-but-no-longer-a-girl
thoughts, or as she describes them, ``fears of dying alone and
being found three weeks later half-eaten by an Alsatian.''
</P>
<P>
   None of this means that Bridget is unappealing. Actually, she is
very funny, in a guileless sort of way. This is because Fielding's
book is written as a diary, so nothing is kept secret from us.
Bridget begins each entry with a record of her weight (anywhere
from 119 to 133 pounds), her calorie consumption (low: 345, high:
8,489), her cigarette and alcohol tally and occasionally her thigh
girth and the number of minutes she spends counting her wrinkles.
</P>
<P>
   We also know the entertaining details of her inner life. We wait
with her as she longs for Daniel's call, which seldom comes. We
squirm with her as the Smug Marrieds quiz her on her sex life. We
share her worries that her daffy mother might end up ``sitting on a
sofa with someone in stone-washed jeans called Gonzales and
explaining that, if you really love someone, a 46-year age gap
really doesn't matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Of Bridget's supporting cast, the best is Tom, her gay friend,
something every single woman needs nowadays. When Bridget
inexplicably loses a few pounds, it is Tom who suggests that she
has a tapeworm. After she musters the resolve to stomp out on
Daniel, Tom pours vodka down her throat from the bottle, adding the
tomato juice and Worcestershire sauce afterward. When Bridget makes
herself up to look like a Hollywood star, he tells her that she
looks like Barbara Cartland.
</P>
<P>
   I should mention something else: Bridget is British. She began
life as the subject of Fielding's London newspaper column, on which
this book is based, and she is wildly popular in Britain.
Fielding's American publisher has smoothed over any semantic
wrinkles that might have interfered with a similar reception here.
</P>
<P>
   But can Bridget win readers in this country? It depends on how
much self-absorption your sense of humor can stand. I, for one, had
not read far into her diary before I found myself thinking of
Mother Teresa, someone I've never had occasion to think much about
before. This was bizarre and bewildering until I realized that
Mother Teresa was as different from the depthless Bridget as you
can get, and it was nice to remember that she, too, existed at the
end of the 20th century. What's more, Bridget _ fresh from
comforting her aging parents over their failing marriage _ knows
just how I felt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is so long since I have done anything at all for anyone
else that it is a totally new and heady sensation,'' she tells her
diary. ``This is what has been missing in my life. I am having
fantasies about becoming a Samaritan or Sunday school teacher,
making soup for the homeless (or, as my friend Tom suggested,
darling mini-bruschettas with pesto sauce), or even retraining as a
doctor. Maybe going out with a doctor would be better still, both
sexually and spiritually fulfilling.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever. Bridget knows what she is, and so do we. And as long
as they put Mother Teresa in the time capsule too, we won't
complain. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-98 1520EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
