<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 15:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3995 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GULF-SYNDROME-HNS &LR;      06-30 1108
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GULF-SYNDROME-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOK RAISES NEW QUESTIONS ABOUT GULF WAR ILLNESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KATHLEEN SULLIVAN  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ After the Gulf War, Gens. Colin Powell and
Norman Schwarzkopf benefited from public euphoria over the victory
_ and their national hero status _ by writing best-selling memoirs
and joining the lucrative talk-show circuit.
</P>
<P>
   But when the men and women who served in the 1991 desert war
began falling ill with a variety of puzzling symptoms and
debilitating ailments, the generals were no longer in command.
</P>
<P>
   When investigative reporter Seymour M. Hersh interviewed Powell
and Schwarzkopf for his new book, ``Against All Enemies _ Gulf War
Syndrome: The War Between America's Ailing Veterans and Their
Government,'' the generals expressed dismay that the government has
failed to provide unstinting medical care for sick Gulf War
soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   ``My God,'' exclaimed Schwarzkopf, who was the commander of
Allied troops in the Gulf. ``Anybody who's sick deserves to be
treated.''
</P>
<P>
   Schwarzkopf stressed that he retired in mid-1991.
</P>
<P>
   ``The minute you are retired, you're cut off from the flow of
events,'' he told Hersh. ``When you leave, someone else is
promoted, and the last thing they want is some old general coming
back.''
</P>
<P>
   Powell, who was the chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff during
the Gulf War, said his responsibilities ended when he retired in
1993. ``If there are still some veterans who say I should have done
more or said more, my answer is, I wasn't in the government,'' he
told Hersh.
</P>
<P>
   ``Against All Enemies'' serves as a primer on the roadblocks
soldiers have faced trying to get medical treatment and
compensation for Gulf War illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview, Hersh said he hoped the book would put
new attention on the plight of soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   Hersh notes in the book that at least 35 soldiers died in
``friendly-fire'' exchanges in the Gulf, accidents in which
Americans were hit by U.S. fire.
</P>
<P>
   But Hersh says the true toll is much higher.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well over 100,000 Gulf War veterans have registered thus far
for physical examinations at Pentagon and VA clinics, with nearly
90 percent reporting some symptoms,'' he wrote. ``Those men and
women are friendly-fire casualties just as surely as if they had
been fired upon by their fellow soldiers.''
</P>
<P>
   Hersh said his hunch is that ailing veterans and active-duty
soldiers were exposed to toxic substances in the Gulf.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists are studying the effects of exposure to pesticides,
chemical and biological warfare agents, vaccines, infectious
diseases, depleted uranium, oil well fires and smoke, and
petrochemical products.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell what's made them sick,'' Hersh said. ``That's a
very complicated issue. The Pentagon has tried skating away by
talking about stress. What that means to most GIs is that they're
sick because they're weaklings. Even if they are suffering from
combat fatigue or shellshock or post traumatic stress disorder, so
what? The bottom line is, it doesn't matter. We should take care of
them.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Against All Enemies,'' Hersh introduces readers to the cast
of characters that has helped _ and hindered _ sick soldiers in
their quest for care and compensation. He also presents people who
were prevented from helping.
</P>
<P>
   The book contains a memo written by a Veterans Administration
doctor who described herself as ``one of the many refusenik
professionals who remain deeply concerned about the integrity and
efficacy of today's federal medical programs.''
</P>
<P>
   The doctor, an infectious disease specialist who treated more
than 600 veterans, was fired in 1997 after sending superiors a
sarcastic five-step outline on how to avoid treating Gulf War
veterans: (1) Keep claims lost in limbo for years; (2) Bill
veterans for services; (3) Alter diagnoses to reflect depression,
stress and postcombat fatigue; (4) Ignore physical, clinical or
laboratory abnormalities in veterans and deny their presence
publicly; (5) Never admit that modern medicine may be facing a new
disease.''
</P>
<P>
   Hersh's slim book _ 100 pages _ focuses on the politics of Gulf
War illnesses. He takes readers behind the scenes, to the months
before the war when the Pentagon was scrambling to figure out how
to protect troops from Iraqi biological and chemical warfare.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hersh also describes the scene on the battlefield: ``The
chemical warfare alarms did not work as designed. Many gas masks,
carried by each soldier as the first line of defense, could not be
made to fit or work properly.''
</P>
<P>
   He relates failures of the U.S. intelligence community: ``The
possibility of low-level exposure to nerve agents from (U.S.)
bombing and demolition (of Iraqi facilities) was not entertained.''
</P>
<P>
   Hersh, an award-winning investigative reporter, concludes: ``It
was more than sloppy, and more than the normal fog of war. A
veteran suffering from Gulf War syndrome could even believe it to
be criminal negligence.''
</P>
<P>
   Hersh's last book, ``The Dark Side of Camelot,'' tackled the
mythologies surrounding the presidency of John F. Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Against All Enemies,'' is the fifth offering in a monthly
series published by Ballantine's Library of Contemporary Thought.
The series is designed to give writers the chance to explore a
topic they feel passionately about.
</P>
<P>
   Hersh said he was inspired to focus on Gulf War illnesses after
the father of an ailing veteran sent him a ``care package'' of
information on the topic.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Against All Enemies'' Hersh shows how America's ailing
veterans have taken the gloss off the victory in the Gulf.
</P>
<P>
   ``The military's inevitable dilemma is profound: Can it protect
our soldiers and sailors in future wars if it was unable to do so
in the Gulf War?'' Hersh wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Hersh says the ``last battle'' of the Gulf War will focus on the
use of depleted uranium ammunition, which is made of metal that is
toxic and radioactive. The Pentagon, which failed to train troops
about its hazards, admitted this year that ``thousands'' of
soldiers may have been exposed to contaminated dust and debris in
the desert.
</P>
<P>
   Despite concern about that exposure, and reports of rising
cancer rates in Iraq, the Pentagon has declined to reconsider its
reliance on the ammunition, Hersh wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``Depleted uranium shells and bombs are now being offered for
sale by the United States to foreign armies and air forces,'' he
wrote. ``Sales are brisk. American know-how, and radioactive
poisoning, is being merchandised around the world.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-98 1521EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980630.0153 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 15:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4012 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-TURTLES-$ADV04     06-30 1427
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-TURTLES-$ADV04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    SEA TURTLES MAY BE CASUALTIES AS MEXICO RUSHES TO DEVELOP
CARIBBEAN COAST
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DUPLICATION ALERT: Moving (i) international and (l) lifestyle
categories. 
 &HT;    EDS: Xcacel is 67 miles south of CanCun, just north of Xel-ha in
the Mexican state of Quintana Roo.
 &HT;    For release on or after Saturday, July 4 
 &HT;    By By SUSAN FERRISS 
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service(at) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   XCACEL, Mexico _ She struggles ashore in darkness, illuminated
only by a milky spray of stars in the Caribbean sky.
</P>
<P>
   The sole sounds on the beach are the waves, the wind and the
steady crunch of webbed fingers scooping sand with amazing agility.
About 90 minutes later, the massive loggerhead sea turtle _ four
feet long, weighing nearly half a ton _ completes her task: she
lays more than a hundred pearl-colored eggs and furiously kicks
sand over her secret nest before lumbering back into the sea.
</P>
<P>
   Since time immemorial, creatures like this have relied on this
secluded Mexican beach called Xcacel (isk-ka-SEL) to come ashore
and reproduce. Only one in 100 hatchlings survive the perils of
nature. Fewer survive the dangers of man, who has pushed sea
turtles toward extinction.
</P>
<P>
   And now, biologists fear, Xcacel, one of the most important sea
turtle nesting grounds in the Caribbean and Atlantic, may soon be
gone. Earlier this year, over protests by sea turtle experts, the
state of Quintana Roo sold 113 acres of this small stretch of
paradise, a little more than a mile long and 390 acres in total, to
the Spanish luxury hotel developer Sol Melia.
</P>
<P>
   More sales of the beach, which is 67 miles south of Cancun, are
planned. They will also result in hotels unless environmentalists
can find a way to stop construction or buy back the land.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of solitude, biologists say, sea turtles who nest at
Xcacel may soon encounter the glare of artificial lights coming
from hundreds, perhaps thousands of hotel rooms, and they will be
driven back into the sea.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will become a hotel sanctuary, not a turtle sanctuary,''
said Julio Zurita, one of Mexico's leading sea turtle specialists
and a marine biologist at Quintana Roo's College of the Southern
Border. He has studied Xcacel for years and helped develop a
pioneering program that places volunteers on the beach at night to
protect the turtles and their eggs from poachers.
</P>
<P>
   The potential destruction of Xcacel ``is indeed one of the most
urgent conservation crises in the world for sea turtles,'' said
marine biologist Brian Bowen of the University of Florida in
Gainesville, who has also studied Xcacel.
</P>
<P>
   Xcacel is home to the largest reservoir of genetic diversity
anywhere in the Atlantic of loggerhead and green sea turtles, Bowen
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Xcacel nesting ground is eliminated,'' he said,
``twenty percent of the genetic diversity in Atlantic loggerhead
turtles and 22 percent of the genetic diversity in Atlantic green
turtles will be lost forever. Such a loss would be disastrous.''
</P>
<P>
   Genetic diversity is the insurance, Bowen said, that allows
species to survive climate changes, pollution and other
environmental challenges.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to Xcacel's fame is evidence that the Mexican beach is
the ``well spring'' from which these turtles eventually colonized
the Mediterranean Sea.
</P>
<P>
   Today, about 15 percent of the sea turtles trapped and found
dead in drift nets off the Azores islands off Portugal are Xcacel
natives, testimony to these turtles' reach and vulnerability.
</P>
<P>
   Construction on sea turtle nesting grounds is a global problem
now, Bowen and other specialists said, as well as one of the top
concerns of Latin American turtle specialists.
</P>
<P>
   In Malaysia, Bowen said, a beach that used to host 1,000 turtles
a season is now down to one or two because of a hotel development
that, ironically, invited tourists to see the turtles.
</P>
<P>
   Sergio Perez Erales, environmental secretary for Quintana Roo
state, accuses environmentalists of acting prematurely and
exaggerating the scope of development that will take place at
Xcacel. First, he said, developers must obtain permits from
Mexico's National Ecology Institute and finish environmental impact
studies that show plans comply with some degree of conservation
required on this coast.
</P>
<P>
   Because of a requirement to protect turtles, Perez Erales said,
Quintana Roo governor Maria Villanueva declared a portion of Xcacel
a state turtle reserve.
</P>
<P>
   But the area only extends 100 meters, or 110 yards, from the
water line, an amount that is ``just a Band-Aid,'' said Bowen.
``Protect a narrow strip of the beach is just not going to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Whispering in the dark, while a turtle laid her eggs at Xcacel,
Zurita too scoffed at the idea: ``This is how they're protecting a
turtle sanctuary? With 100 meters?''
</P>
<P>
   Others said the governor's declaration had no scientific
foundation, and seemed to be more of a move to smooth controversy
over selling Xcacel. The beaches adjacent to Xcacel, which are also
important nesting grounds, have already been sold and are now under
development as part of Mexico's new tourist attraction, the ``Mayan
Riviera.''
</P>
<P>
   Juan Carlos Cantu of Mexico's Greenpeace chapter said, ``Sol
Melia doesn't care at all about turtle protection at Xcacel . . .
And the governor stuck it to everyone by selling the land.''
</P>
<P>
   Sol Melia, which has built large hotels and golf resorts in
Cancun and other parts of Mexico, failed to return requests for
interviews about Xcacel.
</P>
<P>
   Years before the sale, Mexican conservationists had tried to
persuade Mexico's federal government, which controlled the land
until 1993, to declare Xcacel in its entirety a federal reserve.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the turtles, the property is home to other
threatened wildlife and contains mangrove thickets protected under
federal law.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1980s, the Mayab Ecology Group based in Cancun began
to press the government to protect Xcacel. In 1994, it submitted an
official proposal with requisite scientific research. Only this
year did officials respond to the request, turning it down, shortly
before the state sold the land.
</P>
<P>
   Araceli Dominguez of the Mayab Ecology Group said, ``We're
asking for what, two kilometers of beach? Is that too much to
ask?''
</P>
<P>
   Conservationists are also upset because a 1995 land use plan for
the Quintana Roo coast, signed by the governor, included ``strong
recommendations'' to protect Xcacel.
</P>
<P>
   The land use plan included a clause recommending that if Xcacel
were to be sold, environmentalists should have the first right to
buy it.
</P>
<P>
   Conservationists say they were never given that chance. But it
may not be too late.
</P>
<P>
   ``If ecology groups are interested in buying the land, we'll
sell it to them,'' Perez Erala said. But they will have to come up
with the $11 million that Sol Melia paid for its share of the land,
plus additional funds for the remainder of the property if they
also want to buy that.
</P>
<P>
   He said Sol Melia is willing to cancel its Xcacel contract.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists say the $11 million figure is far more than
the price they've heard quoted for the land. Nevertheless, they
would like to buy Xcacel, but fear that raising so much money on
short notice would be difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be really tough, unless they can find someone like
Ted Turner,'' Bowen said. ``By the time they raise the money, those
turtles could be a distant memory.''
</P>
<P>
   Mexican environmentalists are also weighing legal options here,
but worry there are few left before construction starts.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, Mexico banned molestation of all sea turtles, and in a
gesture of good will, it hosted the first two meetings for the
establishment of the Inter-American Convention for the Protection
and Conservation of Sea Turtles. Mexico hasn't signed the accord
yet, however.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Sol Melia has put up a sign at the entrance to
the beach declaring it ``private property'' and advertising a
``tourist development.''
</P>
<P>
   Visitors can ask a guard to allow them onto the beach, and
student volunteers still camp there at night, transplanting eggs to
protected nesting areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone always says, 'Nothing will happen when hotels are
built.' But it's not true,'' said Daphne Gadar, a Mexico City
biology student.
</P>
<P>
   ``I imagine tourists like to come to a place like this now,''
she said, swinging in a hammock, ``with clean water, no big hotels.
Mexico is still exotic in that way, but we're fast doing away with
it.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-98 1525EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980630.0154 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 15:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4016 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-TURTLES-$ADV04     06-30 1427
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-TURTLES-$ADV04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    SEA TURTLES MAY BE CASUALTIES AS MEXICO RUSHES TO DEVELOP
CARIBBEAN COAST
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DUPLICATION ALERT: Moving (i) international and (l) lifestyle
categories. 
