<P>
   Sergio Perez Erales, environmental secretary for Quintana Roo
state, accuses environmentalists of acting prematurely and
exaggerating the scope of development that will take place at
Xcacel. First, he said, developers must obtain permits from
Mexico's National Ecology Institute and finish environmental impact
studies that show plans comply with some degree of conservation
required on this coast.
</P>
<P>
   Because of a requirement to protect turtles, Perez Erales said,
Quintana Roo governor Maria Villanueva declared a portion of Xcacel
a state turtle reserve.
</P>
<P>
   But the area only extends 100 meters, or 110 yards, from the
water line, an amount that is ``just a Band-Aid,'' said Bowen.
``Protect a narrow strip of the beach is just not going to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Whispering in the dark, while a turtle laid her eggs at Xcacel,
Zurita too scoffed at the idea: ``This is how they're protecting a
turtle sanctuary? With 100 meters?''
</P>
<P>
   Others said the governor's declaration had no scientific
foundation, and seemed to be more of a move to smooth controversy
over selling Xcacel. The beaches adjacent to Xcacel, which are also
important nesting grounds, have already been sold and are now under
development as part of Mexico's new tourist attraction, the ``Mayan
Riviera.''
</P>
<P>
   Juan Carlos Cantu of Mexico's Greenpeace chapter said, ``Sol
Melia doesn't care at all about turtle protection at Xcacel . . .
And the governor stuck it to everyone by selling the land.''
</P>
<P>
   Sol Melia, which has built large hotels and golf resorts in
Cancun and other parts of Mexico, failed to return requests for
interviews about Xcacel.
</P>
<P>
   Years before the sale, Mexican conservationists had tried to
persuade Mexico's federal government, which controlled the land
until 1993, to declare Xcacel in its entirety a federal reserve.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the turtles, the property is home to other
threatened wildlife and contains mangrove thickets protected under
federal law.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1980s, the Mayab Ecology Group based in Cancun began
to press the government to protect Xcacel. In 1994, it submitted an
official proposal with requisite scientific research. Only this
year did officials respond to the request, turning it down, shortly
before the state sold the land.
</P>
<P>
   Araceli Dominguez of the Mayab Ecology Group said, ``We're
asking for what, two kilometers of beach? Is that too much to
ask?''
</P>
<P>
   Conservationists are also upset because a 1995 land use plan for
the Quintana Roo coast, signed by the governor, included ``strong
recommendations'' to protect Xcacel.
</P>
<P>
   The land use plan included a clause recommending that if Xcacel
were to be sold, environmentalists should have the first right to
buy it.
</P>
<P>
   Conservationists say they were never given that chance. But it
may not be too late.
</P>
<P>
   ``If ecology groups are interested in buying the land, we'll
sell it to them,'' Perez Erala said. But they will have to come up
with the $11 million that Sol Melia paid for its share of the land,
plus additional funds for the remainder of the property if they
also want to buy that.
</P>
<P>
   He said Sol Melia is willing to cancel its Xcacel contract.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists say the $11 million figure is far more than
the price they've heard quoted for the land. Nevertheless, they
would like to buy Xcacel, but fear that raising so much money on
short notice would be difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be really tough, unless they can find someone like
Ted Turner,'' Bowen said. ``By the time they raise the money, those
turtles could be a distant memory.''
</P>
<P>
   Mexican environmentalists are also weighing legal options here,
but worry there are few left before construction starts.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, Mexico banned molestation of all sea turtles, and in a
gesture of good will, it hosted the first two meetings for the
establishment of the Inter-American Convention for the Protection
and Conservation of Sea Turtles. Mexico hasn't signed the accord
yet, however.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Sol Melia has put up a sign at the entrance to
the beach declaring it ``private property'' and advertising a
``tourist development.''
</P>
<P>
   Visitors can ask a guard to allow them onto the beach, and
student volunteers still camp there at night, transplanting eggs to
protected nesting areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone always says, 'Nothing will happen when hotels are
built.' But it's not true,'' said Daphne Gadar, a Mexico City
biology student.
</P>
<P>
   ``I imagine tourists like to come to a place like this now,''
she said, swinging in a hammock, ``with clean water, no big hotels.
Mexico is still exotic in that way, but we're fast doing away with
it.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
