<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 15:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4062 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FANCY-FOOD-SHOW-ART-N     06-30 0588
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FANCY-FOOD-SHOW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESTAURANTS STAKE OUT YOUR PANTRY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.J., Texas)   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-1243 or 1927.)  
 (af)  
 By FLORENCE FABRICANT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Chefs may want to get you into their restaurants, but
now more than ever, they have their eye on your pantry shelf as
well.
</P>
<P>
   The chefs, and their product lines, were out in force at this
year's Fancy Food Show, the annual trade show that began Sunday at
the Jacob K. Javits Convention Center and ends Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Five years ago, maybe there were five chefs exhibiting
products,'' said Ronald Tanner, the spokesman for the National
Association for the Specialty Food Trade. ``This year there are
close to 100.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the new faces in chef's whites dishing out samples to
buyers, store owners and others was Lidia Bastianich of Felidia,
Becco and Frico Bar in Manhattan, who was introducing a line of
three tomato-based pasta sauces being made under her name by
Colavita.
</P>
<P>
   Alain Rondelli, the French chef who closed his San Francisco
restaurant a few months ago to devote his time to developing a line
of products, was there, too. He has concentrated on a category
that's become popular among chefs, the cooking sauce; his are
champagne-based, and they come in seven flavors.
</P>
<P>
   Jody Denton and Marc Valiani of Lulu's in San Francisco were
handing out little cups with samples of their new condiments to
anyone who stopped at their booth.
</P>
<P>
   With its fig, currant and black cherry balsamic vinegars, the
Lulu's line was as trendy as anything in the show, except perhaps
seasoned dipping oils for bread: the Javits Center was awash in
them. And tangerine oils _ there were at least four at different
booths. But nothing a chef could concoct was as weird as seeing
samples of chocolate cheese alongside the smoked fish at the Royal
Baltic Smoked Fish booth.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Trotter of Charlie Trotter in Chicago was another chef
whose foods, including salad dressings like black olive-caper
vinaigrette and dessert sauces like cinnamon-butterscotch, were
being introduced.
</P>
<P>
   Products like these _ the salad dressings, marinades, sauces,
oils, vinegars and dessert toppings _ are easy for home cooks to
use and add a touch of dining-out glamour.
</P>
<P>
   David Burke, the chef and co-owner of Park Avenue Cafe in
Manhattan and Chicago, who has been at the show in previous years
with the spiced salmon products he developed for Perona Farms in
Andover, N.J., was dishing up slices of duck meatloaf, a new
product that he serves in the restaurant and which is now being
made for retail sale by D'Artagnan.
</P>
<P>
   It's a lucrative niche. ``Chefs are where it's at,'' said
Michael Shine, the president of the Shine Companies in Spring,
Texas, which is making products like Dean Fearing's Caesar Salad
Diablo dressing from the Mansion on Turtle Creek in Dallas. ``As
this industry grows, you need something to set a product apart.
Something that was Mama's recipe is not enough anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   From the chef's point of view, being in business with an
experienced food producer that can take care of the technical side,
the marketing and the distribution is a big plus. A few chefs, like
Rondelli, are putting up their own money for these ventures, but
most have licensing agreements with food producers and receive
royalties.
</P>
<P>
   As Burke put it, ``It doesn't cost me a thing, except some time,
to do this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-98 1551EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980630.0158 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 15:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4064 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOMERS01-COX     06-30 0942
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOMERS01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HEALTH EQUALS WEALTH FOR AGING BOOMERS
 &HT;    570&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By BOB DART and LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For Baby Boomers entering their 50s, staying
healthy may be the key to being wealthy.
</P>
<P>
   For people between the ages of 51 and 61, ``health shocks'' such
as cancer and heart attacks are increasingly frequent, and often
determine whether a family accumulates wealth or depletes it, said
James P. Smith, senior economist and chairman of labor markets and
demographic studies for the RAND Corp., an independent research
group.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said his research showed the loss of wealth is not
necessarily due to out-of-pocket payment of medical bills, but was
more closely tied to loss of income and the opportunity to invest
those earnings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Health insurance is not synonymous with wealth insurance,''
said Smith, summing up his findings of a six-year study of health
and wealth of middle-aged Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Smith was among several researchers who took part Tuesday in a
seminar on the economics of aging sponsored by the National
Institute on Aging, an agency of the U.S. Department of Health and
Human Services.
</P>
<P>
   Smith's findings are based on an ongoing study of 10,236
Americans born between 1931 and 1941 who were interviewed first in
1992-1993 and at two-year intervals since then.
</P>
<P>
   Respondents who describe themselves as having excellent health
have two and a half times as much household income and five times
as much household wealth as respondents who describe their health
as poor, the study found. Wealth includes equity in homes,
financial assets and value of businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Smith cautioned that the relationship between health and wealth
is complicated.
</P>
<P>
   Wealth often has a direct influence on health, he acknowledged.
``Good health is an outcome that people desire, and higher wealth
or income enables them to purchase more of it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   However, he said health often has an equally direct influence on
wealth _ especially as people reach middle age and increasingly
experience ``new health events'' such as high blood pressure. His
research found that this deterioration has ``quantitatively large
effects on wealth accumulation among those in their 50s.''
</P>
<P>
   One illustration is that middle-income earners have dramatic
differences in accumulated wealth despite having had roughly equal
paychecks. The wealthy were more like to have enjoyed good health
than those who had accumulated little.
</P>
<P>
   While paying medical bills does cut into wealth accumulation,
with the prevalence of health insurance this expense is not as
devastating as might be imagined, said Smith.
</P>
<P>
   ``More directly, healthier people may be able to work more,
leading to higher earnings,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The study found respondents often hit with ``health shocks'' in
their 50s. During a four-year period, one third were hospitalized
at least once and 5 percent of those spent at least a month in the
hospital. About one in every eight experienced at least one
``severe new onset'' of cancer, heart disease, stroke or lung
disease.
</P>
<P>
   While people generally know their health may deteriorate as they
age, ``the actual realization, especially its timing, may be
unanticipated,'' said Smith.
</P>
<P>
   With the oldest of the Baby Boomers celebrating their 52d
birthdays this year, and millions more marching into their 50s
every year for the next decade, Smith said more attention should be
paid to the generation's links between health and wealth.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Boomers who plan to retire early need to substantially increase
their savings, said Olivia S. Mitchell, executive director of the
Pension Research Council at the University of Pennsylvania's
Wharton School, who also spoke at the conference.
</P>
<P>
   Private savings among American families is at an all-time low,
and most people will not be able to sustain a lifestyle that
extends beyond two decades of retirement, Mitchell said.
</P>
<P>
   The average couple in which at least one spouse falls in the
51-61 age bracket will need to increase their savings by 16 percent
_ beyond such devices as their present investment and pension
accounts such as 401(k) tax-deferred retirement plans _ to maintain
their pre-retirement lifestyle if they retire at age 62. By
remaining in the work force an additional three years, they could
cut their additional savings in half to just over 7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, high-income earners will have to increase their
savings the most to keep up with their pre-retirement consumption.
</P>
<P>
   A couple with earnings of nearly $12,000 a year would have to
increase savings 6 percent to retire at 62 without a diminution in
consumption, and could even reduce savings nearly 5 percent if they
continued working until 65. But the average couple with earnings of
$102,000 would have to increase their savings nearly 24 percent to
retire at 62, and 16.5 percent to retire at 65.
</P>
<P>
   The analysis, based on a study of 12,000 families in 1992,
assumed that the median household wealth _ including the value of
the home and estimated pension and Social Security benefits _ was
$383,000 for those retiring at age 62 and $420,000 for those
retiring at 65.
</P>
<P>
   While those figures apply to the average family, not every
family meets the prescription for savings, Mitchell said. Nearly a
third of those planning to retire at 62, and 40 percent of those
planning to retire at 65, do not need to increase their current
savings rate to retain their same standard of living.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
