<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980630.0160 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 16:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4078 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WINE-TALK-NYT &LR;      06-30 0998
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUIDED TOURS OF SONOMA, NAPA AND BEYOND 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By FRANK J. PRIAL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two guidebooks designed to make traveling in the California wine
country more fun have just been published. They're both good, even
though neither one offers help on the single most pressing issue
facing the Napa County visitor: How in blazes do you make a
left-hand turn coming out of a winery along Route 29?
</P>
<P>
   Route 29 is the main drag through the Napa Valley. From the Napa
city line to the outskirts of Calistoga, from May to October, from
dawn (almost) to dusk, the traffic creeps past the wineries in a
solid line, defying anyone to break into it. Don't be misled;
Californians are friendly folk, but not when they're in their cars.
They won't hurt you, but they may very well cause you to be late
for lunch at Mustards or Tra Vigne. (Read on for a traffic tip you
won't find in these books.)
</P>
<P>
   Napa and Sonoma Counties, the best-known California wine
regions, are hardly twins, as the Napa and Sonoma Book (Berkshire
House, $17.95) points out. Napa is formal, tony and chic; Sonomo is
laid-back, warm hearted and friendly.
</P>
<P>
   Sonomans never tire of pointing out that they are earthy and
unpretentious, while Napans are socialites who wear designer
clothes. The analogy is sometimes made to two famous regions in
France: that Sonomans are the Burgundians of California, and the
Napa residents are the Bordelais.
</P>
<P>
   For the visitor intent on seeing, and tasting, as much as
possible, the Wine Country Guide to California (Wine Spectator
Magazine, $6.95) is a must, as it covers the entire state.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors to Mendocino, for example, can take in wineries like
Navarro and Roederer Estate, with perhaps a side trip to the wild
Mendocino coast. Or they might want to explore Lake County to visit
Lily Langtry's home at the immense Guenoc Winery estate.
</P>
<P>
   They might choose to zip across the Bay Bridge from San
Francisco to taste some zinfandels at Rosenblum Cellars in Alameda,
or go south to check out Ridge Vineyards high in the Santa Cruz
Mountains at Cupertino.
</P>
<P>
   The Wine Country Guide will get them there. The book is divided
into nine wine regions, with listings of wineries, restaurants,
lodgings, events and diversions that may include beaches, parks,
golf courses, farm tours and balloon trips.
</P>
<P>
   The winery listings include addresses and phone numbers, tour
hours, the kinds of wines offered and tasting charges.
</P>
<P>
   Particularly interesting wineries are designated ``Top Stops''
and singled out with photographs. Some of them in Napa are Clos
Pegase, Domaine Chandon, and Niebaum-Coppola. In Sonoma, Martini &AMP;
Prati and Sam Sebastiani's Viansa Winery and Italian Market Place
are among those singled out.
</P>
<P>
   There is also the Gloria Ferrer Champagne Caves, an underground
winery and art museum, as well as the Jordan Winery, which is a
reproduction of a Bordeaux chateau; an appointment is needed to
visit it.
</P>
<P>
   Not all the Top Stops are well-known. Ever heard of the Cilurzo
Vineyard and Winery in Temecula, south of Los Angeles? Or Chatom
Vineyards in Douglas Flat, in the Sierra foothills? This is a
wine-producing region in the mountainous eastern part of the state,
closer to Nevada than to the Pacific Ocean. Regulars there say it
resembles the Napa Valley 30 years ago in its simplicity and rural
charm.
</P>
<P>
   Detailed fold-out winery maps are included for Sonoma and Napa,
where, let's face it, most of the action is. Most of the better
restaurants are covered, with concise reviews and tips on what to
eat and what to wear. Not covered is the problem of getting a table
in the most popular eateries during the peak tourist season.
</P>
<P>
   What can be more depressing than having someone say, ``We can
take you Tuesday night'' when you will be flying home on Sunday?
</P>
<P>
   The Napa and Sonoma Book, by Tim Fish and Peg Melnik, both local
authors, has much of the same data as in the Wine Country Guide
sections on those two counties _ and much more. It's a good book
for the casual visitor, and a better book for anyone who plans to
stay around Napa and Sonoma for a while. Even travelers on their
3rd, 4th or 20th trip to the region will find valuable tips.
</P>
<P>
   There are long sections on the history of the region, an
excellent treatise on architecture, and sections on local
microbreweries, sports and spas. The wineries are described in some
detail, often with descriptions of the wines and advice on which
ones to buy.
</P>
<P>
   There is plenty of history, good shopping tips for most cities
and towns, and solid sections on local arts and culture.
</P>
<P>
   There is helpful advice on such fundamental things as to how to
get to the wine country and when to go. (not on weekends). The
authors recommend having a designated driver but, unless you can
find a teetotaller, it's cruel to ask someone to tour the wineries
with you and not drink anything. The trick is to visit no more than
three wineries in a day and go easy on the wine samples.
</P>
<P>
   Neither book touches on the tackiness that now blights so many
wineries, which is more prevalent in Napa because it is more highly
developed commercially.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the wineries probably make almost as much money from
T-shirts, baseball caps and ugly souvenirs as they do from wine.
But then these days, Napa and Sonoma counties welcome some eight
million visitors a year; they can't all be interested in cabernet
sauvignon.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there are still lots of small wineries where you can
talk to the owner, try his wines and pet his dog. But you have to
know where you want to go and you must call in advance. Both of
these guides can help you find those places.
</P>
<P>
   As for negotiating Route 29: if you are driving up from the Bay
Area, visit only wineries on the east side of the road as you come
into the valley and wineries on the west side on your way back.
Turn around up past Calistoga, where the traffic thins out, and
where the valley gets rural again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-98 1600EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980630.0161 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 16:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4086 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WINE-TALK-ART-NYT &LR;      06-30 1021
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-TALK-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUIDED TOURS OF SONOMA, NAPA AND BEYOND 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (af)  
 By FRANK J. PRIAL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
