</P>
<P>
   The Napa and Sonoma Book, by Tim Fish and Peg Melnik, both local
authors, has much of the same data as in the Wine Country Guide
sections on those two counties _ and much more. It's a good book
for the casual visitor, and a better book for anyone who plans to
stay around Napa and Sonoma for a while. Even travelers on their
3rd, 4th or 20th trip to the region will find valuable tips.
</P>
<P>
   There are long sections on the history of the region, an
excellent treatise on architecture, and sections on local
microbreweries, sports and spas. The wineries are described in some
detail, often with descriptions of the wines and advice on which
ones to buy.
</P>
<P>
   There is plenty of history, good shopping tips for most cities
and towns, and solid sections on local arts and culture.
</P>
<P>
   There is helpful advice on such fundamental things as to how to
get to the wine country and when to go. (not on weekends). The
authors recommend having a designated driver but, unless you can
find a teetotaller, it's cruel to ask someone to tour the wineries
with you and not drink anything. The trick is to visit no more than
three wineries in a day and go easy on the wine samples.
</P>
<P>
   Neither book touches on the tackiness that now blights so many
wineries, which is more prevalent in Napa because it is more highly
developed commercially.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the wineries probably make almost as much money from
T-shirts, baseball caps and ugly souvenirs as they do from wine.
But then these days, Napa and Sonoma counties welcome some eight
million visitors a year; they can't all be interested in cabernet
sauvignon.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there are still lots of small wineries where you can
talk to the owner, try his wines and pet his dog. But you have to
know where you want to go and you must call in advance. Both of
these guides can help you find those places.
</P>
<P>
   As for negotiating Route 29: if you are driving up from the Bay
Area, visit only wineries on the east side of the road as you come
into the valley and wineries on the west side on your way back.
Turn around up past Calistoga, where the traffic thins out, and
where the valley gets rural again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
