<HEADER>
A4087 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-DOG-RESTAURANTS-AR     06-30 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DOG-RESTAURANTS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE DOGS ARE COMFORTABLE DINING WITH THEIR MASTERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
 (JT)  
 By MOLLY O'NEILL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For dog owners and their pets in search of a dinner
out together, New York can be a town without pity. Yet with the
city's dog population on the increase, man, dog and restaurant seem
to be entering a new era of accommodation.
</P>
<P>
   For months, for instance, the canine cognescenti have eagerly
anticipated the opening of the Fido Cafe and Lounge, the first
indoor place in the city constructed to accommodate people and
their pets. In the New York Dog Spa on West 18th Street, the Fido
Cafe is set to begin serving espresso-bar fare and dog snacks later
this month.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, those seeking quality time _ as well as drinks or
dinner _ with their pets are settling in restaurants with outdoor
seating. Technically, outdoor cafes where no cooking is taking
place are the sole preserve for dining a la dog in New York City,
said Sandy Mullen, a spokeswoman for the city's department of
health. (Fido can serve dogs because it has discrete dining and
cooking areas.)
</P>
<P>
   Many outdoor spots now cater to basic canine needs and more
places are offering elaborate dog amenities like fanciful water
bowls and biscuits. Some places, like the Time Cafe, will
cheerfully serve dogs a steak. Others, like Cafe Giardinetto in
Murray Hill, have entire dog menus featuring minced turkey breast,
chopped beef and an antipasti platter.
</P>
<P>
   But special menus aside, cooks in even the finest restaurants in
have become accustomed to making dinner for dogs. At Verbena on
Irving Place, Diane Forley says her employees are trained to ``be
as hospitable to pets as they are to their owners.'' Regulars
include a fox terrier, a French bulldog and a Jack Russell, who
dines on hanger steak, rare, served cut into bite-size pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Waiters at restaurants all over town have become used to dodging
tails that stick out from under tables and pointing out
dog-appropriate dishes on their menus. (``They like our burgers,''
advised a waiter at the Coconut Grill on the Upper East Side.
``Medium-rare.'')
</P>
<P>
   Busboys fill water bowls as routinely as water glasses. (``No
one should go thirsty on a hot summer night,'' said Mark Oram, the
co-owner of the Chelsea Lobster Company. It has just upgraded its
dog serving ware from aluminum takeout containers to vintage dog
bowls from Fishes Eddy.)
</P>
<P>
   The result? A doggie cafe society rivaling that of Paris, where
city regulations have never excluded Fifi from joining her master
at the table _ inside or out.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason is dogs are good business: an enormous number
of people own dogs, and they tend to return to dog-friendly
restaurants. Although the number of licensed dogs throughout the
city has remained stable at 120,000 for the past five years, said
Ms. Mullen of the Department of Health, the agency estimates that
only one in three dogs is actually licensed. And based on the
increased numbers in city dog-runs, some say that the longstanding
estimate of 300,000 licensed and unlicensed dogs has nearly doubled
in the past five years.
</P>
<P>
   That's a lot potential customers, four-legged and otherwise.
Dogs remember places where they've been spoiled. More than one dog
has lead its owner to dinner.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent evening on Irving Place, for instance, Karen Kopta,
a public relations consultant, was tugged toward Picnic by Lulu,
her seven-and-a-half pound Yorkshire Terrier.
</P>
<P>
   ``We eat out twice a day,'' Ms. Kopta said. ``Picnic is Lu's
favorite. They have a basket of dog biscuits and a bowl of fresh
ice water by the front door.''
</P>
<P>
   Other dog owners are loathe to leave their pets home alone at
night, particularly if they've been there all day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Meal time is quality time and I want to spend all the quality
time I have with Sadie,'' said Rob Abner, the publisher of DGNY, a
bimonthly guide to owning a dog in New York City. Most evenings
find Abner appraising menus for Sadie, his beagle, as a parent
would peruse a menu on behalf of a young child.
</P>
<P>
   ``She loves the negimaki at Sushi Generation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still others deploy their pets as social emblem. ``A dainty dog
like Isabelle is one thing,'' said a woman lunching at the cafe
outside of Le Cirque 2000 with a tiny, be-ribboned teacup poodle
nestled in her lap. Offering the dog a tiny forkful of her poached
chicken, she added, ``Those big uncouth things are another
matter.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
