<HEADLINE>
SUMMER TRAVEL HOT SPOTS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature culled from The
New York Times Syndicate's ``Way To Go!'' travel package _ the rate
is not prohibitive _ contact one of the following sales
representatives:
 &HT;    (_ U.S. and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444.
 &HT;    (_ Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (_ Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles at (310)
996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ---------------------FREE ART!---------------------
 &HT;    ONE COLOR SLIDE is available by mail (or overnight delivery,
using your FedEx or Airborne delivery number) AT NO EXTRA CHARGE to
purchasers of this article. Please specify that you want the art
when you order the article.
 &HT;    ---------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (Our sales staff also has information on how to subscribe to
``WAY TO GO,'' a versatile package of six travel stories a week,
including Q&AMP;A travel tips and ``The Mature Traveler'' column.
Sources include The New York Times Sunday travel section and
leading travel writers.)
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``t'' travel news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By EVERETT POTTER 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Planning to get away this summer? Then act fast. This summer is
promising to be the biggest travel season ever, according to a poll
released by ASTA (American Society of Travel Agents) and Fodor's
Travel Publications on May 22.
 &HT;    The ASTA/Fodor's Annual Summer Hot Spots Survey is the result of
a poll of some of ASTA's 27,000 travel agents. They were asked to
name the top five domestic city destinations they have been booking
for this summer. In descending order: Orlando, Las Vegas, San
Francisco, Los Angeles and New York.
 &HT;    ``Since this is a summer survey, it's really a byword for family
travel,'' James Ashurt, manager of communications for ASTA,
explains.
 &HT;    Orlando was far and away No. 1 because of Disney's continued and
unsurpassed reign as the most popular vacation destination in
America.
 &HT;    There's also the surge of interest in Disney's new ``Animal
Kingdom'' attraction, according to ASTA.
 &HT;    But surprisingly, value also plays a role when American
travelers choose Orlando as a vacation spot. In a separate survey
in which ASTA travel agents were asked about the destinations they
book for the value-conscious consumer, Orlando ranked No. 2 after
Cancun. The value is there because of the wide variety of
affordable air/hotel packages to the area and the selection of room
prices for every pocket.
 &HT;    Las Vegas ranked second. But while gaming enthusiasts will
always come to the Nevada city, the high ranking doesn't
necessarily reflect a huge influx of gamblers.
 &HT;    Las Vegas has become firmly established as a major family
destination, with a variety of packages for parents traveling with
their children. It's so affordable that it ranked third, after
Orlando, in ASTA's poll of destinations for value-conscious
travelers.
 &HT;    The next three cities were ranked closely together. San
Francisco ranked third, attracting visitors because of its scenic
beauty and laid-back lifestyle.
 &HT;    Los Angeles was fourth and Hollywood played a major role in its
ranking. The chance to visit studio lots and step into the
epicenter of the entertainment business is a major draw. So are the
area's fabled beaches.
 &HT;    New York, revitalized, booming and welcoming, was ranked fifth
in popularity for summer travelers. That's due to a reinvigorated
Broadway, with record-breaking productions of such shows as ``The
Lion King'' and ``Ragtime.''
 &HT;    The restaurant scene, from trendy places such as Balthazar to
the latest East Village sushi bar, has never been hotter. And the
civic pride of New Yorkers has never been greater or more
contagious.
 &HT;    The other cities in the ranking, in descending order, were
Seattle, San Diego and Washington, D.C., in a tie for seventh,
followed by Boston and Phoenix.
 &HT;    In terms of international travel, ASTA agents ranked the
following destinations. London was first, followed by Paris, Rome,
Cancun, Frankfurt, Amsterdam, Madrid, Dublin, Vancouver and Athens.
 &HT;    What the poll really means is that there has already been
significant demand for these destinations. With the American
economy booming, domestic hotel rooms will be very hard to find
this summer, especially in New York and San Francisco. Planning
ahead and booking as soon as possible are key to getting a
reasonably good deal on a vacation.
 &HT;    For those who like to do it themselves, the Web is a viable
option. And hotel brokers, such as Quikbook (381 Park Avenue South,
New York, N.Y. 10016; 800-789-9887; www.quikbook.com), Express
Reservations (3825 Iris Ave., Boulder, Colo. 80301; 800-356-1123;
www.express-res.com) and Hotel Reservations Network (8140 Walnut
Hill Lane, Suite 203, Dallas, Texas 75231; 800-96-HOTEL;
www.180096hotel.com) can often provide 20 percent or more off the
cost of a domestic hotel room.
 &HT;    But ASTA, naturally enough, advocates using a travel agent _
someone who has essential travel information at their fingertips,
someone who knows which hotels are likely to have space and a
reasonable room rate. And agents can obtain some of the best prices
around for airfare and car rentals.
 &HT;    ``The Web is an excellent resource and there's lot of
information,'' Ashurst says. ``But that's part of the problem. Not
everyone is technically savvy enough to use it properly. You're not
getting professional advice or experience when you do. There's no
personal insight. And people are busy, they don't have the time to
do what it takes to get the information. The time factor doesn't
get included in the equation about whether the Web is better than a
travel agent.''
 &HT;    Ashurst points out, however, that an increasing number of travel
agents are using the Web themselves, both for communication
purposes and to research on behalf of their clients. And this
research will cost you. The days when an agent gave information
away for free are fast disappearing.
 &HT;    ``You pay a travel agent as you would pay any other
professional,'' Ashurst explains.
 &HT;    It's estimated that about 70 percent of ASTA's members are
either charging fees or are planning to charge fees. Those fees
vary widely, but they might run a consumer between $5 and $15 per
airline ticket. But research fees might be waived or deducted from
the cost of a vacation.
 &HT;    To find the nearest ASTA travel agent, contact ASTA at 1101 King
St., Alexandria, VA 22314; 800-965-ASTA.
