<SLUG> BC-NY-SENATE-DEBATE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN N.Y. DEMOCRATIC PRIMARY, INCUMBENT IS THE COMMON FOE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES M. ODATO  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOLTON LANDING, N.Y. _ One credits her mother. One points to
Ralph Nader. And the third praises two girls, his daughters.
</P>
<P>
   The three seasoned Democrats _ former Rep. Geraldine Ferraro,
New York City Public Advocate Mark Green and Rep. Charles Schumer _
may have distinguished themselves the most when answering the
question: ``Who has been the greatest influence on your life?''
</P>
<P>
   In the first public debate among the three, the Democrats had a
difficult time Monday separating themselves from one another.
Except for one skirmish between Green and Ferraro over accepting
tobacco money, the three candidates agreed on a key point: that
Republican Sen. Alfonse D'Amato must go so that his replacement can
address restoring money for education and improving job growth.
</P>
<P>
   Green, a former Nader associate, added the reform of health
maintenance organizations, and his competitors didn't put him down
for it.
</P>
<P>
   With a bit of sniping at one another, the debaters, hitting on
topics put to them before the New York State Publishers'
Association, tended to direct responses away from themselves,
largely at the urging of Schumer, to attack the Republican
incumbent.
</P>
<P>
   They described D'Amato as untrustworthy and an election-year
liberal, themes that have become common among the primary
contestants.
</P>
<P>
   Green strayed from that script, criticizing Ferraro for taking a
$20,000 speaking fee from a leading cigarette maker, the Philip
Morris Cos., last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope she would rethink that honorarium from Philip Morris
and give it back,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ferraro shot back that Green has taken $250 from a Philip Morris
executive _ in 1993 _ and $3,000 from a cigar company executive and
his wife last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no intention of giving that money back,'' Ferraro said.
``I paid taxes on it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue is Al D'Amato's record on tobacco. He receives huge
amounts and he's been one of the biggest friends'' of the industry,
Schumer said. Except for D'Amato's election-year tough stand on
anti-tobacco issues, Schumer said, the senator has voted with the
industry.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Center for Responsive Politics in Washington,
D'Amato received $17,500 from tobacco interests in 1997 and 1998,
fourth most among senators.
</P>
<P>
   On a related measure, Green's campaign said it would not return
money from Howard Lazar, one of three construction company
executives convicted in a bid-rigging and kickback scheme in New
York City.
</P>
<P>
   Green said the $1,500 was tied to his New York City advocate
campaign, and that campaign is closed. He said such sums couldn't
influence him even if he had recognized Lazar's name among the
25,000 who have contributed to his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer's office said the congressman would return $1,500 sent
to him in 1995 and 1997 from Lazar, of Lehr Construction Co.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for D'Amato, who received $2,200 from Lazar and $500
from his wife, said the senator was writing a check for $2,700 to
the Long Island Breast Cancer Coalition.
</P>
<P>
   As for the D'Amato-bashing at the debate, the spokesman, Harvey
Valentine, declined to speak specifically about tobacco votes.
``It's unfortunate they would rather throw mud than talk about
their own records,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the Democrats did discuss their records in an attempt to
look better than the competition.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer, who called his daughters, ages 13 and 9, the biggest
influences on his life, said his career as the congressman who
wrote the Brady anti-gun legislation and pushed for a bill that put
more police officers on the streets proves he's the top candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Green, crediting Nader for teaching the fundamentals of his
two-decade-plus career as a consumer advocate, said he could fill
pot holes and create policy.
</P>
<P>
   And Ferraro, focusing on her roles as teacher, prosecutor,
mother and congresswoman, said her mother instilled in her the
importance of education.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-98 1625EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
