u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-CROATIA-     06-30 0834
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-CROATIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CROATIA DEFEATS ROMANIA 1-0, ON SECOND PENALTY KICK  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BORDEAUX, France _ Croatia does not occupy much space on the map
of Europe. It is a scenic sliver of land on the Dalmatian coast
with the capital Zagreb for a hub. But Croatia is big enough to
provide a homeland to one of the planet's better soccer teams, and
Tuesday that team advanced to the quarterfinals in its first World
Cup with a 1-0 victory over Romania that was more emotional than
sensational.
</P>
<P>
   The lone goal of the afternoon came on a penalty kick from Davor
Suker in the second minute of injury time in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never has a country as small as Croatia come up with a result
like we did today,'' said Croatian coach Miroslav Blazevic, whose
team will face Germany in the quarterfinals on Saturday in Lyon.
</P>
<P>
   Sport and marketing have become inextricably intertwined in this
bottom- line era, but nations have been using sport as a marketing
tool for centuries, and Croatia, a country of approximately 4.7
million that split from Yugoslavia seven years ago, has no shortage
of athletic ambassadors.
</P>
<P>
   It won the gold medal in team handball at the 1996 Summer
Olympics; its basketball players Toni Kukoc and Dino Radja have
played in the NBA. Tennis player Iva Majoli won the French Open,
and Goran Ivanisevic already would have won Wimbledon if his powers
of concentration had even approached the power of his serve.
</P>
<P>
   Now, two years after reaching the quarterfinals of the European
championships, it is the soccer team's turn to take another star
turn, and Blazevic, the bespectacled, chain-smoking friend of
Croatian president Franjo Tudjman, clearly was delighted to have
excellent news to report.
</P>
<P>
   ``It isn't just sport; there are political repercussions, too,''
he said. ''Before this match, maybe five percent of the people knew
Croatia. Now, maybe 15 percent know. So of course that is important
to our country.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been a World Cup of many matches and few surprises: the
traditional soccer powers have had their way with the parvenues.
Croatia does not quite qualify as an underdog _ not with players
like Suker, captain Zvonimir Boban and Robert Jarni _ but it is one
of two quarterfinalists, along with Denmark, who have had at least
a chuckle at the expense of the pecking order.
</P>
<P>
   Before this event began, the Yugoslavs were considered the
bigger threat from the Balkans, and Croatia's chances were hurt
further by a knee injury to star striker Alen Boksic. But Croatia
still has Suker, its other world-class striker who is fresh and in
fine fettle after spending much of last season on the bench at Real
Madrid. When Suker got his chance to take a penalty kick, he did
not hit the crossbar as his former Yugoslav teammate Predrag
Mijatovic did in Yugoslavia's 2-1 loss to the Netherlands on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had expected to go on holiday to the Adriatic coast, but now
I want to stay in France as long as possible,'' the 30-year-old
Suker said.
</P>
<P>
   Suker helped earn the penalty kick by letting a pass slip
through his legs to teammate Aljosa Asanovic, who was being marked
in the penalty area by Romanian midfielder Gabriel Popescu. There
was contact. Asanovic tumbled to the grass, and referee Javier
Alberto Castrilli of Argentina did not hesitate. Suker calmly put
the ball in the lower right corner of the goal. But his celebration
was cut short because Boban had run into the box too early. The
kick had to be retaken. The 30-year-old Suker simply recreated his
goal, putting the ball past goalkeeper Bogdan Stelea in the same
corner.
</P>
<P>
   Stelea would not be beaten again, and if not for his fine play,
he and his oddly muted teammates would have likely lost by more
than one goal. The Romanians and their creative captain Gheorge
Hagi, better known as ``the Maradona of the Carpathians,'' were
surprise quarterfinalists in the last World Cup, and with a mix of
veterans like Hagi and newcomers like striker Adrian Ilie, the team
had feuded frequently but not lost an official match in nearly two
years. But Tuesday, Romania often looked unsettled, even
unenthusiastic.
</P>
<P>
   After dying their hair yellow after defeating England in their
second group match, they stopped shining on the field, drawing with
Tunisia and losing to Croatia. When the Hagi era ended, Hagi was no
longer on the field, having been replaced in the 57th minute with
what he explained was a sore groin. While it is unclear whether
Hagi, now 32, has really played his last for Romania, Iordanescu,
the army general with the tactical mind, already has signed a
contract to coach Greece.
</P>
<P>
   Croatia now heads for Lyon and a rematch with the German team
that defeated them at the last European championship. ``We will do
all we can to get our revenge,'' Blazevic said. ``The Germans are
our friends, and as everyone knows, there is no greater pleasure in
sport than to beat your friends.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
