<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 16:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4177 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT     06-30 0809
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
Page 1, Wednesday, July 1. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (212-556-1927).
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-CLINTON (Shanghai) _ Talk radio, in China, is still a
relatively new form of communication. Callers are generally polite,
not confrontational. And the idea of trying anything as risque as
voicing a contrary political opinion on the air is altogether
foreign, or maybe the vigilant screeners just make it seem that
way. So when President Clinton turned up on Tuesday at the studio
of Shanghai Radio 990 to make his first-ever appearance on a talk
radio show outside the United States, it may have caused great
excitement among callers but it yielded a decidedly benign, some
would say bland, set of questions and answers for listeners. By
Seth Faison.
</P>
<P>
   HONGKONG-ANNIVERSARY (Hong Kong) _ His hometown is marking the
first anniversary of its return to China on July 1, but Loon
Wai-ting is in no mood to celebrate. Loon has spent the year
without a job. ``When the British were here, there was a lot of
business in Hong Kong,'' he said. Of course, Britain's exit from
Hong Kong has had little to do with the economic downturn of its
former colony, which sits at the crossroads of a becalmed Asia and
has suffered along with its neighbors. But Loon speaks for many
Hong Kong people, who are being ravaged by rising unemployment, a
20 percent drop in the stock market, and a 40 percent decline in
the property market. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   POPE-LETTER (Rome) _ Pope John Paul II, in an apostolic letter,
on Tuesday enshrined into church law an oath obliging theologians
to accept Catholic teachings such as bans on women priests,
contraception, and euthanasia. By Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   IRAN-TRIAL (Tehran, Iran) _ In a huge, woodpaneled courtroom
under the heat and glare of television klieg lights, the mayor of
Tehran is struggling to keep his job, clear his name, and justify
the way he does business. Gholamhussein Karbaschi, the 45-year-old
former cleric who has run Iran's sprawling capital for the past
eight years, is on trial, accused of embezzling nearly $5 million,
receiving bribes, influence peddling, financing political
campaigns, and misusing official funds, charges that could land him
in prison for an unspecified length of time if he is convicted. By
Elaine Sciolino.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-ATTACK (undated) _ An American F-16 attacked an Iraqi
anti-aircraft battery on Tuesday after Iraqi forces aimed radar at
a squadron of British jets routinely patroling the ``no flight''
zone over southern Iraq, officials here said. The American F-16,
accompanying the British squadron, fired a single high-speed,
anti-radar missile, or HARM, at the Iraqi battery north of Basra,
but the missile missed, officials said. Iraq's official news agency
said the missile struck a drinking-water reservoir and accused the
United States of ``unjustified aggression.'' By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BLACKS-BIRTHS (Washington) _ The birth rate for unmarried black
women, long a focal point in the debate over the causes of poverty
among blacks, has reached its lowest point in 40 years, federal
health officials said on Tuesday. According to figures compiled by
the National Center for Health Statistics, there were 74.4 births
per 1,000 unmarried women in 1996, the last year for which complete
data are available. That rate is the lowest since 1969 when the
center first began separately recording the out-of-wedlock birth
rate for black women, and it is significantly below the peak of
90.7 per 1,000 unmarried black women reached in 1989. By Steven A.
Holmes.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL-GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   NY-WORKERS-PROTEST (New York) _ Tens of thousands of
construction workers held a boisterous rally in midtown Manhattan
on Tuesday that stopped traffic and degenerated into scuffling with
the police, as the demonstrators protested the Metropolitan
Transportation Authority's use of a non-union contractor.
Thirty-six people were arrested, and 24 were injured in the
scuffles, including 10 policemen. By Steven Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE-GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-AIDS-THERAPY (Geneva) _ Researchers raised the possibility
on Tuesday that treatment may someday eliminate the AIDS virus from
the body or lower it to a point where the immune system can
successfully control it. ``Eradication of HIV is not a myth,'' said
Dr. Roberto Siliciano of Johns Hopkins University at the 12th World
AIDS Conference. ``This is something we can do.'' By Lawrence K.
Altman.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   Nothing at this hour.
</P>
