<DOCNO> NYT19980630.0179 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 16:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4186 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-RADIO-HNS &LR;      06-30 0933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-RADIO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALLERS QUIZ CLINTON ON CHINESE RADIO SHOW 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CRAGG HINES 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHANGHAI, China _ The first call was from Mr. Fong in Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
   And host Zuo Anlong wanted to get right to the phones.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's do it,'' urged President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   You can take the politician a long way from home, but you can't
keep him away from his favorite communication devices.
</P>
<P>
   So Clinton settled in for an hour Tuesday at the studios of
Shanghai Radio 990, China's most powerful urban radio station, and
was a guest on one of the nation's most popular call-in shows. The
president chatted with folks who inquired about topics from
international policy to the U.S. leader's exercise regime.
</P>
<P>
   It was just midday, and Clinton had already held a 90-minute
discussion session at the Shanghai Library with community leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Both formats _ the more intellectual round-table and the
cut-and-thrust chat show _ have been staples in Clinton's public
communications repertoire for years. And he was clearly in his
element.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought the people were terrific,'' Clinton said after the
radio program. ``I thought they asked very good questions'' _ none
that touched on the sex and fund-raising scandals he left behind in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I have the same feeling I always have when we do this. I
wish we could do it for two more hours,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The traveling White House pointed to Clinton's radio appearance
as another sign of what it sees as new openness of China's
authoritarian Communist government.
</P>
<P>
   ``They could have made it enormously difficult'' for Clinton to
participate, McCurry said.
</P>
<P>
   Like all radio and television stations in China, Shanghai Radio
990 is government controlled.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was seated at a horseshoe-shaped desk, part of a small
studio in one of the dozens of modern skyscrapers that have sprung
up in Shanghai during the past 10 years. Although it was a steamy
summer day outside, the studio was well air-conditioned, and
Clinton kept his coat on as he donned headphones and leaned into
the bulbous microphone.
</P>
<P>
   Judging by host Zuo's comment, he was aware of the caller's
questions, but spokesman McCurry said he did not believe the
inquiries were planted.
</P>
<P>
   ``We asked only that they follow what their normal practice is
and try to encourage as diverse as possible a range of questions,''
McCurry said.
</P>
<P>
   Heavily into his policy-wonk mode, Clinton said he was most
impressed by the number of questions about education.
</P>
<P>
   And Clinton also liked the query from a caller (who identified
himself as ``just a regular citizen'' from Shanghai) who wondered
about the rapid increase in the private ownership of cars in the
city of 13 million residents and the growth of pollution.
</P>
<P>
   But the president initially let Shanghai Mayor Xu Kuangdi, who
accompanied him to the show, handle the inquiry on the air.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor backed a more lenient _ and less costly _ auto
licensing procedure but said that the city needed to insist on
lead-free gas and, by 2000, the use of exhaust purification
systems.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the broadcast, Clinton added that while in Beijing he
had expressed concern to Chinese President Jiang Zemin about the
need to guide the way in which China's economy and industry will
grow.
</P>
<P>
   ``My biggest concern is that China will get rich in exactly the
same way America got rich. But you have four times as many
people,'' Clinton told the caller, ``so no one will be able to
breathe, because the air pollution will be so bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Midway through the show, a Mr. Lee wondered how the president
kept his ``very nice figure'' _ surely a welcome description to
Clinton, who has fought to contain his ``junk food'' urges. The
caller wanted to know about the famous visitor's sports and
exercise program.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton told of playing basketball in college and jogging for
about 30 years, until his tumble in Florida two years ago hurt his
knee, which has him huffing and puffing on a Stairmaster.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I play golf,'' Clinton said. ``It's my favorite sport.
Even though it doesn't burn up a lot of calories, it makes my mind
calm. So I like it.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton passed up an opportunity to predict the winner of the
World Cup soccer competition (``the Brazilians are always hard to
beat``) but nattered on a bit about the politically charged match
the U.S. team lost to Iran.
</P>
<P>
   McCurry said the question exemplified a curiosity about Clinton
as a person.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's most likely is because there's not the same level of
attention to the personal side of leadership here in China that
there is the United States,'' McCurry said.
</P>
<P>
   As for the phenomenon of talk radio, U.S. programs ``are much
more prone to political discourse and political combat,'' McCurry
said. ``I don't think they've reached that point yet here in China
_ and maybe that's to their benefit.''
</P>
<P>
   The noon show is known as ``Citizens and Society.'' Host Zuo,
50ish, a former carpenter and electrician with Shanghai No. 1 Steel
Co., has been with the call-in program almost from its inception in
1992.
</P>
<P>
   Zuo is a peppy host who kept the show moving, but bore little
resemblance to the U.S. shock-jocks such as New York's Don Imus,
whom Clinton appeared with in 1992 during his bid for the
Democratic presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Zuo's program reaches about 70 percent of households in the
region _ meaning it has a potential audience of 10 million
listeners.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. diplomats said Clinton was the first non-Chinese guest on
the show.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
