<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 16:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4190 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YEAR-2000-HNS &LR;      06-30 0573
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YEAR-2000-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEADING BUSINESS GROUP CALLS YEAR 2000 COMPUTER PROBLEM `HUGE' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDs: FILED in ``w'' and ``f'' categories.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Calling the year 2000 computer glitch a potential
``disaster in the making,'' the National Association of
Manufacturers on Tuesday accused President Clinton and Vice
President Al Gore of failing to make the problem a national
priority.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Jasinowski, president of the NAM, a lobbying group
representing 14,000 businesses, said at a news conference here that
many U.S. companies will not have enough time to fix the computer
glitch by Jan. 1, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a large, global disaster in the making,'' he said of the
problem, which experts warn will occur when computers originally
programmed to recognize only the last two digits of a year will
fail or malfunction on that date because they will think the year
is 1900.
</P>
<P>
   Janinowski said Clinton and Gore, who often handles technology
issues for the administration, have neglected the issue and called
on them to increase public awareness of the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we, both in the business community and in the country as
a whole, need is leadership at the national level, and we simply
have not seen it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   However, administration officials said the president and vice
president were both concerned about the problem and were doing
everything possible to help solve it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an issue that the president holds as a high priority,
and he has stressed that to all the government agency heads,'' said
Jack Gribben, spokesman for the President's Council on the Year
2000 Problem.
</P>
<P>
   Janinowski also said the problem is being made worse by the
reluctance of most companies to disclose what progress they have
made toward solving it. He said the companies are holding back
information on their efforts because they fear it could be used
against them in future lawsuits stemming from the glitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Companies are worried that plaintiff lawyers will say, `Look,
the company's own information shows they weren't going to have this
problem fixed in time; so they must be guilty,''' Janinowski said.
</P>
<P>
   He called on Congress to enact legislation that offers companies
some legal protection in return for full disclosure of their
efforts to fix the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless we get complete information on where companies are at
on this problem, we as a country risk large-scale disruptions in
our economy,'' Janinowski said.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Robert Bennett, R-Utah, has introduced legislation that
would require companies to disclose what they have done to solve
the problem and what work they have left to do. But his bill does
not provide companies legal protection for giving the information.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``The millions of people out there putting their money into
these companies have a right to know if they're prepared or not,
and those companies have an obligation to tell them,'' Bennett said
at a Senate hearing last month.
</P>
<P>
   Janinowski's call for legal protection came on the heels of
recent announcements by computer consulting branches of the giant
accounting firms Deloitte &AMP; Touche and Price Waterhouse that they
will not accept new clients seeking Year 2000 help. Both units have
listed fear of lawsuits as a reason for scaling back their
operations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-98 1650EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
