<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 16:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4199 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SONOMA-WINES-ART-2TAK     06-30 1283
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SONOMA-WINES-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN NAPA'S SHADOW, SONOMA SHINES 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo will be sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (Eds: See related WINE-TALK article)  
 (af)  
 By MARIAN BURROS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SONOMA, Calif. _ Residents of Sonoma County will say this much
about their neighbor to the east: the Napa Valley is better known
and has better restaurants. That said, they wouldn't dream of
living there.
</P>
<P>
   They would have to give up their wild and spectacular coastline.
They would have to abandon their magnificent fruits and vegetables,
superb cheeses and foie gras, prize-winning olive oil, succulent
lamb and pristine oysters.
</P>
<P>
   They would have to leave the low-key atmosphere that attracts
fascinating (some would say eccentric) characters. And of course,
they would have to give up bragging rights on those Sonoma pinot
noirs and chardonnays, wines they would put up against Napa's any
day.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all these advantages, Sonoma's sense of being an
also-ran runs deep, as does resentment about the fame of Napa's
premium wines, which, Sonomans say, is partly driven by a
magnificent promotional machine that sometimes strays into pure
hype.
</P>
<P>
   Just the other day, a spokesman for the Napa Valley Wine
Association described Napa as ``the premier food and wine growing
region in the country.'' Food? Olives are just about the valley's
only crop besides grapes.
</P>
<P>
   If Napa is to San Francisco what the Hamptons are to New York _
the weekend outpost for society doings _ Sonoma is the North Fork,
where potato fields still grow Long Island potatoes.
</P>
<P>
   But in Sonoma, the local specialties are more refined than
potatoes. Laura Chenel, in the town of Sonoma, was one of the first
people in America to turn goat's milk into classic French-style
cheeses. Now, there are several excellent cheese makers in the
county, like Redwood Hill Farm, which makes a seductive
Camembertlike goat cheese called Camellia. And Ig Vella of Sonoma
makes probably the best Jack cheese anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   CK Lamb produces succulent and almost fork-tender meat that is
some of the best lamb in America. The foie gras from Sonoma's
Muscovy ducks has an incredibly fine texture _ silky and meltingly
rich, deeply flavored and with a delightful sweetness. And some of
the county's olive oils can hold their own with their European
brethren: DaVero's, with its intense flavor and peppery finish, is
exactly the kind that demands a shady spot and a few crusts of
country bread for dipping.
</P>
<P>
   Sonoma does have a marketing organization for its bounty, called
Select Sonoma County, but the county does not have the money or the
name recognition of its Napa neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe we are looking for respect,'' said Gaye LeBaron, a
columnist for The Santa Rosa Press Democrat in Sonoma's main town
and a longtime chronicler of this county-versus-valley feud. ``When
the national press misplaces things and puts them in Napa when they
belong in Sonoma, it just galls the hell out of me.''
</P>
<P>
   Like fellow Sonomans, she cheered on the county's answer to
Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid _ the Sonoma Valley Wine Patrol,
which in the early 1990s genially hijacked two busloads of European
travel writers on their way to taste Napa wines and ``forced'' them
to sample Sonoma wines instead. The same outfit raided the Napa
Valley Wine Train and cajoled the tourists into pouring their Napa
wine out the windows and drinking Sonoma wines.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that the residents of Sonoma want the glitz and the
glamour of the 20-mile-long, two-mile-wide Napa Valley or the
bumper-to-bumper traffic on its single north-south road as tourists
seek a little of ``Falcon Crest.'' Nor do they want what they call
the Disneyfication of the wine industry, to accommodate the
vacationing hordes.
</P>
<P>
   They especially don't want the 20,000-square-foot homes built by
people who have made their fortunes elsewhere and have bought
wineries as status symbols.
</P>
<P>
   But it may already be too late.
</P>
<P>
   All over Sonoma, property values are rising as outsiders come
in, ``buying wineries and turning them over to professional
managers,'' said Lou Preston, the owner of Preston Vineyards in Dry
Creek Valley, disdain dripping from every word.
</P>
<P>
   The most famous sign of the kind of conspicuous architecture
that could await a more high-profile Sonoma is the new
Ferrari-Carano winery, in the Dry Creek Valley. It is a
25,000-square-foot Mediterranean-style villa of pink stucco and
limestone. Its owners, Don and Rhonda Carano, also own casinos and
hotels in Nevada, and at the winery they sell everything from ties
to refrigerator magnets.
</P>
<P>
   Kathleen Stuart, a Berkeley ex-pat, who moved to Healdsburg in
1980 and opened the Downtown Bakery there in 1987, sees more and
more of these changes, with which Sonomans have a love-hate
relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are social climbers here,'' she said over lunch at
Ravenous, one of the very few good restaurants in the county. ``And
there are a lot of transplants who want to start their own little
version of Napa, wearing their Ferragamos on weekends. They want to
be big fish in a little pond. Big money has come in here.''
</P>
<P>
   And if any town is going to become the center of this Napazation
it will be Healdsburg (population 9,750).
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Stuart acknowledged her bakery's role in the upscaling of
downtown: ``Before, there were a lot of empty storefronts, and it
was mostly farmers. Now, Healdsburg is totally cutesy-poo.'' She
added, ``I keep hoping the next incarnation will be more like 10
years ago, with a grocery store and a shoe store and a pharmacy.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, downtown does have a grocery store. For the rich. It's
called the Oakville Grocery-Healdsburg and it's like a smaller
version of Dean &AMP; Deluca, but with better paneling. The Oakville
Grocery is a branch of a quintessential Napa store that entered
Sonoma only after consulting with a local committee on how to make
a Napa institution acceptable.
</P>
<P>
   Though parts of the county are less than an hour north of the
Golden Gate Bridge, most of Sonoma is still very rural. Once beyond
the unattractive urban sprawl of tract housing and traffic jams
along the main north-south route, Highway 101, at Santa Rosa and
Petaluma, malls give way to gently rounded hillsides, softly peaked
mountains and long stretches of prime flat agricultural land.
Farther west, waves break against a rocky coastline.
</P>
<P>
   Up until now, life in rural Sonoma has been noncompetitive. It
is a place for individualists and eccentrics _ mavericks who
provide the color that keeps the place intriguing.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Skall is a more recent transplant who chose Sonoma over
Napa. Mrs. Skall has the carriage and accent of a San Francisco
grande dame, but she also has smudges of dirt on her face and under
her fingernails. Ten years ago, when she was 59, she and her
husband, Malcolm, started Middleton Gardens in Healdsburg, which
sells organic produce.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our prices are high,'' she said, ``but we don't make any money
at it.'' And the quality of what they grow is such that they have
no trouble selling it. ``It's not a hobby,'' she said, ``it's an
obsession.''
</P>
<P>
   Explaining why she and her husband, a retired investment banker,
chose Sonoma over Napa, she said: ``Over there, they get dressed up
and wear jewels. Over here, we get dressed up by putting on clean
clothes.''
</P>
<P>
   After living in Paris for years as an international lawyer,
Barry Sterling could have chosen either Napa or Sonoma for the next
phase of his life as a winery owner. In 1976, he and his wife,
Audrey, bought Iron Horse Vineyards in Sebastopol.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``Napa is not my style,'' Mrs. Sterling said, sitting before a
crackling fire in her 1870s farmer-Gothic-style home. ``I don't
want to live in Disneyland. We do not conform to what is socially
correct. We are not a social branch of San Francisco.'' Far from
putting on jewels, Mrs. Sterling prefers to go barefoot.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Cannard, whose fruits and vegetables appear on the menu of
Chez Panisse in Berkeley every day, would stand out in any setting.
His theories about farming are well beyond cutting edge: tall weeds
surround his rows of vegetables in happy harmony.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say I look like a lazy farmer,'' said Cannard, who has
been farming this way all his life. ``Twenty years ago, they said,
`You can't do this.' Ten years ago, they said, `Well, OK, but you
have to keep it mowed.' And now it's OK It's totally not true that
the weeds are taking up nutrients. Weeds are the fertilizer. I
don't fertilize.''
</P>
<P>
   Cannard may look like a hippie farmer, with his long scraggly
gray hair under his knitted cap, but he speaks about ecology and
the environment like a college professor. After a look at the lush
vegetation and listening to the songbirds on his mountaintop
paradise in southern Sonoma, it's not hard to come away believing
him when he says his food ``heals you and makes you think the way
the plant wants you to think.''
</P>
<P>
   Cannard is not a hippie type, but Sonoma is filled with present
and former members of that tribe. People like Steven Schack and
Jennifer Lynn Bice, who spent years making and selling yogurt,
mostly to health food stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't believe in capitalism,'' Schack said, ``but my ideals
have changed over 20 years.'' After studying cheese-making in
France, the two came back to their Redwood Hill Farm in Sebastopol,
on a hidden road overlooking Iron Horse Vineyards. Although they
have been making goat's cheese for only three years, their
Camembert-style Camellia is a standout.
</P>
<P>
   Among the farmers-turned-vintners, Tom Rochioli has made it to
the top. His vineyard is one of the hottest labels of the Russian
River Valley, in northern Sonoma. His grandfather moved to Sonoma
in 1916, and the family gave up raising hops in the 1950s to devote
its 160 acres to wine.
</P>
<P>
   Today, J. Rochioli wines are rated among the best in America.
The Wine Spectator describes its pinot noirs as ``silky smooth''
and ``intriguing,'' its chardonnays as ``stellar, sophisticated.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel second to Napa Valley,'' Rochioli said.
``Image-wise, they have a reputation of being slicker, `Falcon
Crest' royalty, while over here we're a bunch of farmers who became
winemakers.'' Putting it another way, he describes Sonoma as
relaxed, like Burgundy; Napa, more formal, like Bordeaux.
</P>
<P>
   If wine prices declined tomorrow, these farmer-vintners would
convert to prunes, or whatever else could make them a living.
</P>
<P>
   In Napa, the farmers _ the people who grow the grapes _ don't
socialize with the winemakers. In Sonoma, the class structure is
much looser. Lunch on a cool, sunny afternoon at the home of
Ridgely Evers, a software millionaire turned olive oil producer,
and his wife, Colleen McGlynn, was a telling Sonoma mix.
</P>
<P>
   One of the guests, Bruce Campbell, who with his wife, Nancy,
raises Sonoma lamb, explained the difference: ``In Napa, producers
are not ever invited to wine dinners. In Sonoma, producers are
invited, and you don't have to cook or clean up to get invited.''
</P>
<P>
   Campbell, a Sonoma County native, did supply the luscious lamb
shanks that were cooked perfectly over a wood fire by Ms. McGlynn.
He's been raising sheep since he was 10. It's no ordinary lamb:
Wolfgang Puck of Spago is one of his customers.
</P>
<P>
   Evers, a member of the entrepreneurial class, supports his olive
oil habit by working in San Francisco during the week. This year,
after a decade, his olive oil business should break even.
</P>
<P>
   ``You plant grapes for your children and olives for your
grandchildren,'' he said of his 4,500 trees. His DaVero olive oil
was the first from America to be accepted as extra virgin by the
International Olive Oil Council, and it won a blind tasting in
Italy, much to the chagrin of the tasters.
</P>
<P>
   With so many superb raw ingredients to go with the top quality
wines, the question is: Will Sonoma outdo Napa in the restaurant
game?
</P>
<P>
   The experience of Toni Robertson, the new executive chef at the
Sonoma Mission Inn just outside the town of Sonoma, is typical.
When she arrived at the inn, she was taken to lunch at two
restaurants, both in Napa: Tra Vigne and the French Laundry, which
has a nationwide reputation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been told there isn't much restaurant competition in
Sonoma,'' Ms. Robertson said. ``Our competition is in Napa.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe all that Sonoma needs to get some noteworthy restaurants
are enough customers with high standards, like those wealthy people
and their 20,000-square-foot homes from Napa. The ones they don't
want.
</P>
<P>
   But once Sonoma's restaurants are as good as its wines, Sonoma
will find itself a world destination, like it or not. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Following are some Sonoma foods you don't have to go to Northern
California to enjoy (prices do not include shipping): &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CK LAMB. The price of a six-pound rolled, boned and tied leg is
$60; two frenched racks (16 chops) are $64; six loin chops (about
2} pounds total) are $38. (707) 431-8161; fax, (707) 431-8100;
