<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 16:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4207 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ECONOMY-2000-01-COX     06-30 0441
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECONOMY-2000-01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    INDUSTRY SEEKS NEW RULES TO EASE Y2K BUG
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Citing a ``global disaster in the making'' as the
year 2000 approaches, the nation's leading industrial trade group
called on the federal government Tuesday to offer antitrust and
liability relief to business users of computers infected with the
so-called ``Millennium Bug.''
</P>
<P>
   The inability of many older software programs to correctly read
dates beyond Dec. 31, 1999 promises ``to have an impact on the
world economy that will be much more severe than generally
anticipated,'' said Jerry Jasinowski, president of the National
Association of Manufacturers (NAM).
</P>
<P>
   Jasinowski said his group will seek both antitrust waivers and
liability protection against private lawsuits as they cope with the
Year 2000 problem, also known as Y2K. Jack Gribben, a spokesman for
President Clinton's newly formed Y2K council, said the White House
will work with NAM and other business groups to solicit an advisory
opinion from the Justice Department on the kind of information that
companies will be allowed to share without risking antitrust
problems.
</P>
<P>
   The New York-based Securities Industry Association in New York
also plans to seek such an opinion soon, Justice Department and SIA
officials said. A departmental official said that once such an
advisory is issued, it automatically will cover companies and
organizations in similar situations.
</P>
<P>
   At the NAM press conference, Edward Yardeni, chief economist at
Deutsche Bank Securities, said ``the administration doesn't want to
panic the public, and that's why they are taking such a low
profile'' on the looming Y2K issue
</P>
<P>
   Yardeni, who was named by The Wall Street Journal as the leading
U.S. economic forecaster in 1997, said efforts by Clinton and other
world leaders to deal with the oncoming problem have been
``pathetic.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They are doing virtually nothing to increase global awareness,
to accelerate the pace of remediation or to prepare for the failure
of vital systems,'' Yardeni said.
</P>
<P>
   In light of the slow progress being made, his personal estimate
of the chances that computer bug will trigger a recession have
risen from 60 to 70 percent, Yardeni said. An economic downturn
sparked by missing or inaccurate information in networked computer
databases could cause a vicious cycle of falling prices, or
deflation, accompanied by a stock market crash, he added.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
