<SLUG> BC-MASTER-CHEF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUILDING A STEW FROM CORN KERNELS 
</HEADLINE>
   (This is the second of eight columns by Deborah Madison, the former
chef of Greens in San Francisco and the author of ``Vegetarian
Cooking for Everyone.'' Her collaborator is Mark Bittman.)  
 (HLW)  
 By DEBORAH MADISON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Many years ago, while traveling in Mexico, I was served a stew
made with an unusually fragrant chewy corn. It was unlike anything
I had ever had before. The complex flavors of the stew _ nutty and
bright and most of all big _ came from something that appeared
utterly simple.
</P>
<P>
   I soon learned that posole is the name for corn kernels that are
dried and then boiled, and are the soul of the stew. The dish,
naturally enough, is also called posole. These kernels can be
ground into masa, the distinctively flavored building block from
which corn tortillas and chips are made.
</P>
<P>
   In Mexico, posole is often the center of a large communal dish
surrounded by an array of garnishes like avocado, for creaminess;
onions, for crunch; and oregano, for aromatic flavor. And then
there are grated cheese and tortilla chips.
</P>
<P>
   In New Mexico, where I now live, posole is more likely to be a
side dish in place of beans. It sometimes serves as a simple main
course, containing pork, onion, oregano, and garlic. The pork makes
a kind of broth as it simmers with the corn, rendering the meat
tender and integrating it beautifully into the stew.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years I have become more inclined to make a vegetarian
version of the dish and to look for other ways to enliven it. My
variation begins with roasted, fresh, mild green chilies. (If you
can't get these, substitute long-frying peppers and add fresh
jalapeno or another hot chili.) I add zucchini near the very end; I
want it to become soft but not mushy. Then, in the Mexican fashion,
I serve my posole with a few condiments, including a fresh cilantro
salsa, avocado, and chopped cabbage.
</P>
<P>
   Like beans, posole takes longer to cook as it ages, so cooking
times are approximate. But this dish can be prepared in advance; it
gets better as it sits. You can double or triple the amounts and
add chunks of pork at the beginning of the cooking time. But
practicalities aside, the result is a beguiling, hearty stew of
bursting corn kernels.
</P>
<P>
   SUMMER POSOLE
</P>
<P>
   Time: at least two hours, plus optional soaking time
</P>
<P>
   1{ cups dried posole, available at health-food stores or stores
selling Mexican or Southwest ingredients
</P>
<P>
   2 or 3 dried red chilies
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons dried Mexican oregano, plus more for garnish
</P>
<P>
   1 large onion, minced
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons minced garlic
</P>
<P>
   4 fresh, mild green chilies, like Anaheims
</P>
<P>
   1 big bunch cilantro, well washed, large stems removed, minced
(there should be about 2/3 cup finely minced cilantro)
</P>
<P>
   1 jalapeno, stem and seeds removed, very finely minced
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup minced scallions or shallots
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup plus 1 tablespoon canola oil
</P>
<P>
   2 avocados, peeled and minced
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   2 medium zucchini, cut the long way into quarters, then into
chunks
</P>
<P>
   Lime wedges
</P>
<P>
   2 cups fresh shredded and chopped cabbage.
</P>
<P>
   1. If time allows, soak posole overnight in water to cover.
Drain, and place in a pot with 8 cups water, red chilies, 2
teaspoons oregano, onion, and all but a teaspoon of garlic. Bring
to a boil, reduce heat so that mixture bubbles gently, and cover.
</P>
<P>
   2. Roast the 4 fresh chilies over an open flame, on either the
grill or a gas stove (you can just let them sit on a burner; they
won't make much of a mess). Turn them frequently, until they are
blackened and blistered all over. Remove them to a bowl, then cover
and let sit while you prepare the salsa.
</P>
<P>
   3. Combine cilantro with remaining garlic, jalapeno, scallion,
oil, and one of the avocados. Add salt and pepper, then taste and
adjust seasoning as necessary.
</P>
<P>
   4. When roasted peppers have sat for at least 30 minutes,
uncover, and remove their skins, stems and seeds. Chop the pepper
flesh roughly, and add it to the stew. When the posole kernels
begin to pop (not audibly, but visibly), add salt and pepper to
taste.
</P>
<P>
   5. The stew is done when the posole is tender but not mushy;
many of the kernels will have popped. Add zucchini, and cook a few
minutes more, until it becomes tender. Taste, and adjust seasoning.
</P>
<P>
   6. Serve with the salsa, the remaining avocado, the lime, a
small bowl of oregano, and the cabbage; each should be added by
individual diners, to taste.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-98 1706EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980630.0188 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 17:07 </DATE_TIME>
