A4237 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WINE-TASTINGS-NYT &LR;      06-30 0179
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-TASTINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINE OF THE WEEK: FULL CABERNET  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By FRANK J. PRIAL    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Cakebread Cellars Cabernet Sauvignon, 1995, Napa Valley, Calif.
About $30. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   For a while there in 1995, it seemed as if nature wanted to even
things up, after having been so generous to the Napa Valley in
1994, one of its best years ever.
</P>
<P>
   There were floods in the winter, rain in the spring, hail in
June and, for good measure, an occasional day of grape-shattering
heat. Just enough alibis to get any winemaker through an iffy year,
right?
</P>
<P>
   Not Bruce Cakebread. He took on the challenge that the weather
had tossed him and managed to turn out a marvelous cabernet
sauvignon. This, to me, is the quintessential California cabernet:
rich, intense, full without being weighty, deep without being
cloying.
</P>
<P>
   The Cakebreads, winemakers all, believe this wine to be a bit
more austere than their 1994. That's good: a touch of leanness
supplies the elegance that so many California cabernets lack. It is
well worth its price.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-98 1707EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980630.0189 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 17:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4242 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SEA-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      06-30 1025
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEA-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WHERE THE SEA USED TO BE': SEARCHING FOR OIL, LOVE, IN THE SNOW 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Publication notes appear at the end of the review.) 
(th) 
 By RICHARD BERNSTEIN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rick Bass is an oil geologist and environmentalist whose books
exalt the world of nature and the practice of solitude. A few years
ago, he spent a year or so in a tiny, isolated, unelectrified
community of 30 human inhabitants in the Yaak Valley of northern
Montana, an experience from which his essay ``Notes From Montana''
was drawn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where the Sea Used to Be'' is Bass' first full-length novel,
and it combines the author's knowledge of oil exploration with his
experience in a snowbound village near the Canadian border.
</P>
<P>
   It is the story of a geologist named Wallis who is sent by a
coarse and power-hungry wildcatter called Old Dudley to find oil in
a place very much like the real-life Yaak Valley. Wallis engages in
a life-and-death struggle with Old Dudley, a struggle that poses
the themes of human love, possession and greed against the
unsparing, harshly beautiful, brutally indifferent background of
nature.
</P>
<P>
   These are not new themes, though they are promising ones, which
Bass here and there exploits with telling effect. But ``Where the
Sea Used to Be'' is encased in an aesthetic of such contrived,
over-elaborated meaningfulness that the effect is stock melodrama
rather than genuine human struggle.
</P>
<P>
   Bass intends this book to be taken for a kind of natural
realism, a psychological, Nietzschean duel to the death among
strongly willed figures whose characters drive them to tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   But Bass' aim is undermined by his propensity for a
self-conscious, epic-heroic mysticism that at times approaches
self-parody, as in passages like this one: ``They drove into and
then through the cold front, so that the snow was behind them and
the stars burned fiercely above, so bright that the stabs and
flashes of them welded and seared old memories in their minds,
summoned things within them, old stories and histories they had not
remembered in a long time, or had never known.''
</P>
<P>
   The Gothic quality of ``Where the Sea Used to Be'' is evident
from the very first pages, where Bass introduces his protagonist,
Old Dudley, a man of ``nearly immeasurable wealth,'' who doesn't so
much employ geologists to help him find oil as devour and destroy
them. ``He could read scents and gestures as other men and women
might read a newspaper,'' Bass' narrator writes, striking an early
tone of hackneyed portent. ``He could follow these scents straight
into their seams of weakness _ the soft places.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallis, a man who had ``lost everything,'' is a new geologist
hired by Dudley. Wallis is sent off in a Jeep to the isolated Swan
Valley in northern Montana with instructions to map the land and
find where the oil is. Wallis wonders about this particular task,
since another of Dudley's geologists, Matthew, has already mapped
the terrain and drilled 19 dry holes there.
</P>
<P>
   He also wonders why Dudley is determined to find oil in the very
spot in Montana where his only daughter, Mel, happens to live. But
Mel, who is Matthew's woman and lives in a cabin in the woods
studying wolves, knows what Dudley is up to.
</P>
<P>
   ``Old Dudley was carving one of them with his blood,'' she says
of her feverishly controlling father, ``and the other with his
hands.''
</P>
<P>
   The scene, in other words, is set for simultaneous struggles:
one is between Wallis and Matthew for the love of Mel, the other
between Mel and Dudley for the contested and tortured soul of
Wallis. As these twin battles are played out in the snow-barricaded
valley where Mel lives, Bass delivers some patches of fine writing
but in a Paul Bunyanesque tall-tale mode that requires a good deal
of credulity.
</P>
<P>
   Mel, for example, carries the arriving Wallis on her back as she
skis the 10 miles into town _ an unlikely exploit. ``They dropped
lower down into the mountains, descending, corkscrewing, as if into
its interior. He could feel the pleasure coming straight through
her _ could feel it like heat conducted, as if it were his.''
</P>
<P>
   Mel teaches Wallis about the deer and the wolves in a way that
is unsentimental about the violence and the blood of nature yet is
saturated in an anthropomorphism that is sentimentalizing in
itself. ``The deer are leaving this layer of earth and are going to
the next kingdom,'' Mel tells Wallis, ``and the cedars are a bridge
between those two worlds.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallis sets about trying to map the geological strata, which is
difficult given that the earth is covered by mountains of snow.
Meanwhile, working in Mel's cabin, he uncovers a diary written by
Dudley that contains his ruminations on geological history, these
too written in what seems a kind of unintended imitation of ``Thus
Spake Zarathustra'': ``We understand now that man's birth was
foreshadowed. It was expressed in the formal gradation of the
continents.''
</P>
<P>
   Dudley himself turns out to be less Zarathustra than simply a
lecher and a megalomaniac. He impregnates a woman by spraying her
with sperm from a distance of six feet (another tall tale). He
leads Wallis and Matthew to drill a hopeless well, which makes one
wonder, if that is Dudley's modus operandi, how he managed to gain
his immeasurable wealth.
</P>
<P>
   Near the end, Wallis and Matthew go off to hunt elk to lay in a
store of meat for Mel's winter, an episode that furnishes Bass with
an occasion for some of the best descriptive writing that appears
in this book, but for some semi-nonsensical rapture as well.
``Forty yards up the ridge, on the flat, the elk rested. Wallis
emptied his mind of them, as he knew he must, so they would not
know he was among them.'' In other words, if you don't think about
elk, they won't think about you.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where the Sea Used to Be'' is a book that seems to mimic an
echo chamber in which sounds are magnified and deformed, leaving
the reader, or the listener, wishing for the rhetorical volume to
be turned down.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   WHERE THE SEA USED TO BE
</P>
<P>
   By Rick Bass
</P>
<P>
   445 pages. Houghton Mifflin. $25. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
