<HEADER>
A4272 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROOTBEER-AZR &LR;      06-30 1107
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROOTBEER-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILL THE REAL ROOT BEER PLEASE STAND UP? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD NILSEN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) - The Fourth of July approaches, and Americans are
going to gobble millions of hot dogs and drink oceans of root beer.
</P>
<P>
   They already know they have no clue what goes in hot dogs _
America has made peace with that ambiguity _ but everyone thinks
they know what root beer is. Unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   Root beer is not an item, but a class. There is no official
definition for the beverage and the differences between brands are
often quite striking.
</P>
<P>
   Especially since 1960, when the federal Food and Drug
Administration made traditional root beer illegal in 1960.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out that the root in root beer _ traditionally
sassafras root _ is a carcinogen. Soft-drink manufacturers had to
scurry around to find replacements for the main ingredient of the
popular drink.
</P>
<P>
   So that no root beer today is made by the same ``Old Timey''
recipe that may be advertised on the label.
</P>
<P>
   What is all the more ironic about this turn of events is that
root beer has its origins in the world of patent medicines. It was
supposed to make you well.
</P>
<P>
   It is a common story among soft drinks. Coca-Cola, Dr Pepper,
7Up and even the once-ubiquitous Moxie all had their beginnings in
the drugstore, sold originally as tonics to make people feel
healthier and more energetic.
</P>
<P>
   Before 7Up took its name from a cattle brand that its inventor
took a fancy to, its name was actually Bib-Label Lithiated
Lemon-Lime Soda.
</P>
<P>
   From the 18th century, naturally carbonated mineral water was
used as a medicine. Wells of the bubbly water were tapped and sold
in spas and health retreats. In 1825, Elie Magliore Durand, a
French immigrant, began selling the stuff in his Philadelphia
pharmacy.
</P>
<P>
   The first to add flavors, in 1838, was Eugene Roussel _ another
French immigrant in another Philadelphia drugstore _ who began to
add sugar and lemon flavoring to the fizz water, then carbonated
artificially. Within a few years, there were no fewer than six
manufacturers of flavored carbonated water in Philadelphia alone.
It soon spread to New York.
</P>
<P>
   After about 1850, other flavors began to appear.
</P>
<P>
   All in the name of health.
</P>
<P>
   Well, two other streams of history added to the story.
</P>
<P>
   The first is that of brewing, which makes another beverage with
bubbles _ beer. When the yeast action is interrupted before it has
a chance to turn all the sugars into alcohol, the result is ``small
beer,'' and it has very little alcohol and a lot of bubbles.
</P>
<P>
   Apple cider is one example, and, later, root beer became
another.
</P>
<P>
   The third stream of this story begins in the mountains of
eastern North America, where inhabitants often collected sassafras
roots to make a tea that was considered a ``spring tonic,'' and was
believed to help healing and get the sluggish inner organs working
fluently once again after a hard winter.
</P>
<P>
   In 1874, the health-giving tea joined the small-beer yeast to
make another carbonated beverage that could be sold in the pharmacy
for its medicinal effect.
</P>
<P>
   The man who brought the three streams of history together was
Charles Hires, a New Jersey pharmacist.
</P>
<P>
   He began, by the way, as a pharmacist in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   On Independence Day, we celebrate the signing of the Declaration
of Independence in Philadelphia in 1776. But, as you see,
Philadelphia had a vital role also in the development of soft
drinks. I leave it to you to decide whether democracy or soda pop
is more American.
</P>
<P>
   Hires began experimenting in the 1870s with a carbonated drink
flavored with roots and berries. He tried juniper, pipsissewa,
spikenard, wintergreen, ginger, licorice, vanilla, hops and
sarsaparilla. But a tonic he had been given by a New Jersey woman _
the landlady of a vacation house he was renting _ put him on the
track of sassafras.
</P>
<P>
   When the 1876 Centennial Exhibition opened in _ where else? _
Philadelphia, Hires was there to begin selling his new beverage. It
caught on.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, close to 2,000 brands of root beer have been sold.
Even now, there are close to 200. Although the popularity of root
beer has declined from its height and colas now dominate, the drink
still makes up about 3 percent of the $54 billion domestic
soft-drink market.
</P>
<P>
   To put it in perspective: In 1993, A&AMP;W _ the most popular root
beer _ sold 53.5 million cases of root beer; the same year, Coke
unloaded 1.6 billion cases.
</P>
<P>
   Still, that is a lot of root beer.
</P>
<P>
   It did take a hit in 1960, though.
</P>
<P>
   The main flavoring ingredient in root beer was sassafras, and
the FDA discovered that one of the components of sassafras could
cause liver cancer in rats. The offending chemical is called
safrole, although it sounds much more baleful by its longer name,
4-allyl 1-1, 2-methylenedioxybenzene.
</P>
<P>
   It was potent enough to be used topically as a pediculicide, or
delousing bath, in the old days.
</P>
<P>
   It sounds worse than it is. A 200-pound man would have to drink
something like 24 gallons of root beer a day to reach the levels of
toxicity the lab rats endured.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, root-beer manufacturers had to find a replacement.
</P>
<P>
   Some managed to remove the safrole from the oil. Others found
artificial flavoring replacements. Still others used substitutes
like wintergreen oil or birch bark.
</P>
<P>
   Root beer has always had an ambiguous relationship with
sarsaparilla.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, sarsaparilla (begin ital) is (end ital)a root beer, but
made with the root of the Central American sarsaparilla plant
instead of the sassafras. Sassafras doesn't grow in the West. So a
replacement was found that was regionally suitable, and
sarsaparilla was born.
</P>
<P>
   Today's drink seems more like a wintergreen soda, but
manufacturers guard their proprietary recipes carefully and we
cannot know for sure.
</P>
<P>
   A related drink is made from birch bark _ or was _ and is called
birch beer. It has a similar flavor to sarsaparilla, partly because
it seems as if some modern birch beers are really wintergreen
sodas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cream'' sodas are vanilla flavored sodas, and some modern root
beers are so vanilla-heavy, it is hard to tell them from cream
sodas.
</P>
<P>
   A final bit of trivia: Men and women have different preferences
in taste. Men, it turns out, tend to like herbal and root flavors
more; women tend to like berry and fruit flavors. So root beer _
although it has fans in both genders _ tends to be a boy's drink.
</P>
<P>
   At any rate, perfect to slosh down with a hot dog slathered in
mustard and onions. &QL; 
Richard Nilsen can be reached at richard.nilsen(at)pni.com &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
