<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAS-MEGA-GRILLS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE THRILL OF THE GRILL IS IN CHARCOAL, NOT GAS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Pa.)   (af)  
 By JOHN WILLOUGHBY and CHRIS SCHLESINGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every day, or so it seems, the mail carrier delivers another
brochure touting a new gas mega-grill. These gleaming steel
behemoths, which can cost more than $5,000, are nothing less than
fantasy kitchens reconfigured for outdoor use. Each promises to
provide ease, convenience and great grilled food at the flip of a
switch.
</P>
<P>
   There are just two problems. First, these grills are no fun.
Second, you can cook better on an oven rack perched on bricks over
a charcoal fire. Because let's face it: no matter how fancy or
high-tech, gas grills are the microwaves of the backyard.
</P>
<P>
   Like microwaves, gas grills are convenient, and there is
certainly no shame in using them. But to us, these new grills are
the very definition of a culinary Faustian bargain. In exchange for
the convenience of gas, the griller must give up the challenge of
unpredictability, that personal interaction with the fire that
forms the very soul of grilling.
</P>
<P>
   We have always seen grilling as more than just a way to cook
food. For each of us, it started out as a bonding activity with our
dads. In the wilds of the backyard, father and son braved the
vagaries of the flames together, faced with the constant threat
that dinner would be turned into ashes.
</P>
<P>
   Pushing and pulling the coals, opening and shutting vents,
moving the food around on the grid, we were totally absorbed in our
task. Finally, triumphant, we bore the dinner unscathed into the
house.
</P>
<P>
   A thrill like this can never be achieved on a gas contraption,
nor can you reach the same level of grilled flavor. You may as well
wheel your stove outside.
</P>
<P>
   There are several reasons for this. Grilling is essentially a
high-heat cooking method. When food is exposed to the direct heat
of a charcoal or wood fire, a crusty, hyper-flavorful, slightly
sweet seared crust develops on its exterior. It is this crust that
is most responsible for the characteristic grilled flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Gas cannot do as good a job of creating this crust. First, the
primary heat of a charcoal fire comes not from flames but from
coals, which provide a more intense heat. And gas is what we like
to call a ``wet heat.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Dr. Harold Schobert, the director of the Energy
Institute at Pennsylvania State University, propane contains some
carbon atoms and some hydrogen atoms. When it burns, the primary
products are carbon dioxide and water vapor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charcoal has a much, much higher percentage of carbon than
propane does,'' Schobert said. ``So of course, there is less water
vapor coming off charcoal when it is burned.''
</P>
<P>
   In our experience, water vapor has the same effect on food being
grilled as moisture has on the surface of food being sauteed _ it
does not sear as well.
</P>
<P>
   OK, but what about the fact that charcoal's messy? Sure, but
after all, it's used outside. Even the convenience of gas grills,
their primary advantage, provides less of an edge than you might
suspect.
</P>
<P>
   Gas grill manuals routinely advise, for example, that the grill
be turned on 10 to 15 minutes before cooking begins. By using
hardwood charcoal and a chimney starter, you can have a charcoal
fire ready to grill in 30 to 35 minutes. Saving 20 minutes hardly
seems worth it for the difference in flavor.
</P>
<P>
   So, the one remaining advantage of gas grills is that they are
easy to light. That we will concede, and those for whom this is a
major concern might opt for the new grills that ignite charcoal
with an instant-on gas flame.
</P>
<P>
   While they don't provide the whole grilling experience, at least
you cook over the real thing once the fire gets going.
</P>
<P>
   But for us, the bottom line is that gas, while handy, simply
can't deliver the flavor or the fun that live fire does.
</P>
<P>
   Lighting, adjusting and generally playing around with the fire
is a kind of ceremony to be reveled in, rather than avoided. Sure,
it may take a few minutes longer, but it engages the cook like no
other cooking method _ getting that fire just right, preparing just
the proper bed of coals for steak or lamb chops, eggplant or fish.
</P>
<P>
   Stepping up to the plate to grill over a real live fire yields
not only incomparable flavor, but also a sense of triumph over the
elements, as well. You can't get that from simply turning yet
another knob. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   GRILLED SHOULDER LAMB CHOPS ON GREENS
</P>
<P>
   Time: 30 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2 bunches arugula (or watercress), trimmed, washed and dried
</P>
<P>
   1 cup whole fresh mint leaves, cleaned
</P>
<P>
   1 small red onion, peeled and thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   4 10- to 12-ounce shoulder lamb chops, about 1{ inches thick
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon minced garlic
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon red pepper flakes
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons roughly chopped fresh rosemary
</P>
<P>
   4 thick slices crusty bread
</P>
<P>
   One-third cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   \ cup fresh lemon juice (about 1 lemon)
</P>
<P>
   12 pickled hot cherry peppers (if desired). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. In large bowl, combine arugula, mint and onion. Toss to mix,
and then set aside. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2. Sprinkle lamb chops with salt and pepper to taste. In small
bowl, combine vegetable oil, garlic, red pepper flakes and
rosemary, and mix well. Cover chops generously with rub. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   3. Grill over medium-hot fire for about 6 minutes a side for
medium. To check for doneness, cut into a chop, and see whether the
center is slightly pinker than you want it to be when you eat it,
since it will continue to cook a bit after you remove it from the
grill. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   4. While lamb is cooking, place bread slices around edge of
grill, and toast until golden brown, about 2 minutes a side. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   5. In small bowl, whisk together olive oil, lemon juice and salt
and pepper to taste. Pour over arugula-mint mixture, and toss well.
Place a portion of this salad mixture on each plate, and top with a
lamb chop and a slice of grilled bread. Serve warm, garnished with
peppers if desired. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GRILLED EGGPLANT CIRCLES WITH SWEET CHILE SAUCE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 30 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons sesame oil
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon minced garlic
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon minced ginger
</P>
<P>
   { cup lime juice (about 2 limes)
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons ketchup
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 medium eggplants, cut into rounds about 1 inch thick
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   8 scallions, thinly sliced on the bias (green and white parts)
</P>
<P>
   1{ tablespoons ground coriander
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon red pepper flakes. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. First, make the sauce: In medium saucepan, place sesame oil
over medium heat until it is hot but not smoking. Add garlic and
ginger, and saute, stirring occasionally, for 3 minutes. Add lime
juice, ketchup and brown sugar, and bring to boil, stirring
occasionally. As soon as mixture begins to boil, reduce heat to
low, and simmer, stirring once in a while, for 20 minutes or until
sauce is thick enough to coat the back of a spoon. Remove from
heat, and set aside. (It may be covered and refrigerated for as
long as 1 week; bring to room temperature before using.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2. Put eggplant rounds, vegetable oil and salt and pepper to
taste into medium bowl. Toss to coat. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   3. Place eggplant directly on grill over medium-hot fire, and
cook until browned and soft, about 4 minutes a side. To check for
doneness, cut eggplant, and be sure interior looks moist (raw
eggplant is dry, cooked is moist). Brush eggplant on both sides
with chile sauce, leave it on grill for about 10 seconds, and then
transfer to plates or platter. Sprinkle with scallions, coriander
and red pepper flakes, and serve warm. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GRILLED NEW YORK STRIP WITH SMOKY CORN RELISH AND GRILLED SPRING
ONIONS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 30 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   4 ears corn, blanched in boiling salted water for 2 minutes,
then drained
</P>
<P>
   { red bell pepper, seeded and diced small
</P>
<P>
   { green bell pepper, seeded and diced small
</P>
<P>
   1 small red onion, peeled and diced small
</P>
<P>
   2 to 3 teaspoons minced fresh chile pepper of your choice
</P>
<P>
   1 cup red wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   One-third cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons molasses
</P>
<P>
   { cup roughly chopped fresh parsley
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   4 12-ounce New York strip steaks
</P>
<P>
   8 whole spring onions (or very large scallions), roots trimmed
</P>
<P>
   2 limes, halved. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Build a hot fire. Place corn around edges of grill, just
barely over the coals. Cook corn, rolling it around frequently, for
about 3 minutes, or until ears are well browned. Remove ears from
grill, and as soon as they are cool enough to handle, slice kernels
from cobs into a small bowl. Add bell peppers, red onion, chile
pepper, vinegar, oil, molasses, parsley and salt and pepper to
taste. Mix well, and set aside. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2. Check fire to make sure it is still hot; if not, add some
coals and wait a few minutes. Meanwhile, sprinkle steaks generously
with salt and pepper. Place on grill, and cook for 5 to 7 minutes a
side for rare. To check for doneness, cut into a steak and see
whether the center is slightly pinker than you want it to be when
you eat it, since it will continue to cook a bit after you remove
it from the grill. Remove steaks from grill, and allow to rest for
5 minutes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   3. While steaks are resting, sprinkle spring onions lightly with
salt and pepper, and place them on the grill over a hot fire. Cook
for 3 to 4 minutes, rolling them over several times, or until
outsides are nicely browned. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   4. Remove spring onions from grill, and slice in half
lengthwise. Serve each steak with halved spring onion, squeeze of
lime and a big spoonful of the relish. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
