<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
GOOD ECONOMIC NEWS A BOON TO NEW YORK GOVERNOR 
</HEADLINE>
 BNY-ECONOMY-HNS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ALAN D. ABBEY  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ New Yorkers are feeling better about the state's
economy than they have in years, a new survey says, and that should
bode well for Gov. George Pataki and other incumbents on Election
Day.
</P>
<P>
   The poll, conducted for the Albany Times Union and Syracuse
Newspapers earlier this month by Zogby International, a Utica-based
independent polling firm, shows that New Yorkers feel better off
financially than they did last summer. It also says they are
strongly optimistic about the state's future and expect their
personal economic circumstances to remain steady or improve in the
next year.
</P>
<P>
   The results, according to pollster John Zogby and other experts,
is that the Republican governor should be able to win re-election.
</P>
<P>
   ``It should be a good year for an incumbent,'' Zogby said.
``Where is the mandate for change? Among those who say they were
worse off, there isn't any anger and focus. It's really going to be
difficult for a nonincumbent party because of two things: To some
degree people are lowering expectations, and there are also lower
expectations for government.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``All in all, it doesn't spell a good year to
challenge the incumbent.''
</P>
<P>
   Thirty percent of those surveyed said they were better off
financially than they were four years ago. That's up by several
points on the positive side from a Zogby poll last August. Only
half as many, 15 percent, said they were worse off. That's down
from a 22 percent negative feeling last summer.
</P>
<P>
   Fully 69 percent of the Zogby survey respondents said they were
optimistic about the state's future, with only 20 percent
pessimistic.
</P>
<P>
   Political analyst Frank Mauro, executive director of Fiscal
Policy Institute in Latham, a research office funded by organized
labor and religious groups, said the good feelings were no
surprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``What has been happening in New York since November 1992 _ when
we hit bottom _ has been a meager recovery under (Gov. Mario) Cuomo
and Pataki,'' Mauro said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first year of the Pataki administration, there was a lot
of government downsizing, a lot of people retired and they were
weaned from the work force,'' Mauro said. ``The situation now is of
steady job growth. It's understandable that people are feeling
better.''
</P>
<P>
   But for Mauro, a regular critic of the Pataki administration,
that recovery has been sluggish, has failed to repeat past
increases in employment, represents increases in income more than
in jobs, is heavily weighted toward downstate financial employment
and would have occurred with or without Pataki in office.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y. ``tells governors and
mayors they will be blamed for the rain, so they may as well take
credit for the sunshine,'' Mauro said.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Pataki administration did not respond to
questions about the survey. Administration officials regularly,
however, take credit for job growth and creation in New York and
are active around the state offering grants and loans to companies
to relocate, grow or remain in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The Pataki administration has said its business-friendly
policies have been responsible for continued private-sector job
growth in the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   Few people surveyed by Zogby said they feared they or a family
member would lose a job in the near future. The June total, 14
percent, is down from 21 percent a year ago. Similarly, only 13
percent reported working at a lower-paying job than their previous
one, down from 17 percent a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven percent said they had lost their job due to downsizing or
a company leaving New York, down from 14 percent a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the good feelings, Mauro said that New York has yet to
reach its historic 1989 peak in employment. Total job count in the
state topped out at 8.3 million that year, and is now at 8.1
million.
</P>
<P>
   He said that economic weakness in western New York and widening
income disparities between the highest- and lowest-paid New Yorkers
could cause Pataki's glow to fade.
</P>
<P>
   But there is little to suggest that the overall economic picture
in New York will change substantially between now and the Nov. 3
election. Echoing pollster Zogby's point, Mauro said that unless
something cataclysmic happens, Pataki is likely to reap the
benefits of a sunny economy come Election Day.
</P>
</TEXT>
