<P>
   &UR; CITY STREETS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   I come from a bunch of pretty typical New Yorkers, each of us
imbued with a healthy dose of self-importance, each of us convinced
that he or she is working harder and doing more than anyone else.
Consequently, orchestrating attendance at a midweek family
occasion, as I needed to do for my daughter's school play, can be
an act of diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of filing legal papers close to deadline, I called
my parents' office to choose a train that would get them to us in
time for dinner and the show. They were in a meeting, and my mother
had little patience as I fumbled with the train schedule. I, in
turn, had little patience with her lack of patience, and we shared
tight-lipped exchanges as we selected a train.
</P>
<P>
   When it was all done, I sighed audibly and asked: ``Mother, do
you have any idea how burdensome it is sometimes to be your
daughter?'' Expecting an argument, I was shocked to hear her sigh
in return and ask: ``Sally, do you have any idea how burdensome it
is sometimes to be me?''
</P>
<P>
   At that moment, I declared a truce.
</P>
<P>
   _SALLY WASSERMAN
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Laitin's 13-year-old grandson, Adam Curtis, lives in a
suburb of Washington and constantly complains to his grandfather
that he's a ``big city boy,'' living too far away from the action.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, Laitin asked him how he'd like to visit New York, and
Adam immediately listed the things he'd like to do there _ the
David Letterman show, F.A.O. Schwarz, and the Metropolitan Museum
of Art among them. The trip was arranged, and Laitin managed to
meet all the requests.
</P>
<P>
   After an exhausting weekend, the two were strolling crosstown on
West 57th Street when Adam summed up his visit. ``Grandpa,'' he
said. ``This is a town that could really keep up with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Estelle Cohen and her husband were in a large bird store looking
for a gift for their son. After buying a feeder and a book on the
care of hummingbirds, they were told they should get a six-foot
pole to hang the feeder on. While Mrs. Cohen was paying, her
husband exclaimed, ``We can't take that pole, we're going on a
plane.''
</P>
<P>
   Without a moment's hesitation, the woman behind them said,
``Just tell them you're a shepherd.''
</P>
<P>
   The blue-haired lady with the fluffy white dog tucked under her
arm was pursuing a second dog that had obviously strayed. As she
looked hither and yon, she called out ``Sotheby. Sotheby.'' Michael
Zentman had no doubt about the name of the dog she was holding. It
had to be ``Christie.''
</P>
<P>
   He asked. It was.
</P>
<P>
   Ian Alterman was leaving a movie theater recently when he
encountered two women with stroller-age children. One woman was
holding both children as the other woman struggled with her
stroller. The struggling woman was becoming increasingly
frustrated.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, she burst out: ``You know, just because we have
maternal instincts doesn't mean we know how to operate strollers.''
</P>
<P>
   It was one of those seriously rainy days that we've had in the
last few months and Steven Ng spent 20 minutes with his arm
outstretched, trying to get a taxi. Finally, a vacant cab appeared.
Ng shook himself off, checked the water content of his clothes,
settled in and spotted the medallion number: 2H2O.
</P>
<P>
   Two young women were taking their seats near the back row of the
Delacorte Theater for a performance of ``The Skin of Our Teeth.''
</P>
<P>
   Donald J. Christensen overheard the following conversation.
</P>
<P>
   First young woman: ``It's so far away from the stage.
</P>
<P>
   Second young woman: ``That's OK. They talk loud in
Shakespeare.''
</P>
<P>
   One: ``This isn't Shakespeare.''
</P>
<P>
   Two: ``Yes, it is. It's Shakespeare in the Park.''
</P>
<P>
   One (looking in program): ``But it says `by Thornton Wilder.'''
</P>
<P>
   Two: ``He's the adapter. They've made it into a comedy.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not his original creation but Armen Khachaturian got a
laugh out of the dictum of his friend, Greg Monsees, to his four
children and their dog. Monsees is separated from his wife, and the
children's primary residence is with their mother.
</P>
<P>
   His communique:
</P>
<P>
   Re: Amy's Stolen Car
</P>
<P>
   1. If you don't have enough money for putting the car in a
parking garage, do not drive to New York.
</P>
<P>
   2. If it is absolutely impossible for me to help you until the
next morning, do not call in the middle of the night. I seem to do
my best sleeping at 3:45 a.m. and
</P>
<P>
   3. If you do call, please do not begin with the phrase, ``Dad
I'm not calling you at this hour of the night with good news.''
I've already made that assumption.
</P>
<P>
   Love, Dad
</P>
<P>
   A message from a guidance counselor at a prestigious suburban
school asked that Phyllis Bocian get in touch as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bocian returned the call almost immediately. A woman with a
foreign accent answered.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bocian: ``Marion Benson, please.''
</P>
<P>
   Voice at other end: ``She isn't in.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bocian: ``May I have her voice mail?''
</P>
<P>
   Voice at other end (after small pause): ``He isn't here
either.''
</P>
<P>
   Selma Glick was reminded recently of the day some years ago when
she had to go to work but two friends, one a visitor from Oregon
and the other a New Yorker, went to the Statue of Liberty. The two,
who had had some experience mountain climbing, decided to walk up
the stairs to the top. The Oregonian reached the top first and saw
a group of people drinking champagne.
</P>
<P>
   This must be the New York reward for climbing, she thought, and
politely asked, ``May I have one?'' She had just received her drink
when the New York friend joined her and was promptly advised to go
over and also claim her reward.
</P>
<P>
   The New Yorker did as suggested and also received a glass of
champagne but she suspected that the champagne wasn't a climbing
reward.
</P>
<P>
   She inquired of the group and was told that they were Russians
who had waited for years for permission to come to the United
States. They promised each other that when they got to America,
they would go to the top of the Statue of Liberty and drink
champagne.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BIG GAME HUNTER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A big-game hunter went on safari with his wife and
mother-in-law. One evening, while still deep in the jungle, the Mrs
awoke to find her mother gone. Rushing to her husband, she insisted
on them both trying to find her mother.
</P>
<P>
   The hunter picked up his rifle, took a swig of whiskey, and
started to look for her.
</P>
<P>
   In a clearing not far from the camp, they came upon a chilling
sight: the mother-in-law was backed up against a thick,
impenetrable bush, and a large male lion stood facing her.
</P>
<P>
   The wife said, `What are we going to do?`
</P>
<P>
   `Nothing,` said the hunter, `The lion got himself into this
mess, let him get himself out of it.`
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SHAGGY GUIDE DOG STORY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   `We will not have him put down. Lucky is basically a damn good
guide dog,` Ernst Gerber, a dog trainer from Wuppertal told
reporters. `He just needs a little brush-up on some elementary
skills, that's all.`
</P>
<P>
   Gerber admitted to the press conference that Lucky, a German
shepherd guide- dog for the blind, had so far been responsible for
the deaths of all four of his previous owners. `I admit it's not an
impressive record on paper. He led his first owner in front of a
bus, and the second off the end of a pier. He actually pushed his
third owner off a railway platform just as the Cologne-to-
Frankfurt express was approaching, and he walked his fourth owner
into heavy traffic, before abandoning him and running away to
safety. But, apart from epileptic fits, he has a lovely
temperament. And guide dogs are difficult to train these days.`
</P>
<P>
   Asked if Lucky's fifth owner would be told about his previous
record, Gerber replied: `No. It would make them nervous, and would
make Lucky nervous. And when Lucky gets nervous he's liable to do
something silly.`
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THOSE CRAZY MORMONS ... &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A Jew, a Catholic and a Mormon were having lunch together after
a business meeting. The Jew, bragging on his virility, said, `I
have four sons. One more and I'll have a basketball team.`
</P>
<P>
   The Catholic, pooh-poohed this accomplishment, stating, `That's
nothing, boy. I have 10 sons, one more and I'll have a football
team.`
</P>
<P>
   To which the Mormon replied, `You fellas ain't got a clue. I
have 17 wives. One more and I'll have a golf course.`
</P>
<P>
   &UR; YUP, ANOTHER BLONDE JOKE ..  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Three women are about to be executed. One's a brunette, one's a
redhead and one's a blonde.
</P>
<P>
   The guard brings the brunette forward and the executioner asks
if she has any last requests. She says no and the executioner
shouts, `Ready! ... Aim! ...`
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly the brunette yells, `EARTHQUAKE!` Everyone is startled
and looks around as the brunette escapes.
</P>
<P>
   The guard brings the redhead forward and the executioner asks if
she has any last requests. She say no and the executioner shouts,
`Ready! ... Aim! ...`
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly the redhead yells, `TORNADO!` Once again, everyone is
startled and looks around, while the redhead silently slips away.
</P>
<P>
   By now the blonde has it all figured out, and the guard brings
her forward. The executioner asks if she has any last requests, she
says no and the executioner shouts, `Ready! ... Aim! ...` and the
blonde yells, `FIRE!`
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AIRLINE HUMOR &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are some actual humorous statements by several airline
flights crews. Occasionally, airline attendants make an effort to
make the `in-flight safety lecture` a bit more entertaining:
</P>
<P>
   `As we prepare for takeoff, please make sure your tray tables
and seat backs are fully upright in their most uncomfortable
position.`
</P>
<P>
   `There may be 50 ways to leave your lover, but there are only 4
ways out of this airplane...`
</P>
<P>
   `Your seat cushions can be used for floatation, and in the event
of an emergency water landing, please take them with our
compliments.`
</P>
<P>
   `We do feature a smoking section on this flight; if you must
smoke, contact a member of the flight crew and we will escort you
to the wing of the airplane.`
</P>
<P>
   `Smoking in the lavatories is prohibited. Any person caught
smoking in the lavatories will be asked to leave the plane
immediately.`
</P>
<P>
   `Good morning. As we leave Dallas, it's warm, the sun is
shining, and the birds are singing. We are going to Charlotte,
where it's dark, windy and raining. Why in the world y'all wanna go
there I really don't know.`
</P>
<P>
   Pilot: `Folks, we have reached our cruising altitude now, so I
am going to switch the seat belt sign off. Feel free to move about
as you wish, but please stay inside the plane till we land... it's
a bit cold outside, and if you walk on the wings it affects the
flight pattern.`
</P>
<P>
   Pilot _ `Folks, if you were with us last week, we never got
around to mentioning that it was National Procrastination Day. If
you get a chance this week, please try to celebrate it. If you
can't get to it, then maybe try to do it at the weekend, but no big
rush. Have a nice day.`
</P>
<P>
   And, after landing: `Thank you for flying Delta Business
Express. We hope you enjoyed giving us the business as much as we
enjoyed taking you for a ride.`
</P>
<P>
   `Last one off the plane must clean it.`
</P>
<P>
   `If you are so lucky to be traveling with small children...`
</P>
<P>
   And from the pilot during his welcome message: `We are pleased
to have some of the best flight attendants in the industry...
Unfortunately none of them are on this flight...`!
</P>
<P>
   &UR; QUOTABLES FROM NBC'S 'THE TONIGHT SHOW WITH JAY LENO' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``Scientists now think birds descended from dinosaurs. I think
that's true. Look how fast 'Godzilla' flew out of the theaters.''
</P>
<P>
   ``12,000 fires are burning out of control in Florida. In fact,
senior citizens are fleeing Miami at speeds of up to 10 miles an
hour.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Had a great night last night. I really slept. I slept like an
airline pilot at 30,000 feet.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Gene Siskel is recovering from brain surgery. Who would have
guessed by looking at the two of them that Ebert was the healthy
one.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The number one movie was 'The X-Files.' David Duchovny and
Gillian Anderson play two government officials who don't have sex
and believe there is a giant conspiracy out there. Actually, it's
based on Bill and Hillary Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For the second straight day, John and Patricia Ramsey
voluntarily met with Boulder, Colorado officials and afterward they
complained about mistreatment by the police. The limo was late, the
oysters were not chilled enough, police served the wrong wine with
dinner. Just a travesty.''
</P>
