<HEADER>
A4328 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROOTSIDE-AZR &LR;      06-30 1144
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROOTSIDE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIZING UP THE MANY ROOT BEERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD NILSEN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) - Comparing root beers is like comparing apples and
oranges. Because there is not one thing that is root beer, but a
whole family of things, I subdivided the category into six
sections.
</P>
<P>
   The process of tasting is much like that of comparing wines. You
pour the cold drink into a glass and watch its head. Some root
beers are stronger on foam; others fizz like colas. Only one _
Henry Weinhard _ had a head that lasted to the end of the glass.
</P>
<P>
   Then you hold the glass under your nose and wiggle it, sloshing
around the beverage. Some had decided ``nose,'' others really
didn't smell like anything. Most had a decided vanilla odor.
</P>
<P>
   A small taste comes next, swishing it around in your mouth to
get at all the contrasting flavors. You try to separate the
component parts, although in most cases nowadays, the only thing
you find is that the basic flavor tastes artificial rather than
vegetative. That isn't necessarily bad, if the flavor is pleasant.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, and most important diagnostically, you swallow, inhale
and feel for an aftertaste, looking for those aromatic, herby
flavors that shade the character of basic taste.
</P>
<P>
   The best root beers had good foam, a slight aroma, a solid
sassafras taste (even if artificial), and an interesting, lingering
herbal afterlife at the back of the palate.
</P>
<P>
   We bought examples of every root beer we could find in Arizona,
save only those ``home-brewed'' by local establishments, and not
available in stores. In the end, there were 20 different brands we
tried.
</P>
<P>
   The envelope, please: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mainstream
</P>
<P>
   These are the buy-at-the-store brands that most people can find.
They are uniformly good.
</P>
<P>
   There is a tie for best in the category between Hires and Dad's.
Hires is the standard for ``regular'' root beer, but Dad's, with
its stronger hint of licorice, has a more individual flavor. Both
also scored high with foam, body and aftertaste.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart's and IBC were also strong contenders and some people
strongly prefer them to the previous two. The falloff, if any, is
minuscule.
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;W, the bestselling root beer, is acceptable, but bland, and
with a heavy vanilla flavor. It is a long way from the franchise
A&AMP;W root beer that used to be sold in the root-beer stands in those
paper containers that were halfway between cups and Chinese takeout
food cartons.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the grocery store repackagings, sold for bargain prices,
compare well with the mainstream brands. Trader Joe's root beer,
sold in cans and bottles, ranked high, although the two versions
tasted slightly different.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Pirate's Keg tasted OK, but it has caffeine and is,
therefore, disqualified.
</P>
<P>
   Specialty
</P>
<P>
   Some call them microbrew, some call them premium, but they cost
more and you don't always get better quality for your expense.
</P>
<P>
   The clear winner is Henry Weinhard. It has the least traditional
flavor, heavily influenced by the honey used to flavor it, but the
flavor it has is better than anything else we tested. It has a
molasses-edged darkness to its taste and a head that lasted longer
than any other testee.
</P>
<P>
   Virgil's is an English brand with an obviously herbal taste.
Nutmeg, anise and wintergreen are mentioned on the label. Some
people like it a lot; others complain that it is not really root
beer.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Kemper is fine, but tastes much like a mainstream root
beer and had nothing to separate it from the pack except the extra
cost.
</P>
<P>
   Mystic Seaport, however, was very bad, with a heavy medicinal
flavor, like a carbonated throat lozenge. It is said to contain
camomile, ginger and tarragon and tastes like a liquid salad.
</P>
<P>
   ``Corporate''
</P>
<P>
   When Pepsi and Coke get their corporate hands on a product, they
put all the money into marketing, not enough into product.
</P>
<P>
   Pepsi sells Mug root beer, which is not actually objectionable,
but is one of the blandest of the tested products.
</P>
<P>
   And Barq's, sold by Coca-Cola, is disqualified for two reasons:
It isn't really a root beer, despite the label puffery that claims
it is ``Good Old Tyme Root Beer.'' It was invented, like Coke, Dr
Pepper or Moxie, to be (begin ital) sui generis. (end ital) No one
claimed it was a root beer until 1995, when Coke took over and
couldn't figure out how to market it. It tastes like a combination
cola and root drink, with a little Dr Pepper fruitiness thrown in.
</P>
<P>
   But worse, it contains caffeine, and nothing with caffeine is
allowed.
</P>
<P>
   Sarsaparillas
</P>
<P>
   Sarsaparilla is a variety of root beer, invented in the West,
where sassafras, which formed the basis for root beer, didn't grow.
The root of the sarsaparilla plant, native to Central America, was
substituted.
</P>
<P>
   Whether any of the current sarsaparillas actually contain
sarsaparilla root is questionable: All their formulas are
proprietary and they aren't saying. But the three brands we tested
all had a strong wintergreen taste.
</P>
<P>
   Sioux City Sarsaparilla was the winner. It pours out red into
the glass, fizzes nicely, has what wine drinkers call ``a good
nose,'' and a complex flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Ol' Bob Miller was similar, but a little sweeter.
</P>
<P>
   And Mystic Seaport was overpoweringly sweet, with a strong honey
flavor. Its label declares vanilla, anise, cassia and wintergreen
as the flavoring agents, but the sweetness drowns it all out. Like
syrup.
</P>
<P>
   Birch beers
</P>
<P>
   It was hard to tell the difference between most birch beers and
sarsaparillas. They all have a wintergreen taste. We tasted two
brands.
</P>
<P>
   Sioux City was good and poured out red, like the sarsaparilla.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Kemper was clear, an unusual look in the glass, and had a
more subtle taste, which means, though, it had less taste.
</P>
<P>
   Cream sodas
</P>
<P>
   These are vanilla flavored sodas, without the herbal additions
of classic root beers. This category gave us our best taste and the
only completely undrinkable product we bought.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Weinhard Vanilla Cream soda is one of the best-flavored
products on the market. I don't know what they do to it that makes
it different from other cream sodas _ the label claims different
varieties of vanilla bean _ but it works. The stuff is nearly
addictive.
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;W cream soda was disqualified, not on account of taste, which
is acceptable and middle of the road, but because it quietly and
unannounced sneaks in caffeine. Be warned, if you are
caffeine-sensitive, A&AMP;W cream soda will keep you up and jittery.
</P>
<P>
   And Mystic Seaport Cream Ale was wretched. It had a strong odor,
was way, way too sweet, and had an aftertaste of burned coconut. It
was like drinking liquid Twinkies filling, but with an off-taste.
Nobody who I shared it with could stand it, and some had to rinse
their mouths out. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
