<HEADER>
A4334 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FRANCE-AMERICAN-CENTE     06-30 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRANCE-AMERICAN-CENTER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRENCH PLAN TO BUY AMERICAN CENTER'S PARIS HOME 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By ALAN RIDING   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ When the new American Center here was inaugurated by
Hillary Rodham Clinton in June 1994, the $41 million building
designed by Frank Gehry looked set to become a hothouse of American
artistic creativity. Instead, barely 19 months later, the center
suspended its activities for lack of funds and its only remaining
asset, its ultramodern headquarters in eastern Paris, was put up
for sale.
</P>
<P>
   The American Center as such survived as a legal entity, but it
could do nothing until it had sold the Gehry building. And for the
best part of 30 months, it stood empty. Tuesday, the search for a
buyer finally ended when France's Ministry of Culture announced
that it planned to acquire the building and turn it into a new
Maison du Cinema, housing a film library and theaters.
</P>
<P>
   If the deal becomes final in the coming weeks, as expected, it
will conclude the most painful and embarrassing chapter in the
center's 67-year history and the beginning of a new era in which
the revenues from the sale will be used to create a fund to promote
American culture. But no longer will there be a physical location
where American and French students and artists can gather.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are delighted that Frank Gehry's exciting state-of-the-art
building will continue to be a place of access, openness and
community for cultural affairs,'' the American Center's chairman,
Frederick B. Henry, said in a telephone interview Tuesday. ``We can
also now prepare to continue the center's mission of supporting
cultural, educational and artistic activities.''
</P>
<P>
   French officials refused to give the exact purchase price,
noting that the deal still required approval by the French
equivalent of the General Services Administration in the United
States, although they estimated the cost of buying and adapting the
building at around $34 million. They estimated the cost of
renovating the building alone at about $13 million, which would
place the proposed purchase price at close to $21 million.
</P>
<P>
   The $20 million difference between the original cost of the
Gehry building and its current market value is the price that the
American Center has paid for its decision in the mid-1980s to sell
its run-down but popular Left Bank home on the Boulevard Raspail
and construct an entirely new headquarters. Its mistake was to
spend almost all its money on the new building and to count on
donations to finance the $6 million annual cost of running it.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after it opened, the center realized it was hard-pressed
for cash and was unable to pay an outstanding $3.4 million debt to
the Paris city government. It mounted a campaign for contributions
from American corporations with interests in France, but almost no
new money was forthcoming. Last December, thanks to a loan from the
New York-based Bohen Foundation, which Henry also leads, the center
was finally able to settle its debt with the city.
</P>
<P>
   Henry said the center's board had already begun studying how it
should use its new fund to promote cultural activities. ``The board
has made no final decision,'' he said, ``but our inclination is to
seek a broader constituency than in the past. For example, we may
make grants, which would be reactive, but we may also be more
proactive by forming partnerships with other organizations. We're
considering different models.''
</P>
<P>
   The center has had enough cash to maintain the Gehry building
since its closing in February 1996. Marc Nicholas, a senior
official from the National Center of Cinematography who was
involved in selecting the building, said that it can be adapted for
use as the Maison du Cinema more quickly and more cheaply than
alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good that it will become a house of culture,'' said
Marie-Claude Beaud, the center's last director, who now runs the
Museum of Decorative Arts here. ``Far better than some of the
alternatives that were discussed, like turning it into the
headquarters of the Gaullist party or a tribunal to judge terrorist
cases or even a Soccer Museum.''
</P>
<P>
   Jean-Claude Moreno, who heads the Ministry of Culture's building
office, said that Gehry had been consulted about changes that might
be carried out by a different architect before the Maison du Cinema
opens in 2000. ``Gehry said he was happy that the building will
recover a cultural role, its original function,'' Moreno added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-98 1743EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
