<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-POLL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLL SHOWS NEW YORKERS PREFER EDUCATION, TREATMENT OVER NEW
PRISONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TRACEY TULLY  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Given a blank check, New Yorkers would spend more
to improve mass transit, education and health care. They are also
willing to pay higher prices for milk to help struggling dairy
farmers.
</P>
<P>
   But they are not anxious to boost funding for welfare or build
new prisons, according to a recent Zogby International poll
commissioned by the Albany Times Union and Syracuse Newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the recent survey of 703 likely voters suggests the
electorate is feeling generous, both with the state's bank account
and in their own attitudes toward rehabilitating convicted felons.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, despite the attention that came with Gov. George
Pataki's strong but unsuccessful push to delay parole for
first-time violent offenders, the public appears convinced that
longer sentences are only part of the solution.
</P>
<P>
   Three out of every four people questioned agreed with Pataki and
would like to eliminate parole for inmates convicted of violent
crimes.
</P>
<P>
   But nearly as many also said the state should send drug
offenders to treatment programs rather than build new prisons. And
slightly more than 70 percent said New York should restore prison
programs designed to provide inmates with educational opportunities
and job training.
</P>
<P>
   ``People understand that building more prisons does not reduce
crime,'' Peter Slocum, a spokesman and policy adviser to the
Democratic minority in the state Senate, said in response to the
poll results. ``This is common-sense stuff and the people
understand it.''
</P>
<P>
   Jenna's Law, which was named for slain Albany nursing student
Jenna Grieshaber, would have blocked the parole board from
releasing violent felons before they had served 85 percent of their
sentences and added a post-release supervisory period. A compromise
version of the bill _ which did not include increased drug
treatment or educational programs _ died in the Assembly this year.
</P>
<P>
   The poll showed 70 percent of the public in favor of drug
treatment over stiff sentences, and the results also would appear
to bode well for those who support changes in the Rockefeller-era
drug laws, which impose harsh, mandatory prison terms on drug
offenders.
</P>
<P>
   A bipartisan group is evaluating the 25-year-old laws with an
eye toward convincing the Legislature and governor to make changes
to the legislation that is frequently cited as a primary reason for
prison overcrowding.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel that judges that should be given discretion and more
effort should be put into rehabilitation rather than strictly
incarceration,'' said former state Sen. Warren Anderson, who was
the Senate majority leader when the laws were enacted in 1973.
Although he supported the laws then, he now believes they are
outmoded.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope that at some point the Legislature and the governor
will move in the direction that we've been encouraging,'' Anderson
said.
</P>
<P>
   Voters appeared split on other controversial issues debated
during the legislative session that ended just over a week ago. It
was a draw, for example, over whether New York should permit casino
gambling on non-Indian lands. Of those questioned, half said they
supported casino gambling, while an equal number said they were
opposed.
</P>
<P>
   A measure that would have started the lengthy process of placing
a casino gambling question on the ballot passed the Assembly this
month, but failed to reach a vote in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Those surveyed also appeared ambivalent over the governor's
decision to veto $1.6 billion in spending and borrowing from the
1998-99 fiscal year budget, an indication that the message
Democratic candidates for governor have been attempting to spread
is either not being heard or not being understood.
</P>
<P>
   While the governor did use his veto power to make some cuts, the
election-year budget Pataki proposed and approved increases state
spending by 9.8 percent, more than three times the inflation rate.
It also creates budget deficits of between $3.75 billion and $4.8
billion in 2001, depending on whether it is the governor or the
comptroller who is counting.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver, D-Manhattan, has led a
campaign to criticize Pataki's vetoes and Democratic candidates
also have seized on the opportunity to try to cast the Republican
governor as uncaring. The message has not, apparently, gotten
through.
</P>
<P>
   Poll results show that 20.5 percent of those questioned said
Pataki was right to use his veto power, while 36.7 percent said he
was wrong. But an even larger percentage _ 38.8 percent _ said they
did not have enough information to make a decision.
</P>
<P>
   The sample group did appear to have strong attitudes on new
spending.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no built-in rejection to spending this year,''
pollster John Zogby said.
</P>
<P>
   But observers cautioned that it is not unusual for voters to
support new or enhanced programs, yet balk when it comes to paying
for them. The poll question did not ask whether people would
support new spending even if it meant a tax increase.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want the programs, but if you ask them if they want the
taxes, they'll say, `No.' And most people are more motivated on the
tax issue,'' said Harry Spector, a spokesman for Assembly Minority
Leader John Faso, R-Kinderhook.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Rein, a researcher with the Citizens Budget Commission, a
non-partisan and nonprofit budget watchdog group, said it was more
accurate to interpret the poll results as a vote for more
responsive and efficient government, not increased spending.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the abstract, everything else being equal, there's a lot of
things people want to spend money on,'' Rein said. ``They're
dissatisfied with a lot of the services they get, and there's
always an impulse: Spend more money. But what we believe you need
to do is increase efficiencies and with the same amount of money
get more bang for your buck.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
