A4345 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPAIN-PHILIP-II-NYT &LR;      06-30 1029
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPAIN-PHILIP-II-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCRAPING AWAY AT THE `BLACK LEGEND' OF A SPANISH KING  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By AL GOODMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN LORENZO DE EL ESCORIAL, Spain _ King Philip II not only lost
the invincible Armada in 1588 while trying to invade England but
also sunk in most history books, as the epitome of the cruelty and
intolerance associated with imperial Spain.
</P>
<P>
   He promoted Catholicism at sword point against Protestants and
Turks. His armies at their zenith controlled the largest empire of
the era, a swath of territory so vast, from Europe to Asia to the
Americas, that yes, the sun never set upon it.
</P>
<P>
   But now, on the 400th anniversary of his death, the government
has organized three major art exhibitions to portray a different
side of Philip, as a Renaissance connoisseur of art and literature,
a bon vivant in his youth who loved royal parties and a devoted
family man.
</P>
<P>
   ``A monarch who collected Titian and Bosch couldn't be such a
demon,'' said Juan Martinez, an art expert on the exhibition team.
</P>
<P>
   Philip collected some 2,000 paintings, including the 40 by
Titian and six by Hieronymous Bosch. He also collected 5,000 books,
far more than his Spanish royal predecessors did.
</P>
<P>
   The question remains whether ruthlessness would be at odds with
refined intellectual tastes. So the commemoration is stirring
discussion of just how much to clean up the image of Philip, and
Spaniards seem to be warming to the debate.
</P>
<P>
   Two recent biographies, ``Philip of Spain'' by Henry Kamen, an
English historian, and ``Philip II and His Time'' by Manuel
Fernandez Alvarez, a Spanish historian, dispel stereotypes of an
austere, narrow-minded Philip. Their combined sales of 60,000
copies are remarkable for the genre.
</P>
<P>
   The commemoration promises just as full and fair a look at
Philip, addressing his ``lights and shadows.'' The first
exhibition, ``The Hispanic Monarchy,'' opened on June 1 and runs
through Oct. 10 at El Escorial, the mammoth granite palace and
monastery he built 30 miles northwest of Madrid.
</P>
<P>
   The other two begin in October: ``A Prince of the Renaissance''
at the Prado, and ``The King's Land and Men'' at the Villena Palace
in Philip's native city of Valladolid, 120 miles northwest of
Madrid. More than 500,000 visitors are expected at the three shows.
</P>
<P>
   El Escorial, with four sharply pointed towers at its corners,
provides a powerful backdrop for the first show. It was here that
Philip received the bad news about the Armada, and here that he
died in Spartan quarters at age 71 and was buried.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition includes 514 items, including paintings, books,
documents, and jewelry recovered from sunken Armada ships, the
latter on loan from the Ulster Museum in Belfast and being shown in
Spain for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   There are two portraits of the proud, steely-eyed young Philip
wearing black armor with gold inlay, one by Titian in 1551 and the
other by the Spanish painter Antonio Moro in 1557, the year after
he took the throne. Each speaks to Philip's power, while the
numerous religious icons on view show his devotion to Catholicism.
</P>
<P>
   Some Spanish conservatives defended him as a model ruler against
his numerous detractors, particularly English and Dutch Protestants
who spread what became known as the ``black legend,'' focusing on
his oppressive tactics in Europe and the New World. That view was
disseminated in books of the period, and six such volumes are part
of the show.
</P>
<P>
   The show at El Escorial takes a fresh approach by emphasizing
the women in Philip's life: his mother, aunts, sisters, his four
wives, and his daughters. They generally helped him build the
empire through their strategic family alliances with other nations,
and they are pictured in chronological order.
</P>
<P>
   He outlived all four wives. His first marriage, at age 16 to
Maria of Portugal, bore a potential heir, Don Carlos, later the
subject of the Verdi opera that bears his name. Next was the stern
queen of England, Mary Tudor, a decade older than Philip.
</P>
<P>
   The third, the young Isabel de Valois, was the mother of his
favorite daughters. A portrait by the Spaniard Alonso Sanchez
Coello, dated 1568-1569, shows the two girls, almost holding hands,
dressed in full-length reddish gowns. Philip often kept the elder
daughter, Isabel Clara Eugenia, at his side.
</P>
<P>
   His fourth wife, the fair Anne of Austria, 22 years his junior,
bore the eventual heir, Philip III. But Philip outlived six of his
eight children.
</P>
<P>
   The show also highlights Philip's early training in Renaissance
values, displaying his handsome books on medicine, science and
music, and how he simply enjoyed himself.
</P>
<P>
   An anonymous watercolor, ``Enchanted Salon of the Binche
Palace,'' depicts one of the lavish parties he attended, in 1549
near Brussels. Three tables stacked like sumptuous bunk beds brim
with porcelain and crystal dishes bearing savories and sweets.
After the guests tired of the treats on the bottom table, the
exhibition relates, the next one was lowered mechanically.
</P>
<P>
   Another striking piece is an anonymous oil, circa 1581, showing
Philip in a suit of gold for his coronation as king of Portugal.
Usually the king wore black in his later years, but the exhibition
historian, Feliciano Barrios, said that the painting showed that
Philip was willing to respect local custom, as the colorful
ceremony in Portugal demanded.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the exhibition, which includes various battle scene
paintings of Spanish victories over the Turks or French and the
Armada's fateful route to England, distinctly conveys the rough
challenges of the era. Even Philip's dog wore a coat of armor,
which is also on display.
</P>
<P>
   The Spanish empire reached its peak during Philip's reign, and
after the Armada's defeat began its slow decline. Kamen argues that
the pragmatic, even cruel policies of his monarchy did not
necessarily mean that Philip himself was an ogre.
</P>
<P>
   But he and some other experts do not predict a quick revision of
attitudes toward Philip.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a rethinking and that is the best one can ask for,''
Kamen said. ``One cannot change views overnight.''
</P>
<P>
   And perhaps not even in 400 years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
