<HEADLINE>
FOR OUTDOOR GRAZING, SOME HELP FROM CAMPAGNA 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By FLORENCE FABRICANT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ At Campagna Home, 29 East 21st Street, assembling a
Fourth of July picnic from scratch is a pleasure. This spacious new
shop, a sibling of Campagna, the restaurant across the street,
carries not only salamis, cheeses and prepared foods like cold
antipasto dishes, but also the accessories you'll need.
</P>
<P>
   His wicker picnic basket can hold food for four. And filled with
$50 or more worth of al fresco fare, basket costs $17, not $42.
</P>
<P>
   Most salad items, like marinated mushrooms, roasted potatoes and
grilled eggplant, are $9 to $12 a pound. The shop also has bread
from Sullivan Street Bakery and excellent fresh meats from DeBragga
&AMP; Spitler, a wholesale butcher that supplies restaurants. Mark
Strausman, Campagna's owner and chef, roasts or grills the meat;
grilled chicken is $2.79 a pound.
</P>
<P>
   Lovely paper plates and napkins ($3.50 to $5 a package) are also
available, as well as Belgian linen napkins ($7.50 each). A little
tempered glass cutting board from Germany is $12.50, and there are
extremely well-balanced knives, also from Germany; a six inch one,
good to tuck into the basket, is $45. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There is no better picnic food than a sandwich. And there is no
better place to buy a sandwich made on great fresh bread than at a
bakery. The excellent bakeries around town, many of them connected
to restaurants, have inventive sandwiches galore.
</P>
<P>
   All these bakeries are open on Saturdays and Sundays. At
Columbus Bakery, 474 Columbus Avenue (83d Street) and 959 First
Avenue (52d Street), the grilled portobello mushroom sandwich, with
fontina cheese, pesto and vegetable slaw on baguette ($6.95), is a
good choice. Francophiles would not find fault with the ham and
Gruyere on buttered baguette ($6) from Balthazar Bakery, 80 Spring
Street (Broadway).
</P>
<P>
   The mozzarella, tomato and basil sandwich on Eli's onion ficelle
($6) from E.A.T., 1064 Madison Avenue (81st Street), has become
something of a classic. It's $3.50 at the Vinegar Factory, 431 East
91st Street, also owned by Eli Zabar. At Amy's Bread, 75 Ninth
Avenue (15th Street) and 672 Ninth Avenue (46th Street), sandwiches
on semolina-fennel bread include tuna salad ($3.60) and roast
turkey ($4.50). Bouley Bakery, 120 West Broadway (Duane Street),
makes a Cape Cod flounder sandwich with tomatoes on rustic mountain
bread for $7.50.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike most of the bakeries, which have sandwiches wrapped and
ready to go, Le Pain Quotidien, 1131 Madison Avenue (84th Street),
makes its sandwiches to order, including smoked salmon with dill
sauce ($13), including a mixed salad on the side.
</P>
<P>
   The new Blue Ribbon Bakery, 33 Downing Street (Bedford Street),
has a smoked peppered bluefish sandwich with cream cheese on walnut
bread for $7.50. The bakery does not open until noon, so it's not
the place to go if you're embarking on an excursion to the country
and need to get an early start. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Murray's Cheese Shop, 257 Bleecker Street (Cornelia Street), has
assembled cheese packages for picnics. A French assortment has
three cheeses plus peasant bread, duck mousse, sausage, cornichons
and olives; an Italian array includes mozzarella, a creamy
pagliattina (similar to Camembert), sun-dried tomatoes and roasted
peppers, plus bread and olives. Each is $50. Overnight delivery in
New York, New Jersey or Connecticut is $15 extra. To order: (212)
243-3289 or (888) 692-4339. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here's an unusual new item to add to the picnic basket: a bottle
of cold borscht. Manischewitz has just started selling it in a
single-serving, 16-ounce bottle, without bits of beet in the
bottom. The borscht is about $1.30 in supermarkets. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The First Brands Corp., which makes Glad plastic wrap and bags,
now has lightweight stackable plastic containers with tight-sealing
lids, perfect for picnic food. They come in a deep 24-ounce size
and a shallow 25-ounce size. A package of five is about $2.40 in
supermarkets. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cherries are among the most convenient summer picnic fruits. And
those from upstate farms have started coming into the market,
including the golden variety. Growers say it's one of the best
seasons for these. Locust Grove Farms stand in the Union Square
Greenmarket has them for $3 a pint basket. At Grace's Marketplace,
1237 Third Avenue (71st Street), they are $3.99 a quart. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But do not plan on buying doughnuts from Georgie's Pastry Shop,
50 West 125th Street, for your picnic, because it has closed.
Similarly, doughnuts and doughnut holes from Fina Pastries, 344
Bowery (Third Street), will not be available because that shop, too
has closed. Fina is reopening in the fall at 1516 First Avenue
(79th Street), but the owners of Georgie's have retired, so those
wonderful doughnuts are gone for good. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
