<HEADLINE>
GROUP TEAMS WITH HEALTH-CARE CENTERS TO TEACH GUN SAFETY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Citing recent killings by children who gained
access to firearms, a national gun-control group Tuesday solicited
the medical community's help in teaching youngsters that guns can
kill and urging firearm owners to lock up their weapons when not in
use.
</P>
<P>
   The Center to Prevent Handgun Violence will provide brochures
and posters to doctors and their aides encouraging them to tell
young patients and parents that guns intended for protection can
end up killing family members if left within children's reach, said
Sarah Brady, the group's chairman.
</P>
<P>
   The Washington-based center plans to disseminate its brochures
and posters at medical conventions and through health-care groups,
such as the American Academy of Pediatrics, she added.
</P>
<P>
   National Rifle Association spokesman Jim Manown said the
center's public education campaign is no different than what the
gun group has been telling families and children for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Firearms should be stored so that they are not accessible to
unauthorized persons,'' Manown said. NRA instructs children who see
guns to ``stop, don't touch, leave the area, tell an adult,'' he
added.
</P>
<P>
   Brady said that conveying the center's message on gun safety
will be as easy for health-care workers as their age-old practice
of telling parents to store poisonous chemicals out of youngsters'
reach. The group's education campaign, which extends to all medical
personnel, broadens the center's original effort in 1994 to
encourage pediatricians to tell gun-owning parents that children
will find and shoot firearms not kept in a locked place.
</P>
<P>
   Fourteen children per day are killed with guns, the National
Center for Health Statistics reported last year. Many of these
deaths can be prevented if greater efforts are made to deny
children access to firearms, Brady said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time to vaccinate our children against gun violence as we
have with other infectious and dangerous diseases,'' she added.
``Many families who only think of their firearms in terms of crime
or self-defense need to realize that deaths and injuries from
firearms are as much of a health risk in this country as many types
of cancer.''
</P>
<P>
   The launch of the public education campaign, which Metropolitan
Life Foundation is funding, follows a spate of school shootings in
recent months. Students have been arrested in connection with
deadly incidents at schools in Jonesboro, Ark.; Springfield, Ore.;
Pearl, Miss.; and West Paducah., Ky.
</P>
<P>
   ``The high-profile shootings we all heard about this year are
just the tip of the iceberg,'' Brady said. ``Around the nation,
access to guns is killing our children.''
</P>
<P>
   Health and Human Services Secretary Donna Shalala praised the
center's enlistment of health-care workers in encouraging safe gun
storage. She noted that doctors and their assistants have great
credibility with the children and parents they heal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who better to be the messengers of firearm safety?'' said
Shalala. ``I think most health care providers would agree it's a
far, far better thing to protect children from gunshot wounds than
to fight to save their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
