<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROOTFACTS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROOT BEER FROM A TO Z 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD NILSEN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) -
</P>
<P>
   TIME LINE OF SOFT DRINKS
</P>
<P>
   1798 _ The term ``soda water'' first is used. &QL; 
1809 _ First U.S. patent issued for the manufacture of imitation
mineral waters. &QL; 
1815 _ The first soda fountain is patented. &QL; 
1835 _ The first bottled soda water is produced in the United
States. &QL; 
1838 _ Sweetened, flavored mineral water first sold, in
Philadelphia by perfume dealer Eugene Roussel. &QL; 
1851 _ Ginger ale is introduced in Ireland. &QL; 
1861 _ Soft drinks first referred to as ``soda pop.'' &QL; 
1874 _ The first ice-cream soda is served. &QL; 
1876 _ Root beer commercially produced, by Charles Hires. &QL; 
1881 _ First cola-flavored beverage is introduced. &QL; 
1892 _ Invention of the bottle cap. &QL; 
1898 _ Barq's introduced in Biloxi, Miss. &QL; 
1919 _ Precursor of A&AMP;W opens for business as a Lodi, Calif.,
restaurant. Root beer goes for 5 cents. &QL; 
1920s _ First vending machines dispense soda in cups. &QL; 
1923 _ Introduction of six-pack cartons, called ``Hom-Paks.'' &QL; 
1929 _ Bib-Label Lithiated Lemon-Lime Soda introduced and . . . &QL; 
1936 _ Changes name to 7Up. &QL; 
1946 _ First diet drinks. &QL; 
1957 _ First aluminum cans. &QL; 
1962 _ Easy opening, pull-ring tabs introduced for soda cans. &QL; 
1965 _ Vending machines first dispense cans. &QL; 
1970 _ Plastic bottles first used for soft drinks. &QL; 
1974 _ The stay-on tab introduced to drink cans. &QL; 
1981 _ Talking vending machines are invented. &QL; 
Source: National Soft Drink Association &QL;
</P>
<P>
   INGREDIENTS
</P>
<P>
   Traditional root beers primarily were flavored with sassafras
root altered by the addition of aromatics. Since sassafras was
outlawed in 1960 by the federal Food and Drug Administration,
commercial root-beer manufacturers have had to find substitutes,
including artificial root-beer flavoring, ``de-poisoned'' sassafras
and wintergreen, none of which is entirely satisfactory.
</P>
<P>
   Commercial root-beer recipes are proprietary, but among the
ingredients used are: allspice, anise, birch bark, burdock root,
coriander seed, dandelion root, ginger, honey, hops, juniper
berries, licorice, molasses, prickly ash bark, sarsaparilla root,
spicewood, spikenard root, wild cherry bark, wintergreen oil,
yellow dock
</P>
<P>
   TRIVIA
</P>
<P>
   _ In 1997, the retail sale of soft drinks totaled more than $54
billion.
</P>
<P>
   _In the same year, per capita consumption of soft drinks was 54
gallons, a total of more than 14 billion gallons of soda pop.
</P>
<P>
   _ Root beer accounts for only 3 percent of the U.S. soft-drink
market.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sales of the seven largest root-beer brands have grown to
219.2 million cases (in a 1993 survey), up from 141.7 million cases
in 1986. &QL; 
_ There are about 200 brands currently made. &QL; 
_ A&AMP;W is the top-selling brand, followed by Barq's and Mug. &QL; 
Source: National Soft Drink Association &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GEEKS AND ROOT BEER
</P>
<P>
   Root beer must be awfully popular with computer geeks, judging
by the dozens and dozens of Web sites on the subject. They offer
history, information, and lots and lots of taste tests.
</P>
<P>
   I need to tell you about only one, ``Anthony's Root Beer
Barrel,'' because it lists about 60 links to other sites. It's root
beer hog heaven:
</P>
<P>
   www.annoyances.com/rb
</P>
<P>
   Check it out. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
