<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 17:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4371 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRITAIN-ROYAL-OPERA-A     06-30 1025
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-ROYAL-OPERA-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GETTING BRITAIN'S ROYAL OPERA HOUSE IN ORDER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV.: a photo for use with this story is being sent to NYT
photo clients. Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by
calling 212 556-4204.) 
(HLW) 
 By SARAH LYALL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ The Royal Opera House, dogged by accusations of elitism
and financial mismanagement, came under renewed attack on Tuesday
when a government-sponsored report said that its internal
organization often ``resembles a World War I battlefield.''
</P>
<P>
   The report, by Sir Richard Eyre, the former artistic director of
the Royal National Theater and one of the most respected champions
of the performing arts in Britain, said that to justify its annual
$24-million government subsidy and earn the public's confidence,
the Royal Opera House would have to get itself in order rapidly.
Among other things, he said, it should develop an effective, open
financial plan; draw new patrons with lower prices and better
education programs; put an end to its entrenched culture of
highhanded arrogance; stop issuing free tickets ``to the London
glitterati'' and establish better lines of internal communication.
</P>
<P>
   The management of the opera house, which includes the Royal
Opera and the Royal Ballet, ``has become ever more deeply mired in
ever more insoluble financial problems,'' Sir Richard said in the
report, ``even as its ability to plan and organize has been
hampered by chaos and misunderstanding.''
</P>
<P>
   He continued: ``All too often, the situation resembles a First
World War battlefield, where the poor bloody infantry are trying to
fulfill a strategy about which they haven't been consulted, and
whose outcome is simply a matter of willful optimism or blithe
unconcern to its creators.''
</P>
<P>
   The opera house management recently said it needed an additional
government subsidy of $16.5 million to $25 million a year to remain
solvent. While saying the request ``was not substantiated by an
effective business plan,'' and that an increase now would be ``a
reward for incompetence,'' Sir Richard said that when the opera
house had finished reforming itself, it was likely to need more
public money.
</P>
<P>
   Sir Richard's report was commissioned in November by Chris
Smith, Britain's culture secretary, in response to the series of
problems that have bedeviled the opera house. In the last 13 months
two of its top executives have abruptly quit, saying they could not
do the job.
</P>
<P>
   In December, its board of directors resigned en masse. (Several
were later reinstated). And, as its home undergoes a $367-million
refurbishing (to be completed next year) that is heavily financed
by the National Lottery, the Royal Opera House is running at an
$8.25 million deficit, with its two companies losing money
performing to often meager crowds in other locations.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's report also looked at two other major performing arts
organizations, the English National Opera and Sadler's Wells, but
reserved most of its criticism for the Royal Opera House, a
showcase for performing arts here. The report also rejected several
of the more drastic measures proposed for the opera house's reform.
It dismissed, for instance, Smith's suggestion last year that the
Royal Opera and the English National Opera pool their resources and
perform from the same building. (The National Opera appears at the
Coliseum, near the Royal Opera House in Covent Garden.) And it
rejected the recent demand by Gerald Kaufman, chairman of the
Culture Committee in the House of Commons and one of the opera
house most venomous critics, that it be privatized.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my view, they have to close or find their own money,''
Kaufman said recently, in response to an assertion by the opera
house management that even if it initiated reforms to the
government's satisfaction, and even if every performance of every
production were to be sold out, it would still need more than $16
million more a year to break even. ``The state cannot go on pouring
money into an enterprise, whatever it is.''
</P>
<P>
   But Sir Richard, speaking to reporters on Tuesday, said that the
British support for the arts in general was woefully low. Echoing
complaints from other leaders of the traditional high arts,
including the director Sir Peter Hall, that the nation is
neglecting theater, classical music, dance, and opera in favor of
rock music and movies, Sir Richard said that the government should
drastically increase its grants to the arts, perhaps by as much as
$99 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   Sir Richard, Sir Peter, and other arts leaders voiced their
concerns at a meeting with Prime Minister Tony Blair on Monday
night. Sir Richard said that the prime minister ``nodded'' when
told the arts needed more money, but Smith said that Blair listened
rather than agreeing, and that no new money was yet forthcoming.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing at a news conference with Sir Richard, Smith said that
he welcomed the report's emphasis on the need for greater access to
the opera house, which has come under criticism for what, to some,
are prohibitively high prices. The opera house, which receives
comparatively little financing from private sources, charges as
much as $243 for a prime seat at the most elaborate opera. (For the
coming season, the top ticket price at the Metropolitan Opera in
Manhattan is $200.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I am pleased to see the weight the report gives to improving
access,'' Smith said. ``It is essential that the companies reach
new audiences and welcome new people in, rather than excluding them
by atmosphere and perceived elitism.'' He gave the opera house a
month to respond to Sir Richard's recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   The composer Michael Berkeley, a Royal Opera board member, said
that the board was ``very encouraged'' by the report and that it
had begun to carry out Sir Richard's proposals. ``He has clearly
addressed all the issues,'' Berkeley said. ``While he clearly
thinks that the previous managements have not run the house in the
best possible manner, he does recognize that if we are to meet our
targets for better management and better access, then we can't run
without more money.''
</P>
</TEXT>
