<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
 (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Wednesday, July 1, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call 212-556-4204.) 
(th) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Scattered showers and thunderstorms, some heavy, will develop
over northern New England on Wednesday as a potent upper-level
trough of low pressure swings slowly eastward over the region. On
the western flank of the trough, drier air from Canada will sweep
across the Great Lakes toward the central Appalachians on
northwesterly winds between 15 mph and 30 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Farther south, potent thunderstorms will erupt over parts of the
southern Middle Atlantic and Southeast states as jet stream
disturbances on the southern flank of the trough combine with a
stationary front to vigorously lift very warm and humid air. A few
of these storms will become severe, with damaging winds posing the
greatest threat.
</P>
<P>
   A few severe thunderstorms are likely on the western high Plains
and Front Range of the Rockies across western Kansas, western
Nebraska, eastern Colorado and eastern Wyoming as warm, moist air
flowing westward behind a stationary front is forced to rise up the
sloping terrain. Damaging winds and a few tornadoes are possible.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, isolated but large thunderstorms will flare over
parts of eastern Florida. The coverage of these storms will be
spotty and will likely not douse the fires that continue over parts
of the Sunshine State. A few storms could become very intense over
northeast Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the morning fog and low clouds will gradually dissipate
from northwest California to western Washington. Isolated afternoon
thunderstorms will speckle areas farther inland in these states.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: PLAINS HEAT
</P>
<P>
   The persistent heat in the southern Plains claimed an all-time
record on Monday, when the mercury soared to 110 degrees in Dodge
City, Kan. Records in the western Kansas town date back 124 years.
While the current heat wave is reaching memorable proportions, the
standard for intense heat in the Plains is still the summers of the
1930s. Many state records in the region date from that decade. In
1936, Kansas City reached 100 degrees or higher on 53 days from
June to September. The sparse rainfall that accompanied the heat
led to the agricultural disaster now called the Dust Bowl. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-98 1802EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980630.0216 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 18:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4380 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CUBA-ALBUM-2NDTAKE-NY     06-30 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBA-ALBUM-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: out there.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bither began targeting the album's logical market, literate 30-
and 40-year-olds who buy music to take part in a culture. Latin
radio in the United States has been resistant to Cuban music and
has barely played the record, partly out of fear of the reactions
of right-wing Cuban exile groups. Nonetheless, it has been a Top 3
Latin record since its release here, and the striking packaging,
including a well-made booklet, makes the CD more than music.
</P>
<P>
   For Cooder, the response to the music springs from a sense of
loss. As many of the great popular music traditions of the Americas
dating from the end of the last century to the middle of this
century vanish, audiences feel a nostalgic need to keep them
intact. And the traditions are still powerful for those who bother
to listen.
</P>
<P>
   ``The son, a Cuban style of music on the album, has everything
you need: improvisation, form, African rhythms, strange elliptical
rhythms with 19th-century chords,'' Cooder said. ``Where else are
you going to find master musicians with that sort of individuality?
Blues and country music and Hawaiian music are dead. Music like
this is dying everywhere. I have a feeling audiences want to hear
melodies and atmosphere. And they want an environment to believe
in, so they can say, `This is a place I can go, I can be in.'''
</P>
<P>
   Cooder's relationship with Cuban music dates to the 1960s, when
he lived in New York and picked up albums by the Trio Matamoros and
others. In the early 1970s, he visited Cuba on a tour boat with
Dizzy Gillespie, and the music there changed him.
</P>
<P>
   But Cooder has a son, Joachim (who plays on the record), and
needed money, so he took time off from touring to make movie
soundtracks. He recorded several acclaimed collaborations with Ali
Farka Toure, the African guitarist. And in 1996, when Nick Gold,
the owner of World Circuit, offered to send Cooder to Havana to
record with Cuban and African musicians, Cooder was ready.
</P>
<P>
   Gold greeted Cooder at the airport in Havana with bad news.
``Nick picks me up at the airport and says, `The Africans aren't
coming,''' Cooder said. ```Good,' I said. `Let's wail. It's fate
intervening.'''
</P>
<P>
   Things didn't go well at first. They looked for Gonzalez, the
pianist, and had been told he had died. People checked again, and
found him alive, but suffering from arthritis. Compay Segundo
couldn't record because he had another contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's a friendly country and the musicians all want to
play,'' Cooder said. ``It all came together.'' Cooder and Gold got
together with Juan de Marcos Gonzalez, the head of a well-respected
band, Sierra Maestra, and they attacked the problem of bringing
together a group. De Marcos directed the band and oversaw the
recording process.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to push the musicians along or you get the same old
stuff,'' Cooder said. ``What was going on in the recording room
were all these people jamming. I'd go: `Wait! What was that, that
little three-note line? That thing you sang was beautiful.'
</P>
<P>
   ``It's stupid to make just another record, you might as well not
bother. So the musicians figured this out, and Compay, he's smart,
he'd come in and say, `I have thought of a great song.' And he'd
remember a song a friend of his wrote in the 1930s. `Now you're
talking,' I'd say to him. `Give me another weird song.'''
</P>
<P>
   In Havana the response to the project has been mixed. Some
people are proud of the album's international success. But at a
news conference in Havana, de Marcos and Cooder were criticized for
supporting prerevolutionary music at the expense of the flowering
of musical talent since the revolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't hear modern Cuban music,'' Cooder said. ``So I
said, `I only know what I know, and I'm recording this music
because I know something about it.' I understand the issues,
there's this sense that the carpetbaggers are coming down. The
Cubans don't need me, but if I can help the situation there, I
will.''
</P>
<P>
   For all the record's success, Cuban music in the United States
is often a losing proposition. The concert Wednesday night, which
cost roughly $150,000, including transportation and lodging, will
lose substantial money, even though it's sold out.
</P>
<P>
   For political, social and musical reasons, Bither of Nonesuch
thought the first American concert of the band had to be at
Carnegie Hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll even lose money doing it, but it's well worth it,
because ultimately we'll sell records. So we're comfortable. We're
investing in our artists.''
</P>
<P>
   De Marcos sees it like a dream. ``We're realizing a social and
political opening, a way of changing the realities of two countries
that have been enemies for so long. This music is that powerful.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-98 1804EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980630.0217 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 18:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4385 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-`ARMAGEDDON'-TEX     06-30 0835
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-`ARMAGEDDON'-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOT EVEN BRUCE WILLIS CAN SAVE THE EARTH FROM `ARMAGEDDON'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Unlike ``Deep Impact,'' which teases viewers with major carnage
in the trailer but waits 'til the end of the movie to show any,
``Armageddon'' crushes New York City with a meteorite shower in the
first 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   It seems you have to be a stand-up comedian starring in a TV
sitcom to survive: Eddie Griffin of ``Malcolm &AMP; Eddie'' and Mark
Cooper of ``Hangin' With Mr. Cooper'' pull through, but you can't
say the same about midtown Manhattan. It's a mess, but then so is
this movie, perhaps the first to combine the steroid-injected
pushiness of an action movie with the lump-in-the-throat
sentimentality of a disaster picture. It's not a pleasant mix.
</P>
<P>
   The meteorite storm that pelts New York City is just an
appetizer. An asteroid ``the size of Texas'' is careening toward
Earth. The result? ``A global killer,'' intones NASA's Dan Truman
(Billy Bob Thornton, who gives a riveting, all-business
performance). The only solution? To drill into the core of the
asteroid and plant a charge to blow the thing up _ the same remedy
``Deep Impact'' used.
</P>
<P>
   ``Armageddon'' has that scramble-a-team-together vibe of many of
producer Jerry Bruckheimer's movies, among them ``The Rock'' and
``Con Air.'' This time, it's an elite squad of oil rig drillers,
led by Harry Stamper (Bruce Willis), whom we meet as he's slamming
golf balls at a boatful of environmental activists.
</P>
<P>
   This movie has more comic relief than all Bruckheimer's previous
films combined; the goofballs include Owen Wilson and Steve
Buscemi, who keeps his footing surprisingly well. Except for
Willis, for the most part, almost everyone functions as comic
relief.
</P>
<P>
   There's also a dizzying shift from low comedy to soap opera,
following the story of the two young lovers, Harry's daughter Grace
(Liv Tyler) and one of Harry's ragtag crew, A.J. (Ben Affleck).
(The presence of Tyler, daughter of Aerosmith's Steven Tyler, may
explain the number of Aerosmith songs that pollute the soundtrack.)
</P>
<P>
   The performances are all over the map as well, although
Bruckheimer is smart enough to cast actors from the indie world,
such as Buscemi, Thornton and Wilson, who can do the job. Bruce
Willis may be one of the best action movie actors ever. He brings
depth of feeling, and he's capable of showing hurt. To his credit,
he plays Tyler's father, instead of her boyfriend. He's mostly the
sour-faced straight man, the daddy figure in this collection of
misfits.
</P>
<P>
   Director Michael Bay, who had to content himself with destroying
large chunks of San Francisco in ``The Rock,'' gets to use all his
smoke-churning technology to create a movie that's a gruesome
combination of cynicism and sentimentality.
</P>
<P>
   The cameras circle the actors like vultures, floating around the
room before stopping for the most dramatic shot possible. This may
be one of the most aggressive movies ever made, with such a premium
on activity that every scene suffers from attention-deficit
disorder.
</P>
<P>
   Bay's feverish ambition is to make every single second mean
something, instead of letting the movie build toward a
less-contrived high point. But when everything is heightened,
nothing means anything. This kind of bravura, pumped-up filmmaking
is the stuff of great trailers; the coming attraction spots take
the top of your head off. But it's exhausting, and you begin to
feel that the movie runs on a special clock in which every minute
lasts 90 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Armageddon'' is not nearly as luridly insane as Bruckheimer's
``Con Air,'' which got more outrageous with every scene. In this
movie, Bay includes several of those Justice League of America
shots, in which the heroes amble majestically toward the camera in
slow motion, clad in their cool, Kool-Aid-orange spacesuits. There
are quite a few slow-mo shots of people waiting for the world to
end that look like Nike ads directed by Norman Rockwell. And when
Harry and his crew are launched on a space shuttle to do battle
with the asteroid, they seem have packed up most of NASA to carry
with them. The asteroid-bound section of the film, where characters
you're barely aware of pop up and disappear, is almost
incomprehensible; it's like watching a foreign film with no
subtitles.
</P>
<P>
   Don't worry about New York being the only global center to be
annihilated either. It might have been cheaper to blow up the world
than it was to make ``Armageddon.'' This is the first time that the
end of the world as we know it has a price tag hanging from it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Armageddon'' is rated PG-13 for violence, adult language,
destruction on a global scale.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Armageddon''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 1 (on a scale of 1-5)
</P>
<P>
   Director: Michael Bay
</P>
<P>
   Stars: Bruce Willis, Ben Affleck, Liv Tyler
</P>
<P>
   Length: 150 min.
</P>
<P>
   Rated: PG-13
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
