<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 18:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4390 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARMAGEDDON-FILM-REVIE     06-30 1137
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARMAGEDDON-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ARMAGEDDON:` HENNY PENNY GETS PRESIDENT'S EAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review) 
(JT) 
 By JANET MASLIN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Doom threatens. Again. This time it's a giant asteroid (``It's
the size of Texas, Mr. President''), and it's the Chrysler Building
that becomes New York's most conspicuously flattened landmark (just
as ``Deep Impact'' toppled the Statue of Liberty and ``Godzilla''
wrecked the Brooklyn Bridge.) That damage is done by a fake meteor
shower during the first part of ``Armageddon.'' The sight, however
apocalyptic, isn't as scary as the prospect of raising a generation
of Americans on movies like this.
</P>
<P>
   Movie isn't actually the best word to describe ``Armageddon.''
More accurately it's a product, a feat of salesmanship, a sight
worth noticing only because, like the asteroid on a collision
course with planet Earth, its size and inevitability aren't easy to
miss. But it should surprise no one to learn that the catchy title
and prime opening date were more vital to the genesis of
``Armageddon'' than the burning need to tell one more derivative
disaster story. Or that, without counting technical jargon,
official titles, ``government'' or profanity, armageddon is easily
the biggest word in the script.
</P>
<P>
   As produced by Jerry Bruckheimer and directed by Michael Bay
with trademark expensive bombast, ``Armageddon'' tries to tell a
coherent story of guts, young love and space travel. (``Everybody
hang on. This could get a little rough.'') Though it means to be
inspiring, it has quite the opposite effect. There's not a
believable moment here (unless you count some boyish carousing in a
strip club). The actors mark time, and the gung-ho heroics on
display are embarrassingly hollow. (They will be even more so when
this show of ersatz patriotism plays overseas.) A real movie about
courage in space is ``Apollo 13,'' in which fear and sacrifice have
meaning. This jingoistic, overblown spectacle is about whistling in
the dark.
</P>
<P>
   First seen chipping golf balls spitefully at a Greenpeace
vessel, Bruce Willis stars as a bullying oil tycoon who is called
Harry S. Stamper and lives up to the name. For the same reasons
that Willis perhaps had the biggest trailer on the set, he
monopolizes the noblest moments in the movie, but he has to
establish Harry's boorishness first. So as the action begins, Harry
noisily tries to shoot A.J. Frost (Ben Affleck), the story's nice
young man, for sleeping with Grace Stamper (Liv Tyler), the big
man's beautiful, sheltered daughter. Though marooned on an oil rig
in the South China Sea, Grace has a silky Asian wardrobe that shows
up nicely at NASA headquarters later in the story.
</P>
<P>
   After a team of experts led by Dan Truman (a strong, no-nonsense
Billy Bob Thornton) determines that the planet faces imminent
destruction, both Stamper and Frost are recruited by the U.S.
government for instant heroism duty. Much is made of what
incredible drillers these guys are. They become part of a rascally
group assembled for an ultradangerous special mission, a group in
which Steve Buscemi provides comic relief as the team member with a
pulse. The idea is to train up, go to space, drill into the
asteroid, obliterate it with a nuclear device and be home in time
for the finale. Piece of cake.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with the prospect of global annihilation, the characters
in ``Armageddon'' still manage to horse around during basic
training and enjoy the chance to play with NASA's fanciest new
toys. Much of the film's lightheartedeness is supposed to come from
Affleck, whose manner is appealingly game but whose romantic scenes
with Ms. Tyler are hopelessly overstaged. He is expected not only
to croon a verse of John Denver's ``Leaving on a Jet Plane'' but to
play a love scene involving the cute use of animal crackers. And he
must mist at the eyes when realizing what a stand-up guy Harry
Stamper happens to be.
</P>
<P>
   Bay, whose background in making commercials keeps his feature
films (``Bad Boys,'' ``The Rock'') looking like advertisements for
themselves, never lets such moments occur gently. Even without its
periodic explosions ``Armageddon'' is desperately frenetic, and it
would have been more enveloping without such furious overediting or
strident cues. The story needn't be followed closely, since the
music constantly informs viewers whether to be happy or sad. Colors
are beer-commercial bold, sometimes with an emphasis on
patriotic-flag accents, sometimes in the blues and greens of video
screens. The pitch is so unvaried that it grows monotonous and
finally exhausting. But when a story has been constructed as if it
were shish kebab, each mood must be wildly overstated if it means
to show up at all.
</P>
<P>
   As ``Armageddon'' forges ahead on two and a half hours' worth of
autopilot, it proves itself an action potboiler with more of a
political agenda than most. American military uniforms and badges
are studied lovingly. Non-Americans are reduced to faceless
stereotypes, mostly seen in large crowds. Prayers are as heavily
emphasized as they are understandable under the circumstances.
(Harry: ``C'mon, God. Just a little help. That's all I'm askin'.'')
Antinuclear protesters get the Greenpeace treatment. A bumbling
Russian cosmonaut (Peter Stormare) is presented as if somebody
wanted to restart the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `ARMAGEDDON'
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Directed by Michael Bay; written by Jonathan Hensleigh and
J.J. Abrams, based on an adaptation by Tony Gilroy and Shane
Salerno of a story by Robert Roy Pool and Hensleigh; director of
photography, John Schwartzman; edited by Mark Goldblatt, Chris
Lebenzon and Glen Scantlebury; visual effects by Dream Quest
Images; music by Trevor Rabin; production designer, Michael White;
produced by Jerry Bruckheimer, Gale Anne Hurd and Bay; released by
Touchstone Pictures.
</P>
<P>
   With: Bruce Willis (Harry Stamper), Billy Bob Thornton (Dan
Truman), Ben Affleck (A.J. Frost), Liv Tyler (Grace Stamper), Keith
David (General Kimsey), Chris Ellis (Walter Clark), Jason Isaacs
(Ronald Quincy), Will Patton (Charles ``Chick'' Chapple), Steve
Buscemi (Rockhound), Ken Campbell (Max Lennert), William Fichtner
(Col. William Sharp), Jessica Steen (Co-Pilot Jennifer Watts),
Grayson McCouch (Gruber), Owen Wilson (Oscar Choi), Clark Brolly
(Freddy Noonan), Michael Clarke Duncan (Jayotis ``Bear''
Kurleenbear), Peter Stormare (Lev Andropov), Stanley Anderson
(president) and Charlton Heston (Narrator).
</P>
<P>
   Rating: ``Armageddon'' is rated PG-13 (Parents strongly
cautioned). It includes explosions, mayhem, profanity and implicit
sexual situations. Though there is little explicit bloodshed, the
film shows a readiness for violence in every pore.
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 144 minutes. This film is rated PG-13.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
