<SLUG> BC-SMALL-MOVIE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SMALL SOLDIERS,' BIG MONEY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(NOTE: A CORRECTION IN THE BYLINE.) 
By JENIFER KNIGHT 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; Think small, think real small.
</P>
<P>
   That's what makers of the new Universal Studios summer
attraction did when they put together ``Small Soldiers'': Behind
the Scenes, which is based on the upcoming film.
</P>
<P>
   According to its makers, the Universal/DreamWorks venture, which
opens Thursday at the theme park, boasts the first ever
walk-through of a Hollywood movie set coupled with an interactive
experience that promises to be ``more kid-friendly than the
movie.''
</P>
<P>
   The digitally enhanced action-adventure film, directed by Joe
Dante (``Gremlins'') and set for release July 10, tells the
life-and-death struggle between two sets of toys _ the
monstrous-looking yet people-loving Gorgonites and the power-hungry
Commandoes, who are accidentally implanted with military
intelligence chips and start an all-out war in suburbia.
</P>
<P>
   Universal's video guided tour of the movie set opens into a
``prep room'' (a clinical name for such a gritty movie) and is
meant to provide background for those who haven't seen the movie.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the studio's Sound Stage 36 is the original set as it
appears in the movie. The tour of the small postwar suburban house
is narrated by the film's co-stars, Kirsten Dunst and Denis Leary,
and includes scenes tied to two special effects: a puff of smoke
cued to a movie clip and an action figure twirling down a garbage
disposal coupled with sound effects.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't want it to be a lecture. We wanted it to be a little
more hands-on,'' said David Weiss the project manager for the
attraction.
</P>
<P>
   But the hands-on part of the tour comes when the set
walk-through dumps out into an arcade room, which offers several
venues, including about three dozen play stations that give kids a
choice between three different games.
</P>
<P>
   There is also a station where anyone can become part of the
movie magic by joining the character Chip Hazard in a chase scene
that is inserted into the movie version.
</P>
<P>
   The last stop is one that might make parents cringe _ the toy
store, the attraction's obvious ploy to get a leg up on
merchandising before the movie's release.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not about the movie anymore, it's about the marketing.
And more than that, it's about the timing,'' said Norman Kahn, vice
president for Universal's entertainment division.
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, the film features spectacular special effects
paired with radio-controlled puppets with digital enhancement from
Industrial Light and Magic.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's changed is that audiences are smarter now _ they expect
more,'' said Weiss.
</P>
<P>
   But the interactive quotient in this attraction relies less on
the technical and more, well ... on the retail.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
