<SLUG> BC-BKN-BIRD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUMBLE BIRD ACKNOWLEDGES HALL OF FAME HONOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Larry Bird was equal parts awestruck and humbled Tuesday, 24
hours after learning he had been inducted into the Hall of Fame. He
used words like ``unbelievable'' and ``the ultimate'' to describe
the feeling.
</P>
<P>
   But did it make up for the 24-year-old snub of not being named
Mr. Basketball in Indiana?
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Once a Hoosier, always a Hoosier. For the record, the Mr.
Basketball award was shared in 1974 by Steve Collier and Roy
Taylor. Bird, despite averaging more than 30 points and 20 rebounds
a game for Springs Valley High, did not even make the Associated
Press All-State team.
</P>
<P>
   Bird will be inducted Oct. 2 and said Tuesday, in a news
conference from Market Square Arena, that he wants Bill Fitch, his
first pro coach, to be one of his escorts. Inductees are allowed
two, one of whom must be a member of the Hall of Fame. Fitch is
not. Bird said he'd think about the matter over the summer. But
although he'll go in as a Boston Celtic, he may not automatically
select a Boston Hall of Famer as his other escort.
</P>
<P>
   ``My Boston days are over,'' he said, adding he'd be in town for
about a week this summer for some appearances. ``I had some great
times there, but it's time for me to move on. I'm back here (in
Indiana) now.''
</P>
<P>
   Bird also revealed he would be back to coach the team next
season, not that there was much doubt. He said the Pacers have the
necessary ingredients to go all the way ``and I'm going to give it
another go'' to see if he can bring a title to Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   The Hall of Fame notification came early Monday and Bird said,
``I didn't have to tell anyone. They all knew.'' He relayed a story
from a few days ago when his son, Conor, saw his father on the
cover of a Wheaties box.
</P>
<P>
   Bird said his son thinks of him as a coach. ``Why are you on the
Wheaties box?'' Conor asked his dad.
</P>
<P>
   Conor may be one of the few people who don't know. Bird was a
mortal lock to make it on his first try. He did say that he
benefited from being on good teams, championship teams, with great
teammates. ``Even Danny Ainge was there,'' Bird said.
</P>
<P>
   He went on, ``it's one of the greatest things to happen to a
sports figure. I guess it means my career is offically over, which
is good.''
</P>
<P>
   He was kidding, of course. There were a number of times this
season that Bird was asked if wished he could have gone in and
bailed out his team.
</P>
<P>
   He was asked if he was disappointed not to be going in with
Magic Johnson. That would have been the case had Magic not made his
ill-advised return to the Lakers in 1996. Magic now must wait until
2002.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not really. I beat him there. I'm there and he's not,'' Bird
said. Then, seriously, he said, ``it would have been nice, but
there are four other people who are going in with me who also are
deserving. I'm happy to be in the company I'm in. I'm sure in a
couple years, Magic will be there.''
</P>
<P>
   And Bird will be there to show him the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought much about the Hall of Fame,'' he said. ``When
I was growing up, I was always told that I wasn't big enough,
wasn't strong enough, wasn't quick enough and couldn't jump. I
fooled them, didn't I?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
