<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS HAS TROUBLE GETTING TEEN ANTI-CIGARETTE MESSAGE OUT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ First, the good news for health officials:
Hundreds of tobacco industry billboards in Texas are coming down
this month, to be replaced by ads discouraging teen-agers from
smoking.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the not-so-good news: For starters, only six billboards in
the state will carry the anti-cigarette message.
</P>
<P>
   A new state law may try to crack down on teen smoking, but
getting the message out is not an easy matter, health officials
admit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goal is to buy a whole lot more (billboards) if the
funding comes in,'' said Ed Rivera, a spokesman for the Texas
Department of Health's office of tobacco prevention and control.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our program has never had a whole lot of money for these
campaigns.''
</P>
<P>
   That will change if the state's $15.3 billion settlement with
the tobacco industry becomes final and the Legislature follows
Attorney General Dan Morales' recommendation to set aside $200
million of the first-year tobacco payments for the anti-smoking
education program.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can do a lot with $200 million,'' said Morales spokesman
Ron Dusek.
</P>
<P>
   But, for now, health officials are relying largely on free
public service announcements on television and radio and on space
donated by billboard companies. They hope to have six billboards up
within the next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The first went up in Austin, on a major thoroughfare a few miles
from the state Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're under 18, tobacco has serious side effects,'' the ad
warns. Just beneath the headline is a large image of a teen-ager's
driver's license with the word, ``suspended,'' stamped on it in
bold, red letters.
</P>
<P>
   A new law, which went into effect Jan. 1, provides that minors
caught smoking or possessing tobacco products can be fined as much
as $250 or have their driver's licenses suspended for as long as
six months.
</P>
<P>
   They also can be required to take a tobacco education course.
</P>
<P>
   Under the tobacco settlement, which was announced only a few
weeks after the crackdown on teen smoking went into effect,
cigarette companies are to remove the remainder of their billboards
in Texas by July 24.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the more than 1,000 billboards the industry had in Texas
when the settlement was negotiated already have come down, Dusek
said.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Huang, chief of the state health department's bureau of
chronic disease prevention and control, said the removal deadline
will mark a ``major milestone in the reduction of marketing tobacco
products directly or indirectly to Texas children.''
</P>
<P>
   Huang said the health department's anti-smoking campaign ``can't
hope to stack up against the hundreds of millions of dollars that
the tobacco industry spends marketing products to Texas children.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said the state program was an important step in
``educating young Texans about this new side effect of tobacco, the
possibility of losing their driver's licenses.''
</P>
<P>
   Rivera said the health department's current annual budget for
fighting youth smoking was about $300,000. He said much of the
money was spent earlier this year on paid radio spots, the
production of a TV public service announcement and ``grass-roots''
education programs.
</P>
<P>
   Tobacco payments to the state, which could significantly boost
funding for the effort, have been delayed by a dispute over
lawyers' fees in the tobacco case and efforts by counties and
hospital districts to share in the settlement proceeds.
</P>
<P>
   State officials said they didn't know how many teen-agers have
been ticketed for smoking since the new law went into effect
because the Department of Public Safety doesn't track that offense.
But the DPS reported that 26 teen-agers had had their driver's
licenses suspended by the end of May for failing to successfully
complete a tobacco education course.
</P>
<P>
   Health department officials said more than 900 youths have taken
the course, which is usually ordered for teen-agers cited for
smoking.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
