<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-CROATIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CROATIA DEFEATS ROMANIA, 1-0 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BORDEAUX, France -- Croatia is a small country with big people.
Since the average height of Croat males is about 6 feet, it is
unsurprising the country has produced some impressive basketball
players.
</P>
<P>
   But for every Drazen Petrovic and Dino Radja there are dozens of
high-level, high-salaried, soccer players. And they helped unify a
large and vocal part of the country by taking a 1-0 victory over
Romania Tuesday. The Croats will meet Germany in the quarterfinals
in Lyon Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a small country but we have a good team and we play for
our country,'' defender Slaven Bilic said. ``We had a lot of
respect for Romania. But the whole team decided to sit back because
we knew how dangerous (Gheorge) Hagi can be.''
</P>
<P>
   They had the support of thousands of Croat fans at Parc Lescure,
who celebrated their relatively recently reacquired national
identity with an impressive ode to ``Hrvatska.''
</P>
<P>
   Those in the Section Virage began singing ``Oh, Oho, Volim Te
Hrvatsko!'' (``I Love You Croatia'') with 20 minutes remaining in
the match. It was an impressive expression of affection for their
country, but it was also a successful attempt to overcome the
Argentinian fans' 15-minute homage during Argentina's 1-0 victory
over Croatia last week.
</P>
<P>
   Equally impressive, the Croat fans continued the chant for
another 10 minutes after the game, overcoming amplified strains of
Kool and the Gang and Aretha Franklin.
</P>
<P>
   The Croats were rambunctious, but good-natured, unlike the
Yugoslav supporters who battled in Toulouse the previous night.
Neither group had complaints about the refereeing. In fact, the
Croats might offer honorary citizenship to Argentinian Javier (The
Sheriff) Castrilli, who awarded a penalty after a questionable
clash between Croatia's Aljosa Asanovic and Gabriel Popescu,
converted by Davor Suker in the 45th minute.
</P>
<P>
   Less than a minute before the penalty, Popescu had been
cautioned for a foul on Mario Stanic. Castrilli made a dramatic
demonstration of the yellow card as Popescu waved him away in
disgust. After the game, two Romanian players briefly confronted
Castrilli in the center circle before being led away by substitute
goalkeeper Florian Prunea.
</P>
<P>
   Popescu then was marking Asanovic just inside the penalty area
as a pass was dummied through the penalty arc. Asanovic fell with a
flourish and Castrilli signaled the penalty. Suker twice converted,
the first time negated by Stanic encroaching into the penalty arc.
</P>
<P>
   The Romanians struggled both with the Croats' size and their
defensive compactness, plus the style of Castrilli. They were
unable to capitalize on their quickness, and the creativeness of
Gheorgi Hagi seemed to bog down, stifled by the heat and
physicality of the defense.
</P>
<P>
   Hagi, the Istanbul-based midfielder whose relatives own a
Northern California pizza parlor, departed early in the second half
as Romanian coach Anghel Iordanescu grasped the desperateness of
the situation.
</P>
<P>
   Iordanescu, whose next assignment is to coach the national team
of Greece, went to four attackerws early in the second half,
substituting Hagi in the 12th minute. In the 32d minute, Romania
went to two defenders, and began creating chances.
</P>
<P>
   But the gamble failed as Croatia remained organized in defense.
Croatia might have increased the lead, as Zvonimir Boban and Petar
Krpan had point-blank chances on the edge of the goal area stopped
by Bogdan Stelea in the 47th minute.
</P>
<P>
   The Romanians had captured imaginations by defeating England,
then created even more interest by peroxiding their hair, keeping a
promise that they would match their heads to a color of their flag.
</P>
<P>
   Croatia had no such gimmicks, just solid play from defensive
midfielder Krunoslav Jurcic, and enough danger in attack with
Boban, Suker and Goran Vlaovic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, we are going to play even better,'' Bilic said. ``We have
to play better against Germany; they will be the favorite because
they are Germany. Two years ago we lost to them in England but we
were the better team.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
