<HEADER>
A4428 &Cx1f; tad-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BEER-MSKUBE02-COX     06-30 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEER-MSKUBE02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Max Lager's among best of brew crew
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL JULY 2: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Max Lager's, the new brewpub in Atlanta, opened last
spring, it almost immediately invited worldwide criticism.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after its opening, the International Craft Beer Conference
brought a thousand or more people to Atlanta, many eager to compare
notes on the city's brewpubs. Not everyone who came to Max Lager's
for a hospitality night was impressed, although most had the good
sense to realize it was too early to judge. Like any other
restaurant, a brewpub needs a few weeks to iron out the inevitable
wrinkles, whether they're in the kitchen, the brewery or the
service.
</P>
<P>
   But now a couple of months have passed, and no one says it's too
soon.
</P>
<P>
   That won't hurt Max Lager's in the least. The wrinkles are gone.
By any standard but parking, Max Lager's is one of the two or three
best brewpubs in metro Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can look at brewpubs in three ways,'' says Phil Doersam,
the publisher of Southern Draft Brew News, a trade paper based in
Canton, Ga. ``How good is the beer? How good is the food? And how
comfortable is the atmosphere?''
</P>
<P>
   The beer might be better at one place, but the food tastier at
another. In still another, the atmosphere might be cozy, but the
beer disappoints.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing that will disappoint at Max Lager's _ only the
parking. The food is good and the two-story red brick structure has
a funky proletarian feel (upscale grunge?), with an informal bar
upstairs and a casual dining area downstairs. ``It's like a place
you'd find in Seattle,'' says Doersam.
</P>
<P>
   Not only that, but John Roberts and his assistant, Chris
Terenzi, are brewing assertive beers like those in the Pacific
Northwest. And guess what?
</P>
<P>
   The hoppiest beer on tap, the pale ale, is one of the hottest
sellers.
</P>
<P>
   It's the same experience that Doug Nace has had as head brewer
at Percy's Fish House, where the intensely hoppy pale ale sells out
with nothing but word-of-mouth advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe there's a lesson here. At many brewpubs, the limpest
offering on tap is the house leader, a fact that usually
embarrasses the brewer. Sometimes it can be attributed to
demographics, but other times it's just a failure of nerve.
</P>
<P>
   Like Nace, Roberts and Terenzi don't believe in dumbing down
their beers or patronizing their customers. ``John and I are
hopheads _ no question,'' Terenzi says.
</P>
<P>
   They've got enough confidence to turn a brown ale, a
traditionally subdued style, into something you might come upon in
hop-happy Oregon or Washington. A brown ale, in fact, isn't a style
that much interested me until I found what Roberts and Terenzi
could do with it.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Roberts is a part-owner tells you he's not some
rogue brewer mindless of the bottom line. But he believes there's a
market for more adventurous beers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our target market,'' he says, ``is the convention people
staying in the hotels downtown and the downtown business people who
come for lunch.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, you could see customers of another kind,
20-somethings _ male and female _ who were into sampling different
styles. A beer getting a strong response from that crowd was the
Belgian White Ale, an aromatic, dryish, faintly citrusy beer
designed by Terenzi. ``You gotta taste this,'' one woman was
telling another.
</P>
<P>
   No one seemed to note the irony of their taking to ales in a
place whose name suggests lagers. The name originated with Allan
Leblanc, one of Roberts' partners. ``I was working in Boston last
year and he called me up one night and said, `Tell me if you like
this _ Max Lager's.' He thought it had a strong sound, and I said,
`Yeah, I like that.'''
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks later Roberts, who once worked at Atlanta Brewing
Co., was back in Georgia laying the groundwork for downtown's first
brewpub. Now all he and his partners need to do is find a way for
people to park. The tiny lot in the back has fewer than two dozen
spaces, and each costs $3.50 during the day and $4 at night.
</P>
<P>
   If Max Lager's can solve its parking problems, people who might
have spent the evening in Midtown or Buckhead will be heading
downtown. Some already are.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
