<HEADER>
A4430 &Cx1f; tad-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GETAWAY-BIRMINGHAM-CO     06-30 1251
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GETAWAY-BIRMINGHAM-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Art on Wheels - Birmingham Museum of Art
 &HT;    By Alan Patureau
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Birmingham, Ala.
</P>
<P>
   There's new magic in Alabama's ``Magic City,'' supplied not by
glowing steel mills as in earlier decades, but by some fun
attractions that will enhance Birmingham's appeal to vacationers
this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Standing at the landmark iron statue of Vulcan atop Red
Mountain, you can survey the forested urban valley and pick out
your prime destinations: a sprawling new theme park, a space-age
science center carved from an old department store, and a big,
sleek art museum that vies with the High in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   -- VisionLand, which opened May 28 in suburban Bessemer, is 35
acres of thrill rides and an elaborate water park, a Disney-style
village of shops and restaurants with touches of old steel mill and
mining decor. I found the Rampage wooden roller coaster to be a
white-knuckle couple of minutes, with a steeper first dip (120
feet) and a smoother track than the Great American Scream Machine
at Six Flags Over Georgia. A delegation from American Coaster
Enthusiasts ranked it among the nation's Top 20, impressed by its
``air time'' _ those moments when riders feel as if they're going
to fly out of their seats.
</P>
<P>
   Financed as a public corporation, VisionLand is aptly named, for
without the persistent, nine-year ``vision'' of Larry Langford,
mayor of suburban Fairfield, the $65 million park would still be
abandoned U.S. Steel scrubland. Langford wheedled $5 million in
seed money from Birmingham and 10 other municipalities in Jefferson
County, enough to persuade the state Legislature to authorize a $60
million bond issue to build Alabama's first major amusement park.
</P>
<P>
   A religious man whose next vision is to be the first black
president, Langford likes to quote the Bible. ```Where there is no
vision, the people perish.' _ Proverbs 29:18. That's my motto.
That's why VisionLand became a reality.'' And, as chairman of the
West Jefferson Entertainment Authority, Langford already wants to
triple the size of VisionLand to more than 100 acres, adding an
aquarium, a civil rights museum, an antique car museum, an outlet
shopping center, a movie complex and more rides.
</P>
<P>
   Which are the best of the present 20 rides? (Six Flags, by
comparison, has 32.) Besides the Rampage, try the Sky Wheel, a
106-foot-tall Ferris wheel that looms over the piney woods; Marvel
Mania, a steel roller coaster scaled down for children; and Cahaba
Falls, a tricky glide-and-splash down a log flume.
</P>
<P>
   Even more popular is the water park, known as Steel Waters (pun
alert!), where kids of all ages float on fat yellow inner tubes
down an Oz-like version of the nearby Warrior River, through caves
and past exotic islands. Squeals of delight come from Tower Works _
full of pumps, geysers and water gags _ when a huge bucket
overturns to splash swimmers below.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it's the admission price _ $21 for adults, $18 for
children _ that has kept weekend attendance somewhat below the
expected 10,000 a day. But Langford isn't worried. He says that
daily crowds of even 4,000 would be a ``payload.'' And visitors
seem to think the park is worth it. ``This is great!'' said
11-year-old Chuck Ramsey of Mountain Brook, Ala., emerging from the
Warrior River ride. ``We don't have to go to Six Flags or White
Water (in Georgia) any more.''
</P>
<P>
   VisionLand, I-20/59 west, Exit 108 and follow the signs. Open 10
a.m. to 10 p.m. daily. Admission $21 adults, $18 senior citizens
and children under 48 inches tall. Season passport (to Nov. 1) $60.
Parking $4. Call 205-481-4750.
</P>
<P>
   -- The McWane Center will be one of the South's largest science
and technology museums when it opens July 11, in a
gleaming-like-new art deco landmark, the old Loveman's Department
Store. It's billed as the anchor attraction needed to revitalize
downtown Birmingham, just as Discovery Place boosted Charlotte.
</P>
<P>
   The McWane's star attraction is sure to be the IMAX Dome
Theater, with a jumbo movie screen (83 feet wide) and grand
circular lobby. The first show will be the critically acclaimed,
44-minute adventure film ``Everest.''
</P>
<P>
   An outgrowth of the smaller Discovery 2000 museum a mile away,
the 150,000-square-foot McWane Center includes the ultimate in
breathtaking exhibits: the HighCycle. It allows you to test gravity
by riding a bicycle on a cable high above the grand lobby. (Don't
worry; wires and weights prevent the cycle from tipping more than
45 degrees.)
</P>
<P>
   Other wonders, laid out on three floors, include Science Quest,
with state-of-the-art, hands-on stuff (feet, too). You're invited
to test the theory that you can walk on a bed of nails without
feeling pain. You can also create your own animated movie, launch a
tennis ball into orbit, build a seven-foot arch and lift yourself
on an air cushion. Nearby is ``Lightning Strikes!'' a 45-minute
show that sends electricity crackling across the room.
</P>
<P>
   In the Challenger Learning Center, youngsters can simulate
blasting into space, with control panels and TV monitors aglow.
``Just Mice Size'' invites small children to explore and build in a
world as viewed by a mouse. The World of Water boasts tanks of sea
creatures, plus exhibits showing river, marsh and ocean habitats.
</P>
<P>
   Named for the late James R. McWane, a local steel baron whose
family donated $10 million to spark the project, the center
preserves a touch of the Loveman's store nostalgia. You can take
the original store escalator to the glittering art deco mezzanine,
which once housed a popular restaurant and beauty shop. It's now
museum offices.
</P>
<P>
   On July 11, the McWane will open with a daylong Adventure
Festival and street party, with free museum admission, live music,
a climbing wall, science demonstrations and roving characters from
history.
</P>
<P>
   McWane Center, 216 19th St. North. 9 a.m.-6 p.m.
Monday-Saturday, noon-6 p.m. Sunday. Admission $6.50 adults, $4.50
children; IMAX $6.50 adults, $4.50 children; combination $9.50
adults, $7 children. Call 205-558-2000.
</P>
<P>
   -- The Birmingham Museum of Art, which has presented blockbuster
shows such as ``The First Emperor: Treasures of Ancient China,'' is
hosting a summertime treat. ``Art on Wheels,'' through Sept. 6, is
an exhibit of 25 classic motorcycles from Barber's Vintage
Motorsports Museum, Birmingham's world-renowned collection of
motorcycles. Included are such rare bikes as a Ducati and an MV
Agusta, both from Italy in the 1970s; a 1920s Indian Factory Racer
from the United States; a 1960 BMW R50 from Germany and a 1996
Britten V1000 from New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
   With 150,000 square feet of exhibit space, the museum has
world-class collections of Wedgwood pottery and modern Chinese
paintings. The new rooftop sculpture garden is considered a work of
art in itself. Through the winter of 1999, children are encouraged
to touch paints, easels and other materials in ``The Artist in the
Studio'' exhibit, which includes typical Renaissance and
21st-century studios. Another show due July 12-Sept. 6 is the
paintings of Tuscaloosa native William Christenberry. Unlike his
previously exhibited works, many of these paintings are startling,
large-scale abstractions that were hidden in Christenberry's attic
for 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   Birmingham Museum of Art, 2000 Eighth Avenue North. 10 a.m.-5
p.m. Tuesday-Saturday, noon-5 p.m. Sunday. Admission free. Call
205-254-2565.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
