<HEADER>
A4431 &Cx1f; tad-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GETAWAY-FESTIVAL-COX     06-30 0535
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GETAWAY-FESTIVAL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Southern Happenings for Wednesday, July 1, 1998
 &HT;    Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   -- Chattanooga _ Bluff View Art District's Fourth Annual Fourth
of July Bar-B-Q Cookoff is Saturday with bluegrass music by the
Dismembered Tenneseans, neo-honky tonk by Uncle Lightnin' and
acoustic sounds, country music and bocce ball with Letty &AMP; Georgia;
plus, barbecue plates for sale, games, art market, guided walking
tours, watermelon eating contests, children's tent and more.
423-265-5033.
</P>
<P>
   -- Brevard, N.C. _ Conductor Mitch Miller will lead the Brevard
Music Center Festival Orchestra Friday in a tribute to his friend
George Gershwin, featuring ``Rhapsody in Blue,'' ``An American in
Paris'' and excerpts from ``Porgy and Bess.'' 828-884-2019.
</P>
<P>
   -- Flat Rock, N.C. _ Flat Rock Playhouse, the State Theatre of
North Carolina, presents the comedy ``The Affections of May'' today
through July 11. 704-693-0731 or online at
www.flatrockplayhouse.org
</P>
<P>
   -- Highlands, N.C. _ Mountain Makings July 4th Weekend Art &AMP;
Craft Show will be held Friday-Sunday at the Sassafras Gap
Campground on N.C. 28 South. Also, live performances by Curtis
Blackwell and the Dixie Bluegrass Boys and folk musicians Chuck
Willhide; Oriental, Cajun, seafood and international food; fudge
and candies; and arts and crafts demonstrations. 828-526-3181.
</P>
<P>
   -- Asheville, N.C. _ The annual Mountain Dance and Folk Festival
is Thursday-Saturday downtown at the City/County Plaza and Diana
Wortham Theatre. 828-258-6107.
</P>
<P>
   -- Young Harris, Ga. _ ``The Reach of Song,'' the official state
historic drama, celebrates its 10th anniversary with this season's
production through Aug. 23 on the campus of Young Harris College.
1-800-262-7664.
</P>
<P>
   -- Dahlonega, Ga. _ The 23rd annual Family Day Independence Day
Celebration Saturday gets under way with a pet show at 8 a.m.,
followed by flag-raising ceremony. Arts and crafts, entertainment,
bingo, tours of Vickery House with colonial demonstrations,
children's activities, barbecue, homemade ice cream, watermelon,
gold panning and fireworks. 706-864-3365.
</P>
<P>
   -- Dahlonega, Ga. _ The Longbranch Buckskinners host the
Sizzling Summer Rendezvous, a living history event Friday-Sunday
with demonstrations and displays of pre-1840s weapons, early
American arts and crafts, Native American leatherwork and beadwork,
blacksmithing, cooking and more. 706-864-6426.
</P>
<P>
   -- Sautee-Nacoochee, Ga. _ The Sautee-Nacoochee Community
Association's 9th annul Echota Performing Arts Festival opens today
with the musical comedy ``Della's Diner.'' Through July 12. Musical
concerts include OrisiRisi, an African folklore performance July 7;
the Sautee-Nacoochee Chorale July 14-16; and classical guitarist
Keith Gehle July 28. The festival concludes with a production of
Shakepeare's ``The Tempest'' July 22-Aug. 1. 706-878-3300.
</P>
<P>
   -- Jonesborough, Tenn. _ Tennessee's oldest town celebrates
Historic Jonesborough Days Friday through Sunday with arts and
crafts exhibits, parade, fireworks, Southern-style cooking and live
entertainment. 423-753-5281.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
