<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 18:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4432 &Cx1f; tad-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ICECREAM-RECIPES-COX     06-30 2210
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ICECREAM-RECIPES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Make your own frozen treats
 &HT;    (ERMBARGOED UNTIL JULY 2: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Jim Auchmutey
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A little mood music for ice cream making: Listen to Kathryn
King, pastry chef at Hedgerose restaurant in Buckhead, explain why
she loves the stuff so much.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was growing up, we'd visit my grandparents in Decatur.
They'd go to the pick-your-own farms and always had the best
peaches. We'd go in the back yard with their ice cream freezer _
one of those old hand-crank models with a wooden bucket that looked
like a barrel _ and we'd start churning. I could hardly stand to
wait. I'd serve ice cream with every dessert if I thought I could
get away with it.''
</P>
<P>
   There you have it: The secret ingredient of great ice cream is
memory. Think back on the summers of your childhood, and get out
the churn.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Silky Smooth Ginger Ice Cream
</P>
<P>
   Makes 1 quart Preparation time: 15 minutes Cooking time: 10
minutes
</P>
<P>
   This ice cream, an example of the eggless ``Philadelphia
style,'' comes from ``CookWise'' (Morrow) by Atlanta food scientist
Shirley Corriher. She credits food testers Susan Mack and Andy
Armstrong for coming up with the idea of using ginger preserves,
adding to the smooth texture.
</P>
<P>
   2cups half-and-half
</P>
<P>
   1cup heavy or whipping cream
</P>
<P>
   1cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon pure vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   1/8teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   4tablespoons ginger preserves
</P>
<P>
   In a medium-size saucepan, heat the half-and-half and cream to
just below a boil (175 degrees). Remove from heat. Stir in the
sugar, vanilla, salt and preserves. Refrigerate 4 to 12 hours, then
place in the refrigerator freezer for 5 minutes. Process in ice
cream maker following manufacturer's instructions. _ From
``CookWise'' by Shirley Corriher (Morrow).
</P>
<P>
   Per 1/2-cup serving: 310 calories, 2 grams protein, 18 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 53), 36 grams carbohydrates, 64
milligrams cholesterol, 74 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Honey Peach Iced Buttermilk
</P>
<P>
   Makes 5 cups Preparation time: 10-15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Freezing time: varies according to manufacturer's instructions
</P>
<P>
   It's July, it's Georgia _ isn't there some state law that says
you have to make peach ice cream? Here's a light version; we say
light because it uses honey, not sugar, and buttermilk, which,
despite its name, is lower in fat than whole milk.
</P>
<P>
   2cups sliced, very ripe fresh peaches
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1/4teaspoon ground cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup honey (or to taste)
</P>
<P>
   3cups buttermilk
</P>
<P>
   Peel and pit peaches. In a large bowl, mash them thoroughly with
a potato masher. Mix in lemon juice and cinnamon. Whisk in honey
and buttermilk. Refrigerate for at least 4 hours. Process in ice
cream maker. _ Adapted from ``The Best Ice Cream Maker Cookbook
Ever'' by Peggy Fallon (HarperCollins)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 96 calories, 3 grams protein, less than 1 gram fat
(percent calories from fat, 6), 22 grams carbohydrates, 2
milligrams cholesterol, 66 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Pink Peppercorn Ice Cream
</P>
<P>
   Makes 10 servings Preparation time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 25 minutes Chilling time: 2 hours or more
</P>
<P>
   Freezing time: varies according to manufacturer' s instructions
</P>
<P>
   This comes with rhubarb cake when pastry chef Kathryn King puts
it on the dessert menu at Hedgerose.
</P>
<P>
   12large egg yolks
</P>
<P>
   1quart half-and-half
</P>
<P>
   1cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   Vanilla bean, scraped, or 2 tablespoons vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   1/4to 1 teaspoon finely ground pink peppercorns, or to taste
(see note)
</P>
<P>
   In a large bowl, whisk egg yolks. Set aside. Fill another large
bowl with ice and set aside. In a stainless steel saucepan over
medium heat, scald half-and-half, sugar and vanilla. Slowly pour
hot liquid into the bowl with the yolks, whisking constantly to
avoid scrambling the eggs. Return the mixture to the saucepan and
continue to cook over low heat, whisking constantly, until the
mixture coats a spoon. Place saucepan over the bowl of ice and cool
about 15 minutes, whisking occasionally. Strain and refrigerate.
When ready to make the ice cream, add the ground pink peppercorns
and freeze according to your ice cream maker's manufacturer's
instructions. Garnish with whole peppercorns and accompany with
fresh fruit.
</P>
<P>
   Note: Pink peppercorns are aromatic but not very hot; even 1
teaspoon is quite subtle. The whole peppercorns make a great
garnish and taste good, too. This is a very rich ice cream;
servings should be small.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 320 calories, 8 grams protein, 20 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 57), 26 grams carbohydrates, 418
milligrams cholesterol, 52 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Kulfi (Indian Ice Cream)
</P>
<P>
   Makes 2/3 quart Preparation time: 15 minutes Cooking time: 70
minutes
</P>
<P>
   India's favorite frozen dessert is a subtle ice cream that gets
its flavor from saffron, cardamom and bits of nut. Street vendors
in India sell it in cone-shaped tins or on a stick. In Atlanta,
diners can find kulfi at most Indian restaurants, where it cools
the heat of a spicy meal. This version comes from Jogi Singh, a
Dunwoody resident who grew up in New Delhi, where kulfi was as much
a part of summer as peach ice cream in Georgia. She tops it with
cornstarch noodles and rose-flavored syrup.
</P>
<P>
   Pinch of saffron
</P>
<P>
   7cups plus 2 tablespoon whole milk
</P>
<P>
   1tablespoon cornstarch
</P>
<P>
   1green cardamom pod
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   10almonds, blanched and finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   10 pistachios, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   Soak saffron in 1 tablespoon cold milk. Set aside. In a nonstick
pan over high heat, bring 3 cups of milk to a boil, stirring
constantly. Reduce heat to medium-high and continue to stir about
30 minutes until milk thickens to consistency of mayonnaise. Set
aside. Dissolve cornstarch in 1 tablespoon cold milk. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Add cardamom seed to remaining 4 cups milk and bring to a boil
in a nonstick pan, stirring constantly, until the milk reduces to 3
cups. Add dissolved cornstarch to milk. Continue to stir until
mixture thickens to custardlike consistency. Remove cardamom. Add
sugar and dissolved saffron. Stir well. Remove from heat. Add
thickened milk and whisk until well-blended. Mix in almonds and
pistachios. Cover with plastic wrap to prevent skin from forming
and refrigerate at least 4 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Process in ice cream maker if you want a lighter texture like
American ice cream. Indians prefer a more solid consistency, which
they get by placing the kulfi in a pan in the freezer, stirring a
couple of times while it sets.
</P>
<P>
   Note: Be sure to get green cardamom (which Indians use in
desserts), not the more common brown cardamom (used in savory
dishes). It's available at Indian markets.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 300 calories, 11 grams protein, 14 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 43), 34 grams carbohydrates, 39
milligrams cholesterol, 143 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Lemon Sorbet
</P>
<P>
   Makes 1 quart Preparation time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   This is as close as you can get at home to making those lemon
ices that wowed Atlanta during the Olympics. The secret to making
creamy sorbet is not letting it freeze all the way through. The
sugar and vodka lower the freezing point and give the sorbet a
smoother texture.
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2cups water
</P>
<P>
   3/4cup freshly squeezed lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4cups granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1tablespoon lemon zest
</P>
<P>
   1tablespoon vodka
</P>
<P>
   In a nonreactive bowl, combine the water, lemon juice, sugar,
lemon zest and vodka. Stir until sugar dissolves. Refrigerate
overnight, or at least 4 hours. Process in ice cream maker
according to instructions.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 132 calories, no protein, no fat, 33 grams
carbohydrates, no cholesterol, 1 milligram sodium.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Chocolate Chip Cookie Dough Ice Cream
</P>
<P>
   Makes 1 1/2 quarts Preparation time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 10 minutes Chilling time: 5 hours-overnight
</P>
<P>
   Freezing time: varies according to manufacturer's instructions
</P>
<P>
   Ben &AMP; Jerry's was the first to put raw cookie dough in ice
cream, and it became its most popular flavor.
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2cups whole milk
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2cups whipping cream
</P>
<P>
   5large egg yolks
</P>
<P>
   2/3cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   2teaspoons vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   CHOCOLATE CHIP COOKIE DOUGH:
</P>
<P>
   5tablespoons unsalted butter, softened
</P>
<P>
   5tablespoons light brown sugar, packed
</P>
<P>
   3tablespoons granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   Pinch salt
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   1tablespoon plus 1 teaspoon water
</P>
<P>
   3/4cup unbleached all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1cup (6 ounces) miniature semisweet chocolate chips
</P>
<P>
   To prepare the ice cream: Heat the milk and cream to about 150
degrees in a large saucepan until it is hot and a few bubbles begin
to form. Do not boil. Put the egg yolks and sugar in the large bowl
of an electric mixer and beat at medium speed until the mixture
thickens slightly and lightens in color, about 45 seconds. Decrease
speed to low and slowly add the hot milk mixture. Return the
mixture to the saucepan and cook the custard over medium-low heat,
stirring constantly, until it reaches 170 degrees. Stir the mixture
often where the side and the bottom of the pan meet. The mixture
will thicken slightly and leave a path on the back of the spoon
when you draw your finger across it. A little steam will just begin
to rise from the custard mixture. Do not boil. Strain the hot
mixture into a bowl and stir in the vanilla. Cover and refrigerate
until very cold, about 5 hours or overnight. Stir the mixture
several times while it is chilling.
</P>
<P>
   To prepare the cookie dough: Put the butter, sugars and salt in
the large bowl of an electric mixer. Beat on low speed until the
mixture is smooth. Mix in the vanilla and water just until it is
incorporated. Mix in the flour just until it is incorporated. Stir
in the chocolate chips.
</P>
<P>
   Recipe makes 2 cups cookie dough. If you are preparing one
recipe of ice cream, you will use only 1 cup of the dough. To
freeze the remaining cup of cookie dough, put it in a plastic
freezer container and press plastic wrap onto the dough. Cover the
container. Label with the date and contents. Refrigerate up to 3
days or freeze up to 2 months. Defrost the frozen dough in the
refrigerator about 3 hours before using it.
</P>
<P>
   To double the ice cream recipe and use both cups of cookie
dough, double the ingredients for the ice cream mixture.
</P>
<P>
   To assemble the ice cream: Transfer the chilled custard to an
ice cream maker and process according to manufacturer's directions.
During the last 2 minutes of churning, add 1 cup of the cookie
dough, breaking the dough into pieces as you add it.
</P>
<P>
   To freeze the ice cream: Transfer ice cream to a chilled
container. Press plastic wrap onto the surface of the ice cream and
cover tightly. Label with date and contents. Freeze overnight or up
to 10 days.
</P>
<P>
   To serve: Soften the ice cream for about 10 minutes until it
scoops easily and has a creamy texture. _ From ``Bake and Freeze
Desserts'' by Elinor Klivans (Morrow).
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 292 calories, 4 grams protein, 20 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 63), 25 grams carbohydrates, 185
milligrams cholesterol, 42 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Double Espresso Gelato
</P>
<P>
   Makes 2 1/2 cups Preparation time: 10-15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Standing time: 30 minutes Chilling time: 2 hours
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 10 minutes Freezing time: varies according to
manufacturer's instructions
</P>
<P>
   2cups whole milk
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup espresso-roast coffee beans
</P>
<P>
   5egg yolks
</P>
<P>
   3/4cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons light corn syrup
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon instant espresso powder
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   In a medium-sized, heavy saucepan, combine the milk and coffee
beans. Bring to a simmer over medium-high heat. Remove from the
heat. Cover and let stand for 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Pour the milk through a medium-mesh sieve set over a bowl; set
aside. In a metal bowl, whisk together the egg yolks, sugar and
corn syrup until blended. Form a kitchen towel into a ring and
place the metal bowl on top to prevent its moving. Gradually pour
the milk into the yolk mixture, whisking constantly. Return the
mixture to the same saucepan and place over medium heat. Cook,
stirring slowly and constantly with a wooden spatula, until the
custard thickens and leaves a path on the back of the spatula when
a finger is drawn across it, about 6 minutes; do not allow to boil.
</P>
<P>
   Pour the custard through the medium-mesh sieve set over a clean
bowl. In a separate small bowl, combine espresso powder, vanilla
and 1 tablespoon custard. Stir until powder dissolves. Combine with
remaining custard. Refrigerate until cold, about 2 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Transfer the custard to an ice cream maker and process according
to the manufacturer's instructions. For the best texture, serve the
gelato immediately. Or transfer to a container, cover and freeze
until firm, at least 4 hours or up to 3 days.
</P>
<P>
   Note: The longer freezing results in a texture more like that of
ice cream. _ From ``Ice Creams and Sorbets'' (TimeLife), part of
the Williams-Sonoma Kitchen Library
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 293 calories, 8 grams protein, 11 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 34), 42 grams carbohydrates, 332
milligrams cholesterol, 71 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
