<HEADER>
A4433 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-ARMAGEDDON-COX     06-30 0765
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-ARMAGEDDON-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ``Armageddon'' follows action movie formula to the letter
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's huge, destructive, unstoppable, and it's certain to blast a
hole in the United States _ at the box office, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not talking about the Texas-sized asteroid aimed at earth in
``Armageddon,'' but about any movie produced by Jerry Bruckheimer:
``Bad Boys,'' ``Con Air,'' ``Days of Thunder,'' take your pick.
</P>
<P>
   Directed by guys (Tony Scott, Simon West, etc.) weaned on the
surging, flashing rhythms of music video and commercials, these
movies are basically an excuse to blow up cars and fire off
thousands of rounds of ammo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Armageddon'' takes the formula into orbit, turning the cars
into shuttles and space stations and swapping lethal meteorites for
bullets. While ``Deep Impact'' treated the same story (asteroid
menaces earth) with a sobriety that left some audiences squirming
for more action, ``Armageddon'' never lets the threat of global
annihilation get in the way of fun. It's a space cowboy movie, with
Bruce Willis and Ben Affleck saving the world for Liv Tyler.
</P>
<P>
   Willis plays Harry Stamper, renowned deep-core oil driller,
whose daughter Grace (Tyler) has grown up on the rig and fallen for
Dad's employee A.J. (Affleck), a guy Harry disdains as a
``roughneck.''
</P>
<P>
   After flaming space rocks lay waste to Manhattan (in a
spectacular scene that still feels familiar, thanks to ``Godzilla''
and ``Independence Day''), Harry gets tapped by NASA to join a
mission to fly into space, intercept the big rock, drill a hole in
it and nuke it. Yeah, the same thing happened in ``Deep Impact.''
</P>
<P>
   In this case, the mission is a chance for director Michael Bay
(``The Rock'') to shoot a chipper, funny montage of Willis and his
hand-picked crew training to be astronauts in an impossibly short
time. The crew includes Steve Buscemi, Owen Wilson, William
Fichtner and Will Patton, bringing good comic relief to the flick.
And Billy Bob Thornton turns in a strong, gravelly performance as
the Houston-based NASA man who oversees the mission from Earth.
Willis is Willis, Affleck maintains his hot-new-thing status, and
Tyler pouts a lot.
</P>
<P>
   Like other Bruckheimer films, ``Armageddon'' is really a form of
superior product placement. But we're not talking Coke or Nike or
Blockbuster. The product being sold here is a corn-fed, corny
self-image of an America that doesn't really exist any more. It's a
landscape of rugged white churches on long green lawns, little boys
trapped in a 30-year time warp as they frolick with toy rockets and
lanky lovers stretched out under ancient trees. Everything is shot
through filters that bind these hokey images in a gold light as
thick and gooey as honey.
</P>
<P>
   When it's not being sappy, though, the flick is about toys: The
rockets, the outer space drills, the loud things the actors get to
play with. The movie is the usual Bruckheimer mix of Hallmark and
hardware.
</P>
<P>
   Its gee-whiz, let's-blow-something-up momentum helps you
overlook the enormous holes in the movie's plot and logic. The
rhythm kicks in early: Our heroes come close to saving the world,
but then something bad happens. They fix that problem ... then
something else happens. It's a series of starts and stops for
adrenalin junkies, a throwback to Buck Rogers cliffhangers, only
without the hanging part.
</P>
<P>
   ``Armageddon'' is another of those flicks that likes to remind
us it's a movie. It throws in self-referential references to ``Star
Wars,'' ``Dr. Strangelove'' and ``Apollo 13,'' and it borrows plot
points from ``The Abyss'' and other flicks. Then there's the pug
dog that looks like the one in ``Men in Black,'' attacking a stand
of inflatable Godzillas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Armageddon'' is more enjoyable than that big-lizard flick. And
it's an improvement over last year's insultingly broad, incoherent
``Con Air.'' You'll see the reported $165 million budget on-screen
in the impressive effects and mammoth sets. But is the movie good
for you? Probably not. It translates the notion of global
destruction into the quick-thrill rhythms of a video game you
probably won't even remember the next day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Armageddon''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   Starring Bruce Willis, Billy Bob Thornton, Ben Affleck. Directed
by Michael Bay. Rated PG-13 for sci-fi disaster action, implied sex
(a young woman is found in her boyfriend's bed), some profanity. 2
hours, 24 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: The world interpreted as a video game.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
