<HEADER>
A4435 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-SURFER01-COX     06-30 0561
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SURFER01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Turner documentry looks at film pioneer Oscar Micheaux
 &HT;    By Lyle V. Harris
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The first instinct people have when you show them a snapshot is
to look for themselves in the picture. Failing that, they look for
someone who looks like them.
</P>
<P>
   For black moviegoers in the early 1900s, a trip to the
neighborhood theater was painfully disappointing: there were few
black actors onscreen, and most of them were playing roles that
were buffoonish and insulting.
</P>
<P>
   Then came Oscar Micheaux, a novelist and bootstrap entreprenuer
whose stated goal in life _ and on film _ was ``to teach that a
colored man can be anything he wants.''
</P>
<P>
   Turner Classic Movies is celebrating Micheaux's work and the
films of the other African-American pioneers with the documentary
``Midnight Ramble'' (8 EDT, tonight) that looks at what used to be
politely called ``race films.'' It's the first installment of the
cable network's weeklong salute to black films billed as ``A
Separate Cinema'' _ and it's a great way to start.
</P>
<P>
   Narrated by James Avery, we learn that Micheaux had the crazy
notion that his books about long-ignored everyday aspects of black
life could be turned into feature films he could distribute
himself. Except it wasn't so crazy and his first effort ``The
Homesteaders'' was an instant hit with black audiences, and the
white South Dakota farmers who had been his neighbors. He went on
to make 39 others before he died in 1951.
</P>
<P>
   Elton Fax, an illustrator who worked on some of the early race
films says they were significant because the characters ``weren't
always rolling their eyes, they weren't always shooting craps,
stealing chickens or turning white when they saw ghosts.''
</P>
<P>
   With Micheaux's success, other black production companies
quickly popped up. More than 500 race films were made between 1910
and 1950, including everything from interracial melodramas about
``mixed marriages,'' to low-budget musicals, to wild west cowboy
adventures . They become so popular that moviegoers in large cities
like Chicago would flock to ``midnight rambles'' that lasted until
2 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   The documentary also examines the influence of another kind of
race film, D.W. Griffth's ``Birth of a Nation,'' an epic paean to
the Ku Klux Klan that portrayed blacks as violent, sex-crazed
savages.
</P>
<P>
   Some blacks were outraged recently when the American Film
Institute listed ``Birth'' as one of the 100 greatest films ever
made. But in 1915 when it was first released, Griffith's film
stirred black boycotts, and even race riots.
</P>
<P>
   Well-researched and and engaging, ``Ramble'' includes interviews
with author Tony Cade Bambera, film archivist Pearl Bowser, and
actor Herb Jefferys who became a box office idol playing a Tom
Mix-type character known as ``The Bronze Buckaroo.''
</P>
<P>
   At a time when black independent films are enjoying a
mini-renaissance with movies like ``Hav Plenty'' and ``Love
Jones,'' TCM's documentary brings viewers a much-needed perspective
about the history of black cinema _ proving that it didn't start
with Spike Lee. It also shows how much Hollywood has changed since
then in its portrayals of black life. And how much it hasn't.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: channelsurfer(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
