<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOAPS-AUDITION-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOAP STUDS: ASPIRING ACTORS AUDITION FOR ROLES ON NBC DAYTIME
PROGRAMS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TERRY LEE GOODRICH 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAPEVINE, Texas _ A muscular young man, clad in a tank top and
standing in a long line, flagged a woman entering Grapevine Mills
mall, then flashed her a smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``Miss? Do you have a mint in your purse?'' he asked. ``I had
tuna fish this morning _ and if I make it as far as a casting
interview, I don't want to be breathing that out.''
</P>
<P>
   No mint. But the woman proffered a small tube of toothpaste to
Jerome Johnson, a 25-year-old from Los Angeles, whose stage name is
J. Jonason.
</P>
<P>
   He squeezed some toothpaste onto his finger, swished it around
in his mouth, thanked the woman profusely and moved forward in
line.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was among nearly 900 men who congregated at Grapevine
Mills this week for an NBC-TV casting call _ and a long shot at
landing a role in a soap opera.
</P>
<P>
   Some men were nervous. Louis Reina, 20, of Arlington, Texas,
said he got little sleep the night before.
</P>
<P>
   Dylan Sawyer, 21, of Arlington was more laid-back. He slapped
the Post-it bearing his number _ 95 _ onto his forehead as he stood
in line, drawing chuckles from those around him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in theater since junior high,'' said Sawyer, a
performing arts major at the University of Texas at Arlington.
``But I just started a job waiting tables at Razzoo's. Now that's
stress.''
</P>
<P>
   A few men, such as Johnson, had acting experience (he's been in
``Walker, Texas Ranger'' and in commercials), publicity photos and
resumes. Others, strolling past while shopping, got curious,
decided to take a number and try for their minutes of fame.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had tremendous success with casting calls at malls,''
said Annamarie Kostura, vice president of NBC Daytime's programs,
which include ``Sunset Beach,'' ``Another World'' and ``Days of Our
Lives.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We did this about a year and a half ago, when we launched
`Sunset Beach.' We went to five cities, and that's how we found
Jason George, who plays Michael, the sexy, hunky lifeguard.''
</P>
<P>
   Kostura said Grapevine is the second of seven cities _ from
Chicago to San Diego _ that NBC is visiting to find folks who have
``the right look'' and the ability to emote.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have a specific role or roles in mind. But we do have
a new soap coming on the air early next week _ `Passions,' '' she
said. ``And we're constantly trying to find fresh faces.''
</P>
<P>
   The men strode in pairs up the steps and across the stage,
stopping and turning around in front of a camera ``just so we can
see how they move,'' one casting director explained.
</P>
<P>
   Then they sat at a table with casting directors for a
pre-screening, a brief chat in which they gave their names and said
why they were there. The few who got the nod went on to the next
table, where they talked a bit more, were given a script of a soap
scene and assigned a time to return to the mall's taping room.
</P>
<P>
   The men attracted plenty of attention from shoppers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't look,'' said Mindy Arthurs, 23, of Edmond, Okla. ``I'm
married.''
</P>
<P>
   That established, she noted, ``the guy with the long hair and
the suit _ he's the best one so far. And the guy in the white on
the right? He's a doll.''
</P>
<P>
   By 4 p.m., 859 men had been through pre-screening. Fifty-one
made it to the taping room.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Compotaro, 28, of Arlington has had great luck at
so-called ``cattle calls.'' He landed a role in ``Born on the
Fourth of July,'' playing the young soldier accidentally killed by
Vietnam War veteran Ron Kovic (played by Tom Cruise).
</P>
<P>
   But he wasn't handed a script Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson fared better.
</P>
<P>
   He and others who made it to the taping room were ushered in,
one by one, directed to stand between two strips of green tape and
rehearse once.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you mess up, don't make a face and don't say, `Can we start
over?' '' taping supervisor Peter Sime directed. ``It's not a big
mistake to make a mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   Then it was ``Rolling ...'' and ``Action!''
</P>
<P>
   The videotapes will be viewed later, along with those from other
cities, and a few prospective actors will be flown to Los Angeles
for screen tests.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really figure I'm too short, too brown and too old,'' said
Scott Latham, 40, of Dallas, who has acted in productions at Stage
West in Fort Worth and Theatre Three in Dallas. ``You don't see
much of that on the soaps.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I figure there's always got to be that guy that runs the
coffee shop they go to, or who runs the surfboard shop and is a
little weird.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
