</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SHANGHAI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON TAKES CASE FOR DEMOCRACY TO THE CHINESE PEOPLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MCGRORY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHANGHAI -- In the heart of China, President Clinton launched
into an American-style campaign schedule Tuesday, shuttling from a
roundtable meeting to a radio talk show to a political reception _
all in an attempt to bring his case for freedom and democracy
directly to the people of China.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton appeared so much in campaign mode that by Tuesday night
he actually repeated the slogan from his 1996 reelection victory to
a gathering of dignitaries. ``In Shanghai, you are building that
bridge to the 21st century, and we want to build it with you,'' he
told them.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the day, Clinton displayed the same considerable
charm that has helped him win two terms as president of the United
States. He talked on radio of using the Stairmaster to stay in
shape and predicted that the Brazilians would be difficult to beat
in the World Cup soccer tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Fresh from what Clinton and his aides believe was a boffo summit
performance in Beijing, the president traveled to this city of 14
million people commonly regarded as China's economic engine to
focus on the national economy and business climate.
</P>
<P>
   Here, glittery skyscrapers -- many of them empty -- stretch
across a vast skyline. American-style restaurants like Tony Roma's
and the Hard Rock Cafe populate new shopping malls. An
eight-year-old stock exchange, housed in an elaborate complex, is
booming.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone understands that there is a new China emerging in the
world that is more prosperous, more open and more dynamic,''
Clinton told a gathering of intellectual and community leaders at a
roundtable discussion in the city library.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton made his most significant policy pronouncement of the
day at that event, where he declared in his most explicit language
yet that the United States opposes independence for Taiwan. The
policy has been repeated in the past by Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright and Clinton's national security adviser Samuel
``Sandy'' Berger, but never by Clinton himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had the chance to reiterate our Taiwan policy which is that
we don't support independence for Taiwan, or `two Chinas' or
`one-Taiwan, one-China,''' Clinton said at the roundtable. ``And we
don't believe that Taiwan should be a member in any organization
for which statehood is a requirement.''
</P>
<P>
   In public, Clinton had previously defined the US-China policy in
vaguer terms, prompted in part by the many Republican champions
Taiwan claims in Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   When communists took control of China in 1949, nationalists fled
to the island of Taiwan. In 1979, the US transferred official
recognition of China from Taipei to Beijing, but maintained
unofficial contact with Taiwan, including an office on the island
similar to an embassy.
</P>
<P>
   On another front, White House officials braced Tuesday for an
onslaught of negative news, as Linda Tripp, the woman who taped
former White House intern Monica Lewinsky, made her first
appearance before the Whitewater grand jury in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   During the hour-long radio show, Clinton sat with Shanghai Mayor
Xu Kuangdi and fielded questions on education, sports, the Chinese
monetary system and the potential for pollution from a glut of
automobiles from callers who began their comments such as, ``Hi, my
name is Lee.''
</P>
<P>
   One caller asked, ``Do you have enough courage when you go back
to the United States to convince the people, the nonbelievers, that
what you're doing is right?''
</P>
<P>
   Another caller told Clinton, ``You seem to be very healthy, and
you seem to have a very nice figure, Mr. President.''
</P>
<P>
   To that caller, Clinton said, ``Well, when I was in college, I
liked to play basketball, which is very popular in America, and I
liked to jog. I am a runner, you know, and I did that for most of
the last almost 30 years. Then, about a year and a half ago, I hurt
my leg, and I couldn't run for several months, and I began to work
on the Stairmaster. I do that quite a lot now because it's quicker
than running.''
</P>
<P>
   To another questioner who wondered how to create better exchange
programs between the United States and China, Clinton resurrected
his campaign promise to connect all schools and libraries to the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I get home, I will ask the people who are in charge of
our major libraries, the Library of Congress and the New York
Public Library and perhaps one or two others, to get in touch with
the Shanghai Library to see whether we can establish a deeper
partnership,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   After it was over, Clinton appeared thrilled with the show. ``I
thought the people were terrific,'' he told reporters. ``I wish we
could do it for two more hours.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Tuesday, Clinton sat with a group of Shanghai
intellectual leaders discussing China's future. At one point, he
tried in jest to solicit a job from the vice dean of the East China
University of Politics and Law.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was hoping you would offer me a job here,'' Clinton said,
when Zhu Lanye asked what he planned to do in retirement.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't speak Chinese,'' Zhu replied.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I'll be about 54 when I leave office and I don't plan to
retire,'' Clinton continued. ``But I haven't decided what to do yet
or where to do it, except I will always have a home in my home
state, in Arkansas, and I intend to build a library there to house
my presidential papers and to tell the story of the time in which I
served as president. But beyond that I have not made any final
plans.''
</P>
<P>
   The academics talked about rule of law, consumer protections and
human rights. At the end of the meeting, Clinton told the group,
``The forces of history are driving us toward a common future. We
have to build a common future. And so it's important that we be
able to discuss these things in an open way.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was Hillary Clinton who offered the most memorable line
at that event. Asked by a panelist whether she felt restricted in
her personal life, the First Lady shot a hard look toward the media
gathered in the room.
</P>
<P>
   ``I often refer to my life before the White House as when I was
a real person,'' she said, ``because when you are in a position
like this, people, particularly all of these people with their
pencils and their cameras, try to record everything you do and then
they try to put meaning into it, whether you intended meaning or
not.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
