<HEADLINE>
REP. FRANK, COMPANION, SPLITTING UP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. MARCUS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Representative Barney Frank, a Massachusetts
Democrat who is a homosexual and an active supporter of gay rights,
has ended his relationship with Herb Moses, his longtime companion.
</P>
<P>
   Frank, who has been candid about his personal life and often
referred to Moses as his ``spouse,'' confirmed reports of the
breakup in an interview Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be separating. ... We'll be selling our house in the
near future,'' Frank said.
</P>
<P>
   Frank disclosed his homosexuality in 1987, saying, ``I have
nothing to hide, nothing to advertise.'' He and Moses often
appeared together at congressional functions and White House social
events. They told journalists that they thought of themselves as
married.
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer who was elected to the Massachusetts Legislature in
1973 and to Congress in 1980, Frank has worked hard to dispel
stereotypes about gays. He spoke in public about his 10 1/2-year
relationship with Moses, and defied criticism from Senator Jesse
Helms of North Carolina and other conservative foes.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional Quarterly's authoritative guide, ``Politics in
America 1998,'' says Frank was the first member of Congress to
announce his homosexuality. In interviews, Frank and Moses also
said they wanted to be role models for gays and lesbians.
</P>
<P>
   For years, Frank said, members of Congress had been afraid to
say they were gay, and so they invented excuses when they were seen
with partners. ``These were people who had you believe that they
were heterosexual and became homosexual when they were drunk,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Moses, a potter, worked as an economist at the Department of
Agriculture before the two met. The separation is amicable, Frank
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
