<HEADER>
A4456 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PROFILE-TRIMBLE-BOS &LR;      06-30 1151
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROFILE-TRIMBLE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRIMBLE TAKES A STEP DOWN UNIONIST ROAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST _ For all the roads he has traveled, David Trimble
cannot get off the Garvaghy Road.
</P>
<P>
   A prickly law professor and passionate lover of opera who has
led reluctant Protestants to compromise with their Catholic
neighbors, Trimble is expected to be elected leader of the new
Northern Ireland Assembly Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   But his triumph is marred by the specter of what may happen on
the Garvaghy Road in Portadown this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Protestants will gather at the town's Drumcree
Church, the place where Trimble proved his unionist mettle three
years ago. Trimble was elected leader of the Ulster Unionist Party
based on his defiant stance at Drumcree in 1995, when he helped
persuade the Orange Order, the society of which he is a member, to
march down the Garvaghy Road for its annual parade despite
opposition from the Catholics who live on it.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when many mainstream unionists felt their traditions
and influence were threatened, Trimble was judged the man to lead
them. But now many former supporters accuse him of selling out.
They say his acceptance of the Good Friday agreement, which gives
the Irish government a role in governing Northern Ireland, amounts
to capitulation to a government determined to drag them into a
united Ireland with terrorists who used bombs and bullets for the
same purpose.
</P>
<P>
   Trimble and his supporters counter that the agreement they
negotiated provides safeguards to maintain the union with Britain.
They say it marks the first time that all strains of Irish
nationalism have accepted the legitimacy of Northern Ireland, and
that it will remain part of Britain as long as a majority of people
living here desire. It also returns local government after 26 years
of direct rule from London.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have made the union secure,'' Trimble insisted in a recent
interview.
</P>
<P>
   British Prime Minister Tony Blair, Irish Prime Minister Bertie
Ahern and President Clinton are among the world leaders who have
praised Trimble's courage and vision. Some 71 percent of voters in
Northern Ireland, including a slim majority of Protestants,
supported the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   But here on the streets of Northern Ireland, compromise can look
like surrender, and it is hard to escape one's past. To some,
Trimble has evolved from a sectarian tribalist to a secular
statesman. But there also are those on both sides of the divide who
accuse him of hypocrisy.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Ian Paisley, once an ally and now Trimble's arch enemy,
says Trimble's past stances on the Garvaghy Road were stunts to
dupe Protestants into thinking he was a hardliner.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is all part of a pattern of treachery,'' said Paisley, a
fundamentalist preacher who leads the rival Democratic Unionist
Party.
</P>
<P>
   But if Paisley considers Trimble a poseur, the vast majority of
Catholics do not. Their views of him are colored by his actions in
Portadown in 1995 and 1996. In 1995, after local residents agreed
to let Orangemen march down the Garvaghy Road, Trimble crowed about
a ``victory'' to the TV cameras, which then recorded him and
Paisley doing an impromptu, triumphant jig.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, when police initially prevented Orangemen from
marching, Trimble was photographed consorting with thugs whose
threat and use of violence led police to back down and club
nationalists off of the Garvaghy Road. Those scenes touched off the
worst rioting here in years.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Catholics find themselves in the awkward position of
needing the enigmatic Trimble. To them, he is the only unionist
leader capable of bringing an increasingly skeptical Protestant
community toward greater accommodation.
</P>
<P>
   But the Garvaghy Road now looms large for Trimble. On Monday,
the Parades Commission banned the Orangemen, whose Protestant
organization is named for William of Orange and celebrate each year
his victory over Catholic forces in the seventeenth century. They
vow to defy the ban and gather in large numbers until they are
allowed to march.
</P>
<P>
   Trimble, whose rhetoric has softened noticeably since the Good
Friday agreement, wrote residents to let the Orange parade pass in
the spirit of accommodation. Trimble said that while nationalists
might find it ``distasteful,'' the parade is meant to commemorate
the soldiers of Ulster, both Protestant and Catholic, who died in
the Battle of the Somme in 1916.
</P>
<P>
   Breandan Mac Cionnaith, leader of the residents group, said
Trimble's refusal to meet with residents is illustrates the larger
problem: ``David Trimble is the MP (member of Parliament) for this
area and he won't meet with his own constituents.''
</P>
<P>
   Diffident, arrogant and pragmatic, Trimble is a tough read. In
1974, he helped wreck the last power-sharing government and ended
the political career of Brian Faulkner, the Ulster Unionist leader
to whom he is now most often compared. Many of the loyalists who
caused mayhem in 1974 are now among Trimble's staunchest allies.
</P>
<P>
   John McQuillan, a member of the Progressive Unionist Party, is
among the working-class loyalists who admire Trimble, despite what
McQuillan calls his dour disposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not the warmest of people,'' McQuillan said, ``but he cut
the best deal possible for his people, knowing that five years from
now he couldn't get as good a deal.''
</P>
<P>
   For all his truculence, Trimble has also displayed a remarkable
degree of realism. In 1995, hoping to dispel the stereotype of
intransigent unionism, he became the first unionist leader in 30
years to meet with an Irish prime minister in Dublin.
</P>
<P>
   When he was prime minister, John Major depended on the Ulster
Unionists to maintain his slim parliamentary majority, and Trimble
refused to enter all-party negotiations with Sinn Fein. Three
months after Blair was elected with the biggest parliamentary
majority in two centuries, Trimble led his party into the
negotiations, but still refuses to talk to Sinn Fein.
</P>
<P>
   Those tactics lead Paisley and Sinn Fein leader Gerry Adams to
denounce Trimble from opposite directions and for different
reasons. Paisley vows never to make peace with Trimble. Adams, who
is assured a position in a cabinet headed by Trimble, is more
sanguine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eventually, David Trimble will talk to us,'' Adams said.
</P>
<P>
   In the complicated new era of Northern Ireland politics, David
Trimble may need Gerry Adams more than he ever needed Ian Paisley.
</P>
<P>
   Some have suggested that Trimble, like Richard Nixon before him,
needed unalloyed hardline credentials to open a dialogue with sworn
enemies. Nixon went to China, as Trimble went to Stormont on Good
Friday. While many politicians might find being compared to Nixon
less than flattering, Trimble had no such problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always had a soft spot for Nixon,'' he said a few years
ago in Boston.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
