<HEADER>
A4459 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOUSE-HIDES-POT-NYT     06-30 0430
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSE-HIDES-POT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FANCY FACADE HIDES POT FARM
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By MIKE GENIELLA NYT Regional Newspapers c.1998 N.Y. Times News
Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HUMBOLDT COUNTY, Calif. _ At first glance, it looked like a
family's country dream home. There were early summer flowers in
front and a child's swing set and swimming pool out back.
</P>
<P>
   But the flowers were plastic and behind the two-story facade was
not the interior of a new house but a custom-built indoor
greenhouse where more than 9,000 pot plants were found growing.
</P>
<P>
   On the ground level, there were even special windows that made
it appear ``you were looking inside to a bathroom,'' said Sheriff
Sgt. Steve Knight.
</P>
<P>
   He said it was all an illusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the time we got through, we felt like we had wandered
around a Hollywood set,'' Knight said.
</P>
<P>
   So far, three people have been arrested in what Knight described
as the state's biggest bust of an indoor marijuana growing
operation.
</P>
<P>
   Last week's raid by local and federal drug agents uncovered an
indoor dope-growing operation that they estimated was capable of
producing an estimated $500,000 worth of processed marijuana every
month.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like a sea of green inside,'' said Knight of the 12,448
marijuana plants found growing in a cluster of four buildings
located on a heavily wooded site in a rural area. Humboldt County
is about 225 miles north of San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   About 9,600 of the plants, ranging in size from a few inches
high to 3 feet tall, were found inside the 4,000-square-foot house.
</P>
<P>
   Agents also found a marijuana nursery, drying room and numerous
rooms containing plants in varying stages of growth. The pot was
being grown under nearly 250 1,000-watt lights powered by a
generator hidden in a nearby creek.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very sophisticated operation, set up to grow
marijuana on a continuous cycle year-round,'' Knight said.
</P>
<P>
   Suspects arrested so far include 29-year-old Shaun Turner, a
resident of England; Lori Handy, 44, of Arcata; and Jeromy Shull,
23, of Eureka.
</P>
<P>
   Knight said the trio are believed to be part of a larger group
of people, ``mostly local,'' who were behind the pot-growing
operation.
</P>
<P>
   The three suspects are in custody in San Francisco, where they
face federal marijuana cultivation and manufacturing charges that
could lead to prison sentences of 20 years to life, if convicted.
They also faced possible fines totaling $4 million each, Knight
said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Mike Geniella writes for The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa,
Calif. This story was distributed by The N.Y. Times News Service.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
