<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLAG-BURNING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOES OF FLAG BURNING AMENDMENT LAUNCH AD CAMPAIGN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service Clients.)  
 By NICOLE TSONG  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Foes of the proposed constitutional amendment to
ban flag burning announced plans Tuesday to target TV ads in
Washington, Oregon and North Dakota to persuade U.S. senators there
to oppose the amendment.
</P>
<P>
   The television commercial sponsored by the People for the
American Way Foundation (PFAWF), a liberal group, features former
Vietnam War POW Jim Warner criticizing the proposed amendment on
the basis that it would limit freedom of expression.
</P>
<P>
   Warner recalls an episode from his five-and-a-half years as a
POW.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once, during an interrogation, an officer showed me pictures
of American kids burning a flag,'' he recalls in the commercial.
```This proves that your country is wrong,' (the officer) said.
`No,' I said, `those pictures prove that we're right and that our
country is strong. We're not afraid of freedom even when we
disagree.'''
</P>
<P>
   Warner told reporters Tuesday that he opposes the amendment
because it would limit freedom of expression.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the first time in the history of the Constitution since
adopting the Bill of Rights in 1791 that there has been a direct,
constitutional assault on the Bill of Rights,'' he said. ``The Bill
of Rights protects a seamless fabric. Freedom is freedom. We ought
not to qualify it.''
</P>
<P>
   The amendment, which states that ``the Congress shall have power
to prohibit the physical desecration of the flag of the United
States,'' was passed last year by the House and is expected to come
up in the Senate before Congress quits for the year in October.
</P>
<P>
   The advertisement targets four senators, Sens. Kent Conrad,
D-N.D., Byron Dorgan, D-N.D., Patty Murray, D-Wash. and Ron Wyden,
D-Ore, because they formerly opposed the amendment but now are
wavering under pressure from amendment supporters, according to
Michael Lux, vice president of the group.
</P>
<P>
   According to Lux, 64 senators clearly favor the amendment, three
short of the required two-thirds majority of 67, if all 100
senators are voting. If the Senate approves it, the amendment would
then be sent to the states for ratification. A three-quarters
majority of the states, 38 states in all, would have to ratify the
proposal before it became part of the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Dana McCallum, a spokesman for Dorgan, said the senator believes
that protecting the flag should be done statutorily instead of
through an amendment to the Bill of Rights. Conrad has expressed
similar sentiments.
</P>
<P>
   According to Tom Scott, a spokesman for Murray, the senator
opposes the amendment. Wyden was unavailable for comment.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, the Supreme Court ruled that state laws banning flag
desecration were unconstitutional under the First Amendment
protection of free speech.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to overcome that decision, Congress enacted a
federal law banning flag desecration.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court then threw out that law on the same First
Amendment grounds
</P>
<P>
   That led to the push by Rep. Gerald R.H. Solomon, R-N.Y., for a
constitutional amendment that would, in effect, overturn the
court's decision. The amendment passed the House 312-120 in 1995
but failed by a slim margin in the Senate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
