TRAVEL NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun., July 5.)  
 (jt)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; European Beaches Get Yearly Report Card &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The European Commission's annual beach report _ always a year
behind _ has just been published, providing information about
bathing conditions at European beaches in 1997. Beaches are
organized in categories that reflect the levels of chemical and
biological pollutants in the water: high quality, minimum quality
or substandard quality. In some cases beaches remain unrated for
lack of information. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Across the board, freshwater sites in Europe's interior, while
showing ``cautiously encouraging'' results for the first time,
remain more polluted than sites along the coast, mainly because
they provide better environments for bacteria. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Almost 90 percent of French coastal beaches meet minimum levels
of cleanliness or better. The western coast of France, with 90
percent of its beaches given a superior rating, fares better than
the Mediterranean coast, where only 73 percent of the beaches were
granted superior bathing status by the commission.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The beaches of vacation hubs in Spain, Portugal, Germany and
Britain are on a par with France's overall performance.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Italy and Greece did considerably better. About 95 percent of
Italy's 4,836 beaches passed minimum standards. Greece's shore did
even better, with over 98 percent of its 1,704 beaches, including
those of the islands, in compliance with minimum standards. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The report, in English, is accessible on the Internet at
europa.eu.int/water/.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A Mini-Philadelphia At Morris Arboretum &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Train buffs and garden lovers may rub shoulders at the Morris
Arboretum of the University of Pennsylvania this summer, where
model trains travel through a miniature re-creation of historic
Philadelphia _ all made with plant material. Large-gauge model
trains traveling on tracks set throughout a scale model of the city
will be on display through Oct. 4.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   More than 550 feet of track run past intricate reproductions of
landmarks that include Independence Hall, Congress Hall and the
Betsy Ross house. In addition to living plants, including flowers
and mosses, the layout incorporates acorns and other seeds, hollow
logs, bark and twigs, water and stones.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The exhibit was designed by the landscape architect Paul Busse.
The tradition of garden railways dates to late-19th-century Europe
when scale models of projects were produced by railroad builders to
attract investors and test layouts. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Morris Arboretum, begun in 1887 as a private estate, was
transformed into a public garden and education center in 1932 by
the University of Pennsylvania. It has 92 acres of public gardens
set in a Victorian landscape of winding paths and streams, with
thousands of rare plants, including many of Philadelphia's oldest
trees. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The arboretum is open daily. Admission is $5, $4 for those over
64 and $3 for students. Children under 6 are admitted free. The
arboretum is in the Chestnut Hill section of Philadelphia, at 100
Northwestern Avenue, between Germantown and Stenton Avenues. More
information: (215) 247-5777 or www. upenn.edu/morris. The Web site
has a coupon good for a discount on admission: call up ``How to get
here'' for the cybercoupon.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Fame Goes to Her Head So Liberty Clips Access &LR;
</P>
<P>
   It's enough to give a lady a headache _ and a lot of tourists
heat exhaustion. Crowds wanting to climb to the crown of the Statue
of Liberty have become so large in recent summers that the National
Park Service has restricted access to the crown _ 22 stories up _
to passengers on the first ferries of the day from Battery Park in
Manhattan and Liberty State Park in Jersey City.
</P>
<P>
   Both of those ferries leave at 8:30 a.m., and visitors who want
to be on them should arrive at the ferry terminals by 7:30 a.m. The
restrictions, which took effect on Monday, were imposed to reduce
the lines in the statue's stairwell, where summer temperatures can
exceed 100 degrees. The heat, combined with a wait of up to three
hours, caused 160 visitors to be treated for heat-related illness
last July and August.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new restrictions, all visitors on the first two
ferries receive passes allowing them to get in line for the
354-step climb to the diadem until noon, when access is cut off.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone else will still be able to enjoy the view from the top
of the statue's pedestal _ and will have more time to do so.
Liberty Island will stay open an extra two hours a day, with the
first ferries leaving an hour earlier than the usual 9:30 departure
and the last ferries leaving the island at 7 p.m. instead of 6 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The new restrictions are in effect through Labor Day. For ferry
information, call (212) 269-5755.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; New Dialing System For Italian Telephones &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Revolutions come in all sizes. In Italy, June 19 marked a
mini-revolution in the national telephone system. People calling
from abroad must now dial the country code (39), then a 0 in front
of the old city area code. Someone calling Venice from New York,
for example, must dial 011-39-041 and then the local number. Even
telephone calls made within a city must now be prefaced by that
city's area code. A Roman calling another Rome number must dial 06
before the local number. The system has been introduced to allow
for the addition of 140 million telephone numbers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; An Artists' Retreat Opens in the Berkshires &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The Berkshires have a new attraction: the Frelinghuysen Morris
House and Studio, next door to Tanglewood in Lenox, Mass., opens
Thursday. The Bauhaus--inspired structure, preserved as it was in
the early '40s, houses paintings by Picasso, Braque, Leger and
Gris, as well as American Cubist art.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Suzy Frelinghuysen and George L.K. Morris, both key members of
the American Abstract Artists Group from its beginnings in 1936,
championed Cubism long after it went out of vogue. They also
collected European abstract art, often buying direct from the
artists, many of whom they knew. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Frelinghuysen both painted and sang soprano for the New York
City Opera, and her works are in the collections of the
Metropolitan Museum of Art and the Philadelphia Museum of Art,
among other places. Morris painted and wrote criticism, often for
the Partisan Review, and the museums where his works can be found
include the Whitney Museum of American Art and the Corcoran Gallery
of Art in Washington. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   They lived most of the year in New York and Paris, but spent
summers in Lenox. Morris co-designed the modernist house (which
shocked conservative neighbors) with the architect John Butler
Swann to be an integration of art and architecture, and it reflects
the Frelinghuysen-Morris marriage and artistic dialogue as well. He
painted the frescoes, which incorporate industrial-glass materials,
in the living room; she painted the ones in the dining room with
musical motifs. Many of their paintings hang on the walls, along
with ``Still Life with Guitar,'' a major work by Juan Gris,
Picasso's ``Dinard'' and Braque's ``Fruit Dish and Glass,'' to name
a few from their collection. In the 46-acre woodlands surrounding
the house is Gaston Lachaise's monumental sculpture ``The
Mountain,'' a reclining woman that Morris commissioned from his
friend. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Morris died in 1975, and Frelinghuysen in 1988. Since then, the
house has been home to their foundation, whose director is their
nephew, the artist Kinney Frelinghuysen. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Admission, which includes a one-hour guided tour, costs $7.50
and allows access to the woodlands' walking trails. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Frelinghuysen Morris House and Studio is at 92 Hawthorne
Street, Lenox, Mass. For information, call (413) 637-0166. Hours
through Labor Day are Thursday through Sunday, 10 a.m. to 4 p.m.
(last tour at 3). Also open June, September and October Thursday
through Saturday, 10 a.m. to 4 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
