<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RICH-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: HOLLYWOOD'S MENTAL BLOCK  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By FRANK RICH    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   There may not be a writer in America in a more delicate spot
than Chris Gerolmo. He is the Hollywood screenwriter (``Mississippi
Burning'') and director who had completed the script of ``Laws of
Madness,'' the Michael Laudor story, and was prepared to start
shooting it when Laudor, a schizophrenic who became an academic
star at Yale, was charged with the brutal stabbing of his pregnant
fiancee, Caroline Costello.
</P>
<P>
   When Ms. Costello was murdered, the reigning assumption was that
``Laws of Madness,'' a project of Ron Howard's Imagine
Entertainment, had died as well. It was no longer a movie with an
inspirational Hollywood ending. It was no longer ``a Ron Howard
movie.'' Or, as Gerolmo put it when I interviewed him this week,
``People who want to finance this movie want to make money, and
overcoming affliction is a genre which Hollywood is comfortable
with. It's harder to get a movie made that ends with a disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he added, ``I still think there is a great story to be
told, though it's gotten more complex and doesn't have the kind of
clear message it had before.'' He wondered, though, if the
mental-health community, which had looked at Laudor as a ``poster
boy,'' would welcome the idea of a revised, tragic version any more
warmly than might bottom-line-driven Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   The answer could be yes _ if Gerolmo can bring off the
complexity to which he aspires. In mass culture, where so many
battles are fought for American public opinion, no one may fare
worse than the mentally ill. The National Alliance for the Mentally
Ill is desperate to get accurate stories out _ the sad ones too _
because it knows that as long as mental illness is stigmatized,
public policy will be backward and discriminatory, whether
administered by the government, corporations or HMOs. Of the two
million-plus schizophrenics in the United States, more than half
get inadequate treatment, according to a study released in March.
</P>
<P>
   On screen, the mentally ill are more likely to be exploited for
slash-movie cash or hammed up for Oscar-seeking performances than
dramatized accurately. Otto Wahl, a psychologist who wrote ``Media
Madness,'' a study of mental illness in entertainment, points out
that ``Halloween,'' with its homicidal maniacs, remains the
hardiest Hollywood perennial. The ``positive'' alternative is often
a movie like ``Shine,'' which blurs the nature and causes of mental
illness while tacking on a simplistically triumphant denouement.
``The happy ending in which you go off to life in the suburbs with
your Ford Explorer and your wife and your dog is also a tremendous
disservice,'' says Peter Weiden, who has long treated
schizophrenics at St. Luke's-Roosevelt Hospital in New York.
</P>
<P>
   A true story is much more nuanced. ``There's so much more to
treating schizophrenia than a doctor's visit and a pill, no matter
how good that pill is,'' says Rona Purdy of the National Alliance.
Though new medicines have brought huge advances to schizophrenics,
they are not a cure. Ms. Purdy feels that people should ``see the
horrible pain of Laudor's mother and fiancee as they tried to get
him care in the last days'' when he abandoned his medication and
may have been forcefully resisting any kind of medical
intervention. ``There's no such thing as a simple intervention,''
she says. ``In the end, it's the moms that are left with these
great big sick sons.''
</P>
<P>
   Before writing his script, Chris Gerolmo screened every movie he
could about mental illness, from ``The Snake Pit'' on, and found
just one, ``The Madness of King George,'' that wasn't ``hokey'' or
``unreal.'' He also spent time with the then-thriving Laudor last
year. ``Michael had difficulties all the time,'' he recalls. ``He
told me that on a good day it took 40 percent of his mental
energies to keep his hallucinations off to the side _ on a bad day,
90 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Like everyone who knew Laudor, Gerolmo is in a state of shock.
``Laws of Madness'' is, as it must be for now, in ``moral and
creative limbo,'' he says. But he doesn't want to walk away from a
story that might help pull mental illness ``out of the darkness in
which it has always resided in the American consciousness.'' To do
so, though, he'll need the support of Imagine Entertainment, which
just this spring announced its intention to remake ``Psycho.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
