<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 18:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4486 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KIDNEY-DISEASE-TEX     06-30 0576
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDNEY-DISEASE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS KIDNEY DISEASE IS A COMMON KILLER THAT'S BARELY KNOWN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROLYN POIROT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   An adult kidney, normally the size of a fist, can swell to the
size of a football in a person with polycystic kidney disease.
</P>
<P>
   PKD is the most common life-threatening genetic illness _ as
common as cystic fibrosis, muscular dystrophy, sickle cell anemia,
Down syndrome and hemophilia added together _ but most people have
never heard of it, says Tanja Heinen, vice president of the
Polycystic Kidney Research Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Heinen was in Fort Worth recently to help organize the North
Texas Friends of the PKR Foundation, a family support group. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a developing fetus, a polycystic kidney can grow so large
that it squeezes out the heart and lungs. Half the babies born with
the recessive form of PKD, known as autosomal recessive polycystic
kidney disease (ARPKD), die before they get out of the nursery.
</P>
<P>
   Of the estimated 600,000 adults with autosomal dominant
polycystic kidney disease (ADPKD), only about 100,000 know they
have it.
</P>
<P>
   PKD can cause high blood pressure, strokes, infections, severe
back and side pains, blood in the urine and kidney failure.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cysts can range from tiny ones the size of a pinhead to
some as large as grapefruits,'' Heinen said. ``Most people who have
it are unaware until it reaches advanced stages. More than 60
percent of those with PKD eventually will develop kidney failure.''
</P>
<P>
   Erma Bombeck died of complications from the kidney transplant
she underwent after ADPKD shut down her kidney function, requiring
her to undergo daily dialysis.
</P>
<P>
   Norman Sereboff, regional coordinator for North Texas Friends,
underwent a kidney transplant for his severe PKD in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   The transplant restored normal kidney function, but he says he
still has a lot of pain from the disease, which he describes as
feeling ``like a screwdriver jabbed through your back.''
</P>
<P>
   ``PKD was just recognized as a separate disease since 1982,''
Sereboff said. ``It used to be called Bright's. You look normal on
the outside while it's ravaging the insides. People were dying of
kidney cyst infections before anyone knew what PKD was.''
</P>
<P>
   Usually there are no symptoms with the dominant form of the
disease until about age 40, said Sereboff, 57. In recent years many
women have coincidentally discovered they have PKD while undergoing
routine ultrasound scans during pregnancy, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still have nothing to stop the cysts from developing, but
we have antibiotics for the infections, and medications to help
people with PKD to get the blood pressure under control. And we
know some diet modifications, such as avoiding caffeine, help
retard the growth of the cysts,'' Heinen said.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers identified the gene that causes 90 percent of the
dominant form of the disease in 1994, and in April a team of
researchers produced a genetically altered mouse that develops the
disease.
</P>
<P>
   There now is hope for a treatment to curb cyst formation and
ultimately halt progression of the disease within five to 10 years,
Heinen said.
</P>
<P>
   For more information about PKD, call the Polycystic Kidney
Research Foundation at (800) PKD-CURE or Sereboff at (972)
241-5639.
</P>
<P>
   (Carolyn Poirot writes on health issues for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
