<HEADLINE>
HEARINGS OPEN ON NEW ENGLAND FISHING REGULATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT ALLEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pushed by a new federal law requiring more conservation at sea,
New England fishing regulators this week began what are likely to
be contentious hearings on new restrictions on what fishermen can
catch from flounder to herring to scallops.
</P>
<P>
   Much of Georges Bank, once the breadbasket for New England's
fishing fleet, has been closed since 1994 when years of overfishing
caused a collapse of cod populations. As fishermen have searched
for new places to fish, regulators say they have depleted
additional fishing grounds, even putting pressure on former
``trash'' species such as the monkfish.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a balloon. If you squeeze the air on one side, it
goes to the other side of the balloon ... There's a real problem
with overcapacity (of fishing boats) out there,'' said Teri Frady,
spokesman for the National Marine Fisheries Service, which must
approve the new limits now being proposed by the New England
Fishery Management Council.
</P>
<P>
   But fishermen at the kickoff hearing in Fairhaven, Mass. on
Monday complained that some of the new limits are both excessive
and sure to drive some of them out of business. In particular, they
objected to a crackdown on scallopers who would be reduced to an
average of 77 fishing days a year from the current 142 days.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Kendall, executive director of the New Bedford Seafood
Coalition and a member of the New England Fishery Management
Council, said he opposed the scallop limits because he believed
fishery analysts had undercounted the scallop population. He said
the prime scallop fishing ground, within the closed area of Georges
Bank, is far more abundant than analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   He predicted that some of the 250 scallop permit holders in New
England will have to leave the business, hurting New Bedford, the
scallop capital of the region, the most. Kendall also said proposed
limits on groundfishing and a cut in the daily catch of cod in the
Gulf of Maine, adopted last week, will hurt the fishing industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope that we really find a better way of managing than this
slash and burn approach,'' Kendall said.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators concede that some fishermen likely will be driven
from business by the new restrictions, which apply to the Eastern
seaboard as far south as North Carolina. But the underlying problem
in the industry, they say, is too much ``fishing power'' pulling
fish from the sea, something that is especially true among scallop
boats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the size of the (scallop) stock that's out there, all
those vessels ... can't continue to operate,'' said Frady, noting
that the Fishery Management Council is considering programs to help
displaced scallopers.
</P>
<P>
   The monthlong hearings _ which resume Wednesday in Ellsworth,
Maine, and Gloucester, Mass. _ follow congressional passage of the
Sustainable Fisheries Act in 1996. The law answered longstanding
criticism that regional management councils were dominated by
fishing interests that could delay or weaken strong actions.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new act, the New England Fishery Management Council
had to redefine ``sustainable'' levels of fishing and be prepared
to take action if the levels are exceeded. And the council must
protect the fishery even if that hurts business.
</P>
<P>
   Among the proposed measures are a ban on so-called
``streetsweepers,'' a new kind of trawling equipment that
regulators fear could greatly increase fishing power. The council
also wants new protections for fish spawning grounds that could
affect all forms of fishing.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators say that the fishing limits adopted since 1994, while
painful, are beginning to show results as stocks of cod, flounder
and haddock in Georges Bank show signs of recovery.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, said Doug Hopkins of the New England Fishery
Management Council, ``We can sustain more jobs from the resource in
New England waters if we rebuild these stocks.''
</P>
<P>
   But, for fishermen already beset by regulations, the new rules
are infuriating. ``I don't think they know what they're doing,'' Al
Cottone, owner of the 45-foot Sabrina Maria in Gloucester, told the
Associated Press. ``Every time they lower an existing limit, or add
another species, it's another nail in the coffin.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
