<SLUG> BC-TV-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV NOTES: `60 MINUTES' II; CABLE CULTURE; EXCLUSIVE SNAG 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By LAWRIE MIFFLIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Only Don Hewitt knows for sure exactly how involved
he will be in supervising the production of a second version of
``60 Minutes,'' the granddaddy of news-magazine programs.
</P>
<P>
   Published reports during the last week have been at odds in
describing a second night of the popular Sunday night program,
which CBS executives dearly want because they believe it will give
their weeknight prime-time lineup the same ratings boost that
``Dateline'' gives NBC and ``20/20'' gives ABC. But the varying
reports of the nature of Hewitt's involvement seem to be a matter
of semantics.
</P>
<P>
   CBS News President Andrew Heyward has beseeched all involved in
the debate over a second ``60 Minutes'' to refrain from speaking to
the press. So Hewitt, who created the program in 1968 and has been
its executive producer ever since, wrote one all-purpose statement
and authorized its release to any interested reporters and will say
no more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to burst upon the scene with a news magazine
that's every bit as different and worthy as `60 Minutes' was 30
years ago,'' his statement said. ``I'm not interested in a rip-off
of `20/20,' `Dateline' or `60 Minutes.'''
</P>
<P>
   This latest attempt to clarify Hewitt's role in a program that
is still in development set off a new wave of tea-leaf reading.
</P>
<P>
   Some think Hewitt's statement means he would refuse to cooperate
with creating a cloned version of his program, but would go along
with producing a completely new type of news magazine. This theory
is backed up by the nickname for the program among members of the
CBS News staff _ ``60 Minutes Jr.'' _ and by the fact that some
junior producers have already been assigned to work on it. In this
view, the program would have a new format and feature some young
noncelebrity correspondents.
</P>
<P>
   Others think the program will resemble ``60 Minutes'' closely,
but with different producers and correspondents. Whatever its shape
or format, everyone who speaks about the program, on or off the
record, is certain it will have the magic words ``60 Minutes'' in
its title _ and that's the crucial point.
</P>
<P>
   More Culture on Cable
</P>
<P>
   New York's public television station, WNET on Channel 13, is
close to getting a new outlet on cable television, people close to
the negotiations say.
</P>
<P>
   Rainbow Media, the programming arm of Cablevision, the largest
provider of cable television in the New York metropolitan area,
will soon announce a new package of cable channels for its 2.6
million subscribers, and one will be partly programmed by Channel
13. It will be called MetroArts, the sources said, and will operate
six hours daily, between 9 p.m. and 3 a.m. EDT, starting in late
summer or early fall.
</P>
<P>
   Some programs will be jointly produced with New York-area arts
institutions, giving many of them their first cable exposure. WNET
has been busy signing production agreements with institutions
including the city's major art museums, the 92d Street Y, the
American Theater Wing and the Emelin Theater in suburban
Mamaroneck.
</P>
<P>
   WNET President William F. Baker was traveling and unavailable
for comment Tuesday, but he has spoken in recent months about his
plans to develop a cable channel with a suitable distribution
partner. Last fall he hired an executive producer for local
programming, Michael Fields, from Pittsburgh's PBS station, and
said he intended for Fields to develop ideas for the cable arts
channel.
</P>
<P>
   Baker emphasized that the proposed channel would be
noncommercial and nonprofit, in keeping with a PBS station's
mandate, and would seek underwriting support.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the reverse of our slogan, `If PBS doesn't do it, who
will?' because we think if we don't do this, somebody else might,''
Baker said a few weeks ago. ``It's also a new side of Thirteen.
We're one of the biggest national producers for PBS, but now we're
saying our community deserves special attention, because of its
great cultural attractions.''
</P>
<P>
   Snagging an Exclusive
</P>
<P>
   Every self-respecting news-magazine program has to have its
share of exclusive interviews, known in the business as ``gets.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that Fox is joining the Big Three broadcast networks in
producing a prime-time news magazine, the network naturally had to
trumpet its big ``get'' for the program's premiere episode: an
exclusive interview with the brother of Diana, Princess of Wales.
The program, ``Fox Files,'' will have Catherine Crier and Jon Scott
as co-anchors, and will appear on Thursdays from 9 to 10 p.m. EDT,
making its debut on July 16.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Crier was in England last weekend to interview the Princess'
brother, Earl Spencer, who also made available some home movies and
still photographs not previously seen, and had Ms. Crier tour the
gardens, estate and museum at Althorp, the Spencer family's estate.
The museum opens to the public Wednesday, the Princess' birthday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-98 1855EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
