<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SANCHEZ VICARIO FINDS THE WAY IN THE SECOND TWO SETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GREENIDGE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Arantxa Sanchez Vicario seems to be getting the hang of
coming back.
</P>
<P>
   She lost the first set but rallied to eliminate Dominique Van
Roost, 3-6, 6-3, 6-2, Tuesday in their fourth-round match at
Wimbledon.
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez Vicario, the fifth seed, has lost the initial set in
three of her four matches thus far, but she may be living more than
dangerously if she keeps up the trend in her quarterfinal match
today against No. 1 seed Martina Hingis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that I raise my level when I am down a set, and I know
it shouldn't be like this, but that's the way it's been
happening,'' said Sanchez Vicario, who fell behind, 5-0, in the
first set.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just come back and at the end play better and win the match.
Obviously, the first set I play normally, it's supposed to be like
this, but it seems like I've been a very slow start.''
</P>
<P>
   In the second set, Sanchez Vicario grabbed a 5-1 lead before
holding in the ninth game. In the decisive set, Sanchez Vicario
broke in the first game before taking the last three games,
including another break.
</P>
<P>
   ``The level I was playing was very strong, so I couldn't
continue and I got a bit tired,'' Van Roost said. ``You don't have
to have the same precision than when you're very fresh, so she
started to get into the match.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the second set, she didn't miss one ball and I started to
miss a few, which is normal with my game. She was very confident.
In the third set, I was tired and she was just running and playing
incredibly good.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez Vicario doesn't have a reason for her slow starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't prefer to be in that situation, but I think that
it's important that I play well at the end and to be able to win in
the situation,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, Sanchez Vicario is delighted with her play. ``I think
that each match has been better and I've been playing a lot lately
and each match is more difficult,'' she said, ``But I feel good
with myself and my game, too. I keep winning.''
</P>
<P>
   Aggressive play has paid off for Sanchez Vicario, who was a
Wimbledon finalist in 1995 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't able to move the ball as well (in the first set), and
she attacked really well and she's a dangerous player,'' Sanchez
Vicario said. ``You have to play and go for your shots, and I
realized that after I lost the first set.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew that if I wanted to win I'd have to do that and that's
why I came back doing it better and I was able to stay in the
match.''
</P>
<P>
   Hingis, however, is an entirely different matter. The reigning
Wimbledon, US Open, and Australian Open champ is 5-1 against
Sanchez Vicario, who is not a grass specialist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, I have nothing to lose,'' Sanchez Vicario said.
``She's the favorite and that can help me. I'm just going to go on
the court and try to start well at the beginning if I can and play
as well as I did these matches, to be aggressive, that's all.''
</P>
<P>
   It took Hingis some time to get going before she defeated
Thailand's Tamarine Tanasugarn, 6-3, 6-2, in an 11 a.m. match.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was still sleeping in practice (before the match),'' she
stated. The turnaround came in the seventh game of the first set,
when Tanasugarn was up, 40-0, and Hingis came back to take the
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have the feel at the beginning of the match; I had
problems getting the rhythm,'' Hingis said. ``I had to get to know
what she dislikes, and in the second set it was much better.''
</P>
<P>
   Long rallies dominated the match. ``I knew she was going to like
my game pretty much because she's playing very flat and she doesn't
mind the speed at all,'' said Hingis. ``So the harder (I hit), the
better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
