<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 19:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4517 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRO     06-30 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEX AND OTHER SANDY ACTIVITIES
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   _ In answer to the question ``How safe is sex on the beach?''
Glamour magazine warns that contact with rough sand ``can cause
tiny tears in condoms or diaphragms.'' On the other hand, salt
water kills bacteria, so sex in the water may reduce one's risk of
contracting a bacterial disease.
</P>
<P>
   (The latest Bride's magazine reports, incidentally, that only
4.4 percent of engaged women are virgins, and 1.1 percent of
engaged men. The average bride has prepared for the occasion with
seven partners, including her fiance.)
</P>
<P>
   _ Brimming with tips for would-be romantics, P.O.V. magazine
says men who listen to the music of  &UR; Erykah Badu  &LR; send the message,
``I am in touch with my feminine side''; men who listen to  &UR; Barbra
Streisand  &LR; announce, ``I am a little too in touch with my feminine
side''; and men who are fans of  &UR; The Artist Formerly &LR; 
 &UR; Known as Whomever &LR;  are saying, ``I am/ have been/ will be in touch
with someone else's feminine side.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Lena Lencek &LR;  and  &UR; Gideon Bosker &LR; , authors of ``The Beach: The
History of Paradise on Earth'' (Viking; $25.95), need geographical
aid. A glorious description of San Francisco's old Sutro Baths
(``At any one time, ten thousand bathers swam, swung from the rings
and trapezes, and dived from the springboards and platforms'') is
followed by mention of ``another gargantuan swimming facility,''
the Fleishhacker Pool ``across San Francisco Bay.'' In real life,
Fleishhacker was just south down the Great Highway.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ Publishers Weekly harrumphs that at the recent Book Expo
America 98 convention in Chicago, ``in non-book industry trade show
style, several exhibitors used barely dressed women to lure
attendees into the booths''; the New Yorker had a party for
advertisers &LR;  but not book reviewers; and Simon &AMP; Schuster gave out
fake Viagra pills.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Paul Sorvino &LR;  plans to star in and direct his own version of
``King Lear, &LR; '' with his daughter,  &UR; Mira Sorvino &LR; , playing Lear's
good daughter, Cordelia.
</P>
<P>
   _ Always awestruck by the wonders of San Francisco,  &UR; Strange &LR; 
 &UR; de Jim  &LR; says he was wearing his ``Nobody Knows I'm a Lesbian''
T-shirt when he encountered a woman wearing one that said, ``Nobody
Knows I'm Elvis.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Dining together after they both received honorary degrees last
week from the California Institute of Integral Studies,
philanthropist  &UR; Laurance Rockefeller &LR;  and professional
consciousness-explorer  &UR; Baba Ram Dass &LR;  _ ``two wise old men,'' said
one observer _ said they are such old pals they couldn't remember
where they'd first met.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Max Shapiro  &LR; of Point Richmond, Calif., owner of Green for
Jeans and collector of vintage Levi's, has paid $8,000 for a rare
pair of never-worn Levi 501s made during World War II. The
stitching on the back pocket is painted on because there was a
thread shortage during the war. Shapiro bought the jeans from a
dealer who'd purchased them for $7.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the market for vintage jeans hasn't exactly held
steady in Japan. Because of the declining value of the yen, the
prices are down 70 percent from last year's highs.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SLINGS AND ARROWS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Political cartoonist  &UR; Timothy Patrick Moynihan &LR; , who goes by the
name of  &UR; Mendl  &LR; and is the son of the New York senator, denied at a
party at Webster Hall in New York last week that his father had
killed an Indian with a bow and arrow when he was ambassador to
India.
</P>
<P>
   The elder Moynihan tried his hand at archery during a
demonstration of the sport at the coronation of the  &UR; King of &LR; 
 &UR; Bhutan &LR; . ``The Bhutanese national sport is archery,'' Moynihan told
the New York Observer, ``and this being kind of a medieval country,
the targets were held by servants.''
</P>
<P>
   The ambassador's arrow wounded one of the target-holders, but he
``didn't kill anybody. Hit him in the leg or something, and the
Bhutanese didn't blink. When you shoot at targets being held by
people, people get hit.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Researchers at UCLA studied 387 baseball players, reports
Muscle &AMP; Fitness magazine, and found that major leaguers have
``better visual skills'' _ including 3-D vision, discrimination
against backgrounds and seeing details _ than minor leaguers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``I was unsure of what to wear before I interviewed the Duchess
of Windsor. I knew that she wore really refined, elegant Chanel
suits. Her bags matched her shoes. So I put on my maroon copy of a
copy of a Chanel suit. I wore maroon shoes and carried a maroon
bag. The Duchess looked like a perfect dragon. She wasn't soft, she
wasn't pretty. As I walked into the room, she said, `My dear. Too
much maroon.' I was crushed.''
</P>
<P>
   _ New York Post gossipist Cindy Adams in Allure magazine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-98 1908EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980630.0267 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 19:09 </DATE_TIME>
