<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 19:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4520 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIDS-RESISTANT-BOS &LR;      06-30 0867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIDS-RESISTANT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRUG-RESISTANT AIDS VIRUS SEEN AS TRANSMITTABLE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA _ AIDS specialists had hoped it wouldn't happen, but now,
they say, they know that strains of HIVthat are immune to the most
potent triple-drug treatments can be passed from one person to
another.
</P>
<P>
   The news, reported here Tuesday at the 12th World AIDS
Conference, sounded an alarm to researchers and treatment
specialists, who fear that more such multidrug-resistant cases are
inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking at the tip of an iceberg,'' said Dr. John W.
Mellors of the University of Pittsburgh, who chaired a session on
AIDS-drug resistance.
</P>
<P>
   In reports presented here, researchers disclosed that one man in
San Francisco and another individual in Geneva recently became
infected with HIV mutants that cannot be suppressed by the widely
used AIDS drug ``cocktails'' that have given thousands of patients
a new lease on life since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Swiss scientists have also documented a handful of other HIV
infections by strains resistant to protease inhibitors alone _ the
most potent ingredient in multidrug HIV treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Mellors said, researchers at the US Centers for
Disease Control and Prevention have discovered that two Americans
were infected by an HIV mutant resistant to virtually all other
drugs in a class known as nucleoside analogues, another key
ingredient in the anti-HIV cocktail. Nucleoside analogues, which
jam the assembly of new viral DNA, include the widely used agents
AZT, 3TC, ddC and D4T.
</P>
<P>
   Like the cases of protease inhibitor-resistant virus,
transmission of a multiply nucleoside-resistant strain represents a
first, Mellors said. The report was presented last week at a
meeting in Italy on AIDS drug resistance.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers have long known that HIV, which causes AIDS, can
rapidly lose susceptibility to any drug in a given patient. The
only way around that _ and the key to success of triple-drug
therapy _ is to hit the virus simultaneously with several different
drugs at once, suppressing its replication to such a low level that
it cannot acquire resistance mutations.
</P>
<P>
   What is new in the recent reports is that the multidrug
resistant strains, and those that have escaped the effects of
protease and nucleoside drugs alone, have been passed from one
individual to another.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of why this is important is that many have speculated it
would be very difficult to transmit a protease inhibitor-resistant
HIV,'' said Dr. Frederick Hecht of the University of California at
San Francisco, who is scheduled to present a report this morning on
one case. ``Many hoped it might not be possible at all.''
</P>
<P>
   The hypothesis, now proved false, was that the multiple
mutations required for HIV to resist protease inhibitors would make
it less ``fit,'' or infectious.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco man was infected through unprotected anal
intercourse with a man who harbored a viral strain resistant to six
of the 11 anti-HIV drugs on the market, encompassing all three
classes of such drugs. The virus became resistant, researchers
said, through sequential treatment with many different AIDS drugs,
as well as interruptions in his treatment for reasons beyond his
control.
</P>
<P>
   Current HIV therapy stresses simultaneous, uninterrupted
treatment with at least three drugs to prevent resistance.
</P>
<P>
   Among the 16,000 people who become infected by HIV each day
around the world, many already acquire strains with built-in
resistance to AZT, the first AIDS drug. In San Francisco, for
instance, about 16 percent of new infections involve AZT-resistant
virus.
</P>
<P>
   While the circulation of AZT-resistant virus is troubling,
doctors have had other arrows in their quiver to treat such
patients. Now AIDS specialists worry those options may eventually
disappear. The development carries big implications, many
researchers said. To name just a few:
</P>
<P>
   --- Doctors must make sure they prescribe the most effective HIV
therapy to avoid giving rise to infectious mutants. Right now, 42
percent of US patients being treated for HIV are on less than
optimal regimens that doctors say are certain to give rise to
resistant strains, according to a report presented here by US
health officials.
</P>
<P>
   --- People on anti-HIV treatments must take their drugs
religiously to suppress the emergence of resistant strains, and
also practice safe sex to avoiding infecting others. ``We need to
put more energy into supporting patients' adherence to their drug
regimens,'' Hecht said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   --- A new push to extend HIV treatment to developing countries
must not ``unwittingly become a factory for resistant virus,''
warned Margaret Chesny of the University of California. This could
happen, she said, if HIV-infected individuals could obtain only the
cheaper two-drug regimens certain to give rise to resistant
strains.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Calvin Cohen, a Boston AIDS specialist, cited a recent
decision by South African health insurers to pay for HIV therapy _
but only for less expensive two-drug regimens. ``They're about to
make a big mistake,'' Cohen said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
