<HEADER>
A4526 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-CLINTON-ART-450     06-30 1206
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-CLINTON-ART-450&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON CHINESE TALK RADIO, POLITE QUESTIONS ON SAFE TOPICS FOR
CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDS: Refiling to include graphics advisory. No other changes.)  (See also: CHINA-NOTEBOOK, CHINA-TAIWAN, CHINA-PEONY,
HONGKONG-ANNIVERSARY, ASIA-RUBIN) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(th) 
 By SETH FAISON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHANGHAI, China _ Talk radio is still new in China, so good
behavior counts.
</P>
<P>
   Callers are generally polite, not confrontational. A host would
never hang up on anybody, the way Howard Stern likes to do. And the
idea of trying anything as risque as voicing a contrary political
opinion is altogether foreign, though maybe the vigilant screeners
just make it seem that way.
</P>
<P>
   When President Clinton turned up Tuesday at the studio of
Shanghai Radio 990 to make his first appearance on a talk radio
show outside the United States, he fielded such questions as the
need for library exchanges, requirements for joining the World
Trade Organization, and the benefits of better education. One
caller even asked about auto emissions. Clinton seemed thrilled.
``One of the things you need to know,'' Clinton replied, ``is that
when a car, an automobile, burns gasoline, about 80 percent of the
heat value of the gasoline is lost in the inefficiency of the
engine. But they are now developing new engines, called
fuel-injection machines, where the fuel goes directly into the
engine and it is about four times more efficient.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I hope that within a matter of just a few years, in the
U.S., in China and throughout the world, all these engines will be
much, much less polluting. And that will be very good for the
health of the people of China and for the health of the world
environment.''
</P>
<P>
   At that, Zuo Anlong, the host of the show, ``Citizens and
Society,'' could not resist a segue into mass transportation and,
after a sip of Diet Coke, Clinton was off and running again. Here
was a chance to delve deeply into policy without obnoxious hosts to
cut in unexpectedly or resort to gotcha questions.
</P>
<P>
   There was no mention of sex, violence or drugs. And certainly no
allusions to Monica Lewinsky. It was an inveterate talker's
paradise.
</P>
<P>
   Allowing Clinton to answer questions from callers on live radio,
uncensored, might have seemed unthinkable only a week ago. The
media in China are tightly monitored, and broadcasting is generally
kept within the narrow confines of approved programming.
</P>
<P>
   After Clinton spoke about sensitive political topics like the
Tiananmen Square massacre and Tibet in a nationally televised news
conference Saturday with President Jiang Zemin, then addressed
students at Beijing University on Monday, having him on Shanghai
radio reinforced the signals of greater openness in China, at least
symbolically.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the reality of Tuesday's program illustrated the firm limits
that also remain on public discourse in this country. As long as
the radio station could screen its callers, even Clinton's presence
could not move the discussion past a collection of safe topics.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Here was one typical question, from Li, in Shanghai: ``As far as
getting the Shanghai Library and American libraries going for
better and better exchanges, what can we do to increase the amount
of exchange and cooperation between them?''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's answer was too long to print here, but suffice it to
say: start with more Internet use, then we will ask someone at the
Library of Congress to follow up.
</P>
<P>
   Another question, from Yu, in Shanghai: ``As far as promoting
cooperation in science and technology between the United States and
China, what are you planning to do?''
</P>
<P>
   The president kept it innocuous, citing earthquake prediction
and spina bifida research, and then asked that anyone wth an idea
write it down and mail it to him. There seemed to be no need to
mention nuclear or satellite technology.
</P>
<P>
   There was one question with a little juice.
</P>
<P>
   ``You seem very healthy, and you seem to have a very nice
figure, Mr. President,'' from another Li from Shanghai. ``When you
were in college, which sports did you like to play? That's the
first question. The second question I'd like to ask, if you could
answer, Mr. President, is how do you maintain your energy in your
work? And then the third thing is: Can you predict who's going to
win the World Cup?''
</P>
<P>
   The short version: He played basketball in college, started
jogging later, and finally settled on golf. ``It's my favorite
sport. Even though it doesn't burn a lot of calories, it makes my
mind calm. So I like it.''
</P>
<P>
   And then he threw caution to the wind and predicted that Brazil
would be ``hard to beat'' in the world soccer tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's host in Shanghai, Mayor Xu Kuangdi, was also in the
studio to answer questions and he could almost hold his own with
the president, talking at length about auto emissions and the
information superhighway.
</P>
<P>
   Then came a question from Wang, in Shanghai: ``Can you both talk
about education exchanges and the future for them between the
United States and China?''
</P>
<P>
   Education seemed to be the favorite topic for each man, so they
were off like horses, taking turns racing in the lead. Clinton
spoke for several minutes about the need for computer literacy,
affordable education and exchange programs, concluding with a
typically innocuous ``and I think it will only grow more important
as we move into the next century.''
</P>
<P>
   Xu came back with a lengthy discussion about the need for
Chinese teachers to consider introducing elements of the American
teaching system in order to foster greater individuality.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Chinese education, we talk about the filling of information
into the student, whereas in the United States, they try to make
students more able, they try to teach you how to have the ability
to do things,'' Xu said. ``So Chinese are very good at tests, but
not necessarily when it comes to scientific research.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said: ``Well, actually, here's a case where I think we
would greatly benefit from working together, because there is no
perfect system. If you just start with the issue of discipline and
order in the classroom, it's impossible for learning to occur. We
also know that if there is too much order, where everything is
structured, the child may close up and not be open to information
and to learning. So we have tried all kinds of things.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now on the second matter,'' and he went on for a while longer.
</P>
<P>
   It was only toward the end of the hour that Clinton found a way
to sound his sole note of political imperative, similar to what he
said at the news conference with Jiang and at Beijing University.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe, as I have said repeatedly, that high levels of
personal freedom are quite important to the success of a society in
the information age,'' he said, ``because you need people who feel
free to explore, to state their views, to explore their own
convictions, and then live out their own dreams, and that this will
add to the stability of a society by enriching it. That's what I
believe.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
