<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 19:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4529 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRIPP-TESTIFIES-BOS &LR;      06-30 0817
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRIPP-TESTIFIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE CURIOUS, THE PRESS CROWD TRIPP VISIT TO GRAND JURY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. MARCUS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Tourists ambling between the Washington Monument
and the Capitol Tuesday added an unlikely destination to their
rounds: the E. Barrett Prettyman federal courthouse, where Linda
Tripp spent six hours Tuesday testifying to a grand jury about an
alleged presidential affair and coverup.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of reporters and camera crews jostled for prime places in
front of entrances on all four sides of the grey, six-story
building. Out-of-towners paused to watch Tripp enter the courthouse
shortly after 9 a.m. Or, more precisely, the tourists stopped to
watch the journalists watching Tripp's arrival.
</P>
<P>
   Tripp, who secretly taped about 20 hours of conversations with
her friend and former White House intern Monica Lewinsky, is the
star witness of the most-covered White House scandal in more than
two decades. Her public appearance Tuesday was her first in months.
Since January, Tripp has become the woman everyone opines about,
even though she has barely said a word and has not revealed her
motivations.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing a dark pantsuit and escorted by Federal Protective
Service Police, Tripp got out of a van with her daughter, son, and
lawyers and headed to the third floor of the courthouse where the
grand jury convened by Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr waited.
</P>
<P>
   Cameras clicked. Reporters scribbled. ``Tripp is in the
building, Tripp has arrived in the building,'' an Associated Press
television cameraman announced into his cellular phone.
</P>
<P>
   The tourists along Constitution Avenue were far outnumbered by
the reporters and photographers who came prepared to stake out days
of Tripp testimony. They brought folding chairs, umbrellas,
stepladders, binoculars, laptop computers, telephones, pagers,
telephoto lenses, crossword puzzles, paperback books, and bottled
water.
</P>
<P>
   Tripp, a 48-year-old Pentagon employee and former White House
aide, ignored reporters' shouted questions. At the end of the day,
her lawyer, Anthony Zaccagnini, gave a morsel to the reporters. By
his account, when Tripp left the grand jury room, she said, ``I
find it very easy to truthfully answer the questions posed to me by
the prosecutors and the grand jury.'' Tripp will testify again on
Thursday, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Tripp's long-anticipated testimony is the centerpiece of Starr's
probe of President Clinton for perjury and obstruction of justice
in connection with his and Lewinsky's testimony in the
now-dismissed Paula Jones sexual harassment case. Tripp's
appearance could put pressure on Lewinsky to make an immunity deal
with prosecutors and testify to the nature of her alleged
relationship with the president.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the courthouse, the scene said a lot about the story
that has captivated Washington since January. Several tourists said
they were repelled by the story, disgusted by the details, and
bored by the repetition and speculation. And yet something about
the spectacle at the courthouse lured them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm tired of having all this on the news with my kids at the
dinner table,'' said Susan Bucci, from Norfolk, Mass., who stopped
by the courthouse with her parents and her daughter, Mary, 13, and
twins, Allison and Laura, 11. At school, Mary said, ``No one talks
about it, and no one cares about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The family was making the rounds of Washington's better known
sites, including the National Gallery, the Franklin Delano
Roosevelt Memorial and the Museum of American History. But the
commotion at the federal courthouse was worth a quick look.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an impressive sight as far as the technical part,''
said Steve Permut, a patent attorney from Detroit, gesturing at the
line of trucks topped by satellite dishes beaming images to
television stations across the country and around the world. ``But
as far as the substance of it, I think China is more important,''
said Permut, who described his politics as ``independent tending
more toward Democrat.''
</P>
<P>
   Karl Mueller and his wife, Irmi, retirees visiting from Munich,
snapped pictures of the mass of journalists, but they were not
impressed. ``In Germany, the chancellor would be allowed to have
his privacy,'' Mueller said.
</P>
<P>
   Tripp has been pilloried as a friend who used Lewinsky to
embarrass Clinton. But she does have her fans, such as Steve and
Cindy Curtis of Dayton, Ohio, who think Clinton has besmirched the
office of the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   In the morning, they stopped by the six-floor courthouse with
their four children to take a picture of Tripp. But just as she
stepped out of the dark minivan, their camera ran out of film.
</P>
<P>
   Having made their Tripp sighting, the Curtis family continued on
to the White House. ``We can't skip the White House just because
Clinton lives there,'' Cindy Curtis said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-98 1914EDT &QL; 
