<TEXT>
<P>
   (pr) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Wednesday, July 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (212-556-1927).
</P>
<P>
   BIRTHS (Washington) _ The birth rate for unmarried black women,
long a focal point in the debate over the causes of poverty among
blacks, has reached its lowest point in 40 years, federal health
officials say _ one result of a national survey of birth
certificates from all the states. By Steven A. Holmes. With
graphic. (Eds. note: budgeted earlier as BLACKS-BIRTHS)
</P>
<P>
   POPE-LETTER (Rome) _ Pope John Paul II, in an apostolic letter,
enshrines into church law an oath obliging theologians to accept
Catholic teachings such as bans on women priests, contraception,
and euthanasia. By Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   photo reefer: CHINA-CLINTON (Shanghai) _ Talk radio, in China,
is still a relatively new form of communication. So when President
Clinton turned up Tuesday at the studio of Shanghai Radio 990 to
make his first-ever appearance on a talk radio show outside the
United States, it may have caused great excitement among callers,
but it yielded a decidedly benign set of questions and answers. By
Seth Faison. With graphic. (MOVED)
</P>
<P>
   HONGKONG-ANNIVERSARY (Hong Kong) _ His hometown is marking the
first anniversary of its return to China on July 1, but Loon
Wai-ting is in no mood to celebrate. Loon has spent the year
without a job. Of course, Britain's exit from Hong Kong has had
little to do with the economic downturn of its former colony, but
Loon speaks for many Hong Kong people, who are being ravaged by
rising unemployment, a 20 percent drop in the stock market, and a
40 percent decline in the property market. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   IRAN-TRIAL (Tehran, Iran) _ In a huge courtroom under the heat
and glare of TV klieg lights, the mayor of Tehran is struggling to
keep his job, clear his name and justify the way he does business.
Gholamhussein Karbaschi, the 45-year-old former cleric who has run
Iran's sprawling capital for the past eight years, is on trial,
accused of embezzling nearly $5 million, receiving bribes,
influence peddling, financing political campaigns and misusing
official funds, charges that could land him in prison for an
unspecified length of time if he is convicted. By Elaine Sciolino.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-STARR (Washington) _ Linda Tripp goes before the grand
jury; other developments in Kenneth Starr's investigation of the
president. By James Bennet.
</P>
<P>
   Reefers:
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-ATTACK (undated) _ An American F-16 attacked an Iraqi
anti-aircraft battery after Iraqi forces aimed radar at a squadron
of British jets routinely patroling the ``no flight'' zone over
southern Iraq, officials say. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-AIDS-THERAPY (Geneva) _ Researchers raised the possibility
that treatment may someday eliminate the AIDS virus from the body
or lower it to a point where the immune system can successfully
control it. By Lawrence K. Altman.
</P>
</TEXT>
