<HEADLINE>
THEN THE TIGER SAYS TO THE DOCTOR ...  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 5) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DR. DOLITTLE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Murphy, Ossie Davis, Kristen Wilson and the voices of Norm
Macdonald, Albert Brooks, Jenna Elfman &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Betty Thomas &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PG-13 90 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Thomas' movie adapts the Hugh Lofting stories and the 1967
film with Rex Harrison. As a child, John Dolittle (Murphy) enjoyed
the unusual talent of being able to talk with animals. Once he
became a doctor, he suppressed his gift, but to his horror it
resurfaces involuntarily after he nearly kills a dog with his car.
</P>
<P>
   Although his wife (Ms. Wilson) has him temporarily committed, an
owl puts the word out among the animals of San Francisco that he
can understand them and thus treat their illnesses and injuries.
Performing death-defying surgery on an ailing circus tiger, the
doctor comes to re-evaluate his ``weirdness'' and actually revel in
it. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE Except for the near-miss with the dog, none. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEX None; the needy animals interrupt any attempt. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY Lots of bathroom humor involving coarse slang for body
parts and functions. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 5-10 There is the language to consider, but despite the
film's slow start, small children should take to the idea of
communicating with animals. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 11-14 They may find the idea corny, but the film may
pleasantly surprise them. And they'll no doubt get the message:
everyone has a difference of some sort that makes them special. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 15 AND UP They'll consider themselves too sophisticated for
such fare, but Mr. Murphy's fans will find some laughs. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Suzanne O'Connor &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ARMAGEDDON &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Willis, Ben Affleck, Liv Tyler, Billy Bob Thornton, Steve
Buscemi &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Michael Bay &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PG-13 144 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In New York it's already raining meteors the size of
Volkswagens, and in 18 days a space rock as big as Texas should hit
about mid-Pacific Ocean, piling up a three-mile-high tidal wave
that will wash up in Denver and otherwise spelling finis for
human-kind. ``What do we do?'' asks the president.
</P>
<P>
   Well, you pull up your socks and hire Harry S. Stamper (Willis)
and his oil-drilling crew to fly out there in a couple of space
shuttles, drill an 800-foot-deep hole in the asteroid and plant a
nuclear device that will blast it to pieces before it reaches
Earth.
</P>
<P>
   A can-do spirit abounds as Harry and his roughnecks, characters
all, train for the big mission. Out in space, though, it's one
confirmation of Murphy's Law right after another as the crew battle
nasty surprises and one another. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE Once again in a major action film, cities are destroyed
but no one is shown getting hurt. On the mission, people come to
bad ends, but aside from a splash of blood here and there, nothing
is grisly. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEX A young woman (Ms. Tyler) having a liaison with her
boyfriend (Affleck) hides under the bedcovers from her angry father
(Willis). Otherwise, none. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY Strong. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 3-8 No. All the noise and wreckage could be upsetting. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 9-12 By this age, they will realize it's only a movie, and
while there is plenty of rough stuff on the mission, there's
nothing here that most children can't handle. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 13 AND UP They'll like a teen-age action movie _ and one
with a PG-13 rating, rather than an R. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Peter M. Nichols &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GONE WITH THE WIND &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Victor Fleming &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Vivien Leigh, Clark Gable, Leslie Howard, Olivia de Havilland &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No rating 222 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Scarlett O'Hara (Leigh) is just a happy, flirtatious teen-age
Southern belle until she learns that the dashing man she loves,
Ashley Wilkes (Howard), is going to marry his cousin Melanie
Hamilton (de Havilland). Then Scarlett's world is truly turned
upside down: by the Civil War, which destroys the Old South she has
grown up in, and by Rhett Butler (Gable), a handsome blockade
runner who has, as he says, ``a way with the ladies.''
</P>
<P>
   Scarlett marries three times, is widowed twice, volunteers as a
war nurse, saves her family's plantation, grieves for loved ones
and generally scandalizes everybody in Atlanta before realizing
where her happiness lies. The classic 1939 film is back, restored
and re-released for yet another generation. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE Scarlett shoots a Yankee soldier in the face. A man is
pushed out of a wagon and over a bridge. Though a war is going on,
there are no real battle scenes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEX A few passionate kisses. The closest thing to a bedroom
scene is Rhett carrying Scarlett, in her dressing gown, up a
staircase. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY Gable's one famous four-letter word at the end. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FOOTNOTE The film, almost 60 years old, reflects some very
negative racial attitudes of its time. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 3-8 No harm, but there isn't much to interest them. And
it's long. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 9-12 They're probably old enough to appreciate the basic
story, the humor and the spectacle. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 13 AND UP Absolutely. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
