<SLUG> BC-MA-TEACHERS-CELLUCCI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELLUCCI SAYS STANDARDS, NOT POLITICS, RULE TEACHER ISSUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ADRIAN WALKER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Acting Governor Paul Cellucci sounded a note of
defiance Tuesday in the face of accusations that he botched the
teacher testing issue, leading to the resignation of Education
Commissioner Frank W. Haydu 3d.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really am not concerned about the political fallout, I'm not
concerned with the personnel fallout,'' Cellucci said. ``I believe
we have to do the right thing, and the right thing is to hold the
line on standards.''
</P>
<P>
   But by the end of the day, Cellucci had suffered perhaps his
stormiest day as acting governor, savaged by opponents in both
parties for indecisive and opportunistic leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paul Cellucci and his board have provided no direction, no
leadership and no stability,'' said Patricia McGovern, one of
Cellucci's Democratic rivals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parents in Massachusetts and our studtents have a right to
direction and stability. This has become a bit of a joke and its a
bad joke because we've become a laughingstock and I don't think
it's very funny.''
</P>
<P>
   The controversy ignited by massive failures on the teachers'
test reached the governor's race Tuesday, further politicizing what
had already become a hot political issue.
</P>
<P>
   With voters showing little passion for the red-meat issues of
yesteryear such as crime, welfare and taxes, politicians have
seized on education in a bid to bond with voters.
</P>
<P>
   But Cellucci's long four days of silence on the teacher testing
issue before springing into action late last week, came back to
haunt him by giving his opponents an opportunity to bash him for
inaction.
</P>
<P>
   They said Cellucci had been in favor of not counting the test
results, then for counting them, then had argued for one passing
grade and then another.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Scott Harshbarger was the first to tee off.
</P>
<P>
   ``At his press conference last week, Paul Cellucci said he took
a walk and came to the realization of how important teacher testing
is,'' Harshbarger said at a press conference. ``I say that for the
last seven years Paul Cellucci has taken a walk on education.''
</P>
<P>
   What Harshbarger did not mention is that Haydu has contributed
to his campaign. Haydu and his wife each contributred the legal
maximum of $500 to Harshbarger last year, according to campaign
finance reports, and hosted a fundraiser for the campaign that
raised about $7,000. Haydu also contributed $150 to Harshbarger in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   Harshbarger and his aides denied that the attorney general
played any role in Haydu's decision to quit Monday, though the two
men did talk after he announced his decision, the Harshbarger camp
acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   McGovern came to the State House and challenged Cellucci to take
the test himself. She also renewed her call for the abolition of
the Board of Education. She said she will, if elected, replace with
a board of broader ideological diversity - a panel that can rise
above what she said is its current practice of squabbling over
minor issues.
</P>
<P>
   But mostly she blasted Cellucci for failing to make a policy and
stick with it.
</P>
<P>
   State Treasurer Joseph D. Malone, Cellucci's rival for the
Republican nomination, said he supports testing, but not Cellucci's
approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is clear to everyone that Paul Cellucci's lack of
leadership has caused a crisis in our pubic education system
today,'' Malone said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
