<SLUG> BC-ANDERSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COULDN'T GURUS HAVE PREVENTED COMPUTER CRISIS?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MONICA ANDERSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 2000, something really, really awful is going to happen.
</P>
<P>
   This is a dire forecast that neither Nostradamus nor the psychic
hot line ever anticipated. There's been a lot of talk about the
2000 compliance catastrophe for several months, but I wasn't sure
what all the whoop-de-do was about. Since everyone else seemed to
be in on the big secret, I inched my way over to Deke's house one
starless night for a little enlightenment.
</P>
<P>
   My neighbor Deke sits in a small room at the back of his garage
listening to a CB radio all day. I figured if anybody knew what the
heck was going on, it would be Deke, or Donkey Breath, the name he
uses on his CB.
</P>
<P>
   ``Deke,'' I said during a lull in trucker traffic, ``what's all
this talk about year 2000 compliance? I'm totally in the dark.''
</P>
<P>
   Deke took off his headphones and spun around on his milk crate.
He spit out a stream of tobacco that killed two mosquitoes
innocently flying by. He peered at me through his eyeglasses with
no lenses and said, ``Well, Moe, as far as I know, Congress has
passed a bill that says in the year 2000 all you liberated women
have to stop nagging 24 hours a day and keep the fridge full of
cold brews and beef jerky.''
</P>
<P>
   I was at a loss for words. Finally, I said, ``Deke, when
lightning struck that big antennae on your roof last month, were
you on the CB?''
</P>
<P>
   Deke just laughed like a hyena and howled at the moon.
</P>
<P>
   Well, after doing a bit of research on the Internet, I finally
figured out what the fuss is all about. Most computer programs
cannot tell the difference between the years 1900 and 2000. Most
computers use a six-digit date field and to a computer 01-01-00
could mean Jan. 1, 2000, or Jan. 1, 1900. The problem will be worst
for financial systems where date calculations are vitally
important.
</P>
<P>
   Now, I understand that computers are rapidly evolving electronic
marvels. In 1953, there were only about 100 in the entire world! In
the 1960s and 1970s, huge million-dollar computers were commonly
used in business. In the 1980s, we witnessed an explosion of
personal computer use when Macintoshes arrived in almost every
school and became the computer of choice for home use. Now,
computers are almost as commonplace as stereos.
</P>
<P>
   That brief and boring history was necessary before I posed this
simple question. Why didn't someone anticipate this problem? We're
talking 15 or 20 years of personal computer popularity and it never
occurred to anyone that this would happen? Either we've got some
very pessimistic engineers who didn't think we could avoid a
nuclear war until the turn of the century or some folks with a lot
of foresight have stock in the expensive software we'll have to buy
to upgrade our computer systems to make them 2000 ready.
</P>
<P>
   I tell you, if it ain't one thing, it's two. Maybe we should
just trade in our computers for CBs. Deke says they're as good as
the Internet. Of course, Deke thinks pigs should be on a leash, so
I'd take that suggestion with a grain of salt if I were you.
</P>
<P>
   (Monica Frazier Anderson is a wife, mother and dentist in
Arlington, Texas. Call her at (817) 548-5564, or write in care of
the Arlington Star-Telegram at 1111 W. Abram St., TX Arlington
76013. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-98 1923EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
