<DOCNO> NYT19980630.0276 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 19:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4541 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-EDUCATION-HAYDU-BO     06-30 0848
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-EDUCATION-HAYDU-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUTGOING EDUCATION CHIEF CITES `DIFFICULT ENVIRONMENT' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JORDANA HART  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The outgoing interim education commissioner said
Tuesday the state Board of Education is fractious, highly
politicized, and sliding dangerously toward top-down education
reform with little input from the most important stakeholders _
teachers and principals.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Tuesday in his office, in suburban Malden,
Interim Education Commissioner Frank Haydu III, who quit Monday
after only four months on the job, called board Chairman John
Silber ``autocratic'' and said that having two Boston University
leaders on the board creates ``a difficult environment at best.''
</P>
<P>
   Silber is chancellor of Boston University and board member Edwin
Delattre is dean of the university's School of Education. Delattre
also oversees the team that manages the university's school
partnership with Chelsea. Others on the nine-member board include
academicians, as well as a union leader, high school student, and
conflict resolution expert.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were staffing this board, I would take John Silber and
four of the best teachers in the Commonwealth and four of the best
principals and say, `You are the state Board of Education,' as
opposed to having a group of academics,'' Haydu said. ``You would
get a very interesting outcome.''
</P>
<P>
   Silber Tuesday said that it would be a conflict of interest to
have teachers and principals as board members, given that they
would be setting standards for themselves. He also said Haydu was
naive if he ever believed that becoming interim education chief in
an election year would somehow be a job free of politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't want to have anything to do with politics, I
don't understand how you would look at a job like this,'' Silber
said. ``It has a political dimension and will be held up to
political scrutiny. We have had to make very important decisions in
an election year. We are bound to be sitting ducks.''
</P>
<P>
   Haydu said he resigned over what he considered Governor Paul
Cellucci's overtly political interference with the teacher test
standards. Cellucci had called on the board to reconsider its vote
on how strictly to score the state's first teacher certification
test; he also urged the state to test all teachers.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the board is meeting Wednesday to vote on whether
to raise the passing score on the certification test to one
originally set by a panel of educators.
</P>
<P>
   Last Monday, the board had voted to follow Haydu's
recommendation that the score be lowered for those taking the test
in April because they had not received adequate notice that the
test, described by Haydu as one of the nation's hardest, actually
counted. Those taking the test in July 11 would also have had the
lower score, but Haydu had agreed to return to the panel's standard
by the October test.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Haydu predicted the board would vote in favor of
Cellucci's demand for the higher test score. The higher score means
that 260 candidates who passed under the lower standard will fail.
Overall, 59 percent of the 1,800 would-be teachers who took the
test failed under the higher standard, while 44 percent failed
under the lower one.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, even Haydu's most ardent supporters Tuesday expressed
surprise and even anger at his decision to leave, despite a
hard-won promise that he stay on until after the November election.
Haydu, a businessman from Dover, is widely seen as a
consensus-builder and calming presence at often heated board
meetings. He has been working for free, donating his $140,000
salary to various schools and programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remain puzzled and distressed by Mr. Haydu's action,'' said
board member Roberta Schaefer in a statement Tuesday. ``He is
certainly experienced enough in public affairs to know how
unrealistic it is that an issue so controversial as education
reform can be addressed without reference to political debates.''
</P>
<P>
   Delattre, meanwhile, said that Haydu should leave the post
immediately. ``He has declared the board dysfunctional and in
principle is opposed to everything that is going on,'' Delattre
said.
</P>
<P>
   Haydu, a board member from 1992 to 1996, has said he would stay
on until September, but would leave earlier if the board asked him
to.
</P>
<P>
   Several observers and board members have privately said that
David Driscoll, a longtime deputy commissioner, should become the
interim chief until a permanent one is selected.
</P>
<P>
   The consensus among most educators is that few potential
candidates for the commissioner's post, particularly people from
out of state, would consider taking the job until it becomes clear
who will run the Commonwealth and how the education board will
fare.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frank brought much needed rationality and an attitude of calm
deliberation to the Board,'' said Representative Harold Lane Jr.
(D-Holden), cochair of the Legislature's education committee. ``My
concern is that he has not just quit on John Silber and the board,
but on kids.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
