<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 19:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4543 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SYMPHONIE-FANTASTIQUE     06-30 1020
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SYMPHONIE-FANTASTIQUE-ART-$ADV05-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEEING MUSIC AND THE WAY IT MOVES  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 5) 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo showing Basil Twist's puppets are underwater in a
500 gallon aquarium in the play ``Symphonie Fantastique'' will be
sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(af) 
 By BERNARD HOLLAND   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ We see music better than we write about it. This is
no surprise. The eye and ear are first cousins, sensory organs on
an equal footing. Writing is something the intellect thought up
later, a concocted set of symbols to put perceivers and perceived
in contact.
</P>
<P>
   Take, for example, Basil Twist's underwater puppetry, currently
at work in the Here theater complex in SoHo. The sights with which
it accompanies the ``Symphonie Fantastique'' tell us more about
Berlioz's sounds than The New Grove Dictionary of Music and
Musicians ever could.
</P>
<P>
   Words fail. Some music lends itself to geometric dissection, and
tacking stories onto music is a device that comes and goes, but
intervals and rhythm have proved pretty much bulletproof when it
comes to descriptive language.
</P>
<P>
   Twist's exercise, called simply ``Symphonie Fantastique,''
manipulates objects and light within a 500-gallon tank of water,
one side of which, 30 by 40 inches, is visible to an audience of
about 100. ``Symphonie,'' performed to an old Philadelphia
Orchestra recording led by Eugene Ormandy, has its halting moments
and flashes of extraordinary beauty. It plays until July 26, and I
suggest that you see it.
</P>
<P>
   Water fascinated Romantic composers and their offspring. Debussy
described its reflected light and orchestrated a day in the life of
the sea. Liszt and Ravel wrote about fountains; Respighi, too.
</P>
<P>
   Ives followed the course of a river through Stockbridge, Mass.
Smetana had his Moldau to celebrate. Handel wrote the ``Water
Music,'' but his piece seems more about being on the water than in
it. So, too, Schubert's ``Auf dem Wasser zu Singen.'' More examples
exist, and I know that I shall hear about them.
</P>
<P>
   Water is legato, and so is the overriding spirit of Romantic
music. Water lets us hear with our eyes the extended melodic
phrase: continous, undulating, devoid of sharp corners and
rectangular shapes.
</P>
<P>
   Twist's scarves and strands of tinsel swim like fish and come
very close to singing like songs: diving, twisting, darting. The
movements, even to the erupting bubbles, are synchronized to
Berlioz's music. A lot of us like to emphasize the uniqueness of
music as an expressive art, but here the parallels between hearing
and seeing won't go away.
</P>
<P>
   Berlioz's detailed story for this piece is not told. What we see
is how music moves. Some kinds of music, sonata form in particular,
move horizontally through time; we follow them as would our eyes
the path of a car. Contrapuntal music seems to expand in all
directions; advanced telescopes tell us that similar things are
happening in the universe. Twist illustrates both arts in three
dimensions.
</P>
<P>
   Twist is not a classical musician, but he doesn't have to be.
The other metaphors are too natural to miss. Low and resonant music
is dark; high ranges and prickly textures are bright. Shrillness
and stabs of intense light are two different weapons inflicting
similar wounds.
</P>
<P>
   Darkness worries us. Light is optimistic; indeed, photosynthesis
identifies it as a source of life. Associating minor keys with
sadness doesn't always work, however. Haydn can make minorness
sound funny; Dvorak, comforting. The German word for minor,
``moll,'' means soft, referring perhaps to the smoother, rounder
harmonic resolutions of the undoctored minor scale.
</P>
<P>
   Assigning colors to sound is no science, but a number of
musicians have been impelled to do it. For some, the associations
are as instinctive as the gift of absolute pitch. But if Scriabin
and Messiaen had their private and surprisingly precise palettes of
red, blue, yellow, no one seems to have arrived at a universal
vision of, for example, F major. (Scriabin heard/saw it as red.) D
major, on the other hand, tantalizes. For Scriabin it was a bright
yellow light; Haydn's eight-measure sunrise in ``The Creation'' is
in D major, too.
</P>
<P>
   The recorded sound for ``Symphonie Fantastique'' was not
exceptional, but it didn't matter too much. More important, Twist's
presentation made the ears stay wide awake, when it could just as
well have distracted their attention.
</P>
<P>
   Spending an hour in the dark looking at this strange little
proscenium also rearranged one's sense of scale. The most startling
moment of a relatively brief evening came after it was over, when
the four backstage operatives came out to take their bows. They
looked huge, like giants.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on your point of view, ``Symphonie Fantastique'' is an
intriguing failure or a flawed success. The performance I went to
left lots of visual wrong notes and bad sonorities for all to see.
Some of the screens dropped awkwardly. Horizontal beams of light
and dancing vertical columns did not have the portent and sense of
the ominous that I think were intended. But some of the flashes of
movement and contrasting sheets of light took the breath away.
</P>
<P>
   This is a collateral art of music that needs more stage
technique and more inspiration to fill in the sagging moments.
Animated cartoons and Disney movies have the means but rarely the
vision.
</P>
<P>
   An important exception may be an old Bugs Bunny episode called
``Rhapsody Rabbit,'' an exercise in musical sophistication and
visual imagination that tells the truth by stretching it. Rarely
has hyperbole been used with such exactitude.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, I doubt that a piano teacher charging $75 to $100 an
hour could teach a student as much as these few minutes do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Symphonie Fantastique'' is more vital than most animation,
because it gives us real people in real time, a live performance
featuring a cast of abstractions. I don't know if Twist and his
crew improvise from time to time, but I hope they do. At any rate,
they are onto something.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
