<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OZZY-POPLIFE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE POP LIFE: OZZY OSBOURNE, SETTLED SURVIVOR
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo of Ozzy Osbourne is being sent to NYT photo
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(nk) 
 By NEIL STRAUSS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ He has battled addictions to drugs, alcohol and
cigars. He has been kicked out of bands, barred from the offices of
his own record company and forced to submit to rabies shots. He has
been charged with inciting teen-agers to suicide, with the
attempted murder of his wife and with urinating on the Alamo. Yet
somehow through these events both tragic and ridiculous, the heavy
metal magnate Ozzy Osbourne has survived.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1970, when he began the loud, violent reaction against
hippie peace and love with Black Sabbath, perhaps the archetypal
heavy metal band, his career has been pronounced finished time and
time again. And time and time again he has rebounded.
</P>
<P>
   Now against all expectations, Osbourne has become one of the
biggest money makers on the road. Last year, in the face of scanty
media exposure, his Ozzfest package tour made over $10 million,
becoming one of the most successful festival tours of the summer,
second only to the all-female Lilith Fair.
</P>
<P>
   The third annual Ozzfest, which begins with performances on
Friday and Sunday at the PNC Bank Arts Center in Holmdel, N.J., is
likely to have another good year. In addition to Osbourne, the tour
features Tool, Megadeth, Motorhead, Limp Bizkit, Coal Chamber, the
Melvins, Soulfly and other hard-rock acts as well as a carnival
sideshow called ``Never Never Land.''
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend, Osbourne called from a tour stop in Zurich to
discuss his Ozzfest and other pressing matters. Every question
asked produced a litany of angry responses, quasi-denials and
rants. Here's what Osbourne had to say:
</P>
<P>
   OZZFEST '97
</P>
<P>
   ``What I was doing last year was I was smoking loads of cigars
and it was messing my chest up and my voice was getting bad. Plus
I've suddenly developed allergies and asthma. But this year I've
been working on it. For me the audience can lift me up out of
anything: they're better than Prozac or a shot of whisky.''
</P>
<P>
   SHARON OSBOURNE, WIFE AND MANAGER
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife is my biggest fan and my biggest adviser and the one I
love. Half of Ozzy is Sharon. I don't come up with these fantastic
ideas and get all the logistics together. I have the easy job: I
just go up there and entertain and do interviews and walk around
hotel rooms all day long. She's a workaholic. She hasn't got a
figure like Pamela Anderson, but I don't care because she's my wife
and I love her more than anything in the world and we've got three
great kids.''
</P>
<P>
   UNSUCCESSFUL LAWSUITS ON THREE TEEN-AGE SUICIDES
</P>
<P>
   ``I was watching this lawyer that was suing me being interviewed
on VH1. He said that he could honestly hear me say on the record,
`Get the gun, shoot, shoot.' I can put my hand on my heart and
swear on my children's lives that those words were never said.
`Suicide Solution' was about me drinking myself to death just after
a friend of mine, the original signer from AC/DC, died from
alcohol.''
</P>
<P>
   SENATE HEARINGS ON OBSCENE LYRICS
</P>
<P>
   ``In my opinion, by having these hearings in the Senate you're
going to get some garage band that thinks it'll get successful and
noticed in the Senate if it writes a song called `Kill Your Mother
Twice.'''
</P>
<P>
   `OZZMOSIS'
</P>
<P>
   ``I recorded that album twice. It became a job. You can't make
records like that. All the songs I liked, the record company
didn't. I've still got a load of stuff that will probably never see
the light of day, unless I get struck by lightning.''
</P>
<P>
   HIS NEXT SOLO ALBUM
</P>
<P>
   ``I keep saying to my wife, `When am I going to make a record?'
It's a painful process for everyone because I am my own worst
critic. When I make a record, I very rarely play it again because
I'll find a fault in it 10 years later and think, `Why did I put
that there?'''
</P>
<P>
   REUNITING WITH BLACK SABBATH
</P>
<P>
   ``Last week the four of us recorded two live shows which were
spectacular and wrote two new studio tracks, `Psycho Man' and
`Selling Your Soul,' and they came together relatively quickly. I'd
like to do another studio album with them, but I'd like to continue
my own solo career first.''
</P>
<P>
   AUTOBIOGRAPHY AND FILM DEALS
</P>
<P>
   ``What I have to do is go around to a lot of old friends and ask
them to jog my memory. If I have one regret it's not keeping a
daily journal because I've been messed up all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   FANS
</P>
<P>
   ``The last thing I say at my concerts most nights is, `Make sure
you go out and get home safely, because I want to see you next year
and rock you again.' If my intention was to do songs that anyone
would harm themselves with, why would I say that?''
</P>
<P>
   Yanni, Business Guru
</P>
<P>
   Concert promoters and booking agents complained this spring that
the New Age composer Yanni was cutting them out of the business.
They griped that he was not honoring business protocol and working
with the concert companies that helped him (sometimes at a
financial loss) earlier in his career. Now that Yanni is a
superstar, they continued, he is bypassing them, arranging concerts
through his management and keeping more money for himself.
</P>
<P>
   Yanni's manager, Danny O'Donovan, said this was the most
efficient way to run a major tour in his client's best interest.
</P>
<P>
   Now concert promoters and booking agents might have even more
reason to complain. According to midyear statistics released by the
concert industry journal Performance, Yanni has made more money
touring in North America than any other act this year. This
curly-haired Greek soothsayer has taken in $40 million since
January, followed by the George Strait Country Music Festival with
$33 million and Eric Clapton with $28 million. The only 90s band to
appear in Performance's midyear Top 10 of top-grossing tours is the
Dave Matthews Band, which has taken in $9 million on its tour so
far, all of which provides more evidence that the album-buying
audience and concert-going crowd are two very different beasts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
