<SLUG> BC-MA-LOTTERY-SQUABBLE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TESTIMONY REFUTES WOMAN'S CLAIM TO $21 MILLION LOTTERY TICKET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILLIAM F. DOHERTY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; BOSTON _ The dispute between convenience-store owner Nick
Havan and Watertown widow Paraskeve Kantges over a winning $21
million lottery ticket shifted again Tuesday when one of Havan's
steady customers said Kantges told him she hadn't won the jackpot.
</P>
<P>
   Testifying before a state Lottery Commission hearing, salesman
James P. McGoldrick Jr., said he approached Kantges in Havan's
store the morning after the Feb. 5 drawing and asked if her ticket
had paid off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said `Are you our newest local millionaire?''' McGoldrick,
44, told the commission. ``She said, `No, I am not.''
</P>
<P>
   When cross-examined by James Merberg, Kantges' lawyer,
McGoldrick insisted he wasn't joking. ``I humored my question, but
my interrogatory was sincere,'' McGoldrick replied.
</P>
<P>
   Kantges claims she telephoned the winning Mass Millions bet to
Coolidge Provisons, but Havan, the store's owner, said he kept the
winning ticket for himself after Kantges called back later to
cancel the bet.
</P>
<P>
   Kantges, who has records to show she played the same number
every day for years, denies she canceled the bet.
</P>
<P>
   Former Massachusetts Lottery executive director Samuel M.
DePhillippo ruled in favor of Kangtes, but Havan appealed. &UR;  &LR; Retired
Superior Court Judge Robert Steadman is hearing evidence and will
make a recommendation to the full lottery commission.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Joseph Malone, commission chairman has disqualified himself
because he has said he believes Kantges. The dispute is likely to
end up in the courts, however.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  On Monday, a third person, Sonia Bardakjian of Watertown also
claims the jackpot. Like Kantges, Bardakjian said she phoned in a
bet on the winning number. The lottery rejected her claim.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Prior to Bardakian's appearance, Havan testified that he did
not come forward and publicly claim the jackpot for several days
because he feared Kantges would cause dispute his claim. But
Kantges has claimed the winner was among about 90 lottery bets she
made that day _ and the only one Havan did not turn over to her.
</P>
<P>
   In his testimony Tuesday, McGoldrick, a traveling salesman, said
he's a frequent lottery player like Kantges. He said he knows her
from seeing her playing the lottery at various locations in
Watertown.
</P>
<P>
   McGoldrick said he spent between 20 minutes and a half hour in
the store with Kantges that morning and ``she seemed calm _ not
like her usual self.'' Normally, he said, Kantges is
``confrontational, verbose, vociferous, argumentative and
hostile.''
</P>
<P>
   After she said she didn't hold the winning ticket, McGoldrick
said he suggested that ``it would be nice if someone local won. She
said, `Yes, it certainly would,'' McGoldrick testified.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Hrach ``Richie'' Abrahamian, Havan's employee in the variety
store, corroborated the conversation between Kantges and
McGoldrick.
</P>
<P>
   Abrahamian, who was partners with Havan before selling his share
of the store, said Kantges came into the store three times that
day. He said Kantges paid for the bets she had phoned in the night
before and even purchasing more lottery tickets, but never claimed
that she owned the winning ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Abrahamian said when he came to work that morning he immediately
recognized the winning Mass Millions number as the one Kantges
usually plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nick was nervous that Ms. Kantges would come to the store and
claim what she is claiming now,'' Abrahamian said. ``I suggested
that he call his lawyer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
