<SLUG> BC-TEN-COLLINS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IVANISEVIC SQUEAKS INTO THE QUARTERFINALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ First of all, the big upset: no rain at Wimbledon. The
celebrated strawberries Tuesday weren't mildewed and the champagne
less watered down than usual.
</P>
<P>
   Upset No. 2: Goran Ivanisevic, the Croat Croaker, got out-aced
by his opponent, yet actually won the match. This was like somebody
pitching a 30-hit shutout. Doesn't happen. ``I'm not only aces,''
he says after losing the zinger race to Todd Martin, 23-15,
nevertheless striding into the quarterfinals, 7-6 (7-5), 6-2, 3-6,
7-6 (7-2). ``I do other stuff. Double faults.'' He did beat Martin
there, 17-14.
</P>
<P>
   Upset No. 3: Martina Hingis overslept past her starting time but
didn't get bounced. ``I had to get up at 8:30 to practice, then
play at 11,'' she yawns. ``Pretty early. I never played that early
here.'' It had to be because downpours intruding on five of the
first eight days stacked up the schedule. ``I slept through the
first set'' _ it looked that way _ ``but woke up for the second.''
That completed a drowsy 6-3, 6-2 win over Tamarine Tanasugarn for
the champ portraying Sleeping Beauty. ``OK,'' Martina opens her
eyes, ``I realize most people in the world have to be at work by
8:30, but I'm glad the final starts at 2.'' She intends to be
there.
</P>
<P>
   Upset No. 4: The sister-brother act of Helena Sukova and Cyril
Suk, mixed doubles champs in 1996-97, lost their crown in the first
round at dusk. Mixed doubles? Picaresque Sam Silverman, the bygone
Boston boxing impresario, always thought that meant a martini in a
very tall glass.
</P>
<P>
   Why would thousands hang around until dark to watch mixed?
Because a very tall young lady, 6-foot-2-inch Venus Williams, was
making her Centre Court debut. She and her even taller accomplice,
6-5 Justin Gimelstob, won, 6-3, 5-7, 6-4. As Australian and French
victors, the pair kept breathing their designs on a mixed Grand
Slam. Only one other team has done it, Aussies Margaret Court and
Ken Fletcher in 1963.
</P>
<P>
   Grand Slam? Silverman would have told you that's what Rocky
Marciano did to Jersey Joe Walcott to win the heavyweight title.
</P>
<P>
   Upset No. 5: Looking to be the heavyweight champion of tennis,
6-4, 210-pound Mark Philippoussis roared into today's quarters
against Pete Sampras by winning the battle of the Good Aussie vs.
the Bad Aussie over Jason Stoltenberg, 5-7, 6-1, 6-3, 6-3.
</P>
<P>
   Philippoussis, the party of the second part, has alienated the
Australian public by refusing to play Davis Cup (a huge matter Down
Under), playing the Lamborghini-driving playboy and declaring after
a first-round loss at Queen's Club three weeks ago that he had no
interest in entering Wimbledon, a shrine in the minds of his
countrymen.
</P>
<P>
   Party of the first part, Stoltenberg, the farm boy off a way-out
New South Wales cotton plantation in Wee Waa, is everything that
city boy Philippoussis from Melbourne isn't. Earnest and
hard-working, devoted father, ready to do or die in Davis Cup at
any time. How they must have groaned at home by the telly-watching
Stolts get beat by the balloon head.
</P>
<P>
   The upset belongs to Gavin Hopper, Philippoussis's
coach/trainer, who has suffered through numerous brain failures by
his pupil, but is slowly shaping him up physically and mentally.
``I've done some rash things,'' the lately improving 21-year-old
giant says. ``But Gavin has stuck with me, and I think I'm together
now. There are people at home who want me to do well. I've beaten
Sampras before (Aussie Open, 1996) and I can do it again.''
</P>
<P>
   Hopper also coaches Monica Seles. ``Two rather different
cases,'' he smiles, as though talking about Dagwood and Blondie.
``Two different outlooks. But she's been on top. She knows what she
wants and how to get there. She'll do the work. Mark takes a little
more attention. I'm just there to help both.'' A Hopper double
wouldn't be a bad bet _ Seles and Philippoussis.
</P>
<P>
   Upset No. 6: Davide Sanguinetti is in the quarterfinals. Here is
an Italian guy who played No. 6 for UCLA when he ran away from home
five years ago to sample the classrooms and fleshpots of Los
Angeles. Though he hasn't beaten anybody you've heard of, Davide
has shown a fine Italian volleying hand in crawling through holes
at the bottom of the draw, afforded when the seeds Marcelo Rios and
Karol Kucera (2d and 15th) vanished in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   He made it fun for the Italian journalists out on Court 18,
raising their voices in somewhat unseemly manner for Sanguinetti
while he beat Rios's conqueror, Francisco Clavet, 7-6 (7-3), 6-1,
6-4.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, no cheering in the pressbox!'' said a straightlaced
American reporter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, yourself,'' replied Ubaldo Scanagatta of Florence's
Nazione. ``We haven't had a quarterfinalist since Adriano Panatta
in 1979. I guess I can scream every 19 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Absolutely. That's about as frequently as rain ignores
Wimbledon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
