<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWINDELL-BOOKSHELF-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOLUME MAKES REDISCOVERING THOMAS MANN MUCH EASIER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LARRY SWINDELL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thomas Mann is a towering figure in world literature, but is
somewhat forbidding for readers who do not warm to a challenge.
</P>
<P>
   In the two major works by which most Americans know Mann _
``Buddenbrooks'' and ``The Magic Mountain'' _ he is a master of the
German ``Bildungsroman,'' the ``novel of education'' or of
``development.'' Such a work treats the social and intellectual
learning experience of an individual, often a youth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buddenbrooks,'' published at the century's turn when Mann was
25, offers a sprawling canvas of characters, but its substance
reflects Mann's own early life and experience and announces a
strongly individual style.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Magic Mountain,'' Mann's alter ego is Hans Castorp. At
a tuberculosis sanitorium in the Swiss Alps where Hans has gone to
visit a sickly friend, he develops his own malady and stays there
seven years _ mainly, however, because of his odd attraction to the
Haus Berghof whose international clientele represents a cross
section of European society in the years preceding World War I.
</P>
<P>
   Mann produced many other works formidable in both size and
scope. Surely his most ambitious project was the tetralogy
collectively titled ``Joseph and His Brothers,'' elaborating on the
narrative in the Book of Genesis. The valedictory novel ``Doctor
Faustus'' (1949) artfully second-guessed Adolf Hitler's regime.
</P>
<P>
   But in a writing marathon that spanned a half-century, Mann also
created miniature works that adhere to the theme of duality, or
dualism, the artist's struggle between reality and the aesthetic
dimensions of his imagination.
</P>
<P>
   More than a few critics have contended that Mann's most
significant achievement is in these less distended works, which are
addressed to Mann's characteristic themes but are more accessible
to the lay reader and less mortgaged to symbolism. Now the best of
these narratives are brought together in a single volume.
</P>
<P>
   ``Death in Venice and Other Tales,'' new in hardback from Viking
($25.95), collects eight stories and four larger compositions,
including the great novella alluded to in the title. (''Death in
Venice'' also was a splendidly tragic film, with Dirk Bogarde as
Aschenbach.)
</P>
<P>
   The other novellas are ``Little Herr Friedemann,'' Mann's first
published work (1898); ``Tristan,'' (1901), one of the author's
frequent excursions into mythology; and ``Tonio Kroger'' (1903),
clearly representing the author's own conflict between ``life'' and
``spirit.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Death in Venice,'' though, is the piece de resistance here. At
the time of its publication (1912), the author disclaimed any
personal connection to his protagonist _ Gustav von Aschenbach,
author of world renown _ who, while visiting in Venice, falls
desperately in love with a frail but incredibly beautiful
adolescent Polish boy named Tadzio.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aschenbach looked forward every day to Tadzio's arrival, and
sometimes he pretended to be busy at the moment and to ignore the
beauty strolling by. But at other times he did look up, and their
eyes met. Nothing in the elderly man's cultivated and dignified
expression so much as hinted at any emotion; but Tadzio's gaze was
filled with questioning, with reflective wondering ...''
</P>
<P>
   The proudly heterosexual Thomas Mann may have denied such a
fixation, but recent Mann biographers _ he has lately been one of
the most written-about classic authors _ have decoded the author's
literary legacy and have documented Mann's continuing devotion to a
young man whom he met in Venice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Death in Venice'' and all the other components in the Viking
volume are newly translated by Joachim Neugroschel (previously a
translator of Franz Kafka), who also provides the introduction.
Restored are controversial passages that were excised from the
first English translation with which American readers have been
familiar.
</P>
<P>
   I'd say Thomas Mann is here _ and there _ to stay.
</P>
<P>
   (Larry Swindell is books editor for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-98 1934EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
