<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-SILVA-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS THE COLA GENERATION READY FOR PRESCRIPTION POP? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 JILL WENDHOLT SILVA  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: If you've stepped inside a health-food store in the
past few years, you've no doubt seen ``tonics'' and ``elixirs''
popping up next to the natural sodas.
</P>
<P>
   The New Age soft drinks come in hues of orange, yellow, red and
green and fruity flavors such as raspberry//tangerine, peach//mango
and lemon//ginger. But most dispense with the fizz and pack more
than a simple caffeine punch.
</P>
<P>
   Sold under names such as Tribal Tonics and SoBe, they're part of
the emerging ``nutraceuticals'' trend _ foods and beverages that
include medicinal herbs like:
</P>
<P>
   - Ginseng _ A mild aphrodisiac believed to enhance memory,
learning, productivity, physical stamina and immune function.
</P>
<P>
   - Echinacea _ The purple coneflower is used for prevention and
treatment of colds and flu.
</P>
<P>
   - Guarana _ A berry that grows in the rain forest and contains
caffeine.
</P>
<P>
   - Ginkgo _ A healing herb associated with the treatment of
stroke, heart disease, impotence, blindness and memory loss.
</P>
<P>
   - St. John's wort _ Touted as ``nature's Prozac,'' it is used to
enhance mood and uplift spirits.
</P>
<P>
   Ancient cultures have relied on medicinal herbs for thousands of
years; they are thought to boost the immune system, relieve stress
or improve mental alertness.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Food and Drug Administration prohibits herbal
beverage makers from making health claims, the labels do sound
healthier than the typical high-fructose lingo found on a
mainstream can of cola.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, a label on Tribal Tonics' Peach//Mango Energy
Elixir with ginseng and guarana says the herbs ``enhance energy,
stamina and endurance.'' But it also adds the following disclaimer:
``This product is not intended to treat, cure or prevent any
disease.''
</P>
<P>
   A 1997 Gallup poll found herb use among American adults had
increased by 70 percent since 1996. Now herbs are going mainstream
in the supermarket beverage aisle and convenience stores.
</P>
<P>
   But the fact that medicinal herbs are showing up in cutting-edge
herbal tonics and are working their way into snack foods _ such as
Robert's American Gourmet, a line of St. John's wort tortilla chips
and vegan chips with ginseng, bee pollen and honey _ has at least
one local herbalist alarmed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not something to fool with, and making snack foods and
putting herbs in it is ridiculous,'' says Bonnie Woods, who
recently taught a six-part course at Johnson County Community
College on the use of medicinal herbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's giving people a mixed message, even if it is a
teensy-weensy bit of echinacia, which is not so bad. Still, you
give people the idea that you can't overdose on herbs ... and you
can.''
</P>
<P>
   For anyone interested in herbal medicine, Woods advises a
healthy dose of common sense. Always thoroughly research herbal
remedies before trying them. And it doesn't hurt to remember that
herbal manufacturers are trying to sell a product, so she never
takes more than half the manufacturers' recommended dose until she
sees how her own body reacts to the drug.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
