<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 19:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4553 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HONGKONG-ANNIVERSARY-     06-30 0730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HONGKONG-ANNIVERSARY-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HONG KONG PLANS MUTED CELEBRATION OF ITS REVERSION TO CHINA 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: CHINA-CLINTON, CHINA-NOTEBOOK, CHINA-TAIWAN,
CHINA-PEONY, ASIA-RUBIN) 
(ps) 
 By MARK LANDLER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ His hometown is marking the first anniversary of its
return to China on Wednesday, but after spending the year without a
job, Loon Wai-ting is in no mood to celebrate. On a recent
sauna-like afternoon, in the teeming neighborhood of Mong Kok, he
stood before a government labor office, fruitlessly searching a
bulletin board for job listings.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the British were here, there was a lot of business in
Hong Kong,'' said Loon, a 51-year-old merchant seaman, whose deeply
lined face bespeaks both a life at sea and a worrisome year as the
unemployed father of four. ``When the British left, the business
left with them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Britain's exit from Hong Kong has had little to do
with the economic downturn of its former colony, which sits at the
crossroads of a becalmed Asia and has suffered along with its
neighbors. But Loon speaks for many Hong Kong people, who have been
ravaged by rising unemployment, a 20 percent drop in the stock
market, and a 40 percent decline in the property market in the last
six months.
</P>
<P>
   For this embattled outpost of commerce, celebrating the passage
of a year under Chinese rule seems almost beside the point.
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong is staging a flurry of events, including a
flag-raising, a cultural pageant, and back-to-back visits on
Wednesday and Thursday by the Chinese president, Jiang Zemin, and
President Clinton. But the government has scrapped the gaudier
elements of last year's celebration, like the laser show and
fireworks display, because they seem ill-suited to these hard
times.
</P>
<P>
   The subdued tone of Hong Kong's anniversary is all the more
notable because until six months ago, the government here would
have had much to crow about. Politically, Hong Kong has scarcely
changed in the year since this capitalist bastion became part of a
communist empire. Defying the predictions of experts here and in
the West, Beijing has left Hong Kong largely untouched.
</P>
<P>
   Since last July 1, Hong Kong voters have turned out in record
numbers to elect a new legislature, enjoyed a lively news media,
and marked the ninth anniversary of the Tiananmen Square massacre
with a huge, candlelight vigil _ one of more than 1,400 protests
against everything from human rights abuses in China to the
plummeting value of apartments in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   However, there are rumors that Chinese officials are seeking to
influence Hong Kong's leaders through hints delivered in
back-channel conversations. And the government recently raised
fears about the integrity of Hong Kong's legal system by amending
laws in ways that seem to favor Beijing. But fears about wholesale
meddling or the muzzling of the media have so far proven
unwarranted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hong Kong is a graveyard for political prognosticators,'' said
Daniel R. Fung, the solicitor-general of Hong Kong and a defender
of the government. ``Everybody predicted we'd have a bumpy ride
politically, but the economy would take care of itself. Exactly the
opposite has happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Fung said Beijing delivered on its promise of ``one country, two
systems,'' a political arrangement that guarantees Hong Kong a high
degree of autonomy as a special administrative region of China.
That agreement was secured after years of often-rancorous
negotiations between Britain and China.
</P>
<P>
   But while the British colonial government was laying the
groundwork for Hong Kong's political future, it was also presiding
over a spectacular inflation of the colony's property market _
creating an Asian Xanadu with more billionaires and Rolls Royces
per square mile than any other city in the world.
</P>
<P>
   When the financial crisis tore through Asia last fall, it
devastated Hong Kong's exports and humbled its stock market. While
Hong Kong fought off the symptoms of the malady longer than its
neighbors, it finally succumbed _ slipping into a recession for the
first time in 13 years.
</P>
<P>
   If economic collapse was not enough, Hong Kong has also been hit
by several calamities, including a deadly outbreak of bird flu last
December, a string of cholera cases, and a creeping red algae tide
in its coastal waters.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   The flood of bad news has left people traumatized. And it has
prompted them to question Hong Kong's government and its chief
executive, Tung Chee-hwa, the conservative shipping magnate who was
chosen by Beijing to lead the territory. Such dissent is
uncharacteristic for Hong Kong, where the British colonial governor
historically ruled in close cooperation with the business elite.
</P>
<P>
   ``Economic prosperity was the major connecting thread between
the old Hong Kong and new Hong Kong,'' said Michael DeGolyer, a
professor of government at Baptist University who studied public
attitudes toward the transfer to China. ``Now Hong Kong people are
getting very irritated.''
</P>
<P>
   Anger may have been one reason people voted in record numbers in
Hong Kong's legislative elections last month. In a gesture of
defiance to the local government and Beijing, the voters elected
pro-democracy candidates to a majority of the popularly elected
seats. Many of those politicians had been sent into political exile
when Beijing dissolved Hong Kong's last democratically elected
legislature before the transfer and replaced it with a hand-picked
body.
</P>
<P>
   Pro-democracy politicians say that Hong Kong's people are even
more committed to a pluralistic political system than they were
before the transfer, when the city's political independence under
China seemed tenuous. Being a part of China, they say, has made
democracy seem more precious.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of the 1.2 billion people in China, we _ the 6.6 million
people of Hong Kong _ are the only people who have the vote,'' said
Martin Lee, the head of the Democratic Party who regained his
legislative seat.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Lee admitted that concerns about civil rights and
individual freedoms are being overshadowed by economic issues.
Indeed, the Democratic Party teamed up with pro-business and
pro-Beijing parties to mount a coordinated assault on the policies
of Tung. The group is calling on the government to use its massive
financial reserves to lessen the burden on people by cutting taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Bowing to pressure, the government last week announced a package
of measures, including a one-time tax rebate, to stimulate the
economy.
</P>
<P>
   For all the noise generated by the newly elected legislators,
Hong Kong is still firmly controlled by Tung. Though Lee and his
colleagues won more than half of the popular vote, they will hold
fewer than one-third of the seats in the legislature. And the
legislature does not have the power to introduce bills on major
issues without the acquiescence of the chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Lee is demanding that the government accelerate the timetable
calling for voters to elect all legislators directly in 2007. But
given that the chief executive and the National People's Congress
in China would have to approve such an amendment to Hong Kong's
constitution, Lee's crusade seems quixotic.
</P>
<P>
   A more pressing concern for some pro-democracy politicians is
the rule of law in Hong Kong. Although the territory has retained
British common law as the foundation of its legal code, some
critics say the government is making subtle changes that may
whittle away the rights of Hong Kong citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Most notably, the government last April granted the Chinese
government the same immunity from local laws that the British Crown
had enjoyed in colonial days. The trouble is, Hong Kong's
authorities defined the Chinese government broadly enough to
include Xinhua, the New China News Agency, which has historically
functioned as Beijing's eyes and ears in the territory.
</P>
<P>
   Xinhua still inspires fear among pro-democracy leaders here, and
the prospect that it will enjoy immunity from local laws is doubly
frightening to them. ``The last year has been little short of
hair-raising,'' said Margaret Ng, a lawyer and pro-democracy
politician who was also recently elected to the legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their qualms, even pro-democracy politicians credit
Beijing with masterful public relations. After marching into Hong
Kong at midnight on June 30, the People's Liberation Army troops
retreated into their barracks and have been confined there since. A
single forlorn soldier stands guard outside the garrison in central
Hong Kong, which is still called the Prince of Wales building.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   China's conduct has given Hong Kong's pro-Beijing politicians a
keen sense of vindication. Tsang Yok-sing, a former high-school
principal and avowed Marxist who heads the main pro-Beijing party,
said Jiang had been scrupulous in maintaining the principle of
``one country, two systems,'' even discouraging pro-Beijing people
in Hong Kong from airing criticisms of the territory while in the
mainland.
</P>
<P>
   For people here who are intent on reaffirming their Chinese
identity, however, China's low profile poses some ticklish
problems. Hong Kong's top civil servant, Anson Chan, said in a
recent speech in Washington that she had felt an ``emotional and
spiritual connection'' in seeing the Chinese flag hoisted over Hong
Kong to celebrate the national day of the People's Republic on Oct.
1.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Chan's speech was greeted with ambivalence at home,
where symbols of official China are rare and Ms. Chan herself lives
in a stately home on the Peak, known as Victoria House. Lee, whose
family fled to Hong Kong from neighboring Guangdong Province, said:
``How can I feel warm when I see the flag go up when so many of my
people are deprived of basic human rights?''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Even staunchly pro-Beijing people are not ready to predict that
Hong Kong will never again clash with China. Though few believe
that the Chinese government will clamp down on Hong Kong over
political issues, a growing number of politicians and business
executives worry that Hong Kong's languishing economy might provoke
China to take a more intrusive approach.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In Beijing on Saturday, Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin, said
that senior Chinese officials had expressed fears to him about the
state of the Hong Kong economy during a discussion of the region.
Rubin was in China as part of President Clinton's state visit.
</P>
<P>
   Beijing's financial stake in Hong Kong is vast and growing. Hong
Kong's stock exchange is the primary means for Chinese companies to
raise capital. With Prime Minister Zhu Ronji pushing to privatize
state-owned enterprises, Hong Kong will become an even more vital
window between China and the global market.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The social contract between Beijing and Hong Kong is predicated
on a simple idea: as long as Hong Kong makes money, Beijing will
leave it alone. If Hong Kong stops making money, people here say,
all bets are off.
</P>
<P>
   ``If China has to bail out Hong Kong, why should they give these
6 million decadent people special privileges?'' said Vincent Lo, a
leading property developer who has extensive business ties in the
mainland.
</P>
<P>
   Or, as the noted Hong Kong author and publisher Louis Cha, puts
it: ``Suppose Hong Kong Bank lends me $1 million and I run my
business well. They will leave me alone. But if I run my business
poorly and can't repay my loans, it's very possible they will send
somebody to look at my books.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
