<HEADLINE>
CAN'T STAND THE SUMMER HEAT? GET OUT OF THE KITCHEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JILL WENDHOLT SILVA  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: Can't stand the summer heat? Get out of the kitchen.
Just be ready for steamy encounters of the food kind.
Kitchenware from a garage
</P>
<P>
   In 90-plus-degree heat on a recent Saturday afternoon my
4-year-old son and I ventured out to inspect just what our
neighbors were trying to clear out of their attics, basements,
garages _ and kitchens.
</P>
<P>
   Our brief but rather steamy outing served as a reminder of just
how inexpensive it can be to outfit a kitchen with bargains gleaned
at neighborhood garage sales.
</P>
<P>
   Consider my Cuisinart food processor. My grandmother found it at
a yard sale a few years back. It was still in its unopened box and
a quarter of the department store price.
</P>
<P>
   My mother, an inveterate garage-saler, also has found an
impressive array of items for my kitchen in recent years:
</P>
<P>
   - French press ($1).
</P>
<P>
   - Clay Romertopff pot ($2) and garlic roaster (50 cents).
</P>
<P>
   - One dozen 10-ounce Crown Corning dessert dishes (still in the
box, $4).
</P>
<P>
   - An unused sake set with ``Made in China'' stickers affixed
($3).
</P>
<P>
   - Glass tumblers to match the set I bought at Home Place a year
ago (10 cents each).
</P>
<P>
   - A clear glass tea kettle identical (except for the packaging)
to my beloved Museum of Modern Art-designed tea kettle that I
bought two years ago at a San Francisco dim-sum restaurant ($5).
</P>
<P>
   For herself, she has nabbed a Tupperware steamer (50 cents),
Corningware pots (50 cents to $1.50) and pressure cookers ($1).
</P>
<P>
   And don't forget the cookbooks.
</P>
<P>
   A 1996 copy of The Children's Step-by-Step Cookbook by Angela
Wilkes was in pristine condition, the spine never cracked, for $1.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing that I sometimes need props for photo shoots, Mom also
has begun collecting such oddities as mismatched pieces of china.
One of her more unusual finds: a cornucopia of papier mache fruits
and vegetables. But I'm hanging on to them. I figure someday
they'll make a great Carmen Miranda costume.
Rhizome riddle
</P>
<P>
   Ready for a rhizome riddle?
</P>
<P>
   What knobby root has a peppery, slightly sweet aroma and is
essential to the cuisines of Asia and India?
</P>
<P>
   Hint: Americans adore using this spice to make
``(fill-in-the-blank)bread'' people at Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   I was checking out at the local supermarket recently when the
young checker held the brownish root up, wrinkled her forehead and
was at an utter loss as to how to key it into the register.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is this? Rawhide?''
</P>
<P>
   As in dog bone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's ginger,'' I replied.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, it looks like rawhide,'' she shot back.
 &LR; brk:Rice-Krispies Rage
</P>
<P>
   We've all heard of road rage. But here's a twist.
</P>
<P>
   As I turned onto Metcalf Avenue the other morning, I stopped at
a light, and I was transfixed by the vision in my rearview mirror.
The guy behind me was eating cereal _ with milk!
</P>
<P>
   Incredibly, in a bowl!
</P>
<P>
   With a spoon!
</P>
<P>
   The light changed and he proceeded to drive down the road,
sucking down his cereal. I couldn't help but continue to stare in
my sideview mirror.
</P>
<P>
   Was he driving with his knees? An automatic, no doubt.
</P>
<P>
   Then he had the nerve to pass me.
</P>
<P>
   Call it Rice-Krispies Rage!
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-98 1938EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
