<DOCNO> NYT19980630.0287 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 19:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4557 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRAN-TRIAL-NYT &LR;      06-30 1235
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAN-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CASE OF THE TEHRAN MAYOR: REFORM ON TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By ELAINE SCIOLINO    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEHRAN, Iran _ In a high-ceilinged courtroom under the heat and
glare of television lights, the mayor of Tehran is on trial,
struggling to keep his job and clear his name.
</P>
<P>
   But his trial, which at times resembles a shouting match, is
more than an attempt to uncover and punish financial corruption. It
is the most prominent part of a campaign by clerical conservatives
to thwart the reformist administration of President Mohammad
Khatami, which they fear will dilute the rigors of the 19-year-old
revolution.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Gholamhussein Karbaschi is a close ally of the president
and a member of his Cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I stand before the law, my neck is thinner than a hair,''
Karbaschi told the packed courtroom Tuesday, using a Persian
expression that means he is prepared to accept any verdict. But he
blended defiance with his meekness, saying in his four hours of
testimony: ``I believe whatever I have done is within the law. It
is an attack on our system to say that billions of rials have been
wasted.''
</P>
<P>
   Karbaschi insisted that he is a loyal servant of God and
country.
</P>
<P>
   Even his supporters fear that Karbaschi, a gutsy 45-year-old
former cleric who has run Iran's capital of 10 million people for
more than eight years, will be convicted on some counts. He is
charged with embezzling nearly $5 million, receiving bribes,
influence-peddling, financing political campaigns and misusing
official funds, charges that may keep him in jail for a long time.
</P>
<P>
   The courtroom, which is used to try public officials, is filled
with icons of the Islamic republic. Huge portraits of Ayatollah
Ruhollah Khomeini, the father of the revolution, and of Ayatollah
Ali Khamenei, his successor, hang on each side of the stage. A
banner strung along one side of the courtroom reads, ``Prayer
clarifies the heart.'' And Tuesday's session began with salutations
to the prophet Mohammed and a five-minute reading from the Koran.
</P>
<P>
   Karbaschi was a staunch supporter of Khatami in the presidential
election in May 1997 that swept him to power, and Karbaschi's
supporters have accused the judiciary of using the case to
discredit the president.
</P>
<P>
   In turn, Khatami supports Karbaschi while battling the
conservatives on another front: About 10 days ago, the Parliament
dismissed one of Khatami's closest allies, Interior Minister
Abdollah Nuri. Khatami swiftly retaliated by naming Nuri a vice
president.
</P>
<P>
   Karbaschi's trial has ignited a debate over Iran's convoluted
system of justice, in which the prosecutor, a cleric, also serves
as judge and jury. Until about a year and a half ago, the roles of
prosecutor and judge were filled by two people. But the judiciary
ruled that it was more Islamic to have one person fill both roles,
even though that was not the case in early Islam.
</P>
<P>
   Karbaschi challenged the credentials of the first judge, who has
been replaced, and he has charged that some people who testified
against him had been coerced.
</P>
<P>
   The trial began three weeks ago and could last weeks more.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the four sessions so far has been broadcast on national
television at 11 p.m., offering most Iranians their first inside
glimpse at a trial of a public official. The trial, part civics
lesson and part soap opera, has captured record audiences and is
debated in detail in Iran's politically diverse press.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's session had been postponed for five days because the
media-savvy mayor asked that the trial not coincide with Iran's
participation in the World Cup soccer matches, which was broadcast
in the same time period.
</P>
<P>
   The proceeding itself was largely a heated debate _ at times a
shouting match _ between the bearded white-turbaned judge, who sat
behind a vast bench on a giant stage with gold colored drapes, and
Karbaschi, who stood several feet below behind a lectern.
</P>
<P>
   At one point Karbaschi demanded that the judge, Gholamhussein
Mohseini Ejei, clarify the charge that the municipality had bought
the land that had once been the Tehran Zoo and resold it to some
city managers at less than market value.
</P>
<P>
   ``The charges were clarified!'' the judge shot back. ``You must
answer, or say that you do not want to answer.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You did not let me finish!'' Karbaschi shouted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't give me the runaround!'' the judge replied. ``I do the
asking and you do the answering.''
</P>
<P>
   At another point, Karbaschi asked that the judge allow others to
testify on his behalf regarding a charge that he had ordered
employees to buy gold coins and give them as a farewell present to
a minister who had been removed from his job.
</P>
<P>
   ``According to the regulations in the law, we can't have
witnesses,'' Karbaschi said. ``We want witnesses!''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you give me a reasonable answer, I'll drop the charges and
there will be no need for witnesses,'' replied the judge.
</P>
<P>
   Karbaschi got a boost Tuesday from the testimony of Ali
Besharati, a conservative who served as interior minister during
some of Karbaschi's tenure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could see the activities of the municipality every day and I
was supporting them,'' Besharati said, adding that the charges
might be of ``neglect and omission by the Tehran mayor and not,
heaven forbid, any bad intention.''
</P>
<P>
   The only role for Karbaschi's two lawyers, who sat at a desk to
his right much like an American defense team, seemed to be to
explain intricacies of the penal code when called upon by their
client.
</P>
<P>
   The section where an American jury might sit was reserved for
four dozen photographers and reporters. Iran's state-run television
strategically placed four cameras in the court.
</P>
<P>
   The trial has exposed the lax system of bookkeeping in Iran, a
country that has thrived on favors and gifts regardless of whether
the country was ruled by clerics or by kings.
</P>
<P>
   Although there is no concrete evidence, at least not yet, that
Karbaschi is personally corrupt, he exploited the lax system,
moving money from one account to another, trading favors,
encouraging employees with bonuses and benefits and pressuring
businesses to contribute to his various beautification schemes.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, he bulldozed apartment buildings and office
buildings built without city approval, removed revolutionary
graffiti from walls, planted thousands of trees, banned much of the
private traffic in central Tehran and opened more than a hundred
parks _ all in the name of transforming Tehran into a city that
worked.
</P>
<P>
   When Karbaschi was briefly arrested after the charges were
leveled against him, many shopkeepers hung a caricature that had
appeared in one of the newspapers showing Karbaschi in a prison
cell chained to a plant.
</P>
<P>
   But Karbaschi also made enemies, angering bazaar merchants by
raising taxes and contributing to the city's soaring real estate
prices.
</P>
<P>
   Trained in the holy city of Qom as a cleric, Karbaschi spent
time in Evin prison for his political activities before the
revolution and holds the same clerical rank as the judge who is
trying him.
</P>
<P>
   Even if he loses, he could be made a political martyr and
eventually re-emerge as an even more important political figure.
Asked in an interview in 1995 about his reputation as ``the most
loved and hated man in Tehran,'' he replied, ``Great people in
history are like that.''
</P>
<P>
   The trial resumes on Sunday. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-98 1939EDT &QL; 
