<SLUG> BC-TOMB-SERVICEMAN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIRMAN'S IDENTIFICATION RELIEVES FAMILY AFTER YEARS OF
UNCERTAINTY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By OSCAR AVILA  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: A 26-year mystery was resolved Monday when the Pentagon
said the remains of a serviceman in the Tomb of the Unknowns are
those of a St. Louis airman.
</P>
<P>
   That ends years of uncertainty for the family of 1st Lt. Michael
Blassie.
</P>
<P>
   On May 11, 1972, Blassie's A-37 was shot down over Vietnam. For
years, loved ones were told that his body had never been recovered.
But earlier this year, a TV report presented new evidence that
Blassie's remains were in the Tomb of the Unknowns at Arlington
National Cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   Blassie's family said Pentagon officials told them a formal
announcement would be made today.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're really happy about what's happened,'' Blassie's sister,
Judy Cozad, said Monday night by telephone from Chesterfield, Mo.
``I think it's going to bring a feeling of closure for everyone,
especially my mom. We still want to wait to hear it officially,
though.''
</P>
<P>
   Four siblings plan to gather in the Florissant, Mo., home of his
mother, Jean Blassie, Tuesday morning to receive a phone call from
the Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
   An Iowa family had hoped that the remains belonged to Capt.
Rodney Strobridge, an Army pilot who also was shot down over
Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   His mother, Althea Strobridge, said that Pentagon officials told
her Monday that the remains were Blassie's.
</P>
<P>
   The mystery had grown to become more than just a struggle for
two families. It also was a delicate political issue.
</P>
<P>
   The Tomb of the Unknowns remains a treasured place for American
veterans, containing one soldier killed in each of the nation's
major wars since World War I. Defense officials were reluctant to
disturb the tomb so Blassie's body could be exhumed for DNA tests.
But they did so.
</P>
<P>
   Blassie's family was invited to Arlington last month for the
exhumation. Defense Secretary William Cohen said the tests were
done ``with the hope that the heavy burden of doubt may be lifted
from a family's heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Blassie's family was devastated when they received word of his
death. After graduating from the Air Force Academy in 1970, Blassie
was accepted to flight school. From there, he was called into duty
in Vietnam in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   Blassie flew 132 missions in his A-37. On May 11, 1972, as part
of what was later known as the Easter Offensive, Blassie's plane
and another A-37 swooped in to bomb An Loc in southern Vietnam.
There Blassie's plane was hit by an anti-aircraft gun and crashed
into a jungle.
</P>
<P>
   Because of enemy troops, it was six months before American
forces could reach the crash site. Near there, searchers found a
man's remains along with Blassie's ID card, dog tag, money and
wallet. The findings were shipped home, but the remains became
separated from Blassie's belongings.
</P>
<P>
   Tests to identify the body were inconclusive, but the Pentagon
said the remains were ``believed to be'' Blassie's. In 1979, the
``believed to be'' designation was removed from the remains, which
then were reclassified as unidentifiable. In 1984 the Pentagon sent
the remains to represent the Vietnam War dead in the Tomb of the
Unknowns.
</P>
<P>
   For years, Jean Blassie couldn't even talk about her oldest son.
A marker in a secluded corner of a St. Louis cemetery had been an
incomplete tribute. Now the family hopes for a proper funeral.
</P>
<P>
   Blassie's siblings still remember the words of their mother when
they asked her whether she wanted to pursue the case after the
initial television report. She didn't hesitate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to bring Michael home,'' she told her children.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
