<SLUG> BC-GUSEWELLE-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TOWN BALL' DISGUISED AS TOP-FLIGHT PROFESSIONALISM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By C.W. GUSEWELLE  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ We went out to the stadium the other night to
watch a game of town ball.
</P>
<P>
   In case you're unfamiliar with the term, ``town ball'' is what's
played on summer evenings in places like Elysian and Waterville,
Minn., by men who get off work at the feed store, the filling
station and the plant that cans sweet corn.
</P>
<P>
   They're pretty good, some of those fellows. They're almost, but
not quite, good enough to play the game for money.
</P>
<P>
   Things might have been different if they'd gotten a break
somewhere along the line _ had the chance to go to college and been
noticed by a scout, whatever.
</P>
<P>
   But that's all in the past. You can't feed a family on
might-have-beens. So now they heave sacks and pump gas and go out
under weak lights to play the team from the town just down the
road.
</P>
<P>
   The pitcher's curve ball hangs more often than it breaks, and
his fast ball comes in fat and straight, big as a cantaloupe to the
batter's eye.
</P>
<P>
   Once in a while one of the town boys will make a play so
spectacular it takes the breath _ the kind you'd expect to see in a
highlight film.
</P>
<P>
   But they also boot ground balls fairly often, and make bonehead
plays, like throwing to the wrong base or getting doubled-up on a
pop fly because they forgot how many outs there were.
</P>
<P>
   What can you expect, though? These aren't professionals, getting
the big bucks to perform. They're just a bunch of ordinary guys who
can't quite leave boyhood behind, and so they play the game for
love.
</P>
<P>
   As I've said, we spent a recent evening at the ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   The pitchers for the home club pooled their ineffectiveness in
surrendering 19 hits, two of which left the premises. The opponents
gave up only 10 hits, but committed three errors.
</P>
<P>
   The stadium was more than half-empty. The loudest cheers were
for fans who caught foul balls. No real spirit could be detected on
the diamond or in the dugout. Shoulders slumped. There was, about
it all, a sense of leaden inevitability.
</P>
<P>
   Truth be told, neither team was much good, a fact to which the
men on the field appeared resigned. Granted, they were more skilled
than the population at large. But so are most town ball players.
</P>
<P>
   And this wasn't really a town team we were watching. In name, if
not in fact, this was big-league baseball. These were lads who
receive a ludicrous wage for something they do not do exceptionally
well.
</P>
<P>
   You think back to the quality of the game before the era of
willy-nilly expansion, and it's plain that in those days a good
many of today's players would have been punching the clock and
holding down regular jobs.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as the notion took hold that every city which meant to
be anyplace at all had to have a major-league baseball team, the
talent inevitably began thinning out.
</P>
<P>
   There still are stars, of course _ still players with prodigious
gifts. There just aren't enough of them to go around. What you get,
as a consequence, is something that resembles town ball, but
without the homespun enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
   I'll say this, though: The stadium is a beauty! The lights are
bright. The hot dogs are good, if a little pricey. All that may be
worth the ticket.
</P>
<P>
   And the grass...well, the grass is an absolute wonder. They
don't grow turf like that on the lumpy fields of Waterville and
Elysian, Minn.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
