<DOCNO> NYT19980630.0292 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 19:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4564 &Cx1f; kan-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOYS-BLOND-KAN &LR;      06-30 0870
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOYS-BLOND-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLEACH BRINGS NIRVANA TO GUYS WHO WANT TO GO PLATINUM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KATHERINE L. DYKSTRA  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ It could be the influence of movie and TV
stars, guys like Drew Carey, Jason Priestley and Bruce Willis. Or
maybe it's art, a bold personality statement. Or maybe they're just
looking for a good time _ after all, blonds have more fun, right?
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the case, more and more young men _ yes, men,
Caucasian, African-American, Asian _ are coming down with a serious
case of blond ambition, soaking their hair in bleach and peroxide.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton Briar, 19, of Olathe, Kan., bleached his a couple of
weeks ago. So did Eric Rice, 20, of Overland Park, Kan. Dan Hunter
of Kansas City turned his naturally brown locks into a blinding
white pate nearly two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get comments on it all of the time,'' Hunter said. ``Most of
the people at my store get a kick out of it.'' Hunter is owner of
Pretzel Time at the Town Pavilion.
</P>
<P>
   They're hardly alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, it's been in Rolling Stone magazine lately,'' said
Tina Steele, a hair colorist at Blondie's Studio of Hair Color and
Design in Kansas City. ``I don't know if they're seeing it on TV
and in the magazines, and that's where they're getting it or
what.''
</P>
<P>
   So what's the fascination? Why turn your head into a white,
short-piled rug?
</P>
<P>
   ``I do it to be noticed,'' Hunter said. ``It's like an art.''
</P>
<P>
   For Briar, his dye job was more of a labor of love: When his
girlfriend colored her own hair and hated it, Briar proceeded to
bleach his hair in an effort to show her that it is, in fact, just
hair.
</P>
<P>
   When and where the fad began is hard to say. In Kansas City the
towheaded trend has gently rolled in the last few years.
</P>
<P>
   A visit to a local salon began Hunter's quest for blond. He
watched the hairdresser bleach a customer's hair and decided he
could save money by doing it himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw what they did and knew that I didn't need to spend $80
on it,'' Hunter said.
</P>
<P>
   He bought a bleaching kit from a local drugstore, which can cost
$7 to $15.
</P>
<P>
   At Blondie's, 39th and Roanoke, a bleach starts at $65, then the
price increases with the hair length, said colorist Steele.
</P>
<P>
   Hunter began by bleaching his cropped hair a natural blond shade
but quickly moved to a stark white. He is most satisfied with his
hair two weeks after a bleach _ yes, when his dark roots peek
through the blond.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the guys that do it seem to wear very short hair, and
they want it as light and as white as you can get it,'' Steele
said.
</P>
<P>
   Every three weeks Hunter takes three hours out of his day to
bleach his hair. He admits it is a big hassle but thinks the visual
effect and the attention he receives is worth the time he spends.
</P>
<P>
   Rice usually has his girlfriend bleach his hair for him. But be
careful whom you trust with your hair, he said: Once a friend
failed to bleach Rice's hair evenly and he turned out looking like
a ``leopard.''
</P>
<P>
   Although younger men seem to have embraced the fad most
fervently, Steele said more older men are choosing to go platinum.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that it is a bigger trend now than when I started
bleaching mine, two years ago,'' Hunter said. ``But I am a lot
older than a lot of the kids who are doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   It's true, many adults just don't get it.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first did it my parents didn't like it and didn't
understand,'' Rice said. ``But, you know, they don't have to
understand.''
</P>
<P>
   Women don't seem to be as excited about the trend. Steele thinks
they realize how much upkeep is involved, while the men tend not to
understand the commitment.
</P>
<P>
   Hunter said the trend also may be more popular among men because
women have more to risk when bleaching their hair. After only four
applications, Hunter's hair becomes so dry that the ends crackle
off like nested linguine.
</P>
<P>
   So he just shaves his head and begins again.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the bleaching damages a woman's long hair, she has much
more to lose,'' Hunter said.
</P>
<P>
   To keep the hair that light and that white, you can't have any
length, Steele said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that I didn't like my hair, it's just that I wanted
to be different, different from anyone else,'' Hunter said. ``I
don't think that anyone is ever really satisfied with their hair.''
</P>
<P>
   So do blonds really have more fun?
</P>
<P>
   ``Girls really seem to like it,'' Rice said.
</P>
<P>
   That just might be answer enough.
</P>
<P>
   Going blond
</P>
<P>
   Thinking about transforming your tresses into the blondest of
blond? Here's some inside advice from platinum guys Dan Hunter of
Kansas City and Eric Rice of Overland Park, if you're going to dye
yourself:
</P>
<P>
   - Covering your head with plastic after applying the chemicals
will help speed up the bleaching process and help make the color
lighter.
</P>
<P>
   - Applying heat, such as a hair dryer, also speeds things along.
</P>
<P>
   - Keep water nearby. If the chemicals start to hurt your scalp,
pour on the water to relieve the burn. Hunter said he uses
lemon-lime soda.
</P>
<P>
   - The bleach will bleach anything it lands on _ carpets, towels,
skin _ so be careful!
</P>
<P>
   - Make sure you cover your hair evenly or you'll end up with
stripes!
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
