<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 19:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4566 &Cx1f; kan-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-INDYPRODUCER-K     06-30 1171
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-INDYPRODUCER-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRODUCER TED HOPE KNOWS ANGST, ART OF INDEPENDENT FILMMAKING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT W. BUTLER  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: This is Ted Hope's Gospel of Independent Filmmaking:
</P>
<P>
   ``The quintessential rule of no-budget filmmaking is that the
budget is the aesthetic.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to know what you can do with the money you have and
shape your production around it. You have to boil down the essence
of what each scene is about and make sure that if you get nothing
else, you have that essence on film.''
</P>
<P>
   Hope knows a few things about making good movies with little
money. As a founding partner (with screenwriter//producer James
Schamus) of New York-based Good Machine Productions, he has
encouraged and nurtured some of the most important directors in
independent films.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston-born Hope produced early efforts by indie stalwart
Hal Hartley. Since the founding of Good Machine in 1991 he has
produced all of Ang Lee's movies, including the Civil War drama
``Ride With the Devil,'' currently filming in the Kansas City area.
He also produced works by Ed Burns (``The Brothers McMullen''),
Todd Haynes (``Safe'') and Todd Solenz (whose ``Happiness'' was the
sensation of the Cannes Film Festival this year).
</P>
<P>
   Hope practices what he preaches. When ``Ride With the Devil''
completes principal photography later this week, it will be on
schedule and within its $38 million budget, he said the other day.
</P>
<P>
   The producer will share some of his insights in a seminar this
weekend at the Tivoli theaters in Westport (see box for details).
</P>
<P>
   ``These seminars are a natural outgrowth of what we do,'' Hope
explained during an interview in the austere trailer he shares with
co-producers James Schamus and Bob Colesberry on the ``Ride With
the Devil'' set. ``In the past it's always been in conjunction with
film festivals where our movies have been shown. In this case I
wanted to do something for the Tivoli Theatre, which I've visited
several times while I've been in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   ``But also I always feel strange when I'm filming on location.
Granted, you bring in money, but I always feel like a carpetbagger
who's somehow exploiting the community. I've found these seminars
are a way of getting across a sense of who we are, of sharing what
we've learned.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Details magazine, Hope's company, Good Machine,
``has become New York's pre-eminent independent production company
by attracting talented young directors and helping them make their
movies on the leanest budgets possible.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Hope said, ``The biggest role of a film producer is to
help directors understand their choices and the repercussions.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you find a first film that's right for you as a
director? One of the things we do as producers is give our
directors reality checks. Sometimes we advise against making a
certain movie now. We'll suggest that this is a topic the director
should tackle as a third or fourth movie.''
</P>
<P>
   Hope is a boyish-looking 35-year-old who talks in a voice that
his partner Schamus has described as ``crossing a Canadian goose
with a South Boston fishmonger.'' He noted that in Good Machine's
seven years the stakes for low-budget movies have been raised.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be that if you made $1 million off your low-budget
film, it was a success. Now you've got to make $5 million.
Moreover, even many distributors of independent films are only
looking for the more mainstream work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even Ang suffered from that. He won an award for making the
best student film at NYU, but it took eight years for him to make
his next movie. His agents wanted him to have a big Hollywood
career; they rejected two offers we made to produce Ang's films.
Finally Ang got so frustrated that he came to us with money he'd
raised in Taiwan and asked us to produce `Pushing Hands.' He said
he'd die if he didn't actually make a movie.''
</P>
<P>
   Hope practically lives on the telephone _ understandable since
Good Machine always has several projects going at once.
</P>
<P>
   ``Currently we have two projects in development from first-time
directors. We're shooting one director's first film, and we're in
post-production on another first film. We have four scripts in
development with directors whose first films we produced.
</P>
<P>
   ``And of course we're filming `Ride With the Devil,' which is
the biggest project we've ever been involved in.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to helping directors understand their options, a
producer's job breaks down into several key functions, Hope said.
</P>
<P>
   - Funding: ``Money can come from lots of sources. You can find
private money, make foreign pre-sales, shop your idea to the
studios _ or you can chop down the budget so you can make the film
on that inheritance your aunt left you. It's always a different
story. One of our directors raised all his money from his
relatives. Another took four years to assemble his money from many
sources.''
</P>
<P>
   - Post-production: ``A good example is `The Brothers McMullen.'
Ed Burns had it shot and cut when we first got a look at it. It was
a two-hour movie that was closer to melodrama than comedy. Every
distributor who saw the film passed on it. But we saw something
there, and we spent lots of time, lots of nights at an editing
machine, working with Ed to reshape the film.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something like that happened even on `The Ice Storm''' _ Ang
Lee's last film. ``The first cuts of that movie played like a
comedy. We realized we couldn't have a film where people laugh for
an hour and then we kill off a character they love. So we had to
eliminate some very funny stuff to better serve the overall tone of
the movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's another thing about being a good producer _ you have to
always look at the movie with the eyes of a first-time viewer.''
</P>
<P>
   - On the set: ``Typically, I'm a hands-on producer. We're not
the kind of deal-making producers you see depicted in movies. James
and I got into this out of our love of film. We really admire what
it takes to get a director's vision out onto the screen. We want to
be available as a sounding board, to help the director do that. If
you see one of our films, we hope you will say that it couldn't
have been made by any other director.''
</P>
<P>
   Good Machine isn't going it alone on ``Ride With the Devil,''
its most expensive effort so far. Universal Pictures has
underwritten much of the film in return for the U.S. distribution
rights. It's a slightly different environment than what Hope and
company have been used to.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got more people to work with, and more people watching
over us,'' Hope said. ``Because there's so much money at stake, you
need more visible actors. As a producer, you then have to deal with
them and their agents to a much greater extent than you might on a
low-budget project. The chain of communication grows with the
budget _ studio people, agents, bigger crews.
</P>
<P>
   ``On a smaller film I'll know everybody on the set by their
first names. Can't do that here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
