<SLUG> BC-PETS-STORMS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOISY STORMS CAN PUT PETS IN A PANIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 LEE HILL KAVANAUGH  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The winds begin to pick up. Boiling clouds
turn daylight into night. They are nature's signs that a storm is
coming _ a storm that can sometimes turn an otherwise calm animal
into a frenzied fur ball.
</P>
<P>
   Instinct tells them they need to move. Run. Hide. Some pace,
some pant. Some begin to tremble.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it's a dog, cat, horse or even a giraffe, severe
thunderstorms such as those that rumbled through the area this week
can truly frighten animals _ even to death.
</P>
<P>
   During storms, dogs have thrown themselves through plate-glass
windows trying to get inside a house, or ripped their teeth out
trying to break free of a chain, said Chris Duarte, a dog
behaviorist and owner of K-9 Connection, a training school for dog
owners in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a client with a golden retriever who would literally
try to hide in the smallest space possible,'' Duarte said. ``One
day the owners came home and found him with his head stuck in a
small plastic toy. He had suffocated.''
</P>
<P>
   And it's not just domestic animals that are afraid of storms. At
the Kansas City Zoo Tuesday morning, the giraffes wouldn't leave
their stalls.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were leery of coming out,'' said Agelon Jones, zoo area
supervisor. ``They don't like storms. I guess it was too much for
them. We didn't force them to leave. When an animal weighs 1,400
pounds and stands at least 15 feet tall, if they decide they don't
want to come out, they don't.''
</P>
<P>
   And they didn't.
</P>
<P>
   Other animals accustomed to life outdoors also may panic _ even
domestic livestock.
</P>
<P>
   At 2:30 a.m. Tuesday, one loud ``BOOM!'' jolted awake horsewoman
Tammy Kesemann, owner of TnT Equine Center in Odessa, Mo. Cruiser,
her stallion, was in the pasture. ``I had to go get him,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   When she found him in the field, Cruiser was trembling and
nervous. ``He was ready to come in,'' she said. ``I've known about
horses and cattle that have been struck by lightning. I didn't want
to take any chances with him. He's too valuable.''
</P>
<P>
   Many dog and cat owners also feel their animals are valuable _
emotionally.
</P>
<P>
   So they'll coo to pets to calm their whining. They'll hug them
to stop their trembling. They'll pour out attention to them. And,
in the process, they unwittingly teach their pets to fear even
more.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you let your dog in bed with you, you're reinforcing his
fears,'' said veterinarian John Cousins, of Animed of Blue Springs,
Mo. ``It feels like you're helping him, but what happens when
you're not there?''
</P>
<P>
   An animal running in a frenzy to escape or hide can harm itself.
But crating a dog is not a good way to keep it calm either, Duarte
said.
</P>
<P>
   One trainer he knew put a dog on an airplane without first
acclimating the animal to the loud noises it would hear during the
flight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before the plane landed, the dog ripped itself out of its
cage, hurting itself in the process, sending blood everywhere,'' he
said. ``It ripped up the suitcases and clothes. By the time they
opened the cargo hold it was a nightmarish scene.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately the dog lived.
</P>
<P>
   There are things that pet owners can do to help animals cope,
Cousins said, primarily through drugs or desensitization.
</P>
<P>
   Prescriptions ranging from a mild form of Valium to a
longer-lasting drug, Tranxene, are available from veterinarians.
The drugs should be administered hours before a storm begins, to
help ease the pet before stress sets in.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem with drugs is that sometimes the owner isn't there
to give it to the dog,'' he said. ``But an animal behaviorist can
often help the dog to be less afraid.''
</P>
<P>
   Teaching owners how to help their dogs is Duarte's speciality.
One technique he uses is the systematic playing of a tape of
thunderstorms for storm-phobic dogs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tell owners to play it softly at first and gradually turn
the volume up,'' he said. ``But even then, the success depends on
how diligent the trainer is, and how the dog takes to it. Rarely
does a bad case ever go away completely, but it can be lessened.''
</P>
<P>
   Storm phobia is a strong fear. Sometimes even a hunting dog
accustomed to gunshots still panics during bad weather.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Lyons of the Lyons Den Kennel in Kingsville, Mo., trains
hunting dogs. A dog can learn to accept loud noises, Lyons said, if
training begins early.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I've never seen a storm-phobic dog lose its phobia,'' he
said. ``If a dog likes birds, I can teach it to ignore gunshots,
because it's focused on a bird. But if it doesn't like storms,
that's a lot deeper. I don't believe that a phobia can be changed.
Ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell owners to go for the drugs if you want to help a
storm-phobic dog. Its life will be much better. And if your dog is
scared of loud noises, board it far away from the city during the
Fourth of July. You'll both be happier.''
Tips for frightened animals
In the face of fear, here's help Although some cats get anxious
during storms, the majority of family pets that are storm-phobic
are dogs.
</P>
<P>
   Here is a list of do's and don'ts for anxious owners trying to
help, adapted from local pet experts:
</P>
<P>
   _Don't be afraid to call your vet for help. Veterinarians have a
wide assortment of drugs that can calm a nervous dog.
</P>
<P>
   - During a storm do not give your dog praise or cuddle him when
he is afraid. That reinforces his behavior. However, don't punish
him; that will make him more fearful.
</P>
<P>
   - Provide a safe place for your dog to hide, a small den that is
dark and shielded from sound. Encourage your dog to go there if you
are around him during a storm.
</P>
<P>
   - Do not force him into a crate. Fearful dogs can hurt
themselves trying to leave a space where they feel trapped.
</P>
<P>
   - Consult an animal behaviorist; your vet may know of one. Be
aware that training is a long-term time commitment and that some
dogs' fears can only be lessened, not eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   - Check the Internet for these Web site resources:
</P>
<P>
   ``Fear of Thunder'' includes training tips for owners with dogs
afraid of thunder and loud noises. It's at
www.ddfl.org//fearthun.html.
</P>
<P>
   ``Medications and Dogs'' is a question-and-answer discussion on
dealing medically with a dog afraid of storms. It's at
www.vetinfo.com/.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-98 1946EDT &QL; 
