<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 19:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4570 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANDERSON-SCI-FI-TEX     06-30 0583
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANDERSON-SCI-FI-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCI-FI SCRIBE IS THE HOTTEST WRITER ON (AND OFF) THE PLANET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TODD CAMP 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the interstellar pantheon of speculative fiction, you
couldn't ask for a more connected writer than Kevin J. Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   Author of three novels based on ``The X-Files,'' as well as the
bestselling ``Star Wars'' Jedi-Academy Trilogy, Anderson already
has a foot in two of the most obsessive science-fiction fan legions
in the world.
</P>
<P>
   But his latest book, ``Ai! Pedrito!: When Intelligence Goes
Wrong,'' a novelization of a screenplay by the late scientology
guru (and occasional deity) L. Ron Hubbard, along with his upcoming
prequel trilogy to Frank Herbert's ``Dune'' stories, elevate
Anderson to a position of sci-fi superstardom.
</P>
<P>
   The tongue-in-cheek twist of ``Pedrito!'' may seem like a
departure from the grim supernatural stylings of ``The X-Files'' or
the epic otherworldliness of his ``Star Wars'' adventures, but
Anderson says the similarities are more surprising than you might
imagine.
</P>
<P>
   Written shortly before Hubbard's death in 1985, ``Pedrito!'' was
originally intended as a screenplay.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of a cross between James Bond and `Raiders of the
Lost Ark,' with Carl Hiassen and Elmore Leonard thrown in,''
Anderson said. ``It's a laugh-out-loud spy-vs.-spy thriller set in
the South American jungle.''
</P>
<P>
   When Anderson was contacted by Hubbard's publishers to adapt the
piece into novel form, it seemed like a perfect fit.
</P>
<P>
   ``My skills are playing around with somebody else's characters
and stories. It's something I've become sort of an expert at doing,
thanks to my work on the `X-Files' and `Star Wars' books,'' he
said. ``It's like borrowing somebody else's toys in a sandbox; it's
still lots of fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Researching the book took Anderson south of the equator to
Ecuador, where he wandered the Andes Mountains and explored Incan
ruins. ``There are a lot of authors who are sort of armchair
researchers who think all they need to do is watch a National
Geographic video and they've got all the information they need,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   His devotion to research was also put to good use on his
``X-Files,'' novels. Anderson worked closely with the FBI, soaking
up the atmosphere at the agency's best crime labs.
</P>
<P>
   Has working intimately with fictional FBI special agents Mulder
and Scully prompted Anderson to try scripting an episode?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really good at writing novels. I've taken a stab at
writing scripts and things, but it really is a different artform,''
Anderson said. ``You know, the best gynecologist in the world is
going to be a pretty poor brain surgeon.''
</P>
<P>
   Next up for the author is ``The Prelude to Dune Trilogy,'' the
first book of which _ ``House Atreides'' _ is due out next year
from Bantam. He's writing it with original ``Dune'' author Frank
Herbert's son, Ryan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just the fact that people's expectations are going to be so
incredibly high when they pick up this book _ it says `Dune' on the
cover, so they're going to expect it to be in the same league with
the bestselling science-fiction book of all time. Those are some
pretty big shoes to fill,'' Anderson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the fans live in these worlds. They know `Star Wars'
inside and out, and they know `X-Files' inside and out. And that
sort of intimidating pressure keeps me honest.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
