<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 19:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4572 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-CHINA-BOS &LR;      06-30 1247
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CHINA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON TO OBSERVE CHANGE IN CHINA HOUSING POLICY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHANGHAI _ Here in an unremarkable, pink-trimmed, five-story
apartment complex that President Clinton visits Wednesday, a
revolution has begun that will likely transform China's economy,
culture and politics in ways its communist founders wouldn't
recognize.
</P>
<P>
   Starting Wednesday in a policy to be phased in by the year's
end, the government will no longer provide virtually free housing
to urban workers, and families will have to purchase homes or lease
state-owned apartments at much higher rents. But that also means
that for the first time since the founding of the People's Republic
in 1949, between 200 million and 300 million urban Chinese will be
able to live wherever and as comfortably as they can afford.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the old days, we were assigned homes by our work units and
it was sometimes unfair. Powerful people in the unit got better
homes'' and people could not move or change jobs because they were
tied to assigned housing, said Fan Xiaoyang, a 37-year-old futures
trader who recently bought an apartment with the help of a mortgage
loan, a new concept in China. ``Now, however good or bad our house
is depends on our ability. We can finally control it.''
</P>
<P>
   Home ownership has long been central to the American Dream, but
in China the implications go far beyond the notion of family
security and the chance to accumulate equity. Housing reform,
perhaps more than any other change to the planned economy, will
fundamentally alter life in China by giving people control over
their lives at the most basic level.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the picture is not entirely rosy. Millions of workers
are so poor that they can barely manage higher rents, much less
buy. Countless others who are being forcibly relocated far from
soon-to-be-demolished state apartments to make way for shiny new
developments for the rich. Even so, for most people, housing reform
will mean more living space and better facilities than ever before.
</P>
<P>
   For China's economy, the implications are tremendous. Housing
reform, which began first in Shanghai in 1991, is expected to give
the biggest single boost to gross domestic product this year. It
should set off a boom in housing-related industries and services.
All told, the ripple effect on the economy from housing could fuel
one percentage point of growth this year _ a key to creating jobs
for millions laid off from state-owned enterprise reform.
</P>
<P>
   Mortgages will bolster China's fragile banks, by injecting more
reliable credit into a system bogged down with 20 percent
non-performing loans.
</P>
<P>
   Private housing will also lift an enormous burden from the
shoulders of flailing state enterprises, by excusing them from the
biggest cost of cradle-to-grave welfare.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, the establishment of private housing will also
accentuate class differences and create more rich and poor
neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   When Clinton tours Jin Hui Gardens, a collection of modestly
landscaped, middle-income housing in the booming financial capital
of Shanghai, he will see the winners of China's economic reforms.
</P>
<P>
   One is Xu Yaosheng, a 38-year-old broker who bought his
four-bedroom, 160-square-yard Jin Hui apartment for his family of
four last year for around 650,000 yuan ($78,313), with the help of
a mortgage loan.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be like in America now. Not everyone can buy a
house; you can rent if you don't have the ability to buy,'' said
Xu. ``But no matter whether you have money to buy a house or not,
housing conditions for almost everyone have gotten better in the
last few years.''
</P>
<P>
   That includes people like Fan, the trader whose new apartment is
a far cry from the state-owned 15-square-yard home in which he grew
up with three other family members. They had access only to a
shared public toilet. Today, he has two living rooms.
</P>
<P>
   But Fan and Xu are the lucky ones. The average price of a
three-room home in Shanghai is $66,000 _ while the average worker
in Shanghai earns less than $120 a month, Ren Xiaobing of the China
Construction Bank told China Daily.
</P>
<P>
   That staggering ratio between housing prices and wages of 46 to
1 is many times greater than the average of 6 to 1 in developed
countries, according to the Shanghai Housing and Land
Administration. The high price of housing here has created a
massive glut in unsold apartments _ 6 million square yards of
vacant residential space, the Shanghai Star reported.
</P>
<P>
   The government is trying to remedy that by offering low-interest
mortgages and subsidized prices and setting up housing funds to
which both employers and employees must contribute. But still not
everyone will be able to buy.
</P>
<P>
   Housing reform will also bring wide-ranging cultural changes. In
a nation with one of the highest savings rates in the world _ but
where many people's savings are still quite small _ home ownership
will force people to borrow and spend more. It will also hasten the
break-up of the extended family unit.
</P>
<P>
   At the no-frills Buo Wen Yuan complex in the Pudong business
district, Li Xiaofeng and his wife Huang Haiyan came to look at a
flat Tuesday, but quickly turned away when they realized the price
was too much.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Li and his wife live with his father, his brother and his
sister-in-law in a two-bedroom, 60-square-yard apartment that will
soon be torn down to make room for a highway. The government has
assigned them a new apartment, but it is too far away. The
government will compensate the family 230,000 yuan ($27,710), which
they will split three ways _ and get three separate homes, a
stunning break from the tradition of living with one's elderly
parents.
</P>
<P>
   Housing reform will also have political ramifications, by
limiting people's dependence on their work unit, and thereby
removing the government one step further from their lives. It &UR;  &LR; will
enable people to change jobs, even marry someone from another city.
The mere fact of ownership is likely to breed a sense of
responsibility and personal freedom that could prompt demands for
things such as legal rights to hold property developers
accountable. &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   As proof of the mobilizing effect of livelihood issues, large
demonstrations in the last couple of years have not been over
democracy and human rights, but over real estate ripoffs, forced
relocations and layoffs.
</P>
<P>
   A few miles from Buo Wen Yuan is an ancient block of housing in
which some 100 residents are still squatting, even as a wrecking
ball hangs in the air, having demolished most of the units. These
last holdouts are resisting efforts to move them to make way for a
shopping mall, even though the government has offered new, bigger
units an hour away.
</P>
<P>
   A 41-year-old saleswoman who gave her name as Fang said she
preferred her dilapidated warren, because she could not afford the
50,000 ($6,024) &UR;  &LR; yuan fee for the additional space, or the money
needed to put in fixtures. ``If the government orders us to leave,
I have no choice. But I feel cheated,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But across town, in another crumbling block where residents have
no heating or toilets, Guo Guiqing, a 42-year-old resident and real
estate agent, says it is a good thing for the government to
relocate them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before we only worried about food and clothing,'' Guo said.
``Now that those are taken care of, we can think about better
housing for our people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
