<HEADER>
A4574 &Cx1f; kan-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILMS-BLACK-KAN &LR;      06-30 1261
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILMS-BLACK-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EARLY AFRICAN-AMERICAN FILMMAKERS GET THEIR DUE ON TCM SERIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 bY CALVIN WILSON  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``A Separate Cinema'' will feature 29 black-made movies, plus a
documentary on race films, on the five Wednesdays in July,
beginning at 7 tonight, on Turner Classic Movies.
</P>
<P>
   Before ``Do the Right Thing,'' there was ``The Symbol of the
Unconquered.'' Before ``Mean Streets,'' there was ``Dark
Manhattan.'' Before ``The Adventures of Priscilla, Queen of the
Desert,'' there was ``Boy! What a Girl.''
</P>
<P>
   The early black cinema of the 1920s through the '40s not only
provided an alternative for black audiences disappointed by
demeaning Hollywood stereotypes, but also set the precedent for the
modern independent film movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Separate Cinema,'' a 29-film series starting tonight on
Turner Classic Movies, showcases the work of Oscar Micheaux (who is
buried in Great Bend, Kan.), Spencer Williams and other
African-American filmmakers who thrived in Tinseltown's shadow.
</P>
<P>
   The series runs each Wednesday in July on the cable channel,
with each edition devoted to a different theme (see schedule). It
offers insights into a parallel movie universe that escaped the
notice of the American Film Institute and its recent list of the
country's 100 greatest films.
</P>
<P>
   ``A large portion of the public, both black and white, is not
aware that before Spike Lee there were film directors who were
African-American,'' said John Kisch, founder of Separate Cinema, a
film archive devoted to black cinema. TCM licensed the firm's name
for the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an awful lot of people that need a lot of help in
understanding both the history of a race on film and film itself,''
he said. ``It's like finding something you never knew existed.''
</P>
<P>
   Micheaux, whose body of work stands out for the scholarly and
critical attention it has attracted, serves as the focus of
tonight's programming.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a true pioneer,'' said Laurence Kardish, curator of the
Department of Film and Video at the Museum of Modern Art in New
York. ``A committed individualist, whose works have a particular
energy and vision.''
</P>
<P>
   The centerpiece of the series' first installment is Micheaux's
``Symbol of the Unconquered,'' a 1921 silent drama attacking racism
and the Ku Klux Klan. The film is regarded as a response to D.W.
Griffith's epic ``The Birth of a Nation'' of six years earlier,
which depicted Klansmen as heroes.
</P>
<P>
   Turner Classic Movies and the Museum of Modern Art worked
together on a reconstruction of the film, which recently was
discovered in a Belgian film archive. The cable channel
commissioned a score by jazz luminary Max Roach.
</P>
<P>
   Micheaux lived in the Dakotas and financed his first feature,
``The Homesteader,'' by selling stock to white settlers there. He
persuaded black theater managers in Harlem to show the film.
</P>
<P>
   Demand for the picture was solid, and his career was launched.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are two distinct Micheaux periods,'' said Jane M.
Gaines, director of the Film &AMP; Video Program at Duke University in
North Carolina and co-founder of the Oscar Micheaux Society. ``The
one from 1918 to around 1931, which is the silent period, and then
there's the sound period, which runs around 1931 to 1948.''
</P>
<P>
   From an aesthetic standpoint, Gaines said, Micheaux's silent
films are arguably superior.
</P>
<P>
   ``In many cases, they're exquisitely beautiful: They're very
well shot, they do really well on the big screen. They're most
interesting because they have quite complex subplots _ fascinating
stories within stories within stories.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Micheaux's work commands attention as much for its social
and historical significance as for its artistic merits, Kisch said.
</P>
<P>
   ``As with any pioneer, it's not really so much the quality of
their work, or the quantity of their work _ it's the direction of
their work,'' he said. ``His films are not great films in the big
picture, but they are unique in the sense that they are among the
only films of their kind during that period _ the early days _ that
were uplifting to a race.''
</P>
<P>
   During Micheaux's 30-year career, Gaines said, ``he probably
made 50 features.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, between 1910 and 1950, black independent films _ also
known as ``race movies'' _ found appreciative audiences among
people hungry to finally see their own stories on the screen. They
were exhibited in theaters in black urban communities and in
segregated rural areas.
</P>
<P>
   An early player in the emerging industry was the Lincoln Motion
Picture Company in Omaha, Neb., run by two brothers, George and
Noble Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   The race films embraced standard Hollywood film genres, such as
the gangster film, the musical and the Western. But they gave them
a new spin.
</P>
<P>
   ``The black filmmakers' works were a lot grittier, and they
weren't as polished,'' Kardish said. ``But I think that simply had
to do with matters of economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that in terms of treating the genres there was
much of a difference: In the Westerns there were good guys and bad
guys; in the mysteries there were femme fatales.''
</P>
<P>
   The race films, which had low budgets by Hollywood standards,
also featured actors who subsquently found success in mainstream
cinema, such as Paul Robeson and Lena Horne.
</P>
<P>
   If Micheaux adhered to the strategy of working within familiar
Hollywood genres, his films also documented the quirks of language
and behavior of their time, Gaines said. Nor did he shrink from
unflattering portrayals of the black community if the story
demanded it.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the same time that Micheaux really worked hard to show a
full range of types, he still was criticized by the black press,''
she said. ``They criticized him for using the pejorative types _
madams, card sharks, lowlife thieves. But he was portraying the
black community top to bottom, so there would be good people and
bad people.''
</P>
<P>
   The pressures Micheaux faced didn't come only from his own
community.
</P>
<P>
   As an editor, Micheaux ``cut his films again and again between
towns, because he had censorship problems in almost every town.''
That was because of the racial politics of Micheaux's times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Within Our Gates,'' a 1920 drama being shown tonight, was
censored because of its subject: lynching in the post-Civil War
South.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1920 when it premiered in Chicago,'' Gaines said, ``it was
just unacceptable to white and black communities alike. Very
terrifying, really, for a Chicago community which had just had
racial riots that summer before. So that film just disappeared.''
</P>
<P>
   But regardless of any negative reaction to race films, black
audiences could see more of their lives on the big screen than they
ever had before. And they could strongly identify with those
big-screen fantasies.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Hollywood's tales of the ``race problem,'' such as the
films ``Pinky'' and ``Intruder in the Dust'' (both 1949), the black
independents rarely made blackness an issue.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, competition from the ``problem'' pictures, along
with the erosion of racial segregation, ultimately resulted in the
collapse of the black film movement by the coming of the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   But not before the filmmakers had made their point.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I found very interesting about many of the films,''
Kardish said, ``is that they picture a self-contained black world.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are many of the films in which there are simply no
whites. The policemen are black, the lawyers are black, everybody
in the film is black. It's just a given. It's the world.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-98 1949EDT &QL; 
