<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-DOWN-REVIEW-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`I WENT DOWN' HAS ITS UPS AND DOWNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT W. BUTLER  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I Went Down,'' a comedy//drama, is rated R for pervasive
strong language, some sexuality and violence. Running time is 1
hour 48 minutes. Two and a half out of four stars.
</P>
<P>
   The long post-``Pulp Fiction'' shadow of Quentin Tarantino
extends even across the Big Pond, as evidenced by ``I Went Down,''
an Irish road movie about two hapless blokes dispatched by a
gangster to abduct and bring back an old acquaintance.
</P>
<P>
   The film is populated by quirky, scuzzy characters, but unlike
numerous Tarantino wannabes in this country, director Paddy
Breathnach and screenwriter Conor McPherson find their own voice,
one that relies more on an unhurried, loping style and sly humor
than in-your-face violence.
</P>
<P>
   Git (Peter McDonald) is a mopey young man who hasn't been out of
prison for 24 hours when he runs afoul of a local gangster, the
coolly menacing French (Tony Doyle). To even things up, French
gives Git a job _ to travel across Ireland and bring back one
Grogan, an old partner in crime who, French says, owes him a goodly
sum of money.
</P>
<P>
   Git's assigned partner is an old hand, Bunny (Brendan Gleeson),
a beefy leprechaun with orange hair, Elvis sideburns and a
reputation for thuggishness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I Went Down'' follows two plot threads. First there's the
relationship between the inexperienced Git and the presumably
hard-core Bunny. As it turns out, Bunny isn't quite the tough case
he appears; though he thinks nothing of robbing a gas station when
he's short of cash, he's genuinely morose about the failure of his
marriage and terribly misses his young daughter. As he gradually
warms up to his young colleague, he attempts to share with Git his
criminal know-how, much of which is patently foolish.
</P>
<P>
   The second plot element centers on just what French is really up
to.
</P>
<P>
   The two bumblers do manage to locate Grogan (Peter Caffrey), but
their captive swears not to know anything about owing French money.
On the other hand, he readily admits to having an affair with
French's wife. Now Grogan muses in a nonstop barrage of blarney,
the jealous husband no doubt will kill him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you ever make love to a gangster's wife?'' he quizzes his
two captors from the back seat. ``Jeez, you really can't enjoy
yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Git is reluctant to turn over the chatty Grogan for slaughter;
Bunny advises him to do what he's told and not even think about the
consequences.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately a third possibility develops _ that French wants
Grogan back so that they finally can complete a crime scheme
initiated before the two pals fell out years before. But are Git
and Bunny essential to this caper, or are they disposable messenger
boys?
</P>
<P>
   ``I Went Down'' somehow manages to be funny and morose at the
same time, with its sad-sack personalities and atmosphere of cheap
pubs and plastic motel rooms.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, the heavy accents make a good deal of the dialogue
indecipherable to American ears, and there's nothing like the sense
of resolution you'd get from an American mainstream film.
</P>
<P>
   But the performances, especially from McDonald as the
perpetually depressed Git and Gleeson as the thick Bunny, make ``I
Went Down'' enjoyable if not exactly compelling.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-98 1950EDT &QL; 
