<DOCNO> NYT19980630.0303 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 19:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4579 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GATECH-ATDC-COX     06-30 0847
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GATECH-ATDC-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Research offspring may seed technology growth
 &HT;    (EDS: May run with GATECH-CLOUGH, GATECH-QNA, GATECH-GTRI.)By
Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If metro Atlanta is going to grow a high-tech garden,
then someone has to tend the greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Filling that roll is the Advanced Technology Development Center,
which was established 18 years ago and funded by the state in the
hopes of nurturing seedling companies. The idea is that the green
growth will in turn produce both roots and its own off-shoots.
</P>
<P>
   Other organizations _ especially the Georgia Research Alliance _
exist to encourage links between academia and the corporate world.
And other efforts to move technology from lab to market are under
way in other settings, including Emory University which is poised
to launch a center focused on biotechnology.
</P>
<P>
   But so far, the ATDC has the longest history, the widest reach
and the most numerous successes sprouted.
</P>
<P>
   So far, graduates of the center _ companies ready to set off to
fresh patch of soil on their own _ include 50 companies that
account for 2,000 employees, more than $250 million a year in
revenue and several high-profile offerings of stock, including that
of Internet provider MindSpring Enterprises. The $2 million ATDC
budget is a line item in the budget of Georgia Tech, which
administers the money. The center itself is formally a part of the
state's university system with three locations that provide the
soil to about 40 companies.
</P>
<P>
   One recent graduate, communications company Media4, grew from
its three founders to a workforce of about 35 in its three-year
incubation, according to Jim Stratigos, co-founder and president.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which specializes in data compression for video,
audio and multimedia, started with 500 square feet and moved into
larger space as it grew. Most leases of prime real estate in a
crowded area permit much less flexibility than a start-up gets from
the ATDC, Stratigos said. ``They are much more than a landlord, but
that function is extremely valuable.''
</P>
<P>
   Putting fledgling companies with researchers and students is a
formula for constant growth, he said. ``I don't think people
recognize how valuable that is to the high-tech community.''
</P>
<P>
   About 15 of the 50 graduates have been merged or acquired by
larger companies. Only two of the 50 have gone out of business.
</P>
<P>
   Long-time director Dwight Holter, who leaves at the end of this
month, said the key may be in screening candidate companies,
accepting only those entrepreneurs who seem ready to do what it
takes to succeed. ``We will kind of draw the line. If it's the type
of person who wants to talk about it and wants someone else to do
the work, we direct them to the Web site and they can see that we
will not do all the work for them.''
</P>
<P>
   But it also means looking for entrepreneurs who have the right
ideas, he said. ``We are looking for companies that have the
potential for rapid growth.''
</P>
<P>
   Once accepted, a company can look to the center to help in a
number of ways. Holter says the word incubator isn't broad enough,
since it conjures up the image of a place that merely shares its
electricity, phones and staples. With a $2 million budget and about
15 employees, the center offers aid in five basic ways, Holter
said:
</P>
<P>
   _ Finding money to get off the ground. .
</P>
<P>
   _ Making contact with the people who may assist with the steeper
funding needs down the road.
</P>
<P>
   _ Finding employees, since skilled workers can be scarce _ and
hard to recruit.
</P>
<P>
   _ Shaping a business plan.
</P>
<P>
   _ Networking in the industry.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is to send a company hurtling out of the center with
momentum _ already succeeding in the market, in possession of the
financial resources it needs to keep growing, Holter said. ``We
like to think that we are helping to accelerate companies and our
staff people think of themselves as venture catalysts.''
</P>
<P>
   Although its budget is relatively small _ less than what IBM
spends on research every five hours _ the ATDC must justify its
expenditures in economic terms for the region. Holter says that for
each $1 in the state's investment, $12 is returned to the
government as successful companies start paying taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Holter believes the ideal program would be more
extensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to have sort of a research park environment, so
that when a company graduates from our facility, it wouldn't have
to go ... out to the Perimeter. They could retain their proximity
to the university.''
</P>
<P>
   By staying close to Georgia Tech, a company could make use of
part-time student help, as well as having closer contact with
research done by the faculty, he said. ``And if you have that kind
of hot environment, you'd have the kind of buzz that stimulates
mature companies as well as an entrepreneurial company.''
</P>
<P>
   To create that kind of situation would take about $8 million and
a commitment of continued funding for up to a decade, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
