A4580 &Cx1f; kan-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-ARMAGEDDON-KAN &LR;      06-30 0659
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-ARMAGEDDON-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
``ARMAGEDDON'' IS A BLAST THAT SHOULD LAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT W. BUTLER  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Armageddon,'' a sci-fi thriller, is rated PG-13 for sci-fi
disaster action, sensuality and brief language. Running time is 2
hours 24 minutes. Two and a half out of four stars.
</P>
<P>
   For its first hour ``Armageddon'' appears to be that rarest of
animals: a genuinely smart summer blockbuster. If director Michael
Bay and company can't consistently deliver the goods over a
too-long 2-hour 24-minute running time, at least audiences won't
leave the theater thinking they've been insulted.
</P>
<P>
   As was the case in ``Deep Impact,'' a heavenly body (this time
an asteroid the size of Texas) is headed for Earth. If it hits,
nothing will survive. Not even bacteria.
</P>
<P>
   NASA chief Dan Truman (Billy Bob Thornton) realizes the asteroid
can be destroyed only from the inside _ by planting nukes deep
below its surface. He goes looking for the world's best deep-core
drillers and comes across Harry Stamper (Bruce Willis) and his crew
of roughnecks.
</P>
<P>
   When we meet Harry he's on a drilling platform on the South
China Sea, driving golf balls at the Greenpeace protesters bobbing
nearby. He discovers that his daughter, Grace (Liv Tyler), has been
having a secret romance with his protege, A.J. (Ben Affleck). The
ultimate roughneck, Harry strongly disapproves of Grace getting
involved with people like himself.
</P>
<P>
   But personal concerns go on the back burner when the world needs
saving. NASA realizes there's no time to train astronauts for a
drilling job in outer space; would Harry and his crew do the
honors?
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the so-serious ``Deep Impact,'' ``Armageddon'' (which
credits writers Jonathan Hensleigh, J.J. Abrams, Tony Gilroy, Shane
Salerno and Robert Roy Pool) balances its grim end-of-the-world
scenario with some very amusing characters. By now Willis' patented
sardonicism is a movie institution, but here he's surrounded by
rugged _ and amusingly twisted _ individualists who practically
turn him into a straight man.
</P>
<P>
   These range from Rockhound (Steve Buscemi), a genius with a
mile-wide womanizing streak, to Oscar (Owen Wilson), a chatterbox
with a gee-whiz attitude; Max (Ken Campbell), a gentle giant; Bear
(Michael Duncan), a musclebound African-American; and Chick (Will
Patton), a sensitive guy who hopes to redeem himself in the eyes of
his estranged wife and son.
</P>
<P>
   And of course there's A.J., who continues to woo Grace in spite
of Harry's objections.
</P>
<P>
   These guys are unlike anything NASA has ever worked with
(although of course we recognize them from dozens of war movies),
and much of the fun comes in contrasting these cocky wild men with
the spit-and-polish military types training them.
</P>
<P>
   It's in the last hour that ``Armageddon'' runs into problems. In
his films ``Bad Boys'' and ``The Rock'' director Bay exhibited a
flair for action, racking up remarkable body counts. But how do you
film the killing of a small planet?
</P>
<P>
   Bay's answer is to present these outer space sequences with the
same breathless editing and kinetic fury he has brought to
shoot-'em-ups. The results often verge on the incomprehensible and
incoherent and will doubtless leave many viewers feeling worked
over by this daze-inducing barrage of images and special effects.
Not to mention some really blatant emotional manipulation.
</P>
<P>
   None of which is likely to prevent ``Armageddon'' from being a
huge hit, the sort of movie that will sell lots of tickets and lots
of popcorn.
</P>
<P>
   And while nobody goes to movies like ``Armageddon'' for the
acting, a couple performances are really good. In his work here and
in ``Primary Colors,'' Thornton is showing himself to be an actor
of remarkable range, subtlety and humor. Affleck (``Chasing Amy,''
``Good Will Hunting'') establishes himself as a charismatic
presence with the makings of a classic leading man.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-98 1951EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
