<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980630.0305 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 19:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4581 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GATECH-CLOUGH-COX     06-30 1431
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GATECH-CLOUGH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SPECIAL FOCUS: Georgia Tech
 &HT;    (EDS: May run with GATECH-QNA, GATECH-ATDC, GATECH-GTRI)
 &HT;    By Ernest Holsendolph
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Wayne Clough, president of Georgia Institute of
Technology, is a nearly perfect Georgia story. He is a native of
Douglas, Ga., a graduate of Tech, and now the school's first
alumnus-president. He knows the state and its history from the days
when agriculture was king, as well as Tech's past, when its pride
was in turning out engineers.
</P>
<P>
   But Georgia has changed, and fortunately Clough, whose name
rhymes with tough, has had an educational sojourn over the last two
decades that gives him a broader view and a better informed
mission. He wants to speed the state along the new paths toward
technological advances and firmer footing in the high-growth
industries.
</P>
<P>
   Clough, who trained as a civil engineer at Georgia Tech, moved
to northern California in the middle 1960's to earn his doctorate
at the University of California at Berkeley. He witnessed firsthand
much of the collaboration between universities and the cluster of
innovative companies that became known as Silicon Valley, where
theoretical expertise joined entrepreneurship to spark the growth
of a global industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``That critically important and fascinating nexus has instructed
the nation in ways to grow,'' said Clough. ``It is not an accident
that the high-growth spots, including here in the Southeast, are
where good schools and aggressive, growth-minded communities come
together.''
</P>
<P>
   As examples, he cited North Carolina's Research Triangle, where
Duke, North Carolina and North Carolina State universities
collaborate to foster industrial innovation, as well as the growth
area around the University of Texas at Austin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here in Georgia it has been more serendipitous than a matter
of strategy,'' Clough said, ``but we are beginning to put together
strategic plans here for cooperating in ways that can accelerate
growth.''
</P>
<P>
   Continuing, he said, ``we all need to do as Stanford did, and
organize more vigorously, more explicitly, to get results.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stanford example, said Clough, was to foster growth in
technology companies by locating them nearby and stimulating a loop
that has the best academic ideas deployed where needed in high-tech
companies, and communication with the companies about the needs,
challenges and hurdles they face so that long-term research can
address them.
</P>
<P>
   There was a private and public partnership fostered between
Stanford and Berkeley, where the schools put aside their rivalries
to contribute their strengths to the mix.
</P>
<P>
   Such a partnership grew between Duke and the Carolina
universities, he said, and in Atlanta, Georgia Tech and Emory are
embarking on a landmark joint effort to establish on the Tech
campus a center for biomedical and bioengineering studies, as well
as scholarship in environmental problems.
</P>
<P>
   The partnership will bring together Tech's top engineering minds
and Emory's medical and life sciences programs to generate ideas
that can advance learning _ and turn into successful businesses.
Don Giddens has been hired by Tech to head the joint effort.
</P>
<P>
   To emphasize the mission of the biomedical partnership, business
incubators will be located in each of the buildings in the complex,
Clough said.
</P>
<P>
   The other component of the Stanford plan, Clough said, was to
use ``judiciously'' land nearby to locate growth industries so that
interaction with the faculty could be made easier and more
convenient. Thus the foundation was laid for Stanford's association
with Hewlett-Packard, National Semiconductor, Intel and others.
</P>
<P>
   The proximity of Stanford and Hewlett-Packard has been a
spectacularly productive one. The company has earned a worldwide
reputation for its innovation, and Clough said it is no accident
that H-P can boast that some 60 percent of sales last year were
from ideas developed over the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``That, sir, is innovation,'' Clough said. He is proud of the
fact that H-P will be a partner in the microelectronics program
that Tech is growing.
</P>
<P>
   Proximity is a key word in Tech's plans for the future. In terms
of buildings, the plan draws together departments that need to
cooperate in the interest of learning and helping economic
development.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the $140 million BEM Complex for Tech and Emory,
as well as for Medical College of Georgia and others will be housed
in a cluster of buildings for bioengineering and biosciences,
biomedical engineering, environmental science and technology as
well as molecular/materials sciences and engineering.
</P>
<P>
   That cluster of buildings, now under construction on 10 acres of
land, will be steps away from a new $40 million advance computing
technology building. That building will be adjacent to the existing
quarters for the college of computing.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have learned is that today's major problems are seldom
within the sphere of one department, but are interdisciplinary in
nature,'' said Clough, ``and so we need to encourage a new level of
cooperation between the departments.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Tech, a distinctly urban school, with the backdrop of
the downtown and Midtown office towers as part of its environment,
does not have Stanford's wide open spaces.
</P>
<P>
   However, school officials have plans to develop land across
North Avenue southwest of the main campus. They are also looking to
land across the Downtown Connector artery for future development of
a center to train executives, a site that would not require them to
come to the campus where parking is scarce.
</P>
<P>
   ``And though the Atlantic Steel site (north of the campus) may
be devoted to retailing, we hope some of the land can be devoted to
small high-tech enterprises,'' Clough said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be very desirable to get relatively high-paying jobs
there, hopefully with suitable downtown housing for those who work
there,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   The teamwork needed to foster economic development encompasses
not only cooperative centers of higher learning, but also
partnership between academics and public policy-makers, including a
strong state component through such organizations as the Georgia
Research Alliance, Clough said.
</P>
<P>
   As for Tech's plan, the school must redouble its efforts to be
more of a research institution, a process that began in the early
1970's under President Joe Petit, another former Stanford man. In
so doing, he said, the school can tap into plans by industry to
farm out more long-term research, and also qualify for new research
dollars for health and other high priority areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We also want to encourage more of an entrepreneurial spirit
among our students,'' Clough said.
</P>
<P>
   ``At Stanford, where I taught for a decade, engineering students
thought of themselves as potential entrepreneurs. Some do so at
Tech, but many aspire to the world of work in the corporate ranks.
That's fine, but we need to achieve more of a balance.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Tech will be recruiting its own alumni for such
important roles as venture capitalists.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll hope to align ourselves more closely with people like
Charles Moseley and Bill Green, who have proven their skill in
those areas.
</P>
<P>
   Charles D. Moseley Jr., founder and partner of Noro-Moseley, is
widely recognized for his work as a venture capitalist.
</P>
<P>
   Moseley said Clough's knowledge of technology is especially
welcome. And clearly it will be helpful to both Moseley and Tech to
maintain close ties for the benefit of companies in the Tech
incubator programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wayne's representation and Tech's representation will be a big
help in attracting technology companies,'' Mosely said in an
interview.
</P>
<P>
   Green, a partner in Craven, Green and Wahlen, is a prime mover
in one of the busiest investment firms in the Southeast and has
assembled a $278 million buyout fund the Wall Street Journal says
is the largest of its kind in the region.
</P>
<P>
   Clough not only has the personal expertise but also the contacts
that could aid Tech in its growing role as a stimulator of economic
growth.
</P>
<P>
   He serves locally on the executive committee of Central Atlanta
Progress, the board of directors of the Atlanta Chamber of
Commerce, as a trustee of the Georgia Research Alliance and
nationally as a trustee of the National Council of Competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
   ''So long as we work in partnership,'' said Clough, ''I think we
can advance toward this community's dreams to excel in
technological innovation.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
