<DOCNO> NYT19980630.0306 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 19:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4582 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GATECH-GTRI-COX     06-30 1013
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GATECH-GTRI-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wearable computers present opportunities and challenges
 &HT;    (EDS: May run with GATECH-CLOUGH, GATECH-QNA, GATECH ATDC)
 &HT;    By Anne Rochell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Coming to a grocery store near you: Chicken inspected
by Robocop.
</P>
<P>
   Armed with computers attached to their waists and heads, poultry
workers soon will be able to inspect chickens and transmit
information without removing their rubber gloves, touching a
clipboard or leaving the plant floor.
</P>
<P>
   A small laboratory at the Georgia Tech Research Institute, an
applied research arm of the Georgia Institute of Technology, is
designing the hands-free, wearable computer system. At least two
Georgia poultry plants are interested in it; one, Cagle's in South
Georgia, may turn their inspectors into cyborgs within the year.
</P>
<P>
   ''We didn't invent the idea of a wearable computer, but we have
worked on the question of what these are useful for,'' said Chris
Thompson, senior research engineer in the Intelligent Machines
Branch of GTRI. His lab, called the Multimedia Information in
Mobile Environments, or MIME, has been working on wearable
computers for several years. ''We study the human issues, like
comfort, and how to present information on the monitor without
distracting them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Georgia Tech Research Institute is tied to the Georgia
Institute of Technology, but not involved in instruction. Most of
GTRI's research is for the military and the defense industry, but
the MIME lab, while sometimes engaged in defense work, also
supports manufacturing industries.
</P>
<P>
   The wearable computer system has a headset worn like a miner's
lamp around the crown of the head, outfitted with a computer
monitor that slides over one eye, a camera lens, and a microphone
for voice-recognition data input. The actual brain of the system
has as much power as a notebook computer, and is worn around the
waist. Optional is a keyboard strapped like a biker's glove around
one wrist.
</P>
<P>
   A clean solution
</P>
<P>
   The wearable computer solves a lot of literally messy problems
in the chicken industry. Poultry plants are wet, greasy places, and
taking notes on a clipboard forces a worker measuring temperature
or looking for disease to pull off and on rubber gloves every time
he writes. These systems have voice recognition, so a worker can
talk into a microphone attached to a visor. The computer screen
slides in front of one eye, leaving one eye free to look at breasts
and thighs.
</P>
<P>
   ''But the real issue is data is accumulating on clipboards all
over the plant, and it has to be taken to the office and put on a
computer, probably not until the end of a shift,'' said J. Craig
Wyvill, who heads the Agricultural Technology Research Program at
GTRI. ''It takes a while for a supervisor to notice a trend, for
example, of contamination. And with the new food safety
regulations, there will be more data and more problems that will
have to be dealt with quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Progress isn't cheap
</P>
<P>
   The system, like any new technology, is costly: Although the
hardware is commercially available and would cost about $5,000 per
system, the software will cost tens of thousands to develop and
use, Wyvill said.
</P>
<P>
   Wyvill's office, which is state-sponsored and responsible for
supporting the various food industries in Georgia, is working with
MIME to bring the wearable computer system to other industries.
</P>
<P>
   ''The entire food industry is becoming very
information-intensive,'' Wyvill said.
</P>
<P>
   And the computers are ideal for on-the-job training, Wyvill
said. Software could be designed to update workers on any changes
in the machines they maintain, for example. That possibility peaked
the interest of Delta Airlines, which is looking into wearable
computers that carry electronic airplane manuals.
</P>
<P>
   ''An airline's most expensive problems occur when a plane is at
the gate and causes delays,'' Wyvill explained. With a wearable
computer, a maintenance crew would not have to sprint back to the
office to look up repair information.
</P>
<P>
   There are military applications for the wearable computer.
Already the Army, independent of Georgia Tech, has been testing
computers soldiers could wear on the battlefield.
</P>
<P>
   No one is sure where the idea for wearable computers was born,
or where it is headed. So far it has been the stuff of science
fiction _ in ''Robocop,'' a 1987 movie, the half-human cyborg
lawman wore a computer that fused together the virtual and real
worlds.
</P>
<P>
   GTRI is one of a handful of institutions developing wearable
computers; none of the major computer and software companies such
as IBM or Microsoft are investing much time in them.
</P>
<P>
   Its day will come
</P>
<P>
   But interest is growing. Another school at Georgia Tech is
working on clothing that has computers sewn into the fabric, for
possible use on the battlefield to measure a wounded soldier's
vital signs. Scientists at the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology are researching wearable computers for everyday use.
They envision computers as comfortable as a favorite pair of blue
jeans, that allow people to exchange e-mail while walking down the
street, or to have non-stop access to the Internet. The second
conference on wearable computer technology will be this fall in
Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   But widespread use is years in the future. The only real-world
use of wearable computers such as the one GTRI is developing is at
a Ford Motor Co. plant, where some workers wear them on the
assembly line. Cagle's may be one of the first industries in the
country to use wearable computer technology. Claxton Chicken
considered having their inspectors wear them, but decided instead
to install computers on the plant floor.
</P>
<P>
   ''We thought we would try that before we made a serious
investment,'' said Marcus Boyd, coordinator of the Hazard Analysis
and Critical Control Points program at Claxton Chicken. ''We were
worried about the expense, and the discomfort workers might have
wearing a computer.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
