u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GATECH-QNA-COX     06-30 0856
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GATECH-QNA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tech's leader wants to compete with pace-setters in economic
development
 &HT;    By Ernest Holsendolph
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Wayne Clough, president of Georgia Institute of
Technology, speaks with the precision and frankness one expects
from a man of science and engineering.
</P>
<P>
   When he speaks of his alma mater, which he now heads as the
first alumnus-president, his expressions are direct, analytical and
unsentimental. The school has a long ways to go, he said, to match
the top competition in the United States and, more importantly, his
lofty expectations and aspirations. He has set the competitive bar
very high.
</P>
<P>
   It may take time, he said, a lot of time, but he wants to catch
MIT, Stanford and Berkeley, the pace-setters, the schools who wrote
the book when it comes to strategies in economic development.
</P>
<P>
   As a graduate student at Berkeley and a teacher at Stanford, he
knows the competition.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some of his comments on that subject and others in a
recent interview:
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where did you get your ideas about the roles of colleges and
businesses in fostering economic development?
</P>
<P>
   A: I learned much of it in the Bay area, where I was privileged
to witness firsthand how Stanford and Berkeley collaborated to help
build Silicon Valley. I met and got to know Fred Terman, dean of
engineering at Stanford, who brought to the campus his experience
at working with other scientists during World War II to help the
war effort.
</P>
<P>
   He came to the campus and succeeded in simulating that kind of
joint effort, that sense of team work, in the mission to develop
technology in the area around Stanford. Two of his students were a
guy named Hewlett and another named Packard.
</P>
<P>
   Q:What were the essential ingredients to the success by Terman
and his Stanford collaborators?
</P>
<P>
   A: They worked with some of the best minds in science and
engineering at Stanford and Berkeley in the effort to foster ideas
for the technology industry. And the intensity of that
collaboration not only fostered exciting companies, but also
fostered work in science and math at the highest levels because so
many people wanted to be a part of the excitement.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Petit was there too, during the same period, and that's why,
when he became president of Georgia Tech in the early 1970s, he
began to focus the school on research.
</P>
<P>
   Q:Were there any other secrets to the success of Silicon Valley?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes, land. Stanford had, as a part of its original holdings,
some 12,000 acres of land nearby or adjacent to the campus that
allowed companies to form and keep constant communication with
professors and other experts on the campus. That's why companies
like Hewlett-Packard, Intel and National Semiconductor got such a
good start and maintained momentum.
</P>
<P>
   Q:Well, we certainly don't have that land advantage, do we?
</P>
<P>
   A:No, we don't. More seriously, we also lack the strong
departments in pure science that have proved so beneficial, so much
a part of the success of schools like the Stanford-Berkeley team,
and MIT also. If you look at us as well as Emory and Georgia, all
rising schools, you find relative weakness in the sciences. It's
all part of our region's misunderstanding of the importance of
basic science.
</P>
<P>
   Q:Why such a lapse, and has it been a factor in the lag in
economic development in the region until recently?
</P>
<P>
   A:We have focused, with success, on agricultural research and on
the development of engineers, but we have not fully appreciated the
relative importance of the sciences as the foundation for
advancement in world class technology.
</P>
<P>
   Q:How do you turn that around?
</P>
<P>
   A:You do it with collaboration, just as Stanford did. And you
need the collaboration not only between schools, but also between
science and engineering departments within schools. Moreover, you
need collaboration between the educational establishment and the
schools at the highest levels in the form of distance learning
facilities that allow industry research departments to link
directly with the best minds on campuses. We need to continue the
important linkages between schools and public policy bodies like
the Georgia Alliance, and between industry and state leaders who
hopefully will follow Gov. Zell Miller's fine example of
leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Q:Schools like Georgia Tech have an important resource in their
alumni, and there must be a role for them, right?
</P>
<P>
   A: Absolutely. Many of our best alumni are at work here in
Georgia and on the West Coast and elsewhere, and many are looking
for a chance to link with Georgia Tech and with Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Many are experts as venture capitalists, skilled in spotting
initiatives that pay off, and we will look to them for that help
even more in the future than in the past. I think the secret for
success, just as in the Bay area, is for all of us to get in touch
and stay in touch with the aspirations of the community. That is
the best way to establish the kind of cooperation and teamwork that
will serve us in the coming years.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
