<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Delta to beef up fleet with used jets until new ones delivered
from Boeing
 &HT;    (EDS: Runs with DELTA01)
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Delta Air Lines has dipped into the used airplane market to buy
14 jets to help expand its fleet while awaiting deliveries of new
aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen of the planes are Boeing 737-300s, a short-haul
workhorse. Nine were previously flown by Germania, a European
carrier, while four come from Western Pacific Airlines, a defunct
discount carrier based in Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   Delta also is buying a 767 widebody from Asiana, a Korean
carrier.
</P>
<P>
   Delta spokeswoman Laura Gillig said the average age of the used
planes is 10.3 years, slightly lower than the average for Delta's
fleet.
</P>
<P>
   The airline usually buys new airplanes, and it placed a massive
order with Boeing last year. But Gillig said the lag time until
deliveries prompted the carrier to seek used jets in the meantime.
</P>
<P>
   The first planes under the Boeing order, updated models of the
737, are to arrive this year. Next year Delta will take delivery of
new 777s, which will become the biggest planes in its fleet.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, Delta confirmed it will eliminate up to 200 jobs in
Frankfurt, Germany, by hiring contractors to perform ground
handling and other tasks. The move follows Delta's decision last
year to dismantle a Frankfurt connecting hub it bought from Pan Am
in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
