<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Southern plays role in two Asian power plant projects
 &HT;    By Matthew C. Quinn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Southern Co. is participating in two new major
electricity projects in China and Thailand, the first big Asian
deals announced by the Atlanta-based company since it took over a
Hong Kong-based power company 18 months ago.
</P>
<P>
   The company Monday announced its participation in a $500 million
power plant project in China's Shanxi Province and Tuesday outlined
an agreement to take a 28 percent stake in a major plant in
Thailand.
</P>
<P>
   Consolidated Electric Power Asia, the Hong Kong-based
independent power company Southern acquired for $2.3 billion, is
taking a minority stake in both projects. Company officials
emphasized both projects are in early stages of development.
</P>
<P>
   Southern said plans call for the Thai plant to be developed by a
consortium that also includes Saha Union Public Co., Thailand's
biggest garment producer; Tomen Corp., a leading Japanese trading
company; and Imatran Voima Oy, an international power company based
in Finland.
</P>
<P>
   Southern purchased its interest from Saha Union, which reduced
its stake from 51 percent to 10 percent. Southern is paying $100
million in cash and financing an additional $236 million with bank
loans and bonds. IVO will also hold 28 percent and Tomen, 34
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The 1,400-megawatt coal-fired power plantwill be in Prachuab
Kirikhan, along Thailand's western coast about 270 miles from
Bangkok. Financing is expected to be arranged by this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Construction would then begin next year and the plant would come
on-line in 2002. The plant will supply power to Thailand's
government utility under a 25-year power purchase agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Thailand was the first Asian country last year to suffer a
currency crisis that has now swept across the region. Thailand's
currency devaluation made the deal a better value for Southern.
</P>
<P>
   The company's new China deal involves construction of a
600-megawatt coal-fired plant 280 miles southwest of Beijing in
Shanxi Province, China's coal-mining region.
</P>
<P>
   The plant will be built near coal mines to alleviate railroad
bottlenecks in transporting coal long distances. It is one of the
first large-scale projects to be sponsored by China's coal
industry.
</P>
<P>
   A partnership that includes Southern and Johnston Development
Co., headed by former Sen. J. Bennett Johnston (D-La.), will own 49
percent of the $500 million project. Shanxi Enhua, which includes
the the Xishan Coal Mining Bureau and Shanxi Provincial Power Co.,
will hold 51 percent. Site preparation begins next year.
</P>
<P>
   An agreement in principle to build the plant was signed Monday
by Southern and its partners in the Great Hall of the People in
Beijing. The ceremony was separate from a raft of agreements signed
in conjunction with President Clinton's state visit. The Thai deal
was signed last week.
</P>
<P>
   CEPA already operates a power plant in China's Guangdong
Province under anagreement that expires in 2016. The company ceded
management of a sister plant to local entities last October.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
