<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOW-ANALYSIS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Market cools down as weather heats up
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The stock market reached the midpoint of 1998 on Tuesday with
the busiest New York Stock Exchange session of the year and a mixed
bag of wins and losses. Big Board volume hit 758.8 million shares
as traders scurried to settle waves of end-of-quarter orders.
</P>
<P>
   While the Dow Jones industrial average was closing out the
quarter with a loss, the Russell 2000, which includes smaller
stocks, and the Nasdaq composite rose. It was a fitting close to a
half-year that A.G. Edwards &AMP; Sons strategist Alfred Goldman
described as a manic-depressive period in the market _ a
first-quarter with ``manic'' gains and a second quarter with
``depressive'' losses.
</P>
<P>
   Indexes that posted first-quarter gains of 11 to about 17
percent suffered declines during the second quarter ranging from 5
percent for the Big Board blue chip sector to 12 percent for
smaller-stock barometers. That left the Dow with a second-quarter
gain of just 1.7 percent after a climb of 11.3 percent in the first
three months of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts attributed the dramatic turnaround to the perception
that Asia's financial crisis will slow the U.S. economy enough to
put a dent in profit growth.
</P>
<P>
   But Asia's depressed economy also gets some credit for
restraining the Federal Reserve from raising short-term interest
rates, as some analysts have anticipated following reports of
still-strong economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is the Fed expected to alter that policy at its meeting that
began Tuesday and ends today. Inflation is still too low to justify
higher interest rates, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   Investor anxiety about Asia was also strong enough to create an
atypical situation between stocks and bonds: the sharp drop in
30-year Treasury yields in the second quarter failed to stimulate
stock buying, as it ususally does.
</P>
<P>
   Falling yields make bonds less attractive as an alternative to
stocks, but this time stocks continued to decline as Treasury
yields dropped to historic lows.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the stock market remains manic/depressive in the second
half depends on what happens in Japan, according to analysts who
see that nation _ with the world's second strongest economy _ as
the linchpin of Asia's financial rescue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until the Japanese government takes decisive action to support
the yen and permanently cut taxes, the Asian markets can expect
troubled waters,'' said John K. Lynch, director of investment
strategy for Interstate/Johnson Lane.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the concern about Asia, mainstream analysts discount
the likelihood that the stock market will suffer anything more than
a correction _ commonly defined as a decline of roughly 10 percent
_ in the second half. They see neither a recession in the economy
nor a bear market in stocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good thing was that the (second-quarter) corrections
worked out excesses in the market and created buying
opportunities,'' said Goldman. There's a strong belief on Wall
Street that the bull market will not end as long as the economy
continues to expand. In the first quarter, the economy grew at a
torrid 5.4 percent annual rate without making inflation worse.
</P>
<P>
   Most analysts believe that growth rate slowed sharply in the
second quarter, but that the economy will continue to expand enough
to boost profits and keep the bull market alive.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
