<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 19:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4589 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WOLF-COX     06-30 0731
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOLF-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fox to be bought by Wolf By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Wolf Camera has agreed to acquire Eastman Kodak's
450-store Fox Photo chain, which will more than double the
Atlanta-based retailer's size at the outset and catapult it to a
near-tie with the country's largest specialty photo retailer.
</P>
<P>
   With a post-purchase count of 790 stores, Wolf closes in on Ritz
Camera Centers, a Beltsville, Md.-retailer that has about 810
stores.
</P>
<P>
   Wolf, whose headquarters is in Alpharetta, Ga., is expected to
announce the transaction today. It is expected to close in
September. Terms of the Fox deal were not disclosed, but industry
sources, characterizing it as a ``fire sale,'' expected a price tag
far below Kodak's $110 million stake.
</P>
<P>
   Privately held Wolf does not disclose financial data, but
industry estimates peg annual revenue at about $260 million.
Revenue figures are not available for Fox Photo, but the typical
mini-lab store similar to the Fox format generates about $250,000
in annual revenue, according to the Photo Marketing Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the biggest moment of growth in our 24-year history,''
said President and Chief Executive Chuck Wolf. ``We used to say we
were a coast-to-coast company, but now we're truly national.'' Fox
Photo, which also operates stores under the names of CPI Photo and
Proex, spans 25 states and Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Wolf enters 19 new states and 50 cities with the Fox purchase,
in addition to doubling or tripling its presence in several
existing markets.
</P>
<P>
   As many as 120 employees at Fox's corporate headquarters in St.
Louis may move to Alpharetta. ``We're talking to each one of them
to find out the best fit,'' Wolf said. The metro Atlanta market,
Wolf's biggest with 65 stores, is not affected by the purchase of
Fox Photo, which has seen several ownership changes in recent
years. Wolf bought 20 Fox Photo stores in Atlanta in 1996 as part
of a 50-store purchase from St. Louis-based CPI Corp., then Fox's
corporate parent. That same year, Kodak acquired a 51 percent stake
in the chain from CPI and bought the remaining interest in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Kodak initially bought the Fox chain as a laboratory for testing
new products and pumping up the Kodak name. It was also a vehicle
for the company's Image Center self-service photo-manipulation
machines.
</P>
<P>
   But it was difficult for the giant manufacturer to manage the
retail end of photofinishing, which remains an intimate, customer
service-oriented business. And that's the bread-and-butter of Wolf,
which has built a high-profile advertising campaign on the message,
``Our expertise is free.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Wolf is one of the most aggressive marketers in the
business,'' said Jerry Johnson, Kodak's vice president and general
manager of consumer imaging for the United States and Canada.
``Wolf Camera is capable and qualified to take the Fox Photo stores
and grow their business.''
</P>
<P>
   While Chuck Wolf doesn't have specific plans yet for the Fox
Photo stores, he said he expects to relocate many stores to bigger
sites. The chain generates most of its business through film
processing and does not carry camera and photo equipment, which
presents a growth opportunity for Wolf.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any buyer would have to prune and consolidate this chain, but
it gets Wolf into markets where Fox has attractive leases and an
opportunity to upgrade,'' said Donald Becker, former CEO of Fox
Photo before it was sold to Kodak. While some stores have been
unprofitable, others _ such as the group in Hawaii _ are strong
performers, said Becker, now an industry consultant.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition will also give Wolf a new service line through
the Proex stores, which specialize in portraits. Those stores are
based in Minneapolis, but Wolf said he'll consider rolling out the
service to other markets.
</P>
<P>
   The timing of the purchase was good for Wolf, which recently
moved into new corporate headquarters that can support 1,000
stores. Wolf already has surpassed its 600-store goal with the
acquisition and shows no sign of easing up.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the next few months, we'll make a few more acquisitions,''
said Wolf, who noted plans to open 50 stores internally this year
as well. ``We've got the infrastructure and systems in place that
make it a lot easier to do this.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
