<HEADER>
A4591 &Cx1f; kan-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-WILDE-REVIEW-KA     06-30 0708
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-WILDE-REVIEW-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MOST QUOTABLE MAN COMES OUT IN THE `WILDE' WEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT W. BUTLER  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Wilde,'' a biography, is rated R for strong sexuality and
language. Running time is 1 hour 56 minutes. Two and a half out of
four stars.
</P>
<P>
   For moviegoers who know little about the Victorian wit,
playwright (``The Importance of Being Earnest'') and homosexual
icon Oscar Wilde, the new screen biography from England should
prove an enlightening introduction.
</P>
<P>
   Actor Stephen Fry (familiar from public TV's ``Jeeves &AMP;
Wooster,'' among other hilarious imports) gives an utterly
believable performance as the flamboyant Irish aesthete, and his
world has been carefully evoked by director Brian Gilbert (``Tom
and Viv'') and screenwriter Julian Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   But a certain level of dissatisfaction creeps in when the viewer
knows a thing or two about the subject.
</P>
<P>
   This film takes a sort of formal ``Cliffs Notes'' approach to
Wilde that would be suitable for the classroom if not for its
matter-of-fact depiction of homosexual life and love in the 1890s.
For those already versed in Wilde, the film seems just a bit flabby
and unfocused. Instead of asking us to view his life with a
particular attitude or from a fresh perspective, it recycles the
usual facts.
</P>
<P>
   The film opens in the Wild West of Leadville, Colo., where the
touring Wilde descends into a silver mine and delivers unto the
shirtless young diggers a lecture on the Renaissance silversmith
Benvenuto Cellini. Clearly he's inspired by all this sweaty young
flesh.
</P>
<P>
   But at this point, Oscar hasn't admitted his homosexuality. He
marries the sweet, unassertive Constance (Jennifer Ehle),
explaining to his friends that ``I do need an audience.'' There's
genuine affection in the marriage _ at least enough to produce two
sons _ but one cannot shake the feeling that Oscar regards his wife
as a sort of life-sized doll; he even selects all her clothes.
</P>
<P>
   The arrival of a family friend, Canadian Robert Ross (Michael
Sheen), forces Oscar to admit something unusual is going on. The
two men are drawn together, although for Ross it will be a case of
unrequited love.
</P>
<P>
   Once he begins indulging his sexual fantasies, Oscar goes whole
hog, frequenting gay bordellos and fixating on Lord Alfred Douglas,
who will become the love of his life, as well as the instrument of
his downfall.
</P>
<P>
   As played by Jude Law, Lord Alfred (or ``Bosie,'' as Oscar
affectionately refers to him) combines a rock star's leonine
sexuality with the petulant selfishness of a rich brat. Which
indeed he is.
</P>
<P>
   When the writer observes that Bosie's spendthrift ways are
ruining him, the young man throws a tantrum, accuses Oscar of being
middle-class and proclaims that ``no gentleman has the slightest
idea of what his bank balance is.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the libertine Bosie is as incapable of fidelity; it
becomes Oscar's sad lot to sit on the sidelines while his beloved
plays the field.
</P>
<P>
   And it is Bosie who brings about Oscar's downfall. Bosie's
father is the blunt, sadistic Marquis of Queensberry (Tom Wilkinson
of ``The Full Monty,'' giving a fierce performance that melds
intellect and malevolence). When the marquis accuses Oscar of being
a ``somdomite,'' the vengeful Bosie urges Oscar to sue his father
for slander.
</P>
<P>
   But in the courtroom Oscar's own sexuality becomes the issue,
resulting finally in a two-year prison term at hard labor that
would break the writer's body and spirit.
</P>
<P>
   Wilde was, of course, one of the most quotable men who ever
lived, and Mitchell's screenplay has nearly as many famous bon mots
as genuine dialogue. The Oscarisms are everywhere:
</P>
<P>
   ``Robbie is a Canadian. You can tell by his youth.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I shall die a Catholic. I couldn't possible live as one.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's perfectly monstrous the way people say things behind
one's back that are absolutely true.''
</P>
<P>
   While much of ``Wilde'' seems emotionally remote and curiously
denatured, the film does achieve a sort of grandeur in its final
passages. Only when we witness Oscar's suffering in prison are we
genuinely moved; the pain of this gentle soul crushed by
institutionalized hypocrisy is achingly real.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
