<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 19:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4593 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FRENCH-GENDER-ART-NYT     06-30 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRENCH-GENDER-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARIS JOURNAL: NO MATTER HOW FEMININE, `LE MINISTRE' IS ALWAYS
MASCULINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: a graphic has been sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.)  
 (JT)  
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ You say ``Madame le ministre,'' I say ``Madame la
ministre,'' the French government decreed on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Let's call the whole thing off, the Academie Francaise thundered
on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The French Academy, a male bastion founded by Cardinal Richelieu
in 1635, is positively beside itself about proposals like making
``ministre,'' which is a masculine noun, feminine when the minister
in question is a woman.
</P>
<P>
   That is one of the changes the Socialist-led government has
proposed to recognize the increasingly visible role women play in
all walks of French life.
</P>
<P>
   It is an idea that has been suggested before and that both sides
have weighed in on before. The major stumbling block for the
Academy remains the requirement that the rules of French grammar
would have to be bent. All French nouns are either masculine or
feminine, a rule that is jealously watched over by the Academy's
guardians of linguistic orthodoxy, who are known as ``immortals.''
</P>
<P>
   Only 2 of the 39 members of the Academy are women, and the
Perpetual Secretary, Maurice Druon, whose tongue is as formidable
as his white mane and his walking stick, left little doubt where he
stood in an interview with the conservative daily Le Figaro
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Socialist ideology is making France go to pot, and the French
language with it,'' Druon said. ``The Academy in charge of this
language will meet this week to see if it is possible to appeal to
the Council of State or the Constitutional Council, because the
appropriation of a post by the person exercising it is contrary to
the principles of equality contained in the constitution.''
</P>
<P>
   Ministers come and ministers go, but ``ministre'' will always be
masculine if Druon and his colleagues have their way. Since they
often heap ridicule on what the ``politically correct'' movement in
the United States does to the English language and fiercely defend
French against all English or American linguistic inroads, they
seem doubly determined never to let it happen here.
</P>
<P>
   Rallying to the cause, another immortal, Jean Dutourd, delivered
himself of a sentence that it is safe to say no American male
chauvinist, however hard-boiled, would ever let traverse his lips
these days, accusing Prime Minister Lionel Jospin of linguistic
travesty:
</P>
<P>
   ``These are the results of polygamy by Jospin, who has
surrounded himself with sultanesses and, to please his harem, has
resurfaced an old idea,'' Dutourd said.
</P>
<P>
   Jospin has five women in his Cabinet, and he explained to them
and their nine male ministerial colleagues four months ago that one
of his predecessors, Laurent Fabius, had tried in 1986 to feminize
titles and job descriptions where appropriate, but to little
effect.
</P>
<P>
   Jospin vowed to do better, appointing a commission to study the
problem and pledging to start right away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even Jacques Chirac now calls me ``Madame la ministre,''
Dominique Voynet, the environment minister, said recently,
referring to the 65-year-old conservative politician who is
France's president. ``Older people resist, but you can understand
that,'' Mrs. Voynet, a scientist by training, said tolerantly.
</P>
<P>
   Bravely, two of her colleagues, Claude Allegre, the (masculine)
minister of education, research and technology, and Segolene Royal,
his (feminine) deputy, circulated a memorandum to educational
establishments on Monday explaining how to feminize grammatically
masculine titles or professions.
</P>
<P>
   An assistant of feminine gender becomes ``une assistante,'' a
word already commonly used in a society where 11.5 million of the
26 million people in the labor force are women. But in the
professions, where integration of the sexes has progressed more
slowly, an architect who is a woman can now, at least in academic
circles, be called ``une architecte.''
</P>
<P>
   The circular gives its blessing to calling a supervisor ``une
chef de service'' if she is a woman, though ``chef'' is
grammatically masculine, and a doctor who is female becomes ``une
medecin.''
</P>
<P>
   Feminizing the noun to make it ``une medicine'' would turn the
doctor into a drug, but other words don't pose the same problem.
Thus a storekeeper can perfectly well be ``une magasiniere,'' a
laboratory technician ``une technicienne'' and a functionary ``une
agente.''
</P>
<P>
   New, perhaps, to this kind of thing, the French ministers think
nothing of calling a female inspector ``une inspectrice'' or a
teacher ``une institutrice,'' particularly since, as they pointed
out, most teachers in France are women. And though French-speaking
purists refuse to say ``software,'' preferring ``logiciel''
instead, the education ministry says transforming ``programmateur''
to ``programmatrice'' where appropriate is OK.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eliminating all sex discrimination remains a general legal
principle for which jurisprudence has for some years been insisting
on constant respect,'' the two ministers said in their circular to
school and university administrators. ``We attach particular
importance to effectuating these measures and will insist that they
be applied scrupulously in texts submitted for our signature. We
invite you to show the same vigilance in the services under your
jurisdiction.''
</P>
<P>
   Anticipating the Academy's attack, the ministry argued that
``mayoresses'' existed in France in the 13th century, and that
brave women like Joan of Arc were not called ``commandant'' but
``commandante'' in the 15th. And in 1701, the ministry said,
somebody even dared to use the word ``academicienne.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
