<HEADER>
A4596 &Cx1f; kan-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-LAND-REVIEW-KAN     06-30 0563
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-LAND-REVIEW-KAN </SLUG>
  
 `LAND GIRLS' is `WOMAN'S PICTURE'  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT W. BUTLER  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Land Girls,'' a romantic drama, is rated R for some
sexuality. Running time is 1 hour 52 minutes. Two out of four
stars.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt it's the height of political incorrectness to label a
movie a ``woman's picture,'' but the British ``The Land Girls''
makes it almost impossible to avoid the phrase.
</P>
<P>
   Except for its frankness in sexual matters, this romantic drama
from director David Leland could quite easily have been made during
World War II as a tribute to the members of the Women's Land Army,
whose members took up agricultural work, filling in for the farm
workers in the military.
</P>
<P>
   Leland's screenplay (based on Angela Huth's novel) centers on
three young women who give up their city jobs for the mud and muck
of a Dorset farm.
</P>
<P>
   They are Pru (Anna Friel), a hairdresser with a working-class
outlook and an aggressive approach to sex; Ag (Rachel Weisz), a
very proper academic sort who at 26 is still a virgin; and Stella
(Catherine McCormack), who narrates the tale and who asked to be
posted to Dorset because it's near the naval base where her
upper-class fiance is stationed.
</P>
<P>
   Their hosts are Farmer Lawrence (Tom Georgeson) and his wife
(Maureen O'Brien). Lawrence is a crusty soul who resents being told
by the government how to use his land and who huffs that the three
young women in his attic regard farm work as ``just an excuse for a
lark.'' Mrs. Lawrence is a sweet, unpretentious woman who seems to
be working herself into an early grave.
</P>
<P>
   Also on hand is their son, Joe (Steven Mackintosh), who talks of
enlisting as an airman but never quite gets around to it. Though
he's engaged to a local girl serving in the military, Joe is the
only young man around and so becomes the target of Pru's sexual
wiles _ not that he needs much enticing.
</P>
<P>
   Before the film is over Joe will have had relationships with all
three women. If Pru wants only a roll in the hay (literally), the
uptight Ag sees him as a sort of amorous teacher. She's fallen for
a sincere Canadian serviceman, and decides that she needs some
sexual instruction so as not to disappoint her true love when the
big moment comes. Joe is the logical _ indeed, only _ choice.
</P>
<P>
   Finally there's Stella, who observes these antics with wry
amusement. But as it gradually dawns on her that her naval officer
isn't the right fellow after all, the earnest but conflicted Joe
starts looking better.
</P>
<P>
   As a re-creation of a time and place, ``The Land Girls'' is just
about perfect. The patriotic attitudes of the young women, the days
of milking, plowing, planting and harvesting, the near-constant
rain _ all of it seems remarkably authentic. To the extent that
it's a tribute to the thousands of women who grabbed a pitchfork on
behalf of the war effort, ``The Land Girls'' works quite nicely.
</P>
<P>
   As drama, though, it's pretty anemic, largely because Leland has
failed to give us fully rounded characters. These women lack
complexity; their motives and actions are unexplained and seem
aimed at fulfilling the story's narrative goals rather than at
revealing who these people really are.
</P>
<P>
   The result is a film beautifully photographed by Henry Braham
whose drama is never as fine as its striking images.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-98 1953EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
