<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VENUS WILLIAMS MOVES INTO WIMBLEDON QUARTERFINALS  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBIN FINN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ Venus Williams, spared the vexing task of
taking on her brash little sister in the Round of 16, made good on
her previously ``broken promises'' to attempt some snazzy
serve-and-volley maneuvers Tuesday during a 6-3, 6-1 dissection of
47th-ranked Virginia Ruano Pascual. The seventh-seeded Williams
reached her first Wimbledon quarterfinal by unveiling a complex
grass-court game, including 24 winners on 29 net approaches and the
conversion of six of eight break chances from the backcourt.
</P>
<P>
   The power brokers were out in full force as clear skies
prevailed Tuesday and a full schedule of quarterfinalists in men's
and women's singles was determined. All 16 winners are scheduled to
whittle themselves into eight semifinalists on Wednesday if the
weather complies. The full schedule produced few surprises.
</P>
<P>
   Only Williams' style against Pascual, the Spaniard who drove out
16-year-old Serena Williams in the previous round, was surprising.
``I was more diligent in coming in today and actually attacking,''
said Williams, 18. ``I think that with every match I'm able to play
smarter.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams will need all her precocious smarts when she faces
29-year-old Jana Novotna, a two-time Wimbledon runner-up whose
experience on grass outshines that of all contemporaries except the
seven-time champion Steffi Graf.
</P>
<P>
   ``Experience plays a huge role in this,'' said the third-seeded
Novotna following her 6-2, 6-3 dismissal of 10th-seeded Irina
Spirlea.
</P>
<P>
   There were no alterations to the grass-court playmaking
epitomized by top-seeded Pete Sampras against 117th-ranked
Sebastian Grosjean. Sampras, the defending champion, stayed on
course to collect a fifth Wimbledon crown and an 11th Grand Slam
title by winning 50 of his 55 prowls to the net. All told, Sampras
required just 14 aces to tame the baseline-bound qualifier, 6-3,
6-4, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was nice to start a match and complete a match in one
day,'' said Sampras, who next faces a formidable server in
Australia's resurgent Mark Philippoussis. Sampras leads their
rivalry by 4-2 and beat the Australian here in 1996. But
Philippoussis entered this event with a new attitude and a new
haircut after almost cutting Wimbledon from his schedule because
his game had turned anemic. Tuesday, he reached his first Grand
Slam quarterfinal with a 5-7, 6-1, 6-3, 6-3 comeback against Jason
Stoltenberg.
</P>
<P>
   Even the tempestuous Goran Ivanisevic kept his nose to the
grindstone. The 14th-seeded Croat turned in a documentary-style 7-6
(7-5), 6-3, 3-6, 7-6 (7-2) performance against Todd Martin. ``It's
the most important tournament for me,'' said Ivanisevic, who is 2-5
against his next opponent, 23d-ranked Jan Sirmerink. ``If I play
like this, I have nothing to fear.''
</P>
<P>
   The last of the seeded quarterfinalists, Richard Krajicek, was
the most flustered of the bunch. Wimbledon's weak-kneed 1996
champion could not understand why, with the courts actually dry and
rain-free for the first time since opening day, he kept falling
down. But he won anyway and accomplished the victory with just 13
aces and inhibited mobility because of a second-set spill that
caused his surgically repaired right knee to seize up. The key,
Krajicek said, to his 6-3, 6-3, 7-5 elimination of South Africa's
Wayne Ferreira was in drawing an opponent even more infirm than
himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm lucky that there was another invalid on the court, that he
couldn't serve, and I won in straight sets,'' said the ninth-seeded
Dutchman of Ferreira, whose chronically sore ankle was complicated
by a temporarily strained stomach muscle. ``It just wasn't his day;
he was struggling with his serve.''
</P>
<P>
   Krajicek was considerably more diplomatic about Ferreira, who
plopped out eight double faults Tuesday, than he has been about
other peers. The outspoken Dutchman attracted the ire of female
competitors here four years ago by referring to them as ``fat, lazy
pigs.'' And last week Krajicek drew a raised eyebrow from Sampras
when he remarked that the top-ranked defending champion has been
playing 10th-ranked tennis this year.
</P>
<P>
   In character, Krajicek said he didn't see any reason to be
tentative about facing his next opponent, Davide Sanguinetti, a
65th-ranked Italian who had never played a match on Wimbledon's
grass until this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I watched him play one game once: he's right-handed, he's got
double-handed backhands,'' Krajicek said. The 25-year-old
Sanguinetti reached his first Grand Slam quarterfinal by downing
Francisco Clavet of Spain, 7-6(7-3), 6-1, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
   On the women's side, Williams was the only relative newcomer to
a Wimbledon quarterfinal cast that includes top-seeded Martina
Hingis, second-seeded Lindsay Davenport, third-seeded Novotna,
fifth-seeded Arantxa Sanchez Vicario, sixth-seeded Monica Seles,
16th-seeded Nathalie Tauziat and Natasha Zvereva, the only unseeded
player in the final eight.
</P>
<P>
   Hingis, undefeated in her last 11 Wimbledon matches after
eliminating Tamarine Tanasugarn of Thailand, 6-3, 6-2, Tuesday, has
a 5-1 record against Sanchez Vicario, who needed three sets to
sneak past 15th-seeded Dominique Van Roost, 3-6, 6-3, 6-2.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
