<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NICHOLAS-DANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DANCE HONORS FOR BROTHERS WHO COULD TAP UP A STORM
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JACK ANDERSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DURHAM, N.C. _ Fayard and Harold Nicholas, the tap dancers who
performed professionally as the Nicholas Brothers in movies,
Broadway musicals, nightclubs and television shows, received the
1998 Samuel H. Scripps American Dance Festival Award on Monday
night in ceremonies at Duke University here.
</P>
<P>
   The $25,000 award, established in 1981 by the philanthropist
Samuel H. Scripps, is given annually at the American Dance Festival
to honor lifetime achievement in American modern dance. Modern
dance is broadly conceived by the selection panel as dance that
reflects a spirit of innovation rather than a specific technique.
</P>
<P>
   The Nicholas Brothers, whose careers began in 1930, developed a
style known as classic tap, notable for its rhythmic complexity,
acrobatic dexterity and elegant use of the arms and upper body. The
award citation praised them for ``strikingly original work which
has enriched our heritage.''
</P>
<P>
   Fayard Nicholas, 83, received the award from festival directors
Charles L. Reinhart and Stephanie Reinhart. Harold Nicholas, born
in 1921, was prevented from attending by illness, as was the
cabaret entertainer Bobby Short, who had been scheduled to present
the award.
</P>
<P>
   Film clips showed excerpts from some Nicholas Brothers movies,
among them ``Stormy Weather,'' a 1943 production with routines
filled with spectacular leaps, slides and rushings up and down a
flight of stairs. Yet despite the acrobatic choreography, the
dancers always retained a sense of poise.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the tap routines he choreographed for himself and
his brother, Fayard Nicholas joked in receiving the award: ``I
can't do that anymore. I don't want to do that anymore. To tell you
the truth, it hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   Sitting at a small table at the side of the stage, he watched a
performance by the Nicholas Sisters: his two granddaughters, Nicole
Elizabeth, who is 12, and Catherine Victoria, 9.
</P>
<P>
   First came a brisk routine without music. Then generations of
tap artists were united. While the Nicholas Brothers were shown on
screen dancing a number from ``The Black Network,'' a film short of
1935, the Nicholas Sisters did the same jaunty dance onstage.
</P>
<P>
   Commenting on the career of the Nicholas Brothers, who made
their last appearance as a team in 1985, Reinhart said: ``They were
not only ahead of their time 60 years ago, they are ahead of their
time today.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
