A4615 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WIMBLEDON-MEN-COX     06-30 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WIMBLEDON-MEN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ivanisevic beats Martin
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Clarke
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ Goran Ivanisevic has about a centimeter of
hair on his head and a matching goatee on his chin in his 1998
media guide picture.
</P>
<P>
   His hair hung to the middle of his neck Tuesday, as he reached
the Wimbledon quarterfinals by beating American Todd Martin 7-6
(7-5), 6-3, 3-6, 7-6 (7-2). The hair was pulled off Ivanisevic's
face with a plain rubberband as a headband and set off by a full
beard.
</P>
<P>
   In his decade as a pro tennis player, the 26-year-old lefthander
also has worn a short waterspout ponytail, a long regular ponytail
and a handful of other styles.
</P>
<P>
   This week's beard, the 14th seed said, is just because he's lazy
and doesn't want to shave. But he feels obligated to change his
hairstyle frequently.
</P>
<P>
   ''The people expect me to do always something new,'' he said.
``They always ask me, 'When is there going to be a new hairstyle?'
or ``Do something new.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, his tennis and his attitude are almost as
changeable as his hairstyle.
</P>
<P>
   ''Every time I am on that court I can, when I play good, beat
anybody,'' Ivanisevic said. ''And I can lose, because my matches
are like horror thrillers. You cannot expect anything. Even me, I
don't know the end of the movie.''
</P>
<P>
   A top junior in Croatia, Ivanisevic turned pro in 1988. By 1989,
he was 40 in the world and two years later, he entered the top 10.
In 1992, he reached the French Open quarterfinals and the Wimbledon
final. He reached a year-end career-high ranking of No. 4.
</P>
<P>
   But since then, he has wandered off his straight-shot march to
the top, earning a reputation for cursing himself and anyone else
nearby when he loses.
</P>
<P>
   He never lost his talent, though, which includes the big serve
and all-around skill. Many experts still consider his mind to be
his biggest obstacle to greatness.
</P>
<P>
   The result has been an erratic career, particularly in the Grand
Slams. He also reached the Wimbledon final in 1994, losing to Pete
Sampras in straight sets, but never consistently advanced in the
big events.
</P>
<P>
   The past 16 months have been the hardest. Before Wimbledon,
Ivanisevic had won just one match in a Grand Slam tournament since
the 1997 Australian Open. His 1997 year-end ranking was 15, his
lowest since 1991.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's been very bad,'' he said. ''Five Grand Slams, one win.
(But) maybe this is the breakthrough. AfteThis year has been
especially difficult, when the normally unpredictable Ivanisevic
was predictably bad. He has won just one title and reached only one
other semifinal, in early January.
</P>
<P>
   ''The last six months has been my worst six months ever in my
carelrhis week. ''I said, 'OK. The first half of the year is gone.
You cannot play worse than the first half of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   As recently as two months ago, he considered practice an
unbearable burden and hated hearing things about himself.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was not easnad he's never going to be back again,' '' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   So instead of practicing or working out, he wanted to watch
sports or hang out with friends. He loves soccer and has been
discussing Croatia's World Cup progress after nearly every match.
When someone told him Croatia had just scored, he laughed and asked
for detaisl.
</P>
<P>
   He ended his bad patch a few weeks ago after a stern
conversation with himself.
</P>
<P>
   '' 'This is the end,' '' he said he told himself. '' 'You can
play better and improve and don't feel sorry for yourself.'
Sometimes I feel sorry for myself.' ''
</P>
<P>
   He has enough talent that he can turn it around with little more
than his will. A few weeks of grass-court practice after a
first-round loss to 144th-ranked Marziosvic reached the fourth
round in a Wimbledon warm-up.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm happier to play. I have more fun on the court and more fun
practicing,'' Ivanisevic said. ''So I think I've passed that bad
time.''
</P>
<P>
   And although other players never know where Ivanisevic's head
will be, just the thought of the 6-foot-4 serve and volleyer on
grass concerns them. He has led the tour in aces four times in the
past six years, averaging 14.8 per match last year.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's got one of the biggest serves ever,'' said top seed Pete
Sampras, who also advanced to the quarterfinals but could only meet
Ivanisevic in the final. ``He gets his mind into it, and he's very
much a threat.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
