<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WIMBLEDON-WOMEN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    For Venus, Martina, now the seeds
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Clarke
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ Martina Hingis, Jana Novotna and Venus
Williams all reached the Wimbledon quarterfinals Tuesday without
losing more than five games.
</P>
<P>
   Today, for the first time, Hingis and Williams will play seeded
opponents. Hingis meets Arantxa Sanchez Vicario, who struggled
early before defeating Dominique Van Roost 3-6, 6-3, 6-2.
</P>
<P>
   Williams _ who beat Virginia Ruano-Pascual 6-3, 6-1 _ faces
Novotna, who defeated Irina Spirlea 6-2, 6-3.
</P>
<P>
   Novotna, 29, is the elder statesmen in this women's draw. She is
the oldest and the most classic serve-and-volley player, reaching
the final here twice.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, she lost to Hingis. In 1993, she led Steffi Graf
early before losing in three sets and then crying on the shoulder
of royalty during the awards ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   Williams recently expressed interest in using more
serve-and-volley but has struggled to do so at Wimbledon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that with every match I'm able to play smarter,''
Williams said. ``I'm able to come in more. I'm able to serve
better.''
</P>
<P>
   Novotna doesn't mind, however, that Williams is far from
perfecting her grass-court game.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm happier that Venus is really not a serve-and-volleyer,''
Novotna said, ''because she really has a huge serve and if she
would be coming in all the time, it would be rather difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Second-seeded Lindsay Davenport also meets her first seeded
player, No.16 Nathalie Tauziat. No.6 Monica Seles is the only
quarterfinalist not to play a seed. But she is concerned about
playing Natasha Zvereva, who eliminated Steffi Graf in the second
round.
</P>
<P>
   ''She has the best hands in the game,'' Seles said of Zvereva.
``So she'll be a tough match.''
</P>
<P>
   Quarterfinals: Frequent rain last week could mean good things
for fans if it holds off again. All four men's and women's
quarterfinal matches are scheduled for today so fans could see both
top seeds, Williams, Davenport, Tim Henman and others with just a
few footsteps around the grounds.
</P>
<P>
   For the remainder of the week, the women should play semifinals
Thursday, rest on Friday and play the finals Saturday. The men
should rest Thursday, play semifinals Friday and the finals Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, Gimelstob advance: Mixed double partners Venus
Williams and Justin Gimelstob upset seventh-seeded Cyril Suk and
Helena Sukova in their first-round match, 6-3, 5-7, 6-4, continuing
their pursuit of a mixed doubles Grand Slam.
</P>
<P>
   The two Florida residents _ Gimelstob lives in Key Biscayne _
won the Australian and French mixed titles this year. Wimbledon
officials, however, chose not to seed them here, instead choosing
to follow doubles rankings.
</P>
<P>
   Serena Williams and partner Max Mirnyi also won, defeating Geoff
Grant and Catalina Cristea 6-1, 7-6 (11-9). The sisters can't meet
until the final.
</P>
<P>
   Lobs: Italian Davide Sanguinetti is the lowest-ranked
quarterfinalist at 65. He never has played Wimbledon, and this is
just his fourth Grand Slam tournament, by far his best result. ...
Simone Amorico, a Delray Beach resident, lost his first-round
junior boys match to Jerome Haehnel of France, 6-3, 3-6, 4-6.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
