r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LUCAS-MAURO-TEX     06-30 0524
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LUCAS-MAURO-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHALLENGER CRITICIZES BUSH DECISION ON HENRY LUCAS
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanies BC-LUCAS-STRANGEODYSSEY) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN MORITZ 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ Democratic gubernatorial nominee Garry Mauro said
Tuesday that Gov. George W. Bush should not have halted the
execution of Henry Lee Lucas, contending that doubts about the
former Death Row inmate's guilt were based on thin evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas, who once confessed to some 600 killings, was scheduled to
be executed Tuesday night for the Halloween 1979 strangulation and
rape of a still-unidentified woman whose body was found near
Georgetown in Central Texas.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush, a Republican who is seeking a second term in November,
commuted the sentence to life in prison Friday, citing reports
suggesting that Lucas was in Florida when the woman was killed.
Mauro questioned the validity of those claims.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twelve jurors and a judge found Henry Lee Lucas guilty and
sentenced him to death,'' said Mauro, a four-term Texas land
commissioner. ``Their decision was reviewed by 23 appeals court
judges, and they didn't find any reason to overrule them. Based on
that, I don't think the governor should have intervened.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's campaign spokeswoman, Mindy Tucker, suggested that Mauro
was seeking to score political points by taking shots at Lucas, who
is serving prison time for at least 10 slayings, including that of
his mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``Serious doubts have been raised about Henry Lee Lucas' guilt
in this one particular case,'' Tucker said. ``The governor is
simply saying it would be wrong to execute someone for a crime they
may not have committed.''
</P>
<P>
   Mauro on Tuesday backed away from a statement he made Monday to
the Austin American-Statesman suggesting that Lucas' other crimes
were so heinous that he should have been executed regardless of his
guilt in the Georgetown slaying.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not the impression I meant to leave,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   By hammering Bush on the Lucas issue, Mauro put himself at odds
with one of the most prominent Democratic office seekers who has
been willing to embrace his underdog campaign against the popular
Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Former Attorney General Jim Mattox, who is hoping to win back
the job he held from 1983 to 1991, publicly urged Bush to spare
Lucas. In 1986, Mattox's office released a report citing work
records that put Lucas in Jacksonville, Fla., during much of
October and November 1979, when the woman was killed.
</P>
<P>
   After Bush announced his decision to commute Lucas' sentence,
Mattox issued a statement saying he ``would defend Governor Bush
against any attack'' in the matter. Tuesday, Mattox did just that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Henry Lee Lucas has done a number of reprehensible things, and
may deserve the death penalty for some of them,'' Mattox said.
``But it should not come on a crime he did not commit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Garry Mauro or any other individual who criticizes the
decision is just wrong,'' said Mattox, who added that he will
continue to support Mauro's bid for governor.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-98 2011EDT &QL; 
