<DOCNO> NYT19980630.0330 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4624 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NASCAR-LIGHTS-COX     06-30 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASCAR-LIGHTS-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Fans, drivers, TV taking to NASCAR at night
</P>
<P>
   By Tom McCollister
</P>
<P>
   c. 1998 cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ It's difficult to get an emotional
reaction from stoic Mark Martin, but even he admitted to getting
chill bumps when he flew over Daytona International Speedway
recently and saw its lights aglow, circling the 2 1/2-mile track
like a pearl necklace.
</P>
<P>
   And when Martin had the opportunity on the following day to test
his Ford Taurus under those lights, it was everything he imagined.
</P>
<P>
   ``The view from behind the windshield is spectacular, just like
daytime, only better,'' said Martin, a Daytona Beach resident, who
will race under the lights for real on Saturday in the Pepsi 400.
``It's spectacular. The job they've done here is so good. When you
leave the track it seems darker everywhere else, because your eyes
are adjusted to such excellent lighting out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin isn't alone in praising the the speedway's new lighting
system. The project began the week after last year's Pepsi race,
and Musco Lighting completed the construction just days before the
first test on June 8. Musco called it the world's largest lighting
project.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a challenging project for us,'' said Musco
President Joe Crookham. ``When designing the system, three factors
came into play _ the driver, the spectator and the television
audience. One of the challenges for that is that light by its
nature has to be intrusive on the object, but we don't want to put
it in anybody's eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   Too late. Night racing seems to be knocking out everybody's
eyes, from the drivers to the fans to television producers. For
that reason, NASCAR scheduled six night races this season. And
while NASCAR officials say they aren't ready for the ``NASCAR at
Night'' logo, more are expected.
</P>
<P>
   Consider:
</P>
<P>
   _ Television likes night racing because of the ratings. Tom
Hughes of TBS said the Coca-Cola 600 in Charlotte, televised at 6
p.m. on Saturday, May 24, carried a 5.0-plus rating, the
third-highest cable TV rating in history. The race carried 6.0
ratings during the last two quarter-hours. H.A. ``Humpy'' Wheeler,
president at Charlotte Motor Speedway, estimated that an afternoon
race would have drawn from a 3.8-4.0 rating.
</P>
<P>
   _ The drivers like Saturday-night racing because it would
provide more quality family time. ``I think they ought to light 'em
all up, so we can race Saturday night every week,'' Mike Skinner
said. ``Then we could have Sundays off and more time with our
families. Qualify Friday night, race Saturday, and then go on to
the house. Of course, I know that's not going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The fans like night racing for obvious reasons _ 70-degree
nights offer more comfort than 103-degree days.
</P>
<P>
   _ Saturday-night racing also creates a built-in rainout makeup
day. If it rains on Saturday, there's always Sunday for racing.
</P>
<P>
   Wheeler predicts NASCAR will begin moving more toward night
racing, but he thinks it will keep its traditional Sunday dates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sunday night is the highest HUT level (household usage
television) of the week,'' Wheeler said. ``It's the lowest on
Saturday night. If the TV money is enough, anything can happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the fans in the stands still outrank those in front of
their TV sets. It's going to be a long time before your television
revenue does more for you than your live gate. The gate is the most
important thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Night racing came to NASCAR totally by happenstance, not because
of television, Wheeler said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was after The Winston, the week after the first night
Winston race,'' Wheeler said. ``Bruton (Smith) and I were going
through the stands after the Coca Cola 600 pre-race show. It was 95
degrees. The fans were yelling at us, 'Let's run at night! Let's
run at night!' They were miserable.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got to the top step, and I said to Bruton, 'I think the
people have spoken.' I don't know how much, or when, but, yes,
there will be more night racing.''
</P>
<P>
   For two-time Winston Cup champion Jeff Gordon, the issue may be
difficult to put in perspective, but he knows why fans and drivers
prefer the nighttime.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I see the cars going around at night, they look faster,''
he said. ``The thing I like most about night-time is the
consistency in the track. The conditions are perfect, nice cool
temperatures. You don't have to deal with clouds and sunshine and
the track changing all the time. Another thing I really like is, I
usually get to sleep late in in the morning.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there's Jeremy Mayfield, who feels strongly in both cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, it seems like there's a little bit more electricity
in the air for night races, but it doesn't really matter to me,''
Mayfield said. ``I just want to race. Temperatures can be an
advantage at night. It's a little cooler. Maybe you can't see quite
as well, but you never have to worry about the glare of the sun,
either. Really, just tell me what time to be there, and I'll be
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Varying opinions aside, Mike Helton, NASCAR's vice president of
competition, doesn't foresee a splurge of night races.
</P>
<P>
   ``Daytona is understandable, considering the heat,'' Helton
said. ``Atlanta has installed lights, but with their two races _
March and November _ the weather is little severe for night racing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winston Cup racing is still a Sunday afternoon sport. There's
a long tradition of racing on Sunday afternoon, one that I believe
will continue.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
