<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4626 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AFRICAN-ALBUMS-$ADV05     06-30 1081
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFRICAN-ALBUMS-$ADV05-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING AFRICAN POP SAFE FOR WESTERN EARS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 5) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JON PARELES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It happens too often. An African rock band comes to New York and
plays a brilliant set, turning listeners into dancers with complex,
scintillating grooves that billow and tickle and drive. Afterward,
full of anticipation, new fans track down the band's latest album,
only to find that it doesn't sound anything like what the band
played on stage.
</P>
<P>
   The pattern is bound to repeat itself after Africa Fete _ the
package tour with Salif Keita from Mali, Maryam Mursal from
Somalia, Papa Wemba from Congo and Cheikh Lo from Senegal _ takes
place Sunday at Central Park Summerstage. Parts of their albums
approximate their performances; Wemba's current album, ``Molokai,''
was recorded live in the studio. But other songs fall prey to a
mistranslation syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   On too many internationally released albums by African stars,
guest vocalists are enlisted to break the language barrier;
American or European producers tweak the rhythms to sound more like
funk or reggae or whatever else they think will reach the
unconverted. It sounds as if the international labels that sought
out African bands went on to second-guess themselves, deciding that
their African talent may know what plays to the folks at home but
needs help overseas.
</P>
<P>
   The musicians, eager to try something new and enticed by the
prospect of international sales, go along with the process. As a
result, band leaders who have spent years or decades refining their
music can end up sounding like sidemen on their own albums.
</P>
<P>
   In April, Baba Maal, from Senegal, played a superb set at Irving
Plaza. He meshed circling, rippling guitar lines, derived from the
kora (harp-guitar) parts of griot songs but with the blunt drive of
rock. Some of his vocal melodies started on off-beats like
responses to instrumental lines and continued in long, curlicued
phrases, as they do in traditional griot songs.
</P>
<P>
   In other songs, the vocal began on the downbeat and stayed with
the short lines that are catchier to rock-trained ears.
</P>
<P>
   Maal was easily straddling two musical worlds; he has been on
the international circuit for a long time. But on his album ``Nomad
Soul,'' which will be released this summer, Maal's own hybrid is
sidelined. The opening track starts with an Irish woman's voice, as
if Maal and a kora have wandered into someone else's session. It
takes a few songs before Maal steps forward on his own, and the
album finally rights itself.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't a purist complaint. Purism is no way to deal with
African music, which draws strength from syncretism: latching on to
outside ideas and hooking them up to African esthetics. Rumba,
jazz, gospel, funk, reggae and rock have all been repatriated
across the Atlantic to rejoin their African kin.
</P>
<P>
   African musician have also found useful ideas in country, Middle
Eastern music and nearly everything else they hear. The title tune
of Cheikh Lo's album, ``Ne La Thiass,'' neatly ties in to flamenco,
positing an Arabic musical pipeline from Spain via North Africa to
Senegal.
</P>
<P>
   The album was produced by Youssou N'Dour, the Senegalese star
who's no stranger to international crossover _ he wrote the theme
song for this year's World Cup competition _ and who has built a
modern recording studio in Dakar so that African musicians can
record in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Other producers aren't so musically diplomatic. Simon Emmerson,
who produced the latest albums by both Maal and Ms. Mursal, bides
his time on Ms. Mursal's album ``The Journey,'' ingeniously placing
her remarkable voice amid African instruments, clever samples and
seething electronics until, halfway through the album, he decides
to indulge himself with a long synthetic stretch intended as a
Somalian soundscape.
</P>
<P>
   Angelique Kidjo from Benin, a previous Africa Fete headliner,
has just released her album ``Oremi,'' and her Paris-based
producers have Westernized her rhythms so thoroughly that only an
occasional hint of African intonation breaks through backup tracks
aiming for lite-rock radio.
</P>
<P>
   There's a fundamental difference between what African musicians
accomplish on stage and what they're aiming for in the studio.
Stage shows set out to get people moving and participating,
something a band can do by creating an irresistible groove; albums
want to sell themselves, and the most direct way to do that is to
get a song played on the radio.
</P>
<P>
   African bands that can groove all night long, while a crowd
keeps getting happier, don't have to concern themselves with pop
concision. But a big part of their producers' job is to hone songs
for radio programmers who want something with simple, catchy hooks
and choruses, and something that's not too different from the rest
of their play lists.
</P>
<P>
   (In Paris, where many French-speaking Africans record their
international albums, producers are also fixated on sappy ballads
and thin, perky synthesizer tones, reflecting French bad taste.)
Many African pop albums lead off with their most homogenized, least
characteristic song; radio programmers may not look any further.
But programmers won't give much African pop a chance anyway,
particularly if it's not in English, so most of those attempts at
crossover are futile.
</P>
<P>
   Crossover ambitions aren't necessarily doomed. With dance music
ascendant in the West, African bands might be better off selling
the magnificent intricacy of their grooves than trying to mimic
Western pop.
</P>
<P>
   Dance-music producers could be the ones who will find a true
bridge between African rock bands and the Western public. They will
have to fight their first impulses, which are to flatten the
cross-rhythms into a house-music thump or a reggae backbeat; their
true job will be to sharpen the friction between all the
cross-rhythmic layers of a good African groove, helping Western
ears hear all the subtleties and share the intoxication.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not going to happen immediately. In the meantime,
African music fans who want to take the music home have limited
choices. They can seek out an occasional live album, like King
Sunny Ade's ``Live Live Juju.'' (His new studio album, ``Odu,'' is
also true to the band's live sound.)
</P>
<P>
   They can also look for albums made in Africa, where lower
budgets favor straightforward live sessions. Or the next time
they're at an African concert, they can sneak in a tape recorder.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
