<HEADLINE>
KANSAS RACE FOCUSES ON THE SOUL OF THE SUBURBS  
 (JT )
</HEADLINE>
   By DIRK JOHNSON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   OLATHE, Kan. _ For all the images of Dorothy's farm, the rail
lines of Topeka or the aerospace plants of Wichita, the typical
Republican voter of Kansas lives here in the traffic-jammed
mallscape of suburban Johnson County.
</P>
<P>
   Once the corn-covered Back Forty of metropolitan Kansas City,
this affluent area booming with new subdivisions and retail centers
has become the state's political quintessence, at least for
Republicans, producing far more votes than even Wichita. And it is
these newer, distant suburbs that are now a crucial battleground in
the Republican primary for governor, between the incumbent, Bill
Graves, a social moderate, and David Miller, former Republican
state chairman and the leader of Kansas' anti-abortion forces.
</P>
<P>
   Among Republicans nationally, the fight is the latest in the
party's long and bitter struggle to define its chief mission:
balancing budgets or saving souls.
</P>
<P>
   Graves, who has cut taxes four times since taking office three
and a half years ago and presided over the kind of prosperous
economy seen across most of America in recent years, would scarcely
seem likely to face a challenge from his own ranks. He enjoys a 75
percent approval rating, according to one recent poll, and most
political analysts say he will be tough to beat come the day of the
primary, August 4.
</P>
<P>
   But Miller, a former state legislator who stepped down as party
chairman to run for governor, believes that Graves' support for
abortion rights makes him vulnerable. And while early polls give
the governor a big lead, analysts caution against discounting
Miller, a former leader of the Christian Coalition who can draw on
the organizational strength of evangelical churches and
anti-abortion groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``You wouldn't think that the most popular governor in memory
would be challenged by a leader of his own party,'' said Burdette
Loomis, a political science professor at the University of Kansas,
who noted that Graves won 102 of 105 counties in 1994. ``But David
Miller is a very good politician. He's not in this unless he thinks
he can win. He can get out all the evangelicals to vote. It's all
going to hinge on turnout.''
</P>
<P>
   The outcome, Loomis said, could well depend on voters in
suburban communities like Olathe. Disputing the notion that
prosperous suburbanites shun the appeals of religious
conservatives, he said:
</P>
<P>
   ``You go into a lot of these affluent subdivisions _ $200,000
earth-tone houses with three-car garages _ and you'll find that
many of these young families are strong fundamentalists. It's not
like these people wear a big X on their forehead. They look like a
bunch of other well-off, mostly white people.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Loomis said, religious conservatives in highest
proportions can be found in the newer suburbs, with their winding
roads into uniform subdivisions and their isolated cul-de-sacs.
</P>
<P>
   So commanding is the early lead of the 45-year-old Graves, a
native of Salina in rural central Kansas, that a poll published on
June 21 by The Wichita Eagle found two-thirds of the state's
Republican voters supporting him. But low turnout makes primary
elections difficult to predict, and surveys have sometimes
underestimated the strength of evangelical voters like Cathy
Kinsella, who runs a business with her husband, has five children
and, as a strong opponent of abortion, says she will be working
hard for Graves' defeat. That the governor has signed a bill
outlawing the late-term procedure that opponents call partial birth
abortion does not change Mrs. Kinsella's view.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has neglected people like me,'' she said as she pushed a
cart across the lot of an Olathe shopping mall on a wilting recent
afternoon. ``He's ignored the family, the Bible, the moral issues
that are the most important thing facing us.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller, a 48-year-old insurance salesman from Eudora, just west
of Olathe, recently held a campaign rally near Wichita that
featured the endorsement of James Dobson, head of the conservative
Focus on the Family, which reaches 28 million people through its
radio and television broadcasts. Between prayers and patriotic
music, Dobson stood before a giant American flag and hailed Miller
as ``a man of courage, a man of conviction and a man of faith.'' He
criticized Graves, calling him ``not pro-life, not pro-family and
not conservative.''
</P>
<P>
   But Dobson has campaigned for several social conservatives this
year and has not been uniformly successful. His horse in the race
for the Republican nomination for Nebraska governor, U.S. Rep. Jon
Christensen, finished a distant third.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Kansas is perhaps the most conservative Midwestern state _
its entire six-member congressional delegation, including the
former track star Jim Ryun, comes from the right end of the
Republican spectrum _ but analysts say the rosy economy and the
personal appeal of Graves should translate into bipartisan support.
Tom Sawyer, minority leader of the Kansas House, looks like a
shoo-in for the Democratic nomination, and among the Democrats who
choose to vote in the Republican primary, the governor is expected
to find strong backing.
</P>
<P>
   One of those Democrats, Charlie Bitts, said that while no one
could ignore social problems like out-of-wedlock births and drug
addiction, he would vote his pocketbook: for Graves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our economy is awfully good right now,'' said Bitts, 63, a
retired landscaper from rural southeast Kansas. ``Our morality in
this country certainly needs to be changed. I just don't think
politics is the place for it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
