<HEADER>
A4633 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-KINGS-LADN     06-30 0786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS EXPECT TO BE ACTIVE IN FREE AGENCY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ With the National Hockey League draft behind him,
King general manager Dave Taylor is about to get even busier.
</P>
<P>
   July has dawned and the start of the 1998-99 season is three
months away, but the start of the free-agency season began when
June ended, and the Kings are expected to be active.
</P>
<P>
   Don't count on them turning themselves into Stanley Cup
contenders this summer. But the Kings are expected to try to find a
defenseman who can run a power play that was at best mediocre last
season, and a forward who can play on one of the top two lines and
spark an offense that sometimes was potent and other times was
maddeningly inconsistent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to say,'' Taylor responded when asked if he expected
any signings right away. ``It's a funny market the last few years,
really crazy. We're willing to spend money, but at the same time,
we're not going to waste it. There are some players we're
interested in, but if it gets out of hand, we're just going to
stop.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the year before the Kings' scheduled move from the Forum
to the glitzy Staples Center, a year before team management's
target for a Stanley Cup contender.
</P>
<P>
   But the Kings did raise ticket prices for 1998-98 by 11 percent
last month, and at the time of that announcement, team president
Tim Leiweke said one reason for the move was an expected 40-percent
increase in the Kings' payroll, which was approximately $24 million
last season.
</P>
<P>
   A hunk of that payroll increase will be eaten up by one of the
Kings' own restricted free agents, Norris Trophy-winning defenseman
Rob Blake, who will get a hefty raise on last season's team-high
$3.15 million salary. Blake was the sixth-highest paid NHL
defenseman, earning about $1.2 million less than top-paid Scott
Stevens of New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Who might Taylor try to sign? He has repeatedly said he's not
interested in making offers to restricted free agents whose teams
invariably match the offer and drive up pay scales (as was the case
with $28-million man Sergei Fedorov, who didn't get his riches
until Carolina signed him, forcing Detroit to match).
</P>
<P>
   Here's a list of some of the unrestricted free agents, by
position, with their teams, ages, last year's salaries, and their
statistics:
</P>
<P>
   Left wings:
</P>
<P>
   Geoff Courtnall (St. Louis, 36, $2.5 million, 31 goals, 31
assists, 62 points); Wendel Clark (Toronto, 32, $2.3 million,
12-7-19); Benoit Hogue (Dallas, 32, $1.25 million, 6-16-22).
Comment:
</P>
<P>
   Seeing Courtnall, the Kings' nemesis during last season's
playoffs against the Kings, join his brother at the Forum would be
like seeing President Clinton hire Kenneth Starr as his press
secretary. On the other hand, Courtnall's brother, Russ, already
plays for the Kings.
</P>
<P>
   Centers:
</P>
<P>
   Doug Gilmour (New Jersey, 35, $3.55 million, 13-40-53); Ron
Francis (Pittsburgh, 35, $1.9 million, 25-62-87); Guy Carbonneau
(Dallas, 38, $750,000, 7-17-24); Marc Bureau (Montreal, 32,
$475,000, 13-6-19). Comment:
</P>
<P>
   Gilmour, then with Toronto, was as big a villain as Courtnall to
King fans in 1993. He's got a lot of miles on him and a hefty price
tag.
</P>
<P>
   Right wings:
</P>
<P>
   Brett Hull (St. Louis, 34, $4.7 million, 27-45-72); John MacLean
(San Jose, 34, $1.65 million, 13-19-32); Brian Noonan (Vancouver,
33, $900,000, 10-15-25). Comment:
</P>
<P>
   Most speculation has Hull leaving the Blues, possibly for father
Bobby's former team, the Chicago Blackhawks, or to join ex-King
Wayne Gretzky with the New York Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   Defensemen:
</P>
<P>
   Steve Duchesne (St. Louis, 33, $2 million, 14-42-56); Uwe Krupp
(Nashville, 33, $1.5 million, 9-22-31); Gary Suter (Chicago, 34,
$1.6 million, 14-28-42); Jyrki Lumme (Vancouver, 32, $1.735
million, 9-21-30); Fredrik Olausson (Pittsburgh, 32, $700,000,
6-27-33). Comment:
</P>
<P>
   The return of popular ex-King Duchesne has been the hottest King
rumor for months, and he would add some juice to the power play.
Tamper-proof Taylor for months has sprinted away from anyone
mentioning Duchesne's name. The Mighty Ducks also have been rumored
to be interested.
</P>
<P>
   Goalies:
</P>
<P>
   Mike Richter (Nashville, 32, $3.9 million, 21-31-15, 2.66
goals-against average); Curtis Joseph (Edmonton, $2.3 million, 31,
29-31-9, 2.63); John Vanbiesbrouck (Florida, 35, $2.2 million,
18-29-11, 2.87); Arturs Irbe (Vancouver, 31, $775,000, 14-11-6,
2.73); Bob Essensa (Edmonton, 33, $300,000, 6-6-1, 2.55). Comment:
</P>
<P>
   The Kings are seeking organizational depth, not a No. 1 or No. 2
goalie, so if they are interested in any of these guys, it's not
the first three listed above.
</P>
</TEXT>
