<HEADER>
A4639 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEAT-CHILDDEATH-COX     06-30 0763
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEAT-CHILDDEATH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Child, 3, dies after daycare van driver leaves him in vehicleBy
Michael Weiss
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Woon Oh was waiting for answers Tuesday that might
explain his son's death. For Oh, the question was unfathomable. How
could a day care center owner forget a little boy in a van, lock
him inside, and leave him to die from the heat?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what happened exactly,'' Oh said. ``I just can't
believe it. Probably she had something to do, but that still
doesn't explain it to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Samuel Oh, 3, died Monday evening, about an hour after a worker
at his day care center found him unconscious on the back seat of
the van. For 2 1/2 hours, the little boy was alone in the van,
parked on the black asphalt of a church parking lot on a blistering
afternoon where temperatures reached 95 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Samuel's father wasn't the only one with questions. Tuesday
evening, Gwinnett County, Ga. police were still trying to arrange
an interview with Eun Shin Cho, owner of the Kids and Kids Academy
and the woman who they said left Samuel alone. And state regulators
and confused parents who showed up all day at the closed day care
center also had to wait for answers.
</P>
<P>
   Police tried to question Cho, 41, Monday night, but she was too
distraught to talk to them and had to be brought to the hospital.
She was released later that night.
</P>
<P>
   Detectives want to find out whether she ever knew that Samuel
was in the 15-seat van. She may have forgotten to drop the boy at
home, or Samuel may have climbed into the van without her knowing,
said Sgt. Jeff Sligar.
</P>
<P>
   Woon Oh, however, believes his son was supposed to be on that
van, because he is usually dropped off at home between 1:30 and 2
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Police don't expect to charge Cho _ who also goes by her maiden
name, Suh _ but they will hand over their completed investigation
to District Attorney Danny Porter, who will decide whether to seek
an indictment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know so little about the case, but there is potential here
as far as charges go,'' Porter said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, administrators in the office that regulates Georgia's
1,410 day care centers said Tuesday that there have been complaints
lodged against Kids and Kids Academy since the facility began
operating under a temporary license two months ago. But Marty
Rotter, director of the Office of Regulatory Services, declined to
reveal the nature of the complaints until after his office has
gathered more facts.
</P>
<P>
   The center _ known as Sae Sak Education Center until March _ was
closed Tuesday, and state regulators were unable to gather any
information about those complaints or Samuel's death, Rotter said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need some time to look at this whole thing and see what
we've got,'' Rotter said. ``It's a tragic situation but how it
relates to (what's contained in the) rules and regulations, I can't
tell.''
</P>
<P>
   Cho left the van in the parking lot of the nearby Korean First
Presbyterian Church around 2:30 p.m. She borrowed the van from the
church because the center's own vehicle was having mechanical
problems. No one noticed that Samuel was missing until 4:30, when
his mother, Kim Choon, called to ask why her son wasn't home,
Sligar said.
</P>
<P>
   Kids and Kids employee Lisa Chang searched the center, then ran
across Lawrenceville Highway to the churchto look inside the van.
When she saw Samuel unconscious on the seat, Chang shattered one of
the van's windows with a brick and carried the little boy inside
the church to call 911.
</P>
<P>
   Paramedics covered Samuel with ice packs to cool him down, but
it was too late. He was pronounced dead at Northlake Regional
Medical Center, from heart failure brought on by heat exhaustion,
Sligar said.
</P>
<P>
   A funeral was set for 4 p.m. today.
</P>
<P>
   His death stunned metro Atlanta's close-knit Korean-American
community, much of which is clustered in northern DeKalb and
southern Gwinnett counties. Friends of the Ohs stopped by their
apartment Tuesday, joining them for a traditional midday meal.
Reporters from the Korean Southeast News and local affiliate of the
Korean American TV Broadcasting Corp. joined the English-language
news crews on the parking lot outside Kids and Kids. Particularly
affected were congregants at Korean First Presbyterian, where both
Cho and the Ohs were members.
</P>
<P>
   ``The church is in a state of shock,'' said church spokesman
Warren Sams. ``They're trying to consolidate their efforts to find
out what's going on and console the family.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
