<HEADER>
A4640 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PEPSI-NYT &LR;      06-30 0628
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PEPSI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW PEPSI DRINK TO USE NEWLY APPROVED SWEETENER
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By CONSTANCE L. HAYS 
  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Food and Drug Administration approved the use of an
artificial sweetener known as Ace-K in soft drinks on Tuesday.
About an hour later, Pepsico Inc. announced it would be rolling out
a new diet cola nationwide by October that will use both Ace-K and
aspartame, known to consumers as Nutrasweet or Equal.
</P>
<P>
   The approval of Ace-K, marketed by Hoechst AG as Sunett and
officially known as acesulfame potassium, had been eagerly awaited
for almost two years. The product, which gives diet soft drinks a
longer shelf life, is already used in baked goods, chewing gum and
other food products in the United States, and is a common
ingredient in diet beverages sold across Europe and Asia. In May,
the FDA approved another artificial sweetener, sucralose, for use
in beverages.
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts have predicted that Ace-K's approval for soft
drinks would have a major impact on the $55 billion U.S. carbonated
soft-drink industry, and Pepsi's announcement of its new drink,
Pepsi One, seemed to confirm that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Innovation is good,'' said Jennifer Solomon, a beverage
analyst with Salomon Smith Barney. ``I'm glad to see that they are
focusing innovation on major categories, and not dilly-dallying in
sectors that don't have significant volume.''
</P>
<P>
   Diet soda sales have been slowing steadily over the last several
years, with market share declining from 30 percent in 1990 to just
23 percent last year, said John D. Sicher, publisher of Beverage
Digest, an industry newspaper. ``There are a thousand theories on
that,'' he said, including the ascendence of alternatives like
bottled water and fruit-based drinks. ``Certainly one reason is
that there has not been much news in the diet soft drink
category.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, shares of Pepsico closed down 6.25 cents, to $41.1875.
Coca-Cola shares fell 50 cents, to $85.50.
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not the Coca-Cola Co. would introduce a similar diet
product was not clear Tuesday. Last week, Coke's chairman and chief
executive, M. Douglas Ivester, told reporters that the company had
``no plans to change the formulation'' of Diet Coke, which it
rolled out in 1982. ``We know Ace-K, we understand it, and we have
supply relationships around the world,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, a spokeswoman more or less reiterated that, saying,
``We have no immediate plans.'' She added: ``It's nice to have
choices.'' Diet Coke's market share last year was 8.5 percent, down
from 8.7 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Still, several analysts said Tuesday that Coke probably would
come up with a similar product before long. ``If Pepsi One is a
success, then you can expect Coke Light,'' said Emanuel Goldman, a
beverage analyst with Paine Webber.
</P>
<P>
   Diet Pepsi, which was introduced in 1964 and has been
reformulated several times since, had a 5.5 percent market share
last year, according to Beverage Digest data. That share had also
declined, from 5.7 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the name Pepsi One, they are clearly hedging themselves
by not giving up the name Diet Pepsi,'' noted Martin Romm, managing
director and a beverage analyst at Credit Suisse First Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Pepsi executives hope that Pepsi One will enjoy a
coexistence with Diet Pepsi, as has happened in Britain. Pepsi Max,
a diet drink very similar to Pepsi One, has a 2.4 percent market
share there, while Diet Pepsi has a 3.2 share, and both are among
the 10 best-selling soft drinks in that market, Sicher said.
</P>
<P>
   Packaged with a silver-colored label, Pepsi One was named for
its single calorie. Any double-entendre that might refer to the
outcome of the cola war was purely coincidental, a Pepsi spokesman
insisted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
