<HEADER>
A4641 &Cx1f; tta-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-ARGENTIN     06-30 1027
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-ARGENTINA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARGENTINA DEFEATS ENGLAND, 4-3, ON PENALTY KICKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also SOC-WORLDCUP-VECSEY-COLUMN, SOC-WORLDCUP-CROATIA) 
(JT) 
 By JERE LONGMAN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAINT ETIENNE, France _ It began as a game tense with history
and the possibility of violence and ended as the longest and most
compelling match of the 1998 World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   From sly nastiness to cramping desperation, Argentina and
England played on valiantly Tuesday night through regulation,
through two 15-minute overtime periods, and extended their
second-round match as far as it could go with the score tied at 2-2
_ to the breathless drama of penalty kicks.
</P>
<P>
   British fans were singing the tune from ``The Great Escape,''
and for long stretches it appeared that England might somehow
prevail despite playing with only 10 men for the final 73 minutes.
Michael Owen was the youngest player on the field at age 18, but he
was also the most dominant, scoring a goal for England with his
brilliant speed and drawing a penalty that produced the other.
</P>
<P>
   But England has grown accustomed to heartbreakingly premature
exits. It had the potential winning goal disallowed in the 81st
minute because of a wickedly thrown elbow. And as this World Cup
advanced to penalty kicks for the first time, Britain again
succumbed, 4-3, just as it had lost on penalty kicks to Germany
both at the 1990 World Cup and at the 1996 European championships.
</P>
<P>
   The end Tuesday night came on the fifth round of penalty kicks
when midfielder David Batty telegraphed his attempt to slot the
ball inside the left post. Carlos Roa, the Argentine goalkeeper who
had not previously allowed a goal in the tournament, dived
confidently to his right and stopped Batty's shot.
</P>
<P>
   Exhausted and exhilarated, Argentine players began removing
their jerseys and windmilling them in their arms as they raced
downfield. Some tried to climb the fences that separated them from
their delirious fans. Argentina now advances to meet the
Netherlands in the quarterfinals on Saturday in Marseilles, while
England must again contemplate another devastatingly early
departure.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to be a jinx,'' said assistant coach Raymond
Clemence. ``But we know what the rules are.''
</P>
<P>
   After the failed penalty kick, fighting broke out at the other
end of the field where English and Argentine fans sat in uneasy
proximity, but the disturbance appeared to be quickly contained.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to contain another outbreak of hooliganism, some
1,500 policemen were placed on duty in this industrial town in the
Loire Valley and the match was not shown on giant television
screens in the town squares. However, local bars did serve alcohol
until 11 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   By that hour, the game was just edging into the tautness of
overtime. Players on both sides knew that this game might mean
everything in soccer terms. England prevailed over Argentina 1-0 in
the 1966 quarterfinals and went on to win the World Cup. Argentina
won 2-1 in the 1986 quarterfinals en route to a World Cup title as
Diego Maradona scored the famous handball goal known as ``The Hand
of God.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night's outcome was largely decided, not on the Hand of
God, but on the foot of English midfielder David Beckham.
</P>
<P>
   Two minutes after halftime, with the score tied at 2-2, Beckham
was shoved down from behind by Argentina's Diego Simeone. Still
lying on the ground, in full view of the Danish referee Kim
Nielsen, Beckham kicked Simeone in the back of the right leg,
drawing a red card and an immediate ejection.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are absolutely distraught,'' said the English coach, Glenn
Hoddle. ``The sending off cost us the match. I'm not afraid to say
that.''
</P>
<P>
   The kick was not vicious, but Nielsen had signaled in the first
10 minutes that he would tolerate no untoward play. Twice he
awarded penalty kicks on plays that arguably did not deserve
penalties.
</P>
<P>
   In the 6th minute, England goalie David Seaman, rolled into
Simeone in the penalty area and Gabriel Batistuta converted the
penalty kick for his fifth goal of this World Cup and ninth
overall, one more than Maradona. Batistuta dedicated the goal to
his day-old son, Joaquin, and performed a rock-the-cradle dance in
celebration.
</P>
<P>
   Four minutes later, Owen went sprawling in the penalty area
after a slight collision with Roberto Ayala, but Nielsen awarded
another penalty kick. Alan Shearer converted for England and tied
the score at 1-1.
</P>
<P>
   With Beckham gone, England was forced to constrict its defense
and play for penalty kicks or a counterattack by Owen. In the 16th
minute, the teenager had shredded the Argentine defense, taking a
pass with his right foot near midfield, running past the jostling
Jose Chamot, feinting to his left, moving to his right around Ayala
and slamming the ball back to his left into the net. It was a
breathtaking goal, but with 10 men, England reduced its risk-taking
and Owen's chances became limited.
</P>
<P>
   Still, England nearly won. Nine minutes from the end of
regulation, defender Sol Campbell headed in a corner kick, but the
goal was disallowed after Shearer clearly threw an elbow at Roa,
the Argentine goalie.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Passarella, the Argentine coach, substituted for both
Batistuta and his other forward, Claudio Lopez, in the second half,
and went for the kill but Argentina stubbornly kept trying to
attack the middle of the English defense instead of exploiting the
flanks.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's probably why we didn't score,'' Passarella said.
</P>
<P>
   Argentina had tied the game cleverly at 2-2 only seconds from
halftime on a free kick. Batistuta stepped over the ball as a
decoy, midfielder Juan Veron pushed the ball around the defensive
wall and Javier Zanetti stunned England with a left-footed blast
into the net. But no additional goals were forthcoming until the
penalty-kick phase.
</P>
<P>
   ``With England on the defensive, the match didn't seem
winnable,'' Veron said. ``But our never-ending battle was finally
rewarded.''
</P>
<P>
   And England was again sent home achingly early.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very difficult,'' said forward Teddy Sheringham. ``We
played our hearts out. It's hard to believe we're done.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
