<HEADLINE>
BALTIMORE, WASHINGTON TEAM UP IN BID TO WIN 2012 OLYMPICS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RON HUTCHESON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANNAPOLIS, Md. _ Arlington, Texas' bid for the 2012 Olympics
picked up some tough competition Tuesday as Baltimore, Md., and
Washington, D.C., joined forces in a united campaign to win the
international games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Washington and Baltimore have come together to form the
strongest bid of any area in the United States of America,''
Washington Mayor Marion Barry said in announcing the regional
alliance. ``We're going to be hosting those games.''
</P>
<P>
   Barry and Baltimore Mayor Kurt Schmoke joined business leaders
from both cities at a news conference in Annapolis, midway between
the two urban centers. The governors of Maryland and Virginia also
endorsed the effort.
</P>
<P>
   The strong cooperation between Washington and Baltimore, two
traditional rivals, contrasts with Arlington's efforts to bring
Fort Worth and Dallas into their Olympic campaign. Dallas, in
particular, has been lukewarm to the idea of a regional bid.
</P>
<P>
   Arlington submitted its preliminary plan to the U.S. Olympic
Committee Tuesday but declined to make the details public. Nine
cities, including Houston, are vying to host the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Some of those cities released details Tuesday, including the
names of athletes and celebrities who will serve on their Olympic
bid committees. Houston, for example, has track star Carl Lewis and
other Olympic athletes on its roster. Cincinnati has former
astronaut Neil Armstrong.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Luce, spokesman for the Arlington effort, said Arlington
won't release the names of its bid committee because the USOC asked
it not to.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone is trying to prove that they are a serious
contender,'' he said. ``We already are.''
</P>
<P>
   Others are trumpeting who they have on their committee to raise
corporate support, but Arlington doesn't need to do that to gain
support, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Moran, a spokesman with the USOC, said U.S. bid cities can
release whatever information they want.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, John Schwieters, a leader of Washington's effort,
said officials in the nation's capital tried to learn from
Arlington's experience in putting together a regional campaign.
Washington and Baltimore had initially planned to compete for the
games, but joined forces after a series of talks between business
leaders and the two mayors.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they're going through, we were going through,''
Schwieters said of Arlington's effort. ``Let's hope they can solve
their problems. I don't mind tough competition.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Olympic Committee is expected to select the U.S.
candidate in 2002. The International Olympic Committee will make
the final selection in 2005.
</P>
<P>
   Schwieters said he considers Seattle and New York the toughest
competition for the Washington area. Baltimore-Washington boosters
said their bid will be strengthened by the availability of 100,000
hotel rooms, three major airports and the tourist attractions of
the nation's capital.
</P>
<P>
   Schmoke said the issues that had to be resolved for the joint
effort included which city would get top billing. Washington won.
</P>
<P>
   (Staff writer Kerry Curry contributed to this report. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
