<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GM-STRIKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GM WORKERS EXPECTED A MUCH BETTER VACATION
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By NICHOLE M. CHRISTIAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLINT, Mich. _ The way Ryan Garland sees it, the two strikes
here that have shut down the General Motors Corp. and put his
father out of work are a blessing.
</P>
<P>
   Before tensions erupted and 9,200 workers walked off their jobs,
the 10-year-old boy mostly fantasized about spending uninterrupted
days with his father, Dean. But now they are inseparable, their
twin smiles so bright that the two often seem out of place among
the throngs of more serious-looking strikers picketing outside the
sprawling stamping factory where the walkout began on June 5.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're doing everything together,'' Ryan said while holding a
picket sign and counting down the minutes before he and his dad
head to a local park. Their days are filled with water-skiing, boat
rides and intense father-son basketball games. ``We didn't have a
lot before. My dad was always working or sleeping.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike his son, Garland talks quietly about his days with Ryan,
low enough to avoid stares from other strikers. After all, this was
supposed to have been the first week of a paid company-wide
two-week shutdown, a time that most GM workers set aside for family
outings and vacations. Now, only the company's salaried workers
will be paid for the time off.
</P>
<P>
   The strikes have already idled virtually all of GM's hourly
employees _ 162,700 as of Tuesday. Twenty-six of the automaker's 29
North American assembly factories are closed. GM said on Tuesday
that the strikes would cost the company $1.18 billion after taxes
in the second quarter. Most of that resulted from a loss of $890
million at GM's North American operations, the company said.
Delphi, GM's large auto parts subsidiary, lost $290 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel bad saying this, but I'm enjoying myself. It's like a
vacation,'' Garland, 45, said. ``I owe my son this time. We could
stay off the rest of the year and it still wouldn't be enough to
make up for what I've given GM and that plant.''
</P>
<P>
   Garland is married to a corporate lawyer and is not yet worried
about family finances, but many strikers say they are having
trouble making ends meet on the weekly strike pay provided by the
United Automobile Workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``On $150 a week with four kids to feed, your priorities get
focused real quickly,'' said June Cone, 40, a groundskeeper at the
second GM plant on strike in Flint.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than traveling to amusement parks as she had planned, Ms.
Cone, a single mother, said her family was spending the two-week
shutdown scouring their neighborhood for odd jobs. Her children
have found work mowing lawns, and she has helped a couple of
neighbors paint their homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to be careful how far I drive because I really can't
afford to waste money on gas,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   A few bits of good news have emerged this week. GM backed off
its plan to cancel health care benefits for those workers idled by
the strikes. And the top national negotiators for GM and the UAW
have resumed talks for the first time since picket signs went up.
</P>
<P>
   But none of that has washed away workers' anger, or their fears
that the strikes will stretch into late summer and be followed
later this year by yet another crippling dispute at two parts
plants in Dayton, Ohio. Workers there, who staged a 17-day strike
in 1996, were scheduled to take a strike vote on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought it would get this big or this bad,'' Robert
Harbin, 59, said. By now, he had planned to be in a rickety canoe,
floating on a river in northern Michigan. Instead, Harbin sat in a
lawn chair on the side of a dusty road, waving a picket sign and
talking about what might have been if not for the strike.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the time I've put in this year, it's hard to think that I
probably won't have a vacation,'' Harbin said, flipping the pages
of a recent issue of Backpacker magazine. Thirty-seven years of
working with loud press machines have left him not only dependent
on two hearing aids, but a big fan of quiet outdoor vacations.
</P>
<P>
   Strikers are required to staff the picket line for only two
hours once a week, but Harbin said he did not feel comfortable
straying home the rest of the time because he was not sure how long
his ``strike savings'' would have to last. And even if he could
afford a trip, Harbin said, it would probably not alleviate the
stress.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're on strike, your whole mind is on strike. You can't
just put it away and go play,'' he said. ``It'll end one day, but
nobody is going to win. We're all losing things we can't get
back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
