<DOCNO> NYT19980630.0345 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 20:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4650 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ECOLI-01-COX     06-30 0975
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECOLI-01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Two more cases tied to water park
 &HT;    By M.A.J. McKenna and Patricia Guthrie
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Two more children have been added to the tally of
cases in the White Water E. coli outbreak, bringing the total
number of cases associated with the water park to 19.
</P>
<P>
   The Georgia Division of Public Health on Tuesday confirmed
infection with E. coli O157:H7, the potentially life-threatening
strain of a common bacteria, in one child from Bartow County, Ga.
and one from Cobb County, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Both cases were known to authorities last week, but test results
confirming the infection as O157 took until Tuesday, said DPH
spokeswoman Joyce Goldberg. Neither has been hospitalized. Both are
believed to have been infected at White Water on June 11, the first
day on which the infection was spread.
</P>
<P>
   No new cases have surfaced from the additional days on which the
infection is believed to have been transmitted, June 12 and 17, and
none have appeared for June 13-16, Goldberg said.
</P>
<P>
   The count of the outbreak so far stands at 19 children in all:
12 in Georgia and seven in five other states (Alabama, Tennessee,
Kentucky, Arizona and Illinois). All have been confirmed by
laboratory tests as suffering from O157 infection, and five of the
cases in Georgia have been proved by genetic fingerprinting to be
caused by an identical strain.
</P>
<P>
   Genetic tests on the rest _ being performed by DPH and the
Centers for Disease Control and Prevention _ are expected to yield
results by the end of the week. The CDC has not officially joined
the investigation, but continues to consult with the state twice
daily and is also talking to health authorities in other states,
Goldberg said.
</P>
<P>
   The theoretical cause of the outbreak is still believed to be an
infected child, or several children, who contaminated a White Water
kiddie pool on at least three days. But as the outbreak goes on,
both parents and infectious-disease experts outside the
investigation are questioning that hypothesis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find it highly unlikely that the same sick child is coming
back and contaminating the wading pool day after day,'' said Randy
Addison, father of the 3-year-old Kentucky victim Matthew Addison,
who is hospitalized in Louisville with hemolytic uremic syndrome
and has been on dialysis since Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The Addison family is being assisted by Dr. Marguerite Neill,
whose husband is a relative of Matthew Addison's mother, Lisbeth.
An associate professor at Brown University School of Medicine and a
former investigating officer with the CDC, Neill has studied O157
for many years.
</P>
<P>
   White Water officials have contended that chlorination in the
park's pools eliminated most of the pathogen, even though records
show chlorination in the kiddie pools dipped well below standards
on several days of the outbreak. But even if chlorination were
adequate, unsuspected faults in the system _ a buildup of mineral
buildup in a pipe, for instance, or a blind pipe in which water can
eddy instead of rushing through _ might blunt the chemical's
impact, Neill said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have, for example, legionella (the bacterial cause of
Legionnaires' disease) that contaminates a plumbing system in a
building, you might chlorinate the water, but the flow of water
through the pipes may be unequal, and so diffusion of the chlorine
into them may be limited,'' she said. ``Or if you have legionella
hiding in plaque or scale _ or in plankton or algae in an outdoor
pool _ they can act as sponges that soak up free chlorine so that
it doesn't actually reach the bacteria at the molecular level.''
</P>
<P>
   And O157 may have additional tricks up its sleeve. Research
shows it has the ability to escape detection in standardized
testing of water, said Rita Colwell, a University of Maryland
micro- biologist.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bacteria don't die. They go into a shutdown or dormant
state,'' Colwell said.
</P>
<P>
   Laboratory testing proved this, using a water sample tainted
with trace amounts of E. coli and looking for it under two testing
methods. While it did not show up using a culture _ the test
normally done to isolate a bug in a person's blood or stool or from
contaminated water or ground beef _ the strain did appear in the
same water sample using genetic testing. Even minuscule amounts of
E. coli bacteria can cause infection.
</P>
<P>
   But this does not mean E. coli is thriving in adequately treated
pool water, waiting to pounce and sicken thousands, though in
theory it could survive in small amounts and infect a child,
Colwell said.
</P>
<P>
   It does suggest that an outbreak such as at White Water can
occur if a variety of circumstances converge: A pool with low
levels of chlorine crowded with very young children, one of whom
had already contracted E. coli O157 and unknowingly exposed other
children to it. The only other known transmission of E. coli in a
pool was in South Georgia in 1996, when 11 children were infected.
</P>
<P>
   And investigators must be careful to look beyond surface
results, added Dr. Glyn Caldwell, the Kentucky state epidemiologist
tracking the Addison case. Not long ago he investigated a similar
swimming pool outbreak, of viruses that infected a swim team even
though their pool's chlorine levels were adequate. It turned out,
he said, that the pool's chlorinating equipment was broken; instead
of metering pool chemicals through the equipment, employees added
them to the water once a day by hand. Tests done in the morning
read within legal limits; but by evening, when the team swam, the
chemicals were almost gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you wind up with pieces that don't fit the pattern,'' he
said, ``you have to ask whether they're part of what you're looking
at _ or whether there are other sources that you need to test.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
