<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 20:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4654 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PEPSI-COX     06-30 0750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PEPSI-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pepsi rushes out new one-calorie cola on day artificial
sweetener is approved
 &HT;    By Mickey H. Gramig
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It's called acesulfame potassium, and Pepsi-Cola Co.
is hoping the calorie-free sweetener will be its ace in the hole.
</P>
<P>
   The Food and Drug Administration on Tuesday approved the
sweetener, also known as Ace-K, for use in soft drinks and other
liquid beverages.
</P>
<P>
   Pepsi-Cola greeted the news by rush-delivering 20-ounce bottles
of Pepsi One, a new Ace-K and aspartame-sweetened cola, to bottlers
and others in the soft drink industry. The company says a massive
national rollout of the one-calorie beverage will follow in 12 to
15 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I truly believe that with Pepsi One, we have the opportunity
to re-energize the refreshment beverage category and reinforce
Pepsi's role as the industry's leading innovator,'' Philip A.
Marineau, president and chief executive officer of Pepsi-Cola North
America, said in a letter to bottlers.
</P>
<P>
   Diet Pepsi will remain on the market ``because we believe that a
two-product strategy provides the best opportunity to make a
significant change in our long-term competitive position,'' said
Marineau, whose company trails Coca-Cola by 13 market share
percentage points in the United States and nearly 30 points
worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta-based Coca-Cola Co. said it has no immediate plans to
use the sweetener in the United States, despite Pepsi-Cola's
announcement. Coca-Cola began using Ace-K in Europe in 1991, and
now uses it in more than 50 countries.
</P>
<P>
   'Another option' for Coke
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of experience with Ace-K,'' Chairman and Chief
Executive M. Douglas Ivester said recently during an investors
meeting. ``We know it. We understand it. We have supply
relationships with those people.''
</P>
<P>
   He said it would be ``a fairly simple thing'' to add Ace-K to
Coca-Cola's mix of sweeteners used in the United States, but called
it ``just another sweetener option.''
</P>
<P>
   The long-awaited FDA approval is being hailed as a way to shore
up sagging diet soda sales in the United States, where the April
approval of sucralose was the first soft drink sweetener innovation
since aspartame was approved in 1981. Almost all U.S. diet soft
drinks use aspartame, which is sold under the brand name
Nutrasweet, though Triarc Co.'s Royal Crown Cola has now switched
to Splenda, the brand name for sucralose.
</P>
<P>
   Other soft drink companies haven't reformulated or introduced
brands using sucralose, analysts said, because it was assumed the
FDA would soon give its blessing to Ace-K.
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly looks like they were ready,'' Caroline Levy, a
beverage analyst with Schroder Wertheim, said regarding Pepsi One's
splash into the marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pepsi is looking very eagerly for a way to have an edge on
Coke because they're being beaten so handily,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coke will see how Pepsi does with it, and if consumers like
it, they'll do it, too,'' said Levy, who thinks the company might
be a little nervous about tinkering with its Diet Coke formula.
</P>
<P>
   Introduced in 1988
</P>
<P>
   Ace-K, made by the Hoechst subsidiary Nutrinova and sold under
the brand name Sunett, was introduced in the United States in 1988,
when the FDA said it could be used in table-top sweeteners, chewing
gum and dry mixes for beverages, desserts and dairy products. It's
200 times sweeter than sugar, and is said to not have the
aftertaste of other artificial sweeteners.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, in soft drinks, Ace-K is blended with other
sweeteners, such as aspartame. The resulting blend has a longer
shelf life than other sweeteners, and could shave a few pennies per
case off the price of soft drinks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The diet segment has long needed a healthy dose of news and
excitement, and I think this has the potential for reinvigorating
it,'' said John D. Sicher, publisher of Beverage Digest. ``I'm sure
Coke is going to take a long, hard look at this.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Bellas, chairman and chief executive of Beverage
Marketing Corp., said soft drinks sweetened with Ace-K blends
compare more closely with sugar-sweetened drinks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the less than 100 percent sugar-sweetened category
will get a huge shot in the arm,'' Bellas said. ``It's not going to
set things on fire, though. It may take share away from the
existing diets or the existing colas. You have a much tougher
competitive environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
