<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 20:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4655 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ADVISORY-BOARDS-AZR &LR;      06-30 1208
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ADVISORY-BOARDS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS OWN ERS NEED ADVI SORY BOARD THAT WORKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JANE LARSON  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) - Margaret Cook runs ION Inc. with her husband, Leroy,
but felt she needed her own circle of business executives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to have an area of business that I could bounce ideas
off of from my point of view,'' said Cook, secretary/treasurer of
the Tempe-based company whose Investigators Anywhere Resource Line
is a referral service for private investigators.
</P>
<P>
   Lynwood Thomas, president of Pioneer Equipment Co. in Phoenix,
wanted to avoid that locked-in-the-office mentality and talk more
often with his peers in management about general business issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're in the mode of day-to-day working, that is when you
can make serious mistakes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Cook, Thomas and scores of other Phoenix-area entrepreneurs have
discovered that, contrary to popular belief, it need not be lonely
at the top. Having built successful businesses and wanting to do
more, they turn to round tables and other groups of outside
advisers to help them better manage their companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many of us can say brilliance and success have solved our
problems? A whole new set comes up,'' Cleveland consultant Donald
Jonovic said at a meeting last month of the Family Enterprise
Institute's Greater Phoenix chapter.
</P>
<P>
   And as Valley of the Sun companies grow, so does the popularity
of advisory groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``People recognize that the challenges are different, and it
doesn't hurt to be sitting across the table from each other,'' said
Tom Hartzler, whose accounting firm, Eide Bailly, recently set up
round tables for controllers of its client companies.
</P>
<P>
   Businesses also are realizing that they need more than the
entrepreneur at different stages of growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can lift ourselves up by the bootstraps only so high,''
Jonovic said.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond-the-bootstraps advisory groups can assume a variety of
forms.
</P>
<P>
   Cook and Thomas are among the entrepreneurs who have turned to
presidents' round tables, collegial groups of their peers who
gather monthly to hear speakers or exchange ideas. Others use more
structured, and more expensive, coach-led groups like The Executive
Committee for Emerging Entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
   An even more serious step is to set up an advisory board,
possibly including the company's lawyer and accountant, that meets
regularly to review the good and bad aspects of the business.
</P>
<P>
   Round tables are regular meetings of nine to 20 top executives,
typically chief executive officers or owners of small businesses,
chief financial officers or controllers, or local managers for
bigger businesses. Membership cuts across industries, ensuring
diversity and reducing any competitive worries. Some are targeted
at specific entrepreneurial groups, such as Cook's round table for
women in business, or at family-owned businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Groups might hear an employment law specialist one month and
discuss a member's new marketing idea the next. Because the groups
are small, entrepreneurs can talk about tailoring solutions to
their businesses, said Georgann Crosby of the Family Business
Roundtable Inc. consulting firm and facilitator for a Phoenix
Chamber of Commerce round table.
</P>
<P>
   Round tables are best suited for entrepreneurs whose businesses
are big enough to face employment and management issues but haven't
grown to the point where professional management takes over, said
Brad Routh, chief financial officer of Edson Electric Supply in
Phoenix and facilitator for another Phoenix Chamber round table.
</P>
<P>
   Round-table members must be open to new information and other
people's perspectives, Crosby and Routh said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hear different ones, and sometimes a light goes on, or
you're encouraged to confront inertia,'' Routh said.
</P>
<P>
   Round tables aren't intended to be a networking opportunity or a
substitute for outside boards, Routh cautions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talk about things people want to bring to the table. Things
are shared in confidence, but that's different from sharing your
financials,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   More structured groups, like The Executive Committee for
Emerging Entrepreneurs, focus on personal effectiveness. Groups
bring in speakers, share expertise with each other and meet
one-on-one with the business executive chairing the group.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Denning, who heads two Valley groups for the San
Diego-based organization, said entrepreneurs usually turn to his
group for help coping with growth or decline in their companies.
Usually lacking a business-school background, they are concerned
about making decisions properly, anticipating change and being held
accountable, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Spouses, attorneys or accountants frequently bring their own
agenda to discussion of a problem, Denning said, but in his groups
the relationship is between fellow CEOs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It requires a commitment to share and participate on both
sides,'' Denning said. ``People are paying for the combined
intellectual capacity of the members.''
</P>
<P>
   Costs vary from group to group. For example, round-table
memberships at the Phoenix Chamber cost $150 a year plus basic
dues, and Emerging Entrepreneurs memberships cost $5,400 a year
with a $400 one-time enrollment fee.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to round tables and executive groups, advisory
boards are put together by a particular small business and focus on
it alone.
</P>
<P>
   Jonovic, a strong supporter of advisory boards, admits that just
a small percentage of small businesses have boards with five or
more outside advisers. The main reasons, he believes, are that some
entrepreneurs don't fully trust outsiders and are worried about
losing control of their companies.
</P>
<P>
   Some companies also aren't ready for advisory boards, he said. A
company might not have formalized ownership agreements or have
installed the proper accounting procedures for tracking progress.
Or owners might not have agreed on their goals and personal reasons
for being in business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shareholders have to come to these answers,'' he said. ``A
board can't.''
</P>
<P>
   But once those issues are settled, an advisory board can provide
strategic oversight for a business and be a prelude to actually
having an outside board of directors.
</P>
<P>
   The advisory role is often a new one for traditional advisers
such as attorneys and financial planners, Jonovic said. Pulling
them together into quarterly board meetings provides mutual
education about the company and controls conflict of interest, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Cooks had an advisory board for two years until key members
moved away, Margaret Cook said. They are thinking of reinstituting
it because it helped give them new ideas, track the business'
progress and held them responsible.
</P>
<P>
   ``Entrepreneurs get so many new ideas all the time. It helps
them get focused,'' she said of an advisory board.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever form an advisory board takes, entrepreneurs say they
value the sharing of ideas and the camaraderie they get from
connecting with peers outside their own businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are many people willing to share their experience, and
all you have to do is ask,'' Margaret Cook said.
</P>
<P>
   Jane Larson can be reached at jane.larson(at)pni.com via e-mail.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
