<SLUG> BC-FORD-JEWELS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    More stolen Ford jewels found
 &HT;    By Val Ellicott
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Investigators have found still more gems
hidden inside the home of a man who has admitted peddling jewels
stolen from Palm Beach heiress Kathleen Ford.
</P>
<P>
   Federal agents and Palm Beach detectives recently found diamond
tennis bracelets and 131 strands of pearls stuffed inside an air
conditioning duct at Barry Marshall's home in Stuart, according to
court papers.
</P>
<P>
   The find, made sometime in the last month, marks at least the
second time agents have discovered a hidden cache of jewels inside
Marshall's home. In January, Marshall's wife directed federal
agents to a hidden compartment under a stairway where about 500
gems were concealed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We keep finding things,'' Assistant U.S. Attorney Nancy Vorpe
Quinlan said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The rings, necklaces, bracelets and brooches are among millions
of dollars in jewels that agents have linked to Alvaro Valdez of
Margate, who is believed to have burglarized the jewels and then
sold them to Marshall. Both men have pleaded guilty to driving
across state lines with jewels stolen from Ford's Palm Beach estate
in January 1997.
</P>
<P>
   About $2 million worth of the jewelry recovered so far belongs
to Ford, and she is making it quite clear she wants it back.
</P>
<P>
   ``There no longer exists any reason why her jewelry should not
be returned to her at this time,'' her attorneys said in a third
demand filed in court last month.
</P>
<P>
   Ford misses her diamonds so much she has offered to put up a $10
million bond to guarantee she will make the jewels available ``for
court and police use'' on 24 hours' notice.
</P>
<P>
   But federal prosecutors say the jewels aren't going anywhere, at
least until Marshall and Valdez are sentenced Sept. 25, by which
time the government will have had possession of the jewels almost
as long as Marshall and Valdez had them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Turning over evidence to third parties while the investigation
and prosecution are ongoing would create numerous practical
problems,'' Quinlan wrote in response to Ford's latest demand.
</P>
<P>
   She notes that Ford is only one of 80 people whose burglarized
jewels are being held by the government as evidence in the case
against the two men.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just about every victim has inquired when their property will
be returned to them,'' Quinlan said in court papers filed last
week.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
