A4658 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-STARR-600&AMP;ADD     06-30 1106
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-STARR-600&AMP;ADDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRAND JURY TESTIMONY PUTS TRIPP BACK IN SPOTLIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ps) 
 By JAMES BENNET   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Flanked by her son and daughter, Linda Tripp walked
into federal court Tuesday to testify before a grand jury, five
months after her furtive tape recordings of a confiding friend
turned Monica Lewinsky into a household name and turned the White
House upside down.
</P>
<P>
   Dressed in black, with her hair pulled back in a thick ponytail,
Mrs. Tripp arrived and left without commenting on her testimony,
which is expected to resume Thursday. Her lawyer, Anthony
Zaccagnini, said that as she left the grand jury, Mrs. Tripp told
him: ``I find it very easy to truthfully answer the questions posed
to me by the prosecutor and the grand jury.'' He did not respond to
questions.
</P>
<P>
   But a lawyer knowledgeable about the day's proceedings said that
the questioning before the grand jury covered a range of topics,
including how Mrs. Tripp met Ms. Lewinsky, a co-worker at the
Pentagon, and the chronology of their friendship. None of Mrs.
Tripp's tapes were played Tuesday, the lawyer said, but they may be
on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Tripp, who scores poorly in public opinion polls, is said
by associates to feel maligned by the press but to be convinced
that once her full story is told she will be vindicated. The
prominent appearance Tuesday of her children, Allison and Ryan,
seemed intended to demonstrate that she is a devoted mother, not a
slippery friend bent on writing a tell-all book and perhaps
toppling a president.
</P>
<P>
   As Mrs. Tripp remained inside the courthouse after her
testimony, the Tripp siblings stood silently beside Zaccagnini as
he made his statement. Allison, who is 19, lost a fight with a
grin, while Ryan, 22, did not bother to fight a frown, his hands
thrust in his pants pockets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to take this opportunity to introduce to you Linda's
children, Allison and Ryan,'' Zaccagnini said. ``Allison and Ryan
have asked me to convey to all of Linda's supporters their sincere
appreciation for the messages of support that have been provided to
Linda.''
</P>
<P>
   As she walked down a courthouse corridor after her testimony,
arm-in-arm with her daughter, Mrs. Tripp answered only one
question. How was it to have her children with her? ``It was
great,'' she said, reaching out to pat her son's back.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Tripp will probably not finish her testimony on Thursday,
according to one lawyer who spoke on condition of not being named.
But she may not appear again next week, he added, because Kenneth
Starr, the independent counsel, may choose to hear from other
witnesses before wrapping up with Mrs. Tripp.
</P>
<P>
   For the jurors, Tuesday was the first chance for face-to-face
scrutiny of the source of the voice they have heard repeatedly on
some 20 hours of tapes that Mrs. Tripp secretly recorded.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Starr declined to comment on Mrs. Tripp's
appearance. The White House also had little to say Tuesday about
her testimony. ``We'll let the American people come to their own
conclusions about Linda Tripp,'' said Jim Kennedy, a spokesman. One
administration official expressed irritation that Starr chose to
call a pivotal witness during President Clinton's trip to China,
but another said that the public was not paying attention as
Starr's investigation dragged on.
</P>
<P>
   The news media, after weeks of lower-profile witnesses parading
tersely past them to the grand jury, was transfixed Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Nathaniel Speights, one of Ms. Lewinsky's lawyers, turned up at
the courthouse on what he called unrelated business and found
himself pursued by a pack of reporters idling in a hallway. Asked
when he expected to negotiate an agreement with Starr's office over
the testimony of his client, who was away on a trip to California,
he replied: ``Give us a month.''
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   Away from the media glare at the courthouse, prosecutors and
lawyers representing President Clinton have secretly begun another
fight over legal privileges, this one involving a private
investigations firm employed by Clinton's personal lawyers. The
prosecutors have issued a subpoena to the firm, Investigative Group
Inc., and its top executive, Terry Lenzner, to see whether it has
dug up material about Ms. Lewinsky or prosecutors in Starr's
office.
</P>
<P>
   But two lawyers involved in the inquiry said that the firm had
resisted turning over material, citing the lawyer-client and
work-product privileges, two legal protections for the confidences
of lawyers and their clients. The lawyers said that Starr had asked
the federal district judge supervising the grand jury to enforce
the subpoena.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of a look at Mrs. Tripp, who has been secluded at
her suburban Maryland home, swelled the already formidable media
encampment outside the courthouse. ``There are a bunch of people
here, probably very lost, saying, `Wow, this is a federal
courthouse,''' said Bob Franken, the CNN correspondent who has
provided regular courthouse bulletins during the furious five
months of the Lewinsky investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Franken was seated on a director's chair on a two-foot stone
pedestal outside the courthouse. With a soundwoman in a crouch and
a cameraman at his lens, the elevated CNN crew, in still moments,
seemed a sculpture in fitting media-age counterpoint to the bronze
of Blackstone beside the courthouse entrance.
</P>
<P>
   A handful of those in Washington to take in the sights also
stopped by. ``I just thought, what the heck, maybe we'll see
something,'' said Clint Meyer of Detroit. But, with his daughter,
Tara, he had staked out the Constitution Avenue entrance this
morning, but Mrs. Tripp came in via Third Street.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   As Mrs. Tripp testified inside, Brian Wilson of Fox News
practiced his standup, declaring that ``witnesses'' had said that
Mrs. Tripp ``looked a bit nervous this morning, and rightfully so,
this is a very key moment in Ken Starr's investigation.'' David
Smith, of the British news service ITN, taped Wilson taping his
spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are you doing here, the media zoo thing?'' asked Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' Smith replied, ``Britain looks in and wonders what's
going on.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   As tourists photographed and videotaped the hundreds of
journalists, a self-mocking air took hold. ``OK, strike the set,''
called out Charlie Archambault, a photographer for ``U.S. News and
World Report,'' as Mrs. Tripp's van vanished into traffic.
</P>
<P>
   That, he added, was ``the First Amendment in action, kids.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
