A4659 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRAQ-ATTACK-ART-NYT &LR;      06-30 0645
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-ATTACK-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. JET FIGHTER FIRES MISSILE AT IRAQI ANTIAIRCRAFT BATTERY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(th) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ An American F-16 fired a missile at an Iraqi
antiaircraft battery Tuesday because the Iraqi forces had aimed
radar at one of four British jets patrolling the ``no flight'' zone
over southern Iraq, officials here said.
</P>
<P>
   The F-16 was accompanying the British planes and five other
American jets on patrol just north of Basra. Its missile missed,
the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The Iraqi Culture and Information Ministry said the missile
struck a drinking-water reservoir near Basra and accused the United
States of ``an aggressive and unjustifiable action,'' Reuters
reported from Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
   The incident was the first American military action inside Iraq
since 1996, when American jets twice fired missiles at Iraqi
antiaircraft batteries that had aimed radar at them.
</P>
<P>
   At the White House and the Pentagon, senior officials said it
was not clear if the Iraqis were actually preparing to fire on the
British jets. Vice President Al Gore suggested the use of radar,
often an indication of an imminent missile firing, did not seem to
be ``a deliberate provocation.''
</P>
<P>
   Either way, the American-led patrols consider aiming radar at
allied aircraft to be a provocation and thus a reason to strike.
</P>
<P>
   All the British and American jets returned safely to their bases
in Kuwait and Saudi Arabia, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   It was possible, the officials said, that the Iraqis were
testing the resolve of the American, British and French forces to
continue the patrols at a time of growing disagreement among the
allies over ending the sanctions imposed after Iraq invaded Kuwait
in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's strike also came only a month after the United States
sharply reduced the size of American forces in the Persian Gulf,
forces that had been increased during last winter's confrontation
over U.N. weapons inspections.
</P>
<P>
   Defense Secretary William Cohen said Tuesday that the patrols
over the ``no flight'' zone, which extends to the 33rd parallel
just south of Baghdad, would continue unchanged.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that we should draw any conclusions from this
particular one incident,'' Cohen said. ``Obviously, if the
situation changes, then we would change our plans.''
</P>
<P>
   American, British and French jets have patrolled the ``no
flight'' zone over southern Iraq since August 1992, when Iraq used
air power to suppress Shiite Muslims rebelling against Saddam
Hussein's government. Within the zone, the allies prohibit the
movement of any aircraft or heavy weaponry on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   The aircraft involved in Tuesday's incident _ four British
Tornado GR1s, four F-16s and two American EA-6B electronic-jamming
jets _ are among the nearly 200 that regularly patrol the zone,
flying 80 to 120 sorties a day.
</P>
<P>
   The officials said the Iraqi battery, equipped with SA-3
surface-to-air missiles, fixed its radar on the British jets long
enough for the American F-16 to fire its missile, which is designed
to follow radar beams to their source. Almost immediately after
firing, however, the radar stopped its transmissions and the
missile missed, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Iraq has in the past taken aim at the patrols, and the situation
in the ``no flight'' zone is, as one senior administration official
put it, ``always at a semi-boil.''
</P>
<P>
   But Tuesday's incident followed a period of relative calm, and
Cohen said Iraq had not recently moved its air defenses or taken
any other military steps that would suggest a new military
confrontation with the United States. The United States still has
20,000 troops in the region and 22 warships plying the Persian
Gulf. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
