<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 20:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4662 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NUHN-COX     06-30 0613
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NUHN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BASEBALL COMMENTARY: Weiss not an all-star shortstop
 &HT;    By Gary Nuhn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ I have a question: Why Walt Weiss?
</P>
<P>
   Let me rephrase that: Why in the world Walt Weiss?
</P>
<P>
   Fine fellow.
</P>
<P>
   But an All-Star shortstop? I don't think so.
</P>
<P>
   I don't want to get into a Barry Larkin rant here, but on his
worst day, after he has gone 0 for his last 30 and pulled a
hamstring, Larkin is on my lineup card before Weiss. They are equal
defensively and in the runs-produced category (runs plus
runs-batted-in minus home runs), Larkin leads Weiss 71-50.
</P>
<P>
   We have been down this road of fans' All-Star voting before.
</P>
<P>
   Fans are neat little creatures who should be allowed in to see
Mark McGwire take batting practice, allowed to boo whomever they
choose and encouraged to return often.
</P>
<P>
   But I truly believe no fan should be given an All-Star ballot
without passing a test. It wouldn't be hideously difficult _ let's
just say 250 questions.
</P>
<P>
   Sample: ``Was Baby Ruth the candy bar named for Babe Ruth the
man?''
</P>
<P>
   Sample: ``What is the link between the names Tracy Stallard and
Sal Durante?''
</P>
<P>
   Sample: ``If a train carrying the Reds left Cincinnati traveling
west at 92 mph, and another train with the Astros on board left
Houston traveling west at 92 mph, would the Reds ever catch the
Astros, and why did neither team think of taking a plane?''
</P>
<P>
   (Answers below.)
</P>
<P>
   But seriously, Walt Weiss?
</P>
<P>
   I'd ask who were the 1,159,960 people who voted for Walt Weiss,
but the answer is self-evident. This is the perfect example of what
happens when you hand ballots to every man, woman, child or space
creature occupying a seat. Colorado leads the NL in home
attendance; Atlanta is next. Weiss played in Colorado for the last
four years and plays in Atlanta now.
</P>
<P>
   He is thus the perfect All-Star candidate.
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't the only retreat from reality in the NL's starting
lineup announced Monday.
</P>
<P>
   How can you have an All-Star starting team in 1998 without Sammy
Sosa? The guy's got 33 home runs, 78 runs batted in and blows
kisses to the camera every time he gets back to the dugout after a
dinger. What other credentials does he need?
</P>
<P>
   It's nice that Larry Walker had an MVP season in 1997, but he is
a faint shadow of that player this year (9 homers, 33 RBIs). In
addition, he has missed 16 games and is on the disabled list. But _
oh, look _ he plays for Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, I question the validity of the entire starting
outfield. Barry Bonds (17 HR, 57 RBIs) is being outplayed by Greg
Vaughn (26 HR, 66 RBIs). And although I like Tony Gwynn, Brian
Jordan is having a better season. As is Moises Alou. As is Vladimir
Guerrero.
</P>
<P>
   One other thing the NL shortstop voting tells us is the immense
gulf between the two leagues at baseball's most important position.
The American League has four legitimate All-Star shortstops _ Nomar
Garciaparra, Derek Jeter, Alex Rodriguez and Omar Vizquel. The NL
has Walt Weiss.
</P>
<P>
   I have volunteered in the past _ every year, actually _ to be a
one-person selection committee to do away with the mockery. For
reasons unexplained, I've not yet been contacted by those in
authority.
</P>
<P>
   I assume that means they're still considering my offer.
</P>
<P>
   (Answers to baseball quiz: The candy bar was named for the
daughter of President Grover Cleveland; Stallard threw the pitch
that Roger Maris whammered for his 61st home run and Durante, a
19-year-old, caught it in the right field stands; and no, the Reds
won't catch the Astros in this decade, by plane, train or
automobile.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
