u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARV-ALBERT-NYT &LR;      06-30 0982
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARV-ALBERT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER DECADES OF WORK FOR ALBERT, SILENCE  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICHARD SANDOMIR    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Marv Albert's life is one without work. Nine months
after pleading guilty to misdemeanor assault three days into an
embarrassing trial, he attends movies; reads voraciously; plays
tennis with Kenny, his oldest son, and his brother, Steve; walks
his new pugs, Lulu and Ruby, and plans a future with his fiancee,
Heather Faulkiner, from their duplex apartment on Columbus Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``You shouldn't think he's having a good time,'' said Steve
Albert, a boxing announcer for Showtime and the youngest of the
three Albert brothers. ``It's been a rough go. He's very anxious to
start working again.''
</P>
<P>
   Albert did not call a National Basketball Association game last
season for the first time in 30 years, but followed the league
passionately via his satellite dish. ``He watches as a fan and
aficionado, but can't resist zinging me for my overreactions to
things,'' said John Andariese, Albert's friend and former sidekick
on the MSG Network's Knick telecasts. ``He knows the roster of all
29 teams, and if you say, `Denver Nuggets,' he knows their
broadcast team.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Albert, who watched Game 3 of the NBA finals with his
brother and Andariese, added: ``It's so novel to watch with him. I
don't know if he finds it tough watching, not being there. But he
doesn't express bitterness to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Once very accessible to reporters, Albert did a series of
television interviews just after his guilty plea but has refused
all requests since. He declined to be interviewed for this article,
which was assembled from talking to friends, associates and
relatives.
</P>
<P>
   Albert has not worked as a broadcaster since calling a Baltimore
Ravens-Giants game for NBC last Sept. 14. One month later, his
unexpected guilty plea led to his being fired by NBC and to his
resignation from the MSG Network.
</P>
<P>
   There appear to be no immediate prospects for work, although
employers may be waiting for Albert to complete the year of
psychiatric counseling that was ordered by a Virginia judge. If
Albert completes the counseling and does not break the law for a
year, the charges against him are to be dismissed. ``Marv
understands the situation and the need for future employers to
perceive him in a state of normalcy,'' Andariese said. ``He knows
the price of fame and is prepared to deal with the price of his
fame.''
</P>
<P>
   Added a friend, ``He needs to be cleansed.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing came of discussions about a talk show on New York's WFAN
and the television play-by-play job for the Miami Heat. A planned
meeting with Turner Sports, the NBA's cable partner, has not
occurred. ``I'd have been foolish not to talk to him,'' said Don
Sperling, who is running the sports operations of the Miami
television station that recently bought the Heat's rights. But the
team would not consider Albert, and rehired the incumbent
announcer. ``He was available, so it behooved us to go after him,''
Sperling said.
</P>
<P>
   Joel Hollander, the general manager of WFAN, said: ``He's really
ready, just waiting to go. But deep down, he knows things won't be
the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Albert's best prospect may be a return to MSG as the permanent
host of the nightly ``MSG SportsDesk,'' replacing the departed Bob
Page, and sharing the Knicks' radio play-by-play job on WFAN with
Gus Johnson. But there is no guarantee of such a return to his old
employer. A Madison Square Garden spokesman would not comment on
its interest in Albert.
</P>
<P>
   According to people who know him, Albert's familiar sarcastic
edge has been blunted, and he is humbler, after the public
spectacle of being charged with sodomy and assault after a February
1997 hotel meeting with a former lover, Vanessa Perhach. The
subsequent news media stampede turned him into the tabloids'
delight.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's dealing with this in a very straight-on way,'' Steve
Albert said. ``I've seen no traces of a `Why me?' attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   Albert maintains a low profile, although he can be seen at local
restaurants, movie theaters and in Central Park. At the start of
his legal imbroglio, he said he would not hole up in his apartment,
that he had nothing to be ashamed of.
</P>
<P>
   Albert has not talked to reporters since his post-sentencing
tour to chat with Barbara Walters, Larry King, David Letterman and
Katie Couric last October. Memorably, he told Walters on ABC's
``20/20'' that during an ``experimental'' phase in his life he met
a transvestite and dominatrix.
</P>
<P>
   Albert and Faulkiner have not married, but friends expect them
to wed soon. She has returned to work, producing freelance reports
for ESPN.
</P>
<P>
   People familiar with Albert's lifestyle say it has been pared
back because of his lack of salary and the high cost of his
defense. ``I presume he's enjoying the benefits of his fame over
many years,'' Andariese said. ``I presume the legal fees didn't
wipe him out. If there were trouble, I'd feel it.''
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer for Perhach would not comment on whether she has
received any payment from Albert in return for not filing a civil
lawsuit. Evan Bell, Albert's manager, also declined to comment. But
Andariese said, ``I'd say he feels all his legal problems have been
taken care of.''
</P>
<P>
   That, of course, is what any future employer hopes. But will an
employer take a risk on Albert, whose talent is unquestioned but
whose image has been forever altered? Will fans and viewers accept
or deride him? What will advertisers tell any network or local
station or regional sports network?
</P>
<P>
   One industry official said, ``Sponsors are afraid if viewers
would be thinking about anything but the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Albert's partisans believe any backlash will be brief. ``Marv's
prepared for anything,'' Steve Albert said. ``He'd be so thrilled
to be back behind the microphone that he has to expect whatever
comes.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-98 2046EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980630.0356 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 20:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4668 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-PEONY-NYT &LR;      06-30 0856
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-PEONY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CULTURE CZAR GETS HER WAY AND BLOCKS `THE PEONY PAVILION' 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: CHINA-CLINTON, CHINA-NOTEBOOK, CHINA-TAIWAN,
HONGKONG-ANNIVERSARY, ASIA-RUBIN) 
 (HLW)  
 By SETH FAISON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHANGHAI _ Nigel Redden, the director of the Lincoln Center
Festival, announced here on Tuesday night that his struggle with
local culture authorities over how to produce ``The Peony
Pavilion'' had finally ended in failure.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Shanghai Bureau of Culture has not given permission
for the company's actors to depart by this Friday as previously
agreed, Redden said, it has become impossible to perform the
classic Chinese opera as a centerpiece of the Lincoln Center
Festival in New York next Tuesday. Logistics involved in arranging
visas and travel for the actors required that a decision be made by
today, he said.
</P>
<P>
   After hoping for an eleventh-hour breakthrough, following 10
days of muddled and confusing negotiations, Redden realized his
efforts were doomed on Tuesday afternoon when Ma Bomin, the
director of the Bureau of Culture, said she was too busy to see
him. As he neared a site outside the city where members of the
Shanghai Kunju Opera Company were rehearsing, his car passed hers,
going in the opposite direction.
</P>
<P>
   Any hope for intervention by President Clinton, who arrived in
Shanghai on Monday evening, seemed to evaporate on Tuesday. In
fact, Ms. Ma could not wait at rehearsal for Redden, she told
others, because she was busy arranging a cultural performance at a
reception for President Clinton that was given by Mayor Xu Kuangdi
at the Shanghai Museum.
</P>
<P>
   At the same hour Clinton was feted by the mayor and Ms. Ma on
Tuesday night, Redden somberly told a news conference in the Garden
Hotel that his hopes for staging a exceptional 55-act version of
``The Peony Pavilion'' were now over. He plans to fly back to New
York on Wednesday. Chen Shi-Zheng, the director hired by Lincoln
Center, also plans to leave Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's really something very sad about something very good
being leveled in this way,'' Redden said. ``It was a monumental
show. It's heartbreaking to lose it.''
</P>
<P>
   The timing of Clinton's visit to China and plans to perform
``The Peony Pavilion'' in the United States were coincidental.
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton's visit so far has been characterized by a spirit
of openness and cooperation between Washington and Beijing, the
failure of such a high-profile example of cultural exchange between
the two countries offers a sour counterpoint. It is also a reminder
of the strength of a Communist Party-run system where government
officials wield substantial power over all manner of life,
including artistic projects.
</P>
<P>
   Redden flew here on June 22, a few days after Shanghai's Bureau
of Culture suddenly blocked shipment of the elaborate sets,
costumes, and props for the classic Chinese opera, raising
objections to the innovative staging of the production, and calling
it too `feudal,' `superstitious' and `pornographic.'
</P>
<P>
   After three days of difficult negotiations, and a dramatic
confrontation with officials at Shanghai's Hongqiao International
Airport, he left for Hong Kong last Thursday, but came back the
next day to try again. All along, Redden said, he had difficulty
discerning whether the mixed signals he got from Bureau of Culture
officials reflected a willingness to negotiate or a drawn-out
rejection.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Ms. Ma, Yuan Huiguo, said that she was
unavailable for comment and that no information was available about
the government's position.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday evening, as he sipped a gin and tonic in a hotel
lounge, Redden lamented the thought that ``The Peony Pavilion,'' as
Chen directed it, and the Kunju Opera Company rehearsed it for
eight months, might never be performed again. Redden himself saw
only small parts of the opera in rehearsal.
</P>
<P>
   Chen, sitting at the same table, said he felt particularly
wounded by the way the actors he worked with for so long had been
partly broken by political circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a deep fear now,'' Chen said. ``It's going to take a
long time before that fear is taken away.''
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, the Lincoln Center Festival repeated its view
that a contract between Lincoln Center and the Shanghai Kunju Opera
Company had been improperly violated, since it was approved by the
Bureau of Culture last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We find this decision truly incomprehensible,'' the statement
said. ``Lincoln Center and Chen have made every effort in the past
10 days to address the concerns of the Bureau of Culture.''
</P>
<P>
   Redden, still unsure what would appear on stage at Lincoln
Center on July 7, said it was likely that each of the performances
at this summer's festival would include a reading of a statement
about artistic freedom.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't realize how much artistic freedom you have until you
come to a place like this and see how easily it can be taken
away,'' Redden said.
</P>
<P>
   Lincoln Center, he also said, will most likely take legal action
against Shanghai officials for breaking a contract worth several
hundred thousand dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
