<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASIA-RUBIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUBIN IS OPTIMISTIC ON THAI SUPPORT FOR IMF REQUIREMENTS 
(JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARK LANDLER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea _ As he continued to gather damage reports
from the crisis-torn economies of Asia, Treasury Secretary Robert
Rubin expressed optimism on Tuesday that the political leaders of
Thailand would be able to marshal public support for the difficult
work of reforming that economy.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin arrived in Seoul late Tuesday night, the final stop of his
six-day four-country tour, after a morning of meetings in Bangkok
with Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai, other senior officials and
business executives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Speaking with the prime minister I thought they felt they had
the public support they needed to proceed on the path,'' Rubin said
in a briefing with reporters on the flight to Seoul. He added that
among Thailand leaders ``there was a recognition that a sufficient
social safety net was important.''
</P>
<P>
   Rubin has urged leaders on each stop of his trip to create
adequate ``safety nets.''
</P>
<P>
   The trip began on Friday in Beijing and ends on Wednesday here.
With Thailand and its neighbors facing an economic contraction of 5
to 10 percent this year, Rubin is plainly worried that unless
people are cushioned from the blow, the dislocation could erupt
into social unrest.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin did not visit Indonesia on this trip, in part because its
capital, Jakarta, was ablaze in riots and arson fires when the trip
was being planned. The turmoil there has shadowed Rubin's trip, a
reminder that the Asian crisis is now less about daily fluctuations
in the ringgit or the rupiah than about the price of basic staples
like food and fuel.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to build a social safety net,'' Mari Pangetsu,
executive director of the Center for Strategic and International
Studies, a research institute, in Jakarta, said. ``This is not just
an economic issue, but a political issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the International Monetary Fund say its rescue
packages for the region have raised the risk of social unrest, with
an emphasis on high interest rates. That has stabilized currencies,
but it has also choked off credit and brought commercial activity
to a near standstill.
</P>
<P>
   In Thailand the opposition has used adherence to the IMF plan as
a club against the government.
</P>
<P>
   But Rubin rejected those criticisms, saying: ``The IMF has not
tried to be Draconian.'' He noted that the fund had begun to show
added flexibility in fiscal policy, as the economic pain in those
countries worsened. In Thailand, for example, the fund has
permitted the government to swing from a budget surplus to a
deficit to free up money for new social programs.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin acknowledged that the crisis had led to ``enormous
hardships for the people of Thailand.'' But in a speech to business
students at Chulalongkorn University in Bangkok he said: ``The
economic difficulties are a product of the crisis, not of the
reform programs your nation has adopted.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite some pointed questions the students gave Rubin a
standing ovation. In general, Rubin appeared more enthusiastic
about Thailand than his previous stop, Malaysia. There he held a
cordial but inconclusive meeting with Prime Minister Mahathir
Mohamad, who faults the West and what he calls its unscrupulous
currency traders for much of the Asian crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin, who oversaw the currency-trading desk at Goldman, Sachs
in New York before joining the Clinton administration, said
Mahathir had raised the issue of short-term capital flows and their
harm in the meeting. ``We didn't really engage in a debate,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   In South Korea, Rubin plans to meet with President Kim Dae-jung,
other senior officials, labor leaders, and the heads of the five
largest conglomerates, Daewoo, Samsung, Hyundai, LG, and the SK
Group.
</P>
<P>
   Like the cases with Thailand and Malaysia, Korea's economy has
shifted into reverse in the last six months. Its output shrank 3.8
percent in the first quarter of 1998, and unemployment war running
at to 6.7 percent. The prospect of growing layoffs has led to
strikes, including a general walkout last month.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin said he would seek an update on the government's efforts
to reform its troubled banking system. The meeting with the
executives could prove interesting, because analysts say the
conglomerates, known as chaebols, have dragged their feet on
cleaning up their debt-laden balance sheets.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
