<HEADER>
A4670 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOLF-FEATURE01-COX     06-30 0530
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLF-FEATURE01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Women face a gentler Open
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KOHLER, Wis. _ Fortunately, the United States Golf Association
doesn't get quite as carried away with its setup for the U.S.
Women's Open as it does annually with the men's U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   If you've already forgotten, the most memorable highlight of Lee
Janzen's win at The Olympic Club 10 days ago will not include Lee
Janzen. It will star the red-plaid-knickered Payne Stewart at the
conclusion of his Friday round, helplessly observing his golf ball
roll slowly, dimple by dimple, from a point just inches under the
cup to an eventual point 25 feet down the slope of the 18th green.
</P>
<P>
   Putt-putt golf, John Daly called it, and who could argue?
</P>
<P>
   This week, Blackwolf Run Golf Course won't be as severe, nor as
comical and embarrassing for the USGA. As setups for women's
tournaments go, this one will rank as tough, but far more
reasonable than Olympic.
</P>
<P>
   The rough won't be as rough. It was as high as 7 inches at some
spots at Olympic. The highest grass at Blackwolf Run will be cut at
approximately 3 inches in the primary rough, 1 1/2 inches in the
intermediate zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think 3-inch rough for ladies golf is somewhat
comparable to 5-inch rough for men's golf, when you bring in the
strength factor,'' said Tom Meeks, USGA director of rules and
competitions. ``I think it would be very unfair to hit out of
5-inch rough at the Women's Open.''
</P>
<P>
   The greens won't be as fast, either _ similar firmness, perhaps,
but not those readings of 12.8 on the stimpmeter that were common
at Olympic when things dried out. Figure on 10 to start with, Meeks
said, maybe 10.6 by the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The fairways won't be cut quite as tight for lies _ one-half
inch, compared with three-eighths at Olympic, and will be 30-34
yards wide. At Olympic, other than the 17th, they were 26-30 yards
wide.
</P>
<P>
   If things go as planned, none of Pete Dye's greens at Blackwolf
Run will turn into the circus that was OIympic's 18th.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just chose a hole location on Friday we thought would work,
and it didn't, and I blame nobody but me,'' Meeks said. ``When you
set holes for the Open, you're flirting with the edge, anyway. You
do this long enough, you're going to set a bad one.''
</P>
<P>
   The subject of widespread criticism last week, Meeks is not
setting holes for the Women's Open. Judy Bell, the USGA past
president, has that job. Meeks is here this week only because
Kendra Graham, the USGA's director of women's competitions, is on
maternity leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't been put on probation,'' Meeks said, chuckling.
``Even if Kendra were here, Judy would still be setting the
holes.''
</P>
<P>
   Meeks' main job this week is monitoring the pace of play, and at
the U.S. Women's Open that's a huge task by itself. Thursday and
Friday at this event are probably the longest two days in
tournament golf. Two years ago at Pine Needles, the field of 150
players _ 50 threesomes off the No. 1 tee only _ failed to finish
Thursday night before darkness. And that was without a weather
delay.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
