<SLUG> BC-BOEING-PAYROLL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOEING DELAYS SCALING DOWN COMMERCIAL DIVISION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KAREN WEST  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The Boeing Co. won't be able to eliminate 12,000
commercial aircraft jobs this year as planned because there's still
too much work to be done to bring the company's ailing assembly
lines back to full health.
</P>
<P>
   While companywide employment has already dropped slightly,
Boeing won't begin scaling back its commercial division payroll in
earnest until later this year, company spokesman Peter Conte said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing executives will most likely address employment issues
this morning when they give progress reports on the company's
aircraft production recovery program to analysts and news media.
</P>
<P>
   The company has been struggling since October to fill all of its
commercial airplane orders on time _ mainly next-generation 737s _
because of parts shortages, lack of trained assembly workers, a
rapid increase in production rates and other manufacturing
bottlenecks.
</P>
<P>
   Last December, Boeing announced that employment in its
Renton-based commercial aircraft division would drop by 12,000 this
year, beginning in mid-year as aircraft production peaks and
assembly line bottlenecks are cleared up.
</P>
<P>
   But because the company is still in the production recovery mode
with continuing backups on its 737 production lines in Renton, the
number of job reductions will be lower than originally planned.
</P>
<P>
   While a delay in job cuts appears to be good news for workers,
analysts had viewed Boeing's previously announced plans to reduce
employment as a sign that the company's production woes were behind
them and improved earnings were ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``This could be a precursor to another charge (against corporate
earnings),'' analyst Paul Nisbet with JSA Research in Newport,
R.I., said Tuesday. ``They are going to be keeping a few more
thousand people for a longer period of time and that amounts to
money.''
</P>
<P>
   Boeing already has spent nearly $3 billion in its effort to get
its troubled aircraft production lines back to normal.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Boeing was forced to make costly design changes on
its new 737 models to gain approval from U.S. and European aviation
authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Write-offs for manufacturing problems combined with costs for
absorbing McDonnell Douglas Corp. resultedin a loss of $178
million last year. It was Boeing's first loss in 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing's Conte said it's too early to tell what the actual
number of job cuts will be by year end.
</P>
<P>
   ``The intention is still there to reduce BCAG (Boeing's
commercial division) employment by 12,000; it just won't be this
year,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Conte said as soon as Boeing gets its assembly lines running
smoothly again, the company will begin reducing employment first
through attrition, then layoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they bring back the lines to full health, then you have the
opportunity to not replace people as they retire, resign or move on
to other positions,'' he said. ``But right now, the work is still
there.''
</P>
<P>
   In May, Boeing executives said the company's production recovery
plan was slightly ahead of schedule but that airline customers
could expect delivery delays on certain models through the end of
the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that things are slipping is not good news,'' Nisbet
said. ``At one time they said they'd be up to full (production)
speed by the end of the second quarter and that slipped to the end
of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   Boeing is increasing total production of all jetliners to 49 a
month in the third quarter and is at maximum capacity in Renton
where the 737 and 757 jets are built.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the company plans to deliver 550 commercial jets this
year. As of May 27, Boeing had delivered 189.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, companywide employment figures released Tuesday show
that as of June 1, Boeing had 238,400 employees.
</P>
<P>
   That's actually 800 more than the company employed as of May 1.
But about 400 of the new hires are summer interns and 300 are
university graduates who were hired as part of Boeing's college
recruitment program, Conte said.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing started out the year with about 238,600 employees
companywide, of which 103,420 were in Washington state.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent employment numbers (as of June 1) show that
Boeing has 104,000 employees in Washington state; 42,300 in
California; 22,000 in St. Louis; 22,000 in Wichita, Kan.; 6,000 in
Philadelphia; and 42,100 in other locations throughout the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
