<SLUG> BC-OBIT-BREZHNEV-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GALINA BREZHNEV, 69, HIGH-LIVING DAUGHTER OF FORMER DICTATOR  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Galina Brezhnev, the high-living daughter of the former
Soviet leader Leonid Brezhnev whose antics often led to scandal,
died on Tuesday in a Moscow hospital. She was 69.
</P>
<P>
   Russian news agencies said she is to be cremated on Wednesday.
There were no details about the cause of death.
</P>
<P>
   Galina Brezhnev was never involved in politics but she figured
in some major scandals in the last years of Soviet power. The
arrests of some of her husbands and some of her friends illuminated
the corruption of the Soviet aristocracy.
</P>
<P>
   A hard-drinking member of the Soviet elite who liked to race her
father's Mercedes, Ms. Brezhnev had her first brush with scandal
when she was just 22 and ran away with a circus acrobat.
</P>
<P>
   ``He could hold 10 people on his shoulders but failed to hold
Galina too long,'' NTV television observed on Tuesday night.
``Galina got married quite often.'' She remained infatuated with
the circus and with circus performers for several decades.
</P>
<P>
   In 1982, a close friend from the circus, known as Boris the
Gypsy, was arrested and charged with smuggling. The arrest took
place when Yuri Andropov was head of the KGB, and Andropov
portrayed the move as part of his anti-corruption drive. But it was
also interpreted as a bid by Andropov to position himself to
succeed Brezhnev as Soviet leader. Brezhnev died in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   That was not the end of her notoriety: In 1988, her husband Yuri
Churbanov was arrested for taking bribes and imprisoned for six
years. Churbanov had been a lieutenant colonel in the police when
he met Ms. Brezhnev and was promoted to post of chief deputy
interior minister soon after their marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Coming in the early years of reform under Mikhail Gorbachev, the
Churbanov case sent an important political signal: that no one was
above the law.
</P>
<P>
   After Churbanov was jailed, Ms. Brezhnev said she was unaware of
his bribe-taking and divorced him, saying he had been a bad
husband. Churbanov was released from prison in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Despite her brushes with scandal, Ms. Brezhnev retained her
privileges and comfortable life style. She won a law suit for the
return of a Mercedes and other valuables confiscated from
Churbanov.
</P>
<P>
   There were no details on Tuesday night about survivors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-98 2057EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980630.0362 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 20:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4675 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POPE-LETTER-NYT &LR;      06-30 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPE-LETTER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POPE ACTS TO STIFFLE DISSENT ON CONTROVERSIAL ISSUES 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ In one of his sharpest rebukes to liberal Catholics to
date, Pope John Paul II on Tuesday made changes to canon law aimed
at stamping out debate on a wide range of passionately-discussed
issues, including euthanasia and the ordination of women.
</P>
<P>
   Reasserting the articles of faith that are ``definitive'' and
binding to all Catholics, the pope on Tuesday inscribed those
teachings into church law, and warned that those who dissent would
be subject to ``just punishment.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Roman Catholic theologians in the United States have
questioned Rome's authority on doctrinal matters. In an Apostolic
letter that was released by the Vatican on Tuesday, the pope made
it quite clear that he was addressing _ and reining in _ those
academics.
</P>
<P>
   The Apostolic letter was both an act of Vatican housekeeping and
a cornerstone laid down for this pope's legacy. On one hand, the
pope was merely filling a gap in the code of canon law, but his
eagerness to make his teachings as clear _ and as binding _ as
possible was one of the most vivid signs yet that in the twilight
of his papacy, Pope John Paul II, at 78, is seeking to make his
rulings irreversible.
</P>
<P>
   The pope explained he was acting ``to defend the faith of the
Catholic Church against errors that arise on the part of some of
the faithful, above all those who dedicate themselves to the
disciplines of holy theology.''
</P>
<P>
   The pope's letter addressed the church's ``profession of
faith,'' a list of essential Catholic beliefs that the pope
reformulated in 1989. All clergymen and Catholic teachers and
theologians are required to follow it.
</P>
<P>
   By inscribing his teachings about the articles of faith into
canon law, Pope John Paul II said he was establishing norms that
would ``impose the duty to observe the truths.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's decree is likely to disappoint those theologians who
had hoped to keep open a discussion of women's ordination, among
other things. But John Paul II had previously made his opposition
to any such deliberations well known.
</P>
<P>
   The Apostolic letter did not specify which teachings the pope
was addressing, but it was published along with a highly detailed
doctrinal commentary written by Cardinal Joseph Ratzinger, who
heads the Congregation for the Doctrine of the Faith, and who is
the Vatican's leading conservative thinker. Ratzinger's definitions
of what constitutes ``infallibly taught'' doctrine are likely to
rekindle debate among the very theologians the Vatican had hoped to
silence.
</P>
<P>
   Dissenters, the cardinal warned, ``would be in a position of
rejecting a truth of Catholic doctrine and would therefore no
longer be in full communion with the Catholic Church.'' The
consequences could range from warnings to excommunication.
</P>
<P>
   It was not the first time the pope has moved to bring dissenting
theologians to heel. Father Charles Curran, an American priest who
differed with the Vatican on contraception, homosexuality and other
issues, was stripped of his right to teach Catholic theology at
Catholic University in Washington, D.C., in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Last year the Vatican excommunicated a Sri Lankan priest, Tissa
Balasuriya, for challenging papal authority and key teachings. The
decision was reversed after he signed the profession of faith.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, the Vatican added a category of fundamental truths _
such as the ban on contraception and on marriage of priests. At the
same time the Vatican broadened the requirement for Catholic
leaders to pledge fidelity to these truths to include theologians
teaching in Church-sponsored schools and universities, not just
members of the clergy. Many American Catholics viewed this as a
blow to academic freedom.
</P>
<P>
   Now, there is a fear that canon law could be used to further
clamp down on dissent. ``The obvious purpose could be to unite the
church but the real consequence could be to divide it,'' said
Father Richard McBrien, a professor of Theology at the University
of Notre Dame, in South Bend, Ind. ``The last thing the Catholic
church needs is heresy-hunting or demands for oath-taking or any
finger-pointing.''
</P>
<P>
   Many American theologians, however, were already troubled by a
previous papal Apostolic letter in 1994 forbidding the ordination
of women. The Vatican's Congregation For the Doctrine of Faith
issued a document in 1995 insisting that the pope's ruling on the
matter was ``infallibly taught.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Catholic Theological Society of America
challenged that interpretation and asked the Vatican for further
study of the question. On Tuesday, the Congregation for the
Doctrine of Faith, which published a ``doctrinal commentary,''
alongside the papal decree, specifically cited the ban on women
priests as an example of doctrine that is ``infallibly taught.''
That doctrine, among others, was inserted into canonical law by
today's decree. And that is likely to disappoint many American
theologians. ``Church documents have to be read very carefully, but
on the face of it, this appears to be quite troubling,'' said Dr.
Jon Nilson, a professor at Loyola University in Chicago, and a
member of the Catholic Theological Society of America. ``Women's
ordination is at the forefront of issues in the process of
reconciliation with other Christian churches _ if you are serious
about unity within the churches you have to keep open discussion of
women's ordination.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-98 2059EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980630.0363 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 21:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4676 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTERNET-PRIVACY-700&AMP;     06-30 1136
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-PRIVACY-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. AND EUROPE CLASH OVER INTERNET CONSUMER PRIVACY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Mass.)   (af)  
 By JOHN MARKOFF   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Differences between European nations and the United States over
how to protect consumer privacy have led to a clash over
technologies endorsed by the world's two leading makers of browsing
software for navigating the World Wide Web, Microsoft Corp. and
Netscape Communications Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The differences between Europe governments, which favor enacting
laws to protect consumer privacy online, and the Clinton
administration, which prefers to let electronic commerce industries
regulate themselves, could delay the much-anticipated evolution of
the Internet into a huge international supermarket of goods and
services.
</P>
<P>
   At issue are two proposed standards: the Privacy Preferences
Project, or P3P, and the Open Profiling Standard, or OPS. Both are
technologies intended to make it possible for individual computer
users to determine how much personal information they are willing
to make available to various Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Both proposals are being considered for possible international
implementation by an Internet standards group, the World Wide Web
Consortium.
</P>
<P>
   But earlier this month, a committee of the European Union issued
a tough report attacking both proposed standards as inadequate and
possibly in violation of European laws designed to protect consumer
privacy.
</P>
<P>
   The report states that P3P and OPS, which will be built into
browsers made by both Microsoft and Netscape, clash with the
European Privacy Directive, which restricts the ability of
businesses to collect private information about individuals without
their permission.
</P>
<P>
   When it goes into effect this October the directive is expected
to toughen national laws of 15 European governments whose privacy
standards are already more stringent than those of the United
States. The European laws require that corporations get people's
permission before collecting demographic or marketing information
about them.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is significant, because the Europeans are saying this
mechanism might not work,'' said Joel Reidenberg, a law professor
at Fordham University in New York City and an expert on
international privacy law.
</P>
<P>
   The European Union's committee, the Working Party on the
Protection of Individuals' Personal Data, issued its draft opinion
on June 16. In addition to criticize the technology itself, the
report stated that ``a technical platform for privacy protection
will not in itself be sufficient to protect privacy on the Web.''
</P>
<P>
   Gerard de Graaf, first secretary of the European Commission
delegation in the United States, said, ``We believe technology has
a role to play in enhancing privacy protection, but we have some
concerns about seeing technology as the magic bullet.''
</P>
<P>
   The committee's report said that such a technology for privacy
protection would still need to be applied within a framework of
enforceable laws if it was to protect privacy.
</P>
<P>
   The committee also said there was a risk that the P3P standard
would mislead European companies into believing that they had met
their legal obligations by offering the software.
</P>
<P>
   There is added risk that European computer users would come into
contact via the Internet with Web sites that do not meet European
data protection standards, according to the report. It warns that
the current P3P does not require, or even allow for, the providing
of information about sanctions or remedies to users, a violation of
European laws.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the report states that Internet users are unlikely to
alter the so-called default settings that are preconfigured with
each browser. The committee warns that the software will be of
minimal privacy protection value if the browsers are not set by
default to the highest privacy protection possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a shot across the bow,'' said Evan Hendricks,
Publisher of Privacy Times, a privacy policy newsletter, which
reported the European Union criticism of the P3P standard earlier
this week. ``If the Europeans enforce their own standards, then the
U.S. is now headed on a collision course over the Directive.'' &QL;
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Until recently, the Clinton administration has pressured United
States industries to arrive at strong self-regulatory standards
that would avoid the necessity of enacting new laws to protect
personal information in the information age.
</P>
<P>
   However, in recent weeks that position has appeared to weaken as
critics _ including the United States Commerce Department _
continued to point out areas in which self regulation is failing as
corporations rush to take advantage of the Internet as a new medium
for marketing and commerce.
</P>
<P>
   ``This could be a flash point,'' said Marc Rotenberg, director
of the Electronic Privacy Information Center, a Washington,
D.C.-based privacy organization. European approaches have tended to
encourage systems that permit anonymity, he said, while American
companies have been building systems that encourage users to
provide personal information.
</P>
<P>
   In April, Microsoft acquired Firefly, a Cambridge, Mass.-based
Internet start-up company that develops technologies that support
P3P.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft declined to comment Tuesday on the European Union
report.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the World Wide Web consortium said Tuesday that
they had been in discussions with members of the European
Commission and that they believed that the technology could be
modified to meet the European privacy concerns. But they also
acknowledged concerned that the technology might become embroiled
in a political war between Europe and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's a middle ground it's going to take some time to
find it,'' said Joseph M. Reagle Jr., a policy analyst at the
consortium. ``I'd hate to see it used as a political straw man
anywhere. While P3P isn't perfect, it is a step forward. Issues
related to the harmonization of data protection regulations and
extraterritorial claims of jurisdiction on the Web will take many
years to resolve.''
</P>
<P>
   Reagle disputed the report's assertion that there were
shortcomings in the basic P3P vocabulary that notifies computer
users of their privacy options. In fact, he noted, the system can
be easily tailored for any set of privacy guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   The European Commission report follows a similar, but less
strongly worded report by the International Working Group on Data
Protection in Telecommunications, a group of privacy officials from
various governments.
</P>
<P>
   The group, which met in Hong Kong in April, stated in its
report: ``Technology cannot in itself be the solution for securing
privacy on the Web. It needs to be applied according to a
regulatory framework.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
