<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLAG-BURNING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CIVIL LIBERTY GROUPS OPPOSE BID TO BAN FLAG-BURNING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ESTELLA DURAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Flying the American flag may be patriotic, but so
is fighting for the freedom to burn it, a civil liberties group
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The group, People for the American Way, unveiled an advertising
campaign Tuesday aimed at rallying opposition in the Senate to a
constitutional amendment that would ban flag desecration. The
measure passed the House last year and could come up in the Senate
soon after the Fourth of July recess. A close vote is likely.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to make the point that it is just as patriotic to
fight for the freedom to burn the flag as it is to wrap yourself up
in the flag,'' said Mike Lux, a vice president of People for the
American Way. ``What is important is the freedom that the flag
represents, not the flag itself.''
</P>
<P>
   In the advertisement, which started airing Tuesday _ in time for
the Fourth of July _ on television stations in Oregon, Washington,
North Dakota, and Washington, D.C., James Warner, a former prisoner
of war in Vietnam, pleads ``don't let them burn our freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, the Supreme Court ruled that flag burning is protected
as free speech by the First Amendment. A year before, the Supreme
Court invalidated state flag protection laws, ruling that Texas
could not fine a protester who burned an American flag on public
property.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, an anti-desecration constitutional amendment, which
requires a two-thirds majority to pass, fell three votes short in
the Senate. Last year, the House passed the measure 310-114, and
the Senate may find it difficult to resist passage in this election
year. Three-fourths of the states would need to ratify the
amendment for it to become part of the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Orrin G. Hatch, Republican of Utah, sponsored the Senate
proposal, which was approved last month by the Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American flag serves as a symbol of our great nation,''
said Hatch, who chairs the Judiciary Committee. ``The flag
represents, in a way nothing else can, the common bond shared by an
otherwise diverse people.''
</P>
<P>
   Senators Edward M. Kennedy and John F. Kerry voted against the
amendment in 1995. Their staffs said the senators plan to oppose
the amendment again.
</P>
<P>
   ``The First Amendment hasn't been amended in the entire 200
years of our history, and now is no time to start,'' Kennedy said
Tuesday. ``The best way to honor the flag is to honor the ideals it
represents.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerry could not be reached for comment Tuesday, but he said in a
statement after his vote against the amendment in 1995 that it was
his responsibility to uphold the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   ``Constitutionally, the substance of the right to dissent, no
matter how ugly it might be, is at the core of who we are as a
country,'' he said. ``It is what separates us from every other
nation on the face of this planet.''
</P>
<P>
   The Citizens Flag Alliance, a coalition including 126 veterans
groups, is promoting the amendment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Amending the Constitution to protect the flag will in no way
impair with anyone's rights,'' said Marty Justis, a spokesman for
the group.
</P>
<P>
   Justis said those who argue that flag desecration is such a rare
act that it does not warrant a constitutional amendment are missing
the point.
</P>
<P>
   ``It isn't a question of how many times it happens; it's a
question of how wrong it is,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Laura W. Murphy, spokeswoman for the American Civil Liberties
Union, said the ACLU is firmly against the amendment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Political expression and dissension from government are
precisely what the First Amendment was designed to protect,'' she
said. ``We think the American people are bigger than this, that we
can tolerate political dissent in this country.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
