<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HILTON-CASINOS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTORS COOL TO HILTON PLAN; STOCK TUMBLES
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Miss., N.J., Nev.)  (nk) 
 By ANDREW POLLACK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Hilton Hotels Corp. announced a long-awaited
transaction Tuesday aimed at enhancing shareholder value, but
investors seemed to focus instead on the deal that got away _
helping to cause shares of Hilton to fall in heavy trading.
</P>
<P>
   As expected, Hilton announced that it was splitting itself into
separate lodging and gaming companies and that the gaming company
would merge with Grand Casinos Inc., the largest operator of
casinos in Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   Several analysts said the deal _ particularly the split of the
company _ would be good for Hilton shareholders in the long run.
</P>
<P>
   But investors had been betting that Hilton would also announce a
merger of its new hotel company with Ladbroke Group PLC, the
British company that controls the Hilton brand overseas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The splitting of the company is rational,'' said Harry Curtis,
an analyst with BancAmerica Robertson Stephens. ``The acquisition
of Grand is rational. The near-term question is what were the
expectations, and they were a lot higher. It disappointed a lot of
fast money.''
</P>
<P>
   Hilton shares fell $2.875, or 9 percent, to $28.625 on Tuesday,
as 4.7 million shares were traded. Shares of Grand Casinos fell
$1.50, or 8 percent, to $17.
</P>
<P>
   Hilton shareholders will receive one share of stock in both the
lodging company, which will retain the Hilton name, and the gaming
company, which has yet to be named. Hilton said it expected the
distribution to be tax-free.
</P>
<P>
   The gaming company will merge with Grand Casinos in an all-stock
transaction. Grand's small business managing Indian casinos will be
spun off to Grand shareholders and will not go to Hilton. Hilton
said it was paying about $650 million and assuming about $550
million of debt to acquire Grand's Mississippi operations.
</P>
<P>
   Hilton shareholders are expected to end up owning about 86
percent of the combined gaming company and Grand shareholders about
14 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Bollenbach will remain chief executive of Hilton, which
will be a pure lodging company for the first time since 1970. He
will also be chairman of the gaming company; Arthur Goldberg, who
now runs Hilton's gaming division, will be chief executive. Thomas
Brosig, Grand's chief executive, will be in charge of gaming
operations for the Midwest, Mississippi and other emerging markets.
</P>
<P>
   Lyle Berman, chairman of Grand Casinos, told analysts Tuesday
that Grand shareholders' stake in the new gaming company would be
worth about $15 to $17 a share. In addition, they will be left with
shares in the new Grand spinoff, worth at least book value of $2.81
a share. That implies a total value to Grand shareholders of $18 to
$20 or more, not much higher than the current market price.
</P>
<P>
   Combining with Hilton's gaming operations, Berman said, is
``about grasping growth opportunities that smaller companies just
can't reach.''
</P>
<P>
   For Hilton, the logic in splitting is that the company's stock
valuation is held down by the gaming business. In addition, many
Hilton shareholders did not like the casino business and were
opposing efforts by Hilton to make gaming acquisitions at a time
when the casino industry is ripe for consolidation, Bollenbach
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is we've got two big companies that are free
to grow,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts agreed that the split made sense and that the
acquisition of Grand would make Hilton a presence in Mississippi,
the third-largest market after Las Vegas and Atlantic City, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   John Rohs, an analyst with Schroder &AMP; Co., said that Hilton's
gaming and lodging company stocks should trade for a combined total
of $33 or $34 a share based on market valuations for other gaming
and lodging stocks. But he said that adding Grand to the mix might
not add much because the Mississippi casinos will face stiff new
competition next year from Mirage Resorts.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts added that Hilton's hotel business, now free of the
casinos, would become a more tempting takeover target.
</P>
<P>
   But Bollenbach said in an interview that he did not think any
companies would pay the price Hilton wants. He also said the
company had no plans to sell off individual hotels such as the
Waldorf-Astoria in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Bollenbach said that a merger with Ladbroke was ``something that
we talk about a lot.'' But it would have to be a stock transaction,
and there are difficulties getting American investors to hold
shares in a British company and British investors to hold American
shares, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bollenbach said the hotel company, rather than being bought,
would be an acquirer, probably not of complete hotel companies but
of individual hotels that are coming on the market, particularly as
troubled Japanese investors unload real estate.
</P>
<P>
   In Tuesday's deal, the combined debt of Hilton and Grand will be
split evenly between the Hilton lodging and gaming companies, which
should leave both with investment-grade credit ratings, officials
said. This could mollify Hilton bondholders who are wary of
Bollenbach. When he engineered a split of the old Marriott Corp.
some years back, he loaded all the debt into one of the two
companies, causing bond prices to drop.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
