<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 21:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4680 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-AIDS-THERAPY-500&AMP;     06-30 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-AIDS-THERAPY-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESEARCHERS EXPRESS CAUTIOUS HOPE OF BEATING AIDS VIRUS 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By LAWRENCE K. ALTMAN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA _ At the 12th World AIDS Conference, some scientists
expressed cautious but renewed hope Tuesday of ultimately
eliminating the HIV virus from the body and thus curing AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cure of HIV infection is not a myth, it is a problem we can
tackle,'' said Dr. Roberto Siliciano of Johns Hopkins University in
Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   Today the best that doctors can offer are combinations of drugs
known as cocktails that can drive the amount of virus in a person's
blood below levels detectable in laboratory tests. But that does
not mean the virus has been eliminated from the body.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists have recently discovered that although the virus
could not be detected in the blood, it was still hiding in certain
cells to produce what is known as a latent reservoir of HIV.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Dr. David Ho and his team from the Aaron Diamond
AIDS Research Center in New York City first discussed the
possibility of eradicating HIV. At the World AIDS Conference in
Vancouver, British Columbia, they announced an experiment of
purposely asking a patient to stop the medication to determine
whether HIV returned.
</P>
<P>
   However, the discovery of a latent reservoir meant that HIV was
primed to bounce back when cocktail drug therapy stopped. That
discouraged Ho from undertaking that widely publicized experiment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never did the experiment. It was a lesson,'' Ho said. In an
interview he explained that when the amount of HIV ``dips below the
level of detection, we get the false sense that virus replication
is shut off.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Ho, Siliciano and others said that they have gone back
to the drawing board to map new strategies to eliminate the latent
reservoir. In pursuing that goal, scientists are moving into
uncharted waters.
</P>
<P>
   Although vaccines can prevent viral infections, drugs do not
cure any viral disease the way antibiotics can cure some bacterial
infections. When a person gets over a viral infection, recovery is
due to the body's natural immune defenses.
</P>
<P>
   However, some viral infections are latent. The chicken pox
virus, for example, persists in the body after a childhood attack,
to come back as shingles in adulthood. No one knows what
reactivates the chicken pox virus to produce shingles.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of HIV, one strategy is to find new drugs to rid the
body of the last cell of the reservoir. Another is to use one drug
to flush HIV out of hiding so that another drug might kill the
escaping virus.
</P>
<P>
   However, ``activating the immune system to flush out the virus
is something that we have no experience with,'' Ho said in an
interview.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, such an approach would fail if the cells in the latent
reservoir continue to become infected.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Anthony Fauci, the head of the National Institute of Allergy
and Infectious Diseases, discussed another possibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be that you don't have to eliminate HIV,'' Fauci said.
If the size of the latent reservoir or HIV is drastically reduced,
then the body's natural immune defenses might keep the remaining
infection in check.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   None of the scientists seeking an AIDS cure knows how many
barriers must be overcome to rid the body of the last HIV, if that
is ever possible.
</P>
<P>
   The current barrier lies in what are known as memory CD4 cells
in the latent reservoir, which forms soon after HIV enters the
body.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, young uninfected CD4 cells emerge from the thymus
gland in the chest and circulate throughout the body in its lymph
system. When such cells meet a foreign invader like HIV, they turn
into a different cell (known as a lymphoblast) and begin to
proliferate. HIV kills many CD4 cells. But some survive in a
resting state in which HIV does not replicate unless something
stimulates it to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Fauci said in an interview that he suspected that it would take
several courses of therapy to successfully purge the body of the
latent reservoir.
</P>
<P>
   No one knows the normal life span of the memory cells. To its
disappointment, Siliciano's team found that the number of memory
cells was no lower among people who had taken the drug cocktails
for up to 30 months than among those who had just started such
therapy. The reservoir's stability suggests that it is replenished
by a low level of HIV replication.
</P>
<P>
   However, Ho was less certain, saying that his team had measured
a small and slow rate of decay of the memory cells.
</P>
<P>
   Even if there is continued replication of HIV, it might not pose
an insurmountable barrier because newer drugs in the pipeline might
eliminate the virus, Ho said.
</P>
<P>
   Ho said his team is ready to try yet another approach. This
summer he expects to start a pilot study using an experimental
vaccine to boost immune responses. The aim is to determine whether
that step will help rid the body of the latent reservoir.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of the scientific goal of an AIDS cure, Ho said: ``We
should unapologetically declare that as the ultimate objective,
even though the challenges are rather daunting right now. If I
thought it was completely unrealistic I would not work on it. But I
cannot quantify what the chance might be.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
