<HEADER>
A4689 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REEBOK-SHAQUILLE-BOS &LR;      06-30 1059
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REEBOK-SHAQUILLE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REEBOK DROPPING AD DEAL WITH BASKETBALL CELEBRITY O'NEAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (f and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In an indication that star power alone can't sell shoes, Reebok
International Ltd. said Tuesday that it will not renew its
endorsement contract with basketball's Shaquille O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   When Shaq inked the estimated $15 &UR;  &LR; million deal with the
Stoughton, Mass. athletic footwear company in 1992, it was hailed
as a landmark endorsement for a potential role model with a size 21
foot. Shoes would be designed for O'Neal and named after him, with
the hope that kids from urban playgrounds to the toniest of suburbs
would covet them.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't work out that way. As sneaker sales have cooled for
the entire industry, companies are re-evaluating their marketing
strategies, and some athletes who once earned millions in
endorsement fees are lucky if they can get free shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, a veritable all-star team of athletes has recently been
dropped from the roster of first-string sneaker pitchmen.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA's Larry Johnson, Oliver Miller, Glenn Robinson, and
Bobby Phills are among those who've seen fees dwindle or have had
their contracts bought out by various sneaker companies. The same
goes for football's Emmitt Smith, who pitched shoes and apparel for
Reebok.
</P>
<P>
   In reality, it's a rare star who has the cachet and charisma to
sell athletic footwear and apparel, said executive director Gregg
Hartley of the Sporting Goods Manufacturers Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are only about four athletes in the whole world who can
actually sell product,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And none of them happen to be named O'Neal, whose multi-year
contract with Reebok, the second-biggest maker of athletic footwear
to Nike, expired Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   According to Hartley, the athletes who might actually be worth
their huge endorsement fees include Jordan, and golfers Tiger Woods
and Greg Norman, who has his own Reebok collection.
</P>
<P>
   Second-tier stars are another matter. They may sink clutch
baskets and birdies. They may score touchdowns and hat tricks. But
they don't put enough money into store cash registers to justify
big endorsement fees. With second-tier stars, shoe companies don't
always get ``a bang for their marketing buck,'' said editor Sean
Brenner of Team Marketing Report, an industry newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   And using athletes always carries a risk of adverse publicity.
When Latrell Sprewell of the Golden State Warriors attempted to
throttle his basketball coach last season, North Reading-based
Converse Inc. moved quickly to fire him as a pitchman for its
sneakers.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, shoe companies are victims of their own success. A
few years ago, a surefire formula for selling sneakers was pretty
straightforward: Hire a National Basketball Association star, put
him on TV, and watch boys and young men eagerly flock to the malls
to buy shoes worn by their heroes.
</P>
<P>
   No one had more success with that strategy than Nike Inc. and
Michael Jordan, although it also worked for Grant Hill and Fila.
</P>
<P>
   Success brought imitation, and the result was a series of
copycat ads that consumers couldn't tell apart. It got to the point
where viewers couldn't keep straight which star was endorsing which
shoe, said Jim Andrews, editor of IEG Endorsement Insider, a
newsletter that tracks endorsements.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, anecdotal evidence hinted that many kids were
switching their sneakers for so-called brown shoes. Instead of
Nikes, they were wearing hiking boots and clunky footwear, perhaps
turned off by the endless bombardment of sneaker ads.
</P>
<P>
   Because there's little sales data to support it, several
industry observers dismissed the brown-shoe trend. In their view,
sneaker ads featuring stars have run their course. It's time for
something new, they say, something that breaks through the clutter,
something that celebrates everyday athletes rather than overpaid
superstars.
</P>
<P>
   ``They oversaturated the market. So many players had signature
footwear, it was no longer unique,'' said Andrews. ``You can't
expect consumers to respond.''
</P>
<P>
   For Reebok, having many stars under contract was vital at one
point. A decade ago, Reebok was known as a company that made
aerobics shoes for women. When it expanded into the men's market,
the challenge was to convince men that Reebok was sufficiently
macho. To do that, Reebok began to sign up athletes en masse. The
thought was that if sports fans turned on their TVs and saw pro
athletes in Reebok shoes, Reebok would gain authenticity as a
performance brand.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Reebok had more than 100 NBA athletes under
contract. At the summer Olympics in 1996, meanwhile, about a third
of the 10,000 athletes wore some Reebok product.
</P>
<P>
   After years of heavy investment, however, Reebok has concluded
that it has gotten across the message that it's a performance brand
for both men and women. And as sneaker sales have flattened _
Tuesday Nike reported the unthinkable: a quarterly loss _ Reebok
has decided it no longer needs to spend so heavily on star
athletes. Other footwear companies, also coping with weaker sales
and a glut of inventory, have reached a similar conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's been cutting back,'' said Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   When sales weaken, one of the first things that companies do is
slash marketing budgets, said Hartley of the sporting goods
association, and that's what shoe companies are doing as their
cyclical industry struggles through the downturn.
</P>
<P>
   Reebok said it will continue to highlight basketball star Allen
Iverson. But instead of a slew of NBA stars, it will rely more on
some women basketball players to help sell sneakers and soccer
stars with global appeal to market athletic shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Reebok spokesman Dave Fogelson said the current strategy is to
put more emphasis on the shoes themselves than on star jocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about doing more with less,'' Fogelson said. ``It's about
a renewed focus on product.''
</P>
<P>
   But don't cry for Shaq over his departure from Reebok.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the 26-year-old star of the Los Angeles Lakers earned
an estimated $28 million in endorsement fees, touting such products
as Pepsi-Cola and fast-food from Taco Bell.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday his agent said O'Neal is ``finalizing plans for future
footwear and apparel commitments.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
