<HEADER>
A4690 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-HORSE-RACING-REPO     06-30 1171
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-HORSE-RACING-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SKIP AWAY SETTLES ARGUMENT IN WINNING STYLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY MOSS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Time and again, he has proven himself. He has won $8.9 million
in purses and is undefeated in seven races under jockey Jerry
Bailey. He set a track record last month while carrying 130 pounds.
Two years ago, he even outran Cigar.
</P>
<P>
   About the only thing Skip Away had left to prove in the
Hollywood Gold Cup is that his victory in the star-depleted
Breeders' Cup Classic should not carry an asterisk.
</P>
<P>
   It won't.
</P>
<P>
   Skip Away and Gentlemen were eye-to-eye as they entered the
stretch Sunday in the defining moment of a showdown that seven
months ago had been anticipated and then delayed.
</P>
<P>
   Gentlemen was supposed to run in last November's Classic, also
at Hollywood Park, but an untimely sickness kept him on the
sidelines. Another top horse, Formal Gold, was hurt and didn't make
the Classic, either. The result was that Skip Away's biggest
victory was diminished not by any fault of his own, but by the lack
of quality competition.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since, more than a few holdouts have insisted Gentlemen is
a faster horse than Skip Away, and that over his favorite track, he
surely would have outrun Skip Away in the Classic.
</P>
<P>
   That verdict _ or as close as we can get to it _ was finally
returned Sunday as Skip Away and Gentlemen raced in tandem into the
Hollywood stretch.
</P>
<P>
   It was a decisive one. Skip Away looked at Gentlemen and,
basically, sneered at him. Or from the other perspective, Gentlemen
looked at Skip Away and backed down, just as so many other rivals
have done.
</P>
<P>
   Gentlemen narrowly defeated Skip Away last summer in the Pimlico
Special in what was a sensational race for both horses. But
Gentlemen maintained that brilliance for only three races, and has
yet to regain it. Skip Away, on the other hand, continues his march
toward Cigar's earnings record of $9.9 million, which he seems
destined to surpass, barring a career-ending injury.
</P>
<P>
   In retrospect, it appears that Skip Away would have won the
Breeders' Cup Classic even with Gentlemen in the field.
</P>
<P>
   It had already become evident that he deserved the controversial
1997 horse of the year award that instead went to juvenile champion
Favorite Trick. Trainer Sonny Hine has cried foul ever since, with
good reason.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the season isn't over yet and almost certainly will
be filled with more twists and turns. Remember that in most years,
a racing snapshot taken in June is nearly unrecognizable when the
Breeders' Cup rolls around. Round two of Skip Away vs. Gentlemen
could transpire in August in the Pacific Classic, also a $1 million
race. Silver Charm might join that field, too, if he ever recovers
from his trip to Dubai.
</P>
<P>
   Before Skip Away proved his final point Sunday, it was merely a
majority opinion that the 5-year-old is presently the best horse in
the United States and maybe the world.
</P>
<P>
   Until we see proof otherwise, that opinion now should be
unanimous.
</P>
<P>
   According to speed figures, Skip Away runs just as fast as
Cigar, the heralded two-time horse of the year (1995, '96). Bailey,
who also rode Cigar, seconds that opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they both ran together, Skip Away beat him,'' said
Bailey, referring to the 1996 Jockey Club Gold Cup at Belmont Park.
``Maybe that tells you something. I have a special place in my
heart for Cigar, but maybe Skip Away is a better horse.''
Two arrivals
</P>
<P>
   Anet and Commitisize, two horses trained by Bob Baffert, arrived
at Lone Star Park at Grand Prairie yesterday after a flight from
Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Both horses were sent for Saturday races. Anet, last year's Lone
Star horse of the meeting who more recently ran second in the Texas
Mile on April 19, will run in the $200,000 Lone Star Park Handicap.
Commitisize is shooting for the $150,000 USA Stakes, won by Anet a
year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Commitisize belongs to Mike Pegram, who also owns Kentucky Derby
and Preakness winner Real Quiet.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't take long for the horses to realize they are no longer
close to the Pacific Ocean breezes.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a little hot,'' exercise rider Lupee Navarro said,
``but they're doing well.''
Long distance rival
</P>
<P>
   On the same week as Lone Star's June 19 NTRA All-Star Jockey
Championship, Prairie Meadows racetrack held a national jockey
competition of its own. And on the same day as Saturday's Lone Star
Park Handicap, Prairie Meadows has scheduled its Prairie Meadows
Cornhusker Breeders' Cup Handicap, worth $300,000.
</P>
<P>
   Corey Johnsen, general manager of Lone Star, is frustrated by
what he claims is a lack of scheduling cooperation by the Altoona,
Iowa, track, where growing purses are funded by a thriving
slot-machine casino.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's in the best interest of horse racing to
have all-star events popping up all over the country,'' Johnsen
said. ``And I was very disappointed at Prairie Meadows' decision to
have their jockey challenge on the Monday before our Friday. The
Jockeys' Guild even asked them to move it to the week after ours,
but they declined.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope it was a nice little promotion for Des Moines, Iowa,
because it sure didn't do anything for our sport.''
Et cetera
</P>
<P>
   Silver Charm is back in training after the virus that knocked
him out of the Hollywood Gold Cup. ... 1997 Belmont Stakes winner
Touch Gold looked sharp in his first race of the year, winning a
Churchill Downs allowance Sunday in 1:34 for a mile, only one-fifth
of a second off the track record. His first summer goal is the Aug.
8 Whitney at Saratoga. ... Instead of migrating over to Louisiana
Downs, the horses of Lone Star trainers Dallas Keen, Steve
Asmussen, Sam David Jr., Mike Stidham, Kenny Smith and Steve Hobby
will instead go to Hawthorne Race Course near Chicago, which opens
today. David also is expected to run some horses at Louisiana
Downs. ... Cowboy Dan finished second in an allowance race Saturday
at Cleveland-area Thistledown, and now is probably out of
contention for the July 19 Ohio Derby. ... Three-year-old Lil's Lad
is back in training after ankle surgery that knocked him out of the
Triple Crown, but don't expect to see him run until late August or
September. ... Skip Away was also on the flight to Texas that
carried Anet and Commitisize, but he stayed on the plane and
continued to New York. ... The stable of Houston-based brothers Bob
and Lee Ackerly includes stakes fillies Little Sister and
Swearingen, who have raced at Lone Star. But their best horse is
3-year-old filly Jersey Girl, who scored her sixth consecutive
victory in Saturday's Mother Goose Stakes at Belmont Park and next
will attempt to sweep the track's filly Triple Tiara on July 25 in
the Coaching Club American Oaks. ... Potential rivals for Anet in
the Lone Star Park Handicap are nominees Silver Goblin and
Spiritbound. ... Churchill Downs ended its spring meeting Sunday
with an average daily purse distribution of $469,643, plus
increases in both on-track attendance and betting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-98 2113EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
