<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 21:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4691 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARKETS-QUARTER-ART-2     06-30 1166
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKETS-QUARTER-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTORS KEEP IGNORING NAYSAYERS' CRIES OF WOLF 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphics have been sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(JT) 
 By DAVID BARBOZA    
 c. 1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The warnings that the bubble is about to burst have
been sounded each quarter for the last few years, but investors in
the stock market continue to ignore them. And so far, despite a
series of blows lately that were widely expected to take the air
out of the balloon, they have been right. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sure, the Asian economic crisis poses a threat to already
slowing corporate profit growth at home. And yes, the recent rise
in wages could eventually mean a revival of serious inflation. Yet
all indications are that the American economy is remarkably sound,
seemingly indestructible, and therefore, investors surmise, so is
Wall Street. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That's why, midway through 1998, share prices are once again
hovering near their all-time highs. The investing public, for all
the complaints of the professionals, remains sanguine about the
unheard-of riches being delivered by one of the greatest bull
markets in history. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index _ a widely followed proxy
for the larger stock market and millions of index-fund investors _
is up nearly 17 percent this year. The Dow Jones industrial
average, the best-known market barometer, is up 13 percent in a
year that many Wall Street pros had forecast full-year gains of
less than 8 percent. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a year well above almost anyone's expectations,''
said Frederick Taylor, the chief investment officer at the U.S.
Trust Co. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even though share prices fell modestly Tuesday and finished the
second quarter with only slim gains of about 2.9 percent for the
S&AMP;P 500, the evidence suggests that investors have not yet cooled
to stocks. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there are dire warnings that weaker profits later in
the year could send investors fleeing and erase most of the gains.
Or that Asia, already in recession and still on the edge of
destruction, could swipe winnings in Europe and topple American
markets.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But for now, the U.S. economy seems to be in the throes of what
the Federal Reserve chairman, Alan Greenspan, has called a
``virtuous cycle,'' of powerful growth, little if any inflation,
low unemployment and rising wage gains.
</P>
<P>
   That's an almost ideal economic scenario that may be
compensating for the gradual slowdown in profit growth, which has
drifted down for large companies to a gain of just 3.8 percent in
the first quarter compared with a 15 percent advance in the period
a year earlier. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This combination of favorable economic factors has been critical
to the market's surge, said Taylor at U.S. Trust. Unemployment,
inflation and interest rates are all low, consumer confidence is
high, and where federal budget deficits reigned, now there are
surpluses. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a whole group of things that if you had forecast
them a few years ago, no one would have believed it,'' he said.
``As an American looking at the U.S. economy these are indeed good
times.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And with soaring consumer confidence, Americans are rushing to
buy their favorite products _ no less than the shares of companies
that create and market those products.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Call investors defiant, narrow-minded, excessively bullish,
naive, or even downright silly. But also call them rich _ billions,
no trillions, richer with each passing quarter. The ``virtuous
cycle,'' for them, is about buying Gap khakis, and then buying into
shares of the Gap and its retail brethren. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, for those counting, the current bull market, which dates
back to October 1990, just before the gulf war, clocked day 2,819
Tuesday _ making it the third-longest bull market in history. It is
now just months away from passing the period that ended
disastrously in October 1929.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Not even the audacious 1980s can match the run of the 1990s for
durability or distance. In the 1980s, the Dow soared 250 percent to
its August 1987 high, before tumbling 22.3 percent on Oct. 19, 1987
_ Black Monday. In the 1990s, however, the Dow has climbed about
280 percent, including a record three consecutive years with gains
of 20 percent or more. (In the 1920s, the Dow gained 496 percent
before plummeting into the Great Depression.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But if there is anything to raise a warning flag about the
sustainability of the remarkable stock market run of the last few
years, it is that the winnings are being concentrated in an
ever-smaller group of blue-chip companies that include well-known
names like General Electric, Dell Computer, Microsoft, Coca-Cola
and Wal-Mart. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lately, Americans, along with a growing mass of foreigners, have
placed their bets largely on companies like Dell Computer, one of
the hottest stocks of the decade. And despite its rocket-like rise,
Dell has gained another 121 percent this year, pushing its market
value to $58 billion _ more than that of General Motors Corp. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Many companies seem protected against even dire attacks by
something resembling a bullet-proof vest. Microsoft, despite the
antitrust action by the federal government and at least 20 states,
has seen its shares appreciate another 67 percent in 1998, pushing
its value up $110 billion in just the last six months to $267
billion, second only to General Electric, which is worth almost
$300 billion.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The market value of corporations _ or what investors value them
at _ has been growing exponentially in the 1990s, along with the
urge to merge.
</P>
<P>
   And when corporations merge, or hint at such deals, share prices
soar, feeding the great bull market. Financial deals, like
Citicorp's agreement to merge with Travelers Group for $70 billion,
have been among the most lucrative. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts see the merger deals not so much as a sign of
health, but as a symbol of a market that is peaking, and readying
for a fall. They argue that companies running out of ways to
increase profits have nothing better to do than seek partnerships
as a way to keep the game going just a little bit longer. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Of all the warning signs, the sharpest concerns corporate
profits. The first-quarter growth was the slowest since 1991, and
the second-quarter estimates are for gains of about 3.5 percent,
according to First Call Inc., which tracks earnings data.
</P>
<P>
   A profit slowdown, conventional wisdom goes, would weigh heavily
on share prices, and at the very least, stall the bull run. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Stock prices and profits go together, and through the 1990s,
you've had a golden age of profits,'' said Ronald Talley, an
economist at the WEFA Group, a forecasting unit in Eddystone, Pa.
``However, it looks like that period may be coming to an end. You
can't have profits growing faster than the economy forever, and it
seems that unusual situation is about to end.'' &QL;
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Gail Dudack, the chief investment strategist at UBS Securities,
says the first quarter's strong economic growth with meager profit
gains portends a difficult second half of the year. ``If you put
those two pieces of information together, it suggests you could
have a negative quarter later this year,'' she said.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But others, like Abby Joseph Cohen, the widely followed market
strategist at Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co., says the ``supertanker''
economy will continue to steam ahead, buoying the major indexes
even if many smaller stocks languish. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Part of the profit picture, though, could be determined by
events in Asia, and they do not look good. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Companies like Boeing and Motorola have issued profit warnings,
creating a group of losers circling a narrower band of big winners.
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Galvin, a market strategist at Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP;
Jenrette, estimates that the top 30 companies that make up the S&AMP;P
500 provided about half of this year's gains, partly because
foreign investors consider them safe and recognizable. Many on Wall
Street talk about a two-tiered market, a market of haves and have
nots. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The big surprise this year has been the focus and narrowness
of the market,'' said Laszlo Birinyi, who heads Birinyi Associates,
a market research firm in Greenwich, Conn. ``Everyone believed that
at some point smaller stocks were going to join in and they
haven't.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The weaker fortunes of smaller-company issues can be seen in the
Russell 2000 index, which has gained just 4.6 percent this year.
``It's really been the General Electrics and the Coca-Colas that
are getting all the activity,'' Birinyi said.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The big losers midway through 1998 are the energy stocks,
suffering from a huge decline in the price of oil, as well as
semiconductor companies with heavy exposure to Asia. National
Semiconductor, an S&AMP;P 500 stock, is down nearly 50 percent this
year. The Rowan Cos., an oil drilling concern, is down 36 percent. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Worries about Asia and profits were said to be behind the
anxious moments in the second quarter, when the Dow first soared to
a record 9,211.84 in May before falling as low as 8,627.93 earlier
in June, a drop of 6.3 percent. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But with each dip has come a resurgence of buying, and that
surge sent the S&AMP;P 500 to a record on Monday, before slipping
slightly Tuesday. The Nasdaq, despite turbulence in recent weeks,
is up 20.7 percent this year. The Dow, meanwhile, closed at
8,952.02 _ hovering around the 9,000 mark.
</P>
<P>
   Could anything end the party? Certainly the Federal Reserve
could if it decides to raise interest rates. For the latest on that
front, tune in Wednesday shortly after 2 p.m. for the conclusion of
the Fed's two-day Open Market Committee meeting.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
