<DOCNO> NYT19980630.0374 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 21:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4694 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIRTHS-ART-NYT &LR;      06-30 1062
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIRTHS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIRTH RATE FOR UNMARRIED BLACK WOMEN IS AT 40-YEAR LOW 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic on birth rates is being sent to NYT graphic
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(ps) 
 By STEVEN A. HOLMES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The birth rate for unmarried black women, long a
focal point in the debate over the causes of poverty among blacks,
has reached its lowest point in 40 years, federal health officials
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   According to figures compiled by the National Center for Health
Statistics there were 74.4 births per 1,000 unmarried black women
in 1996, the last year for which complete data are available. That
rate is significantly below the peak of 90.7 per 1,000 unmarried
black women in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's report showed that the out-of-wedlock birth rate has
been dropping for all age groups of black women. Demographers and
health officials said that the reasons _ an increase in
contraceptive use, sex education and efforts by some community
groups to encourage abstention _ should allow the trend to
continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's just been no let up, and it's not been slowing down,''
said Stephanie Ventura, a demographer with the National Center for
Health Statistics who wrote the report. ``And it's not just for
teen-agers. For all black women under 30, the declines have been
really big.''
</P>
<P>
   The figures on fertility rates for unmarried black women are
part of an annual report on births compiled by the National Center
for Health Statistics, a division of the federal Centers for
Disease Control and Prevention. Using data from birth certificates
submitted by the states, the report analyzed the 3.9 million births
that occurred in 1996 and highlighted a number of trends, including
these:
</P>
<P>
   _ Fewer babies were born that year than in any year since 1987,
part of a continuing decline that put the number of births at 6
percent below the recent high point, which was 1990.
</P>
<P>
   _ The number of women having multiple births rose sharply, and
resulted in 5,298 sets of triplets, 560 sets of quadruplets and 81
sets of quintuplets. The multiple births contributed to a 10
percent increase in the number of low birth-weight babies since
1984.
</P>
<P>
   _ Smoking among pregnant teen-agers increased, particularly
among Mexican, Puerto Rican and African-American teen-agers, though
overall smoking during pregnancy continued to decrease.
</P>
<P>
   But, one of the most closely watched numbers is the
out-of-wedlock birth rate for black women, long considered one of
the clearest indicators of many problems that have plagued poor
black communities. The decline in that rate is part of a continuing
decrease in the birth rate among all black women _ teen-age and
adult, married and unmarried. There has even been a small but
notable decrease in the overall birth rate among unmarried women,
to 44.8 per 1,000 in 1996 from 46.9 per 1,000 in 1994. That stems
from a drop in the birth rate among unmarried white women, which
had more than doubled from 1980 to 1994 before it began to drop,
hitting 37.6 per 1,000 women in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that the out-of-wedlock birth rate among blacks is
lower now than it was in the 1950s and 1960s surprised even experts
who follow these trends.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you had asked me about that before these data came out, I
would not have been aware of that,'' Jacqueline Darroch, vice
president for Research at the Alan Guttmacher Institute. ``And I
don't think most people would be either.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Darroch and federal health officials gave a number of
reasons for the decrease in the out-of-wedlock birth rate for black
women that included improved contraceptive use, especially a sharp
increase among African-American women of passive, long-acting birth
control methods such as Norplant, Depo-Provera and intrauterine
devices.
</P>
<P>
   Some health officials also say that stepped up efforts by
community groups to provide sex education or help young black women
abstain from sex are beginning to pay off. And some said that the
AIDS epidemic is causing more black women to take precautions like
using condoms that can also lower the pregnancy rate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really did scare people,'' said Donna Shalala, secretary of
health and human services. ``The remarkable increase in condom use
by African-Americans is directly attributed to AIDS.''
</P>
<P>
   Changes in the welfare system have not been a significant
factor, according to some people who monitor fertility rates.
Noting that out-of-wedlock birth rates for black women have been
dropping steadily since 1989, they assert that the decline started
before states and the federal government enacted welfare reform
measures.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is happening at a time when the economy is improving,''
said Kristin Moore, president of Child Trends, Inc.,
Washington-based research and advocacy group. ``We're seeing a
trend that predated welfare reform. so I would more likely look at
the economy as a hypothesis rather than welfare reform.''
</P>
<P>
   Even as the number of unmarried black women bearing children has
been dropping, the percentage of black children who are born
out-of-wedlock remains high. It was 69.8 per cent of black births
in 1996. The comparable figures for non-Hispanic whites was 21.5
percent and for Hispanic women, 40.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Demographers say the government has kept accurate birth
statistics by race and marital status since 1955. Until 1969, the
statistics lumped black women into a category that included all
racial minorities, but experts say the vast portion of births to
nonwhites in those years were to black women. The previous low
birth rate for unmarried black women was 75.2 per 1,000 in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   Some experts said that the percentage of children born outside
of marriage was more meaningful than the birth rate of unmarried
women as a sign that too many African American children are being
raised in environments where they are most at risk to become
engaged in crime, drug abuse, or other anti-social behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you care about the link between black poverty and children
in single-parent households, you want to know what percentage of
black babies are born into one-parent households,'' said Stephan
Thernstrom, co-author of ``America in Black and White: One Nation
Indivisible.'' ``I don't think there's been a decline in that. That
would be real news.''  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
