<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-ARGENTINA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENGLAND FALLS TO ARGENTINA IN SHOOTOUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAINT-ETIENNE, France -- Maybe this is Dante's version of soccer
hell. Maybe this is the price the English are damned to pay for
unleashing their lager-besotted hooligans on the continent.
Spending their blood and their sweat and their tears for 120
minutes and losing, again and again and again in shootouts.
</P>
<P>
   So it was again Tuesday night, as England courageously played a
man down for the final 73 minutes only to be knocked out of the
World Cup by Argentina, 4-3 on penalty kicks after a 2-2 draw.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very difficult way to go out of the tournament'', said
English coach Glenn Hoddle, after keeper Carlos Roa had knocked
aside two shots, the last by David Batty, to earn the Pale Blues a
quarterfinal date with the Dutch in Marseille on Saturday. ``Good
luck for Argentina, but it's hard for us to take.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the third time in eight years that the English had been
bounced from a major tournament in a shootout, having lost to the
Germans in the semifinals of both the 1990 World Cup and 1996
European championships.
</P>
<P>
   But this time, they thought the gods were with them once they'd
held off the two-time champions for what seemed an eternity after
midfielder David Beckham was sent off in the 47th minute after
spitefully kicking Diego Simeone after Simeone had fouled him. ``I
thought it was going to be our day,'' said English coach Glenn
Hoddle. ``Obviously, it's a massive disappointment.''
</P>
<P>
   The Argentines, who knocked the English out of the 1986 Cup on
the infamous ``Hand of God'' goal punched in by Diego Maradona,
were happy just to get out alive. They had trailed 2-1 after
Michael Owen, England's 18-year-old greyhound, had humiliated their
defense with a mad 50-yard dash. And with Simeone and star striker
Gabriel Batistuta on the bench and unavailable for the shootout,
the Argentines covered their faces after English keeper David
Seaman batted down the second shot by Hernan Crespo.
</P>
<P>
   The Argentines, who gunned down both Yugoslavia and host Italy
to make the 1990 finals, have a knack for surviving shootouts. But
few inside the Stade Geoffroy-Guichard Tuesday night ever thought
it would come to that, not with the Pale Blues playing 11-on-10 for
as long as they did.
</P>
<P>
   ``England played the way they always do, very much in keeping
with their tradition and character,'' said Argentine coach Daniel
Passarella. ``Even though they lost one player, we were always
struggling.''
</P>
<P>
   Argentina had dealt the English a stunning blow in the sixth
minute, going up on Batistuta's penalty kick after Seaman had
tripped Simeone in the area. But the Reds had gotten it back in the
10th when Owen took an artful dive after Roberto Ayala's bump and
captain Alan Shearer scored from the spot.
</P>
<P>
   When Owen, the boy savior from Liverpool, scored the goal of the
tournament in the 16th, taking a ball from Beckham, blowing by
defender Jose Chamot, skirting Ayala in overdrive and blasting a
goal to the far corner, the English were surging on emotion and
adrenalin, boosted by thousands of fans who rocked this
reverberating cockpit with chants of `Come on England' and choruses
of `Rule Brittania'.
</P>
<P>
   It took a span of three minutes for everything to change. Just
before the half, during added time, the Argentines lined up for a
free kick -- and pulled a sucker play. Instead of looping the ball
over or around the English wall, Juan Veron knocked it across to
Javier Zanetti, who slipped around Darren Anderton and Paul Scholes
and fired a shot past Seaman, as 10 men in white jerseys stood
around sheepishly.
</P>
<P>
   So it was 2-2, and two minutes into the second half it was also
11-on-10 after Beckham (better known in the States as Posh Spice's
boyfriend) got himself sent off by Danish referee Kim Milton
Nielsen. So Hoddle had his remaining midfielders play back and his
squad stiffened their upper lips and got by on what Walt Whitman
called ``the surly English pluck''.
</P>
<P>
   Except for a goalmouth cross in the 61st minute which Shearer
deflected away and a grab by Seaman on Marcelo Gallardo's corner in
the 89th, the Pale Blues managed little for the rest of the match.
Anywhere they went in the midfield, there was an English pit bull
snapping at their ankles. ``We were aiming for victory,'' shrugged
Veron, ``but with the English on the defensive, the match didn't
seem winnable.''
</P>
<P>
   If anything, the English came closer to winning it. Shearer
uncorked a free kick in the 52nd that Roa saved. Owen sprinted into
the area in the 75th but ran out of angle. Then defender Sol
Campbell headed one into the net in the 81st but it was called back
for a foul on Shearer.
</P>
<P>
   Had Nielsen noticed what appeared to be a hand ball in the box
by Chamot a minute into overtime, the English might have gotten
long-delayed justice for Maradona's goal. But he didn't, so it went
to the shootout. And when Seaman thwarted Crespo, the Reds crossed
their fingers and looked to the heavens.
</P>
<P>
   But Roa immediately denied Paul Ince, and it was even. After
Veron, Gallardo and Ayala had scored for Argentina and Paul Merson
and Owen for England, it came down to Batty, the midfielder from
Leeds who had come on for Anderton in overtime. ``You can't force
someone to take a penalty,'' said Hoddle. ``I asked David if he
wanted to take it and he accepted.''
</P>
<P>
   Batty aimed for the left side of the goal, which had been golden
for everybody else. But Roa got there for a clean block and England
was back in its own peculiar circle of Dante's hell. ``At the end
of the day, it's a game of football that we lost,'' Hoddle said.
``And we have to bounce back from it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
