</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GM-DAYTON-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Brake plants OK strike
 &HT;    By Mike Wagner
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ United Auto Workers in Dayton are ready to dust
off their old picket signs and stage another walkout against the
General Motors Corp. as soon as striking workers in Michigan end
their battle with the world's No. 1 automaker.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of UAW Local 696 on Tuesday received approval from their
members at two GM brake plants in Dayton to organize a possible
strike against GM later this summer. About half of the 3,400 hourly
workers voted and nearly 80 percent supported the strike
authorization.
</P>
<P>
   The strike vote means Dayton might be the next battleground in
the ongoing fight between the International UAW and GM. Strikes at
two factories in Flint, Mich., have already closed 26 of GM's 29
North American assembly plants, idling more than 7,000 GM workers
in the Miami Valley, and 162,000 auto workers nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   GM said Tuesday the strikes cost it $1.18 billion, or $1.79 a
share, in the second quarter, more than analysts expected.
</P>
<P>
   Local 696 members chastised GM Tuesday after casting their
votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Contracts don't mean anything to GM. All they want is to keep
taking our jobs from Dayton to Mexico or other foreign countries
and we are sick of it,'' said Mike Boehmer, a 34-year employee at
the brake plant on Wisconsin Boulevard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of us could retire and don't really need to do all this.
But we'd like to keep GM jobs in Dayton and give the kids around
here a chance to have decent jobs,'' Boehmer said.
</P>
<P>
   Local 696 leaders will now ask the International UAW to approve
a five-day strike letter against GM. That letter would set a
five-day deadline to resolves any issues before the International
UAW could organize a walkout. The International UAW, not Local 696,
would decide when to serve GM with that five-day strike notice.
</P>
<P>
   A strike may never happen, but if a walkout does occur, it
likely wouldn't begin until the Flint strikes are resolved,
according to UAW officials.
</P>
<P>
   The Flint strikes have already crippled GM's North American
production, so a strike by Dayton workers would not have much
additional impact.
</P>
<P>
   Still, a lengthy strike in Dayton later this summer could shut
down GM's North American operations within days, just as it did in
March 1996, when Local 696 members staged a 17-day walkout. The job
action ultimately cost GM nearly $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important the corporation understands that local unions
are ready to draw a line in the sand and make GM live up to their
agreements,'' said Gary Hill, president of UAW Local 696.
</P>
<P>
   ``GM's credibility is at an all-time low all over this country.
People say a strike would be disaster for our plants, but GM wants
to take away 1,800 jobs. That's disaster right there,'' Hill said.
</P>
<P>
   GM officials said a strike authorization hurts their ability to
bring business to the brake plants.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very concerned about the message this vote sends to our
customers,'' said GM spokesman Jim Hagedon. ``Without strong
support of our customer base, revenue and jobs disappear and the
long-term future of these plants remains very much at risk,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The two brake plants have been facing the threat of sale or
shutdown unless they become profitable. Documents show the two
plants have lost more than $40 million in the past two years and
projections show they could lose as much as $262 million in the
next five years.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps more than any other manufacturing operation, the local
brake plants symbolize the dilemma facing hard-line unionists
trying to save jobs within a huge company that's determined to cut
costs.
</P>
<P>
   The local issues splitting the UAW and GM in Dayton include:
</P>
<P>
   E Company documents show GM wants to slash about 1,800 jobs from
the brake plants and combine the operations into the factory on
Needmore Road. The union says GM agreed in the local contract to
employ about 2,900 workers at the plants until 2002.
</P>
<P>
   E GM wants to eliminate ``make out and quit,'' a quota clause
that requires workers to produce a certain number of parts in an
8-hour workday. Workers sometimes complete the work in five or six
hours, but get paid for a full shift. Because of the quota clause,
the brake plants have the lowest productivity rating among any of
GM's parts plants, company officials said.
</P>
<P>
   E Union leaders say GM has failed to add 70 jobs it promised
late last year and the company has violated some health and safety
standards. The union also is concerned that GM is subcontracting
the plants' skilled trade and maintenance work.
</P>
<P>
   Local 696 leaders believe a letter from Ricardo Blazquez,
manager of the both brake plants, spurred Tuesday's large voting
turnout and encouraged employees to support a possible strike.
Before the 1996 strike, only about 200 workers attended the strike
authorization vote.
</P>
<P>
   In his letter, Blazquez warned his work force that a strike
authorization would endanger the plants' future.
</P>
<P>
   Union leaders distributed a letter of their own Tuesday and
blasted Blazquez.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your actions in regards to the letter are deplorable and a
blatant violation of the GM/UAW national agreement for attempting
to use fear and intimidation as a means to negotiate directly with
our (members),'' said the letter from Joe Buckley, Local 696 shop
chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Hagedon said the company doesn't regret sending Blazquez's
letter to the union.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say Local 696 is only following the lead of the
International UAW, which is trying to protect its membership at
plants throughout the U.S.
</P>
<P>
   As in many other GM plants, most Dayton workers have more than
25 years' seniority and are nearing retirement. The union's goal,
through a combination of strikes and increased productivity, is to
keep such plants open long enough to allow workers to retire, said
Sean McAlinden, a University of Michigan labor analyst.
</P>
<P>
   If a Dayton walkout occurs, ``it'd be a
`get-me-a-couple-more-years' kind of strike,'' McAlinden believes.
</P>
<P>
   Talks aimed at ending the strikes at the Flint Metal Center and
GM's Delphi East parts plants resumed Tuesday, but no progress was
reported.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
