<SLUG> BC-MEAD01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mead on hunt for mill
 &HT;    By Mike Drummond
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Paper industry analysts believe Mead Corp. is
shopping for at least one of rival International Paper Co.'s coated
paper mills, two weeks after the Dayton-based paper company
announced the sale of its flagging Zellerbach distribution unit to
IP.
</P>
<P>
   Mead has clenched its operations around coated and specialty
paper, packaging and school and office supplies. Last week the
company restructured and combined its coated paper divisions, which
make high-quality paper for the publishing industry.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Purchase, N.Y.-based IP has made no secret it is
disappointed with the performance of its own coated paper business.
The company may sell or restructure the division in the next year
or two.
</P>
<P>
   ``There needs to be significant improvement (with coated
paper),'' said IP spokesman Phillip Giaramita. ``That's high on the
list here.''
</P>
<P>
   The confluence of these events has germinated talk that Mead and
IP are ready to do business again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's something behind that rumor,'' said Mark
Wilde, an analyst with Bankers Trust New York. ``The most likely
business Mead would grow in would be coated paper.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilde believes the primary target is IP's large coated paper
mill in Jay, Maine _ just up the road from Mead's Rumford coated
paper mill, purchased two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Jay millworker Reggie Tardif said talk about a sale has been
swirling for about a year, though no buyer's name has been
mentioned. He said IP is having trouble selling the plant because
of its massive dumping mound _ an environmental liability dubbed
``IP Mountain.''
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Peter Ruschmeier of Donaldson Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette said he
doesn't know of any specific mills Mead would want, but he knows
Mead is on the hunt.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are talking about Mead making acquisitions,'' he said.
``Mead has sold off some assets and its balance sheet is in good
position.''
</P>
<P>
   Kathryn McAuley, an analyst with Brown Brothers Harriman, was
among those who predicted Mead would jettison Zellerbach. She also
thinks Mead and IP will strike another deal.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say other possible Mead acquisitions include Crown
Vantage's mill in St. Francisville, La.; Weyerhaeuser Co.'s mill in
Columbus, Miss.; and Repap Enterprises's mill in New Brunswick.
</P>
<P>
   Coated paper accounted for about $1 billion, or 22 percent, of
Mead's annual sales of $5 billion last year, McAuley said.
</P>
<P>
   Coated Paper sales last year were $1.8 billion, or 9 percent, of
IP's total sales of $20 billion, according to the company's annual
report.
</P>
<P>
   Mead officials declined to comment specifically about potential
acquisitions, citing Security and Exchange Commission rules against
insider trading.
</P>
<P>
   But spokeswoman Elizabeth Russo said, ``We would like to grow
our coated paper business.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
