A4713 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UNDERWRITING-QUARTER-     06-30 0970
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNDERWRITING-QUARTER-775&AMP;ADD-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CORPORATE UNDERWRITING SOARED IN FIRST HALF OF '98 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(th) 
 By JOSEPH KAHN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Wall Street generated more money for corporate
America in the first half of this year than any other six-month
period in history, as historically low interest rates and a still
buoyant stock market gave fresh momentum to the business of issuing
stock and debt.
</P>
<P>
   The frenzied pace of underwriting has helped finance
consolidation in almost every area of industry, reflected in the
record pace of mergers and acquisitions. Companies worldwide
completed mergers and acquisitions valued at $1.36 billion in the
first half of this year, double the figure from the corresponding
period a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   The money-raising boom also channeled funds into start-up
companies and financed investment in technology and production
equipment at larger ones, helping prime America's economy for
strong expansion in the second half, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``My sense is that this reflects a great entrepreneurial spirit
in the economy,'' said Peter Blanton, an equity capital markets
specialist at Credit Suisse First Boston. ``You have people who are
starting companies or companies investing in new growth areas
because of the availability of capital today. That means it is
having an effect on the real economy.''
</P>
<P>
   At just shy of $1 trillion, securities companies raised almost
as much money for clients in the January to June period as they did
during the whole of last year, which was in itself a record,
according to Securities Data Co. of Newark, N.J..
</P>
<P>
   That, in turn, has meant soaring profits for Wall Street's
leading securities companies. Many have seen their already strong
earnings growth accelerate so far this year with jumps of one-third
or more in first-half profits.
</P>
<P>
   The question for many on Wall Street is whether the underwriting
juggernaut will meet resistance in the second half. Some analysts
expect that the drop in interest rates this year prompted a
one-time jump in companies seeking to take advantage of low rates
to refinance earlier debt. That trend will not necessarily continue
in the second half, as debt offerings slowed significantly as the
second quarter came to a close.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been seeing nearly perfect conditions for people to
borrow money,'' said Jeff Chandler, head of the global debt
syndicate desk at Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co., Wall Street's leading debt
underwriter. ``But I would be hard pressed to say that the level of
issuance is going to continue.''
</P>
<P>
   The outlook for stock issues is also murky. Many securities
firms say they have a large backlog of equity offerings that should
keep them busy through the year, as hundreds of companies have
taen the first steps toward raising capital on the public markets
and world governments continue to sell the public stakes in
government-controlled phone and energy companies.
</P>
<P>
   But the stock market has turned choppy in recent weeks and
investors have become fussier about what kinds of newly issued
stocks they want to buy. June was one of the worst months in recent
memory for initial public offerings, with at least a dozen
companies that were scheduled to issue shares deciding to hold off
until market conditions improve.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a combination of a more flattish market and a more
selective buyer. Things are slower going into the summer,'' said
Thomas Tuft, co-head of global equity capital markets at Goldman,
Sachs &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   Others see new stock issues picking up in the fall, however, as
some delayed deals from the summer and a bulging backlog of fresh
corporate offerings compete for investors' attention.
</P>
<P>
   With Wall Street steaming ahead at top speed, there was enough
business to keep every big investment bank bustling. But the battle
to lock up clients and generate fees was as fierce as ever, with
the major brokerage houses fighting for the top spots on the
quarterly league tables, the brokerage house rankings.
</P>
<P>
   For the second quarter, Merrill Lynch was the clear leader in
overall offerings of debt and equity. In total, Merrill underwrote
$169 billion of securities, for a 16.9 percent market share.
Salomon Smith Barney was No. 2, with Morgan Stanley Dean Witter,
Goldman, Sachs and Lehman Brothers rounding out the top five.
</P>
<P>
   Ranked by underwriting initial public offerings of stock, the
most hotly contested brokerage business because of the large fees
associated with that work, Goldman, Sachs took a dominant
leadership position. The private bank underwrote about $2.5 billion
worth of new issues, for a 22 percent market share. Morgan Stanley,
Salomon Smith Barney, Prudential Securities and Credit Suisse First
Boston made up the top five.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch was a surprise laggard in new equity issues so far
this year. A Merrill official said, however, that a large initial
public offering priced Tuesday, the last day of the second quarter,
would make it the second-largest underwriter for the period if that
deal were added to its total.
</P>
<P>
   Salomon Smith Barney, which itself is the result of a merger
late last year, put in a strong equity underwriting performance
after slipping in the rankings last year. The company ranked third
among brokerage firms for equity underwriting so far this year,
compared with a seventh-place performance in the corresponding
period a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is indicative of the type of equity distribution
we put together,'' said Jim Cowles, head of equity capital markets
at Salomon. ``After the merger, we are bringing in clients that we
did not have before.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
