<HEADER>
A4716 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-UCLA-LADN     06-30 1349
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECRUITING GAMBLES PAY OFF BIG FOR UCLA 
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Recruiting classes, especially great ones, are
years in the making. Relationships form, trust develops, the
recruit's inner circle grants approval, and a letter-of-intent is
signed. UCLA's 1998 basketball class is no different. The Bruins
made first contact with JaRon Rush, their heralded incoming
freshman, in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   But the blueprint for UCLA's success was sketched during several
closed-door meetings last fall when coach Steve Lavin weighed two
options: pursue solid Southern California recruits like Ricky
Anderson and Nate Walton, who both eventually signed with Arizona;
or try to snare the top national talent (Rush, Jerome Moiso and Dan
Gadzuric) in the spring.
</P>
<P>
   If the Bruins aimed high and missed, they'd be shut out of
replacements for J.R. Henderson and Jelani McCoy.
</P>
<P>
   Lavin rolled the dice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach Lavin understands that to keep UCLA afloat at the level
the program needs to maintain, you have to take risks,'' assistant
coach Jim Saia said. ``We passed up good players to try to get
great players.''
</P>
<P>
   For the next eight months, Lavin and his assistants solidified
relationships with recruits _ and, equally important, with their
inner circles _ and produced what many recruiting services believe
is the nation's No.1 class.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perhaps the classes when they brought in Bill Walton or Lew
Alcindor were better,'' recruiting guru Bob Gibbons said. ``But in
the 20 years I've been doing this, there has never been a UCLA
class this good. They did it the old-fashioned way. They earned it
by outworking people. I've rated it No.1 (in the nation). It has
the potential to be truly a Fab Five class.'' &QL; 
Caribbean surprise
</P>
<P>
   In April of '97, Lavin dispatched Saia to an all-star game in
Orlando. By that point in the recruiting season, most coaches
reasoned, the top European talent had been tapped. But Orlando was
the first U.S. appearance for Jerome Moiso, a native of the
Caribbean nation of Guadaloupe who attended high school in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Moiso was easy to spot: 6-foot-10, with long arms and a mature
physique, well-skilled offensively. Obviously, a prime talent.
</P>
<P>
   Saia watched Moiso practice, then spoke with him for an hour.
That first contact proved decisive. Their relationship progressed
through the summer and culminated when Moiso visited UCLA last
summer. A week later, he gave the Bruins a verbal commitment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seeing him practice and being able to talk to him was
crucial,'' Saia said. ``That's where it all began with us and
Jerome.''
</P>
<P>
   Moiso was so eager to begin he asked to enroll in December. But
as a marginal student with rudimentary English skills, his grades
and SAT scores prevented it. He matriculated to Milford (Conn.)
Academy, played his way into the national scene, and crammed for
the SATs. He signed a letter of intent last month and attained a
qualifying score several weeks ago. &QL; 
Persistence pays
</P>
<P>
   If ever a player appeared destined for Kansas, it was JaRon
Rush. The 6-6 forward is a Kansas City, Mo., native and starred
locally at Pembroke Hill School. His father-figure, Tom Grant, is a
multimillionaire and a Kansas booster. Last fall, Rush was quoted
in the Kansas City papers as saying, ``It would take an act of God
for me not to go to KU.''
</P>
<P>
   After seeing the comment, UCLA athletic director Peter Dalis
walked into the basketball office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess it's over,'' Dalis said.
</P>
<P>
   Bruins assistant Michael Holton, who doubles as the recruiting
coordinator, would not surrender.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good thing God is in the miracle business,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Jayhawks underestimated Rush's interest in UCLA. He visited
the campus in 1995, he idolized Charles O'Bannon and his AAU coach,
Myron Piggie, was friendly with former Bruins assistant Lorenzo
Romar. When Romar left for Pepperdine in 1996, Holton stepped in.
</P>
<P>
   Through the recruiting process, Piggie grew to respect and trust
Holton. Even when it appeared Rush was headed to Kansas, Piggie
urged Holton to disregard the reports. Grant's influence will fade,
Piggie advised, and Rush will forge his own path.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public perception was JaRon was being groomed to go to
Kansas and just being courteous to other schools,'' Holton said.
``We never believed that. We were patient instead of panicking or
going in another direction.''
</P>
<P>
   There were other factors. Rush is close to UCLA guard Earl
Watson, a native of Kansas City, Kan., who also played AAU ball for
Piggie. Rush also liked UCLA's style of play, he liked Southern
California, and he liked Lavin. ``He's down to earth and easy to
get along with,'' Rush said.
</P>
<P>
   As Rush veered from his patriarch, Grant, he was drawn to the
Bruins' youthful coaching staff and committed to UCLA in February. &QL; 
The center piece
</P>
<P>
   Northern California recruits Ray Young and Matt Barnes had
signed in November. With Moiso committed and Rush in the fold, one
player stood between UCLA and the nation's No.1 recruiting class:
Daniel Gadzuric, a 6-10 talent of Yugoslavian and Caribbean
descent, raised in Holland, schooled at Gov. Dummer Academy in
Byfield, Mass., regarded as the country's top center prospect.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Moiso,Gadzuric was a known commodity. From Kentucky and
Kansas to George Washington and California, every school wanted
him. Nor did the Bruins have an insider (i.e.: Piggie) keeping
watch over their best interests. Instead, they had to convince both
Gadzuric and his coach, Steve Metz, that Westwood was the right
place.
</P>
<P>
   The courting began in earnest last summer, when Gadzuric's AAU
team played in Long Beach, and he visited the campus unofficially.
After three years on a rural campus in Byfield, Mass. _ 30 minutes
outside Boston _ Gadzuric wanted a metropolis. He immediately liked
Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA customized its pursuit. Gadzuric is into Disney characters,
so the Bruins' notes and letters to him included Mickey Mouse
graphics.
</P>
<P>
   ``They sent one with Mickey and Minnie holding a basketball, and
Dan's face was in the ball,'' said Metz, laughing. ``I said, `Would
you go to a school that does that?' And he said, `Yeah, I love that
stuff.'''
</P>
<P>
   When the recruitment began, Metz, who serves as Gadzuric's
pseudo-guardian in the U.S., preferred an Eastern college. He was
wary of UCLA's distance, the young coaching staff and the potential
problems stemming from Jim Harrick's NCAA violations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people at UCLA were very open and generous with their
time,'' Metz said. ``(On the campus visit) Lavin went out with me
at night, and we met with coach Wooden and stayed up late talking
basketball. For the head coach to be that accessible was very
different. They won me over.
</P>
<P>
   ``The final piece was meeting the players. I mean, how can you
not like Baron Davis?''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins had impressed Metz, but there was another hurdle: the
NBA. Gadzuric's Dutch advisers believed an NBA contract and
subsequent shoe deal would turn their man into Europe's most famous
player, worth $15 million a year with unlimited endorsement
possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Saia headed to Germany to discuss options. He explained the
rules governing college eligibility. (Once Gadzuric declared for
the draft, he could not withdraw.) He detailed the NBA's rookie
salary structure. (Gadzuric would not be eligible for massive
free-agent dollars for three years, at the earliest.) And he
described the declining state of shoe contracts. (Rare for big men,
rarer still for rookie big men.)
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Gadzuric's advisers endorsed college over the NBA.
His classroom performance improved this semester, and in May the
NCAA Initial Eligibility Clearinghouse certified his Dutch grades,
removing the final obstacle to freshman eligibility.
</P>
<P>
   He's due in town in August.
</P>
<P>
   ``All that NBA talk was around the Final Four, and it was
scary,'' Saia said. ``It's unbelievable when you have a kid that
good from overseas, because you have to deal with so many people.''
</P>
<P>
   It's easier to roll the dice.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-98 2132EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
