<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 21:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4720 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JORDAN-LOOKALIKE-ART-     06-30 0708
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JORDAN-LOOKALIKE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ULTIMATE HOOP DREAM: TO PLAY JORDAN ON TV 
</HEADLINE>
  (Duplication warning: also moving in `e' category) 
(ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(JT) 
 By PAM BELLUCK    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ In real life, Timothy Smith is a ``mystery shopper''
for Taco Bell, buying chicken incognito at the fast food joints and
reporting to headquarters whether it is cooked too little or served
too cold.
</P>
<P>
   This job may have done little to prepare him for his big moment
Tuesday, but Smith, 30, had other things going for him. For one,
his head was shaved. For two, he had the right answer when the
casting director, Julie Ashton, asked him, ``Timothy, how tall are
you?''
</P>
<P>
   6 foot 4, he answered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perfect,'' Ms. Ashton said.
</P>
<P>
   Smith became one of a handful of men who may just have a shot at
the movie part of a lifetime, the title role in ``Michael Jordan:
The Untold Story of an American Hero.''
</P>
<P>
   This week, television producers have descended on Chicago,
hoping that somewhere in this scrappy workingman's town where the
six-time National Basketball Association champions, the Bulls, are
the municipal religion, they might just find a natural for the part
of the world's most famous athlete in a movie to be made this fall
and broadcast before the end of the year for the new Fox Family
Channel.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unlikely we're going to get the Denzel Washingtons of the
world,'' said Lance Robbins, a producer for Fox Family Channel.
</P>
<P>
   And while actors across the country have been sending in their
head shots and bragging on their hook shots, ``we haven't seen many
professional actors that could play basketball and look like
Michael Jordan,'' Robbins said. ``We've literally had white guys
submit reasons why they should play Michael Jordan: `I may not look
like him but I can play him.' ''
</P>
<P>
   In Chicago, the producers threw open a high school gym on Monday
so that Jordan wannabes could show how they looked on a basketball
court. Several thousand men, teen-agers and boys showed up, some
waiting in line for hours to audition for the boyhood, teen-age and
basketball star phases of Jordandom.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who wouldn't want to be Jordan?'' said Robert Reed, 29, a high
school math and science teacher who tried out for the part. Reed is
such a Michael fan that his 5-month-old son's middle name is
Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   After the aspiring actors dribbled and took a few shots, at the
direction of a former community college basketball coach, and read
a line in front of a camera, Ms. Ashton selected the 30 or so most
promising Jordans for callbacks to a studio Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Parkinson, a 27-year-old firefighter who showed up for
the gym casting call after working a 24-hour shift, was one.
Tuesday, in a dark Italian suit with a red silk pocket
handkerchief, showing Jordan's Armani side, Parkinson sat in a room
full of Jordan look-alikes mouthing a scene in which Jordan, having
left basketball for baseball, decides to respect the baseball
strike: ``I won't cross the strike line, Ron. I'm outta here.''
</P>
<P>
   His Airness himself has nothing to do with ``The Untold Story.''
The screenwriter, Michael Murray, who has written television movies
about the Menendez Brothers and Madonna, has teased a script out of
the many books, magazine articles and newspaper stories that have
been written about Jordan
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't approached him,'' Robbins said. ``But someday, we
would love to have a Michael Jordan meeting. We'd love to have him
bless the project.''
</P>
<P>
   The movie will be overwhelmingly favorable, Robbins said,
touching only briefly on his affinity for gambling and a few
sensitive scenes, like ``the fact that he was very very shy when he
was in college, hardly went out on dates, and joined a home
economics class and got confidence to interact with women.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Ms. Ashton was quite impressed by a few of the
novices, especially Smith, who delivered the lines with emotion and
nuance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually, you're really looking mostly for, like, acting
skills,'' Ms. Ashton said. ``But with this project, it's really a
look. And basketball skills would be nice too.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-98 2132EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
