<HEADER>
A4725 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOLPHINS-INVESTIGATIO     06-30 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOLPHINS-INVESTIGATION-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dolphins' Phillips under investigation
 &HT;    By Ethan J. Skolnick
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ When he signed Lawrence Phillips last
December, Jimmy Johnson said he would give the troubled running
back very little margin for error.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's one rule - do what's right - and that encompasses a
lot,'' the Dolphins coach said of a man whose transgressions
included assaulting a former girlfriend, drunk driving and
disorderly conduct.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's one rule surely does not encompass what Phillips
stands accused of having done late Saturday night. Police in
Plantation are investigating whether Phillips assaulted a West Palm
Beach woman at the Brickhouse Lounge in Plantation, Fla., when she
refused to dance with him.
</P>
<P>
   The woman, Michelle Black, has a criminal history too. Black,
26, was charged with a felony of aggravated battery with a deadly
weapon in 1997, pleading guilty in October to a lesser misdemeanor
charge of battery and paying $1000 restitution to the victim.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now it's an ongoing investigation,'' Plantation police
Detective Steve Geller said of Saturday's alleged incident. A
report will be forwarded to the state attorney's office, and Geller
said Phillips will have a chance to tell his side of the story.
</P>
<P>
   According to the police report, Black was sitting in the
Brickhouse Lounge after 2 a.m. Sunday morning when Phillips
approached her and asked her to dance. She said she didn't dance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you know who I am?'' Phillips allegedly asked, before
threatening to ``break your jaw bone and pull the weave out of your
head.''
</P>
<P>
   The report says Phillips then punched her twice in the face, and
tried to flee the nightclub. Black suffered a minor cut to the
lower lip and a front chipped tooth. She would later say she felt
dizzy, and claim that she blacked out momentarily. She was taken to
Plantation General Hospital for observation.
</P>
<P>
   Black's sister, Seglanda Miller, alerted club security, and
Phillips was detained by three policemen. According to the report,
Phillips denied hitting or knowing Black, and ``was somewhat
uncooperative.'' He ``was told to calm down or he may be arrested
for disorderly conduct.''
</P>
<P>
   Phillips was told by the head of nightclub security that he
would be arrested for trespassing if he returned to the club. He
left with two friends, one of them former University of Miami
quarterback Ryan Collins, who, the report says, ``supposedly ...
offered the victim's sister Miss Johnson $20 to forget the
incident.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the question is whether Johnson forgets it, and in turn,
forgets what he said about cutting Phillips very little slack.
</P>
<P>
   The Dolphins' division rivals, the New England Patriots, have
released two players in the last two years, because of their
off-the-field troubles. In April, they cut Phillips' former
Nebraska teammate Christian Peter, who (among other things) had
received 18 months probation after pleading no contest to sexually
assaulting a former Miss Nebraska. Last month, New England released
Dave Meggett, who was facing sexual assault charges in Canada. The
charges were later dropped.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, during the Johnson tenure, the Dolphins have signed Clayton
Holmes, Roosevelt Potts, Lamar Thomas and Phillips, and drafted
Hudhaifa Ismaeli and Kenny Mixon. Holmes, Potts, Ismaeli and Mixon
all had previously failed drug tests. Thomas served time on
domestic abuse charges.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson is fond of saying that he is very consistent, meaning
that he treats everyone differently. But Phillips was expected to
get the worst of that double-standard. Johnson took a big risk in
signing him, so he could compete with Karim Abdul-Jabbar and now
first-round pick John Avery for the starting tailback spot.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, the risk seemed worthwhile. Phillips got his weight
down from 234 to 216 - he's listed at 210 on the police report -
and until breaking his toe in early June, was making headway toward
playing time. Now he has some explaining ahead of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first I've heard of it,'' Johnson said in a
statement Tuesday. ``If it is true, we will all obviously be very
disappointed. We will take our time with this to look at all of the
facts. Only after we have gathered all the information and the
facts, and I have had an opportunity to speak with Lawrence, will
we make a decision on what action might be taken. Until we do those
things, no action will be taken by the Dolphins.''
</P>
<P>
   The police may take their own action in the interim.
</P>
<P>
   Ethan J. Skolnick writes for the Palm Beach Post. Staff writer
John Holland contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
