r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STREET-SFCHRON &LR;      06-30 0679
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STREET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)  
 
 IPO Gives Sagging Silicon Graphics a $60 Million Shot in the Arm   By Mark Veverka  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
Remember Silicon Graphics, the one-time world-beater whose
technology made dinosaurs in ``Jurassic Park'' roam the big screen?
<TEXT>
<P>
   The company, which now is fighting for survival after frittering
away its initial success, was just made $59.5 million richer
yesterday. Silicon Graphics came into the money by spinning off
about 16 percent of its MIPS Technologies subsidiary, a maker of
high-end computer chips.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; MIPS offered 1.25 million new shares at $14, while Silicon
Graphics sold 4.25 shares of its MIPS holdings during the initial
offering. The stock traded under water much of the day before
closing at $13.44.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the lukewarm reception on a down day for computer chips,
Silicon Graphics certainly could use the extra cash. Chairman and
CEO Richard Belluzzo, a former top executive of rival
Hewlett-Packard, needs it to implement his blueprint for a
turnaround at the ailing computer firm.
</P>
<P>
   And while the majority of Wall Street analysts that follow
Silicon Graphics (SGI) have a dour view of its long-term prospects,
a handful of fund managers and and analysts say the stock is cheap
and poised for at least a near-term rise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying that Silicon Graphics is the most endearing
company in the world, but they just got handed a check for (about)
$60 million,'' says one hedge-fund manager.
</P>
<P>
   The IPO dough certainly will increase Silicon Graphics' asset
value. What's more, the bulls think that investors will warm up to
the stock once Belluzzo starts wielding his cost-cutting blade. The
short-term positive financial impact on operating margins might
give the stock at least a temporary lift, the hedge-fund manager
says.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a pretty speculative call,'' says analyst Kurt King of
NationsBanc Montgomery Securities in San Francisco, who rates the
stock a ``hold.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm a hedge-fund manager and it goes up only a point, I can
still make some money. But there are some long-term concerns for
the business,'' King says.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest problem for Belluzzo is to transform Silicon
Graphics from a maker of high-end graphics products to a
manufacturer of network computer systems.
</P>
<P>
   And SGI's share price reflects the harsh reality that new
management has a long way to go. Thus, Silicon Graphics might look
ripe for speculative investors at around $12 a share, just a point
above the company's 52-week low of about $11 &UR; . &LR;  The low point was
January 12, several days prior to announcements that Belluzzo was
leaving HP to run SGI.
</P>
<P>
   After its initial rise on the news of Belluzzo's new job,
Silicon Graphics' stock climbed again _ hitting its 52-week high of
$30 in September. The run-up apparently was triggered by twin
announcements: a deal with Intel to make new products together, and
plans to take a piece of MIPS public.
</P>
<P>
   But it has been downhill ever since. Once the new-management
euphoria faded, investors woke up to &UR;  &LR; company warnings of quarterly
losses and the reality of the company's core problem of entering a
new business segment dominated by IBM, HP and Sun Microsystems.
</P>
<P>
   Competing with such titans won't be easy. Belluzzo has taken at
least one step in the right direction by arranging to use Microsoft
software and Intel chips to build so-called Wintel computer
workstations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cost-cutting is an ongoing thing'' and should not drive
the stock, says analyst Daniel Kunstler of J.P Morgan Securities in
San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   But Silicon Graphics ``could be an interesting little value
play,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   HEADS UP:
</P>
<P>
   A former U.S. Food and Drug Administration official is expected
to release some noteworthy data on a development-stage AIDS drug
Friday morning at the World AIDS Conference in Geneva.
</P>
<P>
   New test results are expected to support the effectiveness of
Immune Response Corp.'s Remune, an immune-based therapy for the
treatment of HIV infection.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
