<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRODERBUND-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)  
 
 Fast Fall For Maker Of Myst   By Dan Fost  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
 
For longtime fans of Broderbund Software, last week's acquisition
by The Learning Co. wasn't just another merger.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Learning Co. represents everything Broderbund was not: A big
mean merchandising machine. Where Broderbund, the last independent
maker of multimedia, built its reputation on innovation, The
Learning Co. has grown to its mega-status by swallowing companies
whole and undercutting the competition.
</P>
<P>
   That undercutting was among the factors on which Broderbund
blamed its unprofitability. Indeed, it's one of the reasons
Broderbund executives finally took the desperate measure of
shopping the company, and selling it at what many in the industry
saw as the bargain price of $420 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really is a shame to see things end up this way for
Broderbund,'' said Eric Winkler, Broderbund's former marketing
communications director, who now is director of marketing for IBM's
Edmark division in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have the same sad feeling as someone saying goodbye to a
longtime friend. It took (founder) Doug Carlston and (former
president) Bill McDonagh 18 years to build what was a special
place. To see it go to anyone less than a Disney and at a price
that is so far below the value Wall Street placed on the company
just a year ago doesn't seem to do those 18 years justice.''
</P>
<P>
   Winkler recalled a company heyday in which children of employees
filled the halls, employees brought their dogs to work and Friday
get-togethers built a sense of community.
</P>
<P>
   In another irony, in Broderbund's prime, it nearly bought The
Learning Co. That was only two years ago, an eternity in the
consumer software trade. At the time, The Learning Co. was a
smaller, Fremont-based entity.
</P>
<P>
   Broderbund had offered $440 million for The Learning Co. at that
time, a whopping sum _ nearly nine times The Learning Co.'s
revenues. It lost out when Cambridge, Mass.-based SoftKey
International made a hostile $606 million bid. SoftKey changed its
name to The Learning Co. when it completed the transaction.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to those overheated days, The Learning Co. last
month agreed to buy Broderbund for an estimated $420 million, or
roughly the company's revenues plus its cash.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Carlston, a Harvard lawyer, founded Broderbund with his
brother Gary in 1980. In the early years, it was a games company,
but it soared to great heights with Where in the World is Carmen
Sandiego? educational software. Doug Carlston also acquired The
Print Shop, which became another Broderbund mainstay. In the 1990s,
Broderbund scored another hit when it published Myst, a quirky
computer game that went on to top the all-time sales charts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Broderbund basically invented the connection between good
product and good brand in our industry,'' Learning Co. Chairman and
Chief Executive Officer Michael Perik said in a conference call to
analysts when the deal was announced.
</P>
<P>
   Broderbund stock soared in those years, topping $70 before it
fell into a long slow decline. It had fallen as low as $15 a share
this month, finally rebounding on the acquisition rumors. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  The high-tech landscape has changed drastically from
Broderbund's early days as a barn-burner. Several factors hurt the
company, analysts say:
</P>
<P>
   _It was late to recognize the significance of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   _It depended too much on its old hits. ``Myst is still
incredibly successful, but that's more luck than anything they did
on their part,'' said Andrea Williams, an analyst with Volpe Brown
Whelan and Co. in San Francisco. ``You can't be a one-hit wonder
and survive. At least, you can't survive for long on your past
successes.''
</P>
<P>
   _It just couldn't compete in the new land of the software
giants. The Learning Co. and Cendant, in their war to build market
share, offered rebates of as much as the entire price of individual
software titles.
</P>
<P>
   Broderbund officials long complained about the pain such tactics
inflicted. Ultimately, analyst David Cole figures they decided,
``If you can't beat 'em, join 'em.''
</P>
<P>
   When it competed against The Learning Co., Broderbund always
pointed to the quality of its products. Even at the merger
announcement, Broderbund CEO Joe Durrett said the deal brings
``great distribution, execution and management skills to what I
think is arguably one of best sets of evergreen titles the software
industry's ever seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Notice he didn't say anything about joining The Learning Co.'s
strong lineup of titles. ``The original SoftKey was known for
shovelware,'' analyst Cole said, using a derogatory industry term
for software that's crammed into boxes and sold before it can be
polished to a higher quality.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-98 2144EDT &QL; 
