<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOFTWARE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)  
 
 Software's Sequoias   By Julia Angwin  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
Two giants are battling for dominance of the consumer software
industry _ and neither one is named Microsoft.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Despite all the attention paid to the Redmond, Wash., software
giant, it is not the nation's top seller of software in stores.
</P>
<P>
   There are two contenders for that spot: Cendant Corp., a
troubled Southern California conglomerate that owns everything from
hotel chains to software, and The Learning Company, a Cambridge,
Mass., software firm that keeps gobbling up its competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft dominates the overall software market, but most of its
sales come from businesses, not stores.
</P>
<P>
   Until last week, Cendant held the No. 1 consumer software spot.
But then The Learning Company announced its intention to buy rival
Broderbund for $420 million _ which would boost it to the No.1 spot
in sales, according to PC Data.
</P>
<P>
   ``This Broderbund acquisition puts The Learning Company one step
ahead,'' said Stephen Dube, senior analyst with Wasserstein Perella
in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, each company has less than a 10 percent slice of the $2
billion market for consumer software _ which ranges from computer
games to desktop publishing to educational titles.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Their battle illustrates the increasingly competitive nature
of the consumer software industry, where shelf space is hard to
come by and prices are falling.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say the only way to survive the shelf battles and price
wars is to have a huge lineup of titles and hope for a best-seller
_ such as Broderbund's Myst, the best-selling game of all time _
that will pay for the non-hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's beginning to look like the book publishing industry,
where it's hard for a single-title publisher to break into the
market,'' said Jeff Tarter, publisher of Softletter, an industry
newsletter in Watertown, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   ``The small companies are fine as long as they have hits,''
Tarter said. ``But if they hit a dry spell, they go broke.''
</P>
<P>
   To avoid such a fate, Cendant and The Learning Company have both
used acquisitions to build large libraries of titles. In fact, both
firms were born from mergers.
</P>
<P>
   The Learning Company is the successor to SoftKey Software _ a
Cambridge, Mass., company that was created in 1994 as the result of
a merger of three small software companies.
</P>
<P>
   SoftKey changed its name to The Learning Company after buying
the Fremont software firm with that name.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, The Learning Co. has bought eight more firms,
racking up huge financial losses but also ringing up the sales.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, The Learning Company racked up losses of $475 million
on sales of $392 million. But at the same time, its stock has
steadily climbed to yesterday's all-time high of $29.63.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street is betting that The Learning Company eventually will
turn a profit once it has gobbled up the all companies in its way.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Learning Company has acted as a consolidator,'' said Larry
Marcus, software analyst at BT Alex. Brown in San Francisco. ``We
forecast them to be the fastest-growing market share leader.''
</P>
<P>
   The Learning Company also has an advantage because it focuses
only on software, ``while Cendant is more scattered between
categories,'' Marcus said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Cendant is barely a software company. It was formed in
December from the $11 billion merger of direct marketing firm CUC
International and HFS Inc., an owner of hotel chains such as Days
Inn and Ramada, and real estate brokers such as Century 21.
</P>
<P>
   Before the merger, CUC had been on a two-year buying spree in
the software and Internet industry _ snagging software industry
leaders Davidson Associates and Sierra On-Line, as well as a number
of Web site companies.
</P>
<P>
   Since Cendant was created, the company has slowed its
acquisitions, partly because it ran into financial trouble. On
April 16, Cendant shares plunged 46 percent after the company said
it had discovered accounting irregularities.
</P>
<P>
   The firm's stock has not yet bounced back, even though the
company fired the people involved.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Cendant has been leading a software-industry trend
called ``net zero pricing,'' according to David Cole, senior
analyst at DFC Intelligence, a market research firm in San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Essentially, the company is giving away software. For example,
Cendant offers some titles for sale at $29.95 _ and then gives the
buyer a manufacturer's rebate of $29.95, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cendant is a direct-marketing company,'' Cole said. ``They
figure that's a good way to get names'' for future sales prospects.
</P>
<P>
   The Learning Co. has been matching Cendant's deals, Cole said,
but neither side can afford to keep it up forever.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough for companies trying to make money off the software
business,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   However, analysts say the companies that can afford to lose
money in the short term likely will be the long-term winners.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect there to be continued consolidation,'' said Andrea
Williams, Volpe Brown Whelan analyst. ``It's a profitable business,
but it's only profitable for a few companies.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  ``Is it sad because there's less selection?'' she asked.
``Ultimately, the reason for that is, the market's not supporting a
broad selection.''
</P>
<P>
   On the contrary, TLC spokeswoman Susan Getgood said
consolidation is good for consumers. ``To some degree, it
guarantees that the brands that they love and trust will continue
to be available to them,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   One reason is that consumers are paying less for their computers
_ which now cost less than $1,000 _ and they want to pay less for
their software, too. Many PCs now come with the software basics _
word processing, e-mail, spreadsheet, database, Web browser,
graphics program _ already included.
</P>
<P>
   ``Software has to come down in price to reflect those changes,''
said Rob Enderle, analyst at Giga Information Group in Santa Clara.
``There are only a few large players that can afford the cost of
mistakes. We end up across the gamut with larger, more powerful
companies, for good or for bad.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
