<SLUG> BC-CHINA-VOICES-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINESE SAY CLINTON MAKES FEELING FREE CONTAGIOUS, BUT FOR HOW
LONG? 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By ELISABETH ROSENTHAL    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ For the week, millions of curious Chinese have sought
out a chance to lay eyes on President Clinton, on TV or in person,
to catch their first glimpse of what wide open democracy looks
like.
</P>
<P>
   Some watched a joint news conference broadcast live on
television that turned into a genuine public debate about sensitive
political subjects, like human rights and the Tiananmen massacre.
For many it was their first such debate, and more memorable for
being between President Jiang Zemin and Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Others skipped class to gate crash an auditorium at Beijing
University where the president engaged students in a hard-hitting
question and answer session.
</P>
<P>
   American officials openly hoped that these kinds of events would
promote a free political discourse in China.
</P>
<P>
   Many ordinary Chinese who saw the president indeed came away
enthusiastic and impressed _ feeling, even acting, more free. But
others cautioned that only time would tell whether this fuzzy sense
of freedom could outlast the presidential visit or translate into
concrete political change.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this was a very good thing and a important step
towards greater openness in politics,'' said Deng Zhenglai, a
prominent liberal magazine editor. ``In the past the Chinese people
had never seen talks between leaders on sensitive topics, and it
helps them appreciate the importance of open discussions.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he added: ``So now we have seen that leaders can talk
openly in China. But there's no sign yet about whether the average
Chinese can talk openly too.''
</P>
<P>
   In dozens of interviews, a broad mix of Chinese people _ from
students to factory workers to small entrepreneurs _ said that
Clinton's frank discussions and the willingness of China's leaders
to openly respond have left them hopeful that China will move
toward a more democratic political system, and left them feeling a
bit freer to speak out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like now we can talk a little more about sensitive
issues like human rights and Tibet,'' said Song Jiantong, a
middle-aged book publisher who was strolling on Beijing's Chao Yang
Avenue under a big red umbrella with his wife, Fang Shuqing.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Fang described excitedly how she and her husband were
shocked to run across the unannounced live debate between Jiang and
Clinton while channel surfing Saturday. ``I took the debate as a
signal that China's going to be more democratic than before,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Still China remains a tightly controlled dictatorship, albeit
one that is loosening its hold. And, Tuesday, as always, many
people in Beijing were unwilling to be drawn into even vaguely
political discussions. More than a dozen older people said they had
``no viewpoint'' on Clinton's visit when asked, even though many
said they had seen or heard about the extraordinary political
exchange.
</P>
<P>
   But a younger generation of Chinese does have opinions, which
they are increasingly willing to share. And Clinton's trip seems to
have served as a catalyst for them.
</P>
<P>
   On the lush campus of Beijing University many students said they
took time off from studying for final exams to listen to Clinton
answer pointed student questions about human rights and Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   From his perch by the side of the Beijing University's famous
``No Name Lake,'' Xiao Yan, a math major, said that he and five
classmates had rushed from a final exam to watch on TV at a
restaurant, where they had watched the presidents joint news
conference two days before.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very exciting,'' he said. ``This is something we rarely
see, since most of the news avoids controversial topics, so this is
a sign of progress. There's an old saying, `When you hear from many
different sides only then you understand.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that people have heard both sides of the relationship
speak, they'll be able to form their own opinions,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   But he also said that Clinton could not have forced such
discussion if China's government had not itself been willing to
accept more candid discourse. ``The Party is already much more open
than 15 years ago,'' he said. ``It has been a slow step by
step-process.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Zhao Xingang, a 25-year-old businessman who attends graduate
school at night, said: ``This visit has opened the possibility that
Chinese themselves will be able to openly debate such topics. I
think the leaders are leaning in the direction of democracy.'' Like
many young Chinese, he praised Jiang for breaking with tradition to
engage in such a public debate _ and to permit it to be shown live
on television.
</P>
<P>
   But Zhang Xiaojin, a professor of International Relations at
People's University in Beijing, laughed when asked if the Clinton
visit would have a large impact on the rules of Chinese domestic
politics. ``Maybe on the next generation,'' he said. ``The kind of
influence it will have will be subtle and indirect.''
</P>
<P>
   And some people emphasized that the Party's decision to engage
in debate did not mean that it was interested in revising
longstanding positions, but rather reflected a new confidence that
it could chart its own course.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government felt that the debate would not cause an
uncontrollable reaction, and they wanted to show they are moving
towards greater freedoms,'' said a 20-year-old chemistry major at
Beijing University who would only be identified by his surname,
Nie, as he shared a watermelon at a campus stand.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to know how the blunt though cordial exchanges
between Clinton and Jiang on topics like the Dalai Lama and human
rights played in the inner sanctums of the Party compound,
Zhongnanhai. Chinese leaders are never called on to defend their
positions to the Chinese public, let alone to an American public
watching half a world away.
</P>
<P>
   Some Chinese and certainly the hard-line old guard in the Party
must have cringed as they watched Clinton, the guest, attacking
Chinese policy on live TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``No doubt there are some people who do not think so highly of
this, but those people have no impact whatsoever now,'' said Li
Jie, a historian and expert on international relations with the
Communist Party School.
</P>
<P>
   Many Chinese said that it was not Clinton's views, but his style
and the flavor of the open debate that came as a shock. A number of
urban Chinese have Internet access and Hong Kong cable television
so they have read, for example, about the American position on
Tibet and have seen Clinton utter sound bites.
</P>
<P>
   Still, many said they were floored by his live performance in
the television debate. ``Before we had only seen him in pictures,''
said Song Jiantong, of the publishing house. ``We didn't know he
was so funny and easy going. He answered every question. We now
have a better understanding of what U.S. democracy is about.''
</P>
<P>
   Xiu Ruizhaun, a doctor at the Chinese Academy of Medical Science
said, ``Clinton has the right to talk about issues. It was a good
beginning to see that he was not hostile to China.''
</P>
<P>
   Many young Chinese said that Jiang, who read from notes, looked
stiff compared to the loquacious American president. But then
again, Clinton has been doing these performances for 30 years, and
Jiang is new to the business.
</P>
<P>
   Although political freedoms are still severely restricted in
China, many Chinese said they felt and acted more free this week
than they had in years. In a country known for crowd control,
emboldened citizens jumped over barricades to get a better view of
Clinton; they approached Western reporters offering opinions _ even
offering their names.
</P>
<P>
   But experts were unsure whether such enthusiasm would induce the
Chinese government to hasten the pace of change.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clinton's landmark visit might have opened the door to a
possible fundamental transition to democracy in China,'' said Liu
Juning, a political scientist at the Chinese Academy of Social
Science. ``When such a live televised debate takes place in China
between the top Chinese leader and another Chinese person _ rather
than a visiting president _ then democracy will not be far away.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
