HOUSTON CHRONICLE COMPUTER PROBLEMS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lmp) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; EDITORS: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The Houston Chronicle's computer problems will continue through
this cycle (Tuesday, June 30). The following budgeted stories
cannot be moved except by special arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   If you are expecting one of these stories and are able to
receive it by e-mail, please call Anthony Trowbridge at
713-622-0294:
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-INVESTIGATION (Washington) _ Linda Tripp, whose tapes of
her phone conversations with Monica Lewinsky apparently provide the
most damaging evidence against President Clinton, makes her first
appearance before the grand jury investigating sex and cover-up
allegations against the president. By JOHN C. HENRY.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-US (Washington) _ In the latest skirmish over the Iraqi
no-flight zone, U.S. pilots fire a missile at an Iraqi radar
installation that illuminated patrolling British warplanes. By
BENNETT ROTH.
</P>
<P>
   AIDS-CONTROL (Geneva) _ Eradication of HIV from the body may not
be possible anytime soon, but total elimination may not be
necessary to control the disease, experts say at the 12th World
AIDS Conference. By RUTH SoRELLE.
</P>
<P>
   BURNED-BOY (Splendora, Texas) _ On Sunday, Robert Middleton was
the center of attention at a party celebrating his 8th birthday.
That same evening someone doused the boy with gasoline and set him
on fire. Today, he is clinging to life in a Galveston hospital,
burned over 99 percent of his body. By PAUL McKAY and KEVIN MORAN.
</P>
<P>
   OYSTER-RECALL (Galveston, Texas) _ The number of reported
illnesses linked to contaminated Galveston Bay oysters is at least
128. Wholesalers have been working since Friday to keep suspect
oysters from being served in restaurants across Texas, California,
Colorado, Florida, Louisiana and New Mexico. By KEVIN MORAN.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst News Service
</P>
