<HEADLINE>
FIERCE FIGHTING AS SERBS TRY TO PUSH REBELS FROM KOSOVO TOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Map being sent to NYT graphics clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204.)  
 (af)  
 By CHRIS HEDGES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KOSOVO POLJE, Yogoslavia _ Fighting between Serbian forces and
separatist rebels in Kosovo Province was heavy on Tuesday as senior
Serbian officials vowed to drive the rebels from a town near the
provincial capital and open roads obstructed by rebel barricades.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbian authorities blocked reporters from entering the area
of the fighting. But the rattle of automatic weapons and periodic
explosions reverberated from the slag heaps and roads surrounding
the Belacevac open pit coal mine, which was seized by ethnic
Albanian guerrillas from the Kosovo Liberation Army a week ago.
</P>
<P>
   Spirals of black smoke rose from burning houses in the village
of Hade next to Belacevac, six miles west of the provincial
capital, Pristina.
</P>
<P>
   An attempt by a convoy of reporters to enter the town on Tuesday
afternoon was met by an angry crowd of heavily armed Serbian
civilians who smashed the windows of the vehicles and threatened
reporters with automatic rifles and pistols.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said on Tuesday that the
violence in Kosovo was ``unacceptable.'' She called on President
Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia _ of which Serbia makes up the
larger part _ to withdraw Serbian special police units and the
Serbian-dominated Yugoslav Army from the province.
</P>
<P>
   ``Milosevic is digging himself into a hole deeper and deeper in
terms of increasing the level of violence, and the violence has to
stop,'' she said in Shanghai, where she was traveling with
President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The latest Serbian attack, which began on Monday, is part of an
attempt by the 50,000 or so special police and army soldiers
deployed in Kosovo to push back the rebels, who now control about
40 percent of the province.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbian governor of Kosovo, Veljko Odalovic, said on Tuesday
that Serbian forces would soon begin to clear rebel checkpoints and
barricades from all major roads in the province, a push that
Western officials fear could further step up the fighting.
</P>
<P>
   The main road from Pristina to Pec has been blocked by armed
rebels for seven weeks, and the Serbian-held town of Kijevo, 25
miles west of Pristina, is surrounded by rebel troops.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Holbrooke, the U.S. special envoy who visited the area
last week, called Kijevo ``the most dangerous place in Europe,''
saying that an attack to relieve the town could touch off a general
war.
</P>
<P>
   About two dozen Serbian police and some 200 Serbian civilians
are trapped in Kijevo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot wait much longer to open the road,'' Odalovic said
in an interview late on Tuesday afternoon, ``especially considering
the situation of the Serbian population surrounded in Kijevo. The
United States and Europe do not have a constructive attitude
concerning this problem.''
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic League of Kosovo, the province's governing ethnic
Albanian political party, said four people had been killed,
including an 8-year-old boy, and that eight men had been wounded in
the fighting around Belacevac on Monday. There was no way to
confirm the reports independently.
</P>
<P>
   The heaviest fighting remains concentrated around Belacevac.
</P>
<P>
   In much of the province there are daily skirmishes between
Serbian forces, often sheltered behind sandbags, and the rebels.
Special policemen have moved about a half-dozen armored personnel
carriers to within a mile of a barricade of cars set up by rebels
armed with rocket-propelled grenades in Lapushnik, blocking the
road to Pec.
</P>
<P>
   There has been desultory fire and shelling, but the Serbian
forces have yet to crash through the roadblock. On Monday several
houses near Lapushnik were on fire, but there were no reports
Tuesday of fires or heavy combat around the checkpoint.
</P>
<P>
   The three-pronged Serbian assault by hundreds of policemen and
soldiers on Belacevac have driven more than 8,000 people from their
homes in the mining town and the neighboring village of Hade during
the last two days. Serbian officials said the police and Serbian
paramilitary forces had advanced to within 600 feet of Belacevac.
They said the advance had deliberately been slowed to avoid taking
many casualties.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are being very cautious,'' Odalovic said. ``We want to
prevent as many casualties as possible among both our police and
civilians. The terrorists are trying to use the civilians as a
human shield.''
</P>
<P>
   The Belacevac mine supplies coal to the nearby Obilic power
plant, which provides electricity to most of Kosovo and parts of
the rest of Serbia and the neighboring country of Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   The rebel army, which saw its ranks swell with volunteers after
a violent Serbian sweep four months ago that was intended to wipe
out the opposition, is fighting to create a separate state.
Kosovo's ethnic Albanians make up 90 percent of the two million
people in the province. The fighting has left more than 300 dead.
</P>
</TEXT>
