<HEADLINE>
MENTAL ABUSE CAN LEAVE DEEPER SCARS THAN PHYSICAL MISTREATMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By GINGER SCOTT  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ The bruises left from her husband's rage have faded.
She's come to terms with the memories of his swinging fists.
</P>
<P>
   But there are deeper wounds _ some Jan Agardy has carried for 16
years _ that haven't even begun to heal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The physical abuse I have put into perspective and dealt with,
but I am nowhere near dealing with the emotional abuse,'' said
Agardy, 49, who was physically and mentally abused by her husband.
</P>
<P>
   Most physical violence is easily recognized and frequently
discussed, Agardy and other domestic-violence victims said. But the
torturous, sometimes bizarre, acts of emotional abuse are more
deeply hidden and may take years to overcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``Physical things heal,'' Agardy said. ``The mental and
emotional abuse are mixed with your identity _ and it becomes so
fractured that it takes a while for you to get it back.''
</P>
<P>
   It began, Agardy said, with isolation from her friends and
family. Her husband would make her feel guilty for talking on the
phone to friends or family, she said, to the point that she'd
rather not talk to anyone at all.
</P>
<P>
   He would also read every item on her grocery receipt, she said,
pointing out where she spent too much money and telling her she was
too stupid to know how to shop correctly.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes he would assail her with vulgar language and names
until she was on the floor in tears, ready to call police. But she
didn't call. He told her the police wouldn't believe her because
she couldn't show them her ``bleeding guts.''
</P>
<P>
   Emotional abuse can even be inflicted through a victim's
children, said Monalou Callery, herself a former victim who worked
with the Arizona Coalition Against Domestic Violence and now trains
others in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   She said her husband once lined her three children up and forced
each to tell her she was a ``whore,'' ignoring their pleas of
protest.
</P>
<P>
   Extreme as they may sound, these two women's experiences are not
uncommon, domestic-violence counselors say. Other forms of mental
abuse frequently cited by victims include:
</P>
<P>
   Constant name calling, and forcing children to call the victim
names.
</P>
<P>
   Convincing the victim that nobody else would want them.
</P>
<P>
   Threatening to take the children if the victim tries to leave.
</P>
<P>
   Devising strict rules for the victim to follow at home.
</P>
<P>
   Controlling finances and setting aside an allowance for the
victim.
</P>
<P>
   Restricting the victim's freedom by keeping the car keys,
disabling the engine or even locking the victim up at home.
</P>
<P>
   What most domestic-violence victims have in common, however, is
a batterer desperate for control, said Betty Ryan-Della Corte,
founder of Faith House.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wants to control the money, how you dress, or he monitors
your whereabouts,'' she said. ``They do it to control you.''
</P>
<P>
   But a batterer might not stop there, said Marge Di Stasio of the
Sojourner Center. To continue his victim, she said, an abuser also
will work to prevent her from ending the relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``The batterer tries to distort a woman's reality until she
thinks she's crazy,'' Di Stasio said. ``They wear the woman down
until she doesn't have the self-esteem to leave.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not a woman is ready to leave, counselors say talking
to someone is always a good first step.
</P>
<P>
   A woman must learn that she doesn't have to live in an
emotionally abusive relationship, Di Stasio said. But it's hard for
a victim to believe she deserves better when she's constantly being
told that the problem is her.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like trying to get sober at a bar,'' she said. &QL; 
Ginger Scott can be reached at 444-8222 or at
ginger.scott(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
