</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-SOCSEC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOCIAL SECURITY'S FUTURE, AND GORE'S 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ If the prospect of trying to fix Social Security
gives heartburn to nearly all politicians, it could be downright
ulcerating for Vice President Al Gore. His role in any solution to
the retirement system's looming financial problems could prove
either a tremendous accomplishment or a heavy burden going into the
2000 presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   For President Clinton, insuring Social Security's viability for
the 21st century is an overriding goal, but one for the history
books. With no elections in his future, he can afford to cut
benefits, raise taxes or tinker with the basic structure of what is
arguably the most successful of government programs.
</P>
<P>
   It is tougher for Gore, who will be the host of a
town-hall-style debate on Social Security in Cranston, R.I., on
Wednesday. He has to keep his eye on key constituencies like
organized labor, the elderly and other groups that want to keep
Social Security more or less intact, while at the same time
recognizing that many Americans are eager for a chance to invest
some of their Social Security payroll taxes in the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   Already other presidential hopefuls are staking out positions.
Most striking are the emerging differences among Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Traditional liberals like Rep. Richard A. Gephardt of Missouri
want to keep the current guaranteed government retirement benefit
intact, although they would consider allowing the Social Security
system itself to seek higher investment returns by investing in the
stock market.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Bob Kerrey of Nebraska is challenging party orthodoxy by
advocating the establishment of private investment accounts
financed by a portion of payroll taxes. Kerrey sees the accounts as
a way of helping people at the bottom of the income scale to amass
more wealth along with those at the top.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans like Speaker Newt Gingrich and Rep. John R. Kasich
of Ohio are also coalescing around some version of private
accounts.
</P>
<P>
   But at the Rhode Island debate _ the second in a series
organized at Clinton's urging by the American Association of
Retired Persons and the Concord Coalition, a fiscal watchdog group
_ Gore will remain studiously neutral.
</P>
<P>
   His cautious nature might have kept him out of the ideological
fray anyway. But in this case his role was dictated by Clinton, who
wants to spend this year letting all sides in the debate slug it
out before weighing in with a plan of his own at a White House
conference in December.
</P>
<P>
   Some potential opponents in the presidential race ahead are
already suggesting that they are more willing than Gore to make
tough choices and offer innovative solutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's more risk in riding the fence on this one than on most
issues, because it could prove to be a razor-wire fence,'' said
Steve Jarding, Kerrey's national political director. ``No matter
who the candidates are, you'd better lead on this issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Democrats suggest that Gore will suffer, especially in the
primaries, if he strays too far from the party's liberal base and
goes along with Clinton and the Republican Congress in any plan
that reduces Social Security's role as a poverty fighter for the
elderly and the disabled.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's advisers say he will play a high-profile role in reaching
a bipartisan consensus when Congress gets down to serious work on
the issue next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is probably going to be the predominant issue in the
national debate in 1999, and Al Gore plans to be right in the heart
of it,'' a senior adviser to Gore said Tuesday. ``People say Gore's
going to run and hide. That's just not true.''
</P>
<P>
   White House officials say that in internal debates Gore
advocates gutsy approaches to dealing with long-term entitlement
costs regardless of the political fallout.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, he and Clinton could find a way to stake out middle
ground between the varying approaches. One option favored by the
Gore camp would keep the basic Social Security system intact but
create voluntary private accounts for people who wanted a chance to
invest more for their retirement.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we come in between Kasich and Gephardt,'' said one
administration official, ``it plays well for Al Gore.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
