<SLUG> BC-BRAVES-NOTEBOOK01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves notebook: Klesko probably will not go on DL
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ The Braves are going to try to play
short-handed until the All-Star break, which shouldn't pose a
problem. They've been doing it much of the first half of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   The team has postponed any decision to place Ryan Klesko
(appendicitis) on the disabled list, in hopes that he would be able
to return to action before the 15-day inactive period expires. That
decision was contingent on the return of Andres Galarraga (sore
lower back), who played Tuesday for the first time in six days _
and homered in his first two at-bats. That means the Braves will be
down to 24 healthy players until after the All-Star game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we can cope,'' said manager Bobby Cox. ``We've been
playing most of the year with 22 or 23 anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   That's in reference to nagging injuries to Walt Weiss
(hamstring), Keith Lockhart (shoulder) and Galarraga. But the
team's dilemma is also linked to the talent remaining at Class AAA
Richmond. Outfielder Damon Hollins could get his second call-up of
the season, but beyond filling out the bench, would hardly see
action. Class AA Greenville outfielder George Lombard (.332, 14 HR,
33 RBIs) would be a candidate for elevation, but he has been
sidelined with a sore shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ryno could play in 10 days,'' Cox said. ``That's right after
the All-Star break (July 9). He could be back in time for four
games with the Marlins and then go right into the series with the
Mets. If we disable him, he'd miss all those games with the
Marlins.''
</P>
<P>
   Klesko's appendix was removed Monday by Dr. Joe Mims via
arthroscope, which reduces the traditional recuperation time from a
month down to a week to 10 days. He could be released from Piedmont
Hospital today.
</P>
<P>
   Walt's wait
</P>
<P>
   After Weiss finished second in AL All-Star balloting for
shortstops in 1989, he figured it might just take time to make the
team. But that notion gradually faded through low finishes to the
point that he conceded he'd never be so honored.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've thought about it in the past,'' he said, ``but I got to
the point now where I just accepted the fact that I was never going
to play in an All-Star game.''
</P>
<P>
   That changes next Tuesday when he starts for the NL in Denver,
but that news was secondary to the improving condition of son
Brody, 3, who is fighting an E. coli infection. Not only was he
upgraded to fair condition Monday, but doctors at Scottish Rite
Childrens Medical Center could conclude his dialysis treatments
today. At the current rate of progress, Brody could go home this
weekend. Chipper Jones was gratified at being voted the NL's
starting third baseman, at the All-Star but objected when it was
suggested that the balloting hinted a changing of the guard among
the league's top third basemen.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, because if (San Diego's Ken) Caminti is healthy, he's
still probably the premier third baseman, as far as being able to
do it all,'' Jones said. ``He's a Gold Glover. He's been a National
League MVP. Obviously, his numbers are pretty good year in and year
out. When I compare third basemen around the league, Caminiti's is
the statement.''
</P>
<P>
   Etc.
</P>
<P>
   Catcher Eddie Perez took his first crack at DH Tuesday night.
Intricate strategy? ``There's nobody left,'' said Perez.
``Everybody's hurt.'' ... To restock a dwidling roster in Richmond,
the Braves signed former farmhand Andy Tomberlin Tuesday. After
lasting seven years in thesystem without reaching Atlanta,
Tomberlin, 31, had drifted through four organizations since 1993
before being released June 22 by Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
