<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Defensive end Goodloe plans to transfer from Texas
 &HT;    By Mark Wangrin
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Backup defensive end Will Goodloe has been
released from his scholarship at the University of Texas and plans
to transfer, the school confirmed Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Goodloe, a junior who did not go through spring drills because
of family concerns, had planned to return in the fall but decided
he needed a fresh start elsewhere, he told school officials.
Goodloe returned to his hometown of Spring Valley, Calif., to
contemplate his next move. He could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-5-inch, 275-pounder entered the preseason last year
as the projected starter but lost the job in camp. He played
sparingly during the season, making 11 tackles in nine games.
During the spring he reduced his class load to help care for his
wife, who had complications during childbirth, and was ineligible
to go through spring drills. He was projected as a backup in the
fall.
</P>
<P>
   Goodloe, a consensus top-100 national recruit who also received
basketball offers from Villanova, Southern California and Tulsa,
made 14 tackles in 12 games as a freshman in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're sorry the situation did not work out for Will at the
University of Texas,'' Coach Mack Brown said in a statement. ``But
we wish him the best of luck as he continues his college
education.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The AMERICAN-STATESMAN, AUSTIN, TX
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-06-30-98 2044E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
