<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TAIWAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SAYS U.S. DOES NOT SUPPORT INDEPENDENCE FOR TAIWAN  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHANGHAI _ President Clinton, in a concession to Beijing, stated
formally on Tuesday that the United States did not support
independence for Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese government, which considers Taiwan a breakaway
province that should be politically reunited with the mainland, had
pressed Clinton to state the American policy while he was on
Chinese soil.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and other senior officials
have expressed the carefully worded three-part American position on
this trip and on other occasions. But it was important to Beijing
that the words come from the president himself, and he obliged
during a round-table discussion with Shanghai residents today.
</P>
<P>
   In response to a question from Wu Xinbo, a professor in the
American Studies Institute at Fudan University here, Clinton said
that he had told Jiang Zemin, China's president, that American
policy on Taiwan remained unchanged.
</P>
<P>
   Reiterating what has come to be known as ``the three no's,''
Clinton said: ``I had a chance to reiterate our Taiwan policy,
which is that we don't support independence for Taiwan, or two
Chinas, or one Taiwan-one China. And we don't believe that Taiwan
should be a member in any organization for which statehood is a
requirement.''
</P>
<P>
   Taiwan reacted harshly, even though Clinton's words were the
same careful formula that American officials have used before.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States and Chinese Communists have no rights and
are in no position to conduct bilateral talks on anything related
to our affairs,'' said Roy Wu, Taiwan's Foreign Ministry spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   There is considerable debate about how new Clinton's statement
is. The ``three no's'' formula was publicly used last fall by the
State Department, which viewed it as a reiteration of longstanding
policy. But some scholars and supporters of Taiwan say the formula,
as it was expressed then, was more detailed and restrictive than
past statements, and they called on Clinton to disavow it.
</P>
<P>
   Officials traveling with Clinton tried to minimize the
importance of the president's statement. The president told the
same thing to Jiang, they said, and there was no intention of
putting the statement in a written communique, a move that would
give the words more weight.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president himself had indicated prior to coming here that
he would reaffirm longstanding U.S. policy, and he did so,'' said
Mike McCurry, the White House spokesman. ``And I believe during the
course of this visit we've made it clear both publicly and
privately that we hope the people of Taiwan and the people of the
People's Republic find an amicable resolution to the question of
Taiwan. And that obviously would be a useful outcome of
cross-strait dialogue.''
</P>
<P>
   McCurry also noted that the president had restated American
policy toward Taiwan in an answer to a question during an
appearance at Beijing University on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   At that event, Clinton said: ``First of all, the United States
policy is not an obstacle to the peaceful reunification of China
and Taiwan. Our policy is embodied in the three communiques and in
the Taiwan Relations Act. Our country recognized China and embraced
a one-China policy almost 20 years ago. And I reaffirmed our
one-China policy to President Jiang in our meetings.''
</P>
</TEXT>
