<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-ALLSTARS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKS FAIL TO LAND ALL-STAR STARTER 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By JACK CURRY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The fans who punch the holes in the All-Star ballots
were not overly impressed with the individual players on the best
team in the major leagues, since the Yankees did not have any
starters voted to the American League team Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   This was not as shocking as it may sound, because the Yankees
have exemplified a team concept and do not really have one standout
player, like a Juan Gonzalez. They have a handful of stars.
</P>
<P>
   First baseman Tino Martinez, shortstop Derek Jeter and second
baseman Chuck Knoblauch each finished second while third baseman
Scott Brosius, who might deserve the honor more than any other
Yankee position player, finished third. The pitchers and reserves
will be selected Wednesday, and Joe Torre is expecting three to
five Yankees to make the team for next Tuesday night's game in
Denver.
</P>
<P>
   The manager did not feel snubbed by the lack of recognition.
</P>
<P>
   ``In '96, we didn't have anybody in the top 10 in the MVP
voting,'' Torre said. ``If that's any indication what this means,
that's OK. If you're using that as a barometer, it's OK with me.''
</P>
<P>
   While Torre wants his players to be lauded for their
achievements, he emphasized that they are focused on team goals
instead of personal ones like the All-Star team.
</P>
<P>
   Torre spoke with Cleveland's Mike Hargrove, who will pick the
rest of the team, and obviously lobbied for David Wells (who is on
schedule to possibly start the game), David Cone, Paul O'Neill (who
finished sixth among the outfielders), Brosius and Jeter.
</P>
<P>
   Like Torre, the Yankees were not forlorn about being overlooked
in the starting lineup. The Yankees possess a selfless personality,
and grousing about missing out on the All-Star team is as foreign
to them as three straight batters swinging at the first pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kids pick up the ballot card and vote for the biggest
names they know from Nintendo,'' O'Neill said. ``My son does that.
I did that when I was a kid. I wanted to see Willie Mays.''
</P>
<P>
   Brosius added, ``I think if you ask anybody on this team, the
recognition they're interested in is playing on a World Series
team, not an All-Star team.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, who had crept ahead of Cleveland's Jim Thome in the
voting last week, seemed relieved that he had lost by 200,000 votes
because he wants to rest his shoulder injury. The absence of
himself or any Yankees in the lineup did not bother Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at Ken Griffey Jr. and Alex Rodriguez and the types of
seasons that they are having,'' said Martinez, referring to the
Seattle center fielder and the shortstop who will be starters.
Griffey has 32 homers and 71 runs batted in and Rodriguez has 27
homers and 66 RBI. ``I'd say they would trade places with us to be
where we are in the standings.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Cone and Wells both entered Tuesday night's game with the
Phillies with 10 victories, they appear to be cinches to make
Hargrove's pitching staff. O'Neill was the first name Torre
mentioned as a Yankee who should be on the team, Brosius has
probably been the best all-round third baseman in the league and
Jeter was being trumpeted as a most-valuable-player candidate
before straining his abdominal muscle in June.
</P>
<P>
   Of the three, Jeter is most likely to be bypassed because
Hargrove is sure to pick Omar Vizquel, the Cleveland shortstop,
over the matinee idol as a backup to Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really doesn't matter,'' Jeter said. ``People on this team
want to win. Everyone wants to be on the All-Star team, but we have
an ultimate goal.''
</P>
<P>
   That takes place in October, not July.
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE PITCH
</P>
<P>
   _ Bernie Williams, who is on the disabled list with a strained
right knee and who has been rehabilitating in Tampa, Fla., will
join the Yankees on Wednesday. Joe Torre said it is unlikely that
Williams will play until after the All-Star Game, but he wants the
center fielder around the Yankees. ``We're home for a week and I
want him to get back in the team stuff,'' Torre said. ``Hang around
with the guys and be here.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Chili Davis, who is also on the disabled list following right
ankle surgery in April, was at the Stadium on Tuesday and might
return in a month. The American League has not yet ruled on Mike
Stanton's appeal of his five-game suspension. Torre was unsure when
a decision would be rendered and said there is a chance the league
might want Stanton to serve the suspension vs. American League
teams.
</P>
<P>
   _ When catcher Joe Girardi, who is essentially a backup, was
told he had finished third in the All-Star balloting, he said,
``That's funny.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-98 2210EDT &QL; 
