<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LOCKOUT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EWING SAYS OWNERS CAUSE LABOR WOES  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE WISE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   On the night that the National Basketball Association shut down
for business, the Knicks' Patrick Ewing blamed free-spending
franchises for the league's contentious labor situation, but
offered few solutions for a new agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``The owners talk about wanting cost certainty,'' said Ewing,
president of the players association. ``Well, they have cost
certainty. They're the ones with the checkbooks. If they feel that
Patrick Ewing or Michael Jordan or whoever is not worth what
they're paying them, then they have the right to say, `No, this is
all we can pay you.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Then it's up to us, move on, go to another team and get what's
right. In what walk of life are limitations put on workers as to
how much they can be compensated? Wall Street? No. Why should we be
any different?''
</P>
<P>
   The owner-imposed lockout began at midnight after the collective
bargaining agreement expired. Teams are prohibited from negotiating
with, signing or trading players until a new labor agreement is
signed. Financially conscious franchises participated in a flurry
of activity Tuesday before the deadline.
</P>
<P>
   _The Philadelphia 76ers bought out the remaining $5.6 million of
Derrick Coleman's contract, making the enigmatic forward a free
agent.
</P>
<P>
   _The Orlando Magic waived the veteran point guard Mark Price.
</P>
<P>
   _The Seattle SuperSonics released the 37-year-old shooting guard
Dale Ellis.
</P>
<P>
   _The Boston Celtics let go point guard Tyus Edney.
</P>
<P>
   _The Dallas Mavericks came to terms with their No. 1 draft pick,
Dirk Nowitzki, who considered playing in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   If the lockout lasts into the season, NBC and Turner Sports
would pay full rights fees, but would recoup their losses in
different ways. NBC would recoup fees that go to lost games by
paying less over the next three seasons. Turner, which carries NBA
games on the cable networks TNT and TBS, would add more games to
its combined three-night schedule to make up for missed telecasts.
If the lockout is long, a fourth night could be added.
</P>
<P>
   With no negotiations scheduled and both sides preparing for a
long battle that could lead to lost games for the first time in
league history, Tuesday was a day for teams to wrap up loose ends.
</P>
<P>
   In Houston, Charles Barkley moved up a hernia operation that was
supposed to performed later in the month so he could be treated by
a team doctor. In New Jersey, Keith Van Horn worked out at the
Nets' facilities for perhaps the last time this summer. And across
the river in New York, Ewing, the Knicks' franchise center was
playing up themes of unity among the 400-plus players.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing spoke as one of his oil paintings was unveiled at a hotel
in Manhattan Tuesday during a private art exhibit. He did not sound
like a player whose union was about to make concessions soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``What needs to be done? I'm not really sure,'' Ewing said.
``They feel they want a greater share of the pie, like I've been
saying. And we feel we want our fair share. It's unfortunate that
it's come to this.''
</P>
<P>
   The battle is over the owners' desire to put a ceiling on how
much players can earn. They would like to change a system that they
reluctantly approved three years ago, a system that has enabled the
player salaries to account for more than 57 percent of
basketball-related revenue taken in by the league.
</P>
<P>
   Having enjoyed the benefits of the current deal, the players
hold one clause in the deal sacred and refuse to budge. Called the
Larry Bird exception, it enables teams to pay their own free agents
whatever they want _ above and beyond the salary cap.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
