<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABORT01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Enforcement of new abortion law blocked
 &HT;    By Lisa Ocker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ A federal judge Tuesday temporarily blocked enforcement
of a new state law restricting abortion, saying the law could
deprive women of their constitutional right to choose.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Donald Graham said the law also ``threatens
women with irreparable injury because they may be denied
appropriate medical care either because doctors will not treat them
or doctors will be forced to use more dangerous abortion
procedures.''
</P>
<P>
   The law, which was to become effective Tuesday, bans
``partial-birth abortions,'' except when the mother's health is
threatened. Under the law, doctors who perform the procedure could
face penalties of five years in prison and $5,000 fines. They also
may face civil lawsuits by a father or grandparents of the fetus.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys representing several doctors and clinics across
Florida argued that the law's language is so vague it also outlaws
the most common and safest abortions at any time during pregnancy,
including the first trimester.
</P>
<P>
   But Assistant Attorney General Kathleen Burgener rejected that
argument, saying the law allows other medical options for women.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, her right to privacy and to choose is not affected,''
Burgener said.
</P>
<P>
   Burgener declined to comment on the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge to the law was led in part by attorney Priscilla
Smith, representing the Center for Reproductive Law and Policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``This decision makes clear that women and their doctors, not
state legislators, have the right to make private medical
decisions,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The law defines a partial-birth abortion as a procedure where a
physician ``partially vaginally delivers a living fetus before
killing the fetus and completing the delivery.''
</P>
<P>
   Mona Reis, director of the West Palm Beach-based Presidential
Women's Center, which also challenged the law, was glad about the
judge's ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality is that the procedure is only done in the most
severe cases of fetal (birth defects),'' Reis said. ``There are
only a handful of doctors who perform these procedures, which are
done in the third trimester and none of them are in Florida, to my
knowledge.''
</P>
<P>
   Laws similar to Florida's have been enacted in 28 states.
Graham's ruling Tuesday represents the 17th time a state's
partial-birth abortion ban has been blocked by state or federal
courts.
</P>
<P>
   The partial-birth ban, passed by state lawmakers in 1997, was
vetoed by Gov. Lawton Chiles. But legislators this year overrode
the veto. Chiles challenged the timing of the override before the
state Supreme Court, which has not yet decided the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``These judges don't seem to care what the Florida Constitution
says, what the law is, or what the people want,'' said John
Dowless, executive director of Florida's Christian Coalition. The
coalition says the law only outlawed late-term abortions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wish the judges would run for political office and stop
legislating from the bench,'' Dowless said.
</P>
<P>
   Graham's ruling is effective for 10 days. A second hearing would
be required to determine the law's constitutionality.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Ocker writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach, Fla.
Staff writers Lillian Weis and Charles Elmore contributed to this
story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
