<HEADER>
A4779 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DANTZ01-COX     06-30 0528
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DANTZ01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Democrats join together for Governor's race
 &HT;    By Shirish Date
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ Just weeks after calling each other
``plagiarist'' and ``money launderer,'' the top two Democratic
candidates for governor stood side-by-side Tuesday, joined hands
held overhead in the traditional style to a cheering crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Gov. Buddy MacKay and former state Sen. Rick Dantzler made
official what both camps had leaked Monday: Dantzler would join
MacKay's ticket against Republican Jeb Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buddy, I proudly accept your invitation to become your running
mate,'' Dantzler shouted into the microphones at the rally.
</P>
<P>
   In political campaigns, yesterday's combatants can become
today's teammates, often without missing a beat. So it was Tuesday
under a blazing noontime sun.
</P>
<P>
   MacKay, who had accused Dantzler of stealing his plan to fix
health care plans, was asked if he could address their earlier
jibes at one another. ``The answer to that is no,'' he said to
laughs from the friendly crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Dantzler had complained at a news conference that MacKay and the
Democratic Party were unethically transferring so-called ``soft
money'' donations given the party to MacKay, even though Democratic
opponents weren't receiving such money.
</P>
<P>
   That tactic _ which is also used by the Republican Party and
Bush _ was called a ``scam'' in a Dantzler press release, which
closed with this exhortation: ``Stop laundering money, Buddy!''
</P>
<P>
   All of that was forgotten Tuesday as the two arrived together at
a downtown Tallahassee park, in matching short-sleeved shirts _
MacKay wore forest green, Dantzler midnight blue _ and khaki
trousers.
</P>
<P>
   Together they taunted Bush, who so far has raised several times
as much money as MacKay and Dantzler have between them.
</P>
<P>
   MacKay, though, pointed out that between them, they have more
years in state and federal political offices _ 40 _ than Bush can
ever hope for. ``Our Republican opponent can't live long enough to
get the number of years of experience that we've got,'' MacKay
said.
</P>
<P>
   A Bush spokesman turned that figure to fit a Bush campaign
theme: MacKay, with 16 years in Tallahassee and eight in
Washington, is a ``career politician.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been a part of the problem,'' Cory Tilley said.
</P>
<P>
   The third major Democratic candidate, state Rep. Keith Arnold,
of Fort Myers, has said he will remain in the race. Neither he nor
Bush has announced a running mate, which they must do by July 17.
</P>
<P>
   Bush last year named Secretary of State Sandra Mortham, only to
have her resign from the ticket this winter over negative press
reports about her financial management of her office. His running
mate in 1994, Rep. Tom Feeney, was widely seen as damaging because
of some of his unorthodox views.
</P>
<P>
   That difficulty with running mates gave MacKay grist for a
final, parting shot: ``I've made one selection for lieutenant
governor, and I'm real proud of it. Let the Republicans say what
they will.''
</P>
<P>
   Shirish Date writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
