u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRANDS-AD-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      06-30 1026
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRANDS-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: LOWE &AMP; PARTNERS/SMS WILL PROMOTE COMMERCIALS FOR CBS
</HEADLINE>
  (af)  
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Lowe &AMP; Partners/SMS in New York is creating
promotional commercials for CBS as the network gears up to peddle
its wares for the 1998-99 television season. The humorous spots,
meant to assist CBS in the challenging task of attracting a younger
audience, are set in such fanciful locales as inside a space
shuttle and outside a ``Goodfellas''-style social club.
</P>
<P>
   The commercials from Lowe, which is known for sharp campaigns
for familiar consumer brands like Mercedes-Benz, Sprite, Braun and
Perdue, are supplementing work created in-house at CBS as well as
by a boutique shop, Air Creative Group in Los Angeles, which has
been a CBS roster agency for a decade. All the spots carry the
theme ``The address is CBS. Welcome home.''
</P>
<P>
   Lowe, part of the Lowe Group unit of the Interpublic Group of
Companies, recently began working for CBS on a project basis.
Executives say the project is being extended because of the
positive initial reaction to the first three spots that Lowe
created, which CBS quietly began running in the last two weeks
during a variety of programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are already noticing and paying attention,'' said
George F. Schweitzer, executive vice president for marketing and
communications at CBS, a unit of the CBS Corp. in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``And in this business,'' he added, ``that's what you fight
for.'' Billings are not being disclosed, in part because they are
difficult to value because the commercials are running on CBS's own
air time.
</P>
<P>
   The addition of Lowe to the CBS roster points to the increasing
efforts by networks to distinguish themselves from a lengthening
list of competitors by running brand identity campaigns in addition
to the traditional spots that pitch specific shows.
</P>
<P>
   Cable networks like Comedy Central, MTV and VH1 have long looked
to Madison Avenue for brand-building commercials.
</P>
<P>
   As for the broadcast networks, ABC, part of Walt Disney Co. has
been the most prominent proponent of agency-created branding
campaigns with work from the Venice, Calif., office of TBWA
Chiat/Day, part of the TBWA Worldwide unit of Omnicom Group. A
smarty-pants campaign for the 1997-98 season, carrying the theme
``TV is good,'' is being replaced for the coming season with less
cynical ads carrying the theme ``We love TV.''
</P>
<P>
   By developing a relationship with an agency such as Lowe, ``we
went to a team that specialized at taking a look from the outside
in rather than from the inside out,'' Schweitzer said, ``which is
healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   However, he added, ``this is not ABC and Chiat/Day,'' because
``it's a project we assigned without a review; we went to Lee
directly because I believe in his creative vision for helping us
look different.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee is Lee Garfinkel, co-chairman and chief creative officer at
Lowe, who said of the project: ``The idea is to show real
situations where people you wouldn't expect are talking about CBS
programming in a more contemporary and fun way. CBS wants to
broaden viewer appeal to create a more diverse audience.''
</P>
<P>
   That's a tall order given that CBS finished the 1997-98 season
fourth among the four biggest broadcast networks in the demographic
category most coveted by advertisers _ men and women ages 18 to 49.
</P>
<P>
   Even in an older category that CBS is trying to sell
aggressively to Madison Avenue, viewers 25 to 54, the network
finished fourth among men and second among women.
</P>
<P>
   ``CBS is the oldest-skewing network and its audience composition
remains the least desirable,'' said Joe Mandese, editor of The
Myers Report, a media industry newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is that there are a lot of older `demos'
available,'' he added, because older people usually watch more TV,
``and younger `demos' are rarer.''
</P>
<P>
   Schweitzer acknowledged the difficulty of the job ahead in
reaching ``a younger audience, younger baby boomers, but we're
hoping people will see the spots and say: `I didn't expect that
kind of a commercial from CBS. Maybe I'll give those guys another
look.' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mercedes campaign that Lowe created echoed some of the
issues we're dealing with at CBS,'' he said, ``in that it was meant
to enhance a solid product with a stodgy image by using
self-effacing imagery.'' That campaign, for the Mercedes-Benz of
North America unit of Daimler-Benz AG, won kudos for such
unconventional elements as Marilyn Monroe, Marlene Dietrich and a
rubber duck.
</P>
<P>
   The CBS commercial set inside the space shuttle features the
voices of actors playing astronauts, who quarrel with Mission
Control because their launching times conflict with favorite CBS
programs like ``60 Minutes'' and ``Everybody Loves Raymond.'' They
are, the spot asserts, ``just a few of the people on Earth who call
CBS home.''
</P>
<P>
   There are two make-believe social club spots _ shot to resemble
surveillance footage _ that present grainy, black-and-white images
of actors impersonating gangsters. They are described as ``yet
another family who calls CBS home.''
</P>
<P>
   One mobster says to his friend in a dem-dese-dose voice: ``You
see `Touched by a Angel' last night? It really got to me. I haven't
had such a good cry since Tony the Fish got whacked.'' Another,
named Paulie, is welcomed back from an unspecified place that
probably had bars on the windows; his first questions are about the
plot lines of his favorite CBS series.
</P>
<P>
   Told that on ``The Nanny,'' the nanny married her boss, Paulie
replies, ``I can't believe I missed the whole wedding.''
</P>
<P>
   The commercials were created by Garfinkel; Gary Goldsmith, vice
chairman and executive creative director; Seth Fried, a copywriter,
and Steve Kashtan, an art director. The social club spots were
directed by Tom Schiller, who has contributed short films to
``Saturday Night Live.''
</P>
<P>
   The social club cronies will return for additional spots,
Schweitzer said, adding: ``I've looked at a script about our new
Monday night lineup in which one guy says, `Everything's changing;
what should I do?' and his friend advises, `Give it a shot.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
