<HEADER>
A4787 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT &LR;      06-30 0515
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WALKOUTS TO COST GM $1.18 BILLION IN 2ND QUARTER
</P>
<P>
   General Motors said strikes at two factories in Flint, Mich.,
which have forced 26 of the automaker's 29 North American assembly
plants to close, will cost the company $1.18 billion after taxes in
the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   A dispute at two Delphi Chassis Systems brake plants in Dayton,
Ohio, may also lead to another strike by members of the United
Automobile Workers union.
</P>
<P>
   FDA APPROVES NEW SWEETENER
</P>
<P>
   The Food and Drug Administration has approved the use of an
artificial sweetener known as Ace-K in soft drinks. Analysts
predict that Ace-K, marketed by Hoechst as Sunett and officially
known as acesulfame potassium, will add $55 billion in sales to the
nation's carbonated soft-drink industry. An hour after the FDA
announcement, Pepsico said it planned to introduce by October a
diet cola called Pepsi One using Ace-K and aspartame.
</P>
<P>
   SHAREHOLDERS ARE GETTING SKEPTICAL
</P>
<P>
   Investors are growing tired and skeptical of the merger frenzy.
Indeed, so far this year, stocks of 59 percent of the companies
that announced they would buy other public companies fell the day
of the announcement, up from 49 percent in the first half of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   SALES OF WINDOWS 98 ROBUST
</P>
<P>
   Sales of Windows 98 are brisk despite a puny marketing budget
and little fanfare. Retailers sold 530,000 copies of Microsoft's
new operating system in the first four days and one analyst
estimates that Windows 98 will generate revenues of $3.2 billion in
its first 12 months from sales to both computer makers and retail
customers.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN'S FISCAL EFFORTS BOLSTER YEN
</P>
<P>
   The dollar plummeted more than two and a half yen _ its biggest
loss since the United States and Japan sold dollars two weeks ago _
as traders reacted to signs that Japan was making progress to mend
its ailing banking industry.
</P>
<P>
   NIKE REPORTS LOSS OF $67.6 MILLION
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Nike fell even before the athletic shoe and apparel
company reported a net loss of $67.6 million for its latest quarter
because of continued economic woes in the Asia-Pacific region and
weakness in the U.S. market. Nike also said after the market closed
that its orders for the coming six months were off 54 percent in
the Asia-Pacific region and 11 percent in the United States, and
worldwide total orders were down 13 percent.
</P>
<P>
   CONFIDENCE INDEX AT 29-YEAR HIGH
</P>
<P>
   Consumer confidence in the economy rose in June to a 29-year
high, as Americans remained optimistic that the strong labor market
and healthy economic growth will continue.
</P>
<P>
   FIRST BOSTON HIRES TECHNOLOGY TEAM
</P>
<P>
   Credit Suisse First Boston has hired the leaders of Deutsche
Bank's global high-technology banking business in an effort to
build its franchise in the fast-growing area of investment banking
for computer and software companies.
</P>
<P>
   YIELD ON TREASURY BOND DECLINES
</P>
<P>
   The yield on the 30-year Treasury bond fell to 5.62 percent from
5.64 percent. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
