<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 22:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4788 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRAVES-MAIN01-COX     06-30 0442
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAVES-MAIN01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Galarraga's back strong with 2 HRs
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ He grinned as he crossed himself before
taking his first batting practice in a week. He toyed with using a
heavier bat, to lessen the stress of his swing. He fretted about
Tropicana Field's artificial turf and the strain on his lower back.
</P>
<P>
   Who's zoomin' who, Andres Galarraga?
</P>
<P>
   The Braves rolled over Tampa Bay 7-2, as Galarraga, in his first
game in six days because of back trouble, homered with his first
two swings of the night, giving him 27 and his fifth double-homer
game of the year. Though he was subsequently knocked out of the
game in the seventh on a Rick White fastball to the left wrist, he
is expected to be back in the lineup tonight.
</P>
<P>
   Denny Neagle snapped out of a 1-5 spin to improve to 9-6,
allowing five hits while striking out five in six innings. Tampa
Bay's Tony Saunders, 3-0 against Atlanta last year when he pitched
for the Florida Marlins, yielded just four hits but finally fell to
the Braves in his fifth career start against them.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta scored four times and took a 7-2 lead in the seventh,
which Andruw Jones began with his sixth triple. Danny Bautista,
starting in left field against the left-handed Saunders, had looked
bad in two strikeouts but broke out of a 1-for-22 slump with an RBI
single.
</P>
<P>
   That chased Saunders, who allowed just four hits. Reliever
Esteban Yan, who inherited two runners, served up a 1-2 double to
pinch-hitter Keith Lockhart. Eddie Perez scored easily for a 5-2
lead but Bautista ill-advisedly tried for home and was easily
thrown out on Miguel Cairo's relay. After a walk by Walt Weiss and
Gerald Williams' infield single, Scott Aldred was brought in to
face Chipper Jones, who ripped a single through the left side for
two RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves were burned in the fifth by a double steal, resulting
in the first steal of home in Tampa Bay history. Neagle retired the
first two men he faced that inning, but Randy Winn and Miguel Cairo
put together consecutive singles to bring up Bobby Smith with men
on first and third.
</P>
<P>
   On a 1-2 pitch, Cairo, who had stolen four bases in nine tries,
took off from first base and catcher Javy Lopez threw to second,
just as Winn broke for home. Lopez's threw bounced, Winn scored
without a play at the plate and Tampa Bay cut the lead to 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   Galarraga's second homer came with the bases empty in the
fourth, giving Atlanta a 3-1 lead, and it was one of the three
longest balls yet hit at the Trop.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
