<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CORRECTIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR WEDNESDAY, JULY 1
</HEADLINE>
  Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Wednesday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-KOSOVO-NYT (moved on Monday, June 29)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on moved on Monday,
June 29, about a Serbian assault against rebels in Kosovo Province
misstated the assignment of an American Ambassador, Christopher
Hill. He is the envoy to Macedonia, not Montenegro. (There is no
American ambassador to Montenegro, a part of Yugoslavia.)
</P>
<P>
   BC-USNEWS-FALLOWS-NYT (moved on Monday, June 29)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on moved on Monday,
June 29, about the dismissal of James Fallows as editor of U.S.
News &AMP; World Report misspelled the given name of a columnist whom
Mr. Fallows removed earlier. He is Steven V. Roberts, not Stephen.
</P>
<P>
   BC-REPUBS-GAYS-NYT (moved on Monday, June 29)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on moved on Monday,
June 29, about the possible backlash from anti-gay remarks by
Senator Trent Lott and other Republicans referred incorrectly in
some copies to the branch of the armed services that discharged
First Lieut. Kelly Flinn after she faced charges related to
adultery, in a case that divided Senator Lott from some
conservatives. The lieutenant served in the Air Force, not the
Navy.
</P>
<P>
   BC-SCOTUS-DISCRIM-NYT (moved on Saturday, June 27)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on moved on Saturday,
June 27, about the effect of the Supreme Court's decision to expand
the definition of disabilities misidentified the infertility
organization for which Deborah Wachenheim is director of government
affairs. It is Resolve, not the National Infertility Association.
</P>
<P>
   BC-OBIT-BRINNIN-NYT (moved on Monday, June 29)
</P>
<P>
   The obituary of the poet and biographer John Malcolm Brinnin
sent by the New York Times News Service on Monday, June 29, cited a
survivor erroneously. No immediate family members survive. Mr.
Brinnin's companion, Bill Read, died some 20 years ago; he had
lived with Mr. Brinnin in Boston and Duxbury, Mass., not in Key
West.
</P>
<P>
   The obituary also misstated the name of a university at which
Mr. Brinnin taught. It was Boston University, not the University of
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   BC-ROCKWELL-CHIPS-NYT (moved on Monday, June 29)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, June 29,
about plans by the Rockwell International Corporation to spin off
its semiconductor division referred incorrectly to the size of that
business and misstated the state of the company's overall sales.
Automation equipment, not semiconductors, is Rockwell's biggest
business. It is the automation business, not the company as a
whole, that is experiencing flat sales.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
