<SLUG> BC-BBO-SELIG-ELECTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMISSIONER ELECTION SET 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Unless Bud Selig plans to produce a surprise candidate, the
baseball owners will elect him commissioner at a meeting July 9 in
Chicago. ``At the meeting,'' according to a notice sent to owners
Monday, ``the clubs will be asked to conduct an election to fill
the position of commissioner.'' The notice did not say who the
candidate or candidates will be, but there is really only one, and
he has been the acting commissioner for nearly six years.
</P>
<P>
   Selig has virtually no opposition, meaning he should easily
receive the required three-fourths majority of the 30 clubs. Other
owners have said the two Chicago teams have been opposed, but one
official said Tuesday that it wasn't clear that they would vote
against Selig's election. The San Francisco Giants had been listed
as a possible no, but they have more recently indicated that they
plan to vote for Selig.
</P>
<P>
   Selig had expressed reluctance to take the job, but, urged by a
growing number of owners, decided several weeks ago to accept it,
some of the owners said. He has not acknowledged that decision. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
