<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 22:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4795 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KNICKS-OAKLEY-NYT     06-30 0194
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-OAKLEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OAKLEY-CAMBY DEAL IS FINAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Knicks tied up some loose ends Tuesday before the National
Basketball Association locked out its players at midnight. After
the Toronto waived Charles Oakley's physical, the draft-day deal
that sent Marcus Camby to the Knicks and Oakley to the Raptors
became final.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks also used the last day of interaction with players to
hold a workout for a 6-foot-4-inch point guard from Israel, Oded
Katasch, who may be available as a free agent once a new collective
bargaining agreement goes into effect. Until the lockout ends,
teams have to cease their business activities, including free-agent
signings.
</P>
<P>
   Katasch, 23, is a star for the Tel Aviv team that plays in the
European league. He may become part of the Knicks' fallback plan if
they cannot trade for Milwaukee's Terrell Brandon.
</P>
<P>
   Oakley never made it to Toronto for his physical. He flew to
Atlanta because of a family emergency, Raptors officials said.
After General Manager Glen Grunwald and Coach Butch Carter flew to
Atlanta to meet with Oakley, the team waived the physical. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-98 2224EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
