<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 6/30/98. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) NEW HAVEN, Conn. -- June 30, 1998 -- COMER-EDUC, 6-30 --
Dr. James Comer, a professor of child psychiatry at Yale, visiting
a third-grade classroom in New Haven. Comer says learning in school
is tied to children's level of social, intellectual and cultural
development. (Chris Maynard/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) ATCHINSON, Kan. -- June 30, 1998 -- KANSAS-ELECT, 6-30
-- David Miller, left, former Republican state chairman of Kansas,
has mounted an unexpected primary-election challenge to Gov. Bill
Graves, right, a social moderate. Among Republicans nationally, the
fight is the latest in the party's long and bitter struggle to
define its chief mission: balancing budgets or saving souls. (Jeff
Davis/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) CHICAGO -- June 30, 1998 -- JORDAN-LOOKALIKE, 6-30 --
Who is the Air apparent? Robert Reed, right, talks to Will Morton
in Chicago on Tuesday after the two were among those called back
for a second audition for the role of Michael Jordan in a
television movie. (Todd Buchanan/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEW YORK -- June 30, 1998 -- TOWBOAT-CAPTAIN, 6-30 --
Dan Cavaluzzi is a co-owner of three boats that rescue amateur
sailors. He does not refer to the weekend sailors who get hung up
on sandbars or run out of fuel as jerks or morons. Anyone can make
a mistake, says Capt. Cavaluzzi, who works for TowBoat/U.S., a sort
of AAA for boaters. ``No drinking from May to November,'' he says.
``You never know when you'll get a call.'' (Librado Romero/New York
Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) BOSTON -- June 30, 1998 -- MYTOWN-TOURS-BOS, 7-30 -- In
Backbay Station, Denise Thomas, a co-founder of Multicultural Youth
Tour of What's Now (MYTOWN) starts her tour at the statue of A.
Phillip Randolph. Nearly three years old, the nonprofit group uses
young people to point out lesser-known neighborhood landmarks,
providing tour groups with an understanding of recent local
history. Ms. Thomas and Karilyn Crockett came up with the idea when
they were seniors at Harvard University. (Suzanne Kreiter/Boston
Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. -- June 30, 1998 -- 0ZZY-POPLIFE,
6-30 -- Ozzy Osbourne performing in 1996. Since 1970, when he
fronted Black Sabbath, perhaps the archetypal heavy metal band, his
career has been pronounced finished time and time again. Yet time
and time again he has rebounded. Last year, his Ozzfest package
tour made over $10 million, and the third annual Ozzfest Q which
begins with performances on Friday and features acts like Tool,
Megadeth and Motorhead Q is likely to have another good year. (G.
Paul Burnett/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) BOSTON -- June 30, 1998 -- LINKS-SERVICE-BOS, 6-30 -- The
national convention of The Links Inc. is being held this week in
the Boston. Those attending are, front row from left, Stephanie
Wilson, Beulah Brown and Donna Levy Wray. In back row, from left
are Colette Phillips, Patricia Hardiman Long and Audrey Coleman.
The Links Inc., is a community service group of 10,000 black women
from across the United States, Germany, and the Bahamas. (Dominic
Chavez/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) LONDON -- June 30, 1998 -- BRITAIN-ROYAL-OPERA, 6-30 --
Sir Richard Eyre, the former artistic director of the Royal
National Theater and one of the most respected champions of the
performing arts in Britain, said in a government-sponsored report
Tuesday that to justify its annual $24 million government subsidy
and earn the public's confidence, the Royal Opera House would have
to get itself in order rapidly. He claimed its internal
organization often ``resembles a World War I battlefield.''
(Jonathan Player/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) UNDATED -- June 30, 1998 -- WINE-TALK-B&AMP;W, 6-30 --
Passage to California wine country is made easier with two new
guides. They're both good, even though neither one offers help on
the single most pressing issue facing the Napa County visitor: How
in blazes do you make a left-hand turn coming out of a winery along
Route 29? (Naum Kazhdan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- June 30, 1998 -- NY-DOG-RESTAURANTS-2, 6-30
-- You don't have to be tiny, cute and fluffy to be welcomed at
sidewalk spots in New York, but maybe it helps. Manhattan isn't a
particularly dog-friendly place, but there are a surprising number
of restaurants that welcome dogs Q with bowls of water, biscuits,
special menus, reserved tables and more. (Andrea Mohin/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- June 30, 1998 -- NY-DOG-RESTAURANTS-1, 6-30
-- Dogs have their favorite restaurants, too, and dog-friendly
spots have found that welcoming them is good for business. A recent
scene allows for dogs at the Chelsea Lobster Company. (Andrea
Mohin/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) SONOMA, Calif. -- June 30, 1998 -- SONOMA-WINES-3, 6-30
-- Bob Cannard has unorthodox views on farming, yet his Sonoma
County vegetables are served at top restaurants. ``It's totally not
true that the weeds are taking up nutrients,'' he says. ``Weeds are
the fertilizer. I don't fertilize.'' (Terrence McCarthy/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) SONOMA, Calif. -- June 30, 1998 -- SONOMA-WINES-2, 6-30
-- Ridgely Evers and Colleen McGlynn make DaVero olive oil from
their 4,500 trees. Residents here will say this much about their
neighbor to the west: Napa is better known and has better
restaurants. That said, they wouldn't dream of living there, for
they would have to abandon their magnificent fruits and vegetables,
superb cheeses and foie gras, prize-winning olive oil, succulent
lamb and pristine oysters. (Terrence McCarthy/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) KENWOOD, Calif. -- June 30, 1998 -- SONOMA-WINES-1, 6-30
-- Sonoma County's verdant landscape is home to farms and wineries
like Chateau St. Jean in Kenwood. Residents here will say this much
about their neighbor to the west: Napa is better known and has
better restaurants. That said, they wouldn't dream of living there,
for they would have to give up bragging rights on those Sonoma
pinot noirs and chardonnays Q wines they would put up against
Napa's any day. (Terrence McCarthy/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- June 30, 1998 -- FANCY-FOOD-SHOW, 6-30 --
Chef Alain Rondelli and Brook Carey presenting his cooking sauces
at the Fancy Food Show. Chefs may want to get you into their
restaurants, but now more than ever, they have their eye on your
pantry shelf as well. The chefs, and their product lines, are out
in force at this year's annual trade show at the Jacob K. Javits
Convention Center, ending Sunday afternoon. (Dith Pran/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
