<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-SALE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS GROUP REACHES AGREEMENT TO BUY NETS 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By STEVE POPPER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A group of New Jersey businessmen reached an agreement to buy a
majority interest in the Nets on Tuesday, setting the stage for the
team to attempt a move out of the Meadowlands Sports Complex and to
a proposed site in Newark.
</P>
<P>
   The new ownership group, put together by the real estate
developers Finn Wentworth and Stanley Gale of Florham Park, N.J.,
and including Steven Witkoff, a prominent real estate investor in
New Jersey, and Raymond Chambers, a New Jersey businessman and
philanthropist, will execute an option to pay $150 million for
approximately 65 percent of the team.
</P>
<P>
   A $25 million payment was placed Tuesday. According to a news
release issued by the Nets, several members of the current
seven-man ownership group will be part of the new ownership group.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is business as usual for the New Jersey Nets,'' Wentworth
and Gale said in a statement. ``Our group is extremely pleased with
the progress of the organization under Michael Rowe and his
management team. We have a commitment to keep the team in New
Jersey and continue on the positive course that the team has been
on the last couple of years.''
</P>
<P>
   Rowe, the Nets' president, said in the team's statement: ``The
Nets organization is pleased that our team will remain in New
Jersey. We are grateful to the existing ownership group and our new
owners for making it possible. We are dedicated to continuing the
progress the franchise has made in recent years at bringing an NBA
championship to New Jersey.''
</P>
<P>
   The new ownership group had 60 days to complete the purchase,
with the option expiring Tuesday night. It will forfeit the payment
if the deal does not go through, but Gale and Wentworth said they
expected that a final agreement would be completed soon. The sale
is contingent on approval from the National Basketball Association
board of governors.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, if completed, puts an end to the attempts of two other
groups _ a team from Long Island, led by Charles Wang of Computer
Associates, and a group led by the New York Islanders owner Howard
Milstein _ to buy the Nets. Both groups hoped to bring the team to
New York.
</P>
<P>
   The new ownership has ties to attempts to revitalize Newark. It
hopes to bring the team to a new arena that would be built near the
new Performing Arts Center. The move would hinge on the ability of
the group, helped by the political clout of Gov. Christie Whitman,
to urge the Devils to accompany them from East Rutherford to
Newark.
</P>
<P>
   John McMullen, the Devils' owner, has flirted with the notion of
relocating to Hoboken.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like the owners of the team, I am committed to keeping the
Nets in New Jersey and I couldn't be happier that this group has
purchased the team,'' Whitman said in a statement. ``I look forward
to working with the new owners, and the owners of all New Jersey
sports teams to ensure that New Jersey remains the premier sports
venue in the metropolitan region.''
</P>
<P>
   The Nets' lease at Continental Arena runs through 2030, but it
has windows for the team to opt out in 2000 and 2004. Rowe has said
that the team will choose to escape the lease, whether or not it
moves to a new arena.
</P>
<P>
   According to a state official, Whitman will request proposals
through the New Jersey Sports and Exposition Authority, soliciting
ideas on prospective sites as well as ways of increasing
profitability at the current site. But the official, who asked not
to be named, said that the governor was hesitant to support any
site until she was certain that both teams would occupy the same
arena. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
