<DOCNO> NYT19980630.0441 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 22:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4813 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALA-RUNOFF-COX     06-30 0321
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALA-RUNOFF-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    James wins in Alabama
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Montgomery _ On a sultry election night in Alabama's capital,
incumbent Gov. Fob James, a champion for Christian conservatives,
was declared the winner in the Republican runoff with a
double-digit lead over challenger Winton Blount.
</P>
<P>
   With 78 percent of the precincts reporting, James led Blount 56
percent to 44 percent, picking up 192,818 votes to Blount's
150,766. Blount had hoped for a large Democratic crossover,
especially by black voters. While many black Democrats apparently
turned out in Birmingham, black turnout elsewhere was light.
</P>
<P>
   In the main ballroom of the Embassy Suites, James supporters
dined on sliced roast beef and sipped lemonade as Lynyrd Skynyrd's
``Sweet Home Alabama'' boomed over loudspeakers. Across the street
at the Montgomery Civic Center, the Blount faithful ate chicken
wings and meatballs while a live band played Jimmy Buffet songs. As
they did in other parts of the state, voters in James' hometown of
Lanett were split on Christianity in government and whether the
incumbent governor projects the image of an eccentric man behind
the times.
</P>
<P>
   Kennon Goggans, 74, grew up three blocks from where James was
born. Goggans said he voted for James because of the governor's
``Christian attitude toward government. If a man stands up for his
rights and my rights in the courts, I should support him. We need
God in government.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Sorrell, 51, said he cast the first Republican ballot in
his life for Blount.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trouble with Alabama has been the goobers we elect
governor,'' said Sorrell, a textile worker. ``He (James) comes from
a George Wallace tradition of goobers. Anybody who wants to enforce
Christianity at the bayoneted end of a National Guard gun, that's
ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
