<DOCNO> NYT19980630.0442 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 22:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4817 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-CHINA-NYT &LR;      06-30 0493
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CHINA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: GLIMPSES OF CHANGE IN CHINA 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Wednesday, July 1:
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton's trip to China has given Americans an
extended look at political life in that complex and changing
country. Some of what they have witnessed was predictable,
including the Chinese government's effort to clear outspoken
dissidents from Clinton's path. But a good deal was not, like the
uncensored broadcast in China of Clinton's news conference with
President Jiang Zemin. The signs of unexpected openness may be the
most encouraging development of the Clinton visit.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the change is a temporary relaxation or a harbinger of
greater freedom is not clear. China for the most part remains a
repressive dictatorship. But modest liberalizing changes have been
under way for much of the last year. They seem to reflect the
growing confidence and power of Jiang.
</P>
<P>
   Officially, Jiang has been China's top leader for the past nine
years. But it was only after the death of Deng Xiaoping last year
that he defined his own positions, endorsing accelerated
privatization of industry, banking reform and slightly freer
political debate. Jiang took another step last weekend by debating
some of the most sensitive issues in Chinese politics with Clinton
on live television, including the Tiananmen Square massacre of 1989
and Beijing's policies toward Tibet.
</P>
<P>
   Jiang's words conveyed important nuances to Chinese listeners.
His characterization of Tiananmen as a ``political disturbance''
departed from the official line that it was a
``counter-revolutionary riot.'' He also offered a dialogue, with
conditions, to the Dalai Lama, Tibet's spiritual leader. These
words may be taken as a license to broader public debate on both
subjects.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has also encountered less encouraging attitudes. The
nationalistic tone of questions asked by students at Beijing
University, China's traditional democratic hothouse, was
disheartening. It suggested that heavy government pressure directed
against students and faculty there since the Tiananmen repression
had changed the intellectual climate.
</P>
<P>
   Ordinary Chinese, however, are somewhat freer today to express
political views in private, and freedom can become contagious.
Jiang seems to understand that a society organized around
money-making is harder to regiment than one organized around the
nostrums of Chairman Mao. Despite censorship and other government
restrictions, exposure to global commerce, television and the
Internet are chipping away at the old restraints.
</P>
<P>
   As China continues to modernize its economy, it will face new
pressures from within and without to open up its political system
as well. Clinton has repeatedly used his public appearances on this
trip to point out the connection between economic and political
freedom. Millions of Chinese have been listening attentively. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-98 2234EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980630.0443 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 22:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4818 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  CHINA-CLINTON-MAIN-COX &UR; -     06-30 0961
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CLINTON URGES AMERICAN FIRMS TO HELP CHINA AVOID ENVIRONMENTAL
DISASTER
</HEADLINE>
 CHINA-CLINTON-MAIN-COX   -$1STLEDE  &HT;     EDS: New top and writethru 
 &HT;     By MARCIA KUNSTEL and JOSEPH ALBRIGHT 
 &HT;     c.1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHANGHAI _ President Clinton appealed Wednesday to American
firms here to help China sever an ``iron unbreakable link'' between
economic growth and industrial age energy practices that could lead
to environmental catastrophe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no right as president of the United States to ask China
to slow its economic growth,'' Clinton told the American Chamber of
Commerce in Shanghai. ``I don't have a right to do that.
</P>
<P>
   ``But as a citizen of the world, and as a leader of our country,
I have a responsibility to ask us all to work together for a planet
that our grandchildren can all enjoy living in,'' Clinton said on
Day Seven of his China tour.
</P>
<P>
   In his only major meeting with American business leaders,
Clinton warned China already is besieged with pollution crises.
Every major body of water in China is polluted, the water table is
dropping around the nation, and respiratory illness is the biggest
cause of death.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said Shanghai, the most developed industrial and
financial center of mainland China, can be ``the center of an
energy revolution in China'' with the help of the American
businesses that are important investors and producers here. He said
clean growth can lead to faster growth and less resources spent on
cleaning up the pollution mess later, as well as on taking care of
people who get sick from pollution related disease.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping engaged in China also is essential to the growth of
America's economy, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have after all in the United States just 4 percent of the
world's population, but we produce 20 percent of its wealth,''
Clinton said. ``Clearly, we must do something with the other 96
percent of the people on this small planet, in order to maintain
our standard of living, and our ability to stand up for our values
around the world.''
</P>
<P>
   The presidential visit has not been a stellar success from the
point of view of American business.
</P>
<P>
   The White House bypassed visits to any American factories here,
despite heavy pressure from U.S. firms hoping Clinton would
showcase their operations. Business here is still complicated and
restricted, and few American corporations generate notable profits.
A visit by Clinton might impress shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   Corporate America got several other disappointments from
Clinton's nine-day tour of China.
</P>
<P>
   The White House waffled for weeks before deciding not to include
a business delegation as part of Clinton's official entourage. That
would have given commercial relations a high profile role in
Clinton's trip through five cities.
</P>
<P>
   Nor did Clinton and his administration achieve an agreement on
China's admittance to the World Trade Organization, which business
leaders listed as a number one priority of this summit. As a WTO
member China would have to reduce tariffs and loosen tough controls
over foreign firms doing business here.
</P>
<P>
   General Motors especially appealed hard for Clinton to stop by
its new joint venture factory that will turn out a version of the
Buick Regal here in Shanghai, a daring project that carries the
risk of falling flat for lack of big-car demand. GM was still
hopeful by mid-month, but a major strike in the United States made
a presidential visit a bad publicity risk.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Commerce Secretary William Daley also said at a briefing
Tuesday that no progress had been made on reducing China's trade
deficit, with the American side saying China sells about $50
billion more than it buys from the United States. New figures show
the deficit has jumped by another 13-14 percent in the first five
months of this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is, our exports have not grown anywhere near
the degree that their exports to the United States have,'' Daley
said. And he said no ``concrete steps'' have been taken in the last
five days to shrink the deficit.
</P>
<P>
   Recognizing the concern over the deficit and over the existing
barriers to doing business here, China's official news agency
Xinhua this week put out an article trumpeting the country's
profit-making possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``China remains the largest potential market on earth,'' Xinhua
said, underscoring that some companies have mistakenly viewed China
as ``a big nation but a small market.''
</P>
<P>
   It said the State Statistics Bureau found consumer spending in
China has been growing two to three percentage points more than
gross domestic product since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   China's 10 percent growth has dipped to less than eight percent
this year, but Xinhua predicted an upturn ``that will in turn drive
consumer spending and turn China into the world's largest consumer
goods market.''
</P>
<P>
   This visit did not even generate a huge total of new business.
On Tuesday Americans and Chinese signed $2 billion in deals at the
Great Hall of the People in Beijing, an event that Clinton did not
attend. Xinhua reported another $1.1 billion the previous week.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the deals had been expected for months, and some even
previously announced. So there were few surprise contracts like the
big $6 billion package announced when Chinese President Jiang Zemin
visited the United States last fall.
</P>
<P>
   Among the ``new'' deals was $800 million worth of passenger
planes that China is buying from Boeing. That was part of a deal
for 50 planes announced last fall, though Boeing said a new letter
of intent also had been signed to sell another 10 aircraft worth
$400 million.
</P>
<P>
   Another big contract was General Electric's sale of a $161.7
million integrated steam turbine system to the Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; For use by clients of The New York Times News Service &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-98 2236EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980630.0444 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 22:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4820 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-EXECUTIVE-PRIVIL     06-30 0424
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-EXECUTIVE-PRIVILEGE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE OVERSTRETCHED PRIVILEGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Wednesday, July 1:
</P>
<P>
   The White House bristles at comparisons between its tactics in
the independent counsel investigation of President Clinton and
President Nixon's Watergate strategy. Yet echoes of Nixon's effort
to block access to his tapes were inevitable Monday, as Clinton's
lawyers worked to block testimony by Bruce Lindsey, one of his
closest aides. But there was a striking new element in these
arguments before a federal appeals court in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   As one member of the three-judge panel remarked, this was the
first time a sitting president had invoked lawyer-client privilege
to thwart a grand jury inquiry. Showing a refreshing measure of
independence and professionalism, the Justice Department has
declined to endorse the president's unique assertion that an
absolute privilege protects all his conversations with government
lawyers. So, it can only be hoped, will the court.
</P>
<P>
   The White House dropped its flimsy executive privilege claim
earlier this month in order to help deter the Supreme Court from
granting a special expedited review before adjourning. That
strategy worked. But as the lower court judge, Norma Holloway
Johnson, essentially recognized in her decision, Clinton's claim of
attorney-client privilege for Lindsey is really just an executive
privilege claim in disguise. As such, it is no more supportable in
the face of the showing of need by the independent counsel, Kenneth
Starr, in the Monica Lewinsky investigation.
</P>
<P>
   At the hearing the White House lawyer, W. Neil Eggleston,
introduced a provocative new thought. Citing the constitutional
separation of powers, he contended that since Starr had raised the
possibility of an impeachment proceeding, the president had every
right to rely on government layers to defend himself. To be sure,
any investigation of a sitting president is difficult legal ground.
But what the White House is proposing is an untenable expansion of
presidential power.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyer-client privilege is a hallowed principle, as the Supreme
Court just reaffirmed with its ruling last week denying Starr
access to notes taken by the private lawyer for Vincent Foster, the
White House counsel who committed suicide. But it should not be
stretched into a rule that would justify a refusal by every
presidential aide who happens to hold a law degree to cooperate
with an independent counsel inquiry. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-98 2238EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980630.0445 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 22:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4822 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSINESS-TRAVEL-NYT &LR;      06-30 0695
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSINESS-TRAVEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y.) 
BUSINESS TRAVEL: RUNWAY REPAIRS AT WESTCHESTER AIRPORT; SLEEPER
SEATS; HOTEL UPDATE; BYE-BYE BOARDING PASS
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Also moved in ``t'' category) 
(af) 
 By JANE L. LEVERE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Runway repairs at Westchester County Airport in White
Plains are scheduled to be completed early next month, bringing an
end to disruptions that began for travelers in May.
</P>
<P>
   The airport, owned and operated by the county, has been
repairing and upgrading its main runway since May 9. As a result,
it was closed for most service from May 9 through May 18 and a good
part of every weekend subsequently.
</P>
<P>
   The airport, which handles 82 scheduled flights each weekday and
65 scheduled flights each weekend, notified carriers last summer
that it would be making these repairs. The airlines _ which include
AMR's American Airlines, Northwest Airlines, UAL's United Airlines,
and U S Airways and several of its commuter lines _ have rerouted
their passengers to other flights at other airports, usually La
Guardia.
</P>
<P>
   Some airlines said they had to cancel flights at the airport
with little notice, because of repairs that were delayed, in part,
because of heavy rains. According to Marta Laughlin, a spokeswoman
for Northwest, the airline canceled 100 flights in advance, and
between 10 and 20 at the last minute.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're hopeful we will be able to work out a way to recoup our
lost revenues, but we're not overly optimistic,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   David Castelveter, a spokesman for U S Airways, said the repair
schedule had created ``some inconveniences, but we overcame the
obstacles by putting passengers into other airports.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Peter Scherrer, assistant airport manager, the
airport will be closed from 8 a.m. to 8 p.m. on Saturdays and
Sundays during the weekends of July 25 and Aug. 1, after which all
repair work will be completed and regular operations resumed. He
also said the shutdowns were necessary because the airport had only
one main runway. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Following the lead of British Airways, American Airlines is
installing new sleeper seats in the first-class cabins of its new
Boeing 777 aircraft, officials of the airline said last week. Each
seat, which fully reclines into a bed, will feature a reading
light, a power outlet, telephone, interactive entertainment system
and a privacy divider with storage space.
</P>
<P>
   The airline will use the 19 777s it has ordered for long-haul
service like trans-Pacific flights; it plans to take delivery of
the planes in January.
</P>
<P>
   American will also install new business-class seats in the 777s,
as well as in its current 767 fleet.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, over the next 18 months, American plans to open new
service centers for its ``platinum'' level frequent fliers at
airports in Miami and Los Angeles, and new first-class lounges at
airports in Miami, Chicago, Boston and Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   It is also building new arrival lounges at airports in Miami,
New York (Kennedy International Airport), London (Heathrow Airport)
and Dallas, and adding new showers to existing lounges in Los
Angeles; Newark; San Jose, Calif., and Raleigh-Durham, N.C. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thistle Hotels, which owns and operates some 90 hotels in
Britain, including 24 in London, is offering a ``pound for dollar''
rate from July 13 to Aug. 31. Rates that are normally quoted in
pounds will be available in dollars, thus creating a 40 percent
discount.
</P>
<P>
   A one-night stay, for example, at the Selfridge in London will
be $225, compared with the regular rate of 225 pounds ($374).
Bookings must be made two weeks in advance; a minimum stay of two
nights is required.
</P>
<P>
   Vietnam's Hotel Sofitel Metropole Hanoi has a special business
traveler's package that includes a buffet breakfast, a fruit
basket, late check-out, free laundry and pressing, discounted dry
cleaning and free local phone calls. Rates, good through Dec. 31,
are $229 a night single occupancy and $259 double occupancy, not
including service or tax. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As of next Tuesday, U S Airways will no longer issue advance
boarding passes to its passengers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-98 2239EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980630.0446 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 22:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4823 &Cx1f; taf-z
