</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-BEACHES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: NEW YORK'S UNGUARDED BEACHES 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Wednesday, July 1:
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles County does not rely on the mystique of its fabled
beaches to attract summer lifeguards. It scours swim teams in high
schools and colleges on the West Coast, casting its net as far east
as Arizona. New York City, once again in the throes of a lifeguard
shortage, could take a page from California's book. Four miles of
city beach are now closed. Some stretches are shut for
environmental reasons, but two and a half miles are closed because
there are not enough guards. That is unacceptable in a crowded
metropolis, where summer heat and humidity can reach triple digits.
</P>
<P>
   New York needs 600 lifeguards to cover 14 miles of beaches. As
the holiday weekend approaches, it is 70 lifeguards short. It needs
600 more for 60-plus public pools. By the second week of July, the
Parks Department hopes to have 1,000 lifeguards altogether _ an
improvement over last summer, when it could find only 870
lifeguards and had to shut down six miles of beach between Memorial
Day and Labor Day.
</P>
<P>
   Ocean lifeguards must meet rigorous standards _ they must swim
440 yards in 6 minutes 40 seconds, for example. The pay is modest
but hardly a deterrent. Novice lifeguards earn about $8.60 an hour,
experienced guards average more than $14. That is slightly below
California's pay scales, but as Parks Commissioner Henry Stern
jokingly observed in a recent interview with a California
newspaper, ``the surf may not be as good, but the ground is solid
and doesn't shake.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the department's recruiting efforts, which consist
largely of want ads, web site notices and memos to school
officials, should be vigorously expanded to reach competitive
swimmers at colleges up and down the East Coast. California has
devoured NCAA data for promising candidates, with marked success.
</P>
<P>
   No one is asking the department to do the impossible. It cannot
easily halt erosion, which closes some beaches, and it cannot
prevent storms. But it can find lifeguards. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-98 2244EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
