<DOCNO> NYT19980630.0449 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-30 22:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4828 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOWBOAT-CAPTAIN-ART-N     06-30 0911
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOWBOAT-CAPTAIN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELYING THE LEGEND OF THE CRUSTY OLD SALT 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV.: a photo for use with this story is being sent to NYT
photo clients. Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by
calling 212 556-4204.)  
 (HLW)  
 By JOYCE WADLER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Tempting as it may seem, Dan Cavaluzzi, a towboat
captain, does not refer to the weekend sailors who get hung up on
sandbars or run out of fuel as jerks, morons, or any of the other
terms one may use for people who mess up because of their own
incompetence.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone can make a mistake, says Cavaluzzi, who works for
TowBoat/U.S., a sort of AAA for boaters. It is not his job to be
``judgmental.'' What's the point of asking why an $85,000, 35-foot
cabin cruiser ended up roosting on pilings in the Hudson River,
making, when the tide is out, for a remarkable photo that is one of
the first things the captain shows to a visitor?
</P>
<P>
   The job of a towboat captain, as Cavaluzzi sees it, is to allay
distress, emotional and mechanical; to ``diffuse the tension and
anxiety''; to deal with ``the ego problem.'' Which is not to say
certain types do not try his patience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get a call, there are four things I ask,'' Cavaluzzi says,
on the deck of his 25-foot Privateer off City Island, his home
base. `` `Is everyone on board in good health? Are you taking on
water? Are there adequate life jackets?' Then _ if it's not an
emergency situation and they don't have insurance: `This is
commercial marine assistance. You have to be billed for this
service.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The waves lap gently against the boats of the weekend sailors;
the sky is blue and life is good _ though not as good as it was
years ago, when the Coast Guard would tow for nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes they start screaming, `That's a rip-off!' ''
Cavaluzzi says. ``I always say, `Sir, if you like, I can call the
Coast Guard.' They assume the Coast Guard is going to drop out of
the sky in three minutes. Meanwhile, the boat is still pounding on
the rocks.''
</P>
<P>
   Smiling broadly, the captain does an eerie imitation of a prow
grinding against rock.
</P>
<P>
   ``Caaaa-runk, caaaa-runk!'' he growls. ``Then the wife or
girlfriend starts hollering. A couple more slams on the rock
settles it.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking for a hard-drinking, hard-living old salt who lives on
his weathered boat accompanied by a one-eared cat and a can opener
so rusted you could contract tetanus just looking at it? Go to a
movie. Cavaluzzi, except for his pleasure in the misfortunes of
obnoxious sailors, has the aspect of a seafaring Boy Scout.
</P>
<P>
   A cleaning lady comes in every Monday to tidy up the boat. If
you remark, on a perfect Sunday as sailboats skim Long Island
Sound, that all one needs is a martini, Cavaluzzi quickly invokes
duty.
</P>
<P>
   ``No drinking from May to November,'' he says. ``You never know
when you'll get a call.''
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, he is a stickler for proper names.
</P>
<P>
   He seems to have a lot of ropes, a visitor notes.
</P>
<P>
   ``On board, we call them lines,'' Cavaluzzi says.
</P>
<P>
   Do so many boaters get into trouble because they don't read
their maps?
</P>
<P>
   ``We call them charts,'' Cavaluzzi says.
</P>
<P>
   A short history of aid at sea: In June 1983, the Coast Guard
began referring nonemergency calls to private towing operators.
TowBoat/U.S., a division of the Boat Owners Association of America,
one of the major private companies, provides unlimited towing for
an annual fee of $85.
</P>
<P>
   A short history of Cavaluzzi: Born Dec. 4, 1955, in the Bronx,
near Pelham Bay _ ``three blocks from the water'' _ to a New York
City bus driver who would put four sons through college. Graduated
from Bronx Community College with a degree in plastic engineering
and today, married and with a young son, runs a plastics supply
business from his home because, he says, you can't make a living in
the towing business. Was a volunteer with the Coast Guard
Auxiliary. Now is a co-owner of three boats that patrol the
approximately 30 miles of waterway from the Statue of Liberty to
Rye Beach, in Westchester County.
</P>
<P>
   Try to get stories from Cavaluzzi about the early days of
``commercial marine assistance,'' when he was a private towing
operator and it was said to be a ferociously competitive game, and
you'll get little more than a smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's just say you age, you mature,'' Cavaluzzi says.
</P>
<P>
   Regarding his rescues, he is more forthcoming.
</P>
<P>
   He says that many of the devil-may-care Jet Skiers one sees
actually carry both insurance and cell phones and that he fished
two young Jet Skiers out of Eastchester Bay this past weekend after
their panicked father _ still aboard the Jet Ski _ placed a call.
He says that even if someone cannot afford to pay, ``you have a
moral obligation'' to tow the boat to the nearest port. He says,
referring to ``the ego problem,'' that sailboat owners tend to be
more difficult than power boat operators: they feel they know more
about the sea than anyone.
</P>
<P>
   A story comes to mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``A 65-foot sailboat,'' Cavaluzzi says, ``Hung up on rocks near
the lighthouse at Execution Point. I hollered, `You're aground.'
They didn't believe me. I said, `Look at the lighthouse! It's not
moving!' ''
</P>
<P>
   What happened?
</P>
<P>
   Cavaluzzi is smiling again.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just sipped another cocktail,'' he says. ``And we came
back later with another boat and towed 'em. When a sailboat's on
the rocks I have to tip 'em over about 45 degrees. And the wife is
screaming ... .''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-98 2246EDT &QL; 
