<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-FREE-AGENCY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FREE AGENCY OPENS WITH A STRONG CROP 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A general manager with a generous checkbook and several holes on
his roster could rapidly improve his team when the free-agent
signing season begins Wednesday. He could acquire goalie Mike
Richter, center Doug Gilmour, center Ron Francis, right wing Brett
Hull, defenseman Steve Duchesne and defenseman Uwe Krupp.
</P>
<P>
   These players might cost $25 million or more a season. All would
want multiyear contracts, possibly with no-trade clauses. But it
could be done with no compensation because all are over the age of
31. They are among the Group 3 free agents.
</P>
<P>
   Hull's 10-year career in St. Louis ended Tuesday when General
Manager Larry Pleau told Hull the club would not re-sign him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone in our organization believes a change will be good
for the Blues, as well as Brett,'' Pleau said.
</P>
<P>
   Hull said: ``I'm disappointed that the Blues wouldn't agree to a
no-trade clause. I wanted to know that I'd finish my career in St.
Louis.''
</P>
<P>
   There has been much recent speculation that he may go to
Chicago, where his father, Bobby Hull, was once known as the Golden
Jet. Should the Blackhawks sign Hull, it is possible that the No. 9
worn by his father will come out of retirement and be worn by the
son.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers are not expected to bid for Hull. But they may be
interested in Scott Fraser, a 26-year-old Edmonton Oiler right wing
who is an unrestricted free agent in the Group 6 category. He
scored 12 goals in 29 games last season.
</P>
<P>
   For the Rangers, the key question involves Richter, who earned
$3.9 million last season. His price on the market is expected to be
between $5 million and $7 million a season on a multiyear contract.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation throughout last season was that Richter would be
wooed by either Vancouver or Philadelphia. The Canucks have Coach
Mike Keenan and captain Mark Messier, who were with Richter in New
York for the Stanley Cup championship of 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The Flyers are also a logical fit because Richter is from that
area and the team has not solved its chronic goalie problem.
Richter was chosen last week in the expansion draft by the new
Nashville team, but the Predators do not intend to sign him. They
merely hold rights to compensation for him after he signs with
another team.
</P>
<P>
   When he does, the Nashville team will get an at-large choice in
next summer's entry draft. It will come from no specific team but
will be added to the pool of players available, likely in the
second round.
</P>
<P>
   Richter's availability occurs at a time that might not be ideal
for his bargaining leverage. He is coming off a mediocre season
into a market in which unrestricted goalies are plentiful. Among
the best-known are Curtis Joseph of Edmonton, John Vanbiesbrouck of
Florida and Sean Burke of Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Should Richter leave the Rangers, they may be tempted to take
one of the others who would work for less money than Richter is
worth. With rebuilding ahead of them, the Rangers might not care to
pay a premium price for a goalie while filling in at so many other
positions.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers, seeking mobility on defense, are likely to talk
with Krupp, a former Islander who scored the overtime goal for
Colorado that clinched the fourth and final game of the Stanley Cup
finals against Florida in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   If the general manager wished to take a more difficult path to
get a younger star, he could select one of the following Group 2
free agents: defenseman Aleksei Zhitnik of Buffalo, defenseman
Sandis Ozolinsh of Colorado, left wing Tomas Holmstrom of Detroit,
center Doug Weight of Edmonton, defenseman Rob Blake of Los
Angeles, center Saku Koivu of Montreal, defenseman Scott
Niedermayer of the Devils, right wing Zigmund Palffy of the
Islanders, left wing Rod Brind'Amour of Philadelphia, right wing
Owen Nolan of San Jose, center Pierre Turgeon of St. Louis,
defenseman Bryan McCabe of Vancouver or center Andrei Nikolishin of
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   These free agents' former teams have a right to either match
their offer sheets and keep them or lose them and get, as
compensation, up to five first-round draft choices. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
