<SLUG> BC-BANK-EXECS-DEFECT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THREE LEAVE ONE BIG BANK FOR ANOTHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By PETER TRUELL    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a high-stakes game of musical chairs, Credit Suisse First
Boston has hired the leaders of Deutsche Bank's global
high-technology banking business.
</P>
<P>
   The new hires, which are expected to be announced Wednesday, are
an effort by Credit Suisse to build up its own franchise quickly in
the fast-growing area of investment banking for computer and
software companies.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Quattrone, the chief executive of Deutsche Bank
securities' technology group, Bill Brady, its head of corporate
finance, and George Boutros, the group's head of mergers and
acquisitions, told Deutsche that they were leaving Tuesday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been informed of their intention to leave the firm,''
said Macy Egerton, a spokeswoman for Deutsche in New York. She said
that neither she nor her firm had any further comment on the
defections.
</P>
<P>
   The departures, while a potential coup for Credit Suisse, leave
Deutsche Bank's huge investments of recent years in high-technology
banking temporarily without leadership. All three men had built
their careers together at Morgan Stanley &AMP; Co., and had left that
firm with great fanfare in 1996 to head Deutsche's huge effort in
this area of investment banking from their offices in Menlo Park,
Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Bank, the German banking behemoth, had paid millions of
dollars to lure Quattrone and his colleagues and had even granted
them a share of the revenues they generated. The group had scored
some successes, notably the initial public offering for Amazon.com
and several other young Internet companies, but rivals had
repeatedly questioned whether Deutsche was making money on its
investment.
</P>
<P>
   The defections put a further dent in Deutsche's plans to build a
significant worldwide investment banking unit, which would also
service American high-technology companies.
</P>
<P>
   Credit Suisse, which already owns a minority stake in Volpe
Welty, a small high-technology investment bank in California, has
made building up its high-technology banking business a strategic
priority. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-30-98 2252EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
