</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-SOSA-HOMERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOSA SHOWS PATIENCE AT THE PLATE IN HIS FINEST SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By IRA BERKOW    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Once upon a time, Sammy Sosa was the kind of
mad-hatter batter who swung so violently and so indiscriminately
that, it was said, he would attack even a white paper cup if it
came floating toward home plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember pitching against him when I was with the Mets,''
said Mark Clark, now a teammate of Sosa's on the Cubs, ``and you
could bounce a ball in front of the plate, and he'd swing at it.
He'd go for a high, bad slider. You knew he was going to be up
there hacking. You knew he could hurt you, but you felt you could
handle him in tight situations. Not anymore. He's been
incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   Incredible may be an understatement, in a sports world of
galloping hyperbole. Tuesday evening at leafy Wrigley Field, Sosa
concluded the most remarkable home run-hitting month in the history
of baseball. Entering the Cubs' game against Arizona, he had
slugged 19 homers _ breaking the one-month record held by Rudy
York, who hit 18 homers in August 1937 for the Tigers. If Sosa
happened to belt homers as he has in June for each of the six
months of a season, he would wind up with 114 for the season.
</P>
<P>
   Turns out that not even the compactly, powerfully built,
easygoing right fielder for the Cubs is on that pace. More
modestly, he is on track to break the one-season home run record of
61, set by Roger Maris in 1961. At month's end, about the halfway
point of the 1998 season, Sosa has stroked 32 homers, which put him
even with the Seattle Mariners' Ken Griffey Jr. and four behind the
St. Louis Cardinals' masher, Mark McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm no Mark McGwire,'' Sosa said Tuesday. ``He's the man. If
anyone's going to break Roger Maris' record, it's going to be him.
Me, I'm just another kid on the block having a pretty good
season.''
</P>
<P>
   He has been more than just another kid on the block for several
years now, although he has not been as appreciated or as generally
applauded as he is this season. He has not only slugged homers like
crazy, but is also hitting for average _ his .328 is 71 points
higher than his 10-year major league career average _ and has
knocked in 78 runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing people forget when they look at what Sammy has done
this year,'' Cubs Manager Jim Riggleman said, ``is that he's put up
great numbers for a bunch of years. Forty homers, 36 homers twice,
a hundred or more RBIs for three straight seasons. The other fact
is that he has also matured as a ballplayer, especially at the
plate. He has become more patient, waiting for the pitcher to get
the ball in the strike zone.''
</P>
<P>
   The patience and the maturity may be seen in the way the
right-handed-hitting Sosa will go to other fields on pitches that
in the past he would try to pull. ``In Kansas City last weekend,''
Riggleman said, ``he got two big hits for us, both to right field,
and drove in key runs.''
</P>
<P>
   Sosa has even sprayed his soaring home runs around, hitting 13
to left, 10 to center and nine to right.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa is 29, and didn't begin playing organized baseball until he
was 14, in San Pedro de Macoris, the town in the Dominican Republic
that has sent an extraordinary number of players to the majors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing how far he's come when you consider where he came
from,'' said Omar Minaya, the Mets' assistant general manager, who
was a scout for the Texas Rangers in 1985 when he signed Sosa for
$3,500. ``I remember him coming from a poverty-stricken background,
where he lived in a two-room house with his widowed mother and four
brothers and two sisters.''
</P>
<P>
   Sosa remembers selling oranges for 10 cents apiece and shining
shoes for 25 cents to help the finances of his family. Last year,
he signed a four-year contract with the Cubs for $42 million. ``I
think about when I had very little, when I couldn't buy myself a
gift, or my family a gift,'' he said. ``That's changed.''
</P>
<P>
   He has been generous with his money, going to hospitals in the
United States and Latin America, and returning to the Dominican
Republic to spread gifts to the needy and the ailing, as well as
investing in his home country, having developed a mall in hopes of
creating jobs and opportunities beyond baseball. He has also been
generous with himself and his immediate family _ his wife, Sonia,
and their four children, and his mother and brothers and sisters.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa has done it in a circuitous fashion. He came up with the
Rangers, was traded to the Chicago White Sox, hit as low as .203
for them and found himself in the minors before being traded to the
Cubs in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa says that the secret of his success this season has to do,
yes, with more patience, but also with a far better ball club than
he had been accustomed to.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hitting third now with Henry Rodriguez and Mark Grace
behind me,'' he said, ``so the pitchers have to come in with good
pitches to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Sosa has become a huge sports presence in Chicago, a place
dominated by another rather colossal individual. ``The president of
my country, Leonel Fernandez, asked if I could get Mike Jordan to
visit the Dominican,'' Sosa said. ``I agreed to try. I went to the
United Center, where the Bulls were practicing, and I think he will
come. We would play golf. The only problem is, I don't play golf. I
practiced once, but I hit everything a foul ball, and I quit.''
</P>
<P>
   He has had much better luck at hitting fair balls out of Wrigley
Field, among numerous other ball yards in the Western Hemisphere. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
