A4967 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-METRO-CARDS-NYT &LR;      06-30 0559
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-METRO-CARDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IGNORING ORDERS, MERCHANTS SELL NEW METROCARDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By JAYSON BLAIR    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Officially, the new unlimited-ride Metrocards do not
go on sale until Saturday. But some merchants who will be official
vendors of the new cards are ignoring orders not to sell them
before the start of the program and are selling them to subway
riders who fear that the new cards will be in short supply.
</P>
<P>
   Suggesting high interest in the new fare program, the merchants
say riders are trying to beat the rush for the new cards and are
worried that stores will quickly run out once the program begins.
Of 60 dealers questioned in the last two days, 14 said they were
already selling the cards.
</P>
<P>
   But the New York City Transit executive in charge of Metrocards,
Christopher Boylan, said there was no reason to be concerned that
the 3,200 vendors outside subway stations would be running out of
the new Metrocards.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have more than enough to satisfy the needs of our customers
and we can fill the needs of an out-of-station provider
overnight,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Boylan said the merchants were notified that they were not to
sell the unlimited-ride cards until July 4. But he said the
merchants would not be punished for jumping the gun. He also said
buyers would find notification of the July 4 start date on the
cards' wrappers.
</P>
<P>
   New York City Transit officials said they were concerned about
confusion that might result from the early sales. A customer could
buy a weekly or monthly pass, thinking it could be used
immediately, and it would not be usable until Saturday, officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   If someone attempts to use one of the new cards before Saturday,
a message will appear on the turnstile monitor that reads ``valid
only after 07/03/98.''
</P>
<P>
   Gene Russianoff, a staff lawyer for the Straphangers Campaign, a
rider advocacy group, said he would not fault New York City Transit
for any confusion over the new cards. ``They had only six months to
put this program together, and it is a miracle that it looks like
it is going to work,'' Russianoff said.
</P>
<P>
   The new cards, which cannot be used more than once in 18 minutes
at the same entrance to discourage use by nonpaying riders, are
being unveiled Saturday to coincide with the one-year anniversary
of a program that allowed free subway-to-bus transfers with a
Metrocard, New York City Transit officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Boylan, who told the agency's finance committee last week that
nearly 72 percent of the subway system's riders were using
Metrocards, said he expected the new weekly cards would increase
sales immediately and the monthly cards would do the same once
people return to more regular work schedules in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Officials plan to introduce a one-day unlimited-ride Metrocard
for $4 in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   The unlimited-ride passes, which were announced by Gov. George
Pataki in December and will cost $17 a week and $63 a month, are
expected to attract 100 million additional rides a year, a
ridership increase of about 6 percent from last year.
</P>
<P>
   New York City Transit officials said a list of vendors selling
the cards in New York City could be found at the agency's World
Wide Web site (www.mtahq.org/mtacc/demo/zipmaps.htm).
</P>
<P>
   The card is also being sold in Nassau and Westchester Counties,
officials said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
