A4954 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HAYES-SHAFT-COX     06-30 0227
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAYES-SHAFT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Chef, can you dig it? Judge restores old debt
 &HT;    By Henry Farber
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ His career revived by a shift from ``Shaft'' to
``Chef,'' actor and soul singer Isaac Hayes has been ordered by a
Cobb County, Ga. judge to repay a decade-old $88,868 business loan
_ plus almst $100,000 in interest.
</P>
<P>
   Area businesswoman Doris Wall originally obtained a court order
in 1989 demanding that Hayes pay the money.
</P>
<P>
   But her attorney, Lynwood Maddox Sr., said that for much of the
'90s, Wall didn't pursue the money, believing Hayes didn't have the
means to pay.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, she knows he's making a comeback or is reviving his
career or whatever,'' Maddox said.
</P>
<P>
   Once known primarily for his 1971 Oscar-winning theme from
``Shaft,'' Hayes has enjoyed a career boost via TV as the voice
behind the cartoon character Chef, a school cafeteria worker, on
the Comedy Central cartoon ``South Park.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, State Court Judge Robert McDuff revived the 1989
order. With interest, Hayes must pay about $188,130, Maddox said.
</P>
<P>
   The loan occurred sometime in the late 1980s, according to
Maddox, who said he didn't know what the money was for. Hayes lived
in metro Atlanta from 1979 to 1992. He lives in New York now.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
