<HEADER>
A4973 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-CHILDRENS-CLINICS-     06-30 0709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CHILDRENS-CLINICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITICS FEAR SHIFT IN CONTROL OF CHILD CLINICS 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By IAN FISHER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Giuliani administration Tuesday will put into
place the final pieces of its plan to reorganize the city's network
of 39 child health-care clinics, and advocates for the poor are
worried that it will harm the quality of services at clinics that
serve the city's poorest children.
</P>
<P>
   At first glance, the change appears to be merely a bureaucratic
pen stroke. Control over the clinics, for years administered apart
from the city's sprawling public health system, will be moved from
the main office of the Health and Hospitals Corp. to hospitals and
clinics in neighborhoods around the city. Giuliani officials say
there will be no changes in the clinics themselves.
</P>
<P>
   But the advocates contend that the shift represents a subtle
step toward dismantling the child clinics and the distinct role
they have had for the last 90 years as small-scale providers of
health care for children only. Ultimately, the advocates fear, the
shift could signal an end to the idea that the clinics are somehow
special, and then future budget cuts could force the city into
folding them into the rest of the public health system.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, the advocates released a survey showing that a large
majority of parents whose children are treated at the clinics are
satisfied with their services. They said that level of satisfaction
argues against making major changes _ and particularly beginning to
charge fees _ that might make parents less likely to take their
children to the clinics for medical care.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it ain't broke, don't fix it,'' said Judy Wessler, policy
coordinator for the Commission on the Public's Health System and a
frequent critic of the Giuliani administration on health issues.
``They work very well.''
</P>
<P>
   But Dr. Van Dunn, a senior vice president of the city's Health
and Hospitals Corp., agreed, saying the clinics do work well. He
said the city has no plans to close or merge them, or begin
charging fees. Aside from shifting the responsibility from the
health agency's main office to the public hospitals near the
clinics, he said, parents would see no changes in the clinics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can understand their concerns,'' Dunn said. ``They are
worried that when you integrate that things are going to get
lost.''
</P>
<P>
   He said, however, that the city's top health officials are
``committed to these clinics,'' which were first established in
1908 to give milk and water to poor immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   ``They see them as a vital source of health care to the
community,'' Dunn said, ``and we would not, I repeat not,
compromise the delivery of care to children.''
</P>
<P>
   The survey was the latest in a barrage of assaults on the city's
efforts since 1994 to change the way the clinics are administered.
Based on interviews with 142 parents, the report found that 95
percent of them were satisfied with the services and 82 percent
said they could get immediate appointments for their children.
</P>
<P>
   For many years the clinics were under the city's Department of
Health, in an arrangement that the advocates said protected them as
distinct entities for children. Nearly half of the clinics are in
public housing projects, apart from other public hospitals or
primary care clinics.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, the child clinics were transferred to the Health
and Hospitals Corp., which runs the public hospital system, and
advocates worried that they would be lost in its huge bureaucracy.
</P>
<P>
   Concern grew last fall when the agency decided to decentralize
control over the clinics, making them the responsibility of the
eight divisions of public hospitals and clinics (the North Bronx
network, for example, encompasses Jacobi Medical Center, North
Central Bronx Hospitals and several clinics).
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Katherine Lobach, the former city official who oversaw the
child health clinics for 11 years, said she worried that
decentralization would erode what she said had been a hallmark of
the clinic: one office that oversaw the quality of the entire
program and set consistent medical standards for all of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will no longer be any central authority to maintain the
standards,'' Dr. Lobach said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
