<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICAL BRIEFS 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By B. DRUMMOND AYRES Jr.    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLOUDS NEVER LIFT FOR TEXAS UNDERDOG
</P>
<P>
   Just when Garry Mauro thought things could not get any worse in
his effort to unseat Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, things got
worse.
</P>
<P>
   For months the polls have had Mauro, a Democrat and the state
land commissioner, trailing the popular Republican governor, most
recently by better than 50 points. How could it get any worse?
</P>
<P>
   Well ...
</P>
<P>
   First came the bumper stickers, proclaiming ``Vote Texan:
Bush/Sharp.''
</P>
<P>
   That would be John Sharp. He is a Democrat, running for
lieutenant governor. He says he does not have any problem with the
sticker pairing.
</P>
<P>
   Next came the incumbent lieutenant governor, Bob Bullock. He is
the state's highest-ranking elected Democrat. He is not seeking
re-election _ but he is seeking to re-elect Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Then House Speaker Pete Laney, another top Democrat, along with
Paul Hobby, the Democratic candidate for comptroller, said they
would not be getting involved in the governor's race, followed by
state Rep. Robert Junell, a Democrat who is chairman of the House
Appropriations Committee, and a hundred or so Democratic sheriffs
and other county officials, who said they would be getting involved
in the race _ on Bush's side.
</P>
<P>
   Finally came the most embarrassing poll of all, the one released
just a few days ago that found that roughly 40 percent of all
Democratic voters plan to vote for Bush, whereas just 2 percent of
Republican voters intend to support Mauro.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm doing just fine,'' Mauro insists, noting that the
country's top Democrats, President Clinton and Vice President Al
Gore, have both spoken out for him and have helped him raise
campaign money.
</P>
<P>
   But the way many political pros in Texas see it, Mauro is in the
worst of political places. They say he is faring so badly
politically that he threatens to drag down the entire Democratic
ticket this fall and at the same time hand Bush, the former
president's son, not only a second term as governor of the nation's
second-most-populous state but also a running start, if he wants
it, in the next presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   ONE MORE MISSION FOR GUNG-HO B-1 BOB
</P>
<P>
   When Robert Dornan was a member of Congress, representing
California's dependably Republican and conservative Orange County
for the better part of two decades, he was not much given to
Capitol Hill's special brand of civility, comity and convention. He
was better known, instead, as the master of boastful bluster, the
ad hominem assault and the blunt riposte.
</P>
<P>
   So two years ago when he got into political trouble back in his
home district, those Republicans who had felt his verbal sting one
time too often were not there to help. He was turned out of office
by Loretta Sanchez, one of the growing number of moderate Democrats
showing up in the district.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than retreat, Dornan spent almost $500,000 to challenge
the validity of the balloting (again with no help from his party).
When that did not work, he decided to run again, though he was
urged not to by many Republican leaders in California and
Washington, who figured a stronger candidate could be found to
challenge Ms. Sanchez and return the district to Republican
control.
</P>
<P>
   To the dismay of those leaders, Dornan won the primary _ and
immediately demanded that they apologize and reimburse him for his
unsuccessful vote challenge. When they did not, he called Speaker
Newt Gingrich ``a disaster for Republicans'' and threatened to
boycott a June 29 rally in California at which Gingrich was to talk
about party unity and the need to elect every Republican
congressional candidate possible in order to retain control of the
House.
</P>
<P>
   ``Newt, it's time for you to bring me in from the cold,'' Dornan
said.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich sent word on Friday that Dornan, a former Air Force
pilot known as B-1 Bob, would be welcomed at the Monday rally. And
then at the rally, after speaking about party unity and what it
would take to retain control of the House, the speaker added:
</P>
<P>
   ``We are dedicated to electing Bob Dornan and returning him to
his seat in the House. I believe that B-1 Bob has one more mission
to run for his country.''
</P>
<P>
   Dornan jumped to his feet and threw the speaker a salute.
</P>
<P>
   TERM-LIMIT CAMPAIGN: LESS BANG FOR THE BUCK
</P>
<P>
   Advocates of term limits have been unusually active this year,
pressing candidates in just about every state, especially
congressional candidates, to pledge to serve a limited time in
office. Those candidates who have refused have been sharply
chastised in costly advertising campaigns, and those who have taken
a pledge have been roundly praised.
</P>
<P>
   And the results?
</P>
<P>
   Clean-cut examples of legislators' being elected or turned out
of office as a result of the pledge campaign are hard to come by,
even though term-limits groups have spent big money in many races.
For every claim of success, there is at least another claim of
failure.
</P>
<P>
   In last week's special congressional election in New Mexico,
term-limits advocates spent $250,000 in support of one of the
candidates. He lost. But what was the impact of the term-limits
campaign?
</P>
<P>
   Also in dispute this election year is what success the advocates
are having in passing new term-limits laws, previously an area of
considerable success, at least at the state level. Consider:
</P>
<P>
   On the June 2 primary ballot in California, voters found an
initiative that proposed requiring members of Congress to push for
passage of a Constitutional amendment to limit congressional terms.
Pending adoption of that limit, all candidates would be asked to
sign pledges of support for term limits and those who refused would
be publicly identified in ballot material.
</P>
<P>
   The measure's backers conceded even before it was placed on the
ballot that it might be unconstitutional, given that courts have
said that states must not interfere in federal elections. But give
the measure a shot anyway, voters were told, because come the fall
a ``superior,'' more carefully worded substitute would be on the
ballot.
</P>
<P>
   The June initiative passed, narrowly, and presumably will soon
face a legal challenge.
</P>
<P>
   But come November there will be no ``superior'' substitute to
vote on. The term-limits forces missed the mid-June deadline for
obtaining the 433,269 petition signatures required to get it on the
November ballot.
</P>
<P>
   Officials for U.S. Term Limits, a leading backer of the
substitute, characterize the failure as a minor setback and insist
there is still plenty of momentum left in the term-limits crusade. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
