<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI ENDORSES VACCO'S RE-ELECTION BID
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Seeking to prove his loyalty to state Republican
leaders for the second time in a month, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani
embraced the re-election campaign of state Attorney General Dennis
Vacco on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani held a news conference on the steps of City Hall to
announce his endorsement of Vacco, a Republican who is running for
a second term along with Gov. George Pataki. He called Vacco ``an
excellent partner'' and said he deserved much of the credit for
reducing crime in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement came four weeks after Giuliani warmly praised
Pataki, whose candidacy he opposed in 1994, in a speech at the
Republican State Convention in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   In both his convention speech and Tuesday's endorsement,
Giuliani was clearly trying to make amends with state GOP leaders,
whose support could be crucial to his future as a state or national
candidate. Although the endorsement was not shocking _ the mayor
also supported Vacco in 1994 _ it came surprisingly early in the
campaign season. Four years ago, Giuliani waited until September to
endorse Vacco.
</P>
</TEXT>
