<SLUG> BC-NY-REMEDIAL-EDUC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORKERS JAM REMEDIAL CLASSES FOR A TOUGHER CUNY
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By KAREN W. ARENSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A month after trustees at the City University of New
York voted to phase out remedial courses from their four-year
colleges and set higher entrance standards, college officials say
they are seeing a big jump in the number of students applying for
CUNY's summer remedial courses, hoping to master basic reading,
writing and mathematics.
</P>
<P>
   The surge in interest in the summer courses has prompted the
university and its branch campuses _ both the two-year community
colleges and the four-year colleges _ to add thousands more seats
for remedial students. While officials on Tuesday had no precise
figures on how many had applied for remedial courses this summer,
they said they expected to register about 50 percent more students
than last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The colleges have all found themselves inundated with requests
for seats for summer immersion,'' said Louise Mirrer, CUNY's vice
chancellor for academic affairs.
</P>
<P>
   The new entrance standards, which bar students from enrolling in
four-year colleges until they pass placement exams in all three
subjects, do not begin to take effect until the fall of 1999 and
will not be fully in place until 2001.
</P>
<P>
   But college officials and students said that the highly
publicized debate this spring over the fate of CUNY's remedial
programs had made more students aware of the requirements and eager
to get the work out of the way.
</P>
<P>
   The summer immersion classes are particularly desirable because
they are free _ students who take remedial classes during the
school year pay regular tuition _ and the summer classes tend to
have higher pass rates than semester courses.
</P>
<P>
   CUNY officials project that remedial enrollment will be more
than 22,500, up from fewer than 15,000 last summer. Some colleges
still have waiting lists, but no figures were available on how many
total students had applied for summer slots. They include both new
students and those already enrolled in CUNY who have not finished
their remedial work.
</P>
<P>
   Francia Fermin, 19, who began remedial classes at Medgar Evers
College in Brooklyn this week, is typical of the summer students.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were concerned,'' she said. ``I want to be sure I can
complete it. My mother, she's kind of worried, and she wants me to
finish it and get it out of the way.''
</P>
<P>
   A good student at St. Michael's Academy in Manhattan, where she
got mostly A's and B's, Ms. Fermin learned a few weeks ago that she
had failed all three placement exams.
</P>
<P>
   Medgar Evers President Edison O. Jackson said that whenever he
speaks, people ask him whether their children will be squeezed out
of CUNY.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly there is heightened awareness on the part of the
community,'' he said. ``They say, `I want to get my child in
there.' They don't want the door to shut in their face. They don't
want to take the gamble.''
</P>
<P>
   CUNY has budgeted an extra $1 million for this summer's remedial
courses, up 18 percent from $5.5 million in 1997. It is not nearly
enough to pay for the 50 percent rise in seats. But Medgar Evers
and other colleges have rearranged their budgets to try to let more
students take the courses this summer, rather than during the
regular school year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
